<HEADLINE>
DETROIT NIPS CAPITALS,2-1, IN FIRST GAME OF STANLEY CUP SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DTROIT _ In the 60 seasons that the National Hockey League has
used a four-of-seven-game format for the Stanley Cup finals, the
team that has won Game 1 has gone on to win the title almost 80
percent of the time. In the last three seasons, that winning team
has prevailed in a four-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   These long-term and short-term trends suggest a positive and
rapid conclusion of the season for the Detroit Red Wings. In
opening their defense of their championship on Tuesday night, they
jumped ahead by 2-0 in the first period and went on to a 2-1
victory over the Washington Capitals. Game 2 will be here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The first period on Tuesday night was played at a tentative
pace, and the Capitals may have been awestruck after having won the
Eastern Conference title by eliminating the Bruins, Senators and
Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Red Wings got over their own little jitters, they
scored two goals in a span of 2 minutes 14 seconds to hold a 2-0
lead at the first intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the first goal was Joe Kocur, who had not worn a uniform
in four of the six games of the previous round, the Western
Conference final against the Dallas Stars. Kocur charged to the
crease from the right side and put the puck past Washington goalie
Olaf Kolzig at 14:04 after a pass from Doug Brown. Tomas Holmstrom
got the other assist. It was the fourth goal of the playoffs for
Kocur, who also scored in last spring's finals against the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring the second goal was Niklas Lidstrom, who took a
fluttering shot from the blue line. Kolzig seemed screened on the
play, probably by Holmstrom, who occupied the low slot after
winning a battle for possession behind the Capitals' net. It was
Lidstrom's sixth playoff goal.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Juneau, the Washington forward, said between periods that
his team started ``panicking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We started giving the puck away,'' Juneau said in a televised
interview with the Canadian Broadcasting Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second period, one of the highlights was a body
check by Detroit's Kris Draper against Juneau. Draper found him
along the boards while Juneau was trying to play the puck and
leveled him with a hit that knocked the helmet from Juneau's head.
Juneau is one of Washington's most dangerous shooters and,
therefore, a target for checkers such as Draper.
</P>
<P>
   The next bit of mayhem involved Dale Hunter, the ancient
Washington center and captain, against Steve Yzerman, the veteran
center and captain of the Wings. After Yzerman lost a face-off,
Hunter drove him to the ice and pushed against Yzerman's helmet for
emphasis, knocking it off. Yzerman jumped to his skates and slashed
Hunter's legs, earning a two-minute penalty from referee Bill
McCreary.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals cut the lead to 2-1 at 15:57 when Richard Zednik, a
rookie with a scoring touch, put a shot past goalie Chris Osgood,
Detroit's weakest link. Osgood got a piece of the puck before it
fell behind him, over the line. Setting it up were Andrei
Nikolishin and Peter Bondra, the other two-thirds of Washington's
European line.
</P>
<P>
   The next scrum came late in the period, also involving the two
captains. As the Wings threatened around the net of Kolzig, Hunter
landed again atop Yzerman and worked him over. McCreary called no
penalty for this, although he did send Washington's Chris Simon off
for roughing in the same scrum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
