<SLUG> BC-NY-FIRE-CHARGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN CHARGED WITH MURDER IN QUEENS FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police detectives accused a 43-year-old woman of
second-degree murder and arson Tuesday, saying she set a fire that
killed one person and injured nine others on Monday at an
overcrowded home in Queens. City officials also cited the home's
owner for illegally subdividing the two-family residence into six
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   The woman charged with murder, Marsha Manning, 43, was accused
of pouring a flammable liquid on the stairways on three floors and
then lighting the fire because of a dispute with her landlord, said
Frank Gribbon, a Fire Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   A city official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said
investigators began to suspect the woman after hearing reports that
she had recently threatened to burn down the house, at 163-14 109th
Ave. in South Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the man who died, two people were seriously
injured in the blaze. Another resident, a woman eight months'
pregnant, survived the fire by jumping two stories to the sidewalk,
and was treated for minor injuries, city officials said. The
identity of the man who died was not released Tuesday night because
his next of kin had not been notified.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they were still trying to determine whether
the illegal subdivision of the house played any role in the death
of the man, who was found on the third floor.
</P>
<P>
   Buildings Department officials said inspectors from their agency
cited the home's owner, JoAnne Smith, of the same address, with two
building code violations: building walls without a permit and
subdividing the residence without permission from the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you limit access, you create the potential for serious
danger,'' said Ted Birkhahn, a Buildings Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Gribbon, the Fire Department spokesman, said fire investigators
determined that 15 people from 10 families were living in the
house.
</P>
<P>
   The house had been illegally subdivided to create three bedrooms
and a living room in the attic, and five bedrooms, a kitchen and a
bathroom in the cellar, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents near the burned-out home and others said that they had
long complained to city officials about the behavior of the people
who lived in the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of drinking going on over there, a lot of
arguments and fights, with young kids over there smoking weed,''
said Maverick Brown as he held his 20-month-old daughter,
Dimonique, while sitting on the front steps of his brother-in-law's
two-story home. ``I don't like to bring my daughter out here much
because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor, Fred Simmons, complained about landlords acquiring
homes and illegally converting them into mini-apartment buildings
in which they do not crack down on tenants involved in criminal
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, an official with a community organization, has lived
with his family on the block for almost five years. He said that
during that time, the block association complained repeatedly about
the house, where the fire was on Monday, and that there were other
homes that appeared to be overcrowded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is another house on our block that we are concerned
about,'' Simmons said. ``I hope that now, the city will finally do
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
