<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-QUALIFY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTER LEADS 19 INTO TOURNEY FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lee Porter, who lost his card on the PGA Tour twice, shot rounds
of 68 and 69 Tuesday for a 36-hole total of 137, seven under par,
to lead the U.S. Open Sectional Qualifying at Canoe Brook Country
Club in Summit, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Porter led 19 qualifiers into the Open, which
will be played next week at the Olympic Club in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Fuzzy Zoeller, winner of the 1984 Open at Winged Foot, trailed
Porter by two strokes after shooting 73-66-139. A field of 106,
including 15 amateurs, competed.
</P>
<P>
   Porter missed only one green. He had a three-putt for a bogey on
the eighth hole, then sank a 30-foot birdie putt on the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Porter played on the Nike Tour in 1995 and 1996 after losing his
PGA Tour card for the first time in 1993. He finished eighth on the
Nike money list in 1996 to regain his PGA card, then lost it again
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sluman, who won the PGA Championship in 1988, qualified at
142 along with Chip Beck. D.A. Weibring, another tour member,
advanced with a 75-69-144, as did Mike Burke Jr., the reigning Met
Golf Association Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   At 145 was Bruce Zabriski, a former National Club Pro champion
and two-time Met Open winner. Duffy Waldorf had rounds of 74-73-147
and failed to qualify.
</P>
</TEXT>
