<SLUG> BC-ELN-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE HOLDS ITS PRIMARY AMONG MODEST SPENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ Maine's primary on Tuesday could be considered
a breath of cool, fresh political air after the overheated spending
of California's election last week.
</P>
<P>
   The results brought no big surprises. With more than
three-quarters of the precincts reporting, Democrats appeared to
have selected as their candidate for governor Tom Connolly, a
prominent Portland defense lawyer who emphasized social justice in
his campaign. He heavily defeated Joseph Ricci, a racetrack owner
with a tendency to become unprintably outspoken.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans running for governor, Jim Longley Jr., a
conservative former congressman and son of Maine's former governor,
appeared to have defeated two opponents with a campaign that
focused on tax cuts and criticism of the state's economic
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Angus King, an independent, is expected to be easily
re-elected in November.
</P>
<P>
   But for politics-watchers still goggle-eyed at the immense sums
spent on last week's primary in California _ more than $100 million
in all _ the most striking aspect of Maine's primary was its
financial modesty.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest spender in the governor's race, Connolly, had raised
about enough to cover a California campaign's dry-cleaning bills:
$21,477, according to state records. Ricci raised $16,385.
</P>
<P>
   King and the state's two House members, John Baldacci and Tom
Allen, both Democrats who faced no challenges in their primaries,
raised about $200,000. And both contenders in the Republican
primary for the 1st District seat in Congress fell well short of
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Maine did not appear to have reached even the $1
million mark in all its races combined.
</P>
<P>
   That would seem like cause for rejoicing in a state that is
considered one of the leaders in campaign finance reform, and is
expected to put into effect by 2000 a groundbreaking system that
would provide public money to candidates who voluntarily accept
limits on fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   But the coolness of the campaign was a little too cool for some
voters. A low turnout _ reported to be below 14 percent _ bolstered
the general impression of a campaign so lackluster and a public so
apathetic that it was called ``the stealth campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an odd election in that there's nothing going on,'' said
Bill Coogan, a political science professor at the University of
Southern Maine. ``The two parties have conceded the governorship;
there's no Senate race; and though there are two congressional
campaigns in the fall, the results are a foregone conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine, it seems, has a particularly potent case of the
complacency, even somnolence, that often comes with economic
prosperity, political observers said.
</P>
<P>
   In Portland on Tuesday, when several Maine voters were asked as
they left their polling booths in City Hall what issues they wished
had been highlighted, none could come up with any.
</P>
<P>
   King is so popular that neither party had reason to believe its
candidate could beat him. So the top of the ticket in both
primaries appeared to many to be all but moot, and few were willing
to give money to candidates who appeared doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest,'' said Garison Murrell, who had just loyally
cast his ballot in the Republican primary. ``The gubernatorial
nominees don't even have a shot unless Angus King decides to parade
naked down Congress Street.''
</P>
<P>
   In other races around the country, State Rep. Blanche Lincoln of
Arkansas defeated Attorney General Winston Bryant in a runoff to
become the Democratic nominee for the Senate. She will face the
Republican candidate, State Sen. Fay Boozman.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, Rep. Bob Inglis easily defeated Stephen
Brown, a former Republican county chairman, for the Republican
nomination to face Senator Ernest Hollings, a Democrat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
