<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HUTCHINSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPHINE HUTCHINSON, 94, MOVIE ACTRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Josephine Hutchinson, a stage and film actress who
gained prominence in the 1930s and early '40s, died on June 4 at
the Florence Nightingale Nursing Home in Manhattan. She was 94.
</P>
<P>
   After studying as a child at the Cornish School in her hometown
of Seattle, Ms. Hutchinson left for several years of stock work in
New York and Washington before joining Eva Le Gallienne's Civic
Repertory Theater while in her early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   As a leading player she won critical acclaim, particularly as
Alice in the Civic's 1932 production of ``Alice in Wonderland.''
Petite, with golden-red hair framing her heart-shaped face, Ms.
Hutchinson said her interpretation was inspired by her mother's
``cleanliness-is-next-to-godliness technique of dressing little
girls.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1934 she left New York for Hollywood to become a contract
player at Warner Brothers, making her screen debut in Mervyn
LeRoy's ``Happiness Ahead'' in 1934. Melodramas and period films
followed, including ``The Story of Louis Pasteur'' (1936), starring
Paul Muni.
</P>
<P>
   After withdrawing from acting in 1941, Ms. Hutchinson returned
in 1946 in Joseph Mankiewicz's ``Somewhere in the Night.'' Small
roles followed in films including ``Love Is Better Than Ever''
(1952), starring Elizabeth Taylor; ``North by Northwest'' (1959),
starring Cary Grant, and ``Baby, the Rain Must Fall'' (1965), with
Steve McQueen. She appeared in episodes of the television series
``The Twilight Zone,'' ``Perry Mason'' and ``Gunsmoke'' in the late
1950s and early '60s.
</P>
<P>
   No immediate family members survive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
