</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CRUSH EXPOS, 11-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ When the New York Yankees signed Orlando Hernandez in
March, they knew he was brave enough to board a leaky boat. They
knew he had the determination to defect from Cuba. They knew he
possessed a strange delivery that often changed from one pitch to
the next.
</P>
<P>
   But it is evident that even the Yankees, who saw more in
Hernandez's ability than any other team did, had no idea how good a
pitcher he could be. The pleasant shock covered the face of Joe
Torre tonight after Hernandez completed a masterful four-hit, 11-1
victory against the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez struck out nine and walked one; among the last 24
batters he faced, he went to one three-ball count. He maintained a
shutout until Montreal put together a double and single with one
out in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over Hernandez's future is over, for now and the
foreseeable future. El Duque, as Hernandez is known, is staying.
The Yankees could not possibly return him to the minor leagues,
considering his performance in winning his first two starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to see him again,'' said Torre, the Yankee
manager, who has six good starting pitchers and only five spots in
his rotation. ``We're going to have to work it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza will pitch on Friday night against Cleveland.
David Wells will play catch on Wednesday, and if his sore left
shoulder feels better, he will pitch on Saturday, then David Cone
on Sunday, and El Duque next Monday in Baltimore. After that, Torre
may finally have to move Mendoza into the bullpen, the most logical
solution. Returning Hernandez to Class AAA Columbus is not an
option. He knows how to pitch, like Julia Child knows how to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi, Hernandez's catcher on Tuesday night, compared him
to Cone, who compared him to Luis Tiant, a Cuban right-hander who
won 229 games in the major leagues. Hernandez reminded Torre of
Juan Marichal, with the different arm angles, different release
points, different speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was excellent,'' said Girardi, who, like Torre, looked
stunned by Hernandez's dominance.
</P>
<P>
   After Hernandez worked out for scouts before spring training,
the consensus was that his talent was average at best. A No. 4 or
No. 5 starter. Some reported that his fastball was below average,
that his delivery might be problematic; when working with a windup,
Hernandez draws up his front left leg so high that his knee can
touch his cheekbone. Too complicated, with too many moving parts to
maintain, scouts thought.
</P>
<P>
   They thought he threw too much junk, too much soft stuff.
Interest in El Duque was limited. Executives from other teams
involved in the bidding say the Yankees' ultimate cost for
Hernandez of $6.6 million was more than twice any other offer. But
in those abbreviated workouts, scouts could not have possibly seen
what the Yankees are seeing now.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez knows how to take a little off his changeup, add a
little to his fastball. He throws curveballs when hitters are
looking for fastballs, he throws fastballs when hitters are looking
for changeups. He changes the angle of his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's Rondell White had 20 hits in 45 at-bats going into
Tuesday night's game, and he admitted that he had no chance against
Hernandez and his different arm angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing is, he throws all of his off-speed pitches for
strikes,'' White said. ``Everything he threw, a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Hernandez's 124 pitches, he threw 83 strikes. ``I saw the
same pitches from overhand, sidearm, I-don't-know-where-from,''
said Jose Vidro, the Expos' second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   From the third inning through the fifth, Hernandez faced 11
batters and threw first-pitch strikes to 10, but it wasn't as if he
merely exploited his early lead and pumped fastballs over the
plate. He started Vidro with a curve _ strike one. He started
Vladimir Guerrero with a fastball _ strike one. Brad Fullmer swung
and missed at a first-pitch changeup. And, as Cone noted, Hernandez
has a knack for finishing off hitters once he is ahead in the
count.
</P>
<P>
   Catching Hernandez for the first time was a challenge, Girardi
said. His pitches moved so much, particularly his fastball. Girardi
set up his target on the absolute edges of the strike zone and,
through Spanish-speaking teammate Jorge Posada, asked Hernandez in
the middle innings if that was O.K. Oh, yes, El Duque replied, and
kept throwing to those edges. Nothing in the middle of the plate,
Girardi said. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said afterward that he just wanted to help the team.
With three walks and 16 strikeouts in his first 161/3 innings, he
fits right in. The Yankees are 45-13. They have won 44 of their
last 53 games, only the second team in American League history to
go on such a streak of success. The 1941 Yankees also won 44 of 53.
</P>
<P>
   They have won eight straight games. They are running away. And
Joe Torre suddenly has discovered a phenomenon on his staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
