<HEADLINE>
NCAA FORMULA TO DETERMINE TEAMS FOR CHAMPIONSHIP BOWL GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Get out your calculators. The bowl championship series has
settled on a four-part formula for determining the teams that will
play for the football national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The formula, announced yesterday by Southeastern Conference
commissioner Roy Kramer, will be based on polls (news media and
coaches), computer rankings (three versions), strength of schedule
and win-loss records.
</P>
<P>
   The rating system is designed to determine only the top two
teams for the championship game and also to determine which, if
any, teams from conferences or the independent ranks will earn one
of eight berths in the four bowl championship series bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a poll,'' said Kramer, coordinator of the series,
formerly the bowl alliance. ``We are doing this to go beyond the
subjective polls by the media and the coaches. We're moving into
computerized evaluations in all phases of life, and we felt it was
important to incorporate that aspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a very definitive way to determine the two
teams in the championship game. We ran it back over the last 10 or
12 seasons and we think it's very factual.''
</P>
<P>
   By applying the statistical formula to last season, Michigan and
Nebraska would have been ranked first and second. However, those
teams didn't play because the Rose Bowl was not part of the bowl
alliance. Michigan (The Associated Press) and Nebraska (ESPN/USA
Today) each finished ranked No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``No system is perfect,'' Michigan coach Lloyd Carr said. ``But
I think we're all in the same boat. I know there's been tremendous
thought and planning that has gone into it. I'm optimistic it will
work well.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the series will add the Big Ten and Pacific-10
conferences and the Rose Bowl to its lineup. The series
championship game will be played Jan. 4 in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The series system will incorporate the two polls, computer
rankings published in USA Today (Jeff Sagarin), The New York Times
and the Seattle Times, a strength of schedule based on a team's
opponents and its opponents' opponents plus win-loss record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will encourage people to play stronger schedules,'' Big Ten
Conference commissioner Jim Delany said. ``For a first attempt at
coming up with something like this, I think it's a pretty good
formula.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the strength of schedule factor, the first series
rankings, which will list 10 to 12 teams, probably won't debut
until the second or third week of November. The news media and
coaches polls will continue to appear weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The final rankings, which will determine the championship game,
will be released the day after conference championship games.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for a spot in the bowl alliance, teams outside the
series must finish ranked No. 6 or higher. That includes teams from
the Western Athletic, Conference USA, Big West and Mid-American
plus independents such as Notre Dame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
