r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     06-10 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AMERICA, WORLD CUP MEANS NO HANDS, AND FEW FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My, has it been four years already?
</P>
<P>
   Four years since that spell-binding 0-0 tie in the final? Four
years since the biggest news for the home side was that somebody
kicked in a goal for the wrong team?
</P>
<P>
   Four years since we thrilled to the exploits of ... uh ... uh
... El Whatsisname?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Just when you've calmed down after those NHL playoffs, the
world has reconvened in ``la belle France.'' Five weeks of soccer _
``le foot,'' to the French _ good wine and, perchance, an
occasional goal.
</P>
<P>
   World Cup '98 promises to be bigger and better than World Cup
'94 which, of course, was held on our shores and attracted 3.5
million live ticket buyers, most of whom couldn't even tell you El
Whatsisname's number.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the idea, wasn't it? By force-feeding us
world-class soccer, the game would finally gain its toehold on
American sports pages and in American family budgets. We would
finally be able to gather at the office water cooler and discuss
the nuances of the off-side trap. We'd call DirecTV and order the
whole Belgian A League package.
</P>
<P>
   But, no. It hasn't worked that way.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the U.S. World Cup team brandished the irresistible
charms of being (A) the home team and (B) a shameless underdog.
Team USA was studded with ringers (German-born Tom Dooley, among
them) and the ultimate mercenary head coach, Bora Milutinovic.
</P>
<P>
   That part worked. Though the only match the Americans won came
on tragically fated Andres Escobar's wrong goal (he was murdered in
his homeland a week later), the Yanks advanced to the next round.
It was one small leap for soccer-kind, and all that.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, however, it's the Americans who may as well
all be named Whatsisname. Soccer has grown, but there's a feeling
that it has found its audience.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer moms are too tired to take the minivan-full to the Major
League Soccer game. There are still too many dads out there who
couldn't tell you if a soccer ball is blown up or stuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to keep the momentum ball rolling, there's a feeling
that the MLS waited too long after USA '94 to launch. The league is
still too new. Too under-publicized. Too . . . American?
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, as the U.S. team prepares for its Monday opener against
powerhouse Germany, new coach Steve Sampson's main problem is
finding offense. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   In a country that has spawned Michael Jordan, Deion Sanders,
Pistol Pete Maravich and Joe Montana, we can't find someone out
there with the athletic creativity to score even one goal on
Macedonia?
</P>
<P>
   Same problem as 1994, if memory serves correctly. The Americans
tied Switzerland, 1-1, and then came the 2-1 upset of Colombia.
Team USA's next two contests were 1-0 losses.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in World Cup soccer, a 2-1 game is tantamount to a
Home Run Derby. Scoring a goal seems as elementary as rehanging
Stonehenge. The Brazil-Italy final four years ago ended in a 0-0
tie, decided by a first-ever shootout. There was dancing in the
streets. Honest.
</P>
<P>
   That those five weeks of soccer matches became the most-watched
and best-attended World Cup finals in history is a tribute to U.S.
organizers and, yes, to Team USA, which kindled the temporary
flame. The world never thought it would work.
</P>
<P>
   At the opening ceremonies, singer Diana Ross was supposed to
kick a ball into the goal from six feet away. She missed. Oprah
Winfrey was walking off the stage and stumbled, face first. And the
mechanism that was supposed to lift performer Jon Secada onto the
stage in mid-song broke and left Secada standing there, still
singing, only visible from the waist up.
</P>
<P>
   Draw your own symbolism from there.
</P>
<P>
   To most Americans, soccer will never quite make it onto the big
stage. Over the next five weeks, we will read the datelines _
places like Saint-Jean D'Ardieres, Saint-Denis and Montpellier _ we
will hear the players' names, and it'll all get lost in the
translation.
</P>
<P>
   Again, people are saying that a strong U.S. showing will do
wonders for the game in this country. Maybe. The June 21 meeting
with a weak Iran team figures to be the patriotic feel-good hit of
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the world's most popular sport may have already found its
niche back here. If you hear someone talking about it at the water
cooler, let me know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
