<HEADER>
A1995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARATHON-THEATER-REVI     06-10 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARATHON-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARATHON '98: FIVE PLAYLETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) (mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I'm a New Yorker; fear's my life,'' sings the
battle-scarred support-group attendee in ``Rent.'' Free-floating
anxiety may well be the birthright of every son and daughter of the
five boroughs, but everyone knows that in this perilous age, it's
parents who have first dibs on fretting.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Ayvazian knows. Oh, does she ever. In ``Plan Day,'' her
little gem of a monologue, she sets off on a short jaunt into the
mind of a maternal worrywart, the kind for whom life is less a
cabaret than an extended opportunity for the sampling of
antibacterial soaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sun screen, bug spray,'' she says, enumerating the
preventatives as she embarks on a trip to the beach with her unseen
son. ``Keep your shoes on. Got the cell phone and the megaphone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ayvazian, author of ``Nine Armenians,'' escorts us through
the decades, riffing amusingly on the mental notes we make,
obsessively, protectively, superstitiously, to ward off evil, to
keep loved ones safe, to keep ourselves busy.
</P>
<P>
   The piece, which Ms. Ayvazian performs to perfection _ this is
the sort of woman who is the backbone of every PTA _ arrives in the
gift basket of playlets that Ensemble Studio Theater bestows on
audiences in the final segment of its annual one-act marathon.
Unlike the undistinguished series that preceded it, the five pieces
in Series C _ which include a solid new one-act play by David Mamet
and a teasingly funny playlet by Ari Roth, staged expertly by Mark
Nelson _ form a strong and varied evening, much of it full of
promise.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Ayvazian's ``Plan Day'' is a purging of sorts _ the full
complement of middle-age obsessions is cataloged in the planning of
one day, from ``learn something new'' to ``get the estrogen'' _
Mamet's represents a reassessing. The mood of ``The Jade
Mountain,'' like the three playlets that made up his ``Old
Neighborhood,'' is reflective and slightly melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   In the play, tautly directed by Curt Dempster, two men, A (James
Murtagh) and B (Chris Ceraso) discuss A's guilt-laden memories of
military service. An air of misgiving suffuses the room, which may
or may not belong to a psychotherapist. A is a veteran, probably of
Vietnam, who remains in a sense a prisoner of war, still troubled
by the violence. It's not a traumatic disorder exactly; the
feelings are no longer so profound. Rather, it's a low-grade sense
of regret that he seems unable to shed, the kind that festers and
manifests itself in later life as malaise.
</P>
<P>
   Murtagh is especially effective as this contemporary everyman,
seeking specific responses to questions that can be answered only
in generalities. And Mamet, preoccupied these days with decoding
the past, demonstrates in ``The Jade Mountain'' a compassion for
the attempt to interpret what's come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's ``Prelude to a Crisis,'' on the other hand, is just as
resolutely anchored in the here and now. The setup is straight out
of the comedy writer's handbook: A college playwriting instructor,
played by the goofily prepossessing Greg Germann, awaits the
arrival of a saucy student (the excellent Melinda Page Hamilton) in
his hotel room to, ahem, go over her work.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be lust or bust in the afternoon? It's Roth's sharp ear
for the music of the mating call that makes ``Prelude'' so much
fun. ``I didn't see your name in the course guide'' is how Ms.
Hamilton reveals two, three or maybe even four notions at once: why
she initiated this assignation, how conniving she is and what
ultimately is going to happen to this schnook of a professor.
</P>
<P>
   Germann, who plays the truly kooky Richard Fish on ``Ally
McBeal,'' makes an attractive romantic antihero and a terrific foil
for the self-possessed Ms. Hamilton. Nelson, the director,
demonstrates here, as he did with ``June Moon,'' a natural gift for
quick-witted comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining pieces, ``The Earthquake,'' by Joyce Carol Oates
and Elinor Renfield, and ``Mary MacGregor,'' by Keith Alan
Benjamin, are less successful playlets that nonetheless receive
top-notch productions. ``The Earthquake,'' based on an Oates story,
is too psychologically sophisticated for the format: It's the tale
of a lonely boy, Roy (Shelton Dane), who, pining for an absent
father, convinces himself, against reason, that his mother has
disappeared, too.
</P>
<P>
   As staged by Ms. Renfield, the play has an appealing directness,
particularly in the moments dramatizing Roy's sullen withdrawal.
But scenes of some emotional complexity spin by so rapidly you feel
as if you're watching a movie trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin's ``Mary MacGregor'' is also fetchingly acted; Anne
O'Sullivan is utterly convincing as a young widow packing up her
things as the ghost of her dead husband (Andrew Weems) lounges on
the couch. Benjamin's treatment is sweet, but the subject,
unfortunately, seems about as fresh as the reruns featured on
``Nick at Nite.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MARATHON '98` &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Series C. The 21st annual festival of new one-act plays.
Production manager, Tim Gallagher; technical director, Carlo
Adinolfi; lighting by Greg MacPherson; sets by Ann Waugh; costumes
by Julie Doyle; sound by Laura Brown; props master, Ed Miller.
Presented by the Ensemble Studio Theater, Curt Dempster, artistic
director; Jamie Richards, executive producer; Mark Roberts,
marathon producer. At 549 W. 52nd St., Manhattan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `PRELUDE TO A CRISIS,' By Ari Roth; directed by Mark Nelson.
With: Melinda Page Hamilton and Greg Germann.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `PLAN DAY,' by Leslie Ayvazian; directed by Curt Dempster. With:
Ms. Ayvazian. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE JADE MOUNTAIN,' by David Mamet; directed by Dempster. With:
James Murtaugh and Chris Ceraso.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE EARTHQUAKE,' by Elinor Renfield and Joyce Carol Oates,
based on a story by Ms. Oates; directed by Ms. Renfield. With:
Patrica Mauceri, Joseph Siravo, Shelton Dane and James DeMarse.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MARY MacGREGOR,' by Keith Alan Benjamin; directed by Joe White.
With: Anne O'Sullivan and Andrew Weems.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
