<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVIL RAYS STING METS, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hideo Nomo made his pitching debut for the New York
Mets on Tuesday night and created an instant buzz at Shea Stadium.
But neither Nomo nor his teammates could deliver on the
anticipation, with Nomo squandering an early three-run lead and the
Mets leaving runners all over the bases as the Tampa Bay Devil Rays
squeaked out a 5-4 victory in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The winning run, fittingly enough, was set up by an error by
Luis Lopez on a double-play grounder. An inning earlier, Mike
Piazza grounded out with the bases loaded and two out and the
remainder of the crowd of 30,336 pleading for a game-winning base
hit.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of night for the Mets, and it was not that much
better for Nomo. The right-hander with the corkscrew windup lasted
only five innings. He was staked to a 4-1 lead after three innings,
departed after the fifth with the score tied at 4-4 and, over all,
did not look much different than he had as a Dodger in April and
May, when he struggled to a 2-7 mark with a 5.05 earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo did finish with a flourish, though, striking out the tough
Fred McGriff with runners on first and second in the fifth with his
79th pitch of the game. That, Mets Manager Bobby Valentine decided,
was enough for someone who was pitching for the first time in 10
days.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo's final pitching line read like this: five innings, five
hits, four runs (all earned), three walks and five strikeouts.
There were also a wild pitch and a balk. Not atrocious. But not
very good, either. It appears it might take a while for Nomo to
rediscover his old formula, if he can.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Nomo provided a jolt at the box office for the
Mets. On a normal Tuesday night in June, the Mets in recent years
would have been happy to get close to 20,000 fans in the park. They
had a lot more than that on Tuesday night, helped by the 12,336
tickets they sold in the last two days in anticipation of Nomo's
debut. And it was easy to see that the patrons were desperately
looking for something to cheer for.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd reacted noisily before Nomo's first pitch, acting as
if he were about to close out a complete-game victory. But the
noise abated when the Tampa Bay leadoff hitter, Randy Winn, smacked
a 2-1 pitch inside the first-base line for a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Winn would score one out later on a Wade Boggs groundout. And
just like that, Nomo trailed, 1-0. But the Mets rallied to tie the
game for him at 1-1 in the bottom of the second inning without a
hit _ the tying run scoring on Rey Ordonez's one-out chopper over
the mound, after McGriff had thrown a potential double-play ball
into left field for an error.
</P>
<P>
   One inning later, Nomo had a big lead to work with after the
Mets erupted for three more runs off Julio Santana on a one-out
walk to Bernard Gilkey, Piazza's single to left, John Olerud's
two-run bloop double to left and a two-out run-scoring double that
Carlos Baerga spanked off the first-base bag.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive support was something of a rarity this season for
the 29-year-old Nomo, who, in reality, had only three truly bad
starts with the Dodgers before Tuesday night. So why was Nomo 2-7?
Well, in his 12 starts with Los Angeles this season, the Dodgers
had averaged just 2.25 runs in back of him, the lowest run support
for any starting pitcher in the National League. Now the Mets had
just given him four runs in three innings.
</P>
<P>
   The old Nomo, who took the major leagues by storm in 1995 when
he was named the National League's rookie of the year, might have
coasted home from there. But after undergoing off-season
arthroscopic surgery on his pitching elbow to clean out some
calcium deposits, Nomo has struggled this season with his control.
</P>
<P>
   And the walks, the wild pitch and the balk definitely hurt him
on Tuesday night. Boggs singled up the middle to open the fourth
inning, then took second on the wild pitch. McGriff followed by
lining a run-scoring double into the right-field corner. That cut
the Mets' lead to 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later, Dave Martinez slapped a run-scoring single up
the middle and, all of a sudden, it was a one-run game. The damage
could have been worse. But, with one out and Martinez still on
first, the Tampa Bay right fielder tried to steal second on a 1-0
pitch. Piazza's one-hop throw was to the third-base side of second
base. But Ordonez made a wonderful diving slap tag to get the
head-first-sliding Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   It was still 4-3 heading into the top of the fifth inning. And
Nomo quickly recorded the first two outs. But Winn walked on a 3-1
pitch and then took third on a Quinton McCracken bloop single to
left. With runners on first and third, Nomo threw two quick strikes
past Boggs. But before his 0-2 pitch, Nomo lurched forward from the
stretch and the home-plate umpire, Mark Hirschbeck, immediately
called a balk.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously shaken, Nomo ended up walking Boggs to put runners on
first and second. But McGriff took an 0-2 pitch for a called strike
three. And Nomo was finished for the night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
