<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-REDSOX-BRAVES-BOS     06-10 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABERHAGEN HELPS RED SOX FORGET COLLAPSE, BEAT BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BRAVES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the Red Sox were feeling any aftershocks from their
Monday night meltdown in Turner Field, it wasn't apparent on the
mound Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there. Perhaps the Red Sox player best qualified to
put that ninth-inning collapse in perspective is Bret Saberhagen,
the man with the collapsible shoulder who Tuesday night made Monday
feel like ancient history with a 9-3 win over the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, pitching in Atlanta for the first time since he
tried to work on fumes for the expansion Colorado Rockies in the
1995 playoffs and was clobbered by the eventual World Series
winners, did not walk a batter and struck out seven in seven
innings for his third straight win and eighth overall this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a perfect eight innings (Monday night) and lost,''
Saberhagen said. ``To lose a game like that, when we've been on the
other end of those games a lot more ... I think a lot of guys
probably had nightmares. I know I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an experienced ball club like the Braves, when you've got
'em on the ropes, you've got to pull the noose nice and tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, pitching on that rare night when his opposite
number, 43-year-old Dennis Martinez, was older than he is (by nine
years), departed with an 8-3 lead. That's the same-sized cushion
that was not enough for Derek Lowe and the Red Sox the night
before, when Tom Gordon was unmasked as mortal.
</P>
<P>
   But this time the Red Sox added one more run on a walk and the
last of their 13 hits, a double by Darren Bragg, who also tripled
and scored Boston's first run in the first and singled home the
final run in a five-run fourth.
</P>
<P>
   So it was 9-3 when Jim Corsi, Saberhagen's personal valet, took
the mound for the final two innings. They passed without incident,
dashing the hopes of a Turner Field crowd of 43,121 that saw the
Braves lose for only the ninth time in 35 home games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty good handoff, to have it 9-3,'' Corsi said.
``Sabes bowed his neck again, and we played a great game
defensively. What I did was minuscule.'
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, a native of Nicaragua, was bidding to make history in
front of his country's president, Arnoldo Aleman. One more win and
Martinez can claim more victories than any other Latin American
pitcher in big league history, surpassing Dominican Juan Marichal,
who has 243.
</P>
<P>
   But it did not come on the Red Sox' watch. Let's hope that when
it does come, it doesn't take as long as Carl Yastrzemski's 400th
home run, or Nicaragua may be faced with government by proxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see him get his record,'' Saberhagen said of El
Presidente, which is Mr. Aleman's title but Senor Martinez's
nickname. ``I just didn't want to see him get it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, who gave up seven hits and all three Atlanta runs,
one on Danny Bautista's pinch homer, went out on a high note as
second baseman Mike Benjamin made the night's best defensive play _
a sprawling stop of Walt Weiss's bid for a hit after a two-out
single by pinch hitter Ozzie Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's defense deserted him in the fourth, when the Red Sox
scored five runs, four unearned, aided by two errors and Atlanta's
inability to turn a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, whose nine-game hitting streak came to an end the
night before, grounded a single up the middle to open the inning.
Troy O'Leary followed with a grounder to third baseman Chipper
Jones, but first base umpire Randy Marsh ruled that O'Leary just
beat Tony Graffanino's relay on the attempted double play.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez could have helped himself if he'd been able to field
John Valentin's sharp comebacker, but the best he could do was
knock the ball down, and Valentin reached on the infield hit. A
walk to Scott Hatteberg loaded the bases, and Benjamin followed
with a high chopper over the mound that Graffanino tried in vain to
short-hop with a backhanded swipe.
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino was charged with a tough error as two runs scored to
make it 3-1. Saberhagen fouled off a third-strike bunt attempt for
the inning's second out, but Darren Lewis singled up the middle for
another run, and when center fielder Andruw Jones overran the ball,
Benjamin scored to make it 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Bragg's line single to left made it 6-1, but the inning ended
when Chipper Jones cut off the throw to the plate and nailed Bragg
at first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an important win for us, to get our confidence going
again,'' said Saberhagen, whose last three wins have followed
Boston losses, including one that could have required group
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, Vaughn said: ``This team didn't make too much of
(Monday night). We just didn't cash in. We went out there tonight,
Bret pitched a brilliant game, and (we) cashed in this time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
