<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX PUT UP A BRAVE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What ninth inning? What five-run lead? What
embarrassing loss? What Monday Night Horror Theater? Oh, that? Hey,
pal, this is baseball. We play one-six-two. You can't be worrying
about anything that happens in one baseball game, not when it's
early June and you still have 101 games to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have a saying before a game,'' explained Darren
Bragg. ```Yesterday doesn't mean anything.' It doesn't matter
whether you go 4 for 4 or 0 for 5. Every day you start all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say. He had a single, double, and triple as the
Red Sox shrugged off that ninth-inning Monday night disaster with a
crisp 9-3 Tuesday night dispatch of the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   It was all in place for Jimy's Kids Tuesday night. The offense
came through with 13 hits. The defense was superb. Bret Saberhagen
and Jim Corsi were efficient on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   For all we know, everybody probably even smelled good.
</P>
<P>
   They've played 18 innings here at Turner Field these past two
nights, and the plain gospel truth is that the Boston Red Sox have
kicked the stuff out of the Atlanta Braves in 17 of them. And if
you want to go back to Saturday's 1-0 loss to the Mets, a further
unarguable premise is that the Red Sox have played four excellent
baseball games in succession, even if all they have to show for
their efforts are two wins. If they continue to play this type of
baseball, they will win a lot of games and they will be the
American League wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the games we lost,'' said Mo Vaughn, who had two more
line-drive hits Tuesday, ``we've played solid baseball. We're now
getting some runs, and the pitching has been great. They're
throwing strikes and keeping runners off base.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen maintained that he and some others had ``nightmares''
about the horrifying events of Monday, but Vaughn was not one of
them. He looked at the weird goings-on as just one of those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night was a different kind of situation,'' Vaughn pointed
out. ``We did all the right things to put ourselves in a position
to win the game. We just didn't carry it through. I've been saying
all along that Flash (Tom Gordon) has been perfect and that the
streak had to end some night. But overall, we've been playing good
baseball and we carried it over again tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox kicked off their visit to Turner Field with a
thorough dismantling of Tom Glavine Monday night. The hitters were
told to go the other way, and they did as they were told. They
didn't go for his teases in the dirt, either. They made Glavine
come to them, at least insofar as the crafty lefthander will ever
come to anybody. Glavine has made a living out of never giving in
to batters. Even on 3-and-0, he will concede nothing. More often
than not, he will win the battle of the wills. Monday night was a
rare exception.
</P>
<P>
   Equally inspiring was the pitching of Derek Lowe and the
accompanying pitch-calling of Jason Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason did a great job of concentrating and executing the game
plan,'' lauded pitching coach Joe Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth inning? You know, it wasn't even that bad. Gordon took
the shovel out and placed himself in the ground with a pair of
walks, and that set the tone. All season long, he has pounced on
guys. We haven't had that Heathcliff Slocumb Perils of Pauline
stuff. Gordon normally comes in and starts everyone out 0-and-2,
1-and-2. He goes 1-2-3 and you don't even have to sweat out last
call. Monday was different. Monday was aberrational.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Braves weren't exactly bashing the ball around
the lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a couple of chinks here and there,'' said Bragg.
``They did in the ninth what we've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are playing as if they wouldn't mind settling in
here for a spell. We still haven't had a concentrated stretch of
good baseball weather in Boston, but the last two nights here have
been ideal. It was in the mid-70s Monday, and Tuesday was just a
flat-out great night to play baseball. It was warm, with just a
hint of humidity. It felt the way a baseball park should feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect baseball weather,'' agreed Bragg. ``It allows you to
work up a good sweat so you get nice and loose. Perfect baseball
weather. Exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a team that has just built a nice 7-1 lead en route
to a 9-3 victory ought to be in a good mood. And a manager whose
reconstructed second starter has just won his third straight game
following a team loss ought to be grateful for the presence of a
stopper.
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming he actually knew that he had a stopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, you're educating me,'' said the ever affable Jimy
Williams. ``I didn't realize that. All I know is that his last
three starts have been outstanding. His arm is free, he's throwing
nice breaking balls, and he's working both sides of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams could have sat around and talked about all the good
things he saw, starting with Saberhagen's performance, Bragg's
tone-setting triple in the first, and the great diving stop Mike
Benjamin made in the seventh to take away a hit from Walt Weiss. He
knows better than to gloat. There's another game tonight. And then
another. And another.
</P>
<P>
   I guarantee you that Williams would back up Darren Bragg. When
it comes to figuring out what might happen tonight, yesterday
doesn't mean anything. But at least Jimy knows in his heart and
mind that his team does know how to play this game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
