<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-WHALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMPBACKS EXTEND USUAL VISIT OFF COAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DON HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE VANGUARD _ Beyond the confines of land, 22 miles past
the breakwater at Ventura, the 68-foot Vanguard eases toward a pair
of adult humpback whales.
</P>
<P>
   The ship's engines quiet. Chamber music plays. All eyes on board
scan the surface of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, an enormous mass approaches the boat from below and
rises to the surface. Its dual blowholes send a misty plume of
foul-smelling breath into the air.
</P>
<P>
   In an oddly graceful move for a creature its size, the whale
arcs its back to display its tell-tale hump. Then it dives under
the boat for a better, sonar-view of the curious vessel of
landlubbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you, they like Vivaldi,'' quipped the ship's captain,
Glen Galbraith, a veteran of the whale-watching business who is
armed with a ready supply of one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-ton, 40-foot whale swims from one side of the ship to the
other, perhaps a dozen times, as a crowd of usually jaded
journalists scramble like excited children to watch this
spectacular animal do nothing more than look back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's studying us as much as we're studying him,'' Galbraith
said. ``This whale is actually playing with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The humpbacks have returned to the Santa Barbara Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the gray whales that pass by the California Coast twice
each year, these humpbacks are here to hang out a while.
</P>
<P>
   And this year, the krill and plankton that the whales crave are
closer to the mainland, says Jacob Emmons, a naturalist for Island
Packers, a Ventura charter company specializing in whale-watching
and nature tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big spring plankton bloom, so that's why they're
here,'' said Emmons, who never ceases to be awed by the animals.
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite clear what accounts for the bumper crop of sea
life. Some suspect that winter's rainstorms washed fertilizer-rich
runoff, on which plankton and krill feed, into the sea. Others
think the whales are simply becoming more accustomed to people and
are venturing closer to shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It approached us and made contact with us. That's pretty
special,'' said Emmons, still awestruck, 10 minutes after getting
up close and personal with the curious humpback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it puts (life) in perspective, to look at a majestic
whale,'' he continued. ``It's kind of an honor to feel so
insignificant in the presence of such a majestic animal. It makes
you re-evaluate who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Once thought to have numbered 100,000, the humpbacks almost have
been hunted into extinction. After receiving worldwide protection
in 1966, their numbers have slowly increased. Today, the humpback
population is estimated at 10,000 to 12,000, according to the
National Parks Service, which manages the Channel Islands National
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like year after year we see more humpback whales,''
said Galbraith. ``The first 10 years I ran boats in the channel, I
saw one blue whale. Now, it's not that uncommon. And the gray
whales are almost guaranteed. We know where they go and it's almost
become that way with the humpbacks and blue whales.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the whales started returning to feeding grounds
north of Santa Rosa Island, some 45 miles southwest of Ventura.
This year, some of the first humpbacks were spotted about a week
ago _ and much closer to shore. By the end of the month, the
population is expected to once again jump to last year's level of
nearly 300 humpbacks.
</P>
<P>
   A pod of 50 blue whales, the largest living animal to inhabit
the planet, was spotted recently heading up the coast from San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 0104EDT &QL; 
