<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-REDWINGS-CAPITALS     06-10 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS WIN LACKLUSTER STANLEY CUP OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
 WINGS-CAPITALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Hockey's shining moment lacked something in luster
Tuesday night. The Red Wings and Capitals, the best and brightest
of the Original 26, spent the better part of 60 minutes looking
like 40 characters in search of a play.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it looked more like a dress rehearsal than an
Opening Night sensation.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Hockey Town, no one was arguing the final outcome:
Red Wings 2, Capitals 1. The Red Wings, before a sellout crowd of
19,983 at Joe Louis Arena, inched one win closer to their second
Stanley Cup in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk all you want, but now you see what it's all
about,'' said Detroit coach Scotty Bowman, who cautioned earlier in
the day not to get caught up in the hype that had his club easily
repeating as the champ. ``I thought Washington played very well for
being in the finals for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, it was a night when neither club's most skilled players
did much to figure in the outcome. The Wings scored their two goals
in a span of 2:14 of the first period, Joey Kocur and Nicklas
Lidstrom taking advantage of some sloppy play by the Capitals.
Richard Zednik, the 249th pick in the '94 draft, scored
Washington's lone goal with 4:03 left in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Noticeable nonfactors for the Capitals: Adam Oates, Sergei
Gonchar, Brian Bellows, and Peter Bondra. For the Wings, superstar
Sergei Fedorov was anything but a key component and Brendan
Shanahan again went 0-0_0. The bedeviled power forward has gone
nine consecutive games without a point, his longest drought in a
decade. This spell is generating rumors that he is injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought the first 10 minutes we played quite
well,'' said Washington coach Ron Wilson. ``There were just a
couple of shifts there when our first and second lines got
outplayed by their third and fourth lines _ we got a little casual
with the puck, a little lackadaisical _ and they made us pay.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate cost was a Kocur goal with 14:04 gone in the
first. The noted tough guy raced to the crease and provided a
redirect to a Doug Brown feed after Tomas Holmstrom made the key
play, forcing the puck into the zone off a turnover and getting
crunched at the blue line as he crossed into the offensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Next, with 3:42 to go before the break, Lidstrom fired in a
slapper with Holmstrom camped in front of goalie Olaf Kolzig. The
wide-shouldered Holmstrom didn't allow the Washington netminder a
glimpse of the steaming Lidstrom shot, a screening tactic the Wings
attempted to repeat over the course of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic in front of me,'' said Kolzig. ``There wasn't much I
could do. They're such a deep team, with so many guys with the
ability to put the puck in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wings finished with a lopsided 31-17 shot advantage. But
neither side had an abundance of true scoring chances (perhaps
seven for the Wings and five for the Capitals). It's execution,
skating, and passing that lead to good chances. But with the
skilled players either undermotivated or otherwise detained by
checkers, execution wasn't part of the act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hung in long enough and we started to believe,'' said
Wilson, who could be heard on the bench trying to provide an
emotional jump start for his squad. ``We could see they're a team
just like us. In the end, we lost, 2-1, but we don't feel we were
dominated, not by any stretch of the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman blamed himself, in part, for his Wings' tepid play,
especially in the second period when Zednik cut it to 2-1. He
didn't like his line combinations. He felt his players may have
been confused by his pairings and matchups. Not a good night, said
the man who has coached no fewer than seven Cup champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I had a good game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even on an off night, the Wings stayed on course. What
mattered most, perhaps, was that their netminder, Chris Osgood,
didn't allow one of the long, soft goals that have plagued him in
the playoffs. Kolzig also looked sharp. On a night when everything
around them was shaky, they stood secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at his record,'' said Bowman, referring to Osgood,
who is playing in his first finals. ``It speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   One act finished. It can only get better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
