u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOMO-BOS &LR;      06-10 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOMOMANINA COMES TO NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His new home is 3,000 miles east of sunny California.
But Hideo Nomo might as well be back in Japan pitching in the Tokyo
Dome. It feels the same: fun.
</P>
<P>
   In Nomo's debut as a New York Met Tuesday night, Shea Stadium
was a jukebox that held 30,336 fans, most of them used to the din
of rock music and low-flying jets. Noise _ the kind you expect to
hear at a Knicks game in Madison Square Garden _ stung the ears.
The joint was jumping as he took the mound against the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``No-mo, No-mo!'' was the chant from the crowd and on the huge
video screen after every one of his five strikeouts. He didn't get
a victory _ Tampa Bay won, 5-4, in 11 innings _ but Nomo had to be
uplifted by his reception.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo was far from perfect; the former Dodger hadn't pitched in
10 days. Ahead, 4-3, in the fifth, Nomo balked in a run. He broke
his hands winding up, then stepped off the mound. Sound familiar?
(Tim Wakefield would have protested this one, too.)
</P>
<P>
   He left after five innings with the score tied, 4-4. Nomo gave
up five hits and walked three. Five New York pitchers followed him,
but they couldn't prevent the Devil Rays from spoiling the party in
extras.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fresh beginning,'' said Nomo. ``The players on our
bench haven't had a chance to see me too much. I want them to have
confidence in my pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All things considered, I liked what I saw,'' said Mets manager
Bobby Valentine. ``But there is room for improvement, that's for
sure. He's had a long rest, but the health is there, and that's
good. Without the balk, it's 4-3 and we win in regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning run scored on Quinton McCracken's sacrifice fly in
the 11th, after the Mets had the potential go-ahead run thrown out
at the plate in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But on this night, the game details were secondary. Nomo took
his place in a baseball setting that has been starved for a
prime-time pitcher since the days of David Cone, Bret Saberhagen,
and Doc Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   Mets fans prefer to think of Nomo as the pitcher who was
National League Rookie of the Year in 1995 and compiled a 43-29
record over the last three-plus seasons _ not the disgruntled 2-7
hurler who asked for and received a trade out of Los Angeles
Thursday. Maybe now the New York papers will take notice of the
other team in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like this is my first start,'' said Nomo. ``You have
to look at this long-term. I'm a little disappointed. We didn't win
the game. I need to improve my control.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Nomo is new in town, he is not lacking for acquaintances
in the Mets clubhouse. He and Masato Yoshii pitched for the
Kintetsu Buffaloes from 1990-94 before Nomo found a loophole in his
contract and left as a free agent. Valentine used to manage Chiba
Lotte of the Japan League. And Nomo's catcher with the Dodgers,
Mike Piazza, was acquired by the Mets recently after being traded
to the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with my new teammates,'' said Nomo. ``This is a very
good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomo is used to pressure; he has been under scrutiny since
coming to the majors, not only from the media hordes but from his
homeland. And now he's on the biggest stage of all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
