u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARGENTINA-VIDELA-NYT &LR;      06-10 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-VIDELA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRESIDENT FACES POSSIBLE KIDNAPPING CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ Former President Jorge Rafael Videla,
who had previously been pardoned for his role in the disappearances
of thousands of political dissidents from 1976 to 1983, was
detained on Tuesday and could face charges of child kidnapping, the
government announced.
</P>
<P>
   The junta leader was detained late in the day on orders from a
federal judge after several parents of children missing from the
``dirty war'' brought complaints against the 71-year-old retired
general, accusing him of having ordered the kidnappings of children
and then offering them for adoption to military families.
</P>
<P>
   The detention was a stunning surprise and promised to open an
additional chapter in a long-running battle between human rights
officials and the administration of President Carlos Saul Menem,
who has said he believes that the nation should move beyond the
sordid history of the military juntas.
</P>
<P>
   The army chief was sentenced to life in prison in 1987 for human
rights abuses that occurred during his dictatorship. He served
several years before Menem pardoned him in 1990. In an apparent
tradeoff, Menem was then able to cut the military budget as one
means of tackling the overspending and hyperinflation afflicting
the country at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Videla could face charges of stealing children and having them
illegally adopted under his rule, according to a court spokesman,
who added that he could serve 3 to 25 years in prison if convicted.
A total of five children whose parents disappeared after having
been kidnapped by military death squads were illegally adopted, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Detention under Argentine law is short of an arrest. Videla
faces several legal proceedings before he would actually be
arrested and face formal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the children whom he is accused of stealing were
apparently born in secret prisons around Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   At least 15,000 people were killed and ``disappeared'' in the
so-called dirty war against guerrillas and suspected leftists.
Human rights officials say up to 30,000 people were killed under a
series of military juntas.
</P>
<P>
   The police took Videla from his house on Tuesday night for
questioning by Federal Judge Roberto Marquevich in connection with
accusations of ``illegal appropriation of minors,'' according to
television reports.
</P>
<P>
   Abel Madariaga, the husband of a woman who disappeared in 1977
when she was four months pregnant, said in a television interview
that he always knew from witnesses' reports that his wife had given
birth to a boy while in custody at the Campo de Mayo military base
outside Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that my son was given away like many others,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
