<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-BUHNER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUHNER ADMITS NERVOUSNESS IN CLASS AAA REHAB ASSIGNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ Jay Buhner rolled into Cheney Stadium Tuesday
with all the trappings of a big-leaguer. The $75,000 black Hummer.
The personalized bats. The Kingdome clubhouse attendant in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Mariner right fielder, on a two-day rehab assignment to
test his surgically repaired left knee, was an easy fit with the
Class AAA Tacoma Rainiers. He sat and joked with his newfound
teammates. He brought food.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, Buhner, in these lesser surroundings, let people
know he wasn't too good for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm nervous, no doubt about it,'' he said before taking the
field against the New Orleans Zephyrs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really nervous. I'm sure it will be that way every at-bat.
The thing I'm nervous about is nobody wants to embarrass himself.
And I haven't slid yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner started in right field, batted fifth and played six
innings at Cheney Stadium in his first game in nearly two months.
He will play another for the Rainiers tonight, then fly to Oakland
tomorrow morning and rejoin the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   With his Seattle club fading fast, the 33-year-old slugger says
he has been reluctant to speak out. Even now, he won't criticize
anyone. But he is a realist about the damage done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't point fingers,'' he said. ``It takes a team, and
we've been losing as a team. It's come to a head right now. No
doubt there's some frustration in the clubhouse. It's going to be
extremely tough to fight back from where we are. We've dug a hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what anybody's going to do. Anything could happen.
That's ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner's appearance Tuesday was well received. The paid
attendance was more than double the 3,600 average. Gates were
opened at 4:30 p.m. rather than 6 to allow fans to watch the celeb
take batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   The bald one didn't disappoint, driving six of his 23 pitches
out of the ballpark. Two hit the scoreboard in left-center, one
slamming off the top of it, well over 400 feet away. Another struck
a light standard. Rainier players witnessing these feats could only
giggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see that?'' center fielder Shane Monahan asked
excitedly after Buhner's most pronounced scoreboard blast. ``That
was the hardest ball I've ever seen hit. It took the ``s'' off
Rainiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner had a corner locker awaiting him, complete with nameplate
and a new number (49). He ended up wearing his own Mariner jersey
(19) after Rainiers first baseman Randy Jorgenson volunteered to
wear something other than his normal digits.
</P>
<P>
   After backing his Hummer into a parking spot, Buhner was greeted
by seven autograph hounds and Kevin Kalal, the Rainiers' director
of baseball operations. His equipment already was stored in a
locker, compliments of Mariner clubhouse attendant Jam Spears.
Unfortunately, Buhner's batting helmet was left behind, forcing the
attendant to make an unscheduled 70-mile round trip in rush-hour
traffic to retrieve it.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner spent considerable time in the training room before
joining the other Rainiers in the clubhouse. They talked fishing,
his brother (a Mariner farmhand in Memphis) and Mariner troubles.
</P>
<P>
   He borrowed chewing tobacco from Raul Ibanez. He met with
Rainiers manager Dave Myers. He was scolded by coach Dave Brundage
for coming out late for stretching exercises.
</P>
<P>
   During BP, Buhner's cuts were so vicious he knocked the batting
cage supports loose with a foul ball. The contraption had to be
pulled down and put back together, delaying things.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner met with reporters for 20 minutes, signed autographs for
fans for another 20. He is noticeably bigger, having added 10
pounds of muscle, increasing his weight to 236. He says his health
is 85 percent and doesn't expect to be at full capacity the rest of
the summer. He is mulling right knee surgery in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   He said and did all the right things as he spent his first day
in the minors in nine years. Cheney Stadium even got a compliment.
With grass, not Astroturf, you know that had to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ```This place is really nice, nicer than some of the places
we've played in the big leagues,'' Buhner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
