</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S OWNERSHIP A LITTLE UNKEMPT FOR COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What a bad time to invite fellow owners to town.
</P>
<P>
   The place is a mess, the kids are being bad, there's no cash to
party.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for the fact that the lords of baseball are
themselves unzipped and zipless, they could spend their quarterly
meeting at the Four Seasons Olympic Hotel this week mocking
Mariners ownership (motto: ``We're Not the Florida Marlins!'').
</P>
<P>
   These business meetings follow uncomfortably upon the fumes of
the Randy Johnson trade stink, in which a week of speculation about
the fate of one of the game's most glamorous players ended in
national embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   When ownership got cold feet and pulled out of the trade,
leaving Johnson, vice president of baseball operations Woody
Woodward and manager Lou Piniella with varying degrees of fury,
annoyance and humiliation _ to say nothing of the Los Angeles
Dodgers, for whom it will be years before they deal again with the
Mariners _ it also provided a rare glimpse of ownership's disunity
and lack of vision.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the Johnson debacle, which has been a runaway
truck for nearly a year, is money, not relief pitchers or left
fielders. And the heart of the money issue is not Johnson, but the
new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one will admit it officially, the new insurance yard
is about to become a massive money pit for ownership.
</P>
<P>
   With its $25 million contingency fund already spent on the easy
part of the project that's little more than half done, the stadium
will end up so far over its $417 million budgeted cost that
knowledgeable King County employees have estimated the ownership
will be on the hook for $70 million to $100 million in cost
overruns for the most expensive ballpark in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   You might recall about the only thing that worked in the
public's favor in the legislative capitulation over the stadium
financing was a cap on the public's contribution at $336 million.
The owners agreed to absorb all cost overruns, and recently
reiterated their intent to stick to those terms.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they had a choice. As one county staffer put it, ``They
wouldn't get one foot inside the door before getting thrown out.''
</P>
<P>
   A major extra expense for the stadium has been change orders,
the result of designing a stadium while it goes up. Ownership's
insistence on a July 1999 opening has created such a construction
rush that much is being built on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership was so aghast at the overrun projections that it
recently conducted a private audit of the Public Facilities
District that oversees the project. Although the results were not
shared, the Mariners have not yet publicly screamed, ``Ripoff!''
But with these guys, never say never.
</P>
<P>
   The consequence for the team on the field was that no further
investments would be made, since ownership already was claiming red
ink in annual operations.
</P>
<P>
   As it always has been with this ownership, every capital call
requires that at least some of the owners sell some of their
Microsoft stock, which because of its historic rapid increase in
value is considered at least double money. And their share of the
ballpark's cost will have to be paid mostly by the end of
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Nintendo's Japanese investors have reason to want
out. The company's fortunes have sagged not only with the imploding
Japanese economy but with the American success of its rival, Sega.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft's Chris Larson decides to buy out his Japanese
partners, he will need either lots of cash or new investors. But
the summer of 1998 is a wretched time to be attracting new partners
to the Mariners, since the ballpark expenses are uncapped and the
income stream from luxury suites and seat licenses is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The result is paralysis that stymied the Johnson trade. Some
owners don't want to pay Johnson market value, yet they don't want
to squander a franchise asset, as they have done several times in
recent seasons. Aware of the bind, other baseball people figured to
pillage a franchise under duress.
</P>
<P>
   So, rather than risk yet another personnel mistake, ownership
lost its guts and did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with getting nothing for Johnson is that
there is no other player who has value that would be worth trading
to fix any one of the Mariners' numerous shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Getting no fixes not only risks seasonal disaster, it begets a
bigger problem _ diminished sales for a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The rule of thumb among marketers of new sports stadiums and
arenas is that there is one chance to do it right: the first time.
If the Mariners swing from 90 wins last year to 90 losses this
season, which is entirely possible given the mess ownership has
made of Johnson, momentum for the new park will be damaged in spite
of the novelty of outdoor baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders owner Al Davis' marketing disaster with the remodeled
Oakland Coliseum is a stinging example of how not to sell expensive
seats for new digs. The Raiders will take years to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Caught between two massive expenses of team payroll and a new
stadium, paralyzed by lack of unanimity and vision, the Mariner
ownership sits inert, holding on to the chair for dear life.
</P>
<P>
   So feel free, visiting owners, to walk off with the silverware.
Nobody will stop you.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 0204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
