r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     06-10 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It seems hard to believe that less than three
weeks ago, Chan Ho Park sat crunched in his locker, doubting his
fastball and his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Since lasting just two innings that night in Arizona, Park has
regained the form that made him one of the National League's top
young right-handers. For the Dodgers it could not have come at a
better time.
</P>
<P>
   With struggling Oakland and Colorado on the schedule during this
very winnable six-game homestand, Park won Tuesday night for the
first time since May 13 with an overpowering 5-1 victory over the
A's in front of 46,244 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't gain them a game in the standings since the San
Francisco Giants won their 11th straight, but after losing Monday
to the last place A's, the Dodgers were in a good mood again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of confidence tonight,'' said Park, who retired
the first 10 A's he faced. ``My inside fastballs were good. I had a
fever yesterday and I was aching all over, but I feel great
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Dodgers are expected to lose Eric Young, the
major-league leader with 26 stolen bases, for a few days after he
aggravated a thigh injury, Park's performance made the night almost
seamless.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched eight innings and allowed just one run, a
fifth-inning homer to former teammate Mike Blowers. But the Dodgers
already led 5-0 at that point and hardly seemed phased.
</P>
<P>
   Park's success on Tuesday stemmed from his fastball, a pitch he
once believed would not get him through the tough spots. The
Dodgers also have had that problem with tonight's starter Ismael
Valdes and saw it Saturday with their new fifth starter Dave
Mlicki.
</P>
<P>
   But Park, who struck out six and did not walk a batter, no
longer qualifies. The only help he needed was a 1-2-3 ninth from
Scott Radinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give Park a lot of credit, he pitched a heck of
a game,'' A's manager Art Howe said. ``He's got a good arm, a very
good arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Monday night, when they never recovered after trailing
3-0 in the first, the Dodgers took advantage of Oakland mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Young opened the bottom of the first with a single against
right-hander Jimmy Haynes (4-3) and went to second when Scott
Spiezio misplayed Jose Vizcaino's grounder to the right side.
</P>
<P>
   Young rounded the bag but aggravated his strained right thigh
diving back. He scored on a passed ball but walked gingerly off the
field.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers added two more runs when Raul Mondesi walked, stole
second and came around to score when catcher Mike Macfarlane's
throw sailed into center. Vizcaino also scored on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Young singled again in the second, but Juan Castro took over at
second to begin the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Young missed three games after injuring the thigh in Chicago on
May 21 but returned to have a nine-game hitting streak and is
batting .372 (22 for 59) in 15 games since his return.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes, who lasted just four innings, issued walks to Bobby
Bonilla in the second and Charles Johnson in the fourth, and both
came around to score.
</P>
<P>
   That was more than enough for Park, who had a no decision in
last Thursday's 3-2 Dodgers victory against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   In the start before that, he went eight innings in a game the
Dodgers lost 8-4 in 12 innings. That was the nightmare when Park
left after eight leading 4-2, but Scott Radinsky blew the lead in
the ninth and Dennis Rayes gave up five consecutive hits in the
12th.
</P>
<P>
   But it also was a turning point.
</P>
<P>
   Park rarely faced adversity during his breakout 1997 season,
when he went 8-1 in July and August on his way to a 14-victory
season.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, he came out of three games with a sore
lower back, but Tuesday that was not a problem. He winced in pain
when making a pitch to Macfarlane in the fifth. Even when he left
after eight, he held his back, but that was due more to the cold.
He even singled in the fourth, one of the ways he injured his back
earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did what we asked tonight,'' manager Bill Russell said.
``He gave us innings and all of them were good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
