<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2049 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BICKLEY-JORDAN-AZ     06-10 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BICKLEY-JORDAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN'S WILL TO WIN SAVING BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The gerbil of a general manager craves equal billing.
The coach finds the secret of success while meditating in a tepee.
The tattooed goofball flies to Detroit, stealing the spotlight
while hanging out with Hulk Hogan. And the impending breakup
staggers along like a bad soap opera because the owner is gorged on
championships.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, they forget the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these banners, all the rings,'' Steve Kerr said. ``Nobody
would have any of this if not for Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   Something has changed in this title bout, one that started out
as Ali-Frazier and digressed into Tyson-McNeeley. The Jazz, which
appeared ready to take the final step after gutting out a Game 1
victory, has turned to mush. The Bulls, who appeared ready for the
rocking chair and a long nap, should be tested for Viagra. The
series has tilted like a cheap pinball machine, and all because of
one man.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bulls crossed the previous finish line in a wheelchair,
eking by the Pacers, Jordan admitted the swagger was gone. After
losing the opener, there weren't enough knives to accommodate all
the back stabbing. Sensing the end was near, Jordan simply changed
the tone of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to practice the next morning laughing and joking,''
Kerr said. ``The only time in three years I've seen him do that
after a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   So while the Jazz started gagging on its own desire, the Bulls
were liberated by their leader. The results are undeniable. And
while the Jazz can climb back into the series with a victory
tonight, the mental edge is clearly in the other corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they take us seriously at all,'' Karl Malone
said. &QL;  &QL; 
Jackson losing credibility &QL;  &QL; 
This stunning transformation has little to do with Bulls Coach Phil
Jackson, whose mystique has taken a major hit in the past few
weeks. On Tuesday, he was again preaching his spin, coddling Dennis
Rodman at the expense of his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Rodman blew off practice, hung up on his coach, holed
up at Hooters, then bolted for an appearance on WCW's ``Monday
Nitro.'' It is an embarrassment to authority, an insult to the
dignity Jordan has infused into the organization, a slap at the
sanctity of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I wouldn't have him,'' Jazz Coach Jerry Sloan
said. ``Everybody knows what he's all about. Winning has never been
that important to him. I'd just as soon lose if I had to be put in
that situation. When that's more important than the game itself,
we've just lost the whole reason for being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman didn't explain his need to collect a quick appearance
fee, instead indicting Malone as an ``awkward player,'' an
``average player.'' But he did express a desire to get this thing
over quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life just goes to complete hell when I go to Utah,'' Rodman
said. ``That means I have to revert to going to Las Vegas or
somewhere to get my excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   Idiot. &QL;  &QL; 
Sold his soul &QL;  &QL; 
If Jackson had any guts, he would bench Rodman, if not drop him
from the roster altogether. As much as Jackson claims he is working
his Buddhist magic to keep Rodman productive, he has sold his soul
for a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sleeping in a nest that we helped to build,'' a
disgusted Luc Longley said. ``Our acceptance of him and our
tolerance of him perpetuated the myth.''
</P>
<P>
   As well as exposing Jackson's. Really, now. How many games would
Zen be worth if Big Chief Triangle was coaching the Denver Nuggets?
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the full-court brilliance of Scottie Pippen, there
would be nothing without Jordan. Jackson wouldn't be assured a
place in the Hall of Fame. The owner wouldn't have a palatial
stadium. The general manager wouldn't foolishly place himself next
to Red Auerbach. The Bulls wouldn't overcome the odds and the
oddballs to where they are two wins from another shipment of rings.
</P>
<P>
   No man has ever made more money for others, bloated so many egos
or defied defeat with such vengeance. And it's never been more
apparent than now. &QL;  &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
