<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-BUHNER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' BUHNER BEGINS CLASS AAA REHAB ASSIGNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Updates with completion of game.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ Jay Buhner rolled into Cheney Stadium Tuesday
with all the trappings of a big-leaguer. The $75,000 black Hummer.
The personalized bats. The Kingdome clubhouse attendant in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Mariner right fielder, on a two-day rehab assignment to
test his surgically repaired left knee, was an easy fit with the
Class AAA Tacoma Rainiers. He sat and joked with his newfound
teammates. He brought food.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, Buhner, in these lesser surroundings, let people
know he wasn't too good for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm nervous, no doubt about it,'' he said before taking the
field against the New Orleans Zephyrs. ``I'm really nervous. I'm
sure it will be that way every at-bat. The thing I'm nervous about
is nobody wants to embarrass himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner did none of that at Cheney Stadium, doubling down the
third-base line on the first pitch sent his way and going 1-for-2
with a walk in his first game in nearly two months. He will play
again for the Rainiers tonight, then fly to Oakland tomorrow
morning and rejoin the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in right and batting fifth, the 33-year-old slugger
went six innings and came away a little sore but satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt fine. No problem,'' said Buhner, who slid into second
on his hit without hesitation. ``I didn't think about it. I saw it
was going to be a close play and I didn't want to get thrown out.
... It just feels good to get back in the swing of things.''
</P>
<P>
   While his fortunes were improving, the Mariners were losing
another in San Francisco. The club's emotional leader, Buhner won't
criticize his teammates, but he is a realist about the damage done.
He fears nasty repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't point fingers,'' he said. ``It takes a team, and
we've been losing as a team. It's come to a head right now. No
doubt there's some frustration in the clubhouse. It's going to be
extremely tough to fight back from where we are. We've dug a hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what anybody's going to do. That's ownership.
Anything could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner's appearance Tuesday was well received in Seattle's
sister city to the south. The paid attendance was more than double
the 3,600 average. Gates opened at 4:30 p.m. rather than 6 to allow
fans to watch the celeb take batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   The bald one didn't disappoint, driving six of his 23 pitches
out of the ballpark. Two hit the scoreboard in left-center, one
slamming off the top of it, well over 400 feet away. Another struck
a light standard. Rainier players witnessing these feats could only
giggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see that?'' center fielder Shane Monahan asked
excitedly after Buhner's most pronounced scoreboard blast. ``That
was the hardest ball I've ever seen hit. It took the ``s'' off
Rainiers.''
</P>
<P>
   After parking his Hummer to begin this adventure, Buhner was
greeted by seven autograph hounds and Kevin Kalal, the Rainiers'
director of baseball operations. His equipment already had beat him
there, compliments of Mariner clubhouse attendant Jam Spears.
Unfortunately, Buhner's batting helmet was left behind, forcing the
attendant to make an unscheduled 70-mile round trip in rush-hour
traffic to retrieve it.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner had a corner locker awaiting him at Cheney, complete with
nameplate and a new number (49). He ended up wearing his own
Mariner jersey (19) after first baseman Randy Jorgenson, who
normally wears that shirt for the Rainiers, volunteered to switch
to something else.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner spent considerable time in the training room before
joining the other Rainiers. They talked fishing, his brother (a
Mariner farmhand in Memphis) and Mariner troubles. He borrowed
chewing tobacco from Raul Ibanez. He talked privately with Rainiers
manager Dave Myers. He was scolded by coach Dave Brundage for
coming out late for stretching exercises.
</P>
<P>
   During BP, Buhner's cuts were so vicious, he knocked the batting
cage supports loose with a foul ball. The contraption had to be
pulled down and put back together, delaying the pregame activity.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner met with reporters for 20 minutes, signed autographs for
fans for another 20. He is noticeably bigger, having added 10
pounds of muscle, increasing his weight to 236. He says his health
is 85 percent and doesn't expect it to be at full capacity the rest
of the summer. He is mulling right knee surgery for the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   He said and did all the right things as he spent his first day
in the minors in nine years. Cheney Stadium even got a compliment.
With grass, not Astroturf, that was automatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is really nice, nicer than some of the places we've
played in the big leagues,'' Buhner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
