r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-WNBA-INTERNATIONA     06-10 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-INTERNATIONAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY, WNBA GO INTERNATIONAL IN TALENT SEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The moment the Mercury's raiding of the international basketball
arc crossed from real to surreal was when the team drafted 6-foot-8
Russian teenager Maria Stepanova. . . .
</P>
<P>
   . . . and was introduced to her agent Boris Leichitski and his
assistant Natasha.
</P>
<P>
   Can Moose and Squirrel be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   For that humor to be understood at Mercury practice, however, it
first requires an explanation of Rocky and Bullwinkle in French,
Japanese and Russian, providing interpreters can first grasp the
concept. Now you begin to see why some WNBA teams dip no deeper
into the international market than English-speaking players out of
U.S. colleges.
</P>
<P>
   With the league assignment of its first player, Australian point
guard Michele Timms, in January 1997, the Mercury plunged into
worldwide talent scouting. The team could begin its second season
Thursday with more than half the roster born outside the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Final cuts are due today, but the 11-woman squad is certain to
include returners Timms and Marlies Askamp of Germany and first-
and second-round draft picks Stepanova and Andrea Kuklova of
Slovakia. On the bubble are returner Mikiko Hagiwara of Japan and
Kristi Harrower and Michelle Griffiths of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other nine WNBA teams, only the expansion Detroit Shock
is anywhere close to the Mercury in international numbers with
three Australians, a Bulgarian, a Bosnian and a Croatian. Detroit
also put in a claim Monday on forward Natalia Zassoulskaya, whose
20 points and 9 rebounds almost carried Russia past the United
States in the World Championships gold-medal game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Shock's multi-cultural mix pales in comparison to the
Mercury's because the Bulgarian and Croatian speak English, and the
Bosnian can converse with the Croatian and in Italian with one of
the Americans. Zassoulskaya, if she goes to the Shock, would need
an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury huddles will be more like the United Nations, with
Boutros Boutros (aka Cheryl) Miller serving as secretary-general as
much as coach-general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's not about international-American, it's getting the
best players,'' said Seth Sulka, Mercury vice president-operations.
``The only thing you have to be careful about is does that bring a
language barrier, does that bring other cultural barriers and does
it give you the best player as a package? Maybe you get the best
skills, but the package isn't as good. That has to be evaluated
case by case.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the parent NBA, the WNBA thinks globally, not only for
marketing reasons but because there was no domestic women's
basketball between 1984 and '97. ``To have the best basketball
league in the world meant to have the best basketball players from
the world,'' Sulka said.
</P>
<P>
   That approach, combined with the American Basketball League's
early dominance in signing U.S. collegians, attracted a core group
of 15 international players that will almost double this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like having the international players in our league, and
they add a lot to the quality of competition,'' said WNBA President
Val Ackerman. ``We think it has helped make us more attractive to
the rest of the world in terms of fans and international broadcast
alliances.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem Capital Sports, for example, recently agreed to a
two-year contract to televise some 70 NBA and 20 WNBA games per
season. Israel is among 140 countries receiving WNBA games and/or
highlights show. Many of those countries have pro women's leagues
that have financially supported American players for years.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA stars, most of whom top out at $62,000 in salary, can go
overseas and make up to six figures for the other eight months of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact we have so many international players says they're
like the Americans, they see the carrot dangling in front of them
and want to play in a league such as ours,'' said Shock
Coach-General Manager Nancy Lieberman-Cline. ``I know Ticha
Penecheiro (Sacramento's Portguese point guard). Her parents are
going to be able to see her play (on TV). That would be very
appealing to me as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman-Cline played for the Mercury last season and saw the
impact of Timms, not only on the court but in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Because Timms knew the 6-foot-5 Askamp through two seasons as
teammates in the German League, Miller went unexplainably small in
the first WNBA draft, then pulled Askamp out of the hat before
training camp. And when Sacramento gave up on Hagiwara and
considered cutting the 1996 Olympian, the Mercury pulled the first
WNBA trade largely on Timms' recommendation of Hagiwara, who three
times scored 20 points or more against the United States during
international games this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mercury has an Australian assistant coach, Carrie Graf,
and is considering Harrower, who backed up Timms at the recent
World Championships, and Griffiths. It used its first two draft
picks on Stepanova and Kuklova even though the collegiate talent
was ample after the WNBA convincingly beat the ABL in round 2 of
bidding on seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Kuklova speaks what Sulka calls survival English and mostly
communicates through a French interpreter. English is one of
Askamp's three languages, but Russian and Japanese translators are
being hired for Stepanova and Hagiwara.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be pretty annoying on the bench,'' with Miller's
often colorful speeches flying in four tongues, All-WNBA center
Jennifer Gillom said. ``You're trying to concentrate on the game
and you hear all this blah, blah, blah. Sometimes it can be
distracting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury has been lucky with its first two interpreters.
</P>
<P>
   Yasuko Matsumoto had brought a youth basketball team from Himeji
City, Japan, to its sister city of Phoenix for a tournament and
still was here on vacation when the trade for Hagiwara was made.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Guay, who has worked with Kuklova and French free agent
Odile Santaniello during training camp, is a French-Canadian who
came to the Valley to play basketball at Grand Canyon University,
where she met Carolyn Griffiths, now the Mercury trainer.
</P>
<P>
   The new Japanese interpreter is Kyoko Takahashi, an Arizona
State student with no basketball background who has lived in the
United States for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   When expenses for 15 road games are included, the interpreting
cost becomes a factor, Sulka said, especially when tripled. ``Then
there are the logistics. Are they behind the bench? Do they come
into a huddle? This stuff works fine in practice, but when you're
in the thick of a game, it's not as simple as the coach saying,
`Tell the player to run fast.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gillom, an 11-year overseas veteran, has mixed feelings about
the use of international players. Most overseas leagues limit the
number of foreigners to two per team, something she thinks the WNBA
should consider in order to cultivate young American talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may limit itself because of some of the logistical
issues,'' such as obtaining work visas, Ackerman said. ``As for
now, we welcome them, and most of all they have to be good enough
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman-Cline agrees. ``It's about competition,'' she said.
``If we as American players can't continue to work on our games and
be better, then I think the best players should play. That's the
way it works in any industry, and the way it should be in the
WNBA.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
