<HEADLINE>
WNBA TEAM BY-TEAM CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Charlotte Sting &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Coach: Marynell Meadors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Who's back: Vicky Bullett, 6-foot-3 C; Andrea Congreaves, 6-2
F-C; Sharon Manning, 6-3 C-F; Rhonda Mapp, 6-2 C-F; Andrea Stinson,
5-10 G; Tora Suber, 5-7 G. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Who's new: Sonja Chase, 5-9 G; Pollyana Johns, 6-2 C; Tracy
Reid, 5-11 F; Christy Smith, 5-7 G. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Why they're better: Because the athletic Reid fell to seventh
in the draft, the Sting gets better in transition and at the box
office. Reid was a two-time All-America at North Carolina, joining
an N.C. State-laden (Manning, Mapp, Stinson) roster. Smith steadies
the point guard position. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Where they'll finish: 1st East. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; New York Liberty &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Coach: Nancy Darsch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Who's back: Kisha Ford, 5-10 G-F; Kym Hampton, 6-2 C; Vicki
Johnson, 5-9 F; Rebecca Lobo, 6-4 F-C; Trena Trice, 6-2 F-C; Teresa
Weatherspoon, 5-8 G; Sue Wicks, 6-3 F; Sophia Witherspoon, 5-10 G. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Who's new: Albena Branzova, 6-3 F; Elisabeth Cebrian, 6-5 C;
Nadine Domond, 5-7 G; Vanessa Nygaard, 6-1 F (injured list); Alicia
Thompson, 6-1 F. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Why they're better: Even making the transition from power to
small forward, Texas Tech All-America Thompson was a steal at ninth
in the draft. The Liberty gets somewhat younger and adds depth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Where they'll finish: 2nd East. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Cleveland Rockers &QL;
