<HEADLINE>
SON MAY MAKE REUSS A DIA MONDBACKS FAN  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN, PEDRO GOMEZ  AND JIM GINTONIO  
  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former major league pitcher Jerry Reuss is a broadcaster for the
Anaheim Angels. He's also a very proud dad.
</P>
<P>
   Reuss' son was drafted in the 26th round by the Diamondbacks
last week. First baseman-outfielder Jason Reuss is senior at Canyon
High School in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about it,'' said Jerry Reuss, who had a 220-191
record that spanned 22 seasons. ``And I know he is thrilled beyond
belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason recently underwent knee surgery and won't play this
summer, which probably scared a few teams, ``but the rehab is going
great,'' Reuss said.
</P>
<P>
   Reuss said his son will meet with the Diamondbacks on Friday to
discuss a contract. Looking around Bank One Ballpark before Tuesday
night's game against Anaheim, Reuss said, ``If he were down here
looking at this ballpark, he would crawl to that pen and paper.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Field gets repairs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter commented before the game
how good the field looked. A lot of work was done during the club's
11-game trip, the most noticeable being large patches of sod that
replaced worn areas in the outfield, as well as in foul territory. &QL; 
 &QL; 
On the mend &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Jorge Fabregas, on the disabled list since May 31
because of a severely sprained right ankle, finished his
rehabilitation stint in Tucson and is scheduled to begin working
out with the Diamondbacks today. Fabregas is eligible to come off
the DL in time for Tuesday's game in Cincinnati but may not rejoin
the roster then. &QL; 
 &QL; 
No skipping &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wolcott, who pitched eight scoreless innings in his
Diamondbacks debut Friday night in Oakland, will start Thursday
night. Because of Monday's off day, Showalter contemplated skipping
Wolcott and keeping the other four starters on four days of rest. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mr. Irrelevant &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have another first to record: baseball's
initial Mr. Irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Gruner was the last pick _ No. 1,445 in the 50th round by
the Diamondbacks _ and the Irrelevant Club thinks that's pretty
special. So for the first time in the club's 23-year history, a
baseball nobody will join a football nobody as Mr. Irrelevant . . .
only Gruner is even more irrelevant because the last pick in the
football draft gets a bunch of neat stuff, and about all Gruner
gets is a free meal.
</P>
<P>
   Gruner, 18, is a high school catcher from Long Beach, Calif. His
football counterpart is tight end Cam Quayle of Weber State, who
was picked by Baltimore in the sixth round as the 241st selection. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Suspension begins &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim Manager Terry Collins began serving his eight-game
suspension Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Collins left his coaches, Joe Maddon, Larry Bowa and Marcel
Lachemann, to split the managing duties.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was suspended after the Angels and Kansas City had two
bench-clearing brawls during a game last week. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
