<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2069 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANGELS-DIAMONDBAC     06-10 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS SLAMMED  
 FIELDER'S BLAST GIVES ANGELS 9TH WIN IN ROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 11 games on the road, the Diamondbacks returned home
Tuesday night and gave Anaheim ace Chuck Finley his roughest
treatment in nearly a year. They turned a club-record four double
plays and were turned on by Yamil Benitez's first career grand
slam.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes more than that to beat these ascending Angels.
Cecil Fielder hit his own grand slam and drove in six runs, and
Anaheim won its ninth straight, 10-8, before 43,074 at Bank One
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We squandered eight runs against a good club and a good
pitcher,'' Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said. ``That's
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Showalter raved about the Angels, calling them
``one of the more well-rounded clubs,'' and about Anaheim first
baseman Darin Erstad in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erstad is one of my favorite players in the American League,''
Showalter said. ``I love watching him play.''
</P>
<P>
   Love hurts. Erstad went 5 for 5, scored three runs and drove in
the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't walk him (in the ninth), he might have had six
hits,'' Showalter said. ``I've always liked him. It's not just his
skill or his hitting ability, but how he goes about his business.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter had to stick around and watch, but not Angels Manager
Terry Collins, who began serving an eight-game suspension as a
result of last week's brawl with Kansas City. Collins wasn't far
away, however, watching the game on television at a downtown hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Live or on TV, Collins didn't like what the Diamondbacks did
early _ take the lead on Tony Batista's two-run home run off Finley
in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was Batista's second homer of the season, his first since
April 24. And the fun was just beginning. In the third inning with
runners on first and second, rookie first baseman Travis Lee
committed his first error of the season, a hard shot off his glove
that sailed directly to second baseman Batista. Pitcher Willie
Blair seemed to cover first in time for a play, but Batista didn't
throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see he was there,'' Batista said. ``I was a little
confused.''
</P>
<P>
   The bases were loaded for Fielder, who leaned his ample girth
into Blair's first pitch and sent it deep into the picnic area in
center field for his 11th career grand slam and a 4-2 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   That lasted as long as it took for Finley to walk Matt Williams,
Lee and Jay Bell in succession with one out in the bottom of the
third, and then give up Benitez's slam, a shot to right-center. The
Diamondbacks led, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the sixth time in major league history teams hit a
grand slam in the same inning.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Collins admitted he would be tense and said his
hotel room ``is going to have a chance to have a little damage in
it'' if the Angels ticked him off. He was presumably joking, but it
was easy to envision chairs and ice buckets flying at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez was coming off a two-hit, three-RBI game against Oakland
on Sunday that included a home run. Finley came in with a 6-2
record and a 2.22 ERA. He had not allowed more than one run in each
of his last four starts, and these were the most runs scored
against the lefthander since June 27, 1997, a span of 24 outings.
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't matter. The Angels scored a run in the fifth on
Garrett Anderson's single. In the sixth, Blair walked Norberto
Martin and came out for Clint Sodowsky. That didn't help. Sodowsky
walked Gary DiSarcina, and pinch hitter Orlando Palmiero hit a shot
that bounced off Sodowsky's right arm like a goalie making a save.
</P>
<P>
   But Sodowsky had trouble finding the ball in front of him. And
when he did, he threw it past Lee at first. Martin scored on the
error, and the score was tied at 6.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad put the Angels ahead with an RBI single, and another run
scored to make it 8-6 when Dave Hollins hit into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's bases-loaded single in the sixth made it 8-7. Bell also
had the bases full, but he flied out to deep right to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Fielder drove in two more runs in the eighth with a bases-loaded
single off newly-acquired Willie Banks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 0250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
