<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2071 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GOMEZ-D-BACKS-BEN     06-10 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-D-BACKS-BENITEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUE PROFESSIONAL' HAS BIG NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy being Yamil Benitez this season.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the Diamondbacks filled with anticipation, believing
the change in scenery from Kansas City would be the right tonic to
kick-start his big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   Two months into the 1998 season it would have been
understandable if Benitez had wanted to jump ship. Tuesday night's
game marked the first time Benitez had started consecutive games
since April 23-24.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was pulled during the top of the sixth inning as
part of a double-switch, Benitez drew more attention toward his
cause by slamming the first grand slam of his career and adding a
double and line-drive out to third base during his three at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   But with right-hander Ken Hill scheduled to start for Anaheim
tonight, it's probable that Benitez will find himself back on the
wooden bench inside the Diamondbacks dugout, a spot Benitez has
become very familiar with this season.
</P>
<P>
   But the impeccably dressed and coifed Benitez, 26, will never
say a negative word about his situation, preferring to always think
optimistically and positively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing good can come from griping about your situation,''
Benitez said recently. ``Plus, that's not the way I am. I always
think and hope for the best in any situation. That's not to say I'm
not frustrated at times. But I don't make the decisions. All I can
do is prepare myself to play every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Benitez, possibly the quietest player on the roster, is in a
precarious situation. When he was lifted during Tuesday night's
loss to Anaheim, it illustrated his role for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   After starting eight of the first 14 games of the season,
Benitez has been limited to a role where he is used sparingly. All
the while, he has drawn praise from Manager Buck Showalter for
showing amazing patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been an easy role for Yamil,'' Showalter said last
week. ``But he's handled it as well as anyone could possibly ask.
He's been a true professional.''
</P>
<P>
   In this day of players pouting if they are not used, Benitez is
a breath of fresh air. You will never hear Benitez moan like Boston
pitcher John Wasdin, who with an ERA over 5.00 at the time,
complained last week when the Red Sox sent him to Triple A
Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez, who is out of options and cannot be sent to the minors
without being exposed to the other 29 clubs, just wants a chance to
show what he can do.
</P>
<P>
   In his past two games he has shown plenty. During Sunday's
lopsided 12-4 victory over Oakland, Benitez slammed a home run to
lead off the third inning, pumping the Diamondbacks lead to 3-0 at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   He added a single and was later hit in the ribs with a fastball
from Athletics reliever Mike Fetters, a pitch that began the bad
blood that spilled between the two clubs later in the game.
</P>
<P>
   When Benitez was hit, several Diamondbacks on the bench rose to
the top steps of the dugout at the Oakland Coliseum, wanting to
protect their seldom-used outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen how many players wanted something to be
done right there and then,'' Showalter said. ``This is a guy
everyone on this team likes.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Benitez, taken in the first round of the expansion draft
from the Royals' organization, indeed breaks through or not is
unknown. His chances of receiving serious playing time with the
Diamondbacks are not great right now.
</P>
<P>
   With David Dellucci looking every bit the everyday player in
left field and Karim Garcia getting a long look in right field,
Benitez apparently will remain the odd man out.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll never hear him say a peep about his lack of playing
time. Benitez, who has the striking looks of a Latin matinee idol,
believes in his heart he will one day be an everyday major league
player.
</P>
<P>
   It's just one of the intriguing and interesting sidelight to
watch during a baseball season. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
