<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Software Helps Tap Lost Riches in a Company's Patents   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
In the high-tech economy, managing a portfolio of patents can
unlock hidden revenues.
<TEXT>
<P>
   SmartPatents, a startup in Mountain View, is automating this
process with a new software that shows firms how to extract more
wealth from their intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   The software can suggest new ways to license a patent or tell a
company if the patent is obsolete and not worth the fees to keep
it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``There's a huge patent game being played out there at the
highest levels of major corporations,'' said Kevin Rivette, chief
executive of SmartPatents. ``IBM makes a billion dollars a year
licensing patents.''
</P>
<P>
   A company that gets an intellectual lock on a hot technology can
keep competitors out of a market, or charge them to enter it
</P>
<P>
   But analyzing patents has always been a black art. Companies had
to rely on a legal priesthood for advice on when to sue their
competitors, or back out of a market lest they get sued themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Rivette and co-founder Irving Rappaport, both noted patent
attorneys, have spent the past five years creating software with
the legal smarts of a good patent attorney. They won't say how many
firms have plunked down $50,000 or more for their computer-aided
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients consider our software a competitive advantage,''
said SmartPatents President Dan'l Lewin, a former Apple executive
and friend of Steve Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Malley, intellectual property chief for Lucent
Technologies, said he has spent the Last two years using the
program to manage that intellectual gold mine known as Bell Labs.
</P>
<P>
   ``SmartPatents is to patent management what Visicalc was to
accounting many years ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; No free telephony? &LR;  Back in private practice after a
three-year stint at the Federal Communications Commission, attorney
Rachelle Chong is sounding the alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FCC is considering regulating Internet telephony,'' Chong
said. ``This is the next big clash between the government and the
computer industry.''
</P>
<P>
   You remember Internet telephony? Plug your computer into the
Internet, talk into the microphone and dial anywhere in the world,
for free.
</P>
<P>
   But Chong said the five-member commission is starting to wonder
whether Internet service providers who offer some forms of
telephony should be considered long-distance companies. If so, they
might be subjected to the same rules and charges, which can add 5
cents a minute to every ``free'' call.
</P>
<P>
   Chong, who hopes to head off any regulation, says four of the
five current commissioners are new and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the newcomers is FCC Chairman William Kennard, a former
FCC staff attorney familiar with the 1996 Telecommunications Reform
Act.
</P>
<P>
   He is joined by Michael Powell, an antitrust lawyer and son of
Army General Colin Powell; Gloria Tristani, a former state PUC
commissioner from New Mexico; and Harold Furchtgott-Roth, former
aide to Representative Thomas Bliley, R-Va., chairman of the House
Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the panel is veteran commissioner Susan Ness, an
attorney and banker who is an FOH _ Friend of Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Gentrification? &LR;  Sand Hill Road in Menlo Park has been the
haunt of venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   Now, investment bankers are trading in San Francisco for what is
fast becoming the financial nerve center of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense for us to be down here to be next to the VCs,''
said Rex Golding, who runs Morgan Stanley's technology group.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Koenig, who heads Goldman Sachs' technology practice is
also moving 80 bankers into a new office on Sand Hill. Frank
Quattrone's DMG Technology Group is already in Menlo Park, and
Merrill Lynch has an investment banking branch in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Other firms are said to be mulling similar moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be an investment banking ghetto by the time we're
finished,'' Golding joked.
</P>
<P>
   Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by
phone (650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
