<SLUG> BC-CNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   NBC Buys Stake In Cnet to Get Online On-Ramp  
   
 By Jamie Beckett  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In a deal marrying the top broadcast network with one of the
least-known Web directories, NBC said yesterday that it is buying a
stake in Cnet and gradually will take over its Snap! navigation
site.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The TV network will invest $26 million to buy 4.9 percent of San
Francisco-based Cnet, best known for its Web sites offering
technology news. That's just what the network pays for two episodes
of ``ER,'' the top-rated show on television.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is purchasing the 19 percent stake in Cnet's fledgling Snap!
Internet directory and navigation service for an undisclosed sum,
with an option to own 60 percent of Snap! for $38 million.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives, who immediately will start running Snap! jointly
with Cnet, said they hope to turn the site into a major Internet
gateway, or portal, similar to Yahoo, America Online or Excite.
Typically, Net users begin their Internet experiences on these
sites, which often provide news, personalized content and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The portal space is where the eyeballs and the money are on
the Internet,'' said Marty Yudkovitz, president of NBC Interactive
Media. ``It is the pivotal place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Cnet's shares jumped $12.13 to close at $45.13 on Nasdaq
yesterday _ a 36.7 percent rise, making it the second-biggest
gainer of all U.S. stocks. The stocks of other Internet gateway
companies also were up yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet launched Snap! in September and has invested some $25
million in the money-losing service, said Halsey Minor, chairman
and chief executive of Cnet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about making Snap! successful,'' Minor said. ``As
a more mature media company, NBC has a tremendous amount of
expertise, as well as tremendous relationships with advertisers
exceeding those of anyone on the Internet today.''
</P>
<P>
   After the deal closes, NBC will cover Snap! expenses, Minor
said, although he will be its chief executive. Yudkovitz and three
other NBC executives will join the Snap! board to make a majority.
</P>
<P>
   NBC said it intends to promote Snap! on its television network
and on several of its other Internet properties. Snap! likely will
rely on NBC for some of its content, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   That content will give Snap! an edge _ the same way Excite's
recent agreement to run Disney content provides an advantage, said
David Simons, managing director of Digital Video Investments in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's content that moves the masses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NBC officials said they were keen on getting further into the
Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that broadcast television is not a growth
business. This investment is fundamental to NBC's growth,''
Yudkovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   The television network said it will bring in ``select NBC
employees'' to work at Snap! in the future, but it has no definite
plans. All 170 full-time workers and part-time contractors at Snap!
will keep their jobs, Yudkovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   NBC did not indicate when it will exercise its option to raise
its stake in Snap!
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first media company that has really gone into
building a portal,'' said Regina Joseph, senior analyst at Jupiter
Communications in New York. ``I think we'll see a lot of other
media companies follow suit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cnet investment is only the latest of NBC's Internet
ventures. In addition to MSNBC, its 24-hour cable TV and online
news network operated jointly with Microsoft, the network has an
entertainment site, an on-demand Internet video service and a
localized Internet community guide service.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's deal with Cnet is the most recent move by a media titan to
try to cash in on the Bay Area's technology boom.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Forbes Inc. said it will establish a West Coast base
in Burlingame. New York publishing giant Ziff-Davis launched ZDTV,
a cable TV channel for high-tech news, in San Francisco in May.
Knight Ridder said in April that it will transfer its corporate
headquarters to Silicon Valley to make a bigger splash for its Web
operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
