<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Antivirus Firm's British Expansion   By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Fast-growing Network Associates of Santa Clara bought a foothold in
the European antivirus software market yesterday with its $640
million purchase of Dr. Solomon's Group PLC of Britain.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Network Associates makes the leading antivirus software in the
United States _ McAfee VirusScan _ but is always looking for ways
to increase its lead over No. 2 antivirus software-maker Symantec
Corp. of Cupertino.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three goals: To extend our leadership position in
antivirus, to make a geography play in Europe and to add 150 sales
people in Europe,'' said Bill Larson, chief executive of Network
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   This is Network Associates' 12th acquisition since Larson took
over as CEO of what was then-known as McAfee Associates in 1993. He
has used the buying spree to turn the antivirus firm into a
one-stop shop for corporate security and network management.
</P>
<P>
   After the acquisition is completed, Network Associates plans to
give corporate customers Dr. Solomon's Anti-Virus Toolkit along
with McAfee VirusScan, which may sometimes uncover different
viruses. By next year, Larson said, the firm will create a version
of the software for corporate customers that includes the best of
both products.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But the company will continue to sell the two separate
products in stores. Larson said McAfee VirusScan will cost about 29
pounds compared to Dr. Solomon's 69 pounds in England. But in the
United States where Dr. Solomon's is not well-known, he said the
price ratio will be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will let us hit multiple price points,'' Larson said.
``It's kind of a classic Procter &AMP; Gamble play.''
</P>
<P>
   Larson said he also hopes to use the Dr. Solomon's 150-person
sales force to sell other Network Associates products to the 10
million to 15 million Dr. Solomon's customers &UR;  &LR; who are primarily in
England and Northern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives Network Associates an opportunity to expand its
presence quite nicely,'' said Chris Shilakes, an analyst at Merrill
Lynch in San Francisco. ``It certainly makes sense to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts worry that Network Associates, the nation's
10th largest software firm, may be stretching itself too thin with
its long string of acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to buy up a lot of technologies; it's another
thing to integrate and sell them,'' said Jim Balderston, analyst at
Zona Research in Redwood City. ``That is easier said than done.''
</P>
<P>
   And Symantec officials said the move was simply a reaction to
Symantec's recent co-marketing agreement with giant computer-maker
IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``The balance of power was shifting because we had IBM behind
us, so now they're reacting so they don't lose too much ground,''
said Enrique Salem, vice president of the Cupertino-based firm.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street applauded the move, boosting Network Associates
shares up $1.88 _ by 4 percent _ to $43.88 and boosting Dr.
Solomon's stock up $3.38 _ by 11 percent _ to $35.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
