<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Investors Cool to Bank Deal   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Investors apparently are less than thrilled with the planned merger
of Wells Fargo and Minneapolis-based Norwest Corp.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Norwest stock fell 88 cents yesterday to close at $35.94 on more
than three times average daily volume. Taken together with the
$2.88 decline on Monday, the day the merger was announced, Norwest
shares have fallen 9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Wells Fargo shares slumped $12.75 yesterday to $353
after gaining just $2.50 on Monday and are selling well below the
bank's record high of $389.94 reached May 1.
</P>
<P>
   By combining forces to become the nation's seventh-largest bank,
the new Wells Fargo bank, which will be based in San Francisco,
expects to expand services while cutting 2,300 jobs out of 90,000
and reduce costs by $650 million annually within three years.
</P>
<P>
   Bank analysts don't dispute the logic of the merger or the
financial estimates. ``But investors were hoping if Wells sold out,
there might be a bidding contest and they'd get a much higher
price,'' said Michael Ancell, an analyst with Edward Jones in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``A marriage of equals with Norwest wasn't on anyone's radar
screens. They were expecting a merger with First Union, Banc One
and of course, U.S. Bancorp.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Grundhofer, CEO of U.S. Bancorp and located just a block
away from Norwest in Minneapolis, ``was putting the full court
press on Wells,'' said Ancell.
</P>
<P>
   Because of reported clashes with the former Wells vice chairman,
though, Wells CEO Paul Hazen apparently was more receptive to
Norwest's offer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Grundhofer reportedly offered a price that was
slightly below Norwest's bid, which was worth nearly $397 per share
(based on Norwest's higher stock price last Friday).
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo spokeswoman Kim Kellogg would not comment other than
to say Wells Fargo talked to several interested parties and the
deal with Norwest was clearly the best.
</P>
<P>
   Wells' shares got off to a rocky start yesterday after Brown
Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co. analyst Raphael Soifer downgraded the
company to ``neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   Soifer said that Wells stock already was selling at a premium
because of an expected acquisition and that ``there was no point
keeping a `trading buy' recommendation'' after the Norwest deal was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Soifer said that he was encouraged by Wells Fargo's new
estimates that it will earn the equivalent of $22.30 per share by
next year. That is about 10 percent more than he and many other
analysts were anticipating.
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that in the previous merger of Wells and First
Interstate it took a year and a half to really see how it worked
out and it could take equally that long to see the results of this
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest's stock apparently skidded on similar concerns and
worries that it has abandoned its successful formula of expanding
through small acquisitions and internal growth. In the past five
years, Norwest has more than doubled net income from $613 million
to $1.35 billion through this approach.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo and Norwest stocks are not the only ones to decline
following their merger announcement. BankAmerica's stock jumped
$4.63 to $91.13 on the day its deal with NationsBank was reported,
but it closed yesterday at $85.63, or 87 cents below its pre-merger
price two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NationsBank's shares are trading at $77.44, down
$3.31 from its post-merger announcement peak but $1 higher than
before the deal was announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
