 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 389 - JUNE 10, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. GILLIAN ANDERSON, CONSPIRACY THEORISTS' PIN-UP GIRL As
sceptical Agent Scully on ``The X-Files,'' Gillian Anderson is the
love goddess of alien buffs, conspiracy theorists and
paranormalists worldwide. ``The X-Files'' movie will test the range
of her appeal. Anderson talks about the new movie, ``X-Files''
mania, the plot details of the film and why she is diligently
working to separate herself from the series which brought her fame
and fortune. By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words + photo.
</P>
<P>
   _______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   2. JENNIFER LOVE HEWITT, PARTY OF ONE In the romantic comedy
``Can't Hardly Wait,'' Jennifer Love Hewitt plays a high-school
prom queen facing graduation. She is herself a recent high-school
graduate. This 19-year-old is already a star. Hewitt tells Cindy
Pearlman about the new movie, the now-filming ``I Still Know What
You Did Last Summer,'' why she doesn't think on-screen nudity is
for her and what she really thinks of the rumoured competitiveness
between her and ``Party of Five'' co-star/fellow teen-scream star
Neve Campbell. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   3. THE X-FILES : THE QUIZ Just before the big-screen version of
the television hit ``The X-Files'' prepares to reach the cinemas,
Tom Frangicetto offers a thought-provoking 16-question quiz to
probe your knowledge of ``X-Files'' lore ..... from the name of
Mulder's sister and Scully's career ambitions to the murder of
``Deep Throat'' and the sinister Cigarette-Smoking Man. 1,400 words
+ photo.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   4. ROD STEWART COMES FULL CIRCLE Talk about having a full life.
Rod Stewart has five children by three women. He has made more than
20 albums, many of them bestsellers. He is in the Rock Hall of Fame
and he owns several homes around the world. ``Life is good. It
couldn't be better,'' says Stewart, who hopes to have a sixth
child, the third one with his wife, actress-model Rachel Hunter.
The biggest news for his fans though is that Stewart, now 53, is
rocking again. By Steve Morse. From The Boston Globe. 900 words.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. COPING WITH THE DEATH OF A STAR The launch of a major motion
picture and the attendant publicity surrounding it is vital to the
way Hollywood does business - particularly if the film has a
multimillion-dollar advertising campaign behind it. It follows then
that the aura of death and mourning does not sit well with the
healthy glow of excitement that is supposed to surround a
nationwide release. And yet, sometimes a film's star will die
before the film hits the screens. Filmmakers have to respond
carefully and sensitively, yet Hollywood seldom loses sight of the
famous adage ``The show must go on ...'' By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 900
words.
</P>
<P>
   _______________________________________________________________
6. THE B-52'S LATEST WAVE Absent for six years, the B-52's are
back. Cindy Wilson, one of the band's singers, waves a figurative
finger in the wind. ``I think,'' she says, ``it might be the right
mood this summer.'' The new wave music of the early '80s has
bubbled up again and the reconstituted, rejuvenated B-52s are
primed to ride yet another wave. By Jim Sullivan. From The Boston
Globe. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   7. ANI DIFRANCO : FOLK-PUNK VOICE The fiercely independent Ani
DiFranco is a rebel. She is proud of her ``indie girl'' status, her
anti-corporate politics, her sexuality, her refusal to sell her
music for TV ads, saying no to playing at famous music festivals
and the creation of her own label, 'Righteous Babe Records.' Her
female empowerment has made her a fascinating subject for the
media, even though analysts forget to mention the most important
ingredient of her success - her music. By Steve Morse. From The
Boston Globe. 1,300 words.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   8. SOFT OPTION Hardware is expensive, so why not write a radio
in software? Radio stations that sound almost as good as a CD could
be with us soon. By Barry Fox. From New Scientist magazine. 500
words. (N/A Australia, New Zealand, Brazil.)
</P>
