<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The story of the larcenist and the lions
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My lions have been kidnapped, or catnapped.
</P>
<P>
   All that follows is absolutely true. I bought a pair of concrete
lions for the new house, to sit out on the front walk. They weren't
expensive. A small company just south of Lufkin makes and sells
concrete yard art -- lions, dogs, gargoyles, angels and such.
</P>
<P>
   I was looking for a pair of concrete flamingos, but my running
buddy squelched that idea. It's bad enough, she says, that I have a
full-size
</P>
<P>
   cut-out cow that I keep threatening to put in the yard, a
concrete rooster, a statue of St. Francis of Assisi with the bird
on his shoulder missing its head, and a battered weather vane.
She's worried the neighbors might get up a petition about all the
yard art.
</P>
<P>
   So I bought the lions and put them out after the flamingos were
vetoed. Last week, she called me while out inspecting the house,
which is in the final days of construction. The lions were gone.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not a simple act of vandalism or theft, which is
good. In their place were two small ceramic monkeys, the
see-no-evil, and speak-no-evil members of the traditional trio. And
there was a note, sealed in plastic to keep it dry from the water
sprinklers. It read, in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all: Your lions are safe. A few of us animals were
sitting around the other day visiting about things going on in our
lives, when the Lions spoke up and told us a sad tale. They were
lamenting about having to sit on top of this pile of bricks
guarding this new house in this horrible heat.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just about the time the sun goes down and they think they
might get some relief, some little person, dressed like a throwback
from who knows when, comes around and tries to drown them...
(Editor's note: That would be me. As noted last week, I am spending
an inordinate amount of time watering grass at a house I don't yet
live in.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, some of us thought that the lions just needed a break,
you know, a little R and R. Anyway, that's why we are here. Of
course, one of us (monkeys) can't see, and the other won't talk, so
we won't be much help in the case of an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, we are here. After the Lions get their much deserved
rest, we will leave, and they will come home. Until that time, just
be glad that we are here.
</P>
<P>
   It was signed, ``The Monkeys,'' with what appears to be a paw
print in redink.
</P>
<P>
   We obviously have some friends with:
</P>
<P>
   -- Too much time on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   -- A warped sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   -- An ability to lift heavy weights. Those lions weigh about 90
pounds each.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that did not narrow the list of suspects down
much. First, even the skinny women we know who might have pulled
this stunt have spouses or boyfriends able to lift the lions.
Second, by definition and inclination, all the folks we hang around
have warped senses of humor. Finally, none are too busy to pass up
a good practical joke if the opportunity presents
</P>
<P>
   itself. As it apparently has.
</P>
<P>
   The painters at the house said they like the monkeys better than
the lions. I disagree. I don't much like monkeys in general. I
don't find them cute or particularly amusing. Monkeys are not at
all modest. In fact, they're downright showy.
</P>
<P>
   These ceramic monkeys are about a fifth the size of the lions,
which means from the road it looks like two blond squirrels are
perched on my walkway.
</P>
<P>
   I'm about as fond of squirrels as I am of monkeys. Squirrels are
just rats with bushy tails.
</P>
<P>
   We have unsuccessfully sought the culprit(s) of this caper since
discovering the missing lions last Monday. I have skulked around in
back
</P>
<P>
   yards of a few prime suspects, hoping to discover the purloined
predators, figuring a pre-emptive strike would be a just reward. I
have interrogated several friends who are either innocent or
extremely good liars. Still, no luck and no lions.
</P>
<P>
   I must admit that this was a good practical joke, though enough
time has passed that I'm ready for the lions to return and the
monkeys to get the heck out of Dodge. In the belief that there is
no good defense like a good offense, I have prepared a surprise for
the lion larcenists. It is admittedly a weak response to the
original misdeed, but it was the best I could do under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   There are two pink plastic pigs where the monkeys once squatted.
The monkeys are of course safe. And there's a note explaining the
reverse-ransom conditions, also wrapped in plastic since, despite a
welcome rain late last week, I'm still watering regularly.
</P>
<P>
   My running buddy is getting worried that I'm becoming
inordinately fond of the pigs, which cost $1.97 at Wal-Mart. The
pink (begin ital) does (end ital) somewhat match the color of the
brick.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Daily Sentinel in
Nacogdoches. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
