<SLUG> BC-SYMONS-SACRAMENTS?10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    30 years of sacraments questioned by Palm Beach parishioners
 &HT;    By Shannon Colavecchio
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. _ Still shocked by the news that their
religious leader resigned last week in disgrace, many parishioners
of St. Ignatius Loyola Cathedral on Monday, June 8, questioned the
sanctity of sacraments recently given by Bishop J. Keith Symons.
</P>
<P>
   Symons resigned last week after eight years as bishop of the
Palm Beach Diocese, admitting to sexually molesting five boys about
30 years ago. In the two weeks before his resignation, he
celebrated Mass, heard confession, ordained a few priests and
confirmed 163 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the sacraments are valid,'' Monsignor Thomas Kinzling said
emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   Kinzling, who now leads services at St. Ignatius, said he
considered moving to another church because he was so devastated by
Symons' resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect of the sacraments does not depend on the holiness
of the person giving them,'' Kinzling said. ``But it doesn't make
it hurt any less for those people who received sacraments from
(Symons).''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that those recently confirmed ``cannot be
reconfirmed _ that's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cathedral will hold a ``healing service'' or church
celebration for the 163 people confirmed, and the more than 100
present Monday stressed the need to counsel the parish children,
many of whom are altar servers or altar boys.
</P>
<P>
   Kinzling said counselors from area Catholic charities already
have offered and begun to donate their services. He agreed to start
planning a celebration and support service for the St. Ignatius
parish.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've heard, most of the children are doing good,''
he said. ``They seem to be doing OK.``
</P>
<P>
   The parishioners began the meeting with a prayer for guidance
and wisdom: ``Do not let us be led by hatefulness. As we gather in
your name, may we temper justice with love.''
</P>
<P>
   Several parishioners expressed concern for Symons and questioned
his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I understand, he'll probably get six years of
intense counseling and very little time by himself,'' Kinzling
said, adding he does not know when Synons will retire or whether he
will get retirement benefits. ``His future is not the brightest.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he is hopeful for St. Ignatius and other Catholic
churches in the Palm Beach Diocese.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to continue our programs, we need to get better
programs,'' Kinzling said. ``We need to continue to be a
child-friendly church. And we need to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
