<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOSPEL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``International'' music of gospel explored by French filmmakers
 &HT;    By Susannah A. Nesmith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ How do you say ``Operator, information, get
me Jesus on the line'' in French?
</P>
<P>
   A French film producer in Fort Pierce, Florida, to film a local
gospel star would say the music needs no translation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you have a lot of good talents in this country,''
Joseph Licide said during a break in the filming at Miracle Prayer
Temple on Avenue Q.
</P>
<P>
   Licide and his wife, Regine Abadia, are working on a documentary
on American gospel music for French public television. One of the
segments, filmed Monday, June 8, will be about the Rev. Aubrey
Ghent, pastor of the House of God, a Pentacostal church on North
27th Street. Ghent plays lap steel guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reverend Ghent, I think he's the lead lap steel guitar player
of his generation,'' said assistant director Guetty Felin.
</P>
<P>
   Ghent learned lap steel guitar from his father and his uncle.
The instrument resembles the conventional guitar only slightly,
trading the classic acoustic body for a flat surface that is played
horizontally.
</P>
<P>
   Another segment of the documentary was on a Chicago singer,
Ethel Halloway. Halloway put out an album 15 years ago but hasn't
sung much outside of church since then. Felin was able to convince
her to give up baby-sitting her grandchildren for a few days to
come to Florida to sing with Ghent, who accompanied her on the
keyboard along with a Vero Beach minister on a different keyboard
and a drummer from Vero Beach. Four members of Ghent's church sang
back-up. The filming was done in the Miracle Prayer Temple because
the acoustics are better there than in his church. The Port St.
Lucie film office helped Licide's company, Gloria Films, arrange
for production assistants, catering and accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Licide chose to do a segment on Ghent after hearing one of his
CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought the album and I was just astonished,'' Licide said.
</P>
<P>
   Ghent said he wasn't all that surprised when Licide approached
him about doing the documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``My CD is very popular in France so it's not terribly
surprising,'' he said. ``I was a little surprised as far as a film
goes. I was looking for other audio opportunities, not visual.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
