<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Real life is that thing that happens tomorrow
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ My son counted down the weeks and days leading up
to the Big 7th Birthday Party. ``How many days now, Mom? How many
days?'' I opened my mouth, and my mother started speaking: ``Don't
wish your life away.''
</P>
<P>
   How many times, growing up, had I heard Mom say that? I didn't
have a clue what she meant. When I was 7, a day seemed an
interminable wait. Two weeks? Forget it. The summer stretched into
the unimaginable horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Adults look at time from the other end of the telescope. It's
mere moments since our children were born, and only a few weeks
since we were kids ourselves. Yet, as we tick off each day's tasks
like items on a grocery list, we still find ourselves wishing our
lives away.
</P>
<P>
   As we celebrated Alec's birthday this week, I wanted to go back
to the day I held him the first time. He wore his stylish blue knit
cap, and everybody admitted he was an unusually handsome baby.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a newborn, I couldn't wait for him to sleep through
the night, couldn't wait for that first step, couldn't wait for him
to be able to play by himself for a luxurious five or 10 minutes at
a time.
</P>
<P>
   Now I wanted to go back to the beginning. He had come too far,
too fast, more than a third of the distance to independence,
separation from us.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted time in the abstract to slow down, but I wanted this
day to be over, the sooner the better. If I could only get through
this party, I'd be sane again, I could rest. Twenty-five kids in
the back yard, industrial-strength blue icing ground into the
driveway. Hadn't I vowed I would never throw another home birthday
party? What had I been thinking?
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, now I remembered. I decided to do the party at home
because a friend, who goes by the alias Dexterous Dan the Juggling
Man, generously offered to do his show for Alec's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   I snapped lots of pictures, but I knew I wouldn't need them to
remember the moment: Dan juggled bowling balls and machetes! He
chomped bites of an apple while juggling it! Flame-throwing!
Fire-eating! Kids cheered and clapped, held spellbound by something
even more mesmerizing than TV or Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   The show ended, and, with it, my short-lived experiment in
living-for-the-moment. Once again, I prayed for deliverance from
this day. How did I get to be middle-aged _ old enough to
understand that time is finite _ and still wishing my life away?
</P>
<P>
   We spend our childhood and young adulthood straining for that
next milestone. In the spring we can't wait for school to get out;
in late summer we can't wait for school to start. We can't wait to
drive our first car, can't wait to go away to college. We can't
wait to get that first job, can't wait to get a better one.
</P>
<P>
   Now we don't wish huge chunks of our lives away _ just a lot of
little chunks. How many days do you wake up, and wish the day over
before it has begun? ``If I can only get through this project/this
week/this overscheduled day, life will be good.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the first week of summer, and Alec can't wait for camp to
start in two weeks. ``How many days, Mom? How many days?'' I open
my mouth, and my mother starts speaking: ``Stop wishing your life
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I should start listening to her.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty's e-mail address is: mary_mccarty(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
