<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mom's tale shows it's smart to listen for the Bogeyman
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Here's why a mother named Patricia
Fowler Bouton is my new idol:
</P>
<P>
   Let's pretend it's 9 at night and your 8-year-old comes out of
her bedroom. She says she hears something. It's scaring her. She
can't sleep.
</P>
<P>
   You, a woman who recently won Mother Of The Year and possess the
pinched nerve in your neck to prove it, do what any good mother
would do.
</P>
<P>
   You roll your eyes and say:
</P>
<P>
   Go.
</P>
<P>
   To.
</P>
<P>
   Bed.
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   Now. And you say it in a tone of voice that leaves your throat a
little scratchy.
</P>
<P>
   That's why this Patricia lady from Maryland City, Md., is on the
top of my list.
</P>
<P>
   No, she did not return a wallet containing $100,000 to the
owner, who then wept for three days because it was his money for a
new kidney. And she did not win a big lottery and start free day
care nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   This is better. She actually listened when her son came out of
his room one night and said he couldn't sleep because he was
hearing noises.
</P>
<P>
   Turned out it's a good thing she did because there was a man, a
burglar, asleep under the kid's bed. Apparently the guy got trapped
inside the house when the family came home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that at some point in the evening . . . (the man)
had gone into the room to hide because he couldn't leave the house
and subsequently fell asleep,'' said Tracy Morgan, the officer who
handled the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He woke up on the way to the station and asked what was going
on,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Ay caramba! If that was our house, the bad guy would still be
snoozing there. Because the truth about listening? If you do it too
much, you're bound to hear some stuff you didn't really want to
know.
</P>
<P>
   You see, I have what would be called Selective Listening. I
consistently fail to hear things like: Mom, can I have ice cream
for dinner? And, Mom, can Robert come live with us for a week?
Which bothers me. Because if I'm blocking out the little stuff,
it's certain I'm missing some bigger stuff as well. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Yet, just let a mango land on the porch roof and I am convinced
it's an escaped prisoner with a grudge on society and a claw
hammer.
</P>
<P>
   The ceiling fan rattles the newspaper on the table and I think
it's a rat chewing through the wall.
</P>
<P>
   A branch scratches the metal awnings outside our bedroom window.
I think it's Armageddon and curse the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Patricia is my new idol. Because not only did she
have the good sense to listen, she also had the good sense to check
out what she heard.
</P>
<P>
   She's living proof: There could be a bad man under your little
kid's bed. There could be a prisoner on the back porch. There could
be a rat in the wall.
</P>
<P>
   And that noise? That one I'm hearing right now? It's either a
train derailment, or my nose whistling. I'll get back to you when I
know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
