<HEADER>
A2383 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILNER-BOOKS11-COX     06-10 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILNER-BOOKS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cormac McCarthy in same league as Faulkner
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I can remember clearly -- and you can too if
you're old enough to have grown grandchildren -- when Texas was
still pretty much a frontier state. It wasn't that long ago, if you
count in lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   There was no Cotton Bowl; no big league baseball teams; no pro
football teams; no William Faulkner, if you believed at least one
Lone Star best-selling author; the most widely acclaimed
Texas-based writers were pretty much historians and folklorists, if
you didn't count William Humphrey, who lived in Spain much of the
time although his works are set in Texas. And Katherine Ann Porter
more or less denied her Texas roots.
</P>
<P>
   But, boy hidee, has time changed things in our state! Time and I
don't know what all, including the infernal influx of people of all
denominations and persuasions for all kinds of reasons, mostly
economic. And once they were here, fluctuating economic conditions
left them stranded here.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, time marched relentlessly on and the Texas
population grew until, the fact is, there are too darned many
people living within our vast borders nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   But Texans in every direction are now writing and getting
published and some are writing very well, thank you. We might even
have a Faulkner or two.
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   My nomination for a ``Texas Faulkner'' lives way over in El Paso
and is one of those outsiders who moved into the state some time
back for reasons we can only guess at after reading his books,
which are mostly about the dying and dead age of the Texas cowboy.
At least they are so far, but he's a fairly young fellow and no
telling what he'll write about down the road.
</P>
<P>
   His name, in case you haven't already figured it out, is Cormac
McCarthy and he's what you call a ``Serious Writer.'' That is to
say, he doesn't crank out formula novels aimed at being made into
movies, although I hear one of his appears bound for the silver
screen, as we used to call it.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy first came to my attention, as he did many others, with
his novel, ``All the Pretty Horses,'' the first of a trilogy. It is
so very good it made me tell my reading friends to be sure and read
it, and many did and were equally impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a few years later, along came Number Two, ``The
Crossing.'' I didn't get into it as completely as I had ``All the
Pretty Horses,'' but it is another winner.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the final book of the trilogy -- ``Cities of the
Plain,'' (Knopf). I have some complaints about this one, as I did
about the other two, but it is a mesmerizing tale that won't leave
your mind once it's in there.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the books in McCarthy's trilogy might be called
Larry McMurtry on acid. That wouldn't be truly accurate, but it
would be in the right direction. This latest one, number three, is
set on a ranch just outside of El Paso in New Mexico in 1952. The
major characters are John Grady Cole, a terminally idealistic young
cowboy who should have lived in a previous, more innocent time, and
his buddy, Billy Parham, nine years older and ages wiser.
</P>
<P>
   You may remember Billy from ``All the Pretty Horses.''
</P>
<P>
   This one is primarily a love story, a tragedy in a manner of
speaking, although there probably was no other way it could have
gone. The prose is almost poetic. Cormac McCarthy writes like a man
possessed.
</P>
<P>
   My complaints mentioned above have to do with the fact that the
character sometimes speak Spanish at some length and we aren't told
what they are saying by any of the means other writers have used
when their characters speak in other tongues. Maybe that's picky,
but I resented him making it harder for me to follow his story. But
I didn't resent it enough to stop reading. The writing and the
story are too beautifully told to even consider stopping.
</P>
<P>
   Trust me. This man Cormac McCarthy plays in the same ballpark as
the late Mr. Faulkner and other American greats. If you miss him,
you'll be sorry somewhere down the line.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
