</P>
<P>
   NORM _ Sit down to interview Norm MacDonald, whose new and
probably loathsome film ``Dirty Work'' opens Friday, and something
weird's bound to happen. If the movie proves anything it might be
that white guys can ``Good Burger.'' (Jubera, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. ETA: 6 p.m .
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ It's not the same ``Jerry Springer'' _ but maybe it
is. Stripped of its mainstay chair throwing, hairpulling and daily
fisticuffs, ``Springer's'' subject matter still isn't exactly what
kids ought to be watching. Plus this day marks Lyn Vaughan's exit
from CNN Headline News. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GOSPEL _ FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ How do you say ``Operator,
information, get me Jesus on the line'' in French? A French film
producer who traveled to Fort Pierce, Florida, to film a local
gospel star would say the music needs no translation. Joseph Licide
and his wife, Regine Abadia, are working on a documentary on
American gospel music for French public television. One of the
segments, filmed Monday, June 8, will be about the Rev. Aubrey
Ghent, pastor of the House of God, a Pentacostal church on North
27th Street. Ghent plays lap steel guitar. (Nesmith, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   MILNER-BOOKS _ My nomination for a ``Texas Faulkner'' lives way
over in El Paso and is one of those outsiders who moved into the
state some time back for reasons we can only guess at after reading
his books, which are mostly about the dying and dead age of the
Texas cowboy. His name, in case you haven't already figured it out,
is Cormac McCarthy, and he's what you call a ``Serious Writer.''
(Milner, Lufkin Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   VIAGRA _ Though 16 men have now died after taking Viagra,
doctors maintain it is safe _ if patients who shouldn't take it,
don't. Some nitrate drugs interact Viagra, and that's a known risk.
But men who take blood pressure medication and heart medicines also
may be at risk, not because of drug interaction, but weak hearts.
(Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   PLANTS-SOS _ Plants nibbled by caterpillars can send out help
signals by releasing specially-made blends of volatile compounds
that can be picked up by good bugs that zero in to attack the bad
bugs. Georgia agricultural scientists have learned that these
chemical signals are so specific, that they can convey the type and
species of the attacking insect. (Lee, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-DRINKING _ Just say ``maybe.'' Parents are sending this
confused message about drugs and alcohol to their teenagers,
according to a new survey by the Hazelden Foundation, a national
nonprofit drug treatment program based in Minnesota. According to
the survey, only 23 percent of parents said they would flatly
forbid their teens to drink until the legal age, 21. (Susman, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
