 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Forbes Exec Rose From Dust Of Rivals  
 By Tom Abate   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Behind Rich Karlgaard's annointment as publisher of Forbes
magazine lies a dramatic comeback story.
</P>
<P>
   It involves Karlgaard and two former partners turned
competitors: fellow magazine publishers Tony Perkins of Red Herring
and David Bunnell of Upside.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins in 1989 when Karlgaard, then a humble technical
writer, and Perkins, an ambitious ex-banker, decided to found a
magazine about Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Though short on money and publishing experience, they had
already made many friends in the valley by founding the Churchill
Club, San Jose's answer to San Francisco's Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   With Perkins handling sales and Karlgaard driving editorial,
they gave birth to Upside. A few investors _ led by Perkins's
lifelong pal, venture capitalist Tim Draper _ bankrolled this
quixotic effort.
</P>
<P>
   But, undercapitalized from the start, by 1992 Upside was
scrambling to meet payroll. At that point, Bunnell joined Upside's
board of directors to help turn around the flailing magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Already a computer publishing legend, Bunnell had helped launch
a string of successful magazines, including Macworld. But after
Bunnell joined Upside's board, the two founders were eventually
eased out and Bunnell slowly tightened his grip on Upside, which he
has nursed back to profit and prominence.
</P>
<P>
   Karlgaard emerged from the Upside putsch better off. By 1992 he
had befriended futurist George Gilder, whose ideas had bedazzled
magazine magnate Steve Forbes. To create an editorial pulpit for
Gilder, Forbes hired Karlgaard to edit Forbes ASAP, the bimonthly
tech magazine that turned out to be Karlgaard's steppingstone to
Forbes magazine.
</P>
<P>
   While Karlgaard's star was ascending, Perkins was sliding into a
personal and professional slump. Nonetheless, within in a year
Perkins created the Red Herring. With financial backing from
co-founder Chris Alden, he has spent the last five years making the
Herring a force in the valley _ and vindicating himself.
</P>
<P>
   Karlgaard said there was a time when he and Perkins ``were both
mad at each other and certain people on the (Upside) board.'' Since
then, he and Perkins have patched it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real story here,'' Karlgaard said, looking back on the
Upside days, ``is that out of that one troubled kernel, three
successful magazines have sprung up.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; F.Y.I. &LR;  This fall, Upside will move from San Mateo to San
Francisco, taking a floor in the same building on 731 Market Street
that houses Mother Jones.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; 3Com Spin: &LR;  Sources close to 3Com ridicule the notion that the
company's decision to hire a second in command signals any loss of
faith in Eric Benhamou, the company's chairman, president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt for a new president and COO, being conducted by Spencer
Stuart, has so far turned up three possible candidates _ all from
outside the networking industry.
</P>
<P>
   Benhamou recently got the supreme compliment from Cisco CEO John
Chambers, who told reporters that when headhunters phone him, ``I
send them over to Eric. I want somebody to hire that guy out of my
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; New dimension: &LR;  Intervista, the San Francisco startup that
pioneered 3D browsers for the Internet, will be acquired by
Platinum Technology, an Ohio corporate-software firm.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will be announced any day. 3D guru and company founder
Tony Parisi will be among the 28 Intervistites who will don
Platinum name tags. But Intervista President John Lukrich, who
engineered the deal, will supposedly leave to explore new pastures.
</P>
<P>
   The deal highlights the fact that 3D, once heralded as the next
big thing on the Web, is still a ways off. In April, Silicon
Graphics announced plans to spin off _ or disband _ its 120-person
3D effort called Cosmo.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Kudos &LR;  to the California Secretary of State's office for the
superb presentation of election results on its Web site. Bookmark
www.ss.ca.gov for November.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or email (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
