<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPAM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Reputed King of Junk E-mail Says He's Through Spamming  
 By Jon Swartz   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spam king has abdicated his throne and become a turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Wallace _ the self-anointed ``Spamford,'' who claimed to
make millions of dollars peddling unsolicited commercial e-mail but
angered millions of Internet users in the process _ says he is
ditching the industry he pioneered and will testify against
spammers in court in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful twist of fate,'' said Wallace, who once
boasted of being the world's biggest junk e-mailer.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace vows he will speak out against spammers as an expert
witness in lawsuits against the junk e-mailers. He will work for
the same law firm that in March won a $2 million lawsuit against
him on behalf of Internet service provider EarthLink Network Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Sanford's penance,'' said Pete Wellborn, the
Atlanta-based attorney for EarthLink. ``His knowledge of e-mail
practices and the Internet is so vast that I can think of no one
I'd rather have as my technical consultant.''
</P>
<P>
   Many observers contend that Wallace and his company, Cyber
Promotions Inc., were forced out of business by an avalanche of
litigation. At least five ISPs, including America Online,
CompuServe and Concentric Network, have successfully sued Cyber
Promotions in recent years to evict it from their sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legal climate makes it much more difficult to be a
spammer,'' said Randall Boe, AOL's associate general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's defection underscores a growing nationwide crackdown
on unsolicited commercial e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering at least four bills that would either
ban or restrict spam; ISPs are suing junk e-mailers at a furious
clip; and Internet services are offering software that lets
subscribers block unwanted e-mail from specific Internet addresses.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Internet is being buried under the flurry of
an estimated 13 billion pieces of junk e-mail a year, most of which
tout sleazy sex ads, get-rich-quick schemes and miracle drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Since surfacing three years ago, spam has become so pervasive
that it is clogging up Internet pathways and individuals' e-mail
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Cyber Promotions was among the most egregious offenders. The
privately owned company delivered millions ofpieces of junk e-mail
last year on behalf of clients hawking vitamin supplements,
luxurious vacations and health and beauty aids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only hope that Mr. Wallace disappears for good, but I
wouldn't bet on it,'' said Paul Hoffman, director of the Internet
Mail Consortium in Santa Cruz, which represents 30 companies,
including AOL, Microsoft and Netscape. ``He is the consummate
salesman who has a habit of resurfacing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and others assert that Wallace beat a hasty retreat
before anti-spam laws go into the books. Previously, Wallace was a
prolific sender of junk-mail faxes before legislation drove him
from that field.
</P>
<P>
   ``People on the Internet are not going to stand for spam,''
Wallace admitted in a recent interview. ``I will give back to the
Internet by spending time and effort to help clean up the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the normally loquacious Wallace _ who has compared
himself to Madonna and Howard Stern _ isn't saying anything else.
</P>
<P>
   He is tight-lipped about his future plans in marketing, and the
status of Cyber Promotions is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The Dresher, Pa., company's phone numbers are either
disconnected or go unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-03-98 2133EDT &QL;
</P>
