<SLUG> BC-CPT-RAO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Computer Whiz Burns to Learn  
 By Jamie Beckett   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time he was in eighth grade, Ramana Rao knew all the math
his school could teach him. He finished a four-year computer
science degree at MIT in three years. During a trip around the
world in 1983 and 1984, he went six months without sleeping more
than one night in the same place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an enormous interest in knowledge and knowing,'' says
Rao.
</P>
<P>
   Now 35, he's chief technology officer at Inxight (pronounced
``insight''), one of several startups at Xerox's Palo Alto Research
Center (PARC). At PARC, Rao has spent the past eight years helping
create Inxight's software, a new graphical user interface that's
intended to make it easier to get at and organize information.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a computer, you're never in a flow state. You feel like
you're on the phone with someone stupid trying to get them to do
something simple,'' Rao said.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Hyperbolic Tree, the interface lets users see and
easily navigate an entire bank of information _ a Web site, an
organizational chart, a database _ at one glance. Instead of having
to click and scroll through numerous areas, users of the tree can
just select one area to zoom in on that information while shrinking
the rest of the display. It's fast and fluid, and it's especially
useful for Web surfing or handling huge amounts of related
information.
</P>
<P>
   Rao also co-invented Inxight's Table Lens, a technique for
viewing large tables of data that enables users to quickly pick out
patterns and anomalies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cars made all of us be able to run like leopards,'' he says.
``These tools could make us all think more like Einstein.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in India, Rao spent most of his youth in Texas, where his
father taught aerospace engineering at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   He was the only Indian in his class at school, but he says he
was seldom teased about his nationality. Most of his classmates
were more concerned whether he was ``a Yankee or a Rebel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I'm from southern India, so I guess I'm a Rebel,'' Rao
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   He zipped through his studies easily _ in fifth grade, he zoomed
through 200 biographies _ and by the end of eighth grade, Rao had
read all the high school's math books. When his family moved to
Bellevue, Wash., he skipped 10th grade and graduated a year early.
</P>
<P>
   Rao went to MIT in 1979 planning to major in math; however, he
really was undecided about his future. He wanted to be a novelist.
He wanted to be an academic like his parents. (His mother got her
doctorate in microbiology after the family moved to the United
States.) He wanted to travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go to college and take the introductory course in
every subject,'' says Rao.
</P>
<P>
   He tested out of every freshman math and science course. Someone
told him about a computer science course but warned him that it was
too tough for freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``So of course I went into computer science almost
immediately,'' he says. It also fit his need to put off making
decisions about his life.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1980, Rao got a job at PARC. He was 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in and put my hand on a mouse, and I thought, `This
is going to change the world,''' says Rao. ``That inspired me, and
that inspiration is part of what set me off on these paths.''
</P>
<P>
   Rao finished his bachelor's degree and spent what would have
been his senior year working at a consulting firm to earn money. He
was reluctant to commit to a career in computer science _ or any
other career. After graduation, he set off with a backpack to
travel around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Although many people thought he was foolish not to immediately
grab the opportunities available to a bright, young computer
scientist, Rao recalls that PARC's director, John Seely Brown,
encouraged him to travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a profoundly creative mind, a passion for life and a
good feeling for technology,'' Brown recalls. ``I'm a firm believer
in the need to develop balanced creative geniuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip didn't really hurt Rao's technical career. When he
returned 13 months later, he began working toward his master's
degree at MIT. He went to work at PARC in 1986 and finished his
degree there in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the team working on the user interface in 1990.
Inxight was formed six years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``One feeling I had at PARC was that I could figure out the next
big thing,'' Rao says. The Inxight projects interested him because
it was practical and possible. ``I wanted it (what he worked on) to
be something I cared about and could see in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-03-98 2132EDT &QL;
</P>
