<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-BELL-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC ANNOUNCES COMING FAST INTERNET HOOKUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic will bring high-speed Internet access to several
major East Coast cities by the end of the summer. But Boston and
New York will have to wait until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic joins the roster of Baby Bell regional phone
companies that are rolling out Asymmetric Digital Subscriber Line
service, or ADSL, a technology that enables standard copper phone
wires to carry vast amounts of digital data as well as regular
voice telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell Atlantic is determined to keep pace with people's
evolving needs by adding booster rockets to the on-line connections
we provide,'' said Bell Atlantic retail group president Bruce
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts say the Internet cannot become a mass medium until
it is easily accessible by consumers from their homes. Even with
the fastest modems available today, cruising the Internet from home
can be a slow and frustrating experience, especially when sites
include video or complicated graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Communications companies are experimenting with several methods
to make connecting to the Web faster. In addition to ADSL, these
include cable modems, which operate through cable television
networks, and ISDN, or integrated services digital network, a phone
technology that provides high-speed data as well as voice services.
</P>
<P>
   The lowest-priced version of the new InfoSpeed service will
deliver up to 640,000 bits of data per second, a rate 12 times
faster than today's fastest modems. The user will also be able to
transmit data at 90,000 bits per second. This version of the
service will cost $69.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,.1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic will also offer two more expensive options, with
data reception speeds of 1.6 million or 7.1 million bits per
second. These InfoSpeed services will carry monthly charges of
$109.95 and $189.95, respectively, and are aimed at telecommuters
and self-employed people with home offices.
</P>
<P>
   The InfoSpeed system will work with PC and Macintosh computers,
but Bell Atlantic's own Internet service is currently available
only to PC users. However, the company will also offer InfoSpeed
through other Internet providers. Customers who obtain the service
through some other provider will receive a substantial discount
from the standard price.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic plans to charge less than $200 for installation of
the system. But company spokesman Larry Plumb wasn't sure whether
that will include installation of a high-speed data networking card
in the customer's computer.
</P>
<P>
   The price will include installation of an ADSL modem and a
special device called a ``splitter'' that will allow data and voice
traffic to flow over a regular home phone line. A consortium of
computer and telephone companies are completing work on a
``splitterless'' version of ADSL that should be much cheaper to
install, but Bell Atlantic officials said they wanted to enter the
market as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of the new service reflects the legacy of last
year's merger of Bell Atlantic and Nynex Corp., which formerly
served New York and Boston. InfoSpeed will be rolled out first on
Bell Atlantic's old turf, with deployment in Washington, D.C.,
Philadelphia, and Pittsburgh in September. The Hudson River area of
New Jersey will get the service in October. But New York City and
Boston are set to go on line some time next year.
</P>
<P>
   Plumb said personnel in the former Nynex areas aren't as
familiar with ADSL systems as those in Bell Atlantic's old
territory. Besides, Plumb said, Washington is the nation's
second-biggest user of Internet services, after California's
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Doyle, vice president of International Data Corp. in
Framingham, is skeptical that there's a mass market for ADSL
services. His organization has predicted that only about 1 million
households will subscribe to such services by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle noted most residential Internet users pay about $20 a
month. He said if they're asked to pay $70, ``a pretty decent
percentage of the people are going to drop off.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ADSL suffers from a crucial limitation. It only
works for people who live within 18,000 feet of a telephone company
central office _ roughly three miles. Bell Atlantic officials have
estimated that about 60 percent of their local lines will be able
to use ADSL.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-03-98 2101EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
