<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: INTERNET AD DEALS PICK UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pace of deals involving interactive advertising accelerated
Wednesday as three acquisitions and affiliations were announced.
</P>
<P>
   In one deal, 24/7 Media Inc. in New York acquired Cliqnow Sales
Group, the Internet advertising sales representation division of K2
Design Inc. in New York, for $1 million in cash and $3 million in
convertible preferred stock of 24/7.
</P>
<P>
   Cliqnow, which K2 started in 1996, has 10 employees who handle
ad sales for 75 Web sites including those of The Associated Press,
PR Newswire and the Women's Forum. Cliqnow will operate as an
autonomous unit of 24/7 with sales staffs in Chicago, Los Angeles,
New York and San Francisco, and the Cliqnow sub-networks, offering
computer users content on topics like finance and travel, will
operate separately from the 24/7 network.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cliqnow has been successful, said Matthew de Ganon,
president at K2, ``we need to focus specifically on our core
interactive advertising and media business.'' The sale, he added,
would enable K2 to concentrate on that ``and pursue aggressive
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Paternoster, 32, president at Cliqnow, and Joe Apprendi,
31, executive vice president, will continue in those roles and also
become senior vice presidents at 24/7.
</P>
<P>
   The second deal involved Double Click Inc. in New York, an
interactive advertising network, and Ad Knowledge in Palo Alto,
Calif., which provides tools for Internet media planning and buying
and campaign management. The two companies have formed a strategic
partnership; financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the affiliation is to integrate the technologies of
the two companies to create standard industry platforms for Web ad
management that would help make buying and selling online
advertising more efficient and effective. Ad Knowledge will now
focus primarily on operations intended to help advertisers and
agencies buy ads on the Internet while Double Click will support
the Ad Knowledge operations focused on selling ads on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, customers of Click Wise, the Ad Knowledge Web site
ad management software, will now be about to use the Double Click
DART service, a proprietary technology offering ad server,
reporting and tracking abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the online ad industry continues to expand, there is
significant benefit to creating uniform standards for site
publishers and advertising agencies,'' said Kevin O'Connor,
chairman and chief executive at Double Click. ``With the
standardization that this partnership represents, we believe that
online advertising will improve industry-wide. And, by
consolidating our efforts with Ad Knowledge, we believe we can
expand DART's reach and market penetration.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Kauffman, president and chief exective at Ad Knowledge
said, ``We believe DART provides the best solution for Web site
publishers and we are confident our Click Wise customers will
benefit tremendously from the power of Double Click advanced
technology.'' Both Kauffman, 41, and O'Connor, 37, will continue in
their respective roles.
</P>
<P>
   The third deal involved Interactive8, an online marketing agency
in New York, which acquired Tuckett/Parshall Interactive in New
York, a specialist in interactive advertising aimed at black
consumers. Financial terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuckett/Parshall, which will be renamed as the TPI division of
Interactive8, has estimated billings of $500,000 from clients like
Essence magazine, Motown Records and Morgan Stanley, Dean Witter &AMP;
Co. TPI will be headed by Lawrence Tuckett, 43, founder and partner
at Tuckett/Parshall, who also becomes creative director, and
Michael Waite, 30, partner, who becomes executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition ``puts us at the forefront of urban online
marketing and will greatly benefit companies expanding into the
African-American consumer demographic,'' said Bill Markel, partner
at Interactive8. Interactive8 has 37 employees and estimated
billings of $4.9 million from clients like AT&AMP;T Corp., the Citibank
unit of Citicorp and the M&AMP;M/Mars unit of Mars Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The quickening pace of deal-making in cyberspace is echoing the
frenzied deal-making among traditional agencies as well as
reflecting how the dynamics of interactive advertising and
marketing are changing rapidly as the industry grows.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet-related deals in the last month included two
acquisitions by Agency.com in New York; the purchase of Digital
Cafe, a digital media agency in St. Paul, by Campbell Mithun Esty
in Minneapolis, which is majority owned by the Interpublic Group;
the acquisition of Circle Interactive in Boston by Arnold
Communications, a unit of Snyder Communications in Boston, and the
expansion of the online career services of TMP Worldwide in New
York through the purchase of two Web sites, About Work and Student
Center, from Ivillage in New York for $1.7 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-03-98 1902EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
