<HEADLINE>
RIVEN TO DESPAIR BY THE GOLDEN DOME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY  
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I've been stuck at the same place in Riven for
almost a month. How do I get into the golden dome?
</P>
<P>
   _ Frustrated
</P>
<P>
   DEAR FRUS: Just follow the fine example set by presidents, major
corporations, millions of taxpayers and my last six wives: Cheat
your rear end off.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe you have that pride thing going, but get a grip. Are
you going to spend the next two years of your bleak little life
staring slack-jawed and red-eyed at a cruelly mocking computer
screen, coming up with even more and more improbable, incorrect
solutions to your little quandary? Or are you going to rejoin us
here on Earth? It's just a game! You lost!
</P>
<P>
   By the way, I've been inside the dome. Nothing there but more
impossible-to-solve puzzles that will drive you crazy and your wife
to a divorce lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   You've given it a fair shot. It's time to take it like a French
soldier and run up the white flag. Fortunately, for cheats and cads
like us, there is a whole subculture of gamers more than willing to
help.
</P>
<P>
   From the instant a new game hits the shelves, it's as if there's
a contest to see who can finish it first and post the solution on
the Internet. Sure, the game manufacturers may try to bleed another
20 bucks out of you for an official hint book, but you can get the
same stuff for free if you know where to surf.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, try doing a Yahoo! or Excite search with this
phrase: ``Riven and cheat or walkthrough.'' You'll discover entire
Web sites devoted to cheating your way through life. Second, if
you're still foolishly clinging to that bizarre concept of honesty
and morality, try checking out news groups, those bulletin boards
of badinage, banter and bull. Subscribe to some of the gaming
groups. You'll find ones devoted to Riven and Myst, its
predecessor. Here, you can trade hints back and forth, and you only
have to spoil as much of the thrill of conquest as you need to
maintain your sanity.
</P>
<P>
   And, last, if you were so worried about ethics, you wouldn't
have claimed your computer room as home office space on your tax
return, especially not since you just admitted to the whole world
that all you do is play games there. Don't worry, the IRS doesn't
read this column. Well, not very often, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I use the Internet regularly, although just to
access Web sites. I never use chat rooms, etc. Do I need anti-virus
software?
</P>
<P>
   _ Mr. Clean
</P>
<P>
   DEAR CLEAN: Venturing anywhere on the Internet without a virus
scanner is as dangerous as using a bus-station toilet. There are
just too many acne-faced, prepubertal dweebs with no life who think
that messing with your computer makes them elite hackers instead of
pitiful wastes of skin.
</P>
<P>
   Go to www.tucows.com and check out the wide selection of
scanners. Some are shareware, others are trial versions, but please
snag something. Look for one that monitors your system continually
and automatically checks new files you download. It's not just
programs you have to watch out for, though. The little geeks have
even found ways to spread their electronic mayhem though
word-processing documents and Web page coding.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you're reading this column on the Internet without
anti-virus software, you may be susceptible to Bombay Booboo, the
dreaded virus that suddenly causes text on your screen to garble
and krelmar yo radney glitzdorf. .MDBU/.MDNM/ (Noted
computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally accurate
advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on Internet
at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817) 390-7257.
His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
