<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 FTC Seeks Online Privacy Law for Children  
 By Jon Swartz   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Web surfers _ especially children _ have little privacy
protection on the Internet, and Congress should step in to shield
minors, the Federal Trade Commission said in a scathing report
issued yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, part of an exhaustive three-year investigation,
are based on a poll of 1,400 Web sites. Of those monitored, 85
percent collected personal information from surfers, but only 14
percent informed customers how they use it. The five-member
commission said children were more likely than adults to volunteer
information on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed with the Internet industry's attempts to
self-regulate its basic fair information practices,'' FTC
commissioner Mozelle Thompson said in an interview. ``In most
cases, data was collected silently and then dispersed over the
World Wide Web almost instantly. This isn't like losing a credit
card in a restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC report confirms the worst fears of privacy advocates,
who claim the Internet is overrun with sites that ask users to fill
out electronic questionnaires with their names, home and e-mail
addresses, phone numbers and credit-card numbers and then peddle
this information to marketing companies.
</P>
<P>
   Among the survey's findings:
</P>
<P>
   _More than 90 percent of the commercial Web sites polled collect
personal data, but only 2 percent have a comprehensive policy on
how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   _Nine out of 10 sites aimed at children seek personal
information about visitors, yet only 23 percent advise kids to get
parental permission.
</P>
<P>
   _Of the 100 most popular Web sites, 97 percent glean personal
data. However, 71 percent of those sites have policies about what
to do with information they gather.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC is urging Congress to draft a bill that would require
Web sites to get parental consent before collecting information
from those under 13.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also may propose new regulations in the coming
months regarding broader issues of privacy on the Internet, FTC
Chairman Robert Pitofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every AOL, IBM or other online service that has a
legitimate privacy policy, there are thousands who don't,'' the
FTC's Thompson said. ``I find that extremely troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is a searing indictment of the administration's
year-old policy urging Web sites to ensure privacy by disclosing
how personal data would be used and disseminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It underscores the Clinton administration's failed policy of
letting Internet companies police privacy themselves,'' said Jeff
Chester, executive director of the nonprofit Center for Media
Education in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Schwartz, policy analyst at the civil liberties group Center
for Democracy and Technology in Washington, D.C., said the sheer
size and scope of the Internet make it necessary for the FTC and
Congress to ``set some baseline standards to separate the bad
actors from the good actors.''
</P>
<P>
   In a last-minute attempt to stave off legislation, industry
leaders are scrambling to form self-regulating bodies that would
address privacy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a dozen trade groups _ led by the Business Software
Alliance and Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association _
adopted privacy standards to give individuals the choice to ``opt
out'' of data collection.
</P>
<P>
   Former FTC Commissioner Christine Varney and AOL chief executive
Steve Case also are in the process of shepherding organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the FTC report, industry leaders contend that online
shopping is a relatively safe proposition. The leading
electronic-commerce sites have detailed privacy policies against
circulating consumers' personal data without permission, the report
found.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are five to seven times more likely to have your privacy
invaded offline. There are few instances of identity theft,'' said
Susan Scott, executive director of the nonprofit group TRUSTe in
Palo Alto. The company has a privacy-notification seal that is used
by 135 e-commerce sites, including Disney, America Online and
Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to foster trust in order to create consumer
confidence,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-04-98 2143EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
