<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TV-NEWSVIEWERS-MEDIA-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE, INTERNET GAINING AS NEWS SOURCE FOR AMERICANS, SURVEY 
FINDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204
or 1927.)  
By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following a pattern seen in entertainment viewing, Americans now
watch news programs on cable television networks about as regularly
as those on broadcast networks, according to a survey by the Pew
Research Center for the People and the Press.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also found that the number of people who get
their news from the Internet is rising rapidly and they estimated
that almost as many people use the Internet on a typical weekday as
spend time reading a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of American adults, or an estimated 36 million
people, get news from the Internet at least once a week, the survey
found, compared with 6 percent, or about 11 million, two years ago,
when Pew conducted a similar survey. Those who use the Internet for
news are disproportionately younger, better educated and more
affluent, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   As for television, more than half of those surveyed said they
watch the news with a remote control in their hands, poised to
change the channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a quixotic audience,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the
Washington-based Pew research group. ``Post-Cold War, people say
local news is much more important to them than national or
international news. We found that in the survey and in focus groups
afterward, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of Americans who watch the network evening news
and local news only on broadcast television has fallen to 15
percent, from 30 percent five years ago, according to the telephone
survey of 3,002 adults conducted April 24 to May 11.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey done two years ago, Kohut said, ``We found all
news viewership going down, but this time the slide is limited to
broadcast networks and to a certain extent CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Fully 40 percent of Americans said they regularly watched one of
the leading cable news networks (CNN, CNBC, MSNBC or Fox News
Channel), while 57 percent said they watched the major broadcast
networks' morning, evening and prime-time news programs regularly.
When the Weather Channel and ESPN's Sports Center program are
added, the cable figure grows to 60 percent, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   These responses may seem inconsistent with Nielsen ratings,
which show most cable news networks getting minuscule ratings.
Gregory Flemming, one of the survey's directors, said this was
because Nielsen measures actual viewership by program or time
period, while the survey's tally of viewers who say they watch
``regularly'' might include people who watch only one show a day
(but almost every day) or people who tune in for a few minutes
several times a day.
</P>
<P>
   Only 38 percent described themselves as regular viewers of the
ABC, CBS or NBC evening news broadcasts, compared with 60 percent
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   An obvious advantage for the cable news networks is that they
have news around the clock, unlike the broadcast networks. Most
Americans said they would turn to cable channels first if a big
news event broke. Indeed, 46 percent of Americans surveyed said
they only follow national news when a major event is occurring, and
67 percent said that is the only time they follow international
news.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The survey found the average American spends an hour a day
absorbing news _ whether from television, radio or newspapers _ but
the amount of time varies widely with age. Older people watch and
read more news than younger people.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, young people are the most likely to go online to
get news, and even though they pursue news less often, large
numbers of young people said they enjoyed having the wide variety
of choice in news sources that is available today.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate Pew survey about the credibility of news
organizations, conducted May 7-13 among 981 adults, CNN ranked
highest in ``believability'' among broadcast and cable television
sources, with CBS's ``60 Minutes'' second. The syndicated tabloid
television show ``Inside Edition'' ranked lowest, with National
Public Radio second lowest.
</P>
<P>
   The survey broke down respondents by age, income and whether
they were occasional, moderate or frequent news viewers.
Information about the survey may be obtained from the Pew Center
for Research on the People and the Press, 1150 18th Street, NW,
Washington, D.C. 20036, or on the Internet at
http://www.people-press.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-07-98 1845EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
