<HEADLINE>
NEW INTERNET JOB SEARCH SERVICE FOR MID-LEVEL MANAGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many companies, recruiting executives is like looking for
needles in a haystack. The Wall Street Journal and Korn/Ferry
International, a leading executive search firm, hope to use the
Internet to get the needles to emerge on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies plan to announce Monday a national rollout of
``Futurestep,'' a service that seeks to recruit midlevel managers
via the Web and match them with prospective employers. There is a
second high-technology twist: Futurestep automates the cumbersome
recruiting process by using software designed to match a person's
skills and interests with job types.
</P>
<P>
   The service is free to prospective employees, who fill out a
questionnaire at www.futurestep.com, listing background and job
interests. The software then grades the responses; it is capable of
determining what job and corporate culture an employee best fits,
said Man Jit Singh, the chief executive of Futurestep.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective employers who have submitted job openings to
Futurestep will receive a list of potential candidates selected
from the data base _ along with a videotaped interview of the top
prospects. If a company hires a candidate, it pays Futurestep 30
percent of the first year's cash salary, a standard executive
recruiting fee.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is aimed at reducing the time it takes to find
midlevel managers _ who typically make between $75,000 and $200,000
_ and thus make the process cost effective, said Michael Boxberger,
chief executive of Korn/Ferry.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, The Wall Street Journal, a unit of Dow Jones &AMP;
Co., hopes to capitalize on the success of its executive recruiting
classified advertising, which presently is the single largest
classified category in the print version of The Journal, said Mike
Wilson, the company's director of classified advertising. The
Journal plans to make Futurestep a component of its Wall Street
Journal Interactive Edition career site, www.careers.wsj.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal will also seek to entice its print-based advertisers
to participate. The advertisers can put the Futurestep Web address
on their advertisements then have Futurestep sort incoming resumes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-07-98 1834EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
