<HEADER>
A2476 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTELMS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-10 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTELMS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Wintel Showdown  
 By Julia Angwin and Jamie Beckett   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Both halves of the WinTel alliance _ Microsoft and Intel _ now
stand accused of unfair business practices by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   But the case against chipmaking giant Intel _ brought by the FTC
yesterday _ is much less damaging than the case against software
giant Microsoft, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more on the periphery of Intel's business than the
Microsoft case, which goes to the core of its business,'' said
Nathan Brookwood, an analyst at Dataquest in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust enforcers at the FTC yesterday accused Intel of
unfairly withholding crucial information about its computer chips
from customers that challenged its patents. Antitrust enforcers at
the Justice Department and 20 states accused Microsoft last month
of unfairly including its Web browser in its leading Windows
operating system software.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, both cases appear to be similar government
actions against high-tech giants. But in fact, they are as
different as the button-down culture at Intel is from the younger,
feistier Microsoft style.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft CEO Bill Gates, 42, responded to the Justice lawsuit
with a nationally broadcast press conference. In strongly worded
remarks, he accused antitrust regulators of ``trying to promote
their ideas of software design ...and trying to punish an American
company that has worked hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Intel CEO Craig Barrett, 58, was traveling in Japan
yesterday and had no comment on the FTC lawsuit. Intel Chairman
Andrew Grove, 61, also had no comment. The Santa Clara company's
only official response was a six-paragraph statement from chief
counsel Tom Dunlap that addressed the legal merits of the suit in a
mild tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel intends to work through the administrative complaint
process and if necessary appeal to a federal court,'' Dunlap said.
``We believe that ultimately that process will conclude that our
actions are lawful.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts said that Intel's understated reaction is also due to
the fact that it doesn't feel very threatened by the narrow scope
of the FTC lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the suit only focuses on information Intel
distributes to its customers rather than broader questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case doesn't go to the heart of the Intel development and
marketing machine,'' said Jack Russo, a high-tech lawyer in Palo
Alto.
</P>
<P>
   The case also is not likely to resonate with the computer-buying
public in the same way as the Microsoft suit. Unlike the unassuming
Barrett, Microsoft chief Gates, the richest man in the country, has
attained a celebrity status. In addition, while almost every
computer user is familiar with Microsoft's software, relatively few
have opened up their machines to tinker with the Intel chip inside.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel case is not generating as much interest among Silicon
Valley consumers and workers as the hotly debated Microsoft case
did.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those interviewed yesterday knew little about the Intel
case. Those who were familiar with the charges were reluctant to
openly criticize their powerful Silicon Valley neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be applying for a job at Intel someday,'' explained
one engineer, who works for semiconductor equipment-maker Applied
Materials, just a few miles away from Intel.
</P>
<P>
   He and a co-worker were spending their lunch hour browsing
computer superstore T-Zone, a popular Silicon Valley shopping spot.
</P>
<P>
   His companion, also an engineer, said he agrees that Intel has
become too powerful, but hopes the government doesn't come down too
hard because he fears curtailing Intel could hurt the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel does have some unethical practices, but I don't want to
see the FTC put a crimp in the (computer) market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A technology marketer lunching at the Sandwich Construction
delicatessen across the street from Intel declined even to give the
name of his company, which is an Intel customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel's our neighbor. They support the economy. They help
maintain property values. They employ thousands of people in the
Valley,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some said they prefer Intel, the home team, to the upstart
outsiders in Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel keeps quiet and it knows what it's doing,'' added an
electrical technician whose company sells chip-making chemicals to
Intel. ``Bill Gates does not keep quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-08-98 2141EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
