<SLUG> BC-SINKING-YEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINKING YEN BEGINS NEW PHASE OF JAPAN'S CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``i'' and ``f'' categories.)   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Bernard D. Kaplan  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The plummeting yen has opened a new phase in the
Japanese crisis, suggesting that even more serious problems lie
ahead for the world's second largest economy, according to
international analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The yen stood this week at 140 to the dollar, a loss of 40
percent in value over the past four years. Although Japan's
currency has been gradually losing strength for many months, recent
losses have been so great that some experts say the decline signals
a wholesale drop in confidence at home and abroad in the country's
entire economic system and its potential for reform.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Japan's exports have remained an outstanding
exception to a flagging economy crippled by inadequate domestic
demand.
</P>
<P>
   But the financial crisis elsewhere in Asia ``has called into
question the continuing demand for Japanese products in key markets
like Indonesia and Hong Kong,'' according to Frank Satsumi, an
international management consultant here. ``The dramatic fall of
the yen reflects these fears.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the sliding yen will make Japanese exports cheaper and
therefore more competitive in North America and some other markets,
most experts agreed that the advantage to Japan will be marginal.
On the other hand, the fall in the yen will make Japanese imports
more expensive and above all will heighten the anxiety of Japan's
consumers over the way their economy is performing.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government expressed alarm Tuesday that the yen's
fall could have a severe impact on China's economy, reducing
Beijing's exports and lessening investment from abroad. China and
Japan are major trading partners, and the Chinese are worried that
Japan's financial problems will lead Tokyo to cut its investments
in Chinese industries considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Tokyo stock market and Japan's financial
institutions continue struggling unsuccessfully to recover. Shares
on the stock exchange represent barely half of their 1990 value
while the banks have done little to overcome a staggering load of
bad debt that may still total $400 billion. In recent months,
Japanese banks have lost $15 billion in Indonesia alone.
</P>
<P>
   The banks' losses and the deflated stock market are linked
because many banks own shares in companies and have seen their
value sharply decline.
</P>
<P>
   One consequence is that Japanese bankers now refuse to provide
even small loans to their country's own enterprises, according to
Margaret Dupre, a financial specialist here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The banks are panicked at the thought of more bad debt,'' she
explained. ``So Japanese firms aren't receiving the financing they
urgently require. Production is stagnating and may grow by less
than 0.3 percent this year. Unemployment was once virtually
nonexistent but is currently more than 4 percent, unprecedentedly
high for Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's successive plans to relaunch the economy have
floundered, boosting the already high degree of political
disillusionment of the average citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Satsumi pointed out that the thrifty Japanese possess an
estimated $8 billion in savings, which government officials would
like to see spent on consumer goods and invested in the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``People refuse to spend,'' he said. ``They don't trust the
government, which they regard as inept and corrupt. They are
holding onto their money.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Japan's reputation for thrift is only partly
merited. ``The average person saves, but the government is
notoriously profligate,'' he said. ~~``The national debt equals the
annual production of goods and services, making Japan a financially
unstable country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
