<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTEL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL'S GO-GO DAYS SEEM OVER, AT LEAST FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER AND LISA GONDERINGER   
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Intel Corp. faces a triumvirate of troubles: layoffs,
lackluster stock performance and now a government lawsuit that
could define antitrust laws in the digital age.
</P>
<P>
   Are the go-go days of Intel gone-gone, at least for now?
</P>
<P>
   By most indications, yes.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock is down almost $30 since mid-February, it's
earning less money, it was slapped Monday with an antitrust action
by the Federal Trade Commission and it's cutting 3,000 jobs,
including 600 in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad year for Intel,'' said Jeff Weir, spokesman for
the Semiconductor Industry Association. ``They're not all that
different than everyone else in the industry, but they just have
one more example with the FTC action.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, few Intel employees say they're worried. They
praise the company for notifying employees early of the layoffs,
which begin in October and come with four months' pay and benefits,
and shrug off the lawsuit as a political poker game.
</P>
<P>
   Weir agrees, saying the problems are nothing new for the plucky
company that maintains an entrepreneurial spirit despite sales of
$25 billion a year and worldwide employment of 64,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're relentless in their style, with their
take-no-prisoners attitude and only-the-paranoid survive
approach,'' he said. ``They've responded to every challenge
historically and thrived through every challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think given that history, anyone's going to assume
that they can't overcome this,'' Weir said.
</P>
<P>
   But from one insider's perspective, there is worry on the part
of Intel's legion of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These folks are exceedingly achievement-oriented
individuals,'' said a consultant who trains workers at Intel and
other high-tech employers in the Valley. ``The confidence is a
little bit shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   The old adage was that Intel didn't have customers, it had
hostages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, people are a little bit scared,'' added the consultant,
who is prohibited by the company from talking about Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Fear is not obvious in visits to various haunts around Intel
facilities. Some workers believe they are immune from the cutbacks,
either because their job is needed or their work performance is
superior.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who have lost their jobs are optimistic that they'll
land something else with the state's second-largest private
employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in software development, and if that's all I could do,
yeah, I'd be nervous,'' said one female worker, who declined to
give her name. ``But there are so many more things, like systems
analysis, et cetera, that I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   But her optimism might be misguided.
</P>
<P>
   The entire semiconductor industry is in a tailspin, due in part
to the Asian economic crisis. The bust is prompting Motorola Inc.,
the state's largest private employer, to slash 15,000 jobs
worldwide, including perhaps 2,000 in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Motorola's shocking news, it was in the process of
closing two product lines, idling more than 400 workers in the
Valley. The communications giant cut 225 positions with the
shutdown of its Advanced Custom Technologies team in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Another 180 workers lost jobs at the chip-making factory at 52nd
Street and McDowell Road.
</P>
<P>
   The losses mean Intel engineers will have one less place to find
work.
</P>
<P>
   Even Microchip Technology Inc., a Chandler-based maker of
microcontrollers that has weathered the chip downturn better than
most, isn't looking to employ Intel workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have any plans to do promotions or target the
employees that are being laid off at Intel,'' said spokesman Eric
Sells.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's woes are exaggerated by factors both inside and outside
the company.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest chipmaker said May 29 that it will delay its
next-generation microprocessor, Merced, until mid-2000. The chip
had been expected to be released in the second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The company also faces stiff competition from computer systems
costing less than $1,000, which don't use Intel's latest chip
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Added to that are waning financial results. The Santa Clara,
Calif., company made $1.3 billion in the first quarter, down 36
percent from the same period a year ago. It expects revenue in the
second quarter to be flat or even decrease.
</P>
<P>
   The problems come just months after Intel Chairman Andrew Grove,
a co-founder, relinquished his job as chief executive officer to
Valley resident Craig Barrett. Barrett has been with the company
full time since 1974 and was picked last year as its president.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as having their dirty laundry aired in public through
the lawsuit, it does hurt their public image,'' said Bill McClean,
president of Scottsdale-based IC Insights, a market researcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you (Intel) are truly the only option, it doesn't
really hurt the bottom line.'' &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at 444-8975 or at
kerry.fehr(at)pni.com. Lisa Gonderinger can be reached at 444-7976
or at lisa.gonderinger(at)pni.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-08-98 2129EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
