 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Netw(at)atch: She doesn't log on, but 'McBealers' are Web-savvy 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The disturbing news hit the wires late last week. The
24- to 39-year-old age group once dubbed Generation X by author
Douglas Coupland has been renamed by telecommunications company
MCI. MCI has chosen to dub them ``The Ally McBealers'' after the
lovable but neurotic TV lawyer noted for hyper-short skirts and
fantasies about her ex-boyfriend and dancing babies.
</P>
<P>
   Ally McBealers, in their viewing of the Fox show ``Ally
McBeal,'' might have noticed Ally is never shown using a computer.
She's got a laptop, but in all probability she probably spilled
cappuccino on the keyboard one day and now she gets the message
``keyboard error'' every time she tries to log on.
</P>
<P>
   But Ally aside, according to MCI, the McBealers are the most
Web-savvy of any age group. But what Web sites do they have
bookmarked? Here are some likely candidates:
</P>
<P>
   If asked, McBealers would probably say they only read Salon
(http://www .salonmagazine.com) and The New York Times
(http://www.nytimes .com). But in truth, every McBealer worth his
or her salt has surely checked out the online e-zine Swoon
(http://www.swoon.com). The online home of such Conde Nast
magazines as Details, Glamour and Mademoiselle, the site bills
itself as the magazine of ``dating, mating and relating.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, one can peruse items such as Mademoiselle's self-discovery
test called ``What's Your True Passion?'' or the Details article
``One Man. Five Ex-Girlfriends. You Do the Math.'' There's also a
personals section so McBealers can all get over their latest failed
relationship and dive headlong into another one.
</P>
<P>
   And to help McBealers on their way to another iffy relationship
is Match.com (http://www.match.com).The San Francisco-based Web
site is one of the best, least predatory, dating Web sites out
there. For two weeks, it's possible to test the service and search
for suitable mates based on a set of criteria the user selects,
including age, location, religion and even weight. Match.com
doesn't use real names, and the service employs an anonymous
remailer so if there are any psychos lurking on the service,
they'll never be able to find their way to your door.
</P>
<P>
   As anyone who watches ``Ally McBeal'' knows, Ally never goes
right home after work. She goes with all her co-workers to the same
bar, night after night, week after week. Most McBealers need a
little more variety than that in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   For this, there are a variety of entertainment sites this group
can visit to find out what's happening in their little chunk of the
universe. Since Ally lives in Boston, she might check out Boston
Sidewalk (http://boston.sidewalk.com), the Microsoft-run arts and
entertainment Web site with dining, drinking and entertainment
tips. Sidewalk has sites for most major cities, but some cities
have their own locally grown entertainment directories such as
Access Atlanta (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .accessatlanta.com/entertaiment/index.htm), which can send
Atlanta's McBealers on their way to dining, music and movie
nirvana, with content from various partners including The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Some McBealers may have absolutely no idea -- strange as it may
sound -- who in the world Ally McBeal is. If you're wondering what
exactly you've been named after, visit the official McBeal home
page at http://www.foxworld.com/ally. And for those of you who are
hooked, there is always the ultimate Ally McBeal fan page at
http://www.geocities.com/Hollywood/Hills/2927/faq.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-08-98 1905EDT &QL;
</P>
