<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETWATCH09-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Some of Web's best stories may turn out to be myths 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do not believe everything you read.
</P>
<P>
   This may seem like obvious advice, but when it comes to the
Internet, it's worth repeating, or maybe scrawling in indelible ink
across the top of your computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most skeptical news junkie who checks at least five TV
networks and the newspaper before giving it any credibility will
believe anything e-mailed to them by a friend of a friend of a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   So before you hit the ``forward'' button to send any words of
wisdom on to your friends and co-workers, think about the following
Internet ruses.
</P>
<P>
   The Neiman-Marcus cookie story must have circled the globe more
times than all the NASA astronauts put together and is still going
strong. For a while, the official Nieman Marcus Web site had an
entire section devoted to debunking the story of the woman who
supposedly paid $250 for the recipe for Neiman's chocolate chip
cookies. The woman's alleged revenge was to post the recipe on the
Internet in the hopes that it would get as much attention as it is
getting. If nobody has sent you this recipe yet, you can check it
out at http://www.circ.uab
</P>
<P>
   .edu/cookies.html. And if you do have the ingredients on hand,
it won't cost you anything to whip up a batch.
</P>
<P>
   Another e-mail hoax sent round the world, was the alleged 1997
commencement speech given by noted American author Kurt Vonnegut at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. The speech was a
collection of homespun wisdom that began with the sentence ``Ladies
and Gentlemen of the class of '97: Wear sunscreen. If I could offer
you only one tip for the future, sunscreen would be it.''
</P>
<P>
   You can read the rest of the speech at
http://www.cyberlink2000.com/9vonnegu.htm, but you should know
Vonnegut neither wrote nor delivered this speech. What's more
Vonnegut was not MIT's 1997 commencement speaker. Secretary General
of the United Nations Kofi Annan was. The pearls of wisdom were
actually from a column written by Chicago Tribune staff writer Mary
Schmich. Schmich offers her own take on being mistaken (at least in
cyberspace) for Vonnegut in one of her columns, which can be read
at http://www.recoil.com/mqarianstuff/wb/vonnegut.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   Stories such as these quickly pass into legend among cyberspace
veterans. They have become what is known as ``urban legends.''
There is an entire Web site devoted to the cataloguing and
debunking of these tall tales at http://www.urbanlegends.com.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how these rumors get started. But be warned that
once something appears on the Internet it can circle the world at
an astonishing speed.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of the erroneous Associated Press report last
week. In error, the AP posted an obituary for comic Bob Hope on its
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey (R-Texas) believed the report
was real and asked that Hope's passing be announced on the floor of
the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-08-98 1753EDT &QL;
</P>
