<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Sources Say Intel Bullying Into 3-D 
By Tom Abate   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's an allegation against Intel that the Federal Trade
Commission isn't investigating _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   Two industry sources said yesterday that Intel has been trying
to muscle its way into the 3-D market by ``bundling'' its 3-D chip
_ the I-740 _ with its Pentium II microprocessor and Pentium II
chipset.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said Intel has told Taiwanese PC vendors that the
best way to get large volumes of Pentium IIs is to buy them as a
package deal with I-740 3-D graphics chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to at least 20 companies at a trade show here, and
that's what they're saying,'' market researcher John Latta said
yesterday in an interview from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Latta is president of 4thWave, a market research firm in
Alexandria, Va., that publishes a newsletter for industry
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Peddie, a Tiburon-based chip analyst, confirmed some parts
of Latta's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwanese motherboard manufacturers are horny as hell for
Pentium IIs, and they may be accepting these bundle deals to get
more P2s,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust lawyers say it can be anti-competitive if a company
with monopoly power bundles new products with its market-leading
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Peddie said he didn't think that Intel would be ``stupid
enough'' to do anything illegal. But he described Intel as a
newcomer to the 3-D market, trying to take share from S3, ATI,
Matrox, Cirrus Logic, Trident, 3DFX, Rendition and 3D Labs.
</P>
<P>
   An executive at one 3-D firm, who asked to remain anonymous,
told me that Intel's tactics have hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had dinner with one (Taiwanese) customer the day after he
met with (a top Intel exec),'' the source said. ``Our customer said
he would have to buy Intel's 3-D graphics chip'' to get other Intel
chips.
</P>
<P>
   The executive has never complained to the FTC because he doesn't
think the feds can move fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   Intel spokesman Tom Waldrop said Latta is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bundling report is untrue,'' he said, rejecting ``any
inference there that there's some antitrust violation. We are very
careful with our (sales) policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldrop said the supply of Pentium II chips is increasing very
rapidly and that there is no shortage for Intel to take advantage
of.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Intel characterized the 3-D allegations as
``piling on'' by competitors trying to exploit yesterday's
antitrust news.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Here come da judge: &LR;  The FTC's antitrust case now goes to
administrative law Judge James Timony.
</P>
<P>
   Art Amolsch, editor of the FTCWatch Newsletter, described Timony
as an independent jurist who has been known to reject cases that he
feels are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Timony did several years ago, when the FTC voted to
file suit against the college football association, alleging that
it had restricted the supply of televised college football by
deciding which schools could sell broadcast rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timony said the FTC has no power over nonprofit groups, and
ultimately, his view prevailed,'' Amolsch said.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, Timony ruled that New Jersey-based Toys `R' Us
had illegally tried to keep toy manufacturers from selling toys to
shopping clubs. That case is still on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Personal notes: &LR;  The four FTC commissioners who debated
Intel's fate are a colorful lot. Their chairman is Bob Pitofsky, a
former Georgetown University law professor and expert on antitrust
law. It was he who engineered the three-vote majority in favor of
taking action against Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Joining him was Sheila Anthony, a personal friend of Bill and
Hillary Clinton and sister of late White House aide Vincent Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Mozelle Thompson, a former Treasury official, cast the third
``Yes'' vote, leaving Orson Swindle, the commission's lone
Republican, to cast the single dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Swindle was the first national leader of Ross Perot's United We
Stand America group. A former Marine aviator, Swindle was shot down
over Vietnam and spent several years in a North Vietnamese POW
camp. His cellmate was John McCain, now a U.S. senator from
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-08-98 2144EDT &QL;
</P>
