<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PIXEL-MYSPACE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE WAY AROUND WINDOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By WARREN WILSON   
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If Microsoft Windows were a religion, a core belief
would be that the computer screen and the Windows desktop are
nearly the same thing: The desktop fills the screen and displays
everything the user needs to know.
</P>
<P>
   Time for some heresy, Seattle software designer Tom O'Rourke
says.
</P>
<P>
   O'Rourke's new venture, The Pixel Co., unveiled technology
Monday that uses the dark border at the edge of the desktop for a
new control bar called MySpace that is separate from Microsoft
Windows and can launch applications, find Internet content and
control devices such as CD and DVD players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting technology,'' said analyst Bob Sakakeeny of The
Aberdeen Group in Boston. ``We can't think of anything that comes
close.''
</P>
<P>
   If it wins market acceptance, MySpace might loosen Microsoft's
lock on the PC screen. And it could lob a new rock into the pond of
legal, technological, political and economic issues surrounding
Microsoft that led to the federal antitrust lawsuits filed last
month.
</P>
<P>
   While supporting Microsoft's key legal claim that the software
industry is rich with innovation, MySpace could give computer
makers something the government says they lack _ non-Microsoft ways
to customize their machines. It also undermines claims by
Microsoft's critics that the Redmond company stifles innovation by
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a case where a small company did something that Sun,
Oracle and Netscape all said couldn't be done, and that's get
around the Microsoft franchise,'' said Rob Enderle, an industry
analyst with the Giga Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's new, it's fresh, it's different,'' said Martin Mortensen
of The Gartner Group in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a piece of technology that basically shows that Microsoft
isn't that dominant, that they do allow other technologies to come
up to the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokeswoman said the company couldn't comment
because it hadn't yet seen the MySpace technology.
</P>
<P>
   At Ark Interface II, Pixel's parent company, O'Rourke has
specialized in software that sits atop the Windows operating system
to give users what he believes are easier ways to find files and
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Ark developed a program called Navigator (older than and
completely different from the Internet browser made by Netscape
Communications) that employed a home metaphor similar to that of
Microsoft's short-lived ``Bob'' project.
</P>
<P>
   Packard Bell liked Navigator so much that it first licensed
Navigator to install on its machines, then purchased Ark Interface
in 1994. Over time, however, Microsoft's efforts to standardize the
Windows experience made it more difficult for computer makers to
offer shell programs like Navigator, O'Rourke said.
</P>
<P>
   The MySpace project was born 15 months ago, he said, when, in a
fit of frustration, he noticed a picture-in-picture display on his
television and wondered if the same thing couldn't be done on a
computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said, `You can't go there,''' O'Rourke said. He
begged to differ, gradually persuading colleagues that it would be
possible to use the dark territory outside the desktop, called the
overscan area, to deliver new features.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken over that dead space and built a little kernel of
an operating system that lets it have some functionality,'' said
Lora Loftis, Pixel's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   That's a key point: MySpace isn't an application that runs on
top of Windows, it's a separate system.
</P>
<P>
   It can launch Windows applications, but it could just as easily
launch some other operating system _ Linux, Unix, or an eventual
Java OS, O'Rourke said.
</P>
<P>
   It also provides a space where other companies can offer their
content to computer users in partnership with Pixel and the
computer makers, instead of or in addition to partnering with
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   An entertainment company, for example, could put buttons on the
MySpace control bar that connected people directly to its Web sites
for books or television programs.
</P>
<P>
   Ark Interface II spun off The Pixel Co. last year. The two were
recently sold by the parent company, now called Packard Bell NEC,
the fourth-largest PC vendor in the United States and the
fifth-largest in the world, according to International Data Corp.
It shipped 2.8 million units in the United States last year and 4.2
million worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Packard Bell NEC plans to offer MySpace on new Packard Bell
machines and NEC's consumer line, called Ready, in the near future,
though not on its first Windows 98 machines, said Mal Ransom,
senior vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's technology that makes sense,'' Ransom said. ``When you
see it, you think, why did it take somebody so long to discover it?
But the market will have to speak for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Enderle said MySpace offered computer makers a way to make their
products stand out in the marketplace, while Sakakeeny noted that
the legal and political attention focused on Microsoft may work to
Pixel's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is pretty good for acceptance of a product like
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both analysts echoed Ransom's cautionary note.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest struggle is not for them to do a good job creating
the product, it's getting the product accepted,'' Sakakeeny said.
``That's not an easy feat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens a number of doors,'' Enderle said. ``The question is
whether (software) developers will take advantage of them....
</P>
<P>
   ``In reviewing the people they have on board, I certainly think
there's a reasonable chance they can do this,'' he said. ``But it's
by no means a slam dunk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-08-98 1349EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
