<HEADLINE>
DEADLINES SET IN MICROSOFT ANTITRUST CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MICHAEL PAULSON   
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once again making it clear that he does not intend
to let the Microsoft antitrust case grow out of control, U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson Tuesday set a series of
deadlines and limits on government and company attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson appeared to suggest that he believes the case of U.S.
vs. Microsoft should last about three weeks. He said he has set
aside the month of September for the trial, which is scheduled to
begin Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also said he plans to allow each side to present no more
than 12 witnesses. The witnesses must be questioned in writing
prior to the trial, so that only cross-examination will be
conducted at trial.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, as well as attorneys on both sides, is clearly
mindful of the government's previous antitrust cases against IBM
and AT&AMP;T. The IBM case is now considered a model for judicial
inefficiency _ it stretched on for more than a decade, consuming
untold dollars and hours, before finally being dropped by the
government. And even the AT&AMP;T case involved scores of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson is quickly setting a no-nonsense tone for this
proceeding, which is shaping up to be the most closely watched
anti-trust battle of the decade and a test of the judiciary's
ability to keep pace with technology.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government and the attorneys general of 20 states
and the District of Columbia are accusing Microsoft of illegally
seeking to expand a monopoly on computer operating systems into the
market for World Wide Web browsers. Microsoft denies that it has
done anything illegal.
</P>
<P>
   During a status hearing Tuesday, Jackson forbade the parties
from communicating with him except by formal motion, threatened to
appoint a special master if they get into spats over how to conduct
depositions, and refused to excuse Microsoft from filing a motion
it had tried to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to ``the high caliber of counsel we have in this
case,'' Jackson made it clear he expects the attorneys for the
company and the government to work together to make sure that each
side gets the information it needs to be ready for an on-time
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The goodwill between the sides seems somewhat limited, though.
At Tuesday's hearing Microsoft suggested the government should show
restraint in gathering evidence this summer because it has already
conducted a two-year investigation of the company. That prompted
the Justice Department's special trial counsel, David Boies,
alluding to the company's phenomenal wealth, to say ``I think
Microsoft clearly has the resources to respond to some discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, however, appeared sympathetic to Microsoft, telling
Boies ``don't plow ground that you don't need to plow again.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides proclaimed themselves pleased with the hearing. Boies
said the government is pleased by the judge's commitment to hold an
unusually early and speedy trial, while Microsoft vice president
William Neukom said, ``We are pleased with the results of today's
hearing, and are looking forward to an opportunity to dispose of
this matter as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Also this week, Microsoft filed a motion in court urging the
judge to keep under seal certain exhibits and other documents that
were filed by the government as part of its case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Microsoft documents in question detail Microsoft's
development and marketing plans for various Internet-related
technologies,'' Microsoft said in a motion. ``Unfettered disclosure
of such confidential documents to Netscape, Oracle, Sun
Microsystems and other Microsoft competitors would seriously
compromise Microsoft's important business interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The government disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There exists a strong presumption in favor of public access to
judicial proceedings,'' the Justice Department and the states wrote
in a joint brief. ``This (appeals court) circuit has stated that
`the courts are public institutions that best serve the public when
they do their business openly and in full view', and it recognizes
the importance of making court records accessible to the public,
especially when the government is a party to the lawsuit and
objects to the sealing of the records.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-09-98 2016EDT &QL;
</P>
