<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERWEB-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Five young friends' dreams evolve into $11 million Interweb 
By Mike Williams  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Four years ago they were five young friends crowded
into a Midtown, Atlanta studio apartment, dreaming up big ideas for
a company that would capitalize on the hot new technology of the
day: the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that many businesses then barely knew what the
Internet was.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that none of the five had a degree in computer
science, and no venture capitalist would touch their proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, their fledgling company, Interweb, was bought by a
New York firm in a deal worth about $11 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Interweb _ now part of an Internet development firm called Think
New Ideas _ has become a national player in a rapidly-evolving
field revolutionizing the way American companies do business, from
tasks as mundane as ordering paper clips to inventory tracking,
sales, marketing and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a history major who had been a stockbroker, an MBA who
had never run a company, and one guy with real world experience
with computers,'' said Will duPont, 30, Interweb's president. ``We
would go to meetings with potential customers and begin by
explaining what the Internet was.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tool, and a toy
</P>
<P>
   Interweb's swift growth and the evolution of the services it
provides mirrors the Internet's explosive development. The computer
network has become a popular play thing for individuals and an
increasingly important tool for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the statistics show huge growth in the use of the Web,''
said Michael Cummins, head of the Georgia Center for Advanced
Telecommunications Technology. ``It's reached critical mass and
it's going to get faster as we smooth out the bottlenecks.''
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research of Boston estimates Web-related services,
sales and development could reach $2 billion this year, and $10
billion by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has become a nexus for Web development firms serving the
Southeast, with more than 150 outfits listed in the Yellow Pages as
providing Internet services. They range from Mindspring, the
fast-growing Internet access provider, to Web development firms
like Interweb, Macquarium and iXL, to small shops that design home
pages for other small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   From an acorn grew a tree
</P>
<P>
   For all its founders' grand ideas, Interweb started small.
</P>
<P>
   The firm was the brainchild of Daniel Davenport and Paul Goggin,
who met through a mutual friend at Georgia Tech, where Goggin was a
graduate student in atmospheric chemistry. Goggin had the technical
know-how. Although not a computer major, he was helping run a
computer-based data system for the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   He was also playing around a lot on the Internet, which was just
emerging into the public realm from its origins as a tool for the
Defense Department and university researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see the opportunities,'' said Goggin, 30. ``It was
really easy to use and yet so powerful. It was a great way for
getting access to information.''
</P>
<P>
   Over beers, Goggin and Davenport _ a philosophy major in college
_ tossed around ideas on how to build a business based around the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport drew in duPont, then a stockbroker who had been his
college roommate at the University of Georgia, and Nick Owen, a
high school friend who earned an MBA at Georgia and was in the
mortgage and real estate business. Gibson Fenning, another Georgia
grad and friend, was tapped, too. He was working in advertising and
was skilled with graphic design.
</P>
<P>
   They drew up a business plan and started shopping around for
capital. Paul Arne, a lawyer with Morris, Manning and Martin, was
one of their early contacts. ``It's a running joke with us now,''
he recalls from his first meeting with the group. ``They were all
young and none of them had any Internet experience at all. Their
technical person was running an air quality lab at Georgia Tech.
And all they wanted was a few hundred thousand dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Humble beginnings
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital was out of the question, but the partners
persevered. Arne put them in touch with an Internet access firm
that made available some of the equipment they needed at prices
they could afford.
</P>
<P>
   The partners hit up family and friends, took out a loan, and
managed to pool $85,000 in capital. Working out of duPont's
one-bedroom apartment, they were off.
</P>
<P>
   It was late 1994, and the Internet was suddenly the talk of the
national media, which promised the Web would revolutionize
everything from shopping and banking to business inventory, sales
and office management.
</P>
<P>
   At Interweb, the beginnings were decidedly less high-flying.
``Our first customer was a small record label that paid us $1,000
to design a Web site and $100 a month to maintain it,'' duPont
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Other small jobs followed, and then their first big break: a
contract with Invesco, the mutual fund firm. Dozens of other Web
design firms had sprouted up around Atlanta, and the contract
brought credibility for the young firm.
</P>
<P>
   Interweb closed out 1995 with $194,000 in revenue. The only
employees were the five partners, who had managed to rent office
space and move out of duPont's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The start of the good times
</P>
<P>
   Their next big break came in 1996. They had done small jobs for
BellSouth Corp., and put in a proposal when the telecommunications
giant wanted better coordination of its many divisions' Web sites.
Interweb's chief competition was an established company based in
California's Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were only five guys, but we were five guys who were less
than a mile away,'' duPont recalls. ``Our contact knew he could
call us and we'd be at BellSouth within 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract came just as Owen got married _ a big, happy event
for the friends that suddenly became even bigger and happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hired our first employee right before the wedding, and by
the time I got back from my honeymoon, they had hired another,''
said Owen, 32. ``It was very exciting, but suddenly when we had
employees, it got a little scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerns dissolved in a haze of marathon work sessions and
constant meetings with BellSouth people. By the end of 1996,
Interweb had revenues of $1.2 million and 20 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet and what companies wanted from it was changing
almost as fast as the tiny company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, it was a big deal for a business just to have a
presence on the Web. A few let customers order products, make
complaints or ask for information. Most simply put out what in
essence were informational brochures.
</P>
<P>
   The Interweb partners knew they had to do more than just design
pretty home pages with colorful graphics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, they bought Professional Web Applications, an Atlanta
firm specializing in software applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great fit,'' duPont said. ``They were only four guys
and they didn't have much front-office presence. But they were
writing dynamite software.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Interweb was able to expand its services, targeting a
customer's in-house computer network or ``Intranet,'' helping trim
expenses by making in-house tasks more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it is as mundane as ordering paper clips or updating
company software,'' Owen said. ``If you're a company with 5,000
employees and every time you need to update your software you have
to install it on 5,000 machines by hand, you can see the
efficiencies if you can suddenly do it with a few keystrokes on
your computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Interweb also customized an employee locator, a job-line and
employment application-managing system and a conference-room
scheduler for clients. All may seem unexciting, but they are
time-consuming tasks greatly simplified by using an in-house
computer system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Interweb earned $2.7 million in revenues and had 45
employees.
</P>
<P>
   In for the full ride
</P>
<P>
   The sale to Think New Ideas consolidates the vision the partners
had for their firm, which was to remain on the cutting edge of
Internet development and evolution. All five plan to continue
working for the new firm, which has offices in Boston, Seattle, Los
Angeles and New York, as well as an Atlanta operation that will
move into Interweb's building.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is cashing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too much fun,'' said Goggin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is so young, the opportunity is so huge, we'd be
foolish to get out now,'' adds duPont.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-09-98 1859EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
