 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Just for Fun: Printer accepts images from digital camera 
By Yusuf Davis  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Canon's Digital Printer CD-200, which ships next
month, claims to be the industry's first color printer to accept
and print images directly from a digital camera's Compact Flash
card.
</P>
<P>
   Designed primarily for use with Canon digitals, this printer is
compatible with most digital cameras that use the CF card and that
use JPEG compression.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as a virtual ``digital darkroom,'' the CD-200 produces
4-by-6-inch glossy photo prints, without the need for a PC. Each
print costs less than $1 per copy and is delivered in about a
minute and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Compatible with PCs and Macs, the printer allows users to print
still images from TV programs, camcorders and other video sources.
It also allows images to be displayed on a TV monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-200 has an estimated retail price of $699 and can be seen
at the company's Web site: http://www.ccsi.canon.com.
</P>
<P>
   More than a printer
</P>
<P>
   The Sharp UX-2200CM is a six-in-one color inkjet machine. The
company claims it's the world's first multifunctional device to
have infrared direct print and data transfer capability. That's a
fancy way of saying you can hook it up to your computer wirelessly.
</P>
<P>
   Designed for the small office/home office market, this
multifunction machine features a plain-paper fax, color printer,
scanner, copier, PC fax and phone in an affordable, compact unit.
</P>
<P>
   The printer produces documents in up to 600 dots per inch, at a
rate of up to three pages per minute. Like other multifunctions,
the real advantages are price and space consumption. The device
sells for a fraction of the cost of buying each unit individually
and takes up a fraction of the space of separate units.
</P>
<P>
   Build your dream home
</P>
<P>
   Bob Vila, America's favorite do-it-yourselfer, has teamed up
with Mindscape and the Learning Company to create a software tool
that will help users conceptualize, plan and build the home of
their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Though designed primarily for new-home builders, the two-CD Bob
Vila's Home Design also offers hundreds of tips for remodeling and
adding to existing homes.
</P>
<P>
   This comprehensive program contains a suite of 2-D/3-D drafting
and drawing tools, an encyclopedia of more than 1,000 home plans,
animated tours, and video and audio tips from Vila. There are also
links to an ``Ask Bob'' Web site, where Vila or his staff will
answer e-mail questions on personal home design projects.
</P>
<P>
   With a library of blueprints, design symbols for interiors and
exteriors, and a roof editor for dormers, chimneys and skylights,
this program, which retails for $40, will help users plan in 2-D
and view in 3-D almost any home up to 30 stories.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, visit the Web site
http://www.learningco.com.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at sound
</P>
<P>
   The Cosmic Shower is the '90s version of the Lava Lamp, only
better. Created for the Sharper Image by electronic artist Joseph
F. Lozowski, the Cosmic Shower is an interactive light sculpture
that responds to your voice, music or other room sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-tall clear tube is zapped electronically to produce a
complex pattern of brilliant green arcs, which descend in
successive waves through multiple levels.
</P>
<P>
   Turn on the stereo and watch music become visible, as the light
patterns change with the tempo. Green spirals form and dissolve to
the beat, and twists and ripples of light dance through the tube,
from top to base, then in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Users can vary the speed of the display over a wide range, from
slow for meditation and relaxation to fast for high-energy action,
or alter the light pattern and sound sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Designed for low energy consumption, the Cosmic Shower retails
for $299. To learn more, visit the Web site
http://www.sharperimage.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-09-98 1831EDT &QL;
