<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEVELOPING-CO </SLUG>
   -$ADV21-1400&AMP;ADD 
 &HT;     TRIPS BY CLINTON TO DEVELOPING NATIONS SIGNAL GLOBAL
REALIGNMENT
 &HT;     With DEVELOPING-BOX-$ADV21.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Sunday, June 14 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American presidents don't often journey to the
world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, however, will see more of the developing
world this year than the most intrepid collegiate backpacker, with
no fewer than five major forays completed or planned into Africa,
Latin America, Southeast Asia, the Indian subcontinent and China,
where he goes later this month.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he brushes the dust of antiquity off his traveling
shoes at year's end, Clinton will have logged more than 70,000
miles on Air Force One to touch table with countries taking in some
3 billion people _ more than half of whom scrape by on a dollar a
day or less _ who spring from some of the oldest civilizations on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   There's far more to the presidential wanderlust, however, than
ruminations on the past or alms for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton's travels signal are the beginnings of an epic
realignment in U.S. relations with the developing world, whose
fortunes have become tied to the goals of U.S. policymakers and
corporate chiefs like never before.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly much of the change is being driven by commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The United States did a staggering $2 trillion worth of two-way
trade with the rest of the world last year. A large and growing
chunk of that was with developing countries, where hundreds of
American companies have wagered scores of billions of dollars on
future growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in human history, living standards for huge
populations have quadrupled or more in a single generation,''
Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers told a meeting of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) here last week. ``This is good
for many people _ and good for the size of the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Far beyond the shift from aid to trade, however, the new
partnership between the United States and many of the world's
poorest nations is being shaped by sobering geo-strategic
realities.
</P>
<P>
   For whether the issue is the scourge of drugs or the roots of
war, the threat of terrorism or the spread of AIDS, the wealth of
nations, global environmental protection or the harrowing specter
of nuclear Armageddon, it is becoming increasingly clear that the
United States can no longer control its own destiny _ much less
events beyond its borders _ solely in concert with its traditional
allies among the world's wealthy, democratic nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get real cooperation from countries that are not
in that privileged club, we're not going to have a dramatic
impact,'' said Antony Blinken(CQ), senior director for strategic
planning at the White House National Security Council. ``As
powerful as we are, we just don't run the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was rudely reminded of that just last week, when he went
to the United Nations to plead with Mexico and its neighbors to
stop ``pointing fingers'' at the United States in the pitched
diplomatic dispute over how best to combat the illicit narcotics
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Setting aside the public tiff, the White House readily concedes
that it needs Mexico's help in combating illicit drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't buy into the process of trying to solve this
problem,'' said Blinken, ``we can't do it on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Seldom have the limits of U.S. influence been more vividly
displayed than they were on June 3. In the sun-dappled splendor of
the White House Rose Garden, President Clinton formally dispatched
his top diplomat to Geneva to huddle with her counterparts from
Britain, China, Russia and France over how best to staunch a
mounting nuclear arms race between Pakistan and India, both of
which repeatedly tested nuclear weapons this spring over Clinton's
fervent objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do my very best for the president and the American
people,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright dutifully pledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``But do not make a mistake,'' she warned darkly. ``The risks of
the moment are high, and, for the moment, the key choices will be
made in New Delhi and Islamabad. We must all hope and pray those
choices are the right ones.''
</P>
<P>
   As necessity bears invention, so has nuclear saber-rattling
forced U.S. policymakers to finally take seriously a conflict that
has burned for decades in the disputed province of Kashmir, where
thousands of Indians and Pakistanis have been killed in gnawing
sectarian violence that has pushed the two countries toward the
brink of apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must begin to focus on the heart of the India-Pakistan
conflict _ Kashmir,'' an invigorated Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan.,
cautioned earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not only talking about the fate of a disputed state in
the Himalayas,'' said Brownback, chairman of the Near Eastern and
South Asian Affairs Subcommittee, ``we're talking about the
national security interests of the United Sates and its allies and,
indeed, the rest of the world in averting war.''
</P>
<P>
   If the nuclear threat tends to focus policymakers, recent
conventional conflicts in places like Rwanda, Somalia, Haiti and
Bosnia have already proven the dangers that regional animosities
pose to the major powers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union loosed the Cold War
structures that framed the world for half a century, it has been
the troubles of such lesser states, far more than the jousting of
geopolitical giants, that have disrupted the post Cold War peace.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend many analysts expect to persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary security concerns are going to be in the
developing countries, and the U.S. has to realign its strategic
thinking,'' said John Echeverri-Gent, professor of international
political economy at the University of Virginia in Charlottesville.
``Not only will that mean new military strategy, but, hopefully, it
means new diplomatic strategy as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Development experts like Echeverri-Gent, naturally enough, have
been proselytizing for decades about the need to take seriously the
interests of the world's pitiably poor.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, it's technology, markets and realpolitik, not
altruism, that have linked the interests of wealthy nations
inextricably with those of the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sharp turnaround from decades of neo-colonialism, when
U.S. policymakers contented themselves with treating much of the
developing world primarily as a source of cheap raw materials and
labor, an emerging market for American goods and services or as a
chessboard for playing out the geopolitical stakes of the major
powers.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, in the world of the Internet A-bomb and sarin gas; a
place where an AIDS epidemic in Uganda is just a plane flight away
from New York; where dollar-an-hour workers in a Juarez suburb
compete head on with the breadwinner of a family in St. Louis;
where a crack addict on the streets of Chicago can feed a ravenous
crime ring in Colombia; and where missile parts shipped from China
can enable Pakistan to target India with a nuclear bomb; the
developing world's prospects, for better and for worse, pose real
and immediate challenges for the United States and its allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are things that have zero respect for borders,'' said
Blinken. ``A problem that starts at one end of the global village
can become a plague on everyone's house much more quickly than
before, so it requires us to work more closely with these people
than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One helps. And yet, presidential visits are only the
visible tip of the enormous working-level activity such engagement
spawns between countries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's trip to China, for instance _ the first such visit by
a sitting American president since Beijing's bloody crackdown nine
years ago on democracy advocates near Tiananmen Square _ only
symbolizes his broader policy of working with, rather than
isolating, Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   He buttressed that approach on June 3 by renewing China's most
favored nation (MFN) trading status, over the objections of many on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In taking the controversial step, Clinton praised China's
efforts to help defuse the nuclear crisis between India and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is further evidence of the important role China can play
in meeting the challenges of the 21st Century,'' said Clinton.
``This is an important example of how our engagement with China
serves America's interests _ stability in Asia, preventing the
spread of weapons of mass destruction, combating international
crime and drug trafficking, protecting the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ringing endorsement conveniently overlooked the vital
role China played in assisting Pakistan's nuclear weapons quest.
</P>
<P>
   Critics point to Clinton's China policy as an example of U.S.
foreign policy toward developing nations being dominated by the
interests of U.S. companies, which have invested $17.3 billion in
China to date and have signed contracts to invest $23 billion more.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. relations with much of the developing world were held
hostage by Cold War concerns, so today, critics allege, is U.S.
policy toward poorer countries largely a captive of the Fortune
500.
</P>
<P>
   In search of cheap labor and growing markets, American
companies, abetted by Washington, are shaking hands and cutting
deals with some of the most repressive regimes anywhere on Earth _
Vietnam, Indonesia, Nigeria and Saudi Arabia among them.
</P>
<P>
   The White House counters that liberal thought and democracy will
naturally flow from open markets and the resultant rise of a middle
class.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't yet worked in China, where markets have been opening
for two decades, the middle class now tops 150 million and the
political system remains one of the most harshly repressive
anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this view in the political world, and the academic
world, that all one needs to do is open up commercial relations and
favorable political relations will follow in the wake,'' said
Jeffrey Winters, professor of political economy at Northwestern
University in Evanston, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is that democratization comes when
people struggle for it,'' said Winters. ``The markets don't do this
automatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Winters said he would prefer to see the White House impose harsh
economic sanctions on countries that don't move in the direction of
democratization and respect for human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has imposed sanctions on a long list of
developing countries, including Libya, Iran, Iraq and, most
recently, Pakistan and India. In each case, though, it has been
security concerns, not human rights violations, that have prompted
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, said the National Security Council's
Blinken, it is by working with developing countries, far more than
by trying to squeeze them, that U.S. influence will ultimately be
leveraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of these countries there is a tide of history that's
moving very, very hard against dictatorship or repressive leaders
that don't fulfill the rights or demands of their people,'' said
Blinken. ``What we can do is try to get things to move in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
