 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Mac News: Bargain program handles personal information well 
By Charles Haddad  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A program called Consultant is the best new personal
information manager to hit the Mac market in years -- and it's a
heck of a good deal, too.
</P>
<P>
   For about $50, you get a calendar and electronic card file
largely the equal of programs costing twice as much. And, in some
cases, it's easier to use and more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   What's the catch? You can only buy Consultant over the telephone
or the Internet, which eliminates the cost of expensive packaging,
shipping and marketing. That's why the program is so inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   Consultant is representative of a larger trend in software. The
Internet is becoming the distributor of choice for software
developers, who are increasingly trying to entice customers to buy
online rather than in stores.
</P>
<P>
   For Mac developers, this trend is particularly important. Most
stores carry little if any Mac software. Not surprisingly, sales of
Mac software are continuing to fall, and developers are struggling.
They are desperate for ways to cut costs, and the Internet is one
way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how Consultant is distributed, it would be a good
piece of software. It's sharply rendered and attractive. The
program is also responsive and offers some novel twists on features
common in other personal information managers.
</P>
<P>
   Consultant, though, does have its weaknesses. For one, the
program won't let you save searches and sorted information. That
means there's no way to save a list of frequently consulted
contacts. This is a standard feature in most personal information
managers.
</P>
<P>
   Consultant also has no printed manual. Like a growing number of
programs, it has eliminated a manual to save costs. But Consultant,
unlike many other programs, does have excellent help within the
program. There's even more help available on its Web site and in an
electronic manual, which you can download.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Consultant works like most personal information
managers. It has a calendar with multiple views, a to-do list, an
address book and a memo writer.
</P>
<P>
   It also lets you link contacts, notes and documents outside the
program to a to-do or appointment -- all standard stuff today. What
makes Consultant special is some novel twists on these common
features. Take its translate button.
</P>
<P>
   Click the button, type ``meet Bob for lunch at noon Friday'' and
Consultant will turn it into an appointment on that day.
</P>
<P>
   Consultant also offers strong word processing features. You can
keep a daily journal and write memos and notes. Memos can be
formatted like text in any word processor, changing fonts, rulers,
etc. You can also save templates for things such as faxes and
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Consultant is published by Chronos L.C. You'll find the program
on the company's first-rate Web site, at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .chronosnet.com. Chronos will let you download a trial copy of
its program. Or you can order Consultant on CD by calling
801-957-1774.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-05-98 2151E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
