 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Cyberscene: Free, shareware programs can enhance Net experience 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Internet is truly a wonderful and mysterious
place. Besides offering information on how to do anything from bake
a cake to get rid of fleas, it's also the world's biggest source of
both free and inexpensive computer programs.
</P>
<P>
   In just a few hours, you can get dozens of programs that will
help you use the Internet more efficiently. Even if your current
Internet provider included free Web browsing, e-mail and newsgroup
software, there are still plenty of programs that will save you
time and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with Net.Medic. It gives an accurate reading of your
connection speed. Most folks don't understand that modems
constantly adjust in speed, based on line conditions. So, just
because you logged on at, say, 26k bps, that doesn't mean you'll be
operating at that speed later.
</P>
<P>
   You can get a free demonstration version of this software at
http://www.vitalsigns.com
</P>
<P>
   /product/download.html.
</P>
<P>
   Are you still using the e-mail program built into your Web
browser? If you are, you can make sending and receiving e-mail
(especially when files are attached to the e-mail you get) easier
by using Eudora Lite, a free version of Eudora Pro.
</P>
<P>
   Just set your browser for http://eudora.qualcomm.com
</P>
<P>
   /freeware/. You'll find versions of this program for both
Windows and Macintosh machines.
</P>
<P>
   Virus protection is increasingly important. But there's no real
need to buy a commercial anti-virus program. There are excellent
anti-virus programs available free or as shareware (where you
download the program and use it free and only pay if you find it
useful). Payment is on the honor system, and the fee is usually
much less than you'd pay for a program that you'd buy in a store.
</P>
<P>
   You can read about several of these programs -- in a list that
includes both shareware and free programs -- at http://tucows
</P>
<P>
   .pcihost.com/virus95.html.
</P>
<P>
   The next program is one most Internet providers hate. You'll
have to let your conscience be your guide here, so I'll tell you
how the program works and you decide if you'd like to try it.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet providers automatically disconnect you after a
certain number of minutes if you aren't sending e-mail, browsing
the Web or downloading programs. The trouble with that is some
providers also disconnect you when you're actually using the Net
but just not sending or receiving information.
</P>
<P>
   There's software around that fools computers and the provider
into thinking you're actively using the computer. That way, you
don't get disconnected. You can get one of these programs at
http://tucows.pcihost.com
</P>
<P>
   /discon95.html.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems with writing a column like this is knowing
what programs you need and use. Some folks could profit by a better
newsgroup reader; others need to find a new browser or a File
Transfer Protocol program that does a better job of downloading
than when you use a browser.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, there are sites that offer entire menus of downloads
--almost every program you can imagine for using the Internet. One
of these sites is called Stroud's Consummate Winsock Applications
and can be found at http://cws.internet.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you never download a single program there, you'll learn
a lot about the Internet and the possibilities that it offers by
simply browsing the descriptions of what is available. You may find
just the thing to solve a problem you have.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
