 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Motorola's severace package revealed to Austin employees 
By Omar L. Gallaga  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Motorola Inc. gave preliminary details about a
voluntary severance package to employees recently, the first step
in slashing 15,000 jobs, or 10 percent of its workforce.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, where the company has about 10,000 employees, workers
received an e-mail about the package.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola will make the severance package available to employees
whose age and years of experience at the company add up to 75.
Employees who opt to receive the package will receive a week's pay
for every year of service and other benefits depending on their
length of service.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola spokesman Scott Stevens said the company is asking
eligible employees to decide whether they want to take the package
by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the restructuring, Motorola has said it will
consolidate its semiconductor manufacturing and its messaging,
information and media businesses. Poorly performing businesses will
be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The company blamed pricing pressures and a weak Asian economy
for slow revenue growth and what it says will be
lower-than-expected earnings this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Hurst, a spokesman for Motorola's Austin operations, said
for the next week and a half, teams at Motorola will meet to
discuss cost cutting. So far, no specific job cuts have been
announced, Hurst said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's interested in how Austin's going to be impacted,''
he said. ``We don't have all the answers today, but we're putting
together plans to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin is home to Motorola's Semiconductor Products Sector, one
division of Motorola that was targeted in Thursday's announcement
for consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   While cuts are expected in SPS, which employs most of Austin's
Motorola workers, Hurst said the company is still hiring engineers
and focusing on expansion plans for some of its operations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-09-98 1830EDT &QL;
</P>
