u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-NETNEWS-NYT &LR;      06-10 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETNEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNETTERS PUT A TWIST IN WEDDING TRADITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (Charles Stough is an editor at the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News)  
 By CHARLES STOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In June, many young couples turn their attentions to weddings _
the invitations, the decorations, the band, the food, the
bridesmaids, the bar, the federal agents, the cake....
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents? Well, not genuine ones.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents are part of one creative couple's plan. They have
designed a wedding on an X Files theme, after the hit TV series and
coming movie about strange space aliens and even stranger law
enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cerulean blue bridesmaids' dresses, the groom's men in
trenchcoats, masking tape X's on the chapel windows,'' a dreamer
posted in the Usenet newsgroup alt.wedding. It's an Internet site
where people post questions and advice about weddings.
</P>
<P>
   Not marriages. Weddings. They trade chat about marriages over in
soc.couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Implants in the back of the neck of every member of the
wedding party,'' another contributor chimed in, picking up the
thread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bridesmaids carry badges instead of bouquets and walk down the
aisle chanting `FBI.' Put the bridesmaids in scrubs and a white lab
coat, hair in a ponytail, tortoiseshell glasses. No bed in the
honeymoon suite, just a couch. The bride's dance with Dad is
`Beyond the Sea.' As favors, give little metal cylinders that have
nasty pointy things spring out when a button is pushed. And of
course the bride walks down the aisle to the haunting, whistled X
Files theme!''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe invitations that look like a subpoena?
</P>
<P>
   Where this wedding is to take place isn't clear. Contributors to
Usenet groups can be anywhere in the world. Probably not a major
place of worship of any mainstream sect. Well, maybe California.
</P>
<P>
   Other typical wedding-interest postings:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I'm looking for some amusement park or county fair type
touches for our reception. We were thinking about cotton candy and
caramel apples for snacks or favors. Any ideas what to put on the
tables?'' Sure, someone replied. Shop hobby shops for model
railroad stuff, like Ferris wheels.
</P>
<P>
   And have a small rubber duck at each place setting, another
contributor suggested, and the one with a star on the bottom takes
the centerpiece home.
</P>
<P>
   _ Is it a good idea in these modern times for the bride and
groom to live together for a while before the wedding? The question
gets asked two or three times a year in alt.wedding, and always
starts a weeks-long argument.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent posting from a bride offered new insight. Yes, she
said, and no only that, they should buy a house first. ``Now, that
was a stress inducing event that tops planning any wedding!'' she
said. ``Not only do you have to test how compatible you are, but
you have to test making compromises for the good of the
relationship, and stick to a rigorous savings plan as a couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another good test is having to move together. We've moved
together three times. Trying to reach an equitable compromise on
getting rid of whose stuff can start some interesting conversations
as a couple.''
</P>
<P>
   _ How about a gift to give (ital) to (unital) one's parents at
the wedding? One idea is to create a videotape from favorite family
photos. Many photo shops can do it, even adding a touching sound
track.
</P>
<P>
   Alt.wedding postings explore the ways caterers operate, what to
demand from a band or disk jockey, the best man's speech, how to
handle split-family situations, what to do about heavy drinkers _
all the mundane stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Where it becomes most fun is in brainstorming. An X Files
wedding? Some couples would find that a difficult memory to carry
all their lives. But hashing out a wedding theme can cement a
relationship even better than moving a piano into the couple's
third apartment, and with a computer it's much more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stough is an editor for the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   His e-mail address is copyboy(at)dma.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-09-98 1107EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
