<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BOOKS-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AUTHORS MAKE FOR EXCITING LISTENING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 14)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The shelves devoted to suspense at major
bookstores are getting crowded. Every day, it seems, a new author
emerges to compete with the dozens of standard-bearers.
</P>
<P>
   This is a mostly good development, because new voices often
bring fresh characters and perspectives. Not that every man and
woman writing a mystery-thriller is capable of fleshing out
interesting characters, as well as compelling plots. But as more
writers compete for our attention, talented new authors replace
some of the veterans who act like they are writing by rote.
</P>
<P>
   This assumes, of course, that there is more than an ounce of
justice in the publishing and book-buying worlds. If there is,
first-time authors Pamela Thomas-Graham and Margaret Cuthbert will
muscle out longtime best-seller writer Mary Higgins Clark, or at
least rate a seat at her table.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas-Graham and Cuthbert, both talented and successful
African-American professionals, have demonstrated with their debuts
that they know how to develop a compelling heroine, as well as the
suspense-filled plot the genre demands.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some new books available in audio:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Darker Shade of Crimson,'' by Pamela Thomas-Graham; read by
Hazelle Goodman; abridged, approximately 3 hours; Simon &AMP; Schuster
Audio; $18.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas-Graham brings a fresh and welcome voice with her debut,
``A Darker Shade of Crimson.'' Not that Thomas-Graham needs a new
job; she's a poster child for thirtysomething success. At age 32
she became one of the most influential women in American business
when she was named the first black woman partner at McKinsey &AMP; Co.,
the world's largest management consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, she decided to try her hand at what is being billed
the Ivy League mystery series. Thomas-Graham's heroine, Veronica
``Nikki'' Chase, a Harvard economics professor, is a compelling
character who navigates her way through a complex interracial
world. She also is fearless, which helps her as she unravels the
mysterious death of the dean of students. Read flawlessly by
actress Hazelle Goodman, ``Crimson'' hopefully is but the first of
many books Thomas-Graham will share with us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Silent Cradle,'' by Margaret Cuthbert; read by Tonya
Pinkins; abridged, approximately 3 hours; Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio;
$18.
</P>
<P>
   It helps to know your terrain. Cuthbert, who debuts as a
medical-thriller author with ``The Silent Cradle,'' is the vice
chair of obstetrics and gynecology at a medical center in Berkeley,
Calif. As is her heroine, Dr. Rae Duprey, the premier obstetrician
at her hospital in fictional Berkeley Hills who has stumbled on a
series of ``bad baby'' cases coming out of a birth center
affiliated with her hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Cuthbert succeeds on several fronts. The medical complications
she describes seem real and believable, as do the cut-throat
politics within the hospital administration. She also has developed
a winning protagonist in Duprey, the lone black woman in her
department, a passionate and gutsy doctor totally devoted to saving
babies and their mothers. Cuthbert has hit a home run her first
time at bat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You Belong to Me,'' by Mary Higgins Clark; read by Jayne
Atkinson; abridged, about 3 hours; Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio; $18.
</P>
<P>
   Clark is a publisher's dream. She writes a thriller almost once
a year, and without fail there's a subsequent parting in the
bestseller lists. Every one of her 15 novels has rocketed its way
onto the charts. Unfortunately, Clark is not always a reader's
dream, except to die-hard fans.
</P>
<P>
   In her latest, ``You Belong to Me'' (which has been No. 1 on the
hardcover bestseller list), there is plenty of plot, but the
characters are so poorly developed that one-dimensional is a
generous description.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Chandler, a successful New York psychologist and host of a
popular radio talk show, closes in on uncovering a killer who
targets lonely women on cruise ships. People who might help solve
the crimes are stabbed to death, and Chandler is at risk as well.
It's difficult to care about anything other than the killer's
identity, because this is a boiler-plate thriller lacking
originality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
