<SLUG> BC-NODATE-SIDE2-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAD HELPED PREPARE SON FOR MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) -Randal and Erin Palmer met when he was 16 and she was
14. Both had left their hometowns to go on a church mission trip to
Atlanta, and neither was interested in dating or serious
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Teens in the Christian group stayed in touch through letters.
Six months later, Randal and Erin were writing only each other.
From 1990 to 1993, they wrote frequently but never elevated the
relationship beyond friendship. In fact, their parents read their
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Randal's father was a confidant and helped prepare him for
marriage. After Randal turned 18, his father asked if he had met a
young woman he felt particularly drawn to. Erin was the only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed the character of her faith; how much she loved
God,'' said Randal, who lives in Arizona. ``It seemed unrealistic
at the time because she was still in Florida. Dating has so many
expectations and everything seems to be based on the outward. We
were real with one another in our letters.''
</P>
<P>
   His father arranged for her trip to Arizona in April 1993, and
they spent all their time with family. Before she returned home,
the family talked about where their hearts were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much expected that this was leading to a courtship. I
had been praying about it,'' Erin said. ``I really began noticing
that the feelings I thought were just friendship were really love,
that I loved him, that I admired and respected him.''
</P>
<P>
   Erin and her mother made the next trip to Arizona together in
September 1993. Two days after the couple's first date alone -
eating at McDonald's and seeing ``Jurassic Park'' - Randal dressed
as a knight in shining armor. With two dozen roses and a ring in
hand, he proposed in front of everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Four months before the wedding on April 30, 1994, Erin moved to
the Valley and lived with a church family. They spent most of their
time together with family, went to premarital counseling at the
church and were careful about how they spent time alone. The
honeymoon was great, they said with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are really no regrets in terms of whether we did it
right,'' said Randal, sitting close to Erin on their living room
couch, his arm around her. ``We saved ourselves for each other.
This is the way it's supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palmers, who live in Gilbert, are youth leaders at Trinity
New Life Church in Tempe. She works as an administrative assistant
and he as a customer service manager, but they are preparing to
spend a year in Washington, D.C., where he will attend pastor's
college. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
