<HEADER>
A2719 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REHM-VOICE-AZR &LR;      06-10 1602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REHM-VOICE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS RADIO HOST BATTLING VOCAL DISORDER. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - To a woman whose voice is her livelihood, losing the
power of speech was a frightening prospect for Diane Rehm, host of
National Public Radio's ``The Diane Rehm Show.''
</P>
<P>
   But that prospect became a reality when her voice began to
deteriorate several years ago, leaving her wondering whether she
would have to abandon the 20-year broadcasting career she loved.
</P>
<P>
   Rehm has been off the air since Feb. 23, seeking treatment for a
condition diagnosed as spasmodic dysphonia. She has received
injections of botulinum toxin, or botox _ medicine that temporarily
paralyzes the vocal cords. Her voice is returning, and Rehm expects
to be back on the air Thursday (June 11).
</P>
<P>
   Her program originates from American University in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Rehm was interviewed during her recuperation. To avoid straining
her voice, the interview was conducted '90s style _ via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding upbeat about her recovery, she wrote, ``I do believe
there are no accidents and that I have spasmodic dysphonia for a
reason. I believe that reason may be to help educate others about a
problem that really makes people feel such shame and embarrassment
that they choose not to talk at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``What better person to put the word out than a radio talk-show
host?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTION: Describe your ailment and how symptoms first
appeared.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANSWER: About four or five years ago, I began to hear a slight
tremor in my voice. It occurred only occasionally, so I didn't pay
too much attention.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for the first time, an engineer heard it and asked whether
I was nervous. I said of course not, redid the track, and went on.
But I knew something had happened.
</P>
<P>
   I sought out several otolaryngologists, who checked me out and
referred me to neurologists as well. But none saw anything serious
amiss. They initially attributed my vocal tremor to nerves and
prescribed a commonly used drug to calm me down.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the tremor began to be much more noticeable, and
along with it came a difficulty with speaking and articulating
clearly. I encountered moments on the air when I wasn't quite sure
whether the words would come out. It was an enormous frustration to
me, and I'm sure to listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after four or five years of speech therapy, which
brought only modest improvement, my internist insisted I go to
Johns Hopkins University (in Baltimore) for a complete diagnosis.
That's when I first encountered neurologist Stephen Reich and
otolaryngologist Paul Flint, both of whom diagnosed me as suffering
from spasmodic dysphonia.
</P>
<P>
   It's a neurological problem which begins in the basal ganglia,
the portion of the brain which controls muscle movement. The brain
is sending an incorrect message to the muscles of the vocal cords,
telling them to shut down too tightly on the cords themselves _
hence the struggle to get words out or to articulate particular
sounds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Is this a rare condition?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I have seen figures ranging from 50,000 to 500,000 sufferers
in the U.S., but because so few doctors are aware of and can
recognize the symptoms of SD, only about 10,000 have been fully
diagnosed and are undergoing treatment.
</P>
<P>
   People are embarrassed because their voices sound so bad.
Sentences are cracked, the tone of voice fluctuates, and they don't
want to be heard. People who suffer think it's their problem alone
and never look for help.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: How did you deal with the onset of symptoms?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I was not only frightened, I became increasingly depressed,
feeling as though I would have to leave the career I had come to
love and enjoy so much. But at the same time, I had done a
considerable amount of reading about voice problems, and had come
across mention of spasmodic dysphonia and botox in several medical
books.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Before being diagnosed, did you have any hint of what could
be causing the problem?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: When the speech therapy did not seem to do the job, I began
to suspect that it was more complicated than just learning to
breathe correctly. . . . I also began to wonder whether the problem
was stress-related because I had an awful lot going on.
</P>
<P>
   What did seem strange, however, was that, unusual as my voice is
for one on radio, I've always been able to rely on it, even during
other very stressful periods in my life. This was clearly
different.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there's no known specific cause, there is no cure,
and there is no known reason as to why or how it begins. But there
is research going on all over the country, so someday there may be
more answers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: When did you begin treatments?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I had my first injection of botox on May 5. As you might
know, botulinum toxin in high doses is absolutely deadly. But the
injections given are about 1,000 times smaller than what they would
need to be to become lethal.
</P>
<P>
   I was injected with .5 units on either side of the throat,
directly into the muscles controlling the vocal cords. Dr. Flint
attached tiny discs to my throat area, so that he could actually
see on a television screen exactly where the needle was going in.
It was uncomfortable, but not intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   The entire experience lasted less than five minutes. When my
husband and I left Johns Hopkins, we took a long, long walk around
the (Baltimore) inner harbor. I felt fine, my voice was still
working.
</P>
<P>
   We had a lovely dinner at the hotel that night, and I slept
well. The next morning, I still had a voice, which continued
through the next day and evening. Then, at 3:30 a.m. the next
morning, I woke up with only the barest whisper, indicating that
the botox had worked.
</P>
<P>
   I woke my husband, and we did a high five!
</P>
<P>
   Today, four weeks after that first botox injection, I have
considerable voice. I spoke with Dr. Flint (last Wednesday), and he
tells me that the incremental improvement . . . will be
considerable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: What kind of response have you had from listeners?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: The response has just been overwhelming. I spend much of my
days answering e-mail from folks who are wishing me well, wondering
when I'll return and offering prayers for me. I can tell you there
have been hundreds of those messages, in addition to letters and
cards from so many good people. I am so grateful because I know
those prayers and good wishes have made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Have you been able to keep up your spirits?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: When I first left the air on Feb. 23, I was pretty down. I
had done my two-hour show that morning, and then had a car waiting
to take me to a downtown hotel, where I moderated a discussion
before about 300 people. I barely made it. My voice had simply
given out. I rushed back to the station, went straight to my
manager, Kim Hodgson, and told him I'd have to take some time off.
. . . I simply could not control my voice any longer.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, I was not optimistic. I thought I would have
to end my radio career much sooner than I had expected to. The
voice therapy was not working, no matter how much I practiced or
how much I tried. I saw a behavioral therapist and a
psychopharmacolgist, who helped me deal with my anxiety and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   Then, finally, my internist, Carole Horn, stepped in and said,
``Enough! I want you to go to Johns Hopkins and see these two
doctors.'' At first, I was annoyed, feeling as though this was just
one more futile effort. But, thank heavens, I've finally gotten a
diagnosis, the correct treatment, and feel as though I'm on a quick
path to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: How did you recruit so many great people to fill in for you?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Steve Roberts (syndicated columnist with his wife,
journalist Cokie Roberts, and journalism teacher at George
Washington University) and Susan Page (White House correspondent
for ``USA Today'') have filled in for me over the last several
years whenever I've been on vacation, out sick or off making a
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Now with Jim Angle (White House correspondent for Fox News) and
Tom Gjelton (international correspondent for NPR), we feel so
fortunate to have such a marvelous lineup of people willing to
stand in. It is extremely gratifying to know that these very busy
people are willing to do this for me.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: What occupies your time during your time off the air?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I spend much time at the computer answering e-mail
(drehm(at)wamu.org). I am also online or on the phone with the
producers of the show many times a day. We talk about various
options for shows, guests and books. Now that I have a voice, I'm
on the phone with them more frequently. I have also written a diary
for ``Slate'' magazine that has now been posted at my Web site
(www.wamu.org), and, as you might imagine, I am continuing to work
on my book.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, during the first couple of months after I took
off, I was not writing very much at all. I just didn't have the
heart for it. But now that things are looking up, I'm right back to
it. I want to finish it by November so that it will come out in
time for my 20th anniversary as host of ``The Diane Rehm Show.''
It's being published by Knopf, and its title is ``Finding My
Voice.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: How much have you missed being on the air?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I've missed it enormously. We've had some great guests, and
I've been so sad at not being there. At the same time, it's been
fun hearing how each of the guest hosts handled various situations.
It's always good to sit back and listen and learn from pros! My
voice will not be perfect, but judging from listener response, I
trust they'll bear with me. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
