<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2722 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$adv1     06-10 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$adv14-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE MILLENNIAL MELTDOWN
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 14
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, never one to duck an easy
compromise, has declared that 2000 will be known as the
``millennial year.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Clinton has neatly sidestepped the issue of whether
the party to mark the start of the new millennium should be held on
Dec. 31, 1999, or whether we should hold off for another year to
celebrate. The presidential decree leaves us free to pop our
millennial corks either at the start or at the finish _ or twice.
</P>
<P>
   Since the era that marks the birth of Jesus Christ began with
the year 1, rather than with a year 0, scholars insist that the
current millennium won't properly end until midnight on Dec. 31,
2000. Similarly, they hold that 20th century did not began until
Jan. 1, 1901.
</P>
<P>
   But such academic nits carry no weight in the media and
entertainment worlds. They are primed to blast us into the new
millennium as soon as 2000 rolls around _ if not sooner. Thus the
next 18 months or so will bring a heavy dose of pre-millennial
spectaculars, interspersed with nostalgic reflections on what we're
about to leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to the millennium bug, the techies can fairly
stand their ground, since that cyberpest is due to strike a year
before, strictly speaking, the century is due to turn. Until that
happens, there are at least three lessons to be drawn from a
digital Armaggedon that is already receiving a big media sendoff.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson No. 1: Folks fail to plan ahead. If the year 2000 bug
will cause the lights to go out, the planes to be grounded and the
tax refunds to go haywire, to cite but a few of the anticipated
woes, then managers should have insisted at the dawn of the
computer age, whatever the cost, that a full four digits be used in
entering years in software dates.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, they didn't, which leads us to Lesson No. 2: For every
downside, there's an upside.
</P>
<P>
   The downside: Fixing the hidden glitches that gave rise to the
Year 2000 problem will be a time-consuming and labor-intensive job
that will cost the corporate world and the nation's taxpayers, at a
minimum, hundreds of billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The upside: None of those billions will actually go up in smoke.
Rather, they will wind up fattening some other people's bank
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Like those of Microsoft Corp., which currently blankets the
trade press with ads that tout its fully Year-2000 compliant
network servers, which can be swapped out in corporate makeovers.
Like the old programmers who are being brought out of retirement
and, perhaps less honorably, like the lawyers who are busy drafting
class-action suits charging negligence. There's even a new biweekly
magazine out there, with its own Web site, that is devoted solely
to what acronym-prone techies have dubbed ``Y2K'' issues.
</P>
<P>
   The final lesson is that there is more to life than databases.
After all, well before computers were invented, city lights shone,
planes flew, companies wrote orders and newspaper columns got
written. (Anybody still have a typewriter?)
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there's no going back. But if some things don't run
quite right on Jan. 1, 2000, then at least we'll be free to go out
for a fine winter walk.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
