<HEADLINE>
A QUICK LOOK AT THE NUMBERS THAT SUM UP OUR ECONOMIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harper's-like index from numbers in the World Bank's ``World
Development Indicators, 1998,'' unless indicated:
</P>
<P>
   Rank of the United States, Singapore, Switzerland and Hong Kong,
in wealth produced per person, among 148 countries: 1, 2, 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   Rank of the same countries in economic freedom, among 102 judged
the Fraser Institute of Vancouver, B.C.: 4, 3, 5 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   By the Heritage Foundation: 5, 2, 5 and 1 (with two tied).
</P>
<P>
   Country with the fastest-growing economy, 1965-1996: Botswana.
South Korea was No. 2, China, No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Center of the global car culture, judged from the ratio of cars
per 1,000 people: Italy, 571 cars.
</P>
<P>
   No: 2: The United States, 521 cars.
</P>
<P>
   Center of the computer revolution, as judged from the number of
PCs per 1,000 people: Switzerland, 409.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2: The United States, 362.
</P>
<P>
   Center of mobile-phone mania: Scandinavia. Finland has 292
mobile phones per 1,000 people, and Norway, Sweden and Denmark have
nearly as many. The U.S. figure is 165.
</P>
<P>
   Highest in Asia: 216, in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Countries expected to add the most population: India, China,
Nigeria, Pakistan, Ethiopia and Congo, in that order.
</P>
<P>
   Countries expected to lose population: Japan, Germany, Russia,
Italy, in that order (most to least).
</P>
<P>
   Health spending per person, United States: $3,801, the world's
highest.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan: $1,587.
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy at birth in Japan: 80, the world's highest.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States: 77.
</P>
<P>
   Share of income earned by the top 10 percent in the United
States: 28.5.
</P>
<P>
   In Chile: 46.1.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada: 23.3.
</P>
<P>
   The only places where an equal share of each sex smokes: Norway
and Denmark, 36 and 37 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Highest percentage of women who smoke: Croatia, 38 percent (and
37 percent of men).
</P>
<P>
   Of men who smoke: Vietnam, 71 percent (and 4 percent of women).
</P>
<P>
   In America: 28 percent of men, 23 percent of women.
</P>
<P>
   Countries of the Americas losing the most forest land, in square
kilometers per year: Brazil, 25,544; Bolivia, 5,814, and Mexico,
5,080.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining: The United States, 5,886, and Canada, 1,764.
</P>
<P>
   Places with the lowest rate of infant mortality, 4 per 1,000
births: Japan, Sweden, Finland, Singapore and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. figure: 7.
</P>
<P>
   The highest: 174, in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of central government spending on subsidies and transfer
payments in the United States: 59.
</P>
<P>
   In Sweden: 70.
</P>
<P>
   In Singapore: 11.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of central government spending on capital investment in
the United States, Sweden and Singapore: 3, 3 and 23.
</P>
<P>
   Serving in the military, all nations, 1985: 28 million people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995: 23 million.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military manpower as a percentage of the labor force: 1.9
percent in 1985, falling to 1.2 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In China: 0.7 percent, falling to 0.4 (a drop of 1.17 million
soldiers).
</P>
<P>
   Arms exports as a percentage of total exports, United States,
1985: 6.3
</P>
<P>
   In 1995: 2.7.
</P>
<P>
   Largest stock market capitalization as percent of GDP, 1996:
Malaysia, 310 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. figure: 116 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Highest share turnover as a percentage of market capitalization,
1996: China, 231 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S.: 97 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most outrageous place to make a three-minute call to the United
States: Syria, $33.41.
</P>
<P>
   The world's worst currencies, as judged by the street price:
Burma's and Iraq's, less than 5 percent of the official rate.
</P>
<P>
   The world's worst place to invest, according to Euromoney's
estimations: Iraq, 3.6 points out of 100.
</P>
<P>
   The best: The United States, 100.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of Canada and Mexico: 95.4 and 63.5.
</P>
<P>
   Economic aid paid by the United States, per person per year,
1996: $41.
</P>
<P>
   By Norway: $311.
</P>
<P>
   By Japan: $76.
</P>
<P>
   The largest recipient of economic aid per person, 1996: Israel,
$389.
</P>
<P>
   By Bangladesh: $10.
</P>
<P>
   By China and India: $2.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramsey is a writer and columnist for the P-I. His e-mail
address is bruceramsey(at)seattle-pi.com.
</P>
