<P>
   &UR; WEDDINGS UNDER THE INFLUENCE OF MURPHY'S LAW &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By DEBBI J. KARPOWICZ &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   These are the weddings you'll never read about in the
untarnished world of bridal magazines: weddings in which a jealous
ex-lover sets fire to the newlyweds' limousine, the bride's
embittered divorced parents ignite a brawl, the couple's dog
relieves himself accompanying them down the aisle, the bride is
mugged in the ladies' room ... Take a side-splitting walk on the
dark side of matrimony with Debbi J. Karpowicz. (slugged:
BC-WEDDING-HORROR-STORIES-(WEDDINGS)-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code l)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOP 10 WEDDING MYTHS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,200 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By MARTHA A. WOODHAM &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From ``The Bride Did What?!''
</P>
<P>
   Woodham, society columnist for the Atlanta Journal and
Constitution, helps bewildered brides and grooms navigate the wilds
of wedding etiquette. Can the bride walk down the aisle alone? Can
her mother be matron of honor? Can the bride ask a guy to be one of
her attendants? With humor and commonsense, Woodham tackles these
and other thorny questions head-on. (slugged:
BC-WEDDING-MYTHS-(WEDDINGS)-ART-NYTSF, priority code r, category
code l)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING ALONG WITH THE IN-LAWS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,300 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By EVE GLICKSMAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From Elegant Wedding &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The line between amicability and all-out war can be thin where
in-laws are concerned,'' writes Glicksman. ``With practice, though,
experts say, you can learn to get along.'' Glicksman discusses ways
to minimize conflict, especially on potentially explosive issues
such as planning the wedding, juggling holidays, money and handling
criticism. (slugged: BC-KEEPING-IN-LAWS-IN-LINE-(WEDDINGS)-NYTSF,
priority code r, category code l) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEWLYWEDS' GUIDE TO DOMESTIC HARMONY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By EVERETT DeMORIER &QL; 
 &UR; From ``Crib Notes for the First Year of Marriage'' &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Newlyweds may discover that the person whom they love has
domestic habits that they hate. What if the bride is a neatnik and
the groom is a slob? What if he can't bear to talk to anyone when
he first wakes up and she is all bubbly? Even bathroom habits, such
as how one squeezes the toothpaste tube and whether to leave the
toilet seat up or down, can cause domestic turmoil. DeMorier offers
ideas on how to keep the home from turning into a battleground.
(slugged: BC-AVOIDING-DOMESTIC-DISCORD-(WEDDINGS)-NYTSF, priority
code r, category code l) &QL;
</P>
