<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2745 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONTEMPORARY-CW-WOMEN     06-10 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTEMPORARY-CW-WOMEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GIRL POWER' PROPELS TODAY'S COUNTRY DIVAS DOWN NEW PATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TERESA TALERICO  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They wear navel rings, spandex pants and sexy crop-tops.
</P>
<P>
   They strut through music videos that, volume turned down, you'd
swear belong on MTV. They sing about everything from AIDS to
jiltin' a deadbeat guy to standin' up for yourself, girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any man of mine better walk the line,'' belts out Shania
Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy McCready, whose trademark is a bellybutton ring, has a
song called ``Guys Do It All the Time,'' where she gleefully
describes a woman doing everything from driving a pickup to
watching football.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Independence Day,'' Martina McBride sings about a battered
wife who decides to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Meet today's women of country music. Brazen. Beautiful. Ballsy.
Stand by your man? Yeah, right. ``Girl power'' has become the
mantra for many of these '90s singers. Gone are the frilly,
high-necked dresses, the big hair and fringed skirts, the saintly
tolerance of their men's cheatin' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compare Loretta Lynn and Tammy Wynette to Shania
Twain and Mindy McCready _ wow, what a difference,'' says Bev
Devlin, a Seattle traffic announcer and country singer. ``The
gingham and plaid of Dolly Parton are long gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain, 33, performs Saturday at the Tacoma Dome.
</P>
<P>
   With her in-your-face lyrics, sexy, modern look and country-pop
sound finessed by husband Mutt Lange _ former producer for rock
bands such as AC/DC and Def Leppard _ Twain ushered in a new era of
country diva.
</P>
<P>
   Her signature hit: ``Any Man of Mine,'' which has become an
anthem of sorts for young, female country fans.
</P>
<P>
   I can be late for a date, that's fine. But he better be on time.
And if I change my mind a million times, I wanna hear him say,
yeah, yeah, yeah, I like it that way ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The images have changed dramatically,'' says Pat Roberts, a
local concert promoter who brings acts such as Reba McEntire and
Wynonna to the Seattle area. ``Before, there wasn't near the
glamour there is today. The girl-singer was more the
girl-next-door.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's female country stars _ with their feisty, empowering
lyrics and sexy stage acts _ also appeal to a younger, wider
audience, says Bruce Feiler, author of ``Dreaming Out Loud: Garth
Brooks, Wynonna Judd, Wade Hayes and the Changing Face of
Nashville.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider LeAnn Rimes, who sings about ``commitment,'' wears
trendy slip dresses and does a cover of Prince's ``Purple Rain'' on
her latest album.
</P>
<P>
   Or Trisha Yearwood, who does Discover Card commercials in hip,
baggy jeans and platform shoes. Deana Carter performs barefoot, her
blond hair long and hippie-style. Her best-known song? ``Did I
Shave My Legs for This?''
</P>
<P>
   Jo Dee Messina says adios to a lover in ``Bye Bye,'' singing:
</P>
<P>
   I'll catch you later. Got my lead foot on my accelerator and the
rearview mirror torn off. I ain't never lookin' back. And that's a
fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South was much more isolated from the rest of the country
in 1968 than it is in 1998,'' Feiler says. ``There was a much
greater difference between Janis Joplin and Loretta Lynn than there
is between Alanis Morissette and Deana Carter. Today, women in
Seattle can identify with music coming out of Tennessee. This was
something unthinkable 30 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in many ways, today's women of country music do exactly
what their pioneering predecessors did. They sing from the heart
about subjects that matter to women.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, Kitty Wells became the first woman to have a No. 1
country song with ``It Wasn't God Who Made Honky-Tonk Angels.'' The
tune was a rebuttal to a Hank Thompson song that blamed women for
men's cheating. Ahem.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the ``Queen of Country Music,'' Wells blazed a path for
later stars such as Patsy Cline, Loretta Lynn and Tammy Wynette.
</P>
<P>
   Now 78, she recalled that in her day, she was lucky to tour with
her husband, Johnny Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to be very careful when you traveled, or people would
talk about you,'' she says in a phone interview from her Nashville
home. ``Now, the girls go out and have their own buses and people
don't talk about it _ one girl traveling with a bunch of men.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, there were few women making it big in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think about having any obstacles,'' she says.
``I just started singing. It was hard to get a recording contract
at first. But once I had it, it got easier for girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Other early female stars raised eyebrows by singing about
controversial subjects.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Tammy Wynette recorded ``D-I-V-O-R-C-E,'' about a
subject that most people still considered taboo. In 1972, Loretta
Lynn (who had her first baby at 14) celebrated new-fangled birth
control in ``The Pill.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, performers such as Reba McEntire follow in their
footsteps. She sings about a woman infected with HIV in ``She
Thinks His Name Was John.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Loretta Lynn, Tammy Wynette, Dottie West, Patsy Cline _ for
their time, they were as powerful a voice for women as a Reba or a
Trisha or a Faith Hill today,'' says Penny Coyne, a DJ and music
director at radio station KYCW, 96.5 Young Country. ``The way they
went about it may have been different.''
</P>
<P>
   But more often than not, fans of early country remember the
torch songs, the ``my man done left me'' songs. Patsy Cline's ``I
Fall to Pieces.'' Tammy Wynette's ``Stand by Your Man.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Riverside Inn in Tukwila, Linne Bourget takes a break
from two-stepping and line-dancing to muse on the evolution of
country's women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be `He can beat me and kick me, and I don't
mind,''' says the psychologist and country fan. ``Now there's a lot
more wisdom. The songs are much more psychologically healthy.
There's still an occasional victim song. But Reba (McEntire) and
the Judds, they're the epitome of female wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   But country music has always been filled with smart women.
</P>
<P>
   Dolly Parton may have played up her bosom and big blond wigs.
She may have sung ``It's All Wrong, But It's All Right'' about
tolerating a bad relationship. But she's also a savvy entrepreneur
behind the scenes and the voice of the spunky hit ``9 to 5.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's nobody's bimbo,'' says Tony Thomas, music director at
country radio station KMPS. ``She's one of the most successful
businesswomen. And she's not afraid to play with her sexuality
because in the end, she's the one going to the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Sex has always sold well in rock music. But aside from vamps
such as Parton and Tanya Tucker, country women's images have been
more conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with greater competition among female singers and a more
liberal mentality in Nashville, rising hemlines, exposed
bellybuttons and racier lyrics are in.
</P>
<P>
   ``In society at large, sex is selling,'' says Ray Randall, of
Asylum Records. ``Country music finally brought it to the forefront
with people like Shania and Mindy. In the '90s, you have a more
outspoken female perspective, and it shows up in the lyrics of the
songs.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Loretta Lynn sang, ``You ain't woman enough to
take my man.'' Today's divas of country would likely say, ``Girl,
you can have him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
