r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PHOTOGRAPHY-$A     06-10 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PHOTOGRAPHY-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVING THE CAMERA OUT OF THE EQUATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 14)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sign a the Kenya-Tanzania border checkpoint said ``It is
strictly forbidden to photograph the Masai,'' but I was finding it
almost impossible to comply. As I pointed my lens at some distant
giraffes, taking care not to include any forbidden Masai in the
frame, a blurry figure maneuvered itself into the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusting the focus, I found my viewfinder filled with a lanky
young Masai warrior, striking a jaunty pose.
</P>
<P>
   I turned and aimed my camera at a herd of gazelles, but before I
could trip the shutter my new friend had repositioned himself in
front of my lens. He seemed about as camera-shy as a young starlet
at Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   I gestured for him to move, but he just stood there, staring
into the camera and flashing a winsome, semi-toothed grin. I put my
camera away, but the Masai, apparently thinking I'd taken his
picture, rushed forward, palm outstretched, saying, ``Shillings!
Shillings!''
</P>
<P>
   Few souvenirs are as irresistible to the traveler as a photo of
the locals in their colorful, native costumes. But these days I
almost always leave my camera in my backpack: photography has
ruined too many moments.
</P>
<P>
   Laws against photographing the Masai tribe in East Africa stem
from the tribe's traditional belief that cameras capture their
souls. While many Masai apparently still hold to this, many of the
ones who live in areas frequented by tourists have transformed
themselves into willing photo opportunities to raise some quick
cash.
</P>
<P>
   While I sympathize with their need or at least desire to do so,
I can't help feeling uneasy about the loss of dignity for one of
the region's proudest tribes. And I've seen too many encounters
between the Masai and Western tourists suddenly turn sour over
misunderstandings about photos and money. By leaving my camera out
of the equation, I've sometimes managed to have memorable
encounters with the Masai, rather than just quick cash-for-snapshot
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The Masai really do wear distinctive red-plaid togas and carry
spears, but elsewhere in the world a depressing number of
photogenic locals don their colorful costumes as little more than
props for photographers. A few years ago, in Peru, some friends
watched a man in modern, European-style clothes stake out a scenic
spot on the shore of Lake Titicaca and then change into a bright,
multihued pancho and a pointy, ear-covering cap _ becoming, as my
friends called him, an ``instant Inca'' for the benefit of
camera-toting tourists.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Masai, he was obviously entitled to try to make some
money from tourism, but I feel bad about encouraging people to
transform themselves into the equivalent of the guy who dresses up
as Mickey Mouse at Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps my reticence comes from once having been on the other
side of the lens. Many years ago, when I was starting out as a
mountain climber, I made a pilgrimage to the birthplace of the
sport began _ Chamonix, in the French Alps.
</P>
<P>
   On my first morning I was dressed the way the famous French
alpinist Gaston Rebuffat always was in his books: in knickers, a
thick woolen sweater and some cool bug-eyed goggles I'd picked up
in a souvenir shop.
</P>
<P>
   To my horror I quickly discovered that no self-respecting French
climber has dressed this way since about 1952, when my Gaston
Rebuffat books were published. The local alpinists wore loud,
multicolored Gore-Tex parkas and the latest Vuarnet sunglasses.
Among them I looked, frankly, like a doofus.
</P>
<P>
   Before I could slink off to change my outfit a bus pulled up and
three dozen Japanese tourists bounded off, each sporting an
expensive camera and a souvenir-shop felt alpine hat about as
outdated as my clothes. Apparently they read the same Gaston
Rebuffat books. Their leader said something and gestured in my
direction, and instantly 36 lenses were trained on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait!'' I tried to say. ``You don't want me, you want a
picture of one of these other guys. They're the real climbers.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no use. Soon they were posing with me, first two or three
at a time, then the entire group. They ignored the real climbers,
who apparently didn't fit their notion of what an alpinist should
look like _ and who no doubt had better things to do than hold
still for tourist pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The shutters kept clicking, and my smile grew more strained with
each pose. I said I really had to get going, and I felt a hand
press down gently but firmly on my shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Japanese seemed to speak English, but none of them
made any effort to talk to me, to find out anything about me. They
just wanted their photo of the native in his colorful local
costume, and when they were finished they would get back on their
tour bus and move on.
</P>
<P>
   At that point I would have gladly posted a sign saying, ``It is
strictly forbidden to photograph the dorky looking climber.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
