<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-CARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR-PROFIT MENTAL HEALTH SYSTEM HAS ITS CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twice since February, Mel Urban's 30-year-old son has been
denied hospital admission for treatment of psychosis, and he puts
the blame on the state's for-profit mental health managed care
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst I've ever seen him,'' said Urban of his son,
who was diagnosed 11 years ago with bipolar disorder, a mental
illness characterized by periods of mania and of depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just feels very depressed. Where he's headed, I just don't
know,'' said Urban, adding that while his son was finally
hospitalized and released, he still has not gotten the treatment he
needs. ``Now he's angry, he's disturbed, agitated and confused,
because the system has jerked him around so much.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at 1 p.m. at the Statehouse Wednesday,
Urban and other critics of mental health services will challenge
the state's $200-million-a-year contract with the Massachusetts
Behavioral Health Partnership to provide services to 400,000
mentally ill adults and children.
</P>
<P>
   The privatization of mental health services once provided by the
state is leading to denial of needed care, inappropriately short
hospital stays and overreliance on medication, the critics charged,
while the for-profit company makes its profits.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the state and the Partnership have been slow
to respond to requests for information vital to monitoring care,
the critics said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that (monitoring information) hasn't been produced
sets off real alarm bells for me,'' said Susan Fendell, senior
attorney for the Mental Health Legal Advisors Committee, who has
long been requesting information from the state Division of Medical
Assistance (DMA), which administers the contract with the
Partnership &UR; .  &LR; Only last week Fendell got year-old information that
still needs to be analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either DMA is not doing its job properly in monitoring the
program, or they're withholding the information that the public
should have,'' said Fendell, who will be among those at the news
conference. The legal advisors committee, an arm of the Supreme
Judicial Court, is also part of the DMA's behavioral health program
advisory council.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Fendell and Urban, others planning to speak at
the news conference include Barbara Rhuda of the Alliance for the
Mentally Ill, clinical psychologist Paul K. Ling, psychiatric nurse
Patricia Hayward and former state senator and current Democratic
gubernatorial candidate Patricia McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   But state and Partnership officials say that they have responded
in a timely fashion to requests for information, and that the
quality of care has been maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of no complaints,'' said John Widdison, spokesman
for the Department of Mental Health, which used to provide the
services that the Partnership now does.
</P>
<P>
   While Widdison said he could not comment directly on the
Partnership contract, since DMA, also known as Medicaid,
administers it, he added, ``We hold Medicaid accountable and
Medicaid holds the Partnership accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sheola, chief executive officer for the Partnership,
said DMA has been so satisfied with the services that it has agreed
to extend the Partnership's three-year contract an additional year,
through 2000. In addition, DMA has just awarded the Partnership a
two-year, $3.4 million contract to administer another state
program, the primary care clinician network management service for
Medicaid patients, Sheola said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does suggest a high level of confidence that the (DMA)
commissioner has in us,'' Sheola said. In addition, he pointed to
several other organizations that have supported the Partnership's
work, including Mental Health Corporations of Massachusetts Inc.,
which represents providers, such as community mental health
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   While critics such as Mel Urban have charged the Partnership
with denying patients necessary care to make money, Sheola said the
contract is structured in such a way as to discourage that from
happening.
</P>
<P>
   Sheola said patient confidentiality prevented him from
commenting on the Urban case, but he added that under Partnership
policy, rarely, if ever, are patients denied hospital admission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our general policy is our members get access to the highest
quality care as quickly as possible,'' Sheola said. ``We have an
obligation and a commitment to provide access to the least
restrictive, most clinically appropriate care that's available.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
