u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARRY-YEARS-BOS &LR;      06-10 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRY-YEARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOVE STORY OF GLOBE-SPANNING, BLINDNESS AND LONG ABSENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The memories endured over the years: There was a Christmas
party, an ice cream date, a trip to his senior prom. She was the
girl with the beautiful singing voice who won all the solos in
choir.
</P>
<P>
   The details dissipated with time, but some facts remained
indelible _ that Anjali Henry was the girl to whom John Gallagher
had once given a friendship ring, who had so sweetly, so naively
told their friends that they were engaged. That they had grown
apart, as people do, after he graduated from the Perkins School for
the Blind in 1982. That the same year, she had returned home to
India and he had begun growing up and realizing what he had already
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years after they last spoke, John had no means to find
Anjali, except an outdated address and a nagging desire to learn
what had happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   He composed his first letter in 1988, dictating the words to a
volunteer writer, saying that he'd been a fool to lose her. No
reply came. Undaunted, he wrote letter after letter, year after
year, lightly touching on the subject that wore on his heart more
and more: Why didn't she respond?
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, he received his first reply.
</P>
<P>
   This is how John Gallagher found Anjali Henry, the one who got
away.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher, 37, is not shy, not easily intimidated. Though
legally blind _ he can see bright colors and silhouettes _ the
Belmont native set off across country to attend college in
California. Though his balance is hindered by Friedreich's atoxia,
a nerve disorder that causes his hands to shake, makes him stagger,
and sometimes sends him to a wheelchair, he set out for the Florida
Keys nine years ago to swim with dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy just kind of does whatever he wants,'' said his
sister, Deborah Poirier, of Sudbury. ``He does things most sighted
people wouldn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was typical of John _ a man twice elected to Belmont Town
Meeting, who sued the town for failure to better accommodate the
handicapped _ to hang on with pit bull persistence in trying to
locate Anjali.
</P>
<P>
   When he first began sending her letters he used an old address
she'd given him before he graduated. He wrote two or three times a
year over the next eight years, until someone in India took pity on
him and wrote to let him know his letters had fallen victim to a
changed district and zip code.
</P>
<P>
   With childlike optimism, he wrote again to the correct address,
to a girl now grown, graduated, accomplished, and quite surprised
to hear from him. ``I couldn't figure out why, after all those
years, this person was interested in me halfway around the world,''
Anjali said.
</P>
<P>
   Anjali, 33, who is completely blind, had left the Perkins campus
in Watertown in 1982, returning to India to finish high school,
college, and earn a master's degree in medical and
psychiatric &UR;  &LR; social work. She went on to open a psychiatric wing at
Christian Hospital &UR;  &LR; _ where her parents are administrators _ in the
state of Orissa, and thought little about the young man she had
dated for just five months before she left.
</P>
<P>
   When a letter from John first reached her in April 1996, she
considered it a curiosity from an old friend. She didn't answer
until a second one came. But as they began writing regularly, their
words grew more familiar, more intense.
</P>
<P>
   She still remembers the time _ 11:30 a.m. on Sept. 5, 1996 _
when she received an unforgettable letter. ``After 14 years, I know
I still love you,'' John wrote, a message that left her stunned.
``My cousin was with me and read it to me, and I remember saying to
her, `How can he say that? I mean, he hasn't seen me in 14 years,'
'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   John said he carried her in his heart all those years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never let the memory die and always have that glimmer of
hope,'' he said. ``That's what love is _ it never dies.''
</P>
<P>
   Letters were no longer enough for them after that moment. They
began talking on the phone as often as possible, and, when John
suggested a trip to India, Anjali asked him to hurry. ``I just
wanted to know what his intentions were,'' she said. ``And everyone
told me, don't hope too much. It may end up to be nothing.'' So
John began making plans, despite his family's fears for his safety
on a six-week trip to an unfamiliar land.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't believe he was going to undertake this, with
his handicap, and with the people that are in India and how lax
they are with handicapped (accessibility),'' said his father,
Bernard Gallagher of Belmont. ``But John does what he's going to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   So in December 1996, after three months of intense
correspondence and regular phone calls, John boarded a plane for a
21-hour flight to India &UR;  &LR; _ from Logan International Airport to
Frankfurt, Germany, where he had a seven-hour layover until the
flight to Delhi. He had arranged for assistance at the airports.
</P>
<P>
   But his nervousness was magnified by his expensive cargo _ an
engagement ring in his pants pocket. Before he left, he had
scheduled a trip to a jeweler, who described the stones and offered
him ring after ring to feel and choose.
</P>
<P>
   He kept it in his pocket the entire trip. ``I was scared to
death,'' he said. ``I never let it out of my sight.''
</P>
<P>
   When he finally had a chance to see her silhouette, she was just
as he remembered. ``It's almost like a light went on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she was guarded, quiet, wary of his purpose, as her
family members welcomed him with garland. It was the coming weeks,
filled with laughter and remembering, that made her know.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, just after midnight, New Year's Day 1997, John led
Anjali into the hallway of her aunt's home and asked her to marry
him. Years after she'd eagerly accepted his friendship ring, Anjali
was oblivious when he handed her a box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `What's this?' '' she said. ``He said, `A ring.' I
said, `What for?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her family was floored. They urged the couple to take more time
to get to know one another. So Anjali and John held off their
formal engagement _ until Jan. 28. ``I guess I just realized he was
the one for me,'' Anjali said.
</P>
<P>
   They postponed plans for the wedding _ enduring another 10
months of separation, phone calls and letters _ until Anjali could
come to America in December. She had to leave her job, and is
trying to find comparable work here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here she had a fabulous job in India and she took a chance,''
said Roz Rowley, a Perkins teacher who taught Anjali and has
resumed a friendship with her. ``Not many people would do that,
come all the way around a part of the world to see if a
relationship would actually work.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons for her to be frightened, but Anjali is
certain of her decision based on one concept: Faith.
</P>
<P>
   On June 20, before 108 witnesses in the First Congregational
Church in Cambridge, Anjali Henry and John Gallagher plan to begin
a life together, once again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
