<HEADLINE>
CLEAN AIR NEEDED FOR THIS COURTHOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years is a long time to ask anyone to hold his breath, but
that's exactly what the Commonwealth of Massachusetts expects of
employees at Malden District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Clerks and probation officers, court officers and secretaries
have been pleading with Presiding Justice Paul C. Cavanaugh since
1995 to have the air quality of the century-old brick courthouse
tested for contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   In two of the last three years, employees have submitted
petitions to Cavanaugh and his supervisors, alerting them to the
persistent respiratory problems and other ailments plaguing the
staff. According to the employees' survey, more than half of them
experience burning eyes, headaches, nosebleeds, and breathing
problems. None report suffering those symptoms before their
employment at Malden District Court. All suspect indoor pollution
as the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-seven employees signed the most recent memo this spring,
urging ``that air quality testing be performed immediately and that
the results be shared with all employees of Malden District Court.
If air quality problems are identified, we further request that
permanent structural changes be made to the building to correct the
problem rather than a repetition of the inadequate stop-gap
measures taken to date.''
</P>
<P>
   When the judge and administrative offices of the Trial Court
again turned a deaf ear, the employees spent $1,000 of their own
money to hire ATC Associates of Woburn to analyze two ceiling tiles
spirited out of the building.
</P>
<P>
   The results surprised no one.
</P>
<P>
   The ceiling samples contained visible microbiological growth.
The bacteria and fungal spores identified by air quality engineers
included Stachybotrys chartarum, a toxic mold that is known to
cause headaches, skin rashes, fatigue, nausea, nosebleeds, and
respiratory illness, and is a suspected carcinogen.
</P>
<P>
   When Stachybotrys chartarum in much smaller amounts was found on
the ceilings and in the heating ducts at Haverhill District Court
three years ago, the building was closed for eight months until the
sources of water entry and condensation were identified and
eliminated, the contaminated material removed, and the courthouse
thoroughly disinfected.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, individual ceiling tiles conspicuously stained
green, yellow, and brown from the toxic mold at Malden District
Court have merely been replaced, and the source of the
contamination left unaddressed.
</P>
<P>
   To compound matters, employees at the courthouse say they worry
that too much agitation about working conditions could cost them
their jobs. Cavanaugh is said to take a dim view of employee
activism. In his five years as presiding judge he has replaced
clerks with friends from Medford: two waitresses from his favorite
restaurants and his longtime travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Cavanaugh has been unavailable to talk about air quality
at the courthouse. He is vacationing in Paris, a trip court
employees say was booked from the law library telephone by his
administrative assistant/travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, patronage is endemic in the lower courts. Cavanaugh,
a former state legislator and Middlesex registrar of probate,
apparently runs his court in the time-honored tradition of many
political appointees. But even in Massachusetts, intimidation is
frowned upon in the judiciary. Last September Cavanaugh reportedly
removed his robe while on the bench, rolled it into a ball, and
threw it at his session clerk after she pointed out a procedural
oversight. She also happens to be one of those employees pressing
for an air quality review. A colleague who witnessed the outburst
filed a complaint with the Judicial Conduct Commission, which has
yet to rule on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   After the shop steward read the air quality report, the union
filed a class action grievance last month, accusing the
commonwealth of violating the health and safety provisions of the
contract. Even Judge Roanne Sragow, the regional administrative
judge, forwarded a copy of the staff-financed report to Michael
Jordan, director of capital projects for the Trial Court.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has not responded. He may be waiting to see if the
Legislature plans to release the long-delayed $345 million bond
bill to make critical repairs to many of the state's crumbling
courthouses, including the one in Malden.
</P>
<P>
   While court administrators and Beacon Hill lawmakers delay,
employees of Malden District Court begin a fourth year holding
their breath.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
