<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SWITZERLAND-3TAKES-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A TASTE OF ITALY, WITH SWISS EFFICIENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 14)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUGANO, Switzerland _ Slurping the last of the foam from my
cappuccino, I begin the long process of trying to signal the waiter
for the bill and take one final look around sun-splashed Piazza
della Riforma.
</P>
<P>
   It's a balmy May morning, and the scent of jasmine is in the
air. Palm trees shade a nearby avenue buzzing with Alfa Romeos and
Vespa motor scooters. At cafes around the cobbled piazza, men and
women in up-to-the-minute Milan fashions are greeting each other
with kisses and hearty buon giornos.
</P>
<P>
   Finally catching the waiter's eye, I check my watch and realize
I'd better hurry to the ``stazione.'' There is no chance of my
train being late because this is, after all, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes called the Swiss Riviera _ two words one normally
doesn't associate with each other _ the canton of Ticino has been
enchanting and disorienting visitors for centuries. It's a slice of
the Italian Lakes region that, due to 15th-century geopolitics,
happens to be within the political boundaries of Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Separated from the rest of the country by the snow-capped Alps,
it's a region that blends two vastly different cultures: its
language, food, religion, architecture and fashions are Italian,
but Ticino someone makes it all operate with Swiss efficiency,
tidiness and spot-on punctuality.
</P>
<P>
   It's a land with a sun-baked Mediterranean climate, where
vineyards climb steep hillsides and villas with red-tile roofs line
the shores of vast, fiord-like lakes. In craggy valleys reaching
deep into the Alps' southern ramparts, walking paths cross arched,
Roman-style stone bridges and meander past trailside shrines to the
Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   Shaped like an arrowhead pointing toward the Mediterranean,
Ticino once belonged to the Lombardy region of Italy, being wrested
back and forth between Milan and Como until the late 1400s. In
1478, while Lombardy was distracted by internal warfare, the Swiss
began annexing the southern approaches to the strategic and
lucrative St. Gotthard Pass over the Alps. Thirty-five years later,
all of Ticino was in Swiss hands.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered if having a southern European culture and a northern
European government would cause strife, but this particular brand
of diversity seems to sit well with Ticinans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our heart we're more Italian than Swiss, but I think
everybody here is happy to be Swiss,'' said Marilyn Crivelli, a
lifelong Lugano resident who was showing us around town. ``Nothing
against Italy, but here in Switzerland our government works and our
money is stable.''
</P>
<P>
   For exploring Ticino, my wife, Jeri, and I chose as our bases
two towns with confoundingly similar names _ Lugano and Locarno _
and similar locations: each sits on the northwest corner of a
large, finger-like lake that straddles the Swiss-Italian border.
</P>
<P>
   Lugano is the smaller and more prosperous of the two, and claims
to have the greatest concentration of banks in Europe, possibly the
world: There is one financial institution here for every 300
residents. One morning, when I couldn't get my card to work in the
ATM at a Credit Suisse branch, I walked 20 steps across the piazza
to the next bank _ another Credit Suisse branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Renaissance, the only ones who could afford to hire
the great architects of the day were the churches,'' Crivelli said.
``Today it's the banks.''
</P>
<P>
   All that wealth finds an outlet on Via Nassa, the Fifth Avenue
of Lugano. It's a cobbled, pedestrian-only street lined with the
glittering nameplates of Versace, Gucci, Rolex and Patek Phillipe.
Price tags in the windows range from expensive to
surely-you-must-be-joking. If you're looking to spend the price of
a used Volvo on a wristwatch, you'll have no trouble doing it here.
</P>
<P>
   At the south end of Via Nassa, near the shore of Lago di Lugano,
we came to the scaffolded, gutted facade of the once-grand,
once-palatial Grand Hotel Palace, a remnant of the days when Lugano
was a sun-dappled playground for the crowned heads of Europe. Queen
Victoria stayed there, as did Czar Nicholas II.
</P>
<P>
   Lugano still regularly lures a few present or past heads of
state, including King Faisal of Saudi Arabia and, I'm told, George
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Next door to the hotel is the surprising Santa Maria degli
Angioli church. It doesn't look particularly noteworthy from the
outside, and I'd already passed it several times without going in.
But when Crivelli pushed open the thick oak doors, I was stunned: A
massive arch between the nave and the choir was covered by a
remarkable fresco of the Passion and Crucifixion painted in 1529 by
Bernardino Luini, a pupil of Leonardo da Vinci.
</P>
<P>
   The lower reaches of the fresco were partially erased. Crivelli
explained it happened when the walls were scrubbed after the church
was used as a hospital during an outbreak of plague in the 1700s.
On one unscathed wall of the church is Luini's version of the Last
Supper, with his teacher da Vinci sitting in for one of the
disciples; in a little chapel off the nave hangs a depiction of the
Madonna believed to have been painted by Leonardo himself.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Afterward we went for a walk through the tidy civic gardens
along the shore of Lago di Lugano. Beneath palm trees, magnolias
and mimosas were in bloom. Couples strolled with paper cups of
gelato and swans glided through the lake. I checked the newspaper
and found that elsewhere in Switzerland _ on the other side of the
Alps _ it was cool and drizzly. It was hard not to feel smug.
</P>
<P>
   If we needed a reminder we were in Switzerland, we got it the
next day when we checked the train schedule for our short trip to
Locarno. Our train was scheduled to arrive in Bellizona at 10:03
a.m., while the connecting train to Locarno pulled out at 10:07
a.m. It's hard to think of another country that would purposely
schedule connections that closely. But our trains hit their marks
precisely, and we made the Locarno train with plenty of time _
well, 30 seconds _ to spare.
</P>
<P>
   Locarno, you might recall, is the town Hemingway's character
rowed through the night to reach at the end of ``A Farewell to
Arms.'' It's located on the shore of Lago Maggiore, most of which
lies in Italy. At only 672 feet above sea level, Locarno is the
lowest and warmest spot in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lugano, it's sprinkled with cobbled piazzas and arcades
full of inviting outdoor cafes, all connected by narrow, winding
passageways. Lake steamers come and go, connecting Locarno with
Stresa and other Italian resorts along Lago Maggiore.
</P>
<P>
   A transportation hub, Locarno makes a great base for exploring
lakeside neighbors such as Ascona and the rustic mountain valleys
that radiate out from the lake like fingers in a glove.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon we boarded a lake steamer for the half-hour
journey to the Brissago Islands, famous for their vast, subtropical
botanical gardens.
</P>
<P>
   A retreat for the well-to-do since Roman times, the islands were
bought in 1885 by a Russian baroness who built a villa to house her
salon of artists and writers. She traveled the world collecting
exotic plants for her gardens, and cataloged the plants she
cultivated in a diary that was published in 1913 in London.
</P>
<P>
   When the baroness fell on hard times in 1927, she sold the
islands to a wealthy German businessman, who added a Roman bath,
which remains today. Forty years ago the properties passed to the
local government. Today a Swiss conservation and nature group
maintains them and opens them to the public between April and
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   Few English-speaking travelers come to Ticino, and I was
distressed to see that the gardens' only signs in English were the
ones asking visitors not to pick the flowers (which, incidentally,
I saw several non-English-speakers doing). Without knowing
precisely what I was looking at, I relaxed and followed my nose
around the gardens, enjoying the perfumed air and the views of
nearby alpine peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Lacing on our hiking boots, we rode the electric train the next
day up the wooded Val Centovalli (literally, ``a hundred valleys,''
because of the countless side valleys) to Verdasio, beneath the
snow-capped Pizzo Leone. From there we hopped into a gondola that
carried us 1,400 feet up the mountainside to Monte de Comino. In
Ticino, as elsewhere in Switzerland, one rarely has to hike uphill
unless one really wants to.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting at the top, a steaming bowl of homemade minestrone in
her hands, was Signora Sargenti, known locally as the
``minestronessa.'' She sat us down on the granite terrace of her
restaurant, Al Riposa Romantico, with a sweeping view of the valley
and mountain peaks stretching into Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Her restaurant was a typical Ticino ``grotto.'' The name dates
back to the time when mountain peasants found it easier to locate a
small cave than to dig a cellar for storing food and wine. Many
cafes are still built next to caves, although the word grotto has
now come to mean any rustic Ticino restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Signora Sargenti's minestrone was dense with vegetables grown on
the mountainside above her grotto, and we sopped it up with thick
slabs of crusty brown bread. Next came platters of polenta, beef
stew with carrots, salad, cappuccinos and biscotti. In this
Italian-flavored land, multicourse midday meals are served with an
afternoon nap, rather than a hike, in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, our walk was almost all downhill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our path contoured around the mountainside, through pastures
dotted with wildflowers and stone shepherds' huts, and followed a
ridge line as it plunged into a deep, fragrant pine forest. Through
gaps in the trees we caught views of stony villages and terraced
vineyards clinging to distant mountainsides and, at the foot of the
slopes, the blue waters of Lago Maggiore.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
