<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXPORTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS EXPORTS RISE 13.2 PERCENT IN FIRST QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL BOWEN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas exports were up 13.2 percent in the first quarter of 1998
from the same period a year ago, outpacing national export growth
by almost 3-to-1, says the Texas Department of Economic
Development.
</P>
<P>
   Texas exports, a key measure of the state's economic health, hit
$22.2 billion in the first quarter and are on track to surpass
1997's record of $84.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The first-quarter export numbers have been widely anticipated as
an indicator of the effect of the Asian economic crisis on Texas
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Although exports to Asia were, indeed, off, those declines were
more than offset by increases in Texas' exports to what are now its
top three trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   Exports to Japan, Texas' third-largest trading partner in the
past, were off 10 percent. Exports to other major Asian
destinations _ Hong Kong, China, South Korea, the Philippines,
Indonesia and Malaysia _ were also down.
</P>
<P>
   But with export sales increasing on almost every other front,
there is little bad news in the report, according to trade experts.
</P>
<P>
   Exports to Texas' largest trading partner, Mexico, were up 25
percent; to Canada, up 17 percent; and to the United Kingdom, up
21.5 percent. The increases were mostly due to increased sales of
computers, electronic equipment, chemicals and transportation
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing is the increasing importance of our NAFTA
trading partners,'' said Branner Stewart, a research analyst for
the Department of Economic Development. ``Not only are they our top
partners, but they own a commanding share of our export growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Exports to Singapore, Venezuela and the Netherlands also posted
increases of 25 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really matters for Texas is the total numbers of
exports,'' said Bernard Weinstein, director of the Center for
Economic Development and Research at the University of North Texas
at Denton. ``If exports to Mexico and Canada grow faster than what
is lost to Asia, we won't be hurt by Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said the North Texas economy has become tied to trade
growth because of the overseas demand for electronics and other
locally produced goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas and Fort Worth have the most export-sensitive economy
in the state,'' Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the decrease in Texas exports to Japan and South Korea
was in chemicals used in manufacturing, according to Department of
Economic Development officials.
</P>
<P>
   Exports to those and other East Asian countries are expected to
decline further through the year as those countries are faced with
buying more manufacturing goods from overseas using currencies that
are worth less.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will have more problems when their inventories are
exhausted,'' said C.A. Sumangil, a senior vice president for trade
finance for Nations Bank in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   But the looming problems in Asia were outshone by the bright
export picture for Texas goods in Mexico, Latin America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Sales to Mexico jumped to $8.9 billion for the quarter, up from
$7.1 billion during first quarter 1997. Canada was a distant second
at $2.67 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The United Kingdom replaced Japan as the third-largest market
for Texas goods with $703 million. Japan fell to fourth with $687
million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
