<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2790 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SWITZERLAND-3R     06-10 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SWITZERLAND-3RDTAKE-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
  
 LUGANO, Switzerland: of Lago Maggiore.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lower down along the ridge, we came to the old village of Selna,
a smattering of old shepherds' huts and stone barns with slate
roofs. Most were abandoned, the victims of the easier and more
stable livelihoods available in Milan and Locarno, but a few
sprouted solar panels and satellite television dishes. They had
been converted into weekend homes by Locarnans, Morini said.
</P>
<P>
   Our hike the next day was in the Val Verzasca. At Locarno's
train station we hopped aboard a Swiss postal bus, one of the nifty
vehicles that traverse the country's sinuous mountain roads,
delivering passengers _ and the mail _ to remote villages.
</P>
<P>
   The bus climbed a vineyard-covered hillside and entered the
valley, where waterfalls plunged down the sheer limestone walls and
the Verzasca River was a series of emerald pools connected by
frothy cascades. In less than an hour the bus arrived at the end of
the road, the alpine hamlet of Sognogna. Like every village in this
Roman Catholic valley, it was dominated by a towering stone
campanile with church bells that gonged as if to announce our
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   We poked around the town's winding, cobbled streets, but were
soon inundated by German tourists spilling off a tour bus. Passing
a passel of shops selling postcards and Leonardo DiCaprio T-shirts
(he's huge in Ticino), we gulped down a quick cappuccino in a
grotto, shouldered our day packs and hit the trail.
</P>
<P>
   The broad, gentle path meandered down the valley through a
forest of chestnut and oak, crisscrossing the river on arched stone
bridges, always staying on the opposite side from the road.
</P>
<P>
   In no time we'd left Leonardo DiCaprio behind and entered a
world unchanged for centuries. Here many of the stone shepherd huts
and barns were still in use. Above the village of Gerra we heard a
metallic tinkling and rounded a corner to find a herd of black,
bearded billy goats grazing in an idyllic pasture and drinking out
of a stone fountain and trough built in the 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we'd reached Lavertezzo, with its picturesque
double-arched stone bridge _ the Ponte del Salti _ I was famished.
We ducked into the first grotto we saw, and shortly I was tucking
into the signature dish of Ticino, ``risotto al funghi'' _ saucy
rice with pungent forest mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The next day we thought we'd try another gentle, down-valley
walk in the Val Maggia. When the postal bus delivered us to the
hamlet of Cavergno, however, a chilly mist was spilling over the
crest of the Alps from northern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes down the valley, in the village of Bignasco, we
jumped aboard another postal bus and within an hour were back in
bright sunshine, walking along the lakeside promenade in Ascona,
past palm trees and flower gardens.
</P>
<P>
   This colorful, inviting town, filled with galleries and museums,
is the Sante Fe of Ticino, attracting writers and artists from all
over the Continent, including, over the years, Hermann Hesse and
Paul Klee.
</P>
<P>
   Peeling off our polarfleece, we found a table in a cafe along
the promenade and ordered a bottle of white Merlot. And that's how
we spent the afternoon _ soaking up the balmy Mediterranean sun,
inhaling the fragrant breeze and watching the lake steamers out in
Lago Maggiore, crisscrossing between Switzerland and Italy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
