<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NANCY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NANCY JENKINS COOKS UP THE SUNNY WORLD OF TUSCANY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, when Nancy Harmon Jenkins bought a
run-down farmhouse in Teverina, in the northern Italian region of
Tuscany, the area had made so few concessions to modern times that
farm animals were stabled under the houses in the winter. Jenkins
has seen the arrival of electricity, and with it television,
telephones, and refrigerators. Indoor plumbing has come, along with
washing machines. Now there are grand weddings for the children,
and the houses have separate kitchens so that every family event
(except sleep, birth, and death) no longer takes place in one great
room. But what surprises Jenkins most is not the technology that
filtered to the mountain village but subtler changes that eased
into Tuscan farm life _ like the pineapple upside-down cake
Jenkins's neighbor served her several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It might as well have jumped out of the pages of Better Homes &AMP;
Gardens, said Jenkins during a recent visit to Boston. The
pineapple came right out of a can. ``I had never heard of anyone in
Italy making one,'' she says. But Tuscans _ like villagers
worldwide _ are enamored of what is new, she concedes. ``And
there's so much more in the air now.''
</P>
<P>
   It works both ways. Tuscany was the first region of Italy
American chefs turned to when they decided to lighten their food,
discarding the old red sauces common to Italian-American cooking.
Crusty breads, oils for dipping, simple grilled entrees are
standard menu fare as is the ubiquitous tiramisu. Long before the
American larder was stocked with handmade pastas, focaccia, and
sun-dried tomatoes, Jenkins was in the kitchen in Italy, cooking
with her neighbors. Though many cooks are well versed in Tuscan
cooking, Nancy Jenkins is unquestionably the established authority.
And her new ``Flavors of Tuscany'' (Broadway Books) is bound to
become the definitive guide.
</P>
<P>
   The role of authority suits her. She's a food scholar who has
lived in Spain, Lebanon, and Cyprus, and has traveled extensively
around the Mediterranean. She joined The New York Times Living
section to cover food at one point, served as editor of the Journal
of Gastronomy for the American Institute of Wine and Food, and
taught Mediterranean food history at the Radcliffe Seminars at
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   She began her writing career early. As a student at Wellesley
College (class of 1959), she and her Harvard College friend Bill
Bayer wrote ``Love With a Harvard Accent'' under the pseudonym
Leonie St. John. (Bayer is now married to cookbook author Paula
Wolfert.) Since then, Jenkins has written ``The Boat Beneath the
Pyramid'' (a study of ancient Egyptian boats), ``The Mediterranean
Diet Cookbook'' and ``Flavors of Puglia.'' She divides her time
between Tuscany and Camden, Maine, where she was raised.
</P>
<P>
   She landed in Italy &UR;  &LR; as a young mother, then married to Loren
Jenkins, a foreign correspondent based in Europe, now an
international editor &UR;  &LR; at National Public Radio. Their children _
Sara, now 33, and Nicolas, 28 _ used to play with the children on
neighboring farms.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Jenkins remembers when most local farmers raised wheat
instead of turning to tobacco for the cash, when women baked the
traditional salt-free bread in wood-fired ovens, and when there was
hardly any need to buy food. ``It's the rapidity of change today
that's most striking,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she says, the industrious Tuscans are still tending
their olive trees, turning their olives into oil, harvesting summer
crops for the table, slaughtering chickens and pigs, making
sausages and smoking pork legs, pruning their orchards, and boiling
conserves from the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   And they eat and celebrate in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hospitality on such a Homeric scale,'' Jenkins writes, ``is
what continues to bind together Tuscan villages like Teverina,
where family pride is displayed in the simple abundance of a table
on which almost all the dishes represent the fruits of the family's
own labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins's table in Teverina is often crowded with guests,
although she doesn't raise vegetables and livestock. In fact, it
took years to turn the farm into a habitable residence. The
property agent who showed her the house, she says, came armed with
a stick to scare away snakes. She dreams of turning her land into
an organic olive tree grove, but she's making only a little headway
in raising the trees. ``I planted 200, lost 50, and I get a couple
liters of good oil. Several neighbors put their olives together
because you need a certain number to take to the press.''
</P>
<P>
   During her visit, she conducted an olive-oil tasting at
restaurant Tosca in Hingham, while chef Joe Simone cooked recipes
from her book. Over the years, Jenkins has become knowledgeable
about olive harvests, modern extracting machines, and how the
residents around the Mediterranean produce oils.
</P>
<P>
   She showed how to taste oil. ``Take a sip,'' she advises, ``then
add air to your mouth and make a sucking sound. It's a very rude
sound.'' The air brings out grassy or citrusy tastes and other
flavors, she says. Tuscan oil, which she is partial to, is
characterized by its peppery taste because ``the olives are
harvested when they're so young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oils for tasting are all extra virgin. It's like fine wine as
opposed to jug wine. They're not refined. The olives have been
extracted mechanically without solvents or chemicals,'' she
explains, ``and they don't taste of mud, must, or rancidity.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, Jenkins uses only extra-virgin olive oil, the best on
the market. She admits to deep-fat frying with it, though she says
producers send her oil, so she isn't popping a cork on a $30 bottle
to make fritters. ``Nothing in the world fries as well as olive
oil,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   When she's traveling and finds an oil she likes, she tries to
get some shipped to the specialty and take-out market in Rockport,
Maine, that she owns with her sister, Jane Carr, and Carr's
catering partner, Sarah Greer. The chef is Nelda McClellan, who
worked at the former Michela's in Cambridge and Biba in Boston, and
now lives in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The partners bought the shop, called the Market Basket, a year
ago. ``Jane and Sarah are the working partners,'' says Jenkins. ``I
like to think of myself as roaming the globe and finding products.
Actually, I go in once in a while to get chocolate peanut butter
candies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Market Basket is at the crossroads of Route 90 and Route 1,
and there is more traffic than ever since MBNA Corp., the
credit-card company, opened offices nearby. Though the facade is
dreary, says Jenkins, ``we can't keep up with the demand.''
</P>
<P>
   When she returns to Maine, she remembers what it is about
Tuscany that draws her. ``I think of the plain-spoken Tuscans as
the Yankees of Italy,'' she writes, ``which may be one reason why
Tuscany appeals so much to rock-ribbed Yankees like me.'' Another
element surely is the pragmatic way they use their land and cook
their meals. Maine Yankees, like Tuscans, subscribe to a
``use-it-up, wear-it-out, make-it-do, or do-without'' sensibility,
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her cookbook, chapters open with sepia-toned
photographs of the Antolinis, Jenkins's neighbors in Teverina. All
the photos were taken by Nicolas and Sara Jenkins. Sara, who worked
as a chef at Figs in Charlestown for several years, now cooks at a
restaurant in Florence.
</P>
<P>
   The lives of these neighbors open a window into the landscape of
Tuscan life. Mita Antolini, at 70, looks considerably older than
Jenkins (who is 10 years younger) from a harder life. She's the
matriarch of a family that includes her husband, Bruno, and their
three children and their spouses. The only son, Arnaldo, started
raising tobacco when he took over the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Antolini taught Jenkins to make bread in the beehive oven set
into a side wall of her house, then toast the same bread into
crostini and top it with ripe tomatoes sauteed to a pulpy
consistency. And to celebrate a wheat or tobacco or olive harvest,
she taught her how to make feather-light lasagnas.
</P>
<P>
   When Arnaldo Antolini married his longtime sweetheart, Maura,
they began renovations on the house. They raised the roof and made
their living quarters downstairs. ``They live in an apartment
underneath the house _ where the stables once were,'' says Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Maura is in charge of cooking meals for family celebrations,
which might include 30 or 40 relatives of many generations. On this
table goes the real food of Tuscany: livers from their own fowl,
sauteed and mashed with capers and anchovies; back-yard chickens
roasted in the wood-fueled oven; and wild greens collected from the
land for a salad. To this, Mita Antolini might add the tiniest
violets, collected on the farm that morning. She saw this done on
television and copied it as soon as she had the chance. Maura might
produce one of her favorite desserts: the fried cream puff called
bombolini. She no longer fills it with homemade custard but rather
with a nutty-chocolate cream _ spooned directly from a jar.
</P>
<P>
   Tuscan cuisine, writes Jenkins, is born out of history and
geography. Where descendants of the Etruscans, Romans, and ancient
Umbrians meet on the hills of Chianti and the valleys near
Florence, the air is redolent with change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
