<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2798 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CARTE-BOS &LR;      06-10 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CARTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHATEVER HAS HAPPENED TO THE WAITER?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scenario will sound familiar: You and your friends have
sipped your coffee and nibbled desserts. The possible topics of
conversation have pretty much been covered, and the latest photos
of your kids admired several times. In fact, for the past several
minutes, you've sat in silence, all wondering the same thing: Where
is the check? What happened to that waiter? What is going on?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is today's all-purpose reply to any and every
question: It's the booming economy. State unemployment is 2.9
percent _ the lowest rate since 1987. There's a ferment of
restaurants opening, upscaling, and enlarging as good times and
'90s lifestyle trends fuel more dining out.
</P>
<P>
   Finding waiters and waitresses to meet the level of service
demanded by today's customer is a daunting task. Asian restaurants
all over town have ``Help wanted'' signs in the windows. Large
restaurants are running ads in the newspapers. Artists who have
given up the waiting trade, in which so many of them make ends
meet, report calls from former employers and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   New restaurants are especially stretching to fill wait staff
rosters. ``It's been very difficult,'' says Johanne Killeen, who
with her husband, George Germon, took over Cafe Louis in Back Bay
in late April. Killeen says they've been ``getting some applicants
but not as many as I would have expected.'' It's been hard to find
the right kind of applicants, she adds. Killeen and Germon also own
Al Forno in Providence, long known for friendly, knowledgeable, and
extremely competent wait staff, and she speaks passionately about
wanting their new apple-green bandbox of a cafe to be remembered
for the same casual but nurturing service. Killeen thought it would
be easier to gather wait staff in Boston than in Rhode Island but
is discovering the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   And putting together a staff takes time, Killeen says,
especially when training 20 or so people. ``People have to learn to
trust you, and you them,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Bor, the Colonnade Hotel's human resources director,
hires staff for both the hotel and its new restaurant, Brasserie
Jo. The big glitzy restaurant is owned by Jean Joho and Lettuce
Entertain You Inc. of Chicago. Bor says publicity about the place
and the name recognition of Lettuce Entertain You ``drew some
professional wait staff'' right away.
</P>
<P>
   Brasserie Jo is ``really doing the numbers,'' he says, making it
very attractive to wait staff, who depend on tips for a great part
of their earnings. However, Bor is quick to add, when the ``buzz
has passed its prime, we're in with the rest of the food
establishments'' vying for staff. In the last two years, finding
workers in all categories for the hotel has been ``getting tighter
and tighter.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees much advantage in being able to promote from within and
finds that moving a promising worker from the hotel housekeeping
staff to a busing job or back-waiter position in the restaurant is
often successful. ``I don't want somebody who's going to stay a day
or a week. Coming from a hotel perspective, I'm always trying to
bring turnover down.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, and thus the restaurant, is union property, Bor says,
and the pay is above the union wage ``at every level, and benefits
are included,'' a real advantage in hiring. A good training program
also helps, says Bor, so employees aren't set up for failure.
``Training is an integral part of advancement. Employees are very
aware if the company is spending time training them, knowing that
`this company is making sure I do a good job.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bor also collaborates with the Fenway Community Development
Corporation to help people coming from transitional assistance into
the workplace and with the Madison Park High School to Work
program. ``There's no question unemployment is down,'' Bor says,
``and it behooves all of us to find future workers in every nook
and cranny.'' Those workers probably wouldn't immediately help the
food and beverage end but might eventually, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   College students have traditionally been a pool of possible wait
staff, but Yusupha Ceesay, manager of the Elephant Walk in Boston,
says it's hard to fit the flexibility students want into the needs
of a busy restaurant. However, he says, most of the applicants are
students.
</P>
<P>
   Inexperience is another problem. ``Most people have never waited
at a restaurant before,'' Ceesay says, ``and it's hard at a
restaurant like the Elephant Walk because of the volume.'' He has
been extending training time for people who are not students but
have no experience, adding that ``two really worked.''
</P>
<P>
   On Cape Cod and the islands, where college students have
traditionally flocked for summer employment, the situation is also
tight, but many established restaurants find students aren't the
answer. Savoir Faire owner Scott Caskey in Edgartown on Martha's
Vineyard says, ``The days of college kids coming down here and
spending a couple of months waiting tables are over.'' His
restaurant opens in April, shutting out college students. More
crucially, housing on the island is scarce and very expensive.
``With the soaring economy, the real estate market is hotter than a
pistol,'' he adds. His restaurant depends on an ``almost 100
percent return'' of workers who have winter jobs at Boston
restaurants or at ski resorts. The manager at Nauset Beach Club in
East Orleans says the restaurant stays open year-round and the wait
staff will supplement slow months in the winter with part-time
jobs, knowing they'll make more in the busy summer months.
</P>
<P>
   From the restaurants' perspective, the employment outlook
doesn't show any signs of easing. Fred Breimyer, chief economist of
State Street Bank, says this is the tightest labor market of the
'90s. It was expected, but the degree is surprising even the
economists, he adds. The surge in jobs in this segment of the
service industry was predicted, according to the state's industry
occupation projections. In 1994, such jobs were estimated at about
51,000; for the year 2005, the estimate is almost 62,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mary-Catherine Deibel, co-owner of Up Stairs at the Pudding in
Harvard Square, says that as the entire culinary profession has
become more attractive, wait staff jobs have become more
attractive, too. It's ``no longer odious,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Customers are no longer shy about dining out and insist on a
higher level of service than once was common in American
restaurants. ``They expect a lot more and they deserve it,'' she
says, so getting and keeping a good wait staff is imperative. Many
at her restaurant have been there for years, but the wait staff
must form a team and yet welcome newcomers. ``We try to listen to
their concerns,'' Deibel says, adding that over the years she has
added management staff. Then the wait staff is ``asked only to
concentrate on service to the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the hunt for wait staff continues, looking for a few
good men and women. ``We love it when we find a pro who's not on
the way from point A to point B and plans on this as a career,''
says Johanne Killeen of Cafe Louis. ``We don't look for a specific
person but for ones who like people and want to please them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1356EDT &QL; 
