<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SWITZERLAND-INFO-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU GO TO SWITZERLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 14)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting around: A Swiss Pass covers travel on almost all rail
roads, all postal buses and most urban buses and lake steamers
(although not the ones in lakes Lugano and Maggio that are operated
by the Italians), plus discounts on funiculars and gondolas.
</P>
<P>
   Cost for a second-class pass ranges from $188 for four
consecutive days to $400 for an entire month. Passes also entitle
your companion to travel at a 40 percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay: In Lugano we stayed at the Hotel International au
Lac, Via Nassa 68, 6901 Lugano, Switzerland; phone:
011-41-91-922-75-41; fax: 011-41-91-922-75-44. Doubles with bath
start at 180 Swiss Francs (about $120.) Although in expensive by
Swiss standards, it was elegant, spotless and well- located.
</P>
<P>
   In Locarno we stayed at the Villa Pauliska Hotel &AMP; Ristorante,
6600 Mutalto, Via Orsalino 6, Locarno, Switzerland; phone:
011-41-91-743-05-41. Doubles with baths ran from 120 to 150 Swiss
Francs (about $81 to $100.) We stayed in the Green Room, which was
tiny; it's worth paying more for one of the others. The hotel is a
bit far from the center of town if you're on foot, and the staff
seemed to be focusing its attention more on the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat: The Villa Pauliska in Locarno served what were,
without a doubt, the best meals I've eaten in Switzerland. The
dishes were inventive and well-prepared, the dining room was
gorgeous and the service was attentive and delightfully unstuffy.
Four-course fixed- price dinners are 58 Swiss Francs (about $39),
not including wine. Definitely worth a splurge. Reservations
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   What to do: Lugano offers a free, highly recommended walking
tour. Offered on Mondays from April through October, the tour meets
at 9:30 a.m. at the Santa Maria degli Angioli church, where Via
Nassa hits the lake, and runs until 11:45 a.m. Reservations
required: 011-41-91-921-4664. Locarno's tours cost 10 Swiss Francs
per adult, half price for children 7-16, children under 7 free. The
tours are offered Mondays from April 13 to Oct. 30. Meet at the
Casino Locarno at 9:45 a.m.; tours run until 11:30 a.m.
Reservations are required: 011-41-91-751-9070.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: Contact the Swiss National Tourist Office,
222 N. Sepulveda Blvd., Suite 1570, El Segundo, CA 90245-4300; web:
www.switzerlandtourism.com; or by phoning Switzerland Tourism at
(415) 362-2260. This number can supply a list of travel agents
knowledgeable about Switzerland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
