<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PICNICS-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE BEST MEALS (AND VIEWS) AROUND, TRY A PICNIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 14)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Out table had one of the best views in Italy: A breathtaking
sunset vista across the Bay of Naples to the golden isles of Ischia
and Procida and the Sorrento Peninsula, with the cone of Mount
Vesuvius brooding over everything.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of view for which diners would gladly pay
extraordinary prices, but it wasn't costing us a single lira.
Actually, ``table'' isn't quite the right word: our dinner on the
island of Capri was a picnic on a park bench.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my most memorable traveling meals have been picnics: a
bagful of charcuterie goodies and a bottle of Cotes du Rhone on the
steps of Sacre Coeur in Paris; street-vendor falafels and Stella
Lager on the banks of the Nile; a wedge of Emmentaler cheese, a
tart green apple and some Tobblerone overlooking a glacier in the
Swiss Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Jeri and I started having picnics as a way to save money: eating
every lunch and dinner in a restaurant is a budget-buster,
particularly on long trips. But over the years we've found that we
look forward to them even when money is not an issue.
</P>
<P>
   On Capri, we wanted to enjoy the sunset view at dinner, but
found that, for the most part, Capri Town had squandered one of the
best vistas in that corner of the world. On Via Roma, the main
traffic street, the side with the view was taken up by a bus
station, two video arcades and a handful of gift shops. There was a
restaurant or two with window views, but their menus didn't tempt
us. However, right off Piazza Umberto I, where the funicular comes
up from Marina Grande, there were a couple of benches offering that
world-class view for free.
</P>
<P>
   Half the fun of a picnic is assembling it. Scrutinizing the
melons at open-air produce stands, sniffing the camemberts and
Roqueforts in pungent fromageries and pondering over baguettes in
boulangeries is a wonderful way to get inside the everyday life of
the community. There's no better conversational icebreaker than to
ask a signora her opinion of the day's tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before sunset, as the last of the day-trippers was
leaving the island, we began our shopping expedition in Capri Town,
joining the local shoppers thronging through the cool, whitewashed
alleys. Our noses led us to one good-smelling shop _ there was no
name above the door _ where we had the man behind the counter cut
us several thin slices of salty prosciutto from Parma and a thick
chunk of gooey, funky-smelling Gorgonzola cheese. I also had him
count out six dark, musty olives, each half the size of a golf
ball. Cost: 8,000 lire (about $4.60.)
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, at a produce market, we bought two sweet,
vine-ripened tomatoes, a 1.5-liter bottle of aqua minerale and a
ripe-smelling cantaloupe. Yikes! When the woman rang up our
purchases, the melon alone came to 8,500 lire _ about $4.90.
(Moral: always confirm the price of everything before buying.)
</P>
<P>
   With the water and the tomatoes, the bill at the produce market
totaled 12,600 lire _ $7.25.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner, we bought a half-loaf of crusty bread and
examined the wine bottles on the shelf. What amazed me was how
cheap they all were: Italians tend to think of wine as an everyday
ingredient of meals, not a splurge, and price it accordingly. After
some consideration, we chose a bottle of Tiberio Vino da Tavola
Rosso _ a red table wine produced up the road in Anacapri and named
for the Emporer Tiberius, who once ran the Roman Empire from a
villa on Capri and, persistent local rumor has it, hosted
spectacular orgies. The wine, according to its label, had won a
``gran premio'' award at a Buenos Aires competition in 1910 and
another at Rome in 1926, although things apparently have slowed
down quite a bit since then in the awards department.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was only 6,000 lire (about $3.45.) With the bread, the
bill at that shop came to 7,000 lire (about $4), bringing the total
for the entire meal to 27,600 lire (about $15.85) _ nearly a third
of which was the cantaloupe.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving our hotel, we'd grabbed two glasses out of our
room and borrowed two plates and two forks from the kitchen. I also
had my picnic kit, which contains a tea towel, a Swiss Army knife,
a plastic spreading knife (added to the kit after I gummed up my
previous Swiss Army knife with runny cheeses and peanut butter) and
some Handi Wipes.
</P>
<P>
   We got to the bench just as the setting sun was turning the
sweeping panorama golden. Spreading out the tea towel as a
tablecloth, we cut the cantaloupe into little slices (best
cantaloupe I've ever had, by the way; almost worth the price) and
wrapped them in the prosciutto. We tore off chunks of bread and
smeared Gorgonzola on them and dropped olives and slices of tomato
into our mouths, washing it all down with the mineral water and the
surprisingly drinkable Tiberio.
</P>
<P>
   Across the bay, the last light of day was shining on the island
of Procida, where they filmed ``Il Postino'' (``The Postman''). The
lights of Naples were starting to twinkle. Along Via Roma the
citizens of Capri Town, dressed up in their finest, were beginning
their passegiata _ their evening stroll around town.
</P>
<P>
   It was a scene we couldn't have matched in a restaurant _ at any
price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
