<SLUG> BC-TV-MAGIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC JOHNSON'S SHOW NEEDS A LITTLE MORE WORK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE MAGIC SHOW
</P>
<P>
   Starring Magic Johnson
</P>
<P>
   11:30 p.m.-12:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Mon.-Fri. on Fox, Ch. 25.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to judge a season on an opening-night performance _
you need only recall the Celtics' season-opening victory over the
champion Chicago Bulls to get the point.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Magic Johnson, one of the smartest players in the
history of the National Basketball Association, sought to spread
his influence, transferring his formidable skills from the
basketball court to a talk show on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   If Magic thought the NBA schedule was tough, it's a kid's game
compared with the persistent pressure under the glaring lights of a
five-day-a-week talk show.
</P>
<P>
   Based on opening night, it looks as if Magic's showtime is off
to a slow start. He negotiated the essential hurdle to becoming a
successful host _ he listened to his guests; however, none of them
had much to say.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Schwarzenegger tore down Magic's dressing room door and
showed a vintage clip of his TV debut with Lucille Ball and
answered questions from the audience. Question: ``What's the
heaviest thing you ever lifted?'' Answer: ``Magic's wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   After 10 minutes of backslapping with Arnold, Magic brought out
Whitney Houston, who also praised him for having his own show. They
briefly argued over who has won the most awards. Before one
digested this treacly moment, they started talking about how
problematic it is being recognized. So what do they think show
business is about? Anonymity? Then, she vacuumed the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Just before presenting Houston with a Laker jersey with her name
and his number on the back, Johnson slam-jammed her with another
puffball asking if there was going to be a sequel to ``The
Bodyguard.''
</P>
<P>
   As the night wore on, Magic seemed to get a little less nervous,
a little more relaxed. But he's got to ditch the hyperbole.
Everyone can't be the greatest star in the world.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems is that Magic Johnson seems to be a nice
guy. And that's the quickest way to die on TV. He needs a few of
Letterman's mischievous stunts and Arsenio Hall's satiric smarts.
He should take a week's worth of lessons from the lamented Garry
Shandling. More spice. Maybe they should have asked Bill Lambier,
the much-despised former Detroit Pistons star, to be an
opening-night guest. At least that would raise the chance for a
little conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Someone should also tell Magic to stop doing the job of the
audience. We're the ones who are supposed to be sitting down and
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Just before ``The Magic Show'' ended, musical director Sheila E.
performed a song with the repetitive lyric ``Magic's got his own
show.'' Stunt artiste Ray Wold finished off the night by setting
himself on fire. If only the rest of the show were as hot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
