<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2824 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      06-10 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DOES WEEKLY STANDARD TREAT GOLDWATER WITH KID GLOVES?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The odd thing isn't that Barry Goldwater's on the cover of  &UR; The
Weekly Standard  &LR; (June 16). It's that the Standard's treatment of
such a conservative icon should be so ... gingerly. This was the
man who started America's move rightward, after all, and without
whom Ronald Reagan (who made himself a national political figure
with his election-eve speech on Goldwater's behalf) would never
have gotten east of Death Valley. Yet the slightly affronted tone
here recalls that of a ventriloquist annoyed with his dummy.
Goldwater ``was not entirely serious about politics or
government,'' Robert D. Novak grumps. He was ``an unusually
reluctant presidential candidate,'' Jeffrey Bell laments. ``For all
his weaknesses and mistakes, he was a man who deserves to be
remembered,'' writes David Frum. Forgive the invidious speculation,
but when George McGovern goes you don't think The Nation will hem
and haw like that, do you? Maybe it's just the romance of the lost
cause: If only the right hadn't come back after 1964 (the way the
left has yet to come back after 1972), then they'd be nothing to
carp about. Ah, if only ...
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of departed American icons, there are at least six
Frank Sinatra commemoratives now out, one each from  &UR; Entertainment
Weekly &LR; ,  &UR; People &LR; , &UR; Life  &LR; (best in show, hands down), Gold
Collectors Series, Fanzine International, and (ahem) Larry Flynt
Publications. Perhaps the greatest tribute to Sinatra's
pop-cultural stature is his being saluted by such an unlikely pair
as  &UR; Rolling Stone  &LR; and  &UR; The New York Review of Books  &LR; (both June
25). RS gives him a cover line, 10 pages, and billing as ``The
First Rock Star.'' The NYRB offers brief tributes from Whitney
Balliett and the late Murray Kempton. Kempton's piece originally
ran as a 1996 Newsday column and quotes Ella Fitzgerald in what may
be as close to a definition of Sinatra's genius as we'll ever get:
``Frank. Just this little guy telling this story. That's all you
have to be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Sinatra was narrative, then Elvis was ``tableaux.'' Some of
them are as ``vivants'' as anything in our culture (the sneer, the
Sun recordings, the opening and acoustic portions of the '68
``comeback'' special) and many of them, well, maybe even ``morts''
gives them too much credit. It'll be interesting to see if, 20
years from now, there'll be a Frank equivalent of  &UR; Elvis
International Forum  &LR; (spring). True, the quarterly's hagiographical
stance precludes anything like comprehensiveness _ never is heard a
discouraging word, like, oh, girth, pharmaceuticals, or white
cotton panties _ but where else can you find out Elvis's shoe size
(11), how much he paid for his sunglasses ($200), or what brand of
soap he used (Neutrogena)? Elvis was neither the singer nor even
actor Sinatra was; and, if only by dint of longevity, Frank led a
far more interesting life. Yet in terms of cultural impact, there's
no comparison. That Time, in its ongoing effort to co-opt the
millennium, should have made an 11th-hour substitution of Sinatra
for Elvis on its list last month of the century's 20 most important
artists, is laughable. Maybe it's just that Time Warner (which
besides being behind three of the commemoratives, owns Sinatra's
old label, Reprise) figured it owes him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Another American icon, Michael Jordan, remains with us, happily,
and adorns the cover of  &UR; Fortune  &LR; (June 22), which asks, ``Exactly
how many billions has he pumped into the economy?'' It's a silly
question _ exactly how many? it's not as if we're talking rebounds
here _ but the answer arrived at, $10 billion since Jordan entered
the National Basketball Association in 1984, certainly has an
iconic ring to it ... Talk about icons: A full-bleed color head
shot of Lee Marvin stares out from the cover of  &UR; Sight and Sound
 &LR; (June). Bruce Willis? Sylvester Stallone? Eat your pecs out: This
was a movie tough guy. And talk about statistics: Packaged with
this issue is an engrossing pamphlet listing the 360 titles
selected by the British Film Institute (Sight and Sound's
publisher) as the best feature titles in history, accompanied by
much to-ing and fro-ing on hows and whys. The most amusing example
of the latter is Bertrand Tavernier's comment: ``Don't you think it
lacks taste to send to a film director a list of films in which
none of his are mentioned?'' ... And while pondering the
intersection of statistics, film, and taste, there's this week's
most intriguing social-science datum, from Gertrude Himmelfarb's
``Democratic Remedies for Democratic Disorders,'' in  &UR; The Public
Interest  &LR; (spring): ``Well over half of the public, but only 5
percent of leading filmmakers, say that they attend church at least
once a month.'' Maybe the figure would be higher for nonleading
filmmakers? And what about filmmakers whose publicists didn't
return phone calls? Some of these Hollywood people, getting them to
call back, it just takes (you'll forgive the expression) a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &UR; Agni  &LR; (spring) has a special section in memory of Ed Hogan, the
Somerville-based publisher who died last fall. Hogan's operation,
Zephyr Press, was best known for its landmark bilingual edition of
Anna Akhmatova's poetry. Only 47, he had long since distinguished
himself, in the words of Agni's editor, Askold Melnyczuk, as ``one
of the heroes of American small press publishing.'' Hogan was a man
of dreamy implacability, almost comically dedicated to literature.
The comedy had nothing to do with him, but rather with his slightly
ethereal presence in a milieu where getting tenure or making a
reputation often matters more than advancing the cause of letters.
It was in the advancement of that cause that Ed Hogan labored, and
he did so selflessly, unstintingly, and with rare success. Robert
Fitzgerald, another Irishman who worshiped at the altar of the
word, would have recognized him as a kindred soul. The celebrated
translator of Homer and Virgil, Fitzgerald was also a gifted
teacher, as Dana Gioia makes plain in his memoir, ``Learning From
Robert Fitzgerald,'' in the 50th anniversary issue of  &UR; The Hudson
Review  &LR; (Spring). It's hard not to cherish a professor whose
grading system consisted of four abbreviations _ NAAB, NB, NTB, PB
(``B'' meant bad) _ nor a writer who notes, as Gioia does, that
surprise is ``Harvard's rarest emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New Yorker  &LR; (June 15) profiles a dominatrix (ho-hum), with
text by Paul Theroux and photos by (who else?) Helmut Newton. Tina
Brown became editor there, what, six years ago? Clearly, she's
still trying to whip that magazine into shape. Next thing you know
we'll find out William Shawn had a mistress and lived a double
life. Where it will end, knows God.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
