<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, June 11:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions or reruns: &LR;   &UR; (212) 556-1927. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Gary E. McCardell (E-mail,
garymc(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   The evening supervisor is Pat Ryan (E-mail,
patryan(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   The late supervisor is Sam Weiss (E-mail,
saweis(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Technical problems: &LR;  Peter Trigg
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-ECON-II (Seoul, South Korea) _ The bottom line across most
of Asia, from the office suites of Japan to the peasant villages of
Indonesia, has always been that resources are allocated
disproportionately to men and boys. In times of bounty, there are
plenty of leftovers for women; in lean times, it is women who are
the leanest of all. Now, according to aid organizations and
scholars, as resources become more scarce in Asia they are being
shifted in favor of males. Second on two parts. By Nicholas D.
Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate Intelligence Committee
holds first open hearing into satellite export policies of Reagan,
Bush and Clinton administrations. Also, the House is likely to
announce details on its select committee into China allegations. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ The International Monetary Fund has told
the Yeltsin government it must fulfill a series of tough demands
before it can tap billions of dollars in extra assistance. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Paris) _ Trying to increase pressure on Serbia to
end military sweeps against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, officials
from the United States, Russia and four European countries agree
that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia was primarily
responsible for the violence. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FRANCE-STRIKE (Paris) _ Air France begins limping back
toward normal operations after striking pilots accepted a
seven-year pay freeze, ending a strike that had grounded most
flights since the beginning of the month. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ Developments in Nigeria in
the wake of the dictator's death. By Howard French.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-U.N. (United Nations) _ The U.N. General Assembly winds up
its special session on illegal drugs with declaration to sharply
reduce demand and do more to combat money laundering and phase out
opium and coca production. A look at what the session's 150
participating nations achieved and what they avoided tackling. By
Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   (See also DRUGS-ECONSCENE, below under Fiancial)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-EXCHANGE (Jerusalem) _ The Palestinian group Hezbollah
agrees to return the remains of an Israeli soldier in exchange for
the release of about 100 Hezbollah prisoners and bodies of slain
fighters. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-MARRIAGE (Washington) _ A vote is set on a marriage
penalty provision if the tobacco bill as an effort continues to
make tobacco legislation palatable to Senate Republicans. By David
E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation: monitoring Monica Lewinsky immunity talks; Harold
Ickes appears before the grand jury in Virginia. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   BANKRUPTCY-BILL (Washington) _ The House votes on legislation to
make it harder to go bankrupt and easier for credit card companies
to collect from deadbeats. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ The House debate on campaign
finance continues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DRAGGING-DEATH (Jasper, Texas) _ On the mood in Jasper
after three white men were charged with chaining a disabled black
man to the back of their pickup truck and dragging him to his death
along a dirt road.
</P>
<P>
   WIS-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS (Undated) _ In the first such state high
court ruling, Wisconsin's Supreme Court decides that publically
funding vouchers can be used for private, religious schools. Four
other state supreme courts are facing similiar questions.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-REACT (Salt Lake City) _ Reaction to the denomination's
statement on the role of wives from prominent Southern Baptists. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Flint, Mich.) _ The UAW strike against GM has spread,
idling 17,300 workers. And with another strike deadline approaching
Thursday that could shut another plant with 5,000 workers, the
strike threatens to shut down all of GM. The second plant in Flint
produces instrument panel equipment such as spedometers and other
plants could not operate without it. Meanwhile, GM has managed to
launch its latest truck because it took the parts it needed out of
the Flint plant before it went on strike.
</P>
<P>
   KAN-GRAIN-ELEVATOR (Haysville, Kan.) _ Rescuers trying to reach
four men trapped by a grain elevator explosion found two bodies
today, and their hopes of finding the other two alive were dimmed
by a new obstacle _ five to six tons of steel girders and concrete.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TB-GENE (Undated) _ Scientists have sequenced the genome of
one of the world's deadliest pathogens: tuberculosis. It turns out
that the 4,000-gene bacterium, notoriously resistant to
antibiotics, has a clever bag of tricks, including periodically
shifting its protein structure. The sequencing now allows
scientists to embark on an intensive, targeted search for new
therapeutic agents. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-BUDGET (New York) _ The Mayor is to veto the budget that the
City Council drafted and passed in defiance of him.
</P>
<P>
   NY-YANKEE-STADIUM (New York) _ City Council Speaker Peter F.
Vallone moves to put a referendum on Yankee stadium on the fall
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   DUNKIN-THIEF (New York) _ A serial donut thief who held up
several Dunkin' Donuts is finally nabbed. The suspect's name:
George Dunkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FED-GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Red Chairman Greenspan testifies
about the economy and monetary policy before the Joint Economic
Committee of Congress. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The market weighs Greenspan's comments and
the overnight decline of Asian stocks. At 2 p.m., the industrial
average was up 34 points. The long bond was up 27/32. By David
Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate:
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Indications grow that the Japanese
government is once again willing to let some ailing financial
institutions shut their doors. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ High-profile economists ranging from
Milton Friedman to Jagdish Bhagwati to Gavin Wright now assert that
the war on drugs has failed. But that is not so surprising. Most
economists these days are alert to the unintended consequences of
regulation, and in the case of drug policy, they do not have to
look far. By Peter Passell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America'' and William Safire's ``Essay'';
details to come.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving later:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:00 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1 will move at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be
listed by 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
