<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MAKEUP-BOS </SLUG>
  
 MAKEUP GURU TRISH McEVOY CAN RELIEVE SOME OF THAT INSECURITY 
(For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So I'm driving to meet this makeup guru Trish McEvoy at Neiman
Marcus last week and suddenly I'm not sure my foundation color
looks right. And in the rearview mirror, I'm noticing these ugly
black dots on my eyelids created by my still-wet mascara. Oh,
horrors.
</P>
<P>
   When I get there, her handlers take one look and decide I still
need work. ``Let's touch up your makeup before you meet Trish,''
they tell me. How embarrassing! And how outrageous: Do I really
need to wear McEvoy's makeup to meet her? When no one's looking, I
rub off some of my blush. Maybe it's too dark?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not alone: It turns out a lot of women are insecure about
their makeup. More than 250 signed up to have McEvoy look them over
at a promotional makeover fiesta. After all, she's a hot New York
makeup artist who sells her own makeup line at Neiman's and Saks
Fifth Avenue. Her celebrity clients include Sharon Stone, Brooke
Shields, and Marla Maples Trump.
</P>
<P>
   Her makeup shtick? No need to spend a lot of time digging in
your purse for your lipstick or your compact. Instead, buy one of
her ``dayplanners,'' a ring-binder-style makeup bag that holds
foundation, concealer, face powder, eye shadow, and blush all
pressed into plastic ``pages.'' ``Set up the bag chronologically,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Then learn the proper application technique. McEvoy's known for
her precision brushes. Just ask Joan Hathaway of Framingham, who's
arrived to meet McEvoy with six of the artist's brushes in hand to
apply concealer, blush, powder, and eye shadow. ``It's an important
investment,'' she says. Indeed, brushes range from $18 to $68. Eye
shadow averages $14, lipstick $16, blush $16 to $20, and powder
$23.
</P>
<P>
   To highlight your eyes, McEvoy says you can cover your whole
eyelid with face powder. Then feel for the bone above your eye
socket. Run the brush across the bone, first as a dotted line, then
in a windshield-wiper motion, blending up.
</P>
<P>
   Your mascara? ``Wiggle it on,'' she says, concentrating on the
base of the lashes first and then fanning it out in three different
directions. And eyeliner? Forget the sticks. Use your eye shadow
and a proper brush.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, McEvoy says, use makeup to fit your lifestyle.
She says, ``If you're dressing up, your face should be dressed up.
If you're exercising, just put on concealer and sunscreen.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and my look? After ``wiggling'' on new mascara, repowdering
my nose pretty heavily, and brushing my eye-socket bone a few
times, McEvoy says I look ``just fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   What's it like to be a model? What are agents really looking
for? How can a young girl break into such a competitive business?
</P>
<P>
   In the new book ``The Modeling Life,'' Donna Rubinstein, former
model editor for Seventeen magazine, and Jennifer Kingson Bloom, a
New York writer, answer these questions and more through interviews
with more than 50 working models, including Niki Taylor and Tyra
Banks.
</P>
<P>
   The book emphasizes the point that modeling is harder and less
glamorous than it looks. A lot of time is spent on tedious
``go-sees'' to get jobs (where a design house looks over a
potential model), getting fitted in clothes for future jobs, or
waiting for actual jobs to begin. Photo shoots can take days to
complete and sometimes start as early as 5 a.m. And after hours of
preparing hair and makeup for fashion shows, the events only last
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions can be rough too. The book quotes one model who
fainted after modeling ski clothes in California in 110-degree
heat. Another described being hosed down repeatedly with water
while modeling muddy clothes for a laundry detergent ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Banks complains that the endless traveling is grueling,
especially when she's alone in hotel rooms all over the world. Her
phone bill is enormous.
</P>
<P>
   The upside of modeling, of course, includes fame and fortune
(for a few), a boost in self-confidence and independence, and the
chance to travel extensively.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Taylor advises that parental support is one of the
most important aspects of a young woman's career in modeling. She
says, ``If you're under 18, let your parents guide you through the
beginning years. No one out there cares more about you than they
do. You will find a lot of hands reaching out for you, but remember
they are strangers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
