<HEADER>
A2865 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERSPECTIVE-SURREALIS     06-10 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSPECTIVE-SURREALISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN MAKING THEIR MARK IN SURREALISM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women weren't among Surrealism's founders. In the movement's
first manifesto, Andre Breton, the ``Pope of Surrealism,'' used a
dictionary-style definition _ ``SURREALISM, n., masc'' _ that
symbolically left women out of the picture. That was in 1924. By
1966, that picture hadn't much improved. The landmark ``Dada,
Surrealism and Their Heritage'' at the Museum of Modern Art that
year included just one work by a woman _ Meret Oppenheim's iconic
fur-lined teacup.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after Whitney Chadwick's 1985 ``Women Artists and
the Surrealist Movement,'' the first major study of the subject in
English, that the floodgates opened and women Surrealists started
to become the subject of college courses, books, and exhibitions.
By the mid-1990s, curators started assuming that the public
recognized at least vaguely that there were women in the movement,
and their shows became specialized. The Massachusetts College of
Art's 1995 ``Object Lessons: Feminine Dialogues With the Surreal''
explored the legacy the pioneers left to women artists of the
1990s. And, 30 years after that MOMA show, the Guggenheim Museum
responded with the pointedly titled ``Meret Oppenheim: Beyond the
Teacup.'' The battle, if not the war, seems to be won, and now
women Surrealists are blended into shows with their male
counterparts, as Leonora Carrington, Leonor Fini, and Dorothea
Tanning were with Ernst, de Chirico, Magritte, and other male
heavyweights in the recent ``Surrealist Prints'' show at Boston
College's McMullen Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Now MIT's List Visual Arts Center has come up with a major
contribution to the subject, with ``Mirror Images: Women,
Surrealism and Self-Representation,'' which is at the List through
June 28 and will then travel to the Miami Art Museum and the San
Francisco Museum of Modern Art. The show, whose theme is how women
depict women, was organized by the pioneering Chadwick, along with
List director Katy Kline and former List curator Helaine Posner.
</P>
<P>
   Breton and other early Surrealists defined the movement
narrowly. The List show takes a much broader view: It might have
been a surprise to some of the contemporary artists here to be
labeled ``Surrealists.'' The show presents three generations of
women artists, 22 of them, from North and Central America, Europe
and Japan, painters, sculptors, and photographers. That such a
diverse exhibition flows so smoothly is a great credit to the
curators, who have also edited and installed it wisely, so it's a
comfortable size for the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   It opens with a stunner, Dorothy Cross's 1993 ``Virgin Shroud,''
a sculpture that you read as a tall female figure, but only on the
basis of what ``she'' wears _ a long bridal train and veil, which
cover her completely. The train is conventional silk, but the veil
is cowhide, with the teats forming a Statue of Liberty-style crown
around the figure's head. She seems en route both to the marriage
altar and to slaughter, which, the work suggests, may be the same.
Cross, a Dublin-based artist, is one of the stars of the show. Her
1994 ``Stilettos'' also comments on physicality and femininity. A
pair of high heels covered with cow teats, the nipples teasing
stand-ins for toes, ``Stilettos'' also acts as gentle homage to
Oppenheim's fur cup.
</P>
<P>
   You think of contemporary artists using odd materials, like
Cross and her cowhide. But one of the pleasures of the List show is
discovering that artists of an earlier generation were sometimes
prophetic. In ``The Flutist,'' for instance, a 1955 painting by
Spanish artist Remedios Varo, the protagonist has a face made of
inlaid mother of pearl, which gives off a sickly iridescent gleam.
</P>
<P>
   If a generalization can be made about the List show's earlier
works, it's that they're smaller in scale and more delicate in
technique than what came later. French photographer Claude Cahun's
tiny, exquisite black and white photographs from the 1920s and '30s
show the artist in various guises and poses, stuffed into an
armoire or being swallowed by aggressive vegetation. Cahun, born
Lucie Schwob, liked to construct different identities for herself.
In scale and style her works are the antithesis of the contemporary
photographs of Cindy Sherman. But in their mutual let's-pretend
intent, work by the two is similar.
</P>
<P>
   The List show puts Sherman, an artist in danger of overexposure,
into a fascinating, fresh context. Ditto for Ana Mendieta, whose
color photographs of traces left by bodies in sand or on stone are
kin to Cahun's work and even closer to that of Mendieta's
contemporary, Francesca Woodman, whose haunting little black and
white photos depict the figure in retreat. Woodman's 1975-76
photograph ``Nude in Cupboard'' bears an eerie resemblance to
Cahun's armoire self-portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Photography is the strongest medium in the show, perhaps because
people still regard it as the art form that represents the world
the most honestly. It's titillating when photography breaches that
trust, to create surreal, impossible, yet seemingly ``true''
situations. Among the most powerful of the show's photographers is
Marta Maria Perez Bravo, who offers staged shots of a woman bound
to oars, like a slave, or lifting her shirt to reveal bare breasts
protected by ``armor'' of dozens of tiny spikes, or a pregnant
woman holding a kitchen knife in front of her swollen belly. This
last is particularly provocative: Is she protecting her unborn
baby, or about to stab it?
</P>
<P>
   The painting in the show is also strong, and makes for lucid
comparisons. One corner features paintings from the 1930s until
now, by two artists of the first generation, Leonora Carrington and
Frida Kahlo, and one from the third, Lindee Climo, who all depict
themselves or other women in the company of animals. Carrington,
born in 1917, is still alive, working and making willfully weird
paintings, e.g., her 1997 ``Aardvark Groomed by Widows.'' Climo is
one of the lesser-knowns in a show that gracefully combines
household names with artists who are obscure. Her 1996 painting
``Pig With Moly Plant'' shows the partly draped lower half of a
goddess-type straddling the back of a pig, the picture painted in
the meticulous realist style so beloved by Surrealists both male
and female.
</P>
<P>
   Sculpture isn't the show's forte. Three-dimensional works by
Louise Bourgeois, Kiki Smith, and Rona Pondick don't show those
artists at their best. Unlike the works in the exhibition by these
usual suspects, those of the young Mexican artist Paula Santiago
are riveting. Santiago makes doll-sized garments of wax, rice
paper, blood, and hair, all suspended under glass. These macabre
garments are cousins to the bizarre little bee or berry-covered
dresses of Irish artist Alice Maher, which were featured in the
McMullen's show of Irish women artists last fall. They're also kin
to a photograph in the List show, the 1994 ``Dress of Peas,'' by
the contemporary Japanese artist Michiko Kon. ``Dress of Peas'' is
exactly that, a sweet little girl's dress covered in pea pods.
</P>
<P>
   No fur teacup in the show. But among the trio of Oppenheim works
is ``Pair of Gloves,'' which she made in 1985, the year she died.
It's an elegant and economical summation of some of the strategies
of Surrealism, especially its jarring juxtapositions and
transformation of the mundane. On an otherwise ordinary pair of
gray suede gloves, Oppenheim has printed and stitched the veins of
the hands. External protection, the role of the gloves, has been
thwarted: The hands themselves have been turned inside out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
