A2875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-10 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN MONEY STILL BUY A CONGRESSIONAL SEAT IN MASSACHUSETTS?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most astonishing development in Massachusetts politics so
far this election cycle is the decision by a little-known venture
capitalist, Chris Gabrieli, to write the first of what may total
several million in checks to win the open 8th Congressional
District seat.
</P>
<P>
   Not since a hard-eyed rogue capitalist named Kennedy decided 52
years ago to install his son in the Boston-Cambridge seat vacated
by James Michael Curley has a monied outsider had a crack at the
storied seat of Curley, JFK, Tip O'Neill, and, till January, Joe
Kennedy, grandson of Old Joe.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking a lot of politics here. Curley, the Purple
Shamrock, first ran for Boston's Common Council 100 years ago.
Elected mayor in '45, Curley gave up his seat, and JFK won the
free-for-all primary that began the dynasty. Young Joe K won a
similar crowded primary 12 years ago to keep the seat in the
family, so to speak. There's another Oklahoma Land Rush this
September.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielli is opening the vault. From a townhouse on Louisburg
Square, Boston's toniest address, he's hiring far and wide, cutting
a swath through the ranks of consultants, pollsters, and
henchpersons that is breathtaking in scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's paying top dollar!'' marvels a Massachusetts pol
who's already in Congress. When JFK ran, Old Joe's bankroll proved
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   As Michael Bell, a Maine professor, put it in his University of
Wyoming master's thesis on the 8th: ``Perhaps the most important
contribution that Ambassador (Joseph) Kennedy made was providing
unlimited financial resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielli stunned the rest of the 12-candidate 8th district
field with a preemptive opening television ad buy that cost him
some-thing like $315,000 for the initial week's salvo alone. And as
word spreads that he plans to continue spending like that on tube
time to establish his image, the local political world is slowly
coming to grips with the likelihood that a little-known outsider
with effectively unlimited funds is changing the game.
</P>
<P>
   This is like India developing its own A-bomb. An amateur with
assets can barge into the game and demand a seat at the table with
the pros. In the shark-infested waters of Boston politics,
astonishment gives way to consternation. We've seen wealthy
amateurs try pay-to-play before, and lose. Business successes like
Ray Shamie and Mitt Romney found out that knocking Teddy Kennedy
off was an expensive and ultimately losing proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielli's firepower attracts attention. He's collecting
supporters of the caliber of John Cullinane, computer
marketer-philanthropist; banker-turned-businessman Ron Homer; and
Dr. Elaine Kamarck of Harvard's Kennedy School.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielli is said to be close to Vice President Al Gore and a
champion of the Democratic Leadership Council's moderate,
pro-business approach. Gabrielli has embraced the charter school
concept and seems to have leapfrogged the tired, old
``are-you-with-the-teachers-unions-or-against-them?'' litmus test
that hems in timid regular Democrats. Unlike a lot of the nouveau
riche tossed up on the beach by the technology boom and the stock
market run-up, Gabrielli is a policy wonk with an abiding interest
in the arcana of government policy.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidates tend to run as traditional liberals, the
let's-do-more-for-the-poor formula. But Gabrielli, who has
bankrolled the MassInc. thinktank, talks about underlying market
forces. Gabrielli's wife, Hilary, served as legal counsel to the
Massachusetts Legislature's taxation committee when Jim Brett, now
head of the New England Council, was its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Brett says the Gabriellis are a brilliant couple interested in
public policy. And the 8th District gets more federal research and
development grants than any other in the country (Harvard, MIT, the
hospitals, etc.). Without taking sides in the race where he knows
everybody running, Brett says Jim Gabrielli ``would make an
absolutely brilliant congressman'' because of his background. But
it is Gabrielli's ability to write a check that makes him a serious
player. Ray Flynn, the former Boston mayor, is the current
favorite. As mayor and Vatican ambassador, Flynn's been on local TV
more than Gabrielli can ever catch up with.
</P>
<P>
   There are two others whose campaign budgets will go over $1
million each, City Councilor Tom Keane and John O'Connor. The
traditional candidates, such as Somerville Mayor Mike Capuano, an
incumbent who can probably put more workers on the street than
anyone else at this juncture, may find themselves outgunned in a TV
war where ground troops are overwhelmed by the media air attack
overhead. Still, money could not elect California gubernatorial
candidate Al Checchi, a Somerville native who dropped $40 million
on his primary loss. He pancacked bigtime. Ross Perot and Steve
Forbes found a personal fortune only gets you a seat at the table,
not a winning hand.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielli is articulate and intelligent, well-tailored and
obviously flush with cash. But it's one thing to understand capital
flow, leveraged buyouts, and derivative trading. It's quite another
to deal with mud-pie flow, leveraged rabbit-punches, and derisive
attacks from highly motivated rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Businessmen always underestimate the pace, fury, and randomness
of politics. Not till they get those first few
creme-pie-in-the-kisser assaults can we gauge their ability to
recover, counter, and move on in the flow of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And his $300K opening bid ensures return fire from his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
