A2877 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-10 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 McDONALDS' OWNER DEFIES FOUNDER KROC TO MERCHANDISE McVEGGIE 
(For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Did somebody say ... McVeggie?
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence of the decline of Western civilization has
surfaced in Greenwich Village, where four McDonald's outlets are
experimenting with a new menu item _ a vegetarian hamburger. Veggie
perestroika in the Evil Empire? I had to find out.
</P>
<P>
   First, some context. McDonald's has been having problems
peddling its wares in the United States. Same-store sales have been
declining, and heavily hyped new products, like the low-fat McLean
burger and the new so-called Deluxe products (Arch Deluxe and the
discontinued Fish Fillet Deluxe) have fared poorly. Last summer's
``Campaign 55,'' featuring a 55-cent Quarter Pounder, bombed. The
company's domestic operations are being handed over to some genius
from ... Pizza Hut.
</P>
<P>
   Routinely vilified by left-wing Enviro-Greens for a) despoiling
the rain forest; b) littering the world's sidewalks; c) torturing
and killing millions of cows; or d) all of the above, McDonald's
has a longstanding public relations problem with people whose idea
of a tasty meal isn't 100 percent all beef. Substitute the word
``vegetarian'' for ``nonconformist'' in the following quote from
McDonald's entrepreneur Ray Kroc, and draw your own conclusions:
``We cannot trust some people who are nonconformists,'' Kroc once
said. ``We will make conformists out of them in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps vice versa. Jim Lewis, who owns and operates nine
Manhattan McD's, has launched McVeggie in an experimental marketing
campaign being closely monitored by the higher-ups in Oak Brook,
Ill. Lewis says McVeggie is a natural fit with the vestigial
countercultural elements in the Village. The day he introduced the
new burger, a group from People for Ethical Treatment of Animals
even staged an impromptu pro-McDonald's demonstration outside his
flagship store. ``There were these half-naked people dressed as
vegetables dancing on the sidewalk,'' Lewis says. ``It was quite a
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   How's the test going? Lewis says sales lag behind traditional
hamburger products, but are above expectations. I visited three
stores at lunch time, and saw a modest number of McVeggie users.
Because the product isn't being advertised, most customers were
trying the veg-burger on a whim. Travel agent Linda Vieira
pronounced the McV a reasonable hamburger substitute, allowing that
McDonald's burgers ``aren't all that great anyway.'' Next to her,
her 10-year-old and a friend munched contentedly on a Double
Quarter Pounder and Crispy Chicken sandwich, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda During, a high school senior, waxed more enthusiastic.
She had learned of the McV from a vegetarian Web site, and subwayed
down from 65th Street to see what all the fuss was about. During, a
vegetarian, plans to tell all her friends to gobble McVeggies ``so
they'll keep it on the menu.'' How does it taste? ``It's pretty
good, although the ones in London are better,'' she opined. (McD's
has successfully sold vegetarian burgers in Europe for years.)
</P>
<P>
   Ah, taste. Even Lewis concedes that taste is not the long suit
of his custom-made, soybean-based, Archer Daniels Midland ``meat
analog'' patty. Although it has more fat than the ordinary burger,
it is curiously tasteless. Lewis explains that the patty was
engineered to duplicate the tactile sensation of eating a burger,
rather than to mimic the taste. Call it the inflatable blow-up doll
of the hamburger world.
</P>
<P>
   Whither the McVeggie? At last month's annual meeting, McDonald's
Big Cheese Michael Quinlan claimed ``we are open to the idea'' of
selling a veggie burger nationwide. But McDonald's is
simultaneously testing other menu ideas, like pizza or the oversize
MBX (McDonald's Big Extra); the company is notoriously cautious
about rolling out major menu additions nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the company introduced a product with minimal
test-marketing, in response to pressure from nutrition-minded
critics, was in 1991. That was the doomed, seaweed-enhanced McLean,
discontinued in 1996. McVeggies ads on Super Bowl Sunday? Not in
this millennium, methinks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(AT)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
