<HEADLINE>
49ERS ASK COURT TO BLOCK LATEST ANTI-STADIUM EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco 49ers don't want a replay of
last year's close and controversy-plagued vote on a new football
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed Tuesday in San Francisco Superior Court, the
National Football League team asked a judge to stop anti-stadium
activists from putting the issue of a new municipal stadium on the
ballot for the second time in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-stadium activists say the football team is attempting
to trample their free-speech rights and block them from exercising
their right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL team contends that the anti-stadium Committee to
Stop the Giveaway has committed multiple violations of state
election law by ``misrepresenting the facts'' of the 1997 stadium
campaign in an anti-stadium petition now being circulated.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the activists claim the 49ers won their
razor-thin victory in the 1997 stadium vote through voter fraud.
The lawsuit denies the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Team lawyer James Parrinello said the 49ers wanted the court to
order the city not to put the new stadium measure on the November
ballot because of the legal flaws he said the petitions contained.
Parrinello said the 49ers were fed up with the anti-stadium
activists, who mounted a noisy campaign against last year's stadium
measure and have complained since then that the measure's narrow
victory was tainted by voter fraud.
</P>
<P>
   He said the petition now being distributed contains allegations
of massive voter fraud that he said had been ruled unfounded by
investigations by the California secretary of state's office and by
a judge who rejected the activists' own lawsuit challenging the
stadium vote.
</P>
<P>
   Parrinello said state election law prohibits the use of
``campaign rhetoric'' in the language of an electoral petition, but
the petition being distributed is packed with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we're at the point where we think it's time that
people who have been yelling about violations of the law but have
not been able to prove any should be held to account,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But committee leader Barbara Meskunas said the 49ers' lawsuit
would trample the First Amendment rights of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What strange country do they think this is?'' Meskunas said.
``We're still entitled to circulate petitions in the state of
California, last time I checked.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bell, who represented anti-stadium activists in their
unsuccessful voter-fraud lawsuit last year, said the city Elections
Department had approved the language in the petition.
</P>
<P>
   The Committee to Stop the Giveaway is small and under-financed.
But in the bitter 1997 referendum over whether San Francisco should
spend up to $100 million on a new football stadium, the committee
gave the 49ers and Mayor Willie Brown all they could handle.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the stadium measure passed _ by 1,500 votes.
</P>
<P>
   After the votes were cast, the committee joined with a
Washington, D.C.-based group called the Voting Integrity Project
and sued to overturn the election, contending voter fraud.
</P>
<P>
   That challenge was thrown out of court in January.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that, the committee began preparing a new initiative
to put the stadium back on the ballot. Activist Doug Comstock
contended it was appropriate to reconsider the stadium measure
because cost estimates on the project had soared since the vote.
</P>
<P>
   He also charged that proponents didn't tell voters that a
shopping mall being built to accompany the stadium would likely
``wipe out'' the small state park at Candlestick Point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
