<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-REBELS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN TOWN UNEASY AFTER REBELS SHOT DEAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL CHARCO, Mexico _ As a small unit of army troops manned the
low mountaintop above them, Mixtec Indian residents of this
adobe-and-tile village picked through the shreds of their
schoolhouse and murmured about the recent killings of leftist
rebels here.
</P>
<P>
   Fingers poked at holes punched into classroom walls by army
bullets. Toes kicked at broken pottery, bits of clothing and
tattered sleeping mats strewn across the floor. Eyes stared at the
dried blood that marked the spots where 11 people fell dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government says all those killed in the shootout
with the army were members of the leftist Popular Revolutionary
Army, known by its Spanish initials EPR.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the people who died here were peasants,'' said Francisco
Ticurcio, shaking his head and kicking at schoolbooks as he watched
his neighbors pick through the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's incident marked the worst military defeat to date for
the EPR and serves as a reminder that the shadowy and largely
ignored rebel group has continued to recruit followers in the
impoverished mountains of rural southern Mexico since first
appearing two years ago. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; According to El Charco residents, a 15-member unit of the EPR
trudged into their mountain village about 75 miles southeast of
Acapulco on Saturday morning to try to persuade the villagers to
support their cause. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Before dawn Sunday, an army patrol that had slipped into town
on foot opened fire on the rebels, as the guerrillas and dozens of
their supporters slept in El Charco's schoolrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government says that all those killed were adult men
in guerrilla uniforms. According to the government, five people
were injured, and 21 were taken prisoner. There were no army
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Additional army troops rode into El Charco in armored vehicles
or arrived by helicopter once the shooting started. According to
villagers, the trapped rebels fought for nearly three hours.
</P>
<P>
   The government says its troops were patrolling in search of
narcotics when they stumbled upon the guerrillas. But villagers say
that soldiers have never moved through these mountains at night.
They believe the troops were tipped off by an informer.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents of the villages surrounding El Charco fled to
Ayutla de los Libres and other towns following Sunday's shootings.
Though most soldiers had been pulled out of the area soon after the
attack, many of those villages remained deserted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The EPR first appeared in June 1996 at a rally marking the
anniversary of a massacre in which state police killed 17 unarmed
farmers about 90 miles up the coast from El Charco.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1996, the group stunned Mexico by attacking police
stations and other government offices in seven southern states.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the group has gained little notice in Mexico or
outside the country despite occasional clashes with government
troops and police here in Guerrero state and in neighboring Oaxaca
state. Dozens of suspected guerrillas have been arrested. Others
have ``disappeared'' in government custody, EPR rebels claim.
</P>
<P>
   The EPR's movement has been largely overshadowed by the mostly
Maya insurgency in southernmost Chiapas state. The Maya insurgents,
known as Zapatistas, seized the imaginations of many Mexicans and
foreigners when they staged a brief but bloody rebellion in January
1994. Although there have been few armed clashes since then, the
Zapatistas continue to define for many what armed opposition in
Mexico means today.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, officials here say, the EPR has been organizing
in many parts of Guerrero state, where opposition to the government
seems almost as old as the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The EPR's goals, however, remain somewhat undefined. Fliers
distributed at meetings with villagers in the Guerrero mountains
call for more democracy, a fairer distribution of wealth and more
social justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't certain they existed until they started making
appearances around here last year,'' said Rafael Sandoval, a young
assistant district attorney in Ayutla, a market town and county
seat about 10 miles down the mountain from El Charco.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have been trying to persuade villagers to support
them, said Sandoval, who has helped investigate guerrilla sightings
in the area since last year.
</P>
<P>
   El Charco residents said EPR units had been visiting the village
at least once a month since last August.
</P>
<P>
   As they had in past visits, the rebels took shelter at the grade
school, a small cluster of new concrete buildings flanking a
basketball court, residents said.
</P>
<P>
   And, as in the past, scores of people from surrounding villages
walked to El Charco to hear what the rebels had to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They invited the people to join them,'' said Odilon Romero,
the left-leaning mayor of Ayutla. ``They declared themselves
against all the injustices that exist here.''
</P>
<P>
   At the assembly last Saturday, many of the guerrillas spoke the
local dialect of the Mixtec language. According to villagers, they
encouraged people to put a halt to the robberies of passenger buses
and supply trucks that take place on the roads cutting through the
mountains here. They urged people to organize and to press the
government for clean drinking water, better schools and other
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spoke against all the crime and the robberies, telling
parents to discourage their children from taking part in it,'' said
Florencio Morales, who lives in a village across the narrow valley
from El Charco. ``They said they wanted people to prepare in order
to help themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Before classes ended Friday, El Charco's children had been
learning to spell in the schoolhouse where the rebels were killed.
On Monday, rows of words were still written on the blackboard in a
teacher's neat hand.
</P>
<P>
   Four large areas of dried blood stained the concrete floor to
the right side of the blackboard, suggesting that some of those
killed had died where they slept.
</P>
<P>
   A large blood stain covered the wall and floor by the door,
seemingly outlining the place where someone had sat down and died.
A single bullet hole pierced the wall at about the level of a
sitting person's head. Bloody handprints marked the wall on both
sides of the bullet hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were demanding rights,'' Pedro Morales, who was raised in
the area, said of the dead rebels. ``And they died for demanding
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
