<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS WORK TO MAKE SPIRITUAL VALUES PART OF THEIR PROFESSION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The conversations heard inside the fourth-floor library at
Suffolk University Law School are typically about torts,
intellectual property, and the art of writing legal briefs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But on this breezy spring afternoon the conversation was
about subjects that seemingly have little to do with law _
liberation theology, the story of Adam and Eve, the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   The point the speakers _ all attorneys _ were trying to make is
that religious and spiritual themes have a vital role in a
profession sufferring from poor morale and a dismal public image.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by this belief, about three dozen attorneys and law
students gathered last week for a conference entitled, ``Beyond the
Code of Professional Responsibility: Can Spiritual Values Be Our
Compass?''
</P>
<P>
   Religious and spiritual values, the lawyers argued, give meaning
to every aspect of personal and professional life, even in such a
seemingly secular vocation as law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a historic moment in the life of our local
bar,'' said David Hall, dean of Northeastern University's law
school and one of the conference's six speakers. ``To have lawyers
come together to explicitly discuss issues of spirituality is
really a significant event.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that many attorneys, according to several surveys, say
they are unhappy and unfulfilled makes the notion of a turn to
spirituality more understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ``As lawyers doing our job we should be able to be emotionally
and spiritually fulfilled,'' said Michael J. Bohnen, a corporate
attorney and a leader in the local Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   Rita S. Pollak, a divorce attorney, said it took her many years
to realize the connections between her work and her spiritual life.
``As I came to understand my own traditions more deeply,
particularly mystical Judaism, I began to see the links,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Pollak says, she thinks ``long and hard'' about the
language she uses in court or when writing a brief because whomever
she is talking about, criminal or not, is another ``divine being.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl L. Conner, a professor at Suffolk Law School and an
organizer of the conference, said she has leaned on her Tibetan
Buddhist practices to help her deal with recalcitrant clients,
difficult judges, and belligerent opposing attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Patience, Conner noted, is an important virtue in Tibetan
Buddhism and can come in handy in the heat of a court battle. As
the director of the law school's clinical internship program,
Conner shares her Buddhist learning with her students.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Porter, a trial attorney with an interest in
mediation, spoke of the ``divine vocation of the law'' and of the
need to transform lawyers from ``warriors'' seeking to win at any
cost to ``healers'' trying to mend broken relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great spiritual tradition of apology, forgiveness, and
reconciliation is not something you hear talked about at Harvard,''
Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowleged that trying to inject spiritual values into the
legal profession is a tall order. ``I wasn't born yesterday and I'm
a realist, but I think it is worth pursuing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paraphrasing a book written by an attorney, Hall said there are
``no particularly holy works. Everything we do is secular. Our work
becomes holy when it is done in recognition of our service to a
higher purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaped by his African-American Christian tradition and
influenced by liberation theology and its emphasis on religion as a
vehicle to alleviate oppression, Hall said that at Northeastern he
tries to promote the idea of lawyering as a calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get so caught up in the details of what we do, and not
in the people and the possible good to others in society, then we
will forever linger in the dungeon of professional despair and
disdain,'' Hall wrote in a paper prepared for the conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
