<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (212)
556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories from our partners:
Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-POUNDSBURY (Undated) _ It was not the kind of headline
that Charles, the Prince of Wales, was used to in the British
press. ``The Prince Has Got It Right,'' trumpeted The Independent.
What prompted this hearty endorsement of someone the British seldom
tire of tweaking was Poundbury, the new community springing to
daring old life. The planned town perfectly embodies the outspoken
heir to the throne's views of modern architecture as owing a debt
to the past. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   HARLEM-SHOWHOUSE (New York) _ As every voyeur clutching a ticket
and a dream knows, designer show houses are typically celebrations
of the perfection that money can buy. So it came as a pleasant
surprise last Friday night when the Harlem United Show House opened
its wood-and-glass front door to a sound track of furious hammer
blows and furniture being dragged into position. Fastidious show
house devotees might have deemed the evening's gala party a bit
premature, but the 24 designers, their friends, clients and
well-wishers gamely put a cheery spin on the chaos around them. By
Mitchell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   HILTON-SLEEP-TIGHT (New York) _ At the Waldorf-Astoria and other
hotels in the Hilton group, special Sleep-Tight rooms have been
designed in consultation with the National Sleep Foundation. The
special Sleep Tight rooms include apparatus for soothing the
troubled soul (and diminishing that outside noise). Along with a
turbo spa (for a relaxing soak) and blackout curtains (to make it
perpetual midnight), the special rooms offer a clock that simulates
dawn, sound effects like the crash and murmur of streams and waves
and white noise or a gentle heartbeat that seeps from the Sound
Soother. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   FOUNTAIN-DESIGN (New York) _ Moths are attracted to flames;
humans to fountains. Whether they are towering plumes ingeniously
engineered to rise Excalibur-like from a becalmed lake or
monumental gushes churning through the body of some mythological
sea creature, fountains are irresistible messengers. Hope, renewal,
power, melancholy, joy _ almost any ambition or emotion, it seems,
can be served by the clever manipulation of hydraulics. At least,
that's the impression made by the exhibition ``Fountains: Splash
and Spectacle'' that opened on Tuesday at the Cooper-Hewitt
National Design Museum in Manhattan. By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   TROMPE-L`OEIL-DESIGN (Undated) _ A smile. That's the only
possible response to trompe l'oeil designs and photo images on
shower curtains, bed sheets, even end tables. The designs are
contemporary sisters to those by Piero Fornasetti, the Milanese
decorative master of trompe l'oeil. Renewed interest in his work
(which peaked in the 1950s) was apparent at the May 16th auction of
203 of his designs at Christie's in Los Angeles; the bureaus,
dinner plates, magazine racks and hand-painted bathroom fixtures
sold for record breaking prices _ sometimes five times the auction
house's estimates. Fornasetti transferred engravings that tricked
the eye and tickled the imagination. By Marianne Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BEDFORD-STREET (New York) _ Despite Lawrence Selman having,
as he puts it, ``one of the last of the Brooklyn accents,'' his one
wish in life is to live and die at 106 Bedford Street, in Greenwich
Village in New York. Selman lives there now, in a one-room
apartment with his dog, Happy, and his cats, Suzy and Lucky. He has
lived there for 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ The column. By Dora Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lupinski.
