<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NODATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS SPURN LUSTFUL TEMPTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Faith Shepherd went to her prom with 29 of her
friends. Each one of the Mormon teens had a date, but none went as
a mushy, romantic, kissy-face (begin ital) couple. (endital).
</P>
<P>
   Lubna Ahmad, a 13-year-old Muslim, is more interested in music
and math than boys. She plans to stay focused on classes at Corona
del Sol High School in Tempe, and when she's ready to marry, she
will follow Muslim guidelines in choosing a husband, a match based
on common values, beliefs and goals, not on superficial attraction,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Harris, 23, will kiss his fiancee for the first time on
Oct. 3 _ after they are pronounced husband and wife. Harris is a
Christian and national speaker on sexual purity before marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In a culture where magazine headlines preach ``Lust Lessons:
Teach Them Tonight'' and television shows depict prom-night sex as
the norm, these and other young adults are following their
religious convictions and putting off serious romantic
relationships until marriage is in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Their beliefs are grounded in the scriptures of their faiths:
Protestant, Catholic, Muslim, Mormon, Jewish and Hindu. Sexual
purity before marriage is the standard. The teens set boundaries in
an effort to avert temptation and live up to the standard.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't stay-at-home wallflower types. Many don't limit
themselves to double dating or family activities, but they won't be
alone in a car at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   They appreciate good looks, but they are more impressed with
good character. They may not marry the first person they seriously
date, but they don't want to pursue romance and its entanglements
until they are mature enough to make a commitment.
</P>
<P>
   They're not prudes, Shepherd, 17, said and blushingly admitted
that she kissed a boy once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday I'll do it again,'' said the senior at Westwood High
School in Mesa. ``Now isn't the time to find my husband. It's a
time to find the qualities I want in a husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Phil Baniewicz, executive director of Life Teen Inc., which
involves about 50,000 Catholic teenagers in the United States, ``As
much as we see the teens being sexually involved, we're seeing the
other extreme, the positive extreme: Young people who are saying,
`I'm going to hold strong in my faith, and I'm not going to
compromise my values.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They tend to do group dating. You didn't see that a whole lot
five or 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Harris spoke to more than 14,000 teenagers and their
parents at his New Attitude conferences in Phoenix and other U.S.
cities. Since he was 17, he has talked to about 30,000 people about
modern-day courtship. He has also written a book, ``I Kissed Dating
Goodbye,'' in which he lays out guidelines for dating.
</P>
<P>
   His stages for developing a godly romantic relationship are
casual friendship, deeper friendship, purposeful intimacy with
integrity and engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Harris declared his intentions for marriage while he and his
fiancee were in the deeper-friendship phase. This, he said, created
less pressure than dating casually because the relationship was
more purposeful and better defined.
</P>
<P>
   The couple also are committed to wait for that first kiss, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would serve both of us, having a pure relationship and not
to be stoking the fires unnecessarily,'' Harris said. ``We are very
passionate about each other and very anxious to be able to
experience that aspect of our relationship, but it's neat working
to learn to communicate clearly. We can't fall back on the physical
side of our relationship to smooth things over.''
</P>
<P>
   The first printing of ``I Kissed Dating Goodbye'' totaled
170,000 copies, of which more than 120,000 have been sold. Harris,
a pastoral intern at Covenant Life Church in Gaithersburg, Md., has
found Christians and non-Christians who appreciate his message, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how many teenagers out there are not into the
dating scene, and they feel something is completely wrong with
them,'' he said. ``It's like a weight is lifted off their
shoulders. There are others who are really into (dating), and the
book is kind of an annoyance.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg and Joneen Ross of Gilbert found the dating scene awkward
when they were young and wanted a better experience for their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do courtship,'' said Joneen, a homemaker. ``On
looking back on our dating experiences, there was nothing really
positive about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew up in Christian households, and we were taught to
maintain moral purity, but there were no tools to work with,'' said
Greg, a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Ross, 18, thinks that courtship is a good idea, too. He
wants to treat girls as sisters in Christ and not pursue a serious
relationship until he's ready for marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It frees you up,'' Matthew said. ``It just comes back to
basically trusting God.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Mullan, a varsity cheerleader and secretary of the
student body at Dobson High School, finds that the best dates are
those who share her religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could go to church with them and you had this
understanding of belief, and you knew you weren't going to do
things that would compromise your faith,'' said Mullan, who attends
St. Timothy Catholic Community Center in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Rishi Popat wants to marry someone who shares his Hindu beliefs
and Indian traditions. At North High School in Phoenix, two girls
fit that description. At Trinity College in Connecticut, where he
will study to be a neurosurgeon in the fall, he hopes more girls
will be in that category.
</P>
<P>
   In his parents' era, he said, most Hindu marriages were
arranged. He doesn't expect an arranged marriage, but long-term
compatibility will be considered before any serious relationship
begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indian teens like myself date if there is the right chemistry
and not just superficial qualities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other teens see marriage as a distant future.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Farnsworth, 17, says group dating allows him to get to
know girls while doing away with date anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are with groups and with your friends, you're more up
to talking and having fun,'' said the Westwood High senior, who in
about two years will go on a mission for the Church of Jesus Christ
of Latter-day Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go against the standards, you're the oddball. No one
will even try anything because everyone will think they're silly.
We all push each other along and give each other the strength and
the support because we all want the same thing. It's not just the
church's decision or my parents' decision. It's my decision.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kelly Ettenborough can be reached at 602-444-4877 or at
kelly.ettenborough(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
