<SLUG> BC-NODATE-SIDE1-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE FOLLOWED TRADITIONAL MUSLIM RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Love came after marriage for Mubeen and Farah Khan,
young professionals who live in Mesa, Ariz., and followed
traditional Muslim practices in arranging their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   She had rejected two potential suitors before they exchanged
pictures and personal resumes at the suggestion of his mother's
friend. The pair found the information interesting, and the
families, who lived in different states, arranged to meet in
October 1994.
</P>
<P>
   That first meeting was awkward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous, especially when you are meeting under these
circumstances,'' Mubeen Khan said. ``It isn't a meeting to say,
`Hey, do you want to go on a date?' It's meeting with the
intentions of `am I going to marry this person?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The families clicked, and Mubeen and Farah followed up with
phone conversations. They requested a second meeting of the
families at Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family was teasing her that I had left,'' Mubeen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in with roses and a box of chocolates,'' Frah said.
``It was like a done deal, chocolate and flowers, please.''
</P>
<P>
   As they told the story of their courtship and marriage, they
laughed and finished each other's sentences.
</P>
<P>
   There were more phone calls and more family meetings. On April
15, 1995, they were engaged. They wooed each other with letters and
flowers but still did not spend time together alone. They didn't
even see each other for a few months before the Sept. 3, 1995,
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were feelings that existed between us before we got
married, but to call that love after months and after just getting
to know each other?'' Mubeen Khan said. ``After marriage, that's
when I think we really felt responsible toward each other. We felt
the commitment was there and our love for each other started
growing.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes faith in their religion, they said, to believe
everything will work out. And, their marriage is wonderful, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love as far as physical attraction, everyone changes looks
over time,'' Mubeen Khan said. ``To seek out the person within is
the most important thing. That's something that Islam encourages.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, he's a 25-year-old marketing representative at
Caterpillar Financial and MBA student. She's a 26-year-old staffing
manager at Robert Half International. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
