<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATS-ACCESSORIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO, WHAT'S A CLOCHE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Mom and Grandma used to know all about hats. They
wore them to church, luncheons, bridge parties and even swanky
cocktail soirees. And they probably had a favorite milliner (the
fancy, Italian word for hat designer).
</P>
<P>
   Although American women no longer feel obligated to wear a hat,
they're becoming the accessory of the fall fashion season. So we
knew you'd want to brush up on your hat terminology.
</P>
<P>
   BERET _ Actually, this pancake-flat hat that's supposed to be
pulled down over the forehead is a variation on the tam-o'-shanter
cap, with a small pompon in the center of the crown. It's worn by
both men and women in Europe, but in L.A. it's a girl thing, worn
by the likes of Barbra Streisand, Rosie O'Donnell and Cher.
</P>
<P>
   BOATER _ Originally intended for men on the boating scene, this
straw hat with a flat brim and crown is a springtime fave with
women. You'll know it by its sporty striped grosgrain ribbon band,
usually worn with navy and white. A good choice for a first hat.
</P>
<P>
   BOWLER _ A hard, felt hat with a domed crown and narrow brim
that was originally designed for businessmen and horsemen (when
they rode English-style) and now favored by both sexes.
</P>
<P>
   BRETON _ Ah, the hat of choice for first ladies and wanna-bes.
It's an off-the-face felt hat (sometimes worn on the back of the
head) with a slightly rolled back brim, usually worn with ladylike
suits. It can be plain or embellished with flowers and ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   BUBBLE BERET _ Think of a beret that has been stuffed with
tissue paper. Wear it at a slight tilt.
</P>
<P>
   CLOCHE _ Remember the sassy little hat Nancy Drew wore in the
original books? This popular style of the '20s and '30s fits snugly
on the head and features a deep crown with no brim. It usually has
a bow or accent.
</P>
<P>
   DERBY _ The perfect felt hat for jeans and a leather jacket or a
pinstriped pant suit, with its curvy little brim and rounded crown.
It's usually brown or black with a grosgrain ribbon trim, and can
be worn at any angle. (Very similar to a bowler.)
</P>
<P>
   DOLL _ This is a really tiny hat, sometimes just a piece of
fabric with combs attached, usually accented with a short, fluttery
veil. Doll hats were worn by cigarette girls at nightclubs in the
'30s and '40s, and they're hot again at nightclubs like Merv
Griffin's new Coconut Club.
</P>
<P>
   FEDORA _ A man-tailored classic that's going to be super hot by
fall. You'll recognize it by its high, creased crown and narrow
brim. Best with tailored pantsuits.
</P>
<P>
   GARBO _ Named for the '30s film star, the garbo is a
slouchy-soft felt design that you pull down in front for a look of
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   PICTURE _ A glamorous daytime hat with a huge brim that frames
the face. To carry it off like Sophia Loren did in the film ``Ready
to Wear,'' you'll need dark glasses and a sexy suit with a slim
skirt ... and a couple of Afghans on a leash.
</P>
<P>
   PILLBOX _ You know it best as the hat worn by Jackie Kennedy and
Doris Day, dyed to match their suits and pumps. But actually, the
round, brimless style was first seen in the '20s.
</P>
<P>
   PROFILE _ A '30s fave, noted for one side of the brim turned
down to show your stunning profile.
</P>
<P>
   ROLLER _ The name may be unfamiliar, but the close-fitting crown
and narrow, curved brim was popular with young women in the '30s
and '40s and again in the Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTTIE _ A cutesy triangular hat (point worn in front) with a
lowered crown, and trimmed in the back with lots of frou-frou, such
as tulle and feathers. Not for shy types.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
