<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEME-PARKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEME PARK COMPANY WANTS TO SEE STEADY INCLINE IN CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLAIRE HUGHES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE GEORGE, N.Y. _ From a 90-foot perch atop the Giant Wheel
ride at The Great Escape and Splashwater Kingdom, you can look down
on one-fifth of the $10 million the amusement park's new owner has
sunk into the property in the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   It's the $2 million, 65-foot-high, 1,650-foot-long Alpine
Bobsled, which sends its cars up a traditional roller-coaster track
and then down on a free-wheeling, careening plunge along a
high-banked chute.
</P>
<P>
   The thrill ride's course mirrors what Premier Parks Inc. hopes
to do with the Great Escape's attendance: send it steadily up an
incline, then hold onto it with unexpected twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City-based Premier has had some experience at getting
the biggest bang for the buck it invests in entertainment
properties.
</P>
<P>
   With 32 properties, the company is the world's largest owner of
``regional theme parks'' _ which people visit for a day or less _
and has purchased 12 parks since current management took over in
1989. The $1.9 billion purchase of the Six Flags theme parks from
Time Warner Inc. in April brought its annual attendance figures to
more than 40 million, behind only Walt Disney Co., which runs
``destination theme parks'' that attract visitors for overnight
stays.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 11 parks Premier then owned achieved growth in
attendance, revenue and operating cash flow of 17.3 percent, 21.3
percent and 59.5 percent, respectively, as compared to 1996,
according to documents filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a consolidating regional park operator which injects
new life into the parks they acquire by spending carefully on the
capital expenditure side,'' said Jill Krutick, an analyst who
follows Premier for Salomon Smith Barney in New York. ``They've had
enormous success in maximizing the value of these parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Premier has made a number of improvements at The Great Escape
since the $33 million purchase of the park in Lake George. In
addition to the Alpine Bobsled, there are five new picnic pavilions
and a group catering service, a new ice-skating revue, the
Boomerang loop roller coaster, the Lumberjack Splash, a
500,000-gallon wave pool, and Bunyan's Bucket Brigade, a five-story
treehouse tower that spouts water.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of theme parks, keeping current is the formula for
staying out front, said John Collins, a vice president at Premier
and the general manager of The Great Escape and Splashwater
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is very `What's new?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners intend to keep changing the park _ but not so
much that longtime fans won't recognize its roots as a family
entertainment center with attractions based on storybook themes.
There will continue to be the low-tech, horse-driven rides in
pumpkin-shaped carriages around a replica of Cinderella's castle
and peeks ``through the looking glass'' at characters from Alice in
Wonderland.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see over time that existing areas of the park could be
redesigned,'' said Gary Story, Premier's president and chief
operating officer. ``But one area that will never be redesigned is
the Storytown portion of the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles R. Wood established Storytown in 1954 and added rides
and new themed sections over the years.
</P>
<P>
   As for competitors in The Great Escape's own league, Riverside
Park in Agawam, Mass., had been the closest. But the contest
between those two parks got friendlier last year, when Premier
bought the 160-acre property for $22 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
