<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3023 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATS-FASHIONS-LADN     06-10 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATS-FASHIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MILLINERY MAGICIAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Poor Hillary. She got so much flak for her
unflattering hats on her husband's inaugural day that Tipper took
pity on her.
</P>
<P>
   The second lady didn't swap hats ... or take the boss's wife
shopping ... but the perky, fashion-forward wife of Vice President
Al Gore did share her haberdashery secret: Jo Lichtman.
</P>
<P>
   Lichtman, a Los Angeles psychologist who decided to take her own
advice about following one's dreams, is now a hat maker. More
accurately, she's a milliner's milliner.
</P>
<P>
   In her home-based studio overlooking the San Fernando Valley,
Lichtman imports Czech rabbit fur felt and Milan straw and creates
the shapes with antique wooden and papier-mache blocks from the
'20s and '30s and some actually used for Dior's New Look in the
'50s. She uses small metal tools to create the creases in the
crown, or those ``waves'' on the side of a cloche. She even makes
the silk flowers that accent many of her hats, and does her own
embroidery and beading.
</P>
<P>
   But the real secret to Lichtman's success is her ability to
analyze a client's personality and facial features, and come up
with the perfect hat.
</P>
<P>
   So, don't ask her for a frou-frou garden hat or something funky,
because she knows what's best. Her idea of a casual hat is more
like the late Princess Diana's idea of casual, which we all know
was fresh but never frisky, says Lichtman of her highest-profile
client.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, her ``royal'' clientele includes Tipper
Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton, as well as Cher and Quincy Jones,
and the 1996 U.S. Olympic Team.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting over tea and scones in her Victorian-decorated home,
Lichtman chatted about some of her customers who appreciate what a
custom-made hat can do for one's appearance. For instance, she
confides, Cher has a small head, about 21{ inches around (the
standard hat size is 22 inches), which makes her an easy fit for
most hats. And, since she can carry off a lot of drama, Lichtman
designed a '20s-style cocktail hat, properly referred to as a doll
hat and reminiscent of those worn at a rakish angle by nightclub
cigarette girls in old movies.
</P>
<P>
   Another easy fit is the vice president's wife. ``Tipper is a
born hat model. She's got an oval face and can wear a wide range of
hat styles,'' says Lichtman.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, Hillary has a round face and a slightly
bigger-than-average head size (22{ inches around). So, the wrong
hat can make her look very matronly, as we've seen in the press.
And while we're talking, I didn't design the hats she wore at the
beginning of the Clinton administration. My first one for her was a
black hat with cording and a molded crown, worn for a state
visit.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, the milliner suggests, women with round, full
features look best in a hat that has a flat top on a flat, straight
brim, such as a boater ... or maybe a Breton (see accompanying
glossary).
</P>
<P>
   Although she's never made a hat for U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer,
she's noticed that the politician has a square face and would look
best with a beret crown on a hat with a slight up-tilt.
</P>
<P>
   Besides flattering your face and keeping the sun at bay, a hat
helps create an image.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, she says, Monica Lewinsky would look most
respectable for her court appearance in a simple ivory suit topped
with an elegant off-white boater. ``And it would be so lovely with
her coloring,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought hat tricks were only for those on the White House
hot seat, think again. Women's Wear Daily predicts the return of
hats for fall, which means we all may be trying to figure out which
suits our suits or jeans best _ a cloche or a fedora.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1536EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-     06-10 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, June 14,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORIES  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MACHO-MUSIC (Undated) _ One of the fundamental myths of rock was
that it was essentially a man's game, a macho sport that knocked a
generation of unctuous crooning mama's boys out of the batter's box
of popular culture and allowed ``real'' men to step to the
pop-music plate. Girls who sought membership in this boys' club had
better be butch. But even performers like Patti Smith and Joan
Jett, who affected male bravado, were never fully accepted into the
highest reaches of rock's pantheon. The reality behind that myth,
of course, is something quite different. By Stephen Holden. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   TALKING-ART-BOWIE (Undated) _ Talking art with David Bowie: A
musician's parallel passion. By Michael Kimmelman. (Editors: This
is the first in an occasional series of talks with people who, in
one way or another, have a special connection to art but aren't
(primarily) artists themselves: writers, musicians, scientists,
politicians, collectors.) By Michael Kimmelman. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-VINOLY (Undated) _ Even though Rafael Vinoly is the
most elegant architect now practicing in the United States, he
probably doesn't want to hear about it. The elegance of his work is
ascetic as well as esthetic. By Herbert Muschamp. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-SHAKESPEARE (New York) _ There probably isn't a scholar or
critic in the world who would rate ``Henry VIII'' as one of
Shakespeare's great history plays. Yet as presented by the Royal
Shakespeare Company during its recent 18-day residency at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music, ``Henry VIII'' is suddenly revealed to
be a vivid and compelling theatrical artifact. By Vincent Canby.
Moving 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-FIRST-RUN (Undated) _ Altogether it has been a
high-profile month for First Run Features. Once again the small New
York film and video distributor is succeeding in acting a little
too big for its acquisition budget. By Peter M. Nichols. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   KEN-LOACH-MOVIES (London) _ Surprisingly, perhaps, given his
distaste for the prevailing social order, Ken Loach was never an
angry young man. Shy and soft-spoken, he was almost 30 by the time
he set off down the path that three decades later would earn him
recognition in Europe as the dean of leftist movie makers. By Alan
Riding. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-TWEENERS (Undated) _
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood hasn't quite given up on the tweens _the 9- to
12-year-olds _ but it is as perplexed about how to entertain them
as parents are about how to rear them. ``There's very little being
made anymore for the tweeners,'' says Terry Press, head of
marketing for Dreamworks. ``We figure they are either going to be
dragged to `Quest for Camelot' with their younger siblings or they
reach 8 and want to see `Titanic' and everything else. They've
really become a niche market.'' By Michele Willens. Moving 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   ALY-SHEEDY-MOVIES (Undated) _ To Americans, Aly Sheedy is still
the shining conscience of the Brat Pack of the 1980s, the sprightly
valentine at the center of classic films about the transition to
adulthood like ``The Breakfast Club'' and ``St. Elmo's Fire,'' the
touchstone for a million awkward adolescences. She is the farthest
thing imaginable from a middle-aged lesbian drug addict
photographer, which is what she plays in ``High Art.'' By Margy
Rochlin. Moving 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-JACOBS-PILLOW (Undated) _ On June 23, when the nation's
oldest summer dance festival opens in tiny Becket, Mass., it will
have a new director, Ella Baff. Running Jacob's Pillow Dance
Festival is hard work, but Ms. Baff is full of ambitious visions.
By Jennifer Dunning. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLTRANE-JAZZ (New York) _ It is a perfect indicator of jazz's
restricted place in American society that Ravi Coltrane _ who is
the son of John Coltrane _was nobody special as a boy growing up in
Woodland Hills, a suburb of Los Angeles, far away from the bohemian
world. By Ben Ratliff. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-THORNBIRDS-CHAMBERLAIN (Undated) _ Richard Chamberlain talks
about the series that captivated a country in 1983 on the eve of
its revival. By Anita Gates. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-WODEHOUSE (Undated) _ In 1927, when James H. Heineman
was 10, he demonstrated a bibliographic bent: he began buying first
editions of the novels of his favorite author, the British writer
P.G. Wodehouse, whose works poked fun at bumbling English
aristocrats. Over the next 60 years, Heineman continued to buy the
works of Wodehouse, amassing a collection of some 6,300 items. Next
Sunday, Heineman's entire Wodehouse collection goes on view for the
first time at Sotheby's in New York, where it will be auctioned in
150 lots on June 26. By Rita Reif. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PORTUGAL-CASTLES (Undated) _ Exploring the cobblestone
streets and medieval castles of Portugal's hilltop towns. By
Mitchel Levitas. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PORTUGAL-EXPO (Lisbon) _ Lisbon looks to the future as
well as to its glorious maritime past with Expo '98. By Alan
Riding. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ How can you get anywhere if you
won't fly and can't drive? Very slowly. By Betsy Wade. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRAZIL (Salvador, Brazil) _ Bahia makes room for a
Candomble Pantheon. By Jon Pareles. Moved.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Travel notes and news: U.S tour
companies venture to Iran; Denmark town celebrates 1,000 years;
Pacific Aquarium opens in Long Beach; a wetter, wilder Dollywood.
Moved.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ The Czar's burial; Tudor events in
