<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3063 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     06-10 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ABOUT THE PRESIDENT'S MORALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 14)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ These are difficult times for many Americans to
decide what is right and what is wrong with the actions taken by
the men and women who run our government and shape the future of
the republic.
</P>
<P>
   While love of country and faith in the future continue to
motivate those of us whose vision has not been blinded by the
cynicism that has spread across the nation in recent years, we each
must try to determine our own perspective of the strange events
that have taken place in our society and undercut Bill Clinton's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Many individuals, basking in the prosperity of the moment and
looking to an even better tomorrow, approve Clinton's performance
in the White House despite the aura of scandal that surrounds him.
Many approve the direction taken by House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and congressional Republicans,
despite their refusal to reform campaign fund-raising and their
reluctance to force the big tobacco companies, which contribute
heavily to the GOP, to pay billions in taxes to strengthen
antismoking efforts among young Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The standing of the president and Congress have risen in public
opinion polls although many Americans are dissatisfied with the
performance of Congress and dismayed by the allegations about
Clinton's personal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   As for myself, I feel that if Clinton's relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky, whether sexual or otherwise,
was consentual, then it should be a matter for discussion by the
two of them and Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if the president of the United States lied to
a grand jury about the matter or if he sought to persuade others to
cover up any misdeeds, then he is guilty of a serious crime and
should pay the penalty, whether it be a reprimand by Congress or
resignation from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when I first read of Warren G. Harding's sexual
liaisons with Nan Britton, who bore him a daughter, I was offended.
When I learned that they had sex in a broom closet adjacent to the
Oval Office, I was repulsed by the knowledge that such conduct
could take place in the house that has been home to every president
and first lady since John and Abigail Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when I covered the White House, most of my colleagues and
I suspected that John F. Kennedy was indulging in extramarital
activities when he journeyed without his wife Jacqueline to such
places as Los Angeles, Palm Springs, New York and Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   But we had no proof and, even if we had, we would not have
written about it. In those days, presidents' private lives were
usually kept private.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in the late 1940s, I read a column in which Westbrook
Pegler alluded to the fact that Franklin D. Roosevelt's ``girl
friend'' was at his side in Warm Springs, Ga., when he died in
1945. But I rejected Pegler's report because his thinking was so
corroded by his hatred of FDR.
</P>
<P>
   A number of years later, one my close friends, Washington Post
White House correspondent Carroll Kilpatrick, told me that Jonathan
Daniels, a former aide to FDR, had suggested that they write a book
together about Roosevelt's longtime love affair with Lucy Mercer
Rutherfurd who, indeed, was in Warm Springs on that fateful April
12, 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Kilpatrick did not become involved in the project, but Daniels
published a book in which he told of Roosevelt's romance, which
began in World War I when Lucy Mercer was Eleanor Roosevelt's
secretary and ended in World War II with his death from a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to decide what moral code another individual
should follow, especially when that individual is the president.
The judgment is one that each of us must determine for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   On the matter of the Clinton administration's relationship with
China, the issue is ethics rather than morality.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans assert that the president's policies toward Beijing,
including the transfer of missile technology, have been influenced
by contributions to the Democratic Party from wealthy Chinese.
Clinton denies the accusation, just as Gingrich denies that huge
campaign contributions from the tobacco industry are at the root of
GOP efforts to prevent heavy taxation of the big tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   For many reasons, including memories of the Tiananmen Square
massacre of hundreds of pro-democracy protesters in 1989 and
Beijing's continued violations of human rights, critics have
contended that Clinton should cancel his planned visit to China
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   He has refused and he is on solid ground in doing so. I
journeyed to China with President Ronald Reagan in 1984 and with
Vice President George Bush in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   During those visits America's presidents did not agree with all
China had done or was doing. But our leaders recognized that
Communist Party Chairman Deng Xiaoping, who masterminded government
strategy, wanted to improve relations with the noncommunist West.
</P>
<P>
   Although Deng is now dead, there is strong evidence that the
current leaders want to continue that policy.
</P>
<P>
   It should be clear to any thinking person, therefore, that
America can exercise far more influence on China's leadership
through an enlightened dialogue between leaders than through a
boycott that would take us back to the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Among today's political leaders, Clinton is the most eloquent
spokesman for the kind of world many of us seek in the 21st
century. That would make any moral or ethical misadventures all the
more difficult to defend and all the more tragic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
