<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-ECONOMY (Wahington) _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan says the U.S. economy is in a ``virtuous cycle'' of low
inflation and strong growth, suggesting he's prepared to extend the
Fed's bet that no interest rate increase is needed in the months
ahead as the economy slows. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR2000-INVESTORS (Washington) _ With Americans shifting more
of their savings into the stock market, technical and financial
experts warn that the year 2000 computer glitch could threaten the
safety of millions of investments. Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah,
introduces a bill to force companies to disclose what they're doing
about the problem. By MARK HELM. (Story will also be filed in the
FINANCIAL NEWS, or ``f,'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHKOREA-INVEST (Washington) _ South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung makes a pitch for greater U.S. investment in South Korea.
In speeches before Congress and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, he
says protectionist trade barriers are coming down and that new
investments ``will be rewarded many times over.'' By DAN FREEDMAN.
(Story will also be filed in the FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS, or ``f,''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-BILL (Washington) _ A proposal to use some of the money
contained in the Senate tobacco legislation to provide tax breaks
to married couples gains support from the White House. By BENNETT
ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-AWARDS (Washington) _ Good Housekeeping magazine honors 10
women for government service. Recipients include Philadelphia's
health commissioner, who was recognized for helping the poor, and
the mayor of San Jose, Calif., who has created a program to recruit
minorities for government jobs. Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif.,
presented some of the awards. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-RENO (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno announces
plans for an instant check of criminal records to allow gun
purchases under the Brady Law's waiting period. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL-ATTACK-JACKSON (Jasper, Texas) _ Civil rights leader
Jesse Jackson visits the family of a black man whose gruesome death
has prompted nationwide horror, while law enforcement authorities
search for ways to seek the death penalty against the three white
suspects. The three men are accused of chaining James Byrd Jr., 49,
to the back of a pickup truck and dragging him to his death. By
RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-BAPTISTS (Salt Lake City) _ In a not-so-subtle
reference to fellow Southern Baptist Bill Clinton, the Southern
Baptist Convention adopts a resolution urging voters to remember
that character does count in politics and to elect moral, honest
and virtuous public officials. By RICHARD VARA.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SINKING-YEN (Paris) _ already filed _ The plummeting yen, which
has lost more than 40 percent of its value in the last four years,
has opened a new phase in the Japanese crisis, suggesting that even
more serious problems lie ahead for the world's second largest
economy. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Story was also filed in the
FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS, or ``f,'' category.)
</P>
