<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILTON-SLEEP-TIGHT-NY     06-10 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILTON-SLEEP-TIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO SOOTHE THE WEARY, STRESSED AND JET LAGGED 
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PHIL PATTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the Waldorf-Astoria and other Hilton hotels,
special Sleep-Tight Rooms have been designed in consultation with
the National Sleep Foundation. A survey of international business
travelers by Hilton and the sleep foundation in 1997 found that
outside noise and, more important, noise from neighbors were most
often cited as keeping travelers up at night.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton's Sleep-Tight Rooms include apparatus for soothing the
troubled soul (and diminishing that outside noise). Along with the
Helen of Troy Dazey Turbo Spa, the Roc Lon TLC black-out curtains
and the Biobrite Sunrise Clock for a gentle wake-up, various
devices offer the sounds of streams or ocean waves and the Sharper
Image Heart and Sound Soother provides white noise.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton is jumping on a trend. Equipment that produces white
noise _ a generic hum that eliminates irritating noises _ is being
marketed to travelers. (Doesn't the central air conditioning of
most hotels constitute white noise by itself?) Now, for those who
are most alienated from nature, digital chips offer up ocean waves
or the rain forest. Brookstone's Tranquil Moments for Travel
promises to block out stress with the sounds of the ocean and the
forest. The device's blue, rounded shape with a digital clock face
is as smooth as beach glass.
</P>
<P>
   The Relaxation Machine plays ``six of nature's most comforting
sounds.'' It promises clarity of mind through sound. The machine,
it is promised, can soothe a baby, help meditation or increase
concentration on work. But most of all it redesigns the space it
enters and, the promotional material says, ``creates instant
ambiance anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Discus shaped, lying flat or tilted up, the relaxation machine
has no visible speakers. Its design is as reassuring as the sound
of the wind through the trees. Its controls are circles and little
ovals shaped like nail polish samples. Push this one for heartbeat,
that for spring rain, mountain stream or summer night, and set the
device to fade away.
</P>
<P>
   These are new-age sounds, moving beyond white noise to beige
noise, teal noise _ pastel noise. And the devices that produce them
go out of their way to look sleek and nontechnological. The design
is intended to keep the customer from suspecting that these sounds
could be obtained just as easily from a tape or a CD.
</P>
<P>
   But nature's sounds may not be as soothing as the makers of
sound appliances would have us believe. Not long ago, I went to
sleep with the sound of a waterfall in my hotel room _ not a
digitally recorded one, but the Snoqualmie Falls in Washington
State. Its noise is as white as the foam and spray at its base, but
its meanings are not so simple.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds more sinister than soothing because, as I had learned,
this was the waterfall in David Lynch's television series ``Twin
Peaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The most natural ambient sounds, it occurs to me, can be far
less soothing than the makers of sound appliances would have us
believe. Is it stranger to hear a real waterfall in your hotel
room, or a recorded one?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond ``Songbirds at Sunrise'' or ``Dawn at Trout Lake,'' don't
some of us need ``Broadway Boogie-Woogie,'' with taxi horns and
ambulance sirens, or ``Madison Avenue Bus, 5 a.m.'' and
``Sanitation Department: Greatest Hits'' to feel at home?
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that the appeal of these machines lies not in
the sounds themselves but in the promise that travelers can control
their environment. It's not the nature in the natural sound that is
important, but its predictability. These sounds present a familiar
picture for the ear.
</P>
<P>
   Adrift in unfamiliar cities, at the mercy of airline schedule
changes, control is what travelers lose. And wanting to control
your environment, wherever you are, is only natural.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
