<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3124 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DIGITAL-CAMERAS-A     06-10 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DIGITAL-CAMERAS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOT FIRST, E-MAIL PHOTOS TO GRANDMA LATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927. Color
Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first digital cameras aimed at consumers were interesting
computer peripherals that captured pictures on a sliver of silicon
instead of film. Beyond some simple business applications that
required instant electronic publishing, like making computer
records of dented fenders, new home listings or smiling employees
of the month, the first digital cameras were no match for even a
simple point-and-shoot disposable camera.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, however, a harmonious convergence of several
different technologies and trends has significantly raised the
quality, lowered the price and broadened the creative possibilities
of consumer digital photography. As a result, digital cameras are
clicking with consumers as never before.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, a new class of digital cameras _ called megapixel
cameras because each image they capture can be made up of more than
a million picture elements, or pixels _ has emerged, with prices
between $500 and $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   While they are still far more costly than many conventional film
cameras, and twice the cost of the first generation of digital
cameras, these new megapixel cameras are the first to challenge
their film-based counterparts seriously with regard to image
quality and controls.
</P>
<P>
   There are limits, of course. Even at their best, these new
sub-$1,000 consumer cameras are no match for a decent 35-millimeter
film camera if the goal is merely to take pictures and print them
out. In fact, even a $10 disposable camera and a one-hour film lab
will produce equal or superior results, just as a typewriter is
probably a better choice than a $3,000 computer system if the only
task is typing the occasional short memo.
</P>
<P>
   But digital cameras, harnessed to a personal computer with
image-editing software and attached to a color ink-jet printer,
offer a tremendous leap over conventional film photography for some
applications. Images can be cropped, enhanced, distorted, resized,
rotated, recolored, tweaked or otherwise fancied up in ways that
only darkroom virtuosos could hope to match with conventional
photographic techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the newer digital cameras have a built-in liquid crystal
display that allows the user to see the image just captured. With
the press of a button or two, any image in the camera's memory can
be saved or deleted. There is no penalty for taking a bad shot,
other than the time it takes to erase it.
</P>
<P>
   The images can then be stored and sorted, sent around the world
instantly by electronic mail, added to letters or calendars or
greeting cards, embedded in Web pages or printed on glossy paper as
prints that are virtually indistinguishable from conventional photo
prints.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the new megapixel cameras _ which including the
Kodak DC260, the Fuji MX-700, the Olympus D-600L and the Nikon
Coolpix 900 _ offer image resolutions that until now were found
only in high-end digital cameras costing $2,500 to $15,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Such expensive professional digital cameras typically have more
features, like interchangeable lenses and a greater color range,
than the consumer models. They are used mainly by magazine and
newspaper photographers who need to publish in a hurry or by
photography studios that want to let customers review and order
shots while they are still in the studio. (Sports Illustrated, for
example, has not shot an inch of film at the last two Olympic
Games, relying instead on digital cameras.)
</P>
<P>
   But the new consumer cameras are just one part of the new
digital imaging picture. Prices of personal computers, image
scanners, portable storage and memory chips have also been falling
sharply, allowing consumers to assemble powerful and versatile
systems that used to be the province of graphics professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Inexpensive software for editing and manipulating digital images
is getting more sophisticated yet easier to use, and it often comes
bundled with cameras or scanners.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the images out of the camera is easier, too, which was
not the case with earlier models. There are new ways to beam
pictures to a printer via infrared links, to transfer them at high
speed from the camera's memory via a cable to a computer's hard
disk and to display them on television screens.
</P>
<P>
   A number of companies offer novel ways to publish digital
pictures on the Web or send them to Grandma as an e-mail
attachment.
</P>
<P>
   Color ink-jet printers, some costing as little as $250, now have
the ability to produce photo-quality prints on special (albeit
fairly pricey) paper.
</P>
<P>
   Film companies, which might be expected to resist the rise of
filmless cameras, have instead embraced them enthusiastically. Both
Fuji and Kodak have set up ambitious programs in film processing
centers and on the World Wide Web to help customers get started in
digital photography.
</P>
<P>
   Many photo labs now routinely ask whether you want your prints
on paper, disk or e-mail. Some, like Seattle Filmworks, will even
set up a password-protected Web page for customers and post
digitized photos there. Several companies will also print favorite
digital snapshots on items ranging from coffee mugs to mouse pads.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the age of the digital desktop darkroom is here, and
millions of computer users already have some or all of the
necessary components. The main problems, or at least the central
ones, have been the cost and quality of the digital cameras. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the new digital cameras have been domesticated somewhat
for the consumer market, they are still primarily computer
peripherals _ and thus susceptible to all the gremlins that can
plague computers. Users must have at least basic computer skills, a
willingness to read instruction manuals and learn new software
applications, a tolerance for dealing with cables and connectors,
and the patience to figure out various file formats.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras may be ``point and shoot,'' but getting the pictures
out of the camera, at least in the beginning, can still be
frustrating. And a downside of taking pictures at such high
resolutions is that each image takes up more memory and file space,
so it takes longer to transfer to and from the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential technical headaches, there is a certain
magic when one sees a digital image appear for the first time on
the computer screen, just as there is when a conventional
photograph begins to emerge in a tray of chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The single most salient measure of the quality of a digital
camera is its resolution, which refers to the level of image detail
it can capture. Resolution is measured in pixels, short for picture
elements, expressed by the number of pixels both horizontally and
vertically. The more pixels, the higher the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   An early benchmark for digital cameras was so-called VGA
resolution, or 640 by 480 pixels. Multiplying the two numbers
yielded a total pixel count of 307,200. While that sounds like a
lot of dots, it is barely enough to make a decent wallet-size color
photograph.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Those same 300,000 dots scattered over a larger area, like a
5-by-7-inch photo print, result in a jagged, or ``pixelized,''
picture.
</P>
<P>
   The VGA-level cameras are just fine for grabbing small images
suitable for Web pages or e-mail attachments, for viewing on a
computer screen (which is relatively low-resolution) or for
inclusion in the family newsletter produced with desktop
publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The more pixels the camera can capture in one image, the better
the image quality. As a practical matter, the higher the pixel
count, the larger the prints that can be made.
</P>
<P>
   The new megapixel cameras, using larger image-capturing chips,
can capture more than a million pixels per image (hence the term
megapixel, like megabyte for a million bytes). At these levels, the
print size can be increased to 4 by 6 without succumbing to the
jaggies.
</P>
<P>
   Even amateur photographers are now able to produce
photo-quality, 5-by-7 glossy color prints at home, using relatively
common gear. (Kodak asserts that its new 1.6-megapixel camera can
yield acceptable 8-by-10 prints, but other manufacturers make more
conservative claims.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the megapixel cameras came out, there was a high
incidence of returns or dissatisfied customers _ not at our store,
of course,'' said Jeff Miller, sales director at Capitol Camera in
Austin, Texas, referring to the early VGA-level cameras. If
customers bought a VGA-level camera with the expectation that it
would be a digital-age Polaroid, they were often disappointed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 1.2 million of the cameras were sold in North America
last year, said Jonathan Pepper, publisher of Digital Focus, a
digital-imaging newsletter. Some 1.6 million digital cameras
costing less than $1,500 each will be sold in 1998, he projected,
with that number doubling, to 3.2 million, in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for the VGA cameras have fallen 35 percent in the past
year, and megapixel cameras are sure to follow. Olympus broke the
megapixel price barrier last year with the impressive D-600L; at
$1,299, it was only half the cost of previous megapixel models.
Olympus recently cut the price of the D-600L to $999.
</P>
<P>
   Angele Boyd, vice president of peripherals research at IDC, a
market research company in Framingham, Mass., said consumer digital
photography was not very likely to become a mainstream phenomenon
until megapixel camera prices fell below $300. Some models are now
getting close to $500.
</P>
<P>
   But price is not the only consideration. Each of the new
megapixel models has a unique strength or two. The Nikon Coolpix
900, for example, uses high-quality Nikkor glass lenses, with
optional wide-angle and fish-eye lenses. The pocket-size Fuji
MX-700 has a snazzy aluminum case and a brilliant two-inch LCD
screen for previewing images.
</P>
<P>
   The new Kodak D260 has a zoom lens (3X optical, the equivalent
of a 38-115 millimeter, and 6X digital telephoto, 230 millimeter
equivalent); manual focus options; a ``burst mode'' for rapid-fire
picture-taking; a time-lapse setting, and a synchronized flash and
a microphone that lets the user annotate each image with a spoken
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The D260 is also the first consumer digital camera to have a
Universal Serial Bus connection, which means that it can blast a
megapixel file to a U.S.B.-enabled computer (standard on many new
PCs) in just a few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   On the printer side, Hewlett-Packard, which makes a line of
Photosmart printers and scanners for digital-photography
enthusiasts, has hinted that it will introduce USB-ready
peripherals this fall, enabling users to send pictures directly
from the camera or scanner to the printer, bypassing the PC.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard has also developed new inks and printing
processes for the Photosmart line that minimize fading in photos
from ink-jet printers. In the past, homemade photos tended to fade
quickly, especially if left in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they are expected to have life spans similar to those of
conventional photographic prints, although leaving them in the sun
is still a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   At the rate the new cameras are falling in price and climbing in
features, potential buyers are faced with the same dilemma they
face with PCs: do you buy today, knowing prices will inevitably
fall as soon as the plastic is back in the wallet, or do you wait
until the holiday season, when new, improved models _ perhaps
approaching two megapixels _ are certain to crack the $1,000
barrier?
</P>
<P>
   ``These new cameras today will be entry-level products a year
from now,'' said Carl Holec, senior imaging products analyst at
Associated Research Services in Irving, Texas, supporting the
buy-later view. ``But,'' he said, taking the buy-now side, ``the
ones today are light-years ahead of ones a year ago.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)The four programs listed are some of the popular ones
you can use once you get images into your computer.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ADOBE PHOTOSHOP VERSION 5.0 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adobe Systems; list price $995; Windows and Macintosh.)
Expensive professional tool for creating, editing, enhancing and
retouching graphic images like digital photos. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ADOBE PHOTODELUXE 2.0 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adobe Systems; list price $49; Windows and Macintosh.) A good
balance of ease of use and creative features makes this the leading
consumer program for manipulating, organizing and publishing
digital photos. Often included with cameras and scanners.
Photodeluxe Business Edition ($99) is for Windows only. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT PICTURE IT 2.0 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Microsoft; list price: $54.95; Windows.) Probably the easiest
photo-management software for beginners. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KAI'S SUPER GOO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Metacreations; street price $50; Windows and Macintosh.) A tool
for distorting and morphing images. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
