<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3142 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-EYESTRAIN-CARE-NY     06-10 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EYESTRAIN-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER MONITOR NEED NOT TAKE A TOLL ON THE EYES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a number of ways to reduce eyestrain at the computer.
Much of the advice is common sense, but some of it is contradictory
and some is idealistic _ who wouldn't prefer a 20-inch screen?
</P>
<P>
   MAKE THE DISPLAY SHARP AND CLEAR. The eyes like to focus on
distinct borders, which is a challenge with fuzzy pixels and
consequently fuzzy letters. Make the type as distinct and readable
as possible:
</P>
<P>
   _ Large, dark letters. Dark letters on a light background work
better than the reverse. Experiment with the typefaces; some are
easier to read than others.
</P>
<P>
   _ Large monitor: A 20-inch screen is easier on the eyes than a
14-inch. Given good software, the larger screen will in effect
increase the resolution, which is helpful.
</P>
<P>
   _ Uncluttered viewing: Remove notes and decorations from the rim
of the monitor to reduce distractions.
</P>
<P>
   USE GOOD LIGHTING. Reduce or eliminate reflections:
</P>
<P>
   _ Glare from outside: Place the monitor perpendicular to the
window. Adjust blinds or shades to minimize the amount of direct
light on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Glare from inside: Use a glare screen approved by the American
Optometric Association, (800) 365-2219. Adjust lights and the
monitor to keep light from reflecting into the eyes. Cover white
shirts with a darker jacket or sweater. Clean the screen regularly.
</P>
<P>
   REST OFTEN.To help the eyes, you can take several steps: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Blink: People blink less frequently when they fix on the
screen, and the eyes become dry. Remind yourself to blink.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take frequent breaks: Look away from the screen into the
distance, then close the eyes for 5 to 10 seconds. Do this at least
every hour.
</P>
<P>
   ADJUST THE SCREEN POSITION. The height of the screen and
distance from the user should be adjusted for each person: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Height: Don't place the screen at an angle that requires you
to look up. That makes the eyes dry more quickly, and the position
bothers the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Try looking at the monitor screen at an angle 10 to 20 degrees
below the horizontal, directly in front of the eye. (If you use
bifocals and are reading through the lower part of lenses, lower
the position of screen.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Distance: The monitor should be an arm's length away _ 18 to
28 inches _ given the constraints of a desk. Adjust the chair so
the screen can be read without leaning forward. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
