<HEADLINE>
GOOD HOUSEKEEPING HONORS WOMEN FOR GOVERNMENT SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Good Housekeeping magazine honored 10 women for
excellence in government service Wednesday, including the mayor of
San Jose, Calif., and a member of the Los Angeles County Board of
Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose Mayor Susan Hammer was one of nine women receiving
$2,500 during an awards ceremony in the Capitol. She was selected
for creating Project Diversity, a program to recruit minorities
into government jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., who spoke at the ceremony, said
Hammer ``rolled up her sleeves and by reaching out to everyone of
talent, turned that city around.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Molina, a member of the Los Angeles Board of Supervisors,
also won for launching a program called Greater Avenues to
Independence, which helped bring thousands of welfare recipients
into the workforce and is considered a model for the rest of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The top winner, Estelle B. Richman, Philadelphia city health
commissioner, was presented with a check for $25,000. She was
recognized for creating a nonprofit corporation, Community
Behavioral Health, which provides care for the city's poor.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond said she was accepting the award ``on behalf of all
those who suffer from mental health and substance abuse problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Levine, editor of Good Housekeeping, said by establishing
the award, the magazine ``hopes to identify women fighting to make
a difference in today's society and re-establish a trust in
government... It is our editorial responsibility to help make a
difference in women's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer cited women's suffrage leaders Elizabeth Cady Stanton and
Susan B. Anthony who argued that women should be active in politics
because they bring a fresh perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, as we honor these 10 gifted leaders, it makes me think
that, perhaps, we are coming close to realizing the dreams of the
visionary women who began the fight for women's rights a century
ago,'' Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas Gov. Ann Richards, who attended the ceremony and
luncheon with about 100 women, said she hopes the Good Housekeeping
award encourages women who are in government to stay there _
despite the frustrations and low pay.
</P>
<P>
   The award ``says to young people this is a good, a noble and an
honorable profession,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners included:
</P>
<P>
   _ Harriet Cornell, who developed programs in Rockland County,
N.Y., to prevent violence, promote arts and help women with
political goals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Susan Daniels, deputy Social Security commissioner for
disability and income security, a polio survivor, who launched a
government program that has helped disabled people in 22 states buy
their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mary Gade, director of the Illinois Environmental Protection
Agency, who helped form an association of 37 states to figuring out
how to clean up ozone, a polluting gas that causes respiratory
problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nancy Mayer, treasurer for the State of Rhode Island, who
revamped her state's pension system.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Powell, superintendent of the Robert E. Ellsworth
Correctional Center for Women in Union Grove, Wis., who has helped
inmates with drug rehabilitation and job training.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kelly Shepard, a park ranger who has helped safeguard
artifacts and archaeological sites in Colorado's Mesa Verde
National Park.
</P>
<P>
   _ Natacha Seijas Millan, a county commissioner in Miami-Dade
County, Fla., who started the county's ``stroller parking law,''
which requires large parking lots to provide special spots for
families with small children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
