<HEADLINE>
PLANNING AN ONLINE DATE NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's Saturday night in the big city. After weeks of
busy work and busier schedules, a loving couple has set these hours
aside for some overdue quality time, in the form of a cozy evening
at home.
</P>
<P>
   This experience has become something of an urban ritual in
Manhattan, a sometimes-prized amenity of life in a city with easy
access to restaurants for take-out or delivery, eclectic video
stores, and late-night wine shops.
</P>
<P>
   As Woody Allen once said, he wouldn't want to live where he
couldn't get a bowl of wonton soup at four in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Internet companies are trying to make it even easier
to stay home. Just boot up, surf to the food or video delivery
sites, place the orders, then wait for the goods to arrive. To find
out if this is really better than the offline way, the couple
decided to road test the options, planning one date night online,
and another offline.
</P>
<P>
   Every good date night needs a bottle of wine. For now, ordering
a bottle of Chardonnay via the Net is a work in progress. One site,
Virtual Vineyards (www.virtualvineyard.com), aims to be the
Amazon.com of vino, carrying hundreds of bottles of wine from $10
up.
</P>
<P>
   Someone craving, say, an Austrian Merlot can use the site's
search engine to narrow down the choices by wineries and types. For
those who just don't know what to serve with a salmon mousse, the
vineyard's self-described ''Cork Dork'' answers e-mail questions
about the delicate art of pairing wine and food.
</P>
<P>
   Once the bottle's selected, it's $5 - $10 for shipping,
depending on the size of the order, with deliveries taking 2 - 5
days. So much for spontaneity. And if one hopes the Zinfandel comes
chilled, forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   Online wine delivery makes more sense now for the serious
collector who wants to order cases of a particular brand or
vintage. Otherwise, daters are better off running down to the local
store; the clerk might not be as knowledgeable as the Cork Dork,
but is liable to have some good suggestions anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Next, it's time for a restaurant delivery site like NY Delivery
(www.nydelivery.com). Run by an East Village restaurant owner, NY
Delivery contains over 500 restaurant menus from around Manhattan
(other boroughs coming soon). Click the appropriate neighborhood
from the city map on the home page, and it links to a list of
nearby dining establishments.
</P>
<P>
   Each restaurant has its own page, listing the entire menu. Click
through the items desired, and each gets added up immediately on
the site.
</P>
<P>
   Once the order is sent, NY Delivery e-mails back a confirmation
then sends a fax to the appropriate restaurant, which prepares and
deliver the food. NY Delivery is not yet able to process credit
card transactions, so all payments are cash.
</P>
<P>
   There's no extra cost for the service, since NY Delivery takes a
6 percent cut of the restaurants earnings. Best of all: no
rummaging through the junk drawer for a half dozen torn menus.
</P>
<P>
   With the food and wine on the way, boot up a video delivery
service like Kozmo.com (www.kozmo.com), a service in New York that
plans to expand in other cities. Unlike the neighborhood video
store, which might have 10,000 videos, Kozmo stocks over 20,000,
ranging from Psycho to Stealing Beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Videos are categorized by genre, plus there's a search engine
and staff recommendations. Feeling romantic? Try David Lynch's Lost
Highway, Kozmo says.
</P>
<P>
   Once the video's chosen, top it off with some Milk Duds or
popcorn, then click the order through. Each video is $3.50 and gets
delivered to the door within an hour. Tipping is not required,
though the video recipient might feel guilt with no tip.
</P>
<P>
   When the film's over, customers can either have Kozmo pick it up
(for an extra $1) or can deposit it at designated drop-off centers
_ though most are not open 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the online method seems best suited for serious
Webheads or workers too busy to leave their desks. And as any
couple knows, the real challenge in planning a date night _ at
home, or anywhere _ is choosing what to see, eat, and drink. If
agreeing on a video seems hard, just imagine deciding who gets to
hold the mouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
