<SLUG> BC-CIR-DIGITAL-TYRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAPING CENTURIES IN A SINGLE STEP, A MINIMALIST GOES DIGITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARGARET LOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trained the old-fashioned way in her native
Copenhagen to photograph without light meters and to make her own
emulsions in the darkroom, Marianne Engberg is cheerfully
nonchalant about the lengths she goes to in pursuit of her art.
</P>
<P>
   She takes black-and-white photographs with pinhole cameras,
equipment so primitive that she has made the ones she uses out of
Quaker Oats boxes and black masking tape. The speed of the pinhole
is so slow that she thinks nothing of waiting out exposure times
ranging from 7 to 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by The New York Times to try a point-and-shoot digital
camera _ the polar opposite of her technologically challenged
pinhole camera _ Ms. Engberg was instantly intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   She tried an early-generation digital camera, widely available
and not too expensive _ the Sony Mavica FD5, the world's first
digital still camera using standard 3{-inch high-density floppy
disks to store images that can later be viewed on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   t was a sunny spring day, perfect for pictures of shadows, which
Ms. Engberg has been photographing with her pinhole camera for the
last year or so. She chose a few blocks in the low 80s on the Upper
West Side.
</P>
<P>
   She was initially distracted by the digital camera's
point-and-shoot inflexibility. But she quickly realized that there
was something familiar about her inability to select an F-stop
(controlling the amount of light passing through the lens) or
change the shutter speed (the duration of the exposure).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is strange,'' she said. ``It's like using a pinhole.''
(The pinhole camera, which is devoid of all helpful photographic
gadgetry, has a simple underlying principle: light passing through
a small hole on one side of a darkened box casts the outside image
on the opposite side of the box.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Engberg also realized that the digital camera, like the
pinhole camera, offers an infinite depth of field: everything is in
focus.
</P>
<P>
   She wondered, though, why Sony had not thought of providing a
hood for the LCD screen on the camera that allows the photographer
to compose the desired images. In bright sunlight, it was difficult
to see what was on it.
</P>
<P>
   As she took pictures of a succession of shadows of railings cast
on walls and on the ground, Ms. Engberg marveled at the ease and
speed of her picture-taking. ``I'm used to having a long time
thinking about each shot,'' she said. ``Suddenly, here I am, going
click click click.''
</P>
<P>
   As she got used to the digital camera, Ms. Engberg remembered
that she could lighten or darken her exposures. She liked that
feature. ``With a regular camera,'' she said, ``you make a
photograph lighter or darker, but you have to do it in your head.
You don't see it. Here, I could actually see it by pressing a
button.''
</P>
<P>
   The playbacks on the LCD screen were very reassuring, and Ms.
Engberg began to appreciate the attraction of digital cameras. ``I
like being able to see instantly what I've shot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then, she forgot that she was not dealing with a
traditional camera. When it came time to change the floppy disk,
she wondered if she should ``go to someplace dark, as with a
regular camera.'' Reminded that there was no film in the camera,
Ms. Engberg caught herself and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Engberg, taking pictures with the digital camera at
night in Times Square was disconcerting, she said, because the
images on the LCD screen ``are flat _ there is no mood on the
screen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sony Mavica FD5, or MVC-FD5, has shutter speeds that range
from one-sixtieth to one four-thousandths of a second, so a flash
is necessary only for a picture in virtual darkness. Because the
camera is so sensitive to light, Ms. Engberg found that when she
tried to make the images on the LCD screen lighter, she got shots
that resembled daytime scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to give up, she took a full disk of night images, not
expecting much to come out of them.
</P>
<P>
   When the floppy disk files were viewed through Netscape, the
images Ms. Engberg had taken held a few disappointments. The
digital camera seemed unable to cope with sharp contrasts in light
and dark in indoor shots; bright sections were reduced to white
patches.
</P>
<P>
   The camera also found it difficult to deal with complex
compositions. At the time the images were taken, the LCD screen
registered perfectly wonderful compositions. With 640-by-480-pixels
resolution, the $500 MVC-FD5 does not offer the truly sharp
contrasts one can get with a $300 regular camera.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, the results were a pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The initial images were on the anemic side, as expected, because
Ms. Engberg had not adjusted the exposures. Then the images got
sharper, and Ms. Engberg was amazed by the unusually rich tones in
images taken under direct sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colors are different from those produced by a regular
camera,'' she said. ``The greens are greener and the yellows are
yellower. I like the colors here.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Engberg photographed a scavenger silhouetted by rays of
sunlight, she was not sure what she would get. With a regular
camera, she said, the rays of the sun would appear white. But the
digital camera caught a lovely shower of green and red and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprises of all were the night pictures. Ms.
Engberg knew that the digital camera would not produce good images
of, say, a whole city block. And no amount of exposure adjustment
would make the camera record the delicately nuanced reflection of
light on a stainless steel wall.
</P>
<P>
   But where the camera did not have to take into account a host of
conflicting light readings, it gave astonishingly striking images,
like the Times Square Tower bathed in light, for instance. Or the
oscillating billboard at the corner of 43rd Street and Seventh
Avenue, with the camera arresting a moment the eye could not see.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
