<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE-AHEAD MORSELS TAKE THE ANGST OUT OF ENTERTAINING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sammye Irwin of Arlington sent a request labeled ``Panic Note.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any recipes for petite quiches and petite
cheesecake that can be served at weddings, open houses, etc.?''
</P>
<P>
   I see just a hint of hysteria here, so this week's column
addresses all you folks who are hosting a festive event this
summer. Bless your hearts.
</P>
<P>
   This quiche recipe is from Barbara Kafka's ``Party Food: Small &AMP;
Savory'' (Morrow, $25), a book I always turn to when planning a
party. It's well worth the purchase price. Kafka obviously is an
experienced hostess who knows how important it is to be able to
make party fare in advance. Every recipe in the book gives freezing
or make-ahead directions.
</P>
<P>
   The second recipe, for sweet mouthfuls, is from ``Dessert in
Half the Time'' by Linda West Eckhardt and Diana Collingwood Butts
(Crown, $25). I'd suggest doing this in pretty little foil cupcake
liners.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MINIATURE MUSHROOM QUICHE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 24
</P>
<P>
   Cream cheese pastry: 4 ounces (1/2 cup) cream cheese at room
temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Beat cream cheese and butter together in mixing bowl until
smooth and creamy. Add flour and salt and gradually work into dough
until mixture comes together to form a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate for at least 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   On lightly floured surface, roll out dough to about 1/8-inch
thick. Cut out pastry shapes to fit your 2- to 3-inch pans and
press in pastry using your knuckles. Prick base of pastry in each
pan twice with a fork and place filled tins on a baking sheet.
Re-roll pastry scraps to use up all pastry. Each cup needs about
1/2 ounce of pastry per tartlet shell. To use this dough for
quiche, only partially bake the shells. To use for an already
cooked mixture (or an uncooked mixture, such as chicken salad),
bake the shells fully.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees with rack in center. Place shells in
oven and bake for 12 minutes for partially baked crust and 17
minutes for fully baked crust.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven; tip baked shells out of pans and transfer to a
wire rack to cool completely. The partially baked shells can be
filled with any quiche mixture and baked as for quiche recipes.
Fully baked shells can be used immediately, or they can be
carefully packed in airtight boxes and kept at room temperature for
up to 2 days. Don't fill until shortly before serving. Partially
baked shells that are not being used immediately for quiche should
be carefully packed in plastic bags and stored in the refrigerator
for a week or freezer for up to a month.
</P>
<P>
   Partially baked and frozen or refrigerated shells for use as
quiches should be re-placed in tins and allowed to come to room
temperature before filling and normal baking. Partially baked and
frozen or refrigerated shells to use as containers for precooked
mixture should be placed on a baking sheet (not air-cushioned) in a
350-degree oven; from room temperature, the shells take 4 minutes;
directly from refrigerator, 6 minutes, directly from freezer, 8
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mushroom filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces fresh small domestic mushrooms, wiped clean, trimmed
and coarsely chopped by hand
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons Pernod
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh dill sprigs or fennel fronds
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in small skillet over medium heat. Stir in mushrooms
and cook for about 2 minutes or until they just start to give off
some liquid. Stir in cream and Pernod and continue to cook for
about 2 minutes or until mixture comes to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat and allow to cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly beat egg in small mixing bowl. Stir in mushroom mixture
with dill or fennel. Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Fill partially baked pastry shells and bake for 10 minutes.
Remove from oven and allow to cool slightly on a wire rack before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   The completed quiches can be frozen after baking and being
allowed to cool. Reheat frozen quiches in a single layer on a
baking sheet (not air-cushioned) for 10 minutes at 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per quiche: 76 calories, 7 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 30 milligrams cholesterol, 88
milligrams sodium, 76 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE RITZ RASPBERRY CHEESECAKE CUPS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 36
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 10-12)
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces light process cream cheese product
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup 1 percent low-fat cottage cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons framboise or Chambord, raspberry-flavor liqueur
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons semisweet mini-chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   36 fresh raspberries and fresh mint leaves, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. In bowl of food processor fitted
with steel blade, process cream cheese product, sugar, cottage
cheese, flour, liqueur, cocoa, vanilla, egg and salt until smooth
and creamy. Fit 3 miniature muffin pans with paper liners. (Batter
may be stored, covered, at room temperature if you need to bake
these in 2 batches.)
</P>
<P>
   Carefully pour batter evenly into lined pans or pour all batter
into large measuring cup with a lip and pour into liners. Sprinkle
each with 4 or 5 mini-chocolate chips. Bake for 18 minutes. Let
cool in pans for 10 minutes. Remove and allow to cool to room
temperature. Cover and refrigerate for at least 2 hours. Garnish
with optional raspberries and mint leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cup: 42 calories, 2 grams fat, 6 grams
carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 11 milligrams cholesterol, 58
milligrams sodium, 35 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Anne Harrell is trying to find a recipe for the carrot
cake once served at The Holy Cow in Dallas. The cake was very dark
and very rich.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader would like two recipes from the defunct Weldon's
Tea Room on West Seventh Street in Fort Worth. One is for their
spiced ice tea. The other is that lunch spot's spinach salad with
green peas.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Star-Telegram, Box
1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
