<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING CHAMPION BRAZIL STRUGGLES IN CUP OPENER, A 2-1 WIN OVER
SCOTLAND  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. DENIS, France _ Brazil's coach, Mario Zagallo, said he would
know in the first match whether he had great players or a great
team. The fans had already made up their mind. When Zagallo was
introduced Wednesday, he was booed. But his team did what a
defending champion must do in the opener of the World Cup. It
survived, even if it took Scotland putting a goal into its own net
to provide a 2-1 victory for Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain fatalism about this team, which Brazil's fans
and media have accused of abandoning ``the beautiful game'' for
defense and individualism. And there is always tremendous
expectation and pressure on a defending champion in the opening of
the World Cup, especially when that champion is Brazil, where the
passion for the game is overwhelming and perhaps irrational.
</P>
<P>
   So, few people will be satisfied with Wednesday's outcome, but
that is beside the point. Brazil won its first match, which
Argentina could not do against Cameroon in 1990 and which Germany
struggled to accomplish against Bolivia in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   With 3 points in the standings, Brazil can now relax for a few
days and perhaps even look ahead to the next round after upcoming
group matches against Morocco and Norway. Those teams played
Wednesday night in Montpellier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult but a big satisfaction,'' said Zagallo,
66, who has been a coach or player on all four of Brazil's World
Cup championship teams. ``This was very important win because it
was the first match of the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The deciding goal came in the 73d minute, three minutes after
Zagallo had benched his subdued forward, Bebeto, and enlivened his
team with the open play of Denilson.
</P>
<P>
   Cafu, the Brazilian defender, slashed into the penalty area and
Dunga chipped a perfect pass to his feet. Cafu tried to lift the
ball over the Scottish goalkeeper, Jim Leighton, who at 40 is the
oldest player in the tournament, but the ball bounced off
Leighton's face toward his teammate Tommy Boyd. Scrambling to help,
Boyd could not prevent the rebound from bouncing off his shoulder
into the goal. Incredulous, and a little lucky, Cafu did a flip in
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's first goal, in the fifth minute, was also unorthodox.
Bebeto aimed a corner kick toward the goal and midfielder Cesar
Sampaio timed his jump, only to have Scotland's Craig Burley put a
hand on his shoulder and shove him in the back. Sampaio was thrown
off slightly, but the ball richocheted off his right shoulder past
a stunned Leighton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no denying the better team won, but we had a great
chance not to lose,'' said Craig Brown, Scotland's coach. ``We gave
away two very bad goals from a technical point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Scotland had positioned itself for a welcomed 1-1 tie after
Sampaio committed a foolish foul on Scottish striker Kevin
Gallacher in the 38th minute, shoving him down in the penalty area
and drawing a yellow card. John Collins took the penalty kick and
slammed a low blast inside the left post, past the dive of
Taffarel, the Brazilian goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Brown sandwiched seven players into the penalty box area in the
second half, determined not to give Ronaldo any room to operate.
Not that he needed any. The 21-year-old Brazilian forward is
considered the world's best player and his talents _ at least all
but goal scoring _ were on full display Wednesday. Every time he
touched the ball or raced toward the goal, the 80,000-seat Stade de
France throbbed with anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo did not disappoint here in the northern Paris suburbs.
In the first half, he dribbled his way through three Scottish
defenders in the penalty area, like a slalom skier going through
gates, and fired a wicked line drive that Leighton saved with a
desperate lunge.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The game was flawed but always entertaining, as was the
beautifully inscrutable opening ceremony that has become de rigeur
for the French since the Fellini-esque opening to the 1992 Winter
Olympics in Albertville, France. Ladybugs entered on stilts and
bounded on trampolines while giant flowers budded from a canvas
lawn in what appeared to be the world's most extravagant tribute to
cross-pollination. Trapeze artists rapelled from the roof of the
futuristic stadium, bearing flags of the 32 teams competing in the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Brazilian fans in their gold and green shirts, and
Scottish fans in their tartan kilts and red wigs, mingled
peacefully before the match; if there was no common language,
alcohol provided a common purpose. Jimmy McKay, an actuary from
Chicago, said his wife let him travel to Europe once a year to
watch Scotland play soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a condition of our marriage,'' McKay said. ``She's from
Kentucky. She doesn't like football. She doesn't like the state I
get into, the state of alcoholic refreshment.''
</P>
<P>
   Said John Irvine of Glasgow: ``If we win, the Eiffel Tower will
be wearing a kilt.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil fans seemed to think that, no matter Wednesday's outcome,
this team would not repeat as World Cup champions. ``They don't
play Brazil's kind of football,'' said Helio Souza of Sao Paulo,
where the Stock Exchange was closed for Wednesday match. ``Zagallo
likes defense too much. He doesn't take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be much debate about who should start at forward next
against Morocco _ the ineffective Bebeto, the magical Denilson or
the volatile Edmundo. But that is a turmoil for another day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to have a win,'' Ronaldo said. ``The first match is
always the most difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
