<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CATSKILLS-COMIC-AR     06-10 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CATSKILLS-COMIC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUMULT OVER WHO IS KING OF `SIMON SAYS' GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two things irk Allan Tresser, the 77-year-old ``tummler'' who
has been entertaining hotel guests in the Catskills for nearly 60
years and the self-proclaimed king of Simon Says.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that the management of the Fallsview Hotel in
Ellenville, N.Y., where Tresser roams the lobby in his shades, a
stained, blue track suit and a thick gold ``Simon Sez'' necklace,
has decided Tresser can no longer do the warm-ups for the stage
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The other is the parade of guests who confuse Tresser with his
ancient bete noire, Lou Goldstein, interrupting Tresser even when
he's in the middle of a very important conversation to ask if he's
the guy who led them in Simon Says 30 years ago at Grossinger's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou Goldstein,'' Tresser says shortly, grudging the time it
takes to wrap his mouth around the name.
</P>
<P>
   Then, to the reporter: ``No, don't write it down, I don't want
to give him any publicity. I hate that guy. You know what Lou
Goldstein was before he was at Grossinger's? A basketball player at
Long Island University or someplace. A good ball-player. But never
an entertainer.''
</P>
<P>
   We're indoors, Tresser _ what's with the sunglasses?
</P>
<P>
   Tresser removes them briefly, showing red-rimmed eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My eyes are burned out from the spotlights,'' Tresser says.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the summers of the '40s and '50s, when hundreds of
small hotels dotted the Catskills Mountains and the tummler, whose
name means ``the maker of noise and merriment,'' led the summer
guests in games, often ending a set with that perennial mountain
favorite, jumping into the pool fully clothed.
</P>
<P>
   Tresser, who leads a one-hour game of Simon Says at the
Fallsview, now takes a break for guests to take their
nitroglycerine pills.
</P>
<P>
   The years have also taken their toll on Tresser. Twice divorced,
he now lives in a small room at the Fallsview.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might as well move into the hotel,'' Tresser's last wife
said, before departing. ``You're in love with the hotel, raise the
hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Tresser was a Lower East Side guy who went to the Catskills, as
a musician, in 1936. He can't take credit for inventing Simon Says,
Tresser says _ it's an old English game _ but he did make it famous
in the Borscht Belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing Sam Fisher's Plaza in Mountaindale _ there was a
man doing Simon Says, but it had no end,'' Tresser says.
</P>
<P>
   How can there be no end to Simon Says? If you do something Simon
doesn't tell you to do, you're out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way to put people out fast,'' explains Tresser.
``My game is based on reflexes. I played in it every hotel in the
mountains. In '42, I go into the service. I get out in '45, five or
six guys have been doing it. I have to start from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   Tresser did a Simon Says act with blue jays. He did Simon Says
on the Mike Douglas Show in 1968, eliminating the participants so
fast, he claims, that Mike Douglas himself had to play for eight
minutes to fill the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, the management of this hotel offers $10,000 to
any competitor I can't put out in a three-minute period,'' Tresser
says.
</P>
<P>
   Management clarifies this later.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such guarantee,'' says Charles Slutsky, the
managing director of the Fallsview. ``I've threatened Allan's life
numerous times for saying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tresser's telling of his life story omits this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, I wanted to have a show,'' Tresser says. ``Me, Lou
Goldstein, Lee Berman from the Concord, just the three of us on
stage doing Simon Says. Just let me go first. Nobody would do it.
Why? Because if I go on first, they can't go on. Because nobody
will be left standing. I'm that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Where is Berman these days?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead,'' says Tresser.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein?
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in a little place in Liberty, I think,'' Tresser says.
``I had lunch with him six months ago. I loaned him $200. The check
bounced. You know, when he did Simon Says, he wouldn't let little
kids play. What kind of a man does that?''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, now 70, is indeed living a half-hour away, in
Liberty, N.Y. Hearing the name ``Allan Tresser,'' he comes close to
hanging up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested,'' Goldstein says. ``I hope I don't sound
bitter, but the man is an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein is willing, however, to discuss his current
circumstances, which are not as dire as Tresser suggests. Goldstein
does Simon Says at the Raleigh Hotel and at halftimes of National
Basketball Association games. Goldstein did not lunch recently with
Tresser.
</P>
<P>
   Tresser's claim that he is the king of Simon Says?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I don't want to discuss him _ the man doesn't know
what he's talking about,'' Goldstein says. ``I came to Grossinger's
in 1950 to play basketball; Abe Sharkey, who worked at
Grossinger's, told me he started doing it in 1936. It was strictly
a Catskills thing. Nobody knew about the game outside the Catskills
until I went on national TV in 1960 and I popularized it.''
</P>
<P>
   The charge that Goldstein does not allow children in his game?
</P>
<P>
   A long silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God, '' Goldstein says, aggrieved and disgusted. ``You
don't take a game that is played by kids _ look, I do the Simon
Says Championship for Kids three times a year at the Concord. I did
it on a kid show called `Wonderama.' You ever hear of
`Wonderama'?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1647EDT &QL; 
