<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WORLD'S TEAM KICKS OFF WORLD CUP  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST.-DENIS, France _ The No. 13 metro train was bobbing up and
down from the sheer brute rhythm of hundreds of Scots jumping in
place, singing utterly salacious lyrics to familiar tunes. You
wouldn't believe what they did to Ronaldo to the tune of ``Walking
in a Winter Wonderland.''
</P>
<P>
   What was amazing was that along with their blue wigs and painted
faces and tartan kilts, many of the Scots wore something yellow _
something Brazilian. They could chant crude ditties about their
opponent, but they wore Brazil's colors all the same.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is soccer, the heart, the soul, the flashing feet,
whether in the era of Pele and Garrincha, the era of Socrates and
Zico, the era of Romario and Bebeto, or now, the era of Ronaldo
There was a highly unofficial all-time soccer team named the other
day, and although the organizers aimed for political correctness,
to give many nations a touch of action, there were four Brazilians
among the top 11. Sounds about right.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians were back in the World Cup Wednesday, with exotic
flicks with their insteps, sudden 90-degree swerves, nifty passes
that made the crowd gasp. They forced one goal with a shoulder and
one goal off an opponent for a 2-1 victory in the opening game.
</P>
<P>
   Their fans don't seem to take the metro. One could imagine them
in their familiar swarm, dancing the samba, hundreds of them,
shimmering and strutting, from the center of Paris _ boom,
gaga-boom, gaga-boom _ all the way to the new stadium. If they had
taken the metro, it would have swayed back and forth. Brazil has
the beat.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Mario Zagallo _ who has been a part of all four
Brazilian World Cup championships as player or assistant coach _
needed a jump start in a 1-1 tie. Romario, the star of 1994, was
home with premature old age. Bebeto was on the field, but
ineffective. The crowd chanted for Edmundo and it got Leonardo at
the half, then Denilson. What a sense of richness, what national
treasures Brazil has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have put in Edmundo, but that would have strengthened
our inside game,'' Zagallo would say later. ``Instead, I wanted an
open game. That was the correct move.''
</P>
<P>
   Denilson entered in the 70th minute and started dancing with the
ball like a street entertainer working for the coins of the crowd.
He would do anything to please, a feint here, a dash there, maybe
even a pass. He opened up the game so suddenly that Brazil scored
on an own goal by the hapless defender, Tommy Boyd, only 3 minutes
later. And the stands went boom, gaga-boom, gaga-boom.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil brings that beat to the World Cup. The people from
MasterCard asked a panel of soccer experts to pick the mythical
all-time 11: Lev Yashin, the late Soviet goalkeeper; Franz
Beckenbauer of West Germany, the late Bobby Moore of England, Johan
Cruyff of the Netherlands, Alfredo diStefano of Argentina, Michel
Platini of France, and Diego Maradona of Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the Brazilians _ Carlos Alberto, Nilton Santos,
Pele and the late Garrincha, the star of the 1958 and 1962 World
Cups, who died young and destitute from his excesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with him, I lived with him, he was the godfather of
my daughter,'' said Nilton Santos, now 73. ``Every Jan. 20, I light
a candle for him. People think of what he did with the Brazilian
national team but they forget what he did for his club. He was
fantastic, as a player and as a person, and he never hurt
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony included old videos of all these stalwarts _
remarkably limber and inventive, wide open, before the defensive
technicians arranged chains and bolts and nets and clamps to slow
down the world's offense.
</P>
<P>
   The four old lions (the three Brazilians and diStefano) who
attended the press conference on Tuesday seemed to love their game
with a personal passion that exceeds the way old American athletes
talk about their sports. And they lamented the defensive tactics of
today, however inevitable they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the coaches want to be the star,'' Pele said. ``In my
time, the star was the player. Today, strategy is more important
than the game. That is a problem today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians were not entirely delighted when Carlos Alberto
Parreira won in 1994 by playing brusque efficient soccer. The fans
today mutter when Zagallo talks about curbing the Brazilian flair.
But when the crowd gets edgy, and Brazil needs a life, there is
always a Leonardo, there is always a Denilson, and the beat goes
on, boom, gaga-boom, gaga-boom. Even Scots wear yellow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
