<HEADLINE>
STATES EXPLORE ALTERNATIVES TO FEDERAL DISASTER RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE HUREWITZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As officials in upstate New York anxiously await
a decision on whether federal aid will be available for areas
damaged by recent severe weather, Congress is pushing to shift more
of the financial burden to local governments, according to
emergency administrators around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Several states, including California, Florida and Vermont, have
created rainy-day disaster funds to augment federal aid and upgrade
emergency preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Congress is telling the states,'' said Fred Koutnik, a
top Florida emergency-management administrator, ``is we are no
longer going to fund these horrendous, spiraling upwards costs of
disasters. And they are looking to us guys _ New York,
Pennsylvania, Florida, Texas and California as the bad guys. We
gobble up most of the presidential funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Special federal funds flow to states when the president
determines that a disaster is beyond the resources of state and
local governments. The decision is based on data compiled by the
Federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are still assessing whether the five counties in New
York hit hardest by last week's destructive storms are eligible for
disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   Since the summer of 1995, New York has had six presidential
disasters declared, according to Dennis Michalski of the State
Emergency Management Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hot issue between the states and federal government
at this point,'' said David Rodham, undersecretary of public safety
for the Commonwealth of Massachusetts and past president of the
National Emergency Management Association.
</P>
<P>
   James Lee Witt, director of the FEMA, has urged states to
establish rainy-day funds, spokesman Barbara Yagerman said.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for New York Gov. George Pataki said the
governor is confident that New York's current approach is
satisfactory. The state finances disaster relief from its general
fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think under Gov. Pataki's direction, we demonstrated that
the state has been effective in meeting the needs of victims of
several disasters _ from the Long Island wildfires, to the ice
storms, and more recently, the tornadoes,'' said Pataki spokesman
Patrick McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering five presidential disasters in three years, the
Vermont Legislature earlier this year approved an emergency
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally don't think states across the country are going
to get presidential-declared disasters as easily as they have in
the past,'' said George L. Lowe, director of Vermont Emergency
Management. ``Can you imagine what you would do if you had a major
event and the feds didn't come. That could happen over in Albany or
here in Montpelier. It sounds hokey, but you've got to be
prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Massachusetts and South Carolina are weighing measures that
would establish a so-called rainy-day fund. Rodham said the
approach is prudent because it budgets for the unexpected and
doesn't require the legislators to return for a special session to
approve supplemental financing.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for passage in both states is uncertain. But the
proposals generally founder in state legislators because of
controversy over how the reserve will be funded. Often it is
through a surcharge on insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   That was the approach adopted by Florida, whose 1993 legislation
was perhaps the first of its kind in the country. It was approved
in the aftermath of the $25 billion in damages caused by Hurricane
Andrew, which hit Aug. 24, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Initially opposed by the insurance industry, it puts a $4
surcharge on every commercial policy and $2 for every private
insurance contract. This year it raised $16 million.
</P>
<P>
   Florida used 48 percent of the funds to enhance local emergency
management offices, 27 percent to finance projects that may limit
future storm damage and sets aside roughly 20 percent, or $4
million, to supplement FEMA aid.
</P>
<P>
   California used its emergency-relief fund to help the needy who
suffer disaster losses. It will augment by up to $10,000 the
$13,400 maximum that FEMA offers to individuals and families who
are uninsured and too poor a credit risk to qualify for the
low-interest loans that are made available when a federal disaster
is declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
