u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GAMES-E3-NYT &LR;      06-10 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GAMES-E3-NYT </SLUG>
  
 IN THE HEADLIGHTS: PDAs AND VIRTUAL PETS  
 (bl)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Georgia World Congress Center in Atlanta contains 35
football fields' worth of exhibition space. During the Electronic
Entertainment Expo in May, it contained the equivalent of 35
football fields filled with video games _ PC games, console games
and handheld games _ peripherals and accessories of all
descriptions, as well as thousands of developers, software
publishers, retailers, investors and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Crammed with 12-foot screens and massive speakers, looming
exhibition domes, lasers, showgirls and video game mayhem at every
turn, it's sheer heaven or sheer hell, depending on your
personality. But whether you wallow in the spectacle or run
screaming, E3 is a once-a-year chance to view the universe of
interactive entertainment and to see what's on the horizon for
Christmas and early '99. Here's a report from the trenches:
</P>
<P>
   GAME MACHINES _ No new ones this year. Sony and Nintendo are
sitting tight with their consoles. The PC standard for gaming has
stabilized with the Pentium II and a 3DFX graphics accelerator
card. That is a good thing for consumers and developers alike
because people get to catch their breath and concentrate on great
games instead of racing to catch up with the hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Sega is coming out with a new machine for Christmas 1999 that
promises the moon _ superfast graphics, multiplayer online games,
e-mail, chat, 3-D audio and a Windows CE operating system (and
breakfast in bed?) _ for less than $300, but for now, we are in the
eye of the technological hurricane. So content is king. Hallelujah.
</P>
<P>
   PERIPHERALS _ Stable platforms have brought dozens of accessory
manufacturers out of the woodwork. It is now possible to buy video
game controllers in every color of the rainbow and hundreds of
ergonomic configurations, like game pads, joysticks, headsets,
gloves and racing wheels. Force feedback _ a tactile sense of
explosions, body blows or the torque of a racetrack through a
controller _ is the cool technology du jour. All the new joysticks
are going to rumble, rattle and throb.
</P>
<P>
   More significant in the grand scheme is a new crop of video game
storage devices. Interact's Dex Drive, for instance, hooks into
your PC. Pop a Playstation or Nintendo memory card into the drive
and you can upload game saves, characters or sports rosters to your
computer, then e-mail the data or post it to a Web site. Anyone
else with a Dex Drive can download the information, plug it into a
console and play with your levels, characters or teams, modifying
them or mailing back new ones. At $40 (less than the cost of a
Nintendo game), this peripheral knits together the console, PC and
the Internet in an accessible way and could make game saves and
video game characters as tradable as baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   Along the same lines, the Sony PDA (personal digital assistant)
is a $30, key-chain-size device that plugs into the Playstation
like a memory card. After downloading game data, the PDA converts
into a portable gaming device. It has a calendar and a clock as
well as an infrared transmitter that lets you beam data _ words,
symbols and animations as well as game information _ across the
room to other PDAs. You can transfer secret moves, trade weapons,
play head to head and pass notes to your friends. This device will
no doubt be the bane of every schoolroom from Seattle to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BUILDING FOR THE LAITY _ It used to be that if you wanted
to build your own levels of a PC game, you had to be a programmer.
No more. A slew of computer games, particularly first-person
shooters, will include built-in point-and-click-level editors that
let you create your own versions of a game by importing geometric
shapes into a void and giving them qualities like size, weight,
hollowness, texture and lighting effects. It's the holodeck, more
or less.
</P>
<P>
   GT Interactive's Unreal and Sierra Studio's Half-Life are
standouts in this respect, allowing players to create their own
game worlds and distribute them on the Internet or play them on
line. Building these worlds becomes a game in itself _ perhaps a
more rewarding pastime than the original code (witness the
sprawling virtual community of amateur Doom designers).
</P>
<P>
   ARTIFICIAL LIFE _ Bad news for grown-ups: the virtual pet is not
a passing fad.
</P>
<P>
   Digital creatures are only getting stronger, more numerous and
more sophisticated. From monster-breeding combat games to
Cyberlife's sequel to Creatures, virtual vermin abound. Nintendo is
releasing its own menagerie this fall. They're called Pokemon (a
portmanteau word derived from ``pocket'' and ``monster''). They
live on your belt loop and come in 150 flavors, each with its own
plush doll counterpart. Tamagotchi meets Beanie Babies. Be very
afraid.
</P>
<P>
   THE S-WORD _ After Silicon Valley's disastrous first date with
Hollywood, synergy is back. Fox Interactive is trotting out a
series of showbiz titles _ Alien vs. Predator, an X-Files game, Die
Hard Interactive and the Simpsons' Virtual Springfield. Activision
is transforming ``The Fifth Element'' into a console game. GT
Interactive is bringing ``Beavis and Butt-head'' to the PC and the
Playstation. Acclaim is tackling ``South Park,'' and MGM is
animating James Bond in Tomorrow Never Dies. Movie-based games have
usually been stinkers, but this time around, developers have used
the silver screen as a springboard instead of a crutch. They're
finally getting it right. Chalk one up for the media empires.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCOTS! _ An economic development agency financed by the
Scottish government has determined that video games represent a new
engine for economic growth, so scores of computer science grads and
art school students are being funneled into interactive
entertainment. The result? A convention hall teeming with game
designers in kilts. Bagpipes on the concourse. Interactive
renditions of ``Braveheart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The object of the game is to become the king of Scotland,''
said Wai Ming Yuen, the Glaswegian producer of Tartan Armies, a
strategy game based on 13th-century clan warfare. ``And then you
get to invade England.''
</P>
<P>
   FEMALE PROTAGONISTS _ From Lara Croft to the trash-talking,
gunslinging truck-stop waitress in Panasonic's Space Bunnies Must
Die and the heroine of Square Soft's epic Parasite Eve, female game
characters are shooting first and asking questions later.
</P>
<P>
   As one game designer so eloquently put it, ``There's something
about a chick with a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Author's e-mail address: Herz(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
