</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BEDFORD-STREET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING THE MAYOR OF BEDFORD STREET TO STAY ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite Lawrence Selman's having, as he puts it,
``one of the last of the Brooklyn accents,'' his one wish in life
is to live and die at 106 Bedford St., in Greenwich Village in New
York. Selman lives there now, in a one-room apartment with his dog,
Happy, and his cats, Suzy and Lucky. He has lived there for 27
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If God wants me to live another 20 years, I'm going to stay
here, on Bedford Street,'' Selman, 56, said, sitting on the steep
short stoop of his friend Alice Elliot's house across the way at
107 Bedford St., one of a historic row of five Greek Revival
houses.
</P>
<P>
   If streets are veins, residents like Selman are their blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's community,'' said Selman, who rarely searches for the
right words _ they seem instead to find him. ``Other areas are not
a community. Neighbors aren't neighborly. Here, it's neighborly.''
</P>
<P>
   Selman has been called ``the mayor of Bedford Street'' by his
neighbors, who are creating a trust to keep him where he wants to
be _ and where they believe he belongs.
</P>
<P>
   Selman has a New Yorker's problems. He struggles with his rent.
He is often lonely. He also has problems of his own. He is
developmentally disabled. He receives monthly federal disability
payments, which are his income.
</P>
<P>
   Like a single-minded family, Selman's Bedford Street neighbors
and other members of the Bedford Barrow Commerce Block Association
are establishing a community trust, to be administered by
UJA-Federation of New York. By creating a fund that will dispense
payments for quality-of-life uses like clothing, meals, baseball
tickets and veterinary care for Selman's animals, the trust will
strengthen his ability to continue living independently in his own
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   A personal advocate, assigned by the trust to Selman for his
life, will also insure that he receives appropriate payments from
government programs.
</P>
<P>
   Morton Asch, the UJA-Federation senior development executive
working with the Bedford Street group, considers the neighbors'
coalition a precedent for the organization's trust program, which
was designed to assist family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest these folks have taken in this gentleman _ he's
got to be a very special guy,'' Asch said.
</P>
<P>
   He is. Selman knows his neighborhood. He is like a chamber of
commerce map that revises itself each day as he walks Happy.
</P>
<P>
   Selman knows the local businesses, from Lilac Chocolates on
Christopher Street, where he has been blacklisted from buying
chocolates because he is diabetic, to the Hudson Diner at the
corner of Grove Street, where he orders _ and recommends _ the
flounder.
</P>
<P>
   He sells raffle tickets and solicits prizes for the Bedford
Barrow Commerce Block Association street fair, which took place
last month and at which, as usual, Selman held informal court. Last
year, he was the largest individual solicitor of funds for muscular
dystrophy in the metropolitan area. At Christmas, he plays Santa.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany last week, Selman was introduced on the floor of the
state Assembly as part of the proceedings for passage of three
disability-related bills, and he was presented with a citation for
his service to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't meet Larry without him asking a question about you _
he's a curious, generous, outgoing person,'' said Ms. Elliot, who
is making a documentary film about Selman and who initiated the
trust effort. ``There are a lot of high-functioning people in our
neighborhood, with high-powered, challenging jobs. Here's a person
who can't work, who has an intuitive sense of community, and he
teaches us,'' Ms. Elliot said. ``That you have to know your
neighbors, that you ask questions about the little things in life:
`How's your dog?' `When's your daughter's birthday?' That those
seemingly trivial things build community.''
</P>
<P>
   However far from full adult mental development Selman may be,
experience has provided him an extreme kind of intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Selman was born weighing just over three pounds and was not
expected to live. An only child, he lived with his parents, Philip
and Minnie Selman, in Brooklyn until 1968, when both died, four
months apart, in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Selman had a nervous breakdown. He was hospitalized for two
months. On his release, he lived briefly in a small Brooklyn
apartment he rented, and then, at the suggestion of a neighbor, he
moved to Coney Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like jumping from the pan into the fire,'' Selman said.
``The landlord took advantage of me. People see they can take
advantage _ they do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Selman's closest surviving relative, an uncle, Murray Schaul,
found him an apartment, near his own, at 106 Bedford St.
</P>
<P>
   Because of what his neighbors agree is the force of Selman's
personality, he has forged a bond with the neighborhood that has
fostered a two-sided adoption.
</P>
<P>
   By arrangement with his neighbors in the five historic houses,
Selman superintends the buildings, organizing recycling bins and
garbage removal on appropriate days. With the help of Schaul, who
brings him meals three times a week, he keeps the street swept and
cleans the debris from the parties that descend on Greenwich
Village each weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look after the houses, to make sure they're OK,'' Selman
said. ``If I see people who don't belong here, I try to chase them
off, but they give me lip,'' he added. In exchange, those in the
five houses and members of the block association beyond have
provided him services as friends and professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Lanes, a radiologist who moved into 115 Bedford St. last
year with his wife, Susan Wyland, an executive for the online
division of Walt Disney, helps Selman check his blood sugar once a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Dill, an artist who lives at 88 Bedford St., accompanies
Selman to a dental clinic, ``to give him moral support,'' she said.
She put drops in his ear when he had an ear infection.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Steele, at 48 Commerce St., takes in baseball games with
Selman from seats between home plate and third base at Shea
Stadium, where Selman can keep an eye on the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an incredible Mets fan,'' Steele said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to 15 or 16 games,'' Selman said. ``In the loge, but I
get the cheap seats. I know the guys at Shea, Pat and Al.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight months ago, Ms. Elliot realized that the neighborhood's
relationship with Selman had deepened into responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murray is aging,'' Ms. Elliot said of Selman's uncle, who is
82. ``I realized how much Larry depended on Murray.''
</P>
<P>
   The trust, to be made final on June 24 at a block association
meeting, is to be used as needed when Selman's uncle can no longer
help care for him. A $25,000 minimum balance to establish the trust
must be met with pledges, many of which have already been made;
$5,000 has been raised for the assignment of an advocate for
Selman.
</P>
<P>
   If concern for Selman has galvanized the community, his life is
something that sits at the center of every village _ a lightning
rod, that has attracted both good and bad, in bright flashes. Grief
and charity have been just two bolts in the sky. When he was 18, he
and his father were called out as air wardens to control the crowds
that mobbed the scene when a TWA flight from Ohio collided in
midair with a United Airlines jet that fell in Brooklyn, killing
128 on board and 6 on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   At 26, released to the frightening company of neighbors after
his hospitalization, Selman rode all night with the Fire Department
because he didn't want to go home.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 40, his best friend, a neighbor on Bedford Street,
was stabbed to death in her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend Peggy lived across the street, and she looked after
me,'' Selman recalled. ``But she got murdered. They took me in for
questioning, because I had a key,'' he said. He looked after her
houseplants.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Selman's Bedford Street neighbors find themselves part of
his story, which is taking another turn, like a wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're trying to do is pay back,'' Steele said. ``We all
live and work next to each other. But most of us don't reach out
the way he does. He's kind of the glue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about the Midwest,'' Sally Dill said on the subject
of small-town values. ``Well, I lived 51 years in the Midwest and
I've never seen anything like this. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
