<SLUG> BC-TROMPE-L'OEIL-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITTY TROMPE L'OEIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By MARIANNE ROHRLICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A smile. It's the only possible response to trompe
l'oeil designs and photo images on shower curtains, bed sheets,
even end tables. The designs are contemporary sisters to those by
Piero Fornasetti, the Milanese decorative master of trompe l'oeil.
</P>
<P>
   Renewed interest in his work (which peaked in the 1950s) was
apparent at the May 16 auction of 203 of his designs at Christie's
in Los Angeles; the bureaus, dinner plates, magazine racks and
hand-painted bathroom fixtures sold for record-breaking prices _
sometimes five times the estimates. Fornasetti transferred
engravings that tricked the eye and tickled the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary versions of the technique include the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ A moss-green cotton velvet pillow cover is patterned with a
hand-screened photo image of a sunflower by Jan Milne of Glasgow.
The down-filled cushion, 20 inches square, reverses to silk; $225
in several colors at Salon Moderne, 281 Lafayette St. (Prince
Street).
</P>
<P>
   _ Phototransparencies of rocks form a translucent surface for a
nest of blackened-steel-legged tables by the photographer Amanda
Weil. The limited-edition tables can also be ordered with images
like flowers or water. The nest of three tables, the largest 17
inches square, is $2,000 from Weil Studio, 34 Renwick St. (Spring
Street).
</P>
<P>
   _ Weatherproof lampshades on a string of lights with photos of
leaves are $45 from Smith &AMP; Hawken, (800) 776-3336.
</P>
<P>
   _ Images on Bloom pillowcases, shams and duvet covers were
adapted from old botanical engravings. The 300-thread-count fabric,
by Bonjour of Switzerland, is 100 percent cotton sateen. A pair of
pillowcases is $150, a duvet cover that reverses to a solid-color
sateen is $300 for a twin, $350 for a full/queen and $400 for a
king. To order from Harris Levy, 278 Grand St. (Eldridge Street).
</P>
<P>
   _ A cork-backed place mat with a photograph of artichokes is $24
at Ad Hoc Softwares, 410 West Broadway (Spring Street).
</P>
<P>
   _ An 8-inch drum-style shade of ``Little Lamp'' is a
phototransparency of dogwood blossoms. A 20-inch-tall table lamp
with shade (also available in rocks, pears or fern leaves) is $300
from Weil Studio.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Meadow,'' a plastic shower curtain by Waterware, looks like
a lush green lawn but never needs mowing; $24.99 at Bed, Bath and
Beyond, (800) 462-3966.
</P>
<P>
   _ The lavender cotton velvet slipcover on a slipper chair has a
photographic image of a daisy on its seat and back. Ms. Milne's
fabric can be ordered in other colors and with other flowers like
lilies and tulips. The slipcovered chair is $1,850 at Salon
Moderne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
