A3226 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-JAVA-NYT &LR;      06-10 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-JAVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGUAGE CALLED JAVA TRANSCENDS BARRIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JIM MCMANUS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a familiar name with many meanings: an ancient kingdom in
what is now Indonesia, slang for a cup of coffee and one of the
most important developments in the short life span of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Java, a programming language for applications used on networks,
is being heralded, at least by Scott McNealy, chairman of Sun
Microsystems, which developed and licenses Java as the next great
thing, ready to change the nature of computing.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is quite so optimistic, but Java's growth and
success so far is clear. Created in 1991 by James Gosling and his
associates at Sun Microsystems, Java (originally called Oak, after
a tree outside Gosling's window) began as part of an effort to make
a consumer-oriented home control unit (a device to start the coffee
in the morning, regulate the temperature in the house, operate the
VCR, etc.). The device never took off, but the ascendance of the
Internet three years later opened unforeseen channels for Sun's new
language.
</P>
<P>
   Most often associated with the whirring and spinning elements on
a favorite Web page, Java has uses far beyond that. It has become
ubiquitous to the point that its name is no longer just a noun but
also an adjective used to describe all sorts of devices, virtual
and physical, McNealy said at a recent conference at Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes Java from other major programming languages
is that applications, or programs, written in Java can run on any
computer operating system, be it Windows, Mac OS or Unix.
Applications written in Java are some of the most advanced ways to
take advantage of computer networks. The Java programming on your
computer goes out to the Internet to retrieve bits of computer code
from other computers to do specific tasks. Applications of the new
language range from the grand (Home Depot uses Java-based
applications to track inventory across its 560 stores) to the minor
(the various flashing advertisements on innumerable Web pages are
small programs written in Java known as applets). And as networks
become more sophisticated and allow more data to be carried more
quickly, Java-related applications will become more commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, reliance on a network does have its limitations.
As Rob Currie, vice president of engineering at Marimba, a company
that develops business applications using Java-based programming,
said, ``When you're connected, great,'' but when you're not, ``then
you really want the whole program there with you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3231 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MATH-GAMES-2TAKES     06-10 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MATH-GAMES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMES ADD FUN TO SUMMER MATH PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (jt)  
 By ALICE KEIM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As summer approaches and the school year ends, my students are
anticipating their time away from school. While they may miss their
friends, it would be rare for any child to spend the summer months
dreaming about math class.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean that the next three months need to be devoid
of academics. A little practice during the break can make next year
easier. Educational computer programs are a good way to integrate
academics into your child's summer, especially during rainy days
and quiet times. Math programs are a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   My own students, in the third through sixth grades, are as
likely to play a well-designed math game during their free time in
school as they are a nonacademic program. As long as the program is
fun, children do not think of it as just work. And with more and
more quality software available, parents can make sure that their
children's computer time is active brain time.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of considerations when looking for software
for your child, but there are no strict rules. Most math software,
for example, presents questions a child must answer correctly to
advance in the program. But it is the program's design and bells
and whistles that will decide whether a child plays the game in the
first place. The most important thing is whether your child enjoys
the program. Is the format appealing? Is your child engaged with
the characters? Are the games engaging?
</P>
<P>
   Education researchers who have studied software have found that
young children (through third grade) tend to respond better to
programs that use women's voices, that students usually prefer
characters they can relate to and that a program should take into
account children's attention spans. In addition, experts know that
programs should encourage children, even when they make mistakes.
We also know that children benefit from repetition of instruction
and rules; if something is spoken in the program, it should also
appear in writing to reinforce the concept.
</P>
<P>
   I have encountered these guidelines as part of my academic
studies, but my classroom teaching experience has provided me with
real insights. When I first looked at Math Munchers, for example, I
thought that students would lose interest because of the lack of
diverse activities. I also thought the commercial-break spoofs
would annoy my fourth- through sixth-grade students and entertain
the younger ones. I was wrong on most counts. My older students
laughed at the commercials. The pop-culture references hit a chord
with them. The program's repetitive assignments did not bother them
because the math tests became progressively more demanding. And to
my surprise, the younger students did not take to Math Munchers at
all. The pop-culture references were over their heads. They did not
like the fast-paced game atmosphere, preferring the softer
environment of a program like Math Splash.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, too, that while some of these programs are very good
at reinforcing math skills learned elsewhere, few, if any, teach
new skills. If a program claims, as Number Maze does, that by using
the program ``whole-number math skills are learned and practiced,''
it is fair to be somewhat suspicious of the first claim. These
programs provide an outlet and environment to practice skills but
they are not a substitute for traditional education.
</P>
<P>
   The four programs reviewed here reach a balance between
entertaining and reinforcing math skills. That combination, if done
right, can keep a child's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Solving the Maze Challenge
</P>
<P>
   NUMBER MAZE CHALLENGE
</P>
<P>
   (Great Wave Software; $49.95; Windows 3.1 and 95, Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   NUMBER MAZE CHALLENGE is the newest version of the classic
Number Maze program from Great Wave Software. It does a remarkable
job of providing a fun and rather enthralling environment for
students to practice their skills and an impressive range of math
problems for different ages. But even though Great Wave recommends
this program for children 5 to 12 years old, the presentation of
Number Maze does not always get more sophisticated as the questions
get harder.
</P>
<P>
   Users make their way through mazes by solving math problems. At
certain junctures, students have the opportunity to solve problems
that allow them to pick up keys or books that open locked doors and
permit them to keep moving through the maze. The program lets
students choose how to navigate through the mazes, using a
two-dimensional or three-dimensional map.
</P>
<P>
   Number Maze is essentially a drill program enhanced with clever
graphics, but it does offer limited mathematical instruction. As
each new concept is introduced, a tutorial explains the method of
calculation. An animated character narrates an explanation and
graphics illustrate the problem. The graphics help explain the
function but may require an adult's assistance to be understood.
The tutorials are only spoken, not spoken and written, so they may
prove difficult for early learners.
</P>
<P>
   Great Wave says its maze can be customized for children in
kindergarten through sixth grade, but I found that some aspects of
the presentation would have a narrower appeal. The math levels
covered, however, roughly correspond to these grade and skill
levels. Unfortunately, the instructions and tutorials, which tend
to be repetitive and didactic, cannot be bypassed and are likely to
discourage older users.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of finishing the maze, however, should keep upper
elementary and early middle school students hooked. My students
loved the graphics of this program, but younger students, through
second grade, found that they ended up bumping into a lot of walls
while trying to reach a maze opening. The higher-level math
problems require long division and some complex word problems that
even some adults may find a challenge. Older children will also
enjoy the ability to choose three levels of intricacy for each
maze.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the many options that customize the maze and math
levels, Number Maze provides good assessment and tracking tools.
These allow you to evaluate both the degree of difficulty completed
and the areas where practice is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Number Play for the Young
</P>
<P>
   STICKYBEAR'S MATH SPLASH (Optimum Resource; $59.95; Windows 3.1
and 95, Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   For young math students, even preschoolers, it does not get much
more fun than this. Sticky-bear's Math Splash offers primary
students several exciting game and adventure areas to practice
their skills.
</P>
<P>
   The program's principal character is Bumper, an animated brown
bear who is spending the day at a water park with his family.
Bumper has four places to explore, each offering math challenges.
In one game, a pirate bear sits on a ship, ready to be dunked by
the player. As the student solves each group of problems, the
reward is a cannonball. Once the student has collected five balls,
it is time to shoot them at a swinging pendulum. If the child hits
the target, the pirate bear is dunked.
</P>
<P>
   In another activity area, the user enters a submarine. Sea
creatures swim by the submarine's window, offering answers to the
math question on the screen. The student earns points by choosing
the right answer.
</P>
<P>
   Each correct answer also earns the child a verbal pat on the
back from the characters. Comments like ``You're a brainiac''
brought repeated smiles to my third graders' faces. Incorrect
answers are accompanied by positive encouragement and the correct
answer. Children are not, however, given second chances.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
