<HEADER>
A3236 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MATH-GAMES-2NDTAK     06-10 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MATH-GAMES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: second chances.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For kids who love carnivals and fairs, the Rapid Fire section is
a friendly place (despite the name) to practice math. The user
picks one of several water pistols shaped like a shark's mouth.
Instead of pulling the trigger, the user answers math questions to
shoot through to the finish line. There are other sharks in the
race, so winning is not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The areas that include shooting resemble carnival games and are
not violent. Each activity environment contains many hidden treats
and secrets. For example, if you click on the pelican sitting to
the side of the boat in Overboard, it will try to catch a flying
fish.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher recommends this program for children 5 to 10. That
seems fairly accurate although some preschool children may also
enjoy this program, depending on their math skills. The younger
players would especially benefit from having an adult play with
them. While the math levels are appropriate for children at various
levels, the characters and activities may grow tiresome for upper
elementary students. I found that this program appealed more to my
younger students, particularly the girls. The program ``makes math
fun and lets me think and stuff,'' one of my third-graders said.
</P>
<P>
   Math Drills That Imitate Video Games
</P>
<P>
   MATH MUNCHERS DELUXE
</P>
<P>
   (The Learning Co.; sold as part of Mega Munchers package,
$39.95; Windows 3.1 and 95, Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   Math Munchers Deluxe is a program for the child raised on MTV
and arcade games. An animated green monster called the Muncher is
drawn into a television screen at the beginning of a fictional game
show. The student player is challenged to help him answer the
questions on a game-show number board. When the student completes
each board, the Muncher rejoices and moves to a harder screen.
</P>
<P>
   The program, designed for children in grades two through six,
allows a child to practice specific math skills. For example, one
area, recommended for sixth graders, reinforces the idea of prime
numbers. Two on-screen potato-head announcers give the
instructions, ``Say, can you munch those primes?'' Different
numbers are on each of the board's 20 squares as the student moves
the Muncher to all the squares with prime numbers.
</P>
<P>
   While completing this essentially simple task, the student must
also avoid the menacing Troggle characters, which come in various
forms, like a flying spider and a walking piece of toast. If your
child answers incorrectly or is eaten too many times, the game
ends. After three screens are cleared, there is a Muncher
commercial (which can be skipped) to offer a break.
</P>
<P>
   While this is the simplest of the programs reviewed, my students
love this game, even though the younger children seem to play for
only short periods. One of my early elementary students said the
program was too easy and did not have enough different activities.
</P>
<P>
   The program provides an opportunity to practice skills already
taught. Parents can adjust the level of difficulty, as can most
children. Math Munchers Deluxe has the appeal of a video game while
relying on tried and true math drill techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Trolls Help Dress Up Math
</P>
<P>
   MATH BLASTER: AGES 6 TO 9
</P>
<P>
   (Davidson; $30; Windows 3.1 and 95, Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   Math Blaster is a favorite among kids, and no wonder. This
exciting program is essentially a space rescue adventure. The
heroes are Blasternaut and the Galactic Commander. The villain,
Gelator, also known as the Brain Drainer, has kidnapped Spot,
Blasternaut's droid friend. It is the student's job to help
Blasternaut and the Galactic Commander find three magic energy
crystals and use them to weaken the Brain Drainer's powers and
rescue Spot.
</P>
<P>
   Sound complicated? It is. There is a lot to keep track of: evil
trolls to be conquered, crystals to win and math problems to solve.
The problems appear in gooey drips from the roof of a cave, in
space pods, in a giant generator and in the control panel inside a
space ship.
</P>
<P>
   To conquer the enemy, the student must use clothespins,
pacifiers and banana peels. The details keep the game interesting
and exciting while simultaneously providing a slightly overwhelming
game environment.
</P>
<P>
   Math Blaster is very likely to become addictive once the child
has learned when to use the mouse, keyboard and arrows to direct
the game. The main character, Blasternaut, is childlike and easy to
relate to. The game progresses at a fast pace, keeping the child
involved and interested. At each level, there is voice instruction
and a help menu, but parents are more likely to understand the help
offered. Progress reports can be printed, creating a clear sense of
progress at every level.
</P>
<P>
   The game presents a diverse set of math skills to be practiced.
There is also some room for parental control of the different
difficulty levels and subjects. And a Math Tips component provides
a number line and number grid to help solve and understand
problems. While this section is likely to be confusing to young
children, parents and teachers can use it to explain mathematical
concepts. They can even import their own data for problems if they
feel ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   This Math Blaster program is recommended for ages 6 to 9 (Math
Blaster is also available for ages 9 to 12). The program is
entertaining and enticing, providing an excellent environment for
practice, but I would strongly encourage adults to help explain the
game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
