<HEADER>
A3238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARLEM-SHOWHOUSE-ART-     06-10 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-SHOWHOUSE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPIRIT OF IMPROVISATION LIVES IN HARLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As every voyeur clutching a ticket and a dream knows,
designer show houses are typically celebrations of the perfection
that money can buy. More often than not in these open-to-the-public
alliances of charity fund-raising and design-industry public
relations, sumptuous taffetas shadow windows, kitchen cabinets
flaunt labor-intensive hand-painted finishes, and there is always a
room where the cost of one of the antiques would finance an Ivy
League education.
</P>
<P>
   So it came as a pleasant surprise last Friday night when the
Harlem United Show House opened its wood-and-glass front door to a
soundtrack of furious hammer blows and furniture being dragged into
position.
</P>
<P>
   Fastidious show house devotees might have deemed the evening's
gala party a bit premature, but the 24 designers, their friends,
clients and well-wishers gamely put a cheery spin on the chaos
around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little crazy about the situation, but we decided to
make it into a positive,'' said Joan Gibbs, an interior designer
whose entrance hall was an environmental album to African-American
creativity, from photographs by James Van Der Zee to 19th-century
furniture made by largely unrecognized black cabinetmakers who
worked in Louisiana, Missouri and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people who came had never seen a designer at
work,'' continued Ms. Gibbs, who admitted she would probably keep
tinkering with her space for a few more weeks. ``They had only ever
seen the finished product in a magazine. But this was something
different. It gave everyone an opportunity to ask questions about
how the painting was being done, things like that. It was a
wonderful experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Women clad in sequins and sky-high stilettos gingerly clutched
wobbling banisters as they climbed to the top of the four-story
Edwardian town house at 459 W. 141 St., between Convent and
Amsterdam Avenues. Dressed in black tie, their escorts brushed
plaster dust from their shoulders as Alma Nugent shrugged at the
electrical wires coiling around her feet and calmly explained what
her second-floor landing would eventually look like.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loose ends and atmosphere of resigned improvisation,
the Harlem United Show House, which runs through July 3, is a
revelation. Not only for its good natured jousting against the odds
_ after all, who knew it would take eight weeks to strip seven
layers of paint from all the woodwork and install new plumbing and
electrical systems _ but for the window it opens on New York City's
African-American design community.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two dozen participating interior and landscape designers,
all but two are black. And not one of them bears a name that would
be familiar to the readers of any of the leading American
interior-design publications.
</P>
<P>
   Spearheaded by Roderick Shade, a Manhattan designer who noted
that another organization's attempt to stage an African-American
show house last year fell apart over production difficulties, the
Harlem United Show House bills itself as America's first
African-American show house. It is not the last, however: two
others are scheduled to open this fall. In September, a benefit for
the United Negro College Fund will be staged in the opulent
Irvington-on-Hudson home of the turn-of-the-century beauty expert
Madame C.J. Walker, whose hair-straightening formula made her
America's first black millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   The Harlem show house, which benefits the Harlem United
Community AIDS Center, is located in another black landmark. Built
in 1906 for a white merchant, the four-story limestone and brick
town house was once the home of Charles Blackwell, a black dancer,
writer and stage manager whose credits included ``Sunday in the
Park With George'' and ``The Tap-Dance Kid.'' Blackwell's widow,
Frances, loaned part of the couple's collection of African statues
for use in the Harlem show house dining room, decorated by Gail
Green and Cheryl Flanagan.
</P>
<P>
   Those skeptics might question the wisdom of racially-focused
design expos like the Harlem United Show House, its participants
are comfortable with the distinction _ for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't doing this to segregate ourselves from the rest of
the design community but to make people aware that we are here,
that we have our own offices and companies,'' said Alma Nugent,
whose clients include the family of Reginald Lewis, the late
leveraged-buyout mogul who orchestrated the takeover of Beatrice
Foods, and Ron Sweeney, a senior vice president of Sony Music. ``We
don't want to be just black designers, but merely designers who
happen to be black.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that goal, however, has taken a a long time in the
white-dominated American design world. While designers and
architects from minority backgrounds have become celebrated in
recent years, like the Hispanic-Americans Vicente Wolf, Orlando
Diaz-Azcuy and Juan Montoya, precious few of their black
contemporaries have achieved wide national recognition.
</P>
<P>
   In the 26-year-history of the Kips Bay show house, for example,
only three black designers have ever been asked to participate:
Conchita Legendre, Rita Falkner and Robert S. Hart, said Kips Bay
chairman Harry Hinson. And only recently, thanks to the surge of
interest in Southern furniture of the 18th and 19th centuries,
spurred by studies at Colonial Williamsburg, have the contributions
of African-American craftsmen won the attention of scholars and
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to draw on a tradition that we're part of, too,''
said Joan Gibbs, who anchored the entrance hall with antiques
created by black craftsmen in the 1800s and then arranged to have
them reproduced for retail customers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the pieces are a humble ladder-back chair made by William
Kunze, a Missouri slave; a luxurious 1850s mahogany day bed from
the New Orleans workshop of Pierre-Charles Dutreuil Barjon, a
Haitian immigrant, and a sober American Empire oak side chair by
Thomas Day, a North Carolina cabinetmaker active in the 1870s.
Prices for Ms. Gibb's reproductions will range, she said, from
$1,500 for a Day side chair to $7,000 for a Barjon day bed with
oversize scroll feet.
</P>
<P>
   Black culture was an obvious springboard for the show house, but
many of the designers stretched the obvious into the universally
appealing. A hypnotic lava-like pattern of flowing orange and
brown, the mural that Selma Jackson and Brenda Brunson-Bay created
to wrap the four-story service stair took its inspiration from the
mud huts colorfully painted by the women of South Africa's Ndebele
tribe. ``It's not exact,'' said Ms. Brunson-Bay, whose
interpretation of the patterns seems to owe as much to Peter Max as
to traditional African art.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Black culture of a saucier sort led Wilbert Louis Shaw to
transform his second-floor space into a sincerely garish
super-affordable boudoir, whose second-hand chairs from Scotty's
New &AMP; Used Furniture are covered in cut-rate white bridal satin.
The sheer white curtains are trimmed with inexpensive tear-drop
crystals the size of half dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration, Shaw said, were Marie Antoinette-style
boiseries _ the fireplace is a scaled-down version of one at
Fontainebleau. ``I wanted to do a room to showcase an African
American associated with Europe,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Robeson came immediately to mind, but Shaw nixed that idea
as geographically inexact, not to mention politically
controversial. ``He's Russia, not France.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the designer settled on the expatriate black
chanteuse, Josephine Baker, whose joie-de-vivre proved a lot more
fun to channel. In honor of Baker's famously abbreviated
professional outfits, many nothing more than a feather
strategically placed, Shaw scattered his room with avian accents,
from an 1860s birdcage to crystal sconces shaped like ostrich
plumes. Even the air twittered, thanks to a cassette tape of Baker
singing cabaret tunes.
</P>
<P>
   The second-floor media room, a show house debut of Manhattan
designers Leyden Lewis and Catherine Kim, got the lion's ahre of
attention on opening night, thanks in part to its piece de
resistance: a Fuji plasma screen television, almost as thin as a
billfold (and given the price, not a bad comparison) suspended from
the ceiling by a horseshoe-shaped armature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work like this is bound to get them into Kips Bay,'' said Joan
Regenbogen, who hovered over the space like a proud mother hen, and
for good reason. A Manhattan decorator, she hired Lewis to be an
aide in her office, and was so impressed with his eye and comments
that she urged him to go to the Parsons School of Design. ``He's
got really innovative ideas,'' she said, pointing out that the
room's Constructivist-style patchwork walls were not covered in
grey suede, as many people assumed; they are actually sheathed in
Homosote, a pressed-paper soundproofing material, whose velvety
finish is the result of hand-sanding.
</P>
<P>
   Homosote's special properties came in handy. It effectively
blocked the sound of hammering coming from the kitchen and pantry
below, where representatives of the Design &AMP; Development Group, a
Manhattan firm directing the rooms' renovation were completing the
work of a pro bono contractor who pulled out of the project two
weeks before the show house was to open. A behind-the-scenes
glimpse was promising: a sleek and vaguely nautical chamber with
black granite counters and walls of burl chestnut.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvan Ebanks, a director of D&AMP;DG, described the design as ``a
coccoon'' _ an embracing phrase that was an apt metaphor for the
entire Harlem show house, from its chaotic birth to the hopes that
continues to buouy it to completion. Neighbors who see work being
done _ including one woman from an SRO _ come by to offer help, and
for every sponsor that turned them down, another has stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   Ebanks said that the kitchen would be unveiled Friday, six days
behind schedule, at a cost to the young company of $40,000. But if
it isn't, he and his workers _ indeed the entire show house staff _
can repair to Alma Nugent's meditation chamber on the second floor,
where dozens of votive candles and the peaceful sound of flowing
water await.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all this,'' Ms. Nugent said, ``what we need is a good
long rest.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Harlem United Show House is at 459 W. 141st St. (between
Convent and Amsterdam Avenues), around the corner from Hamilton
Grange _ Alexander Hamilton's home _ and City College. The show
runs through July 3. Tickets, $20 for adults, $10 for students, no
charge for children 13 and under, available at the house or through
Ticketmaster: (212) 307-7171. Hours: Saturday and Sunday, noon to 6
p.m., and Monday through Friday, 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. For information:
(212) 531-1300, extension 415.
</P>
</TEXT>
