<HEADLINE>
Q &AMP; A: SPEED LIMITS ON MODEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I own a 56 K modem. The manual says the highest speed that
the modem can legally attain is 53 kilobits per second because of
speed limits. What are these limits and why do they exist?
</P>
<P>
   A. The Federal Communications Commission does not explicitly set
a speed limit on how fast a modem can transmit data. But it does
regulate the power of the signal that such devices may transmit,
which in effect puts a limit on speed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The power limit of -12dBm _ in plainer language, about 63
microwatts _ for phone lines was set to prevent possible
interference or noise bleeding into adjacent lines and other
electrical devices. (Imagine trying to hold a quiet conversation
with someone at a party where everyone is when music is playing
loudly and people nearby are yelling.) At that upper limit, the
maximum attainable speed is about 53 K (kilobits per second). With
the maximum capacity of a telephone line being about 64 K, the FCC
wants to limit the noise within a safe, respectable limit to make
sure electronic devices in use do not conflict with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Although improvements to the technology are under development,
the 56 K boast has always been somewhat conditional. Unlike the
slower modems that came before them, the current 56 K models
operate at different speeds depending on whether the data is coming
toward you (being downloaded) or you are sending data from your
computer (uploading).
</P>
<P>
   Many modem companies claim the 56 K speed for downloading, but
uploading often tops out at 33.6 K or 28.8 K.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology by
postal mail to:
</P>
<P>
   Questions
</P>
<P>
   Circuits
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd Street
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036-3959
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to
</P>
<P>
   QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
