<HEADLINE>
SURVEY FINDS LITTLE HARM IN SURFING FOR CYBERSEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sex is definitely a hot topic on the Internet,
but the Web is not breeding a generation of sex addicts, according
to a new study by Stanford researcher Alvin Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cooper found, Web surfers are looking for a little
cybersex entertainment, and the anonymity of the Internet lets them
feel more comfortable exploring sexual topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like the Web is this irresistible sexual magnet,
where people who venture in are going to get trapped,'' he said.
``Most people use it for sexual purposes in a recreational way,''
much as they might watch ``Baywatch'' or flip through a Playboy
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper heads the Marital Services and Sexuality Center in San
Jose, Calif. He and his research team posted a 47-question survey
on the MSNBC Web site in April, asking people about their ``on-line
sexual behavior,'' what they look at and what they get out of it.
</P>
<P>
   The team was hoping to exceed the largest previous study, which
looked at 400 people, Cooper said. But it was overwhelmed by the
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 5,000 people responded during the first 24 hours,''
said Sylvain Boies, a clinical psychology fellow at Stanford
University who helped produce the study. The survey yielded 13,500
responses, of which 9,100 were deemed usable.
</P>
<P>
   Of the respondents to the poll, roughly 8 percent could be
qualified as cybersex compulsives, using sexual sites more than 10
hours a week and reporting that their use distressed them or
interfered with their relationships. Cooper said 3 percent to 6
percent of the general population engages in compulsive sexual
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex on the Internet is like alcohol,'' Cooper said. ``It's not
inherently good or bad, it's what you do with it. If you drink a
glass of wine a day, it might enhance your life. If you get sloppy
drunk every night, it's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper cited in his report statistics gathered by Relevant
Knowledge, a Web traffic-tracking company, that found 9.6 million
users, or 15 percent of all Web users, logged on to the 10 most
popular sexual sites in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty widespread phenomenon,'' Boies said.
</P>
<P>
   For people predisposed to sexual compulsivity, the accessibility
and anonymity of the Internet can make it easier to fall into
destructive behavior, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But those same traits of cyberspace may help people feel more
comfortable exploring erotic pursuits there. That may be why a
growing number of women are turning to sexy Internet sites, Cooper
speculated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the survey found that men seeking sex on the Internet
outnumber women five to one. And they're looking for different
things. Men went after pornographic pictures, while women joined
steamy ``chat rooms'' for hot talk.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers acknowledged that their respondents were
self-selected, not a random sample, and all were MSNBC users, whom
Cooper characterized as more professionally successful and affluent
than average Internet users. But because of the size of the survey,
he said, he believes it provides a valuable snapshot of people who
go on-line for sexual pursuits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3275 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHKOREA-INVEST-HNS     06-10 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHKOREA-INVEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT KIM MAKES SALES PITCH FOR INVESTMENT IN SOUTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ South Korean President Kim Dae-jung played
traveling salesman Wednesday, pitching his economically troubled
homeland as an ideal spot for American investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built one of the leading economies in the world in just
three decades, rising from the ruins of war,'' Kim said in an
address before a joint session of Congress. ``We have a proven
potential. We are resilient. But we now need your help.''
</P>
<P>
   In that speech and an earlier one before business executives at
a breakfast sponsored by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, Kim painted
a picture of a nation in transition.
</P>
<P>
   The old South Korea, built out of the devastation of the Korean
War that ended in stalemate in 1953, was governed by political
strongmen and their military allies. They fostered an economic
system centered around chaebols, huge family conglomerates built
with government-directed financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corruption prevailed,'' Kim told Congress. ``Imprudent
borrowing weakened our nation's banks and businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of South Korea's economy last year paved the way
for the December election of Kim, a pro-democracy dissident who had
spent six years in jail under the previous regimes.
</P>
<P>
   The new South Korea, he said, is committed to free elections,
representative government and free trade. Kim's government is
sending signals to North Korea that reconciliation is possible if
both sides take steps to achieve it. Under the old regime,
rapprochement was unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie B.C. Oh, professor of Korean studies at Georgetown
University here, said later that Kim ``wants to let the American
public, especially the business community, know the worst of
(South) Korea's economic troubles are over. These kinds of economic
reforms never would have occurred without cataclysmic economic
difficulties. So, in a way, the economic downturn is a shot in the
arm.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Chamber of Commerce, Kim ticked off structural changes
his government is promoting in South Korea's economy to make it
more attractive to foreign investment: Companies will be open to
hostile mergers and acquisitions, non-Koreans may buy and use land
in South Korea, the government is developing a ``one-stop'' service
center for investors, and South Korea is drafting a new law on
foreign investment designed to stimulate overseas financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to make our country the most favorable, the most
convenient, the most safe place for foreign investments,'' Kim said
through a translator.
</P>
<P>
   A $57 billion cash infusion last December from the International
Monetary Fund saved South Korea from economic collapse. Although
its economy is still troubled, Kim insisted things are better now.
South Korea had just $3.9 billion in foreign exchange on hand on
Dec. 18, the day Kim was elected. Now it has $35 billion, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Strapped with huge debts, many of the huge South Korean
conglomerates are making deals with U.S companies to create or
consolidate joint ventures. Last month, Hewlett-Packard Co., the
Palo Alto, Calif., computer manufacturer, purchased Samsung
Electronics Co.'s 45 percent stake in a joint venture,
Hewlett-Packard Korea for $73 million.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Samsung Heavy Industries Co. sold its
forklift truck business to a U.S. company, Clark Material Handling
Co. of Lexington, Ky., for $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kim invited executives at the chamber breakfast to ``make a
mental note'' to invest $100 million each in South Korea, ``maybe
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded at the breakfast that he was due on Capitol Hill to
address Congress, Kim joked that he was in no hurry. ``You are my
most important audience on this trip,'' he told the executives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his speech to Congress, Kim, 74, offered an emotional
recounting of the heavy price he paid as a democratic activist.
</P>
<P>
   He said he survived five attempts on his life _ one by agents of
communist North Korea and the other four by the ``military
dictators'' of the south. In addition to his six years in prison,
he was in exile or under house arrest for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He credited U.S. diplomatic intervention for saving his life
when South Korean government agents kidnapped him in 1973 and 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never forget America and the destiny that so strongly
binds my political life to your nation,'' he told lawmakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
