<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BAPTISTS-COX </SLUG>
     CLINTON VIEWS BAPTIST WRIT ON WIVES'
SUBMISSION WITH `WRY AMUSEMENT'
 &HT;     By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton reacted with ``wry amusement''
Wednesday to news that his fellow Southern Baptists are urging
wives to ``submit'' to the will of their husbands, a spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He noted with wry amusement the article this morning and
thought about how he might call it to the attention'' to First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton, White House spokesman Michael McCurry told
reporters. ``I don't know whether he elected to do so or not.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Southern Baptist Convention amended its
statement of faith to include an admonition that a woman should
``submit herself graciously'' to her husband's leadership. A
husband, in turn, should ``provide for, protect and lead his
family,'' declared the statement, a sort of spiritual road map for
the 16 million Americans the denomination claims.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a Southern Baptist, does not agree that women should be
expected to submit to their husbands' will, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are occasions when the president's views as a Southern
Baptist are not always identical to those of the Southern Baptist
Convention,'' said McCurry. ``This is clearly one of those cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has long worshipped as a Methodist. She attended a
Methodist church in Little Rock, and she and the president
regularly attend a Methodist church in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president, as someone who worships both with his
wife in the United Methodist Church and occasionally in the
Southern Baptist Church and then at other denominations as well,
would consider himself a practicing and devout Christian,'' said
McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
