<SLUG> BC-EDISON-CONTROVERSY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL TO PRIVATIZE PUBLIC SCHOOL DRAWS CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Labor leaders and child advocates assailed a
proposal to hand one of San Francisco's lowest performing
elementary schools over to a for-profit company.
</P>
<P>
   The Edison Project educational management company offered $1.3
million each for start-up costs at two San Francisco elementary
schools. The Board of Education has rejected half the proposal, to
let the company run the new Tenderloin Community School.
</P>
<P>
   The other part of the proposal is to take over operations of the
Edison Elementary School in Noe Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Edison Elementary, however, is unknown. Parents and
teachers at the school _ which has among the lowest test scores in
the district and has had four principals in less than a year _ will
vote on the proposal Friday. The school board is expected to cast a
final vote June 23.
</P>
<P>
   No one at Tuesday night's board meeting voiced support for the
private-public partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Johnson, secretary treasurer of the San Francisco Labor
Council, vowed to put ``thousands of people in the street'' to
protest the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought that the privatization cloud would
hover over our schools?'' Johnson asked. ``Privatization is a fancy
name for contracting out. Contracting out is a fancy name for
copping out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Donald and Doris Fisher Foundation has pledged $25 million
to schools in California that agree to become Edison sites.
Fisher's son John owns 4 percent of the Edison Project.
</P>
<P>
   The Edison Project was created by Christopher Whittle, the
Tennessee media entrepreneur who brought child-geared television
into classrooms through Channel One. The company operates 25 public
schools in eight states. Although California has 125 so-called
charter schools, which are independent public schools, most are
not-for-profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not allow desperate parents and demoralized teachers
to feel the only option they have is to turn the school over to the
Fisher family and Chris Whittle,'' said San Francisco youth
lobbyist Margaret Brodkin.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, school Superintendent Bill Rojas said the
real decision will be made by the parents and teachers at Edison
Elementary. If they approve the plan with a majority vote Friday,
the Edison Project will take over the school, Rojas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
