<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DEFACING-WINDOWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY OWN PERSONAL ANTITRUST ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a child, I liked to rip off mattress tags, the kind that
threatened prosecution to anyone who removed them. So I was excited
to learn a few days ago about a simple shareware program that
allows a computer user to deface the Windows operating system in
much the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the program, called Logo Manager, doesn't do actual
damage to Windows, any more than removing that tag makes a mattress
lumpy. The program simply enables a user to bypass the Microsoft
start-up screen, which pops up on the monitor each time the
computer is booted.
</P>
<P>
   But in these days of intense debate over the legality of
Microsoft's iron-fisted control over the look of the desktop, I
felt some action was warranted. Let the government lead the broader
charge; I wanted to open my own personal antitrust offensive,
striking a small, symbolic blow in favor of free choice by
replacing the familiar image of the Windows flag silhouetted
against a blue sky with one of a dozen alternatives from Logo
Manager.
</P>
<P>
   Would I pick the Western sunset? Or the scene with a miner
panning for gold? Or perhaps the pair of preening geishas, whose
pink robes reminded me of a Halloween costume from my distant past?
</P>
<P>
   Still, I wanted to be cautious. I checked with Microsoft to make
sure that the minor rebellion I was contemplating would not cause
my operating system to explode. It was a logical concern; if the
browser is an integral part of the Windows product, who is to say
that the start-up screen is any less important?
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cullinan, a Microsoft spokesman, reassured me. ``You're an
end user,'' he said, although that was not the reassuring part.
``So do whatever you want to change the look and personality of
your computer. We just want to insure that you're buying a product
that is guaranteed to our standards. If someone between Microsoft
and the consumer makes changes, who knows what that will do to the
product?''
</P>
<P>
   Legal talk. I was far more focused on installing those geishas.
Was that too much to ask?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, yes _ as I found out after I downloaded Logo Manager
from ZDNet's software library (www.hotfiles.com). The program
didn't work. Well, to be fair, only part of it worked. I did easily
install the shareware on my hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the Help file, I learned how to click on a single button
to attain my first goal: suppressing the Windows start-up screen. I
rebooted the computer a few times, smugly reveling in the absence
of on-screen advertising for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   But I still needed to complete my mission by substituting the
image of the fan-wielding geishas. Following the instructions, I
scrolled through Logo Manager's list of images until I found them,
then clicked on the image. That's when the problem occurred. No
matter how many times I rebooted, no geishas. Instead, the pesky
Windows start-up screen appeared again!
</P>
<P>
   Like any respectable self-taught home computer user, I harbored
a nagging suspicion that I was doing something wrong. I repeated
the steps with no luck. Other features of the program worked
perfectly. I was, for instance, easily able to substitute the
geishas for the Windows shutdown screen. But no matter what
permutations of keystrokes I typed, I could not replace the
start-up screen.
</P>
<P>
   As I fought a familiar urge to put my head down on my keyboard
and cry, a tiny, hopeful thought occurred: What if the problem
wasn't my fault? I congratulated myself because I had come so far
from the days when I once panicked so badly over a system error
message that I screamed at my husband: ``Get the children out of
the house to safety! The cats, too!'' And I wasn't really that
attached to the cats.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned Tim Smith, ZDNet's production and programming manager,
to see if he could help. ``It's working fine on my machine right
now, but I'm running NT instead of Windows,'' Smith said. ``It's
also fine on an old 486 from Dell, which is here running Windows
95.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's me?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Support issues are always tough to figure out,'' he said.
``Let me try it on some of the other machines in the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, Smith called back. He reported that the
geishas behaved just fine on some of the other machines in his
office, including a computer running Windows 98. But when he tried
to run Logo Manager on a twin of my nearly new Micron Millenia
333-megahertz machine, he could not replace the Windows start-up
screen with the geishas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's depressing,'' Smith said. ``Every manufacturer's machine
is a little different. If we had a week or a month to work on it,
we could probably figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   I was starting to feel bad for him. ``Well, just call Micron and
ask what they did and then take it into consideration in the next
release of Logo Manager,'' I suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what if it's not just Micron?'' Smith said. ``It could be
Gateway, too, maybe H-P, IBM _ who knows? We'd have to get every
machine from every manufacturer to know for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a long pause while we both considered the
possibilities. Then Smith said, ``It kind of stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, it does. Logo Manager is a really nifty program, so
it's too bad that not everyone can take advantage of all its
features. Worse, you cannot even blame anyone for the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, of course, hardware and software will be truly
standardized and will work as reliably as all the televisions in
the world or all the toasters. We will all benefit because it will
be that much easier to harness the tantalizing power of a
ubiquitous network to work and play.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime? I searched for words to comfort Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Microsoft has a point,'' I said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
