<HEADER>
A3326 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN11-COX     06-10 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Our history rears its ugly head
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A few weeks ago I wrote a piece recalling the
1961 book, ``Black Like Me,'' and the horrors of segregation that
it exposed.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow I know, who says he likes most everything I write, said
he didn't like that one.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed that those bad old days should be put to rest, that
the era is over and done with, and there's nothing to be gained
from stirring the awful memories.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't say anything. I didn't want to argue.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a few weeks ago. Now the argument has been settled
in the worst possible way.
</P>
<P>
   An hour's drive from here toward the Louisiana border, a black
man was brutally and cruelly murdered in cold blood and without
mercy, dragged to death on a chain behind a pickup truck until an
arm and his head were torn away from his body.
</P>
<P>
   Law officers have charged three white men who are said to have
ties with Ku Klux Klan-type organizations. The FBI has joined the
investigation. So has Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   It's a time of shame and sorrow. Just when we get to the point
of thinking it can't happen here, it happens again.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven help us, we're not that far removed _ a mere 30 years _
from a time when racism was our way of life, passed along from one
generation to another.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians campaigned on it.
</P>
<P>
   Policemen enforced it.
</P>
<P>
   Preachers preached it.
</P>
<P>
   Parents believed it.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers taught it.
</P>
<P>
   Children learned it.
</P>
<P>
   And it's among us yet _ now and maybe forever.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a racist. Why shouldn't I be? It was everything I was ever
told as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, I wonder if I'm the only one who is.
Everybody else is so quick to tell you he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   At best, I'm a recovering racist. At worst, I'm a racist who
sounds no different from the worst of them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes for a joke, sometimes in anger or disgust, I repeat
the evil words _ sometimes before I even realize it.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it's the same as taking the Lord's name in vain. I catch
myself, and I say a prayer of forgiveness for my sins against my
fellow man.
</P>
<P>
   Today I say a prayer for my fellow man who died at the hands of
bigots. Cause of death, ignorance and hatred.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Jasper, pop. 8,000, is itself a victim. This
community where more than 40 percent of the citizens are black,
including the mayor, will be remembered for years to come in terms
of racially motivated murder.
</P>
<P>
   The white people will realize how unfair it is. The black people
already know.
</P>
<P>
   For every crime committed by a person who happens to be black,
white racism indicts an entire people.
</P>
<P>
   I only hope that good people everywhere will not judge us in the
same way.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is
P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas 75915; e-mail is
awew18a(at)prodigy.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
