<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3342 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-POUNDBURY-ART     06-10 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-POUNDBURY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PRINCE'S CAUSE IS ANOTHER MAN'S CASTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DORCHESTER, England _ It was not the kind of headline that
Charles, the prince of Wales, was used to in the British press.
``The Prince Has Got It Right,'' trumpeted The Independent.
</P>
<P>
   What prompted this hearty endorsement of someone the British
seldom tire of tweaking was Poundbury, the new community springing
to daring old life here. The planned town perfectly embodies the
outspoken heir to the throne's views of modern architecture as
owing a debt to the past.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles' blunt expression of those attitudes in the 1980s
started a public shouting match with the country's design
establishment that attracted world attention. He taunted
architects, saying that the Luftwaffe had treated London with more
care than they had. They cast him as a feckless intruder into a
refined world, with taste they classed as pedestrian, retrograde
and fustian.
</P>
<P>
   The crusading magazine he founded to advance his ideas,
Perspectives on Architecture, folded in April, and the institute he
created to instill students with more respect for tradition has had
revolving-door leadership and minimal impact.
</P>
<P>
   But here in the Dorset countryside, he may have hit on a way of
redeeming his breathtaking claim that the country's architects were
more out of touch with the desires of ordinary Britons than the
future leader of the famously remote British monarchy was.
</P>
<P>
   Poundbury is an attempt to create a 21st-century community that
looks as if it grew up over time, with a long linger in the 18th
and 19th centuries when this rural part of southwestern England _
with its stone villages, thatched white cottages and twisting lanes
_ inspired Thomas Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   Its 400 acres will one day be home to 5,000 people living in
houses and cottages of period design with stores and offices all
within walking distance.
</P>
<P>
   It takes some imagination to visualize all this from the 12
acres that have been developed. With 142 tidy new homes up, less
than a tenth of its planned population to animate its streets, and
recently planted trees in their gawky adolescence, Poundbury can
still strike a visitor as the freshly carpentered back lot for the
latest big-budget clogs-and-shawls setting of ``The Mayor of
Casterbridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Built on land that the prince's Duchy of Cornwall owns, and
designed by Leon Krier, an architect from Luxembourg who is a
champion of traditional town planning, Poundbury is an ambitious
project that is meant to change attitudes about building, housing
mix, traffic, energy savings, parking, zoning and shopping.
</P>
<P>
   With its first two sections nearing completion this summer, it
is emerging as a pleasingly chockablock village of rusticated
stonework homes, meandering streets, alleys and mews, and market
arcades and public squares. Street lanterns with ornamental caps
hang from metalwork struts on the sides of buildings or on gently
curving masonry walls, casting Poundbury each evening in a soft
play of light and shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Poundbury was derided as a kitschy time warp using a sentimental
pastiche of outmoded styles and toy-town concepts when plans first
emerged in 1989. In answer to written questions from The New York
Times, Prince Charles wrote that he remembered ``a torrent of
criticism and abuse that was beyond all belief and amounted, over
the years, to a continuous stream of `knocking' stories in the
press.''
</P>
<P>
   But the town has recently begun to gain favor with the writers,
designers, architects, planners and backpacking day-trippers who
swarm over the project in growing numbers. Cabdrivers now
affectionately call the destination Charleyville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over all, the effect is polite, elegant and as English as a
vicar's tea party,'' the magazine Homes and Antiques said. ``I
arrived a skeptic,'' a critic from The Financial Times said. ``I
left a convert.''
</P>
<P>
   In his response, which he penned in flowing red ink, Charles
wrote that he thought opinion had swung around in the project's
favor because ``more and more people are going to look at Poundbury
for themselves and finding it is completely different from the
negative propaganda they have read about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Its residents have become its most vigorous advocates. ``Try as
hard as they can, the media cannot find many people in the local
area to knock it,'' the prince wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Paying particular attention to the one part of his architectural
campaign that seems to be impressing people, he is a frequent and
apparently welcome visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just sat down there on the sofa, took his boots off and
nattered on like anyone else,'' said Diane Bryant, whose husband,
Peter, is the head of the Poundbury Residents' Association. ``He
wasn't patronizing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The locals are even good-natured about the way all the visitors
talk to them as if they were the stand-in blacksmiths and wig
makers of Colonial Williamsburg. ``I've been gardening, and people
will walk up the path expecting us to be dressed in period costume,
doing the Hardy bit,'' said Jennie Fellowes, a schoolteacher who
lives in a rented cottage with her 11-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Her home is one of 55 subsidized ``social housing'' units
interspersed throughout the community; it is a source of pride here
that these rental buildings are indistinguishable from the
privately owned homes. ``I challenge you to try to tell,'' Bryant
said, sweeping his gaze up and down the streets of stucco and brick
and flint-work town houses. ``People who buy here know they're
coming into a mixed community,'' Mrs. Bryant said. ``They don't
find out only after they've parted with their money.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, it seems, no NIMBY problem in Poundbury. ``Our
principle from the start has been to pepper-pot the social housing,
scattering it through the development,'' said Andrew Hamilton, the
development director. ``Builders said: `We can't build private
houses next to social housing. They won't sell.' But we have proved
that this is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment all 142 homes are sold and, according to Hamilton,
resale value has increased as much as 20 percent in three years.
Plot sizes range from 1,500 square feet to 80,000 square feet.
Every house is designed by an architect, and cannot be the same as
any other in the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   Architects must work in the ``vernacular,'' which in the case of
Dorset means Purbeck marble and Portland stone and a rich local
vocabulary of brick, chalk, roof slate and stucco called
``render.'' There can be no decorative tricks like half-timbering
or gaudy ornamentation.
</P>
<P>
   The houses may look antique from the outside, but they have
double-glazed windows, high-efficiency condensing boilers, extra
insulation and computer-controlled energy-management systems to
reduce fuel consumption.
</P>
<P>
   All services _ telephone, electricity, gas and drainage _ are
buried in channels behind the housing; one large satellite dish
hidden behind a high masonry wall serves the community. All you
will see protruding from a Poundbury roof is a stately brick
chimney or a polished weather vane. Houses stand flush with the
street so that when you step from your front door, you're already
in town.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Krier's decision to have his streets and alleyways wander and
their breadths widen and narrow randomly has created bends and
blind corners that add a sense of anticipation and theater to
taking a stroll or running an errand.
</P>
<P>
   They have the added value of controlling traffic without
resorting to gimmicks like speed bumps. There are no straightaways
in Poundbury that allow drivers to exceed 20 mph. ``The streets are
simply short and winding on the same principle that stream beds
slow down water,'' Krier said.
</P>
<P>
   The developers realized early on that they had to coexist with
automobiles. ``We decided not to murder the car, but to suppress
it, to make it subservient,'' said Simon Conibear, an executive of
the Duchy of Cornwall. They wrestled highway regulations that
called for providing each family space for 2.5 cars down to 2.3 and
have held out the promise of larger garden space for smaller
parking space, an alluring trade-off for flower-besotted Britons.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of houses ranges from $95,000 to $300,000, but even the
most expensive stick to modest dimensions. To maintain firm control
over the quality of the finished product, the duchy does not sell
the land to the builder until the construction is done and
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is studded with red-brick suburbs that march in numbing
grids up and down its contours. Built originally for men returning
from the war, they proved functional but uninspiring. Now the
government estimates that Britain must build 4.4 million new homes
by the year 2016.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the very real threat to the quality and integrity of the
British countryside from the insensitive uglification of standard
housing developments,'' the prince responded, ``people have begun
to realize that Poundbury might just offer a more imaginative and
attractive approach from which to draw inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he also hoped the example of Poundbury would rattle the
bureaucracy. ``Some of the most difficult attitudes to change are
those rigidly conventional ones held by local councilors and by
professionals such as planning consultants, road and traffic
engineers, building standards regulators, lighting engineers and
the kind of social engineers who seem to regard human beings as
technological units of some millennial utopia,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The origins of the Poundbury project began in a controversy that
is sometimes forgotten because of the succession of subsequent
attention-getting crises in the prince's life.
</P>
<P>
   His fight with the British modern-architecture establishment
preceded news of the breakdown of his marriage; the tapes of his
tangy conversations with his mistress, Camilla Parker-Bowles; and
zestful accounts of his bent for communing with mystical beings on
the Scottish moors.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time when the percussive single-syllable words like
``twit'' and ``prat'' that Britons use to dress down their
well-born often accompanied mention of the prince's name in
broadcast satires and newspaper commentaries.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1984, at the celebration of the 150th anniversary of the
Royal Institute of British Architects, Prince Charles declared his
views on what its members had done. In the most famous line from
the speech, he compared the planned extension of the facade of the
National Gallery in London's Trafalgar Square to ``a monstrous
carbuncle on the face of a much loved and elegant friend.''
</P>
<P>
   He complained that people were never consulted about the
construction of communities they were to live in, and that the
establishment deliberately made them feel ``guilty or ignorant if
their natural preference is for the more `traditional designs' _
for a small garden, for courtyards, arches and porches.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, he took on the design establishment again,
deploring the modern buildings and proposals for new ones in
Paternoster Square, the area around St. Paul's Cathedral. His 1989
book ``A Vision of Britain'' outlined 10 simplistic rules for
architecture, and the battle lines were drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rogers, a leading British architect and lecturer on
planning, threw down the gauntlet. ``As a man with strong views
about architecture, a high public profile and enormous private
wealth,'' the architect said of the prince, ``he has an
extraordinary opportunity to commission buildings for his large
estates, but he has yet to produce a noteworthy construction.''
</P>
<P>
   The prince was at that time pondering a request from the local
council to sell the 400-acre Poundbury farm to a national developer
for housing that was much needed. (The Duchy of Cornwall, which
comprises 128,000 acres in 22 counties of England, was created in
1337 by Edward III to provide income for the heir to the throne.)
</P>
<P>
   The prince instead asked Krier to do a master plan, liked what
he came up with and made Poundbury the cornerstone of his
architecture campaign. Krier, whose most recent book carries the
dedication ``A mon Prince,'' found Charles a refreshingly untypical
English client. ``Lots of English people say exactly the opposite
of what they mean,'' he said. ``The prince is absolutely frank.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he permitted himself to gloat over the welcome his
once-derided project is now receiving, Prince Charles made it clear
that he was happy he hadn't followed an easier path. ``If the duchy
had sold the land to the highest bidder for several million pounds
and then walked away to have a developer build yet another housing
estate on the edge of yet another English town as happens
elsewhere,'' he said, ``would anyone have uttered a word of
criticism?''
</P>
</TEXT>
