<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-FOOD11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Palm Beach airport asks vendors to offer affordable food prices
 &HT;    By Rebecca Goldsmith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Restaurants in Palm Beach International
Airport will have to serve up better prices if they want to win a
contract to sell food.
</P>
<P>
   Airport Director Bruce Pelly said he is tired of seeing
customers abandon their orders at the register when they hear how
much they owe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a feeling out there in the public that, one,
airport food isn't that good, and two, it's overpriced,'' Pelly
said. ``If the prices are good, then you'll sell more food, and
everyone will make more money.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why a new request for bids, due June 18, asks would-be
food concessionaires to offer ``street level'' prices, which are
markedly lower than the ``captive audience'' prices at airports and
food courts.
</P>
<P>
   The current contract with CA One Services Inc. expires Sept. 30.
The Buffalo, N.Y.-based company has run the airport's food and
beverage outlets since 1988, when the terminal opened.
</P>
<P>
   By Oct. 1, a new contract will be in place, ushering in nine
months of construction and transition for the airport's four
restaurants and half-dozen food stands.
</P>
<P>
   Besides lower prices, proposed changes include:
</P>
<P>
   Coffee kiosks at the end of concourses.
</P>
<P>
   More name brands and local restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   A lounge with telephones and business machines where the
Atlantic Cafe and Lounge used to sit.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-year agreement with one, five-year renewal possible.
</P>
<P>
   Pauline Armbrust, editor of Palm Beach Gardens-based World
Airport Retail News, said PBIA's plans fit in with a trend toward
name brands and more reasonable prices at airports in the past four
years.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: ``When you provide customers with value and quality,
the airport can make a lot of money out of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   PBIA made $870,719 last year from its food and beverage
concessions, but officials are aiming higher with the next
contract.
</P>
<P>
   CA One got a five-year contract in 1988, with three renewal
options of five years each. But in 1992 county commissioners
decided to terminate the contract at the end of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Department of Airports attributed the problems
to lower-than-expected passenger counts, the poor location of the
Atlantic Cafe, and trends toward brand names and casual dining.
</P>
<P>
   CA One, which runs concessions in 30 airports nationwide, plans
to bid again, said general manager Tim Bannigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our facilities have addressed the needs of the travelers in
Palm Beach County very well,'' he said. ``Can we do better? I
certainly hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever serves the snacks next at PBIA will have to ground their
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to not gouge people when they go through the
airport,'' Pelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Goldsmith writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
