<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ernest Holsendolph's Business Commentary: Families discover the
wonders of WebTV
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some pursuits are solitary, like stamp collecting or
developing pictures in a darkroom. Pleasant, absorbing, but
solitary. Much about personal computing matches that pattern, a
single person and his or her computer, surfing and exploring into
the night.
</P>
<P>
   When I ask people why they are among that massive 60 percent of
households that have no computer at home, many people, especially
those with families, say it's because Internet venturing is
cloistered, a poor way to spend time after a long day at work.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons why Bill Gates has bought WebTV technology is
because he, more than most of us, realizes something new is needed
on the landscape. The romp through the computer networks for fun
and information needs transformation, a new setting, an alternative
way to bring new kinds of people into the information age.
</P>
<P>
   If that's his aim, Gates again may be on to something.
</P>
<P>
   WebTV was born as an inexpensive way to get onto the Internet
using a black box and a television set. It was dismissed by many
computer veterans as, at best, a training wheels version of
computer surfing -- or worse yet, computing for people who hate
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than two-thirds of people who own WebTV do not have
personal computers in their homes,'' said Greg Goodruff, vice
president at Sony Electronics in New Jersey. ``That's how we know
WebTV is a different kind of experience, appealing to a different
group.''
</P>
<P>
   WebTV has advanced, and so has its fans.
</P>
<P>
   I was surprised recently when Ken Beauchamp, manager of retail
sales at the Computer City store near Dunwoody, told me that WebTV
was his medium of choice for Internet surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way,'' he said. ``I have a lot more fun
doing my surfing on my 35-inch television set than you can on your
15-inch monitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest version of the system, called WebTV Plus, has added
dimensions that allow subscribers to access cable television and
the Internet through the same box. Several unique features include
an electronic TV guide that describes program offerings quickly,
and also permits subscribers to see cable programs and Internet
information simultaneously on the same screen.
</P>
<P>
   Beauchamp said his family can gather around the TV and do such
group activities as explore travel options, looking at the pictures
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also look at movie choices together, planning our weekends
together,'' he said. ``We can even sit in our living room and plan
movies and other entertainment in California, where I go to visit
family.''
</P>
<P>
   In my own experience with the WebTV, I found evidence to support
that view. We hooked up the system in my living room and left it to
my teenage son, Joseph, and his school friends, Rico Harmon and
Corey Daniels. Since two of them are baseball players, they
immediately found on the Internet baseball manuals on fielding and
pitching, read them together and had animated discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Then they looked up music CDs, and even found the lyrics to rap
songs, and had a rollicking good time ``singing'' them.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from the quiet, solitary individual surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young children get it right away,'' said Goodruff, the Sony
vice president, who happens to have two pre-teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boys, age 7 and 12, sit with me and watch `Wheel of
Fortune,''' Goodruff said, ``and then they surf for music, which
comes through louder and more clearly on the stereo system of our
entertainment center than it would on those little computer
speakers.''
</P>
<P>
   What families and experts agree on is this: WebTV is a new kind
of connecting point in the home, and we are likely to see newer
systems in the next year that resemble it. Examples include digital
pipelines from the cable companies that will include video, phone
service, computer access and more.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some communications specialists speculate that Bill
Gates' primary interest in WebTV is the licensing agreements that
will give him speedier access to this new kind of one-stop
entertaining center.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gates wants to sell that kind of system to others,
including cable systems, the cable operators appear determined to
do it their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Gates comes control,'' said Dave Woodrow of Cox
Communications, a major cable operator. ``We would rather do our
own system, and it may be available next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Justice Department, in its growing list of charges
against Microsoft, is reportedly investigating how the computer
giant may install its WebTV-like features into its latest Windows
program and serve to forestall competition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the new WebTV system has many features familiar to
the sophisticated PC user, including fast Internet connections at
56 kilobits per second. The new black box contains a hard drive, so
information can be stored, thus helping to keep the system speedy.
Also, the new systems have printers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Versions right around the corner will help subscribers import
much more data,'' said Goodruff, so WebTV will have many of the
advantages of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, WebTV is a medium for lovers of television. But it adds,
as an extra component, the ability to surf the Internet. And before
long, that feature will be married to the television components to
create a seamless service that just might attract a mass audience.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-05-98 2152E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
