<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Town council agrees to lift Neiman Marcus ad ban
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH _ The town council Tuesday, June 9, backed away from
barring Neiman Marcus from advertising on television, radio or in
major local newspapers for a year after it opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you impose this condition on this store and not on
every other store on the island?'' asked council President Lesly
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The council reversed itself as it was reviewing an agreement
with landowner Murray Goodman to allow the upscale Dallas-based
retailer to build a three-story store on Worth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Members last week approved the store, contingent on the
advertising ban suggested by Councilman Leslie cq Shaw. Shaw said
he wanted to ensure the store's target customer lives on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Under town law, larger than 2,000 sq ft stores, restaurants and
other businesses must prove that more than half their customers
live, work or are staying at hotels and homes in Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Town Attorney John Randolph warned the council against telling
merchants how to meet the law. ``I begin having a concern when
you're doing more than requiring them to be town-serving,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To replace the advertising restriction, the council agreed, 3-2,
to substitute a condition that the store meet the ``town-serving''
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw and Smith voted against the change. ``I don't think the
(condition) is necessary at all,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Allen Wyett suggested an advertising blackout of
end-of-season sales since they attract the most traffic. Other
council members disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Worth Avenue goes on sale, the world comes,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The council will consider a final draft of the agreement
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   end
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-09-98 2058E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
