<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINKNEY-ARENALEAGUE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Texas player Pinkney changes attitude, league
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ In August 1997 Lovell Pinkney was competing for a
roster spot with the then-Super Bowl champion Green Bay Packers
when he decided he didn't want to be in De Pere, Wis.. Even though
the training camp likely represented his last chance to make it in
the NFL, he no longer had a passion for football.
</P>
<P>
   So he packed his bags and walked out of the team dorm, leaving
his new coaches and teammates wondering what prompted his sudden
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkney, one of the most gifted and most controversial athletes
ever to play for the University of Texas, was troubled. His
61-year-old mother, who was home in Washington, D.C., had suffered
her second heart attack in three years. She needed dialysis
treatment for her ailing kidneys. He also was going through the
breakup of an 18-month marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if it wasn't fun anymore, I didn't need to be doing
it,'' Pinkney, 25, said of playing football.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkney's attitude, on the field and off, has taken a drastic
turn. He said he has discovered Christianity. His ailing football
pysche also received a jolt of optimism because for at least the
month of May, he was a star in the Arena Football League, which two
years ago he would have considered not worthy of his talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who knew me then (back in Austin) probably wouldn't
recognize me now,'' Pinkney said during a telephone interview last
week. ``Personality- wise, I'm still the same guy, a fun guy to be
around, that's still the same. But what kind of crowd I hang out
with, my Lord and savior has changed all that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinkney moved home last summer to care for his mother, Helen
Lancaster. For several months he worked for a group that lobbies
the U.S. Congress for family- oriented issues. But when he got a
call from Michael Trigg, a former star for the Arena League's
Detroit Drive, Pinkney decided to return to football. He accepted
an invitation to play for Trigg, who coaches the Grand Rapids
(Mich.) Rampage, which in a previous incarnation was the Drive,
winner of four Arena Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   For a month, until he broke his right arm, he was the Rampage's
brightest star, playing wide receiver and linebacker for a team
that sells out its converted hockey arena in a league that requires
all but a handful of players to compete on both offense and
defense. Pinkney even was catching passes from a former rival,
Texas A&AMP;M quarterback Corey Pullig. Defensive tackle Stonie Clark,
Pinkney's former Longhorns teammate, was given a two-day tryout
with the Rampage but was cut.
</P>
<P>
   Most Arena League players make from $500 to $800 a week, but the
stars can make as much as $2,000. The team also pays a player's
rent for the four-month season. Pinkney would not say what he made,
adding that he is honoring the wishes of his coaches not to reveal
his salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This league really has helped build my self-esteem,'' Pinkney
said. ``It's helped to build my mind-set and make football fun
again. In this league, they score like 50 to 70 points. And the
defensive backs, they're all like 5-6 or 5-7.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5-inch Pinkney was enjoying his distinct height
advantage, catching 12 passes for 162 yards and four touchdowns in
three games. He also had four tackles, one for a loss, and had
broken up a pass. But his season ended prematurely May 28 when he
broke a bone in his upper right arm trying to make a tackle against
San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame he got hurt, because we were building our team
around him,'' said Tony Lasher, a Rampage spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns once pinned their hopes on Pinkney, who despite
his defensive- end-like size could outrun the quickest running
backs. He was a key recruit in Coach John Mackovic's first class in
1992 and, along with fellow wide receiver Mike Adams, earned a
place on USA Today's freshman All-America team.
</P>
<P>
   But Pinkney, a product of a tough inner-city D.C. neighborhood,
constantly found himself in trouble in Austin. Mackovic benched him
midway through his freshman season for missing class. An off-season
dormitory prank prompted a one- game suspension his sophomore year,
and he was barred from living in the dorm for one year. He was
suspended for a total of three games in 1994, for breaking curfew,
improperly accepting the use of an expensive rental car and
misleading investigators about why he took a spring trip to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkney declared for the NFL draft in 1995, leaving UT after his
junior season with the school record for career touchdown
receptions (15). He hasn't returned to Austin. However, he is
trying to reestablish ties. Last week he called UT Coach Mack Brown
to wish the new coach well. He also wanted to get back in touch
with Cleve Bryant, the new UT assistant athletic director who as an
assistant under Mackovic recruited Pinkney to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pinkney once was projected as a first-round NFL draft
pick, the St. Louis Rams selected him in the fourth round in 1995.
Teams had questions about Pinkney's suspensions at UT, and they did
not know what position he should play in the pros. In his three
years at UT, he gained about 30 pounds, so that by 1995 he weighed
about 250. He maintained most of his speed but he looked more like
a tight end, albeit a tight end who never had to block.
</P>
<P>
   As a pro, he remained a lightning rod for controversy. He was
suspended for a game with the St. Louis Rams in 1995 because he
missed a practice to attend the Million Man March in Washington. He
was waived the next year. Pinkney's name even was linked to the
suspension last December of Penn State running back Curtis Enis,
who improperly accepted clothes after going on a shopping trip with
agent Jeff Nalley of Houston. Pinkney also was represented by
Nalley, who told Penn State officials the $400 worth of clothing
was meant for Pinkney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went shopping with Jeff in Pennsylvania,'' Pinkney said.
``But I don't know what happened. I never saw Curtis. I don't know
if people thought I was Curtis or not. Does Curtis favor me? I
don't know what he looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinkney said he has calmed down since college. He became a
Christian two years ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of my problem, I was trying to do everything on my own,
instead of allowing God to take over,'' said Pinkney, whose parents
are Muslim but didn't raise their 12 children with those beliefs.
``I remember I was playing for the Rams and this voice kept coming
to me. There was this guy who played for the Rams named Todd
Kinchen, and he was a real good Christian. I asked him about it one
day. We sat in a car in the parking lot of Wendy's for three hours.
He told me the voice I kept hearing was God trying to come in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinkney started attending a Baptist church in Washington. In
Grand Rapids, he participates in informal, weekly Bible studies
with some of his teammates and in game-day chapel services.
</P>
<P>
   He still dreams of one day playing in the NFL. But he has placed
those dreams on hold because of the fun and acceptance he has had
playing Arena ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nice town. They're football crazy here,'' Pinkney
said. ``They pack this place every weekend. You know, the New
Orleans Saints called me last year, but I didn't want to go back to
the NFL. They just wanted me for like an insurance tight end. I
like to compete. I don't want to ride the bench. I want to play
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL is not my main focus. I've got some years left in me,
but my main focus right now is to return back to this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Haliburton writes for The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
