<SLUG> BC-REDS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds revamp while season revs up
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO, Calif. _ With the team spinning its wheels and
apparently on a road to nowhere this season, the Cincinnati Reds
are in full-throttle revamping mode. Shortstop and captain Barry
Larkin, the 34-year-old anchor of the team, is being offered in
trade to several teams, the Dayton Daily News learned recently.
Sources said general manager Jim Bowden has contacted the San Diego
Padres, Los Angeles Dodgers, San Francisco Giants and St. Louis
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   And Larkin knows it. His agent, Eric Goldschmidt, told Larkin on
June 9 that the Reds are trying to move him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, the Reds apparently are asking too much for me,''
Larkin said during an early-afternoon special batting practice
session at Qualcomm Stadium. ``They've asked for San Diego's top
three prospects and were told (by San Diego general manager Kevin
Towers), `We wouldn't trade those three for Mo Vaughn.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moving Larkin makes sense for two reasons: The Reds are in a
payroll-reduction mode, and they are in a youth and development
phase in which he doesn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   The longer they wait to move him, the tougher it will be. His
contract this year and next year calls for $5.3 million and another
$5.3 million in 2000 if he makes 525 plate appearances in any of
the next three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting impatiently for his time in the sun is 25-year-old
shortstop Pokey Reese, the team's No. 1 draft choice in 1991, who
is wasting away on the bench. Reese has appeared in 28 games this
season and has started 10 at shortstop, most of those when Larkin
missed the start of the season recovering from neck surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin is hitting .270 with four homers, 26 RBIs and 12 stolen
bases in 13 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin has professed a desire to finish his career with a
winning team, one with a chance to get him into the World Series
one more time, and it appears it will be too late for him by the
time the Reds complete their rebuilding plans and complete a new
stadium to generate revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know by the time they get done around here what they want to
get done, it'll be too late for me,'' Larkin said. ``Sure, I'd like
a chance to play for a winner, for a team that could use me to help
them win, before I finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin, a Cincinnati native and graduate of Moeller High School,
was the Reds' No. 1 draft pick in 1985 and is the last remnant from
the 1990 World Series champion. He has a career .299 batting
average with 143 home runs, 672 RBIs and 302 stolen bases in his
11-plus seasons with the Reds. He was National League MVP in 1995
when he led the team to the NL Championship Series with a .319
average, 15 home runs, 66 RBIs and 51 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres (Chris Gomez), Giants (Rich Aurilia), Dodgers (Jose
Vizcaino) and Cardinals (Luis Ordaz) all could use a multi-faceted
offensive and defensive shortstop, and they could afford Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' payroll is at $22 million; trading Larkin for
prospects would reduce it to less than $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
