<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lexus making bold pitch for younger buyers
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Lexus is not changing its image, it is most
certainly expanding it to include an entirely new genre of
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the bold styling of its lightning-fast GS 400
sedan and continuing with the debut of the RX 300 sport-utility
vehicle, Lexus is seeking to expand its horizons to a broader and
potentially more youthful customer base.
</P>
<P>
   The GS 400's rounded shape exudes the same type of youthful
appeal as Volkswagen's New Beetle. While equally as elegant as the
Lexus LS 400 flagship, this Lexus screams, ``Hey, notice me!'' It
also screams when the driver pushes the accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus likes to brag about the GS 400's steering-wheel-mounted
button-shift capability, which is derived from Formula One
technology. The irony is that the system is overkill. The GS 400's
five-speed automatic is one of the finest in the industry. In a
spirited test drive, I never once was tempted to use the steering
wheel shifter. The GS's automatic always provided the proper gear
at the proper time.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping even further out on the styling limb is the new RX 300.
My first impression: a copycat of the Mercedes M-Class. Nothing
could be further from the truth. The RX 300 has its own
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Its futuristic styling evokes an almost spaceship type of image,
highlighted with bold headlight and taillight treatments. While
maintaining all the creature comforts synonymous with Lexus, the
futuristic concepts carry on to the RX 300's interior, with the
gearshift lever being mounted in an extension pod of the dashboard.
At first glance, it was a bizarre visual concept, but it proved to
be exceptionally functional.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of this instrument pod is an LCD screen that houses
ventilation, audio, trip computer, outside temperature and clock
functions -- sort of your own personal mini computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the RX 300 is its driveability. Powered by a
3.0-liter, 220-horsepower, four-cam, 24-valve V-6, the RX 300 is
one of the more spirited sport-utilities on the market.
</P>
<P>
   From a ride and handling standpoint, the RX 300 gets a thumbs
up. Not surprisingly, it drives more like a car than its big
brother, the LX470. That's because it is based on a Camry platform
rather than a full boxed frame. It is also exceptionally
maneuverable and parkable.
</P>
<P>
   But don't mistake the RX 300 for a wimpy player. The RX 300's
full-time four-wheel-drive connected with a four-speed automatic
with ``snow mode'' switch can carry soccer moms and business moms
alike through the most treacherous terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
