<HEADER>
A3358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DVDD-DIVX-ART-2TA     06-10 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DVDD-DIVX-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DVD VIDEO APPEALS TO A VANGUARD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Circuits)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dc) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christian Hennings is enthusiastic about his DVD movie player
and the disks that go with it, but it remains to be seen if the
technology mainstream will move in the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   Hennings, a movie buff from Springfield, N.J., jumped into DVD
when it became available about 15 months ago. ``There wasn't
anywhere you could rent disks, so I started buying them right off
for $22 or $24,'' he said. So far, he has bought 50 or 60 movies on
DVD disks to watch on his television set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little leery when they first came out,'' he said. ``I
always loved laser disk'' _ another disk format for movie
enthusiasts _ ``but now there are a thousand titles on DVD and the
quality is better than laser. And the price makes it awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   But all is not well with DVD, which stands for digital video
disk or digital versatile disk, depending on who is doing the
talking. Movies on DVD are luminous and clear, with a depth of
field that looks very much like what you see in a movie theater.
Yet DVD, promoted as the next hot thing by the home electronics
industry and movie companies, has made a debut that is widely rated
as mildly disappointing or guardedly promising.
</P>
<P>
   For DVD sales to consumers, the industry ``got the early
adopters in the first year,'' said Martin Greenwald, president of
Image Entertainment, a distributor of laser disks and DVDs for
several Hollywood studios. ``The reason DVD hasn't hit a nerve with
videotape buyers is that people don't perceive the economic value
of the product.''
</P>
<P>
   The public seems generally satisfied with the video cassette
recorder and is slow to see a need for DVD movies. Players cost
from $400 to $1,000. Distributors recall that the VCR didn't really
take off until the price fell to $300.
</P>
<P>
   DVD comes in several forms besides DVD-video for playing movies
on television screens. DVD-ROM can run games and other software as
well as movies on computer monitors; it is widely expected to
eventually replace CD-ROM because of its superior storage
capabilities. There are also recordable forms of DVD disks and
Divx, which plays movies on special players. DVD technology for
audio is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   A disagreement in the industry over competing plans for DVD
players is thought to have slowed consumer acceptance of the
format.
</P>
<P>
   It is movie buffs like Hennings who are most interested in the
video end of DVD. About 300,000 DVD video players are now in use, a
far cry from industry predictions of a million or more players by
now. Richard Kelly, president of Cambridge Associates, a consulting
company for disk and tape replicators, said that player sales could
reach 900,000 to a million by the end of this year. He sees steady
if not spectacular growth after that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see good acceptance,'' he said, ``but I'm not sure
you'll see a player in 10 percent of homes in a couple of years.
There won't be that kind of penetration.''
</P>
<P>
   DVD movies look sharp and clean on computers, which makes the
disks ideal for taking movies along to play on laptops equipped
with DVD-ROM players and for other specialized uses. Otherwise,
computers aren't what most people think of when it comes to a
two-hour feature film. ``I have a 36-inch television, so the idea
of watching movies on a 15-inch computer screen isn't that
appealing,'' Hennings said.
</P>
<P>
   To play DVD movies on a television set, one needs a separate
set-top player that looks like a VCR and, depending on its
features, costs from $400 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Do you really need another movie player? That depends. Image and
sound are vastly superior to videotape, but is that important
enough to you to warrant buying a new video system for the
television set?
</P>
<P>
   Like many other movie buffs, Hennings is attracted by the extras
that are on many, but not all, DVD disks: documentaries about the
making of the film, behind-the-scenes interviews and other
supplementary information.
</P>
<P>
   If you aren't entirely sure where you stand on such matters, it
is perhaps best to see DVD in operation, or even to give it a trial
run. Not every video store carries DVD, but ones that do often have
demonstration areas, and some will rent players for trial purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions a prospective DVD buyer might want to ask
are whether the sparkling, crisp images of DVD, plus the disks'
movie extras, are worth the investment in the first generation of
DVD players.
</P>
<P>
   Another important question is this: Will DVD develop into a mass
commodity, along the lines of VHS and the VCR, which is now in
almost 90 percent of American homes? Or as with the laser disk,
will it always be a niche item for technically inclined film
enthusiasts? Opinions vary wildly, but moderate voices in the
business say that if DVD for television is to enter the mainstream,
it will be bit by bit over the next several years, perhaps faster
if prices drop.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is the quantity and range of movies available on
DVD. Both Kelly and Greenwald say supply will affect the prices of
both DVD players and DVD movies. ``Studios should get very
interested in DVD after players hit the million mark,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   The more players sold, the more movies will be put on disk, he
said. That, in turn, might stimulate player sales, which will
increase the number of movies available, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Will you be able to get all the movies you want when you want
them? With the exception of Fox, which has not entered the DVD
market, all the major studios say they will release movies on DVD.
How many and when is unclear. Now, the vast majority of DVD titles
are older catalog films that appeal to collectors who aren't
necessarily interested in having the latest hit.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest issues for prospective DVD purchasers is the
question of the industry disagreement over the format for DVD
players: DVD vs. Divx. Let's say you want to rent movies and not
buy them. Within the next year, there could be two competing types
of DVD on the market, introducing elements of potential
incompatibility that recall the VHS-Beta competition of the early
80s.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DVDD-DIVX-2DTAKE-     06-10 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DVDD-DIVX-2DTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: early 80s. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A format war? Not exactly, but the upshot could be the same.
Both DVD video and Divx offer digital video disks, but the
marketing concepts are different, as are the players, which could
cause a problem if you have one and not the other. The first type
of system, available now, is called open DVD. The second is Divx,
for digital video express, which began tests this week.
</P>
<P>
   Open DVD is designed for collectors like Hennings who buy disks.
Only lately have studios and retailers begun to acknowledge that
many potential DVD consumers want to rent, not buy. Large chains
like Blockbuster and Tower have introduced trial rental programs.
</P>
<P>
   Divx is DVD designed for rentals. You buy a disk for $4.50,
which serves as a base rental fee. For that $4.50, you can watch
the film as many times as you want within 48 hours. If you play the
disk again after that, you pay an extra fee, which is billed
automatically to a credit card via a phone modem in your Divx
player. If you want to buy the movie, you are charged more.
</P>
<P>
   The Divx plan has caused a furor among video dealers who dislike
the idea because people will not have to go back to stores to
return the disks. Critics also say the system is too complicated
for consumers to use easily. Advocates say it is no more
complicated than ordering movies via pay-per-view cable or
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The studios see advantages in Divx because the system of
consumer payment for movie rentals enables them to collect a fee
for every transaction. Videocassettes, by contrast, are sold to
retailers for one price up front. At present, Paramount, Disney and
Universal say they will put out movies in both open DVD and Divx.
Warner and Columbia-Tri-Star, which inaugurated DVD last year, say
they will stay with only open DVD.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone contemplating getting into DVD, there is a very
important point to remember: all DVD disks will play on Divx
machines, but Divx disks will not function on standard open DVD
players. So should you wait for Divx, a system that isn't ready and
isn't assured of success?
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, Greenwald and most other informed observers say they
expect all the studios to promote rentals and issue movies in both
Divx and open DVD formats. No one expects a repetition of the
VHS-Beta tangle. ``I can't imagine any studio head allowing that to
happen,'' Kelly said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
