<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Test Drive: Lexus RX 300 has plenty of power, with silky comfort
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Try as you might, it's really difficult to couple the
usual sport-utility vehicle-associated phrase ``trucklike'' with
the new-for-'99 Lexus RX 300 sport-utility. The words ``luxury
car-like'' keep getting in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because of all the leather and real wood that came
with the pearl-painted test RX 300. Or maybe it's because of the
high-end stereo with in-dash six-CD changer, trip computer and
fold/slide rear seats. Then, again, it just may be the
220-horsepower V-6 engine, four-speed automatic transmission and
supple independent suspension that combine to give the RX 300
luxo/sports sedan performance (zero to 60 mph in eight-plus
seconds) and ride on the road.
</P>
<P>
   It's also quite likely these attributes can be traced to the RX
300's heritage, heavily influenced by the Lexus ES 300, the Toyota
Camry and, seemingly, the new and lavishly greeted Mercedes-Benz
M-Class. After all, all those factors are positives in the market
segment catering to status-seeking buyers with money and little
desire to go off-roading.
</P>
<P>
   The RX 300 will go off-road, quite willingly in fact, and is
more manageable for most drivers than the larger, costlier Lexus LX
450. The RX 300 transmission lacks the low range demanded by
serious off-roaders, but the RX 300 has sufficient ground clearance
(7.8 inches), bulk (two tons) and the strength and suspension to
handle moderate off-road jaunts without it or occupants feeling
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   The steering -- too luxury car-like to ever rebound and whang
around your wrists -- is helpful up and down reasonable terrain,
and the power anti-lock disc brakes are very adequate. Still, the
RX 300 and driver can't help but go into a
stranger-in-a-strange-land mode when this gleaming,
upscale-appointed vehicle is slipping around trees and splashing
mud.
</P>
<P>
   A far more natural environment for the RX 300 is found on paved
surfaces, and its real utility comes when it's loaded with people.
The handling is nicely balanced, with little chance of the RX 300
giving an impression of being tippy. Bumps are noted, but not
telegraphed to occupants.
</P>
<P>
   The interior, in addition to being cushy, is quite functional.
The car-type instrumentation and controls, including the shifter
found on the busy center dash, are sensibly arranged. The only
anomaly is the information display screen in the center dash pod
that seems to be waiting for an onboard navigation system to
appear.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all this and the cachet of Lexus badging, though, what
endows the RX 300 with appeal is precisely what makes the high-end
Lexus 300 and 400 cars winners: sheer power and silky comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Chart:
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Lexus RX 300 four-door, five-passenger,
all-wheel-drive sport-utility vehicle
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $38,389 (base price: $32,950)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front air bags, dual side-mounted air
bags, power anti-lock disc brakes, side-impact beams, adjustable
head rests at all seating positions, daytime running lights
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 3.0-liter V-6 engine with 24 valves (220
horsepower), four-speed automatic transmission with power, economy
and snow settings
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: in-dash 6-CD changer, $1,050; power
tilt/slide glass sunroof with shade, $1,000; package with leather
trim, driver's seat memory, electrochromatic inside/outside
mirrors, air filtration system, $1,860; roof rack, $234; towing
package, $248; mats, $177
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 19 mpg regular unleaded city; 22 mpg highway
(premium recommended)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
