<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Very warm and humid air will make slow progress toward the
Northeast as high pressure moves farther off the New England coast.
The leading edge of the sultry air will reach from North Carolina
to northern Iowa. Winds at 5,000 feet will transport large amounts
of moisture from the Gulf of Mexico into the central Appalachians
and Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A few disturbances in the jet stream will intersect this current
of humid air, leading to the development of several clusters of
thunderstorms from southern Michigan to western Virginia. Hail and
flooding rains are likely with these storms.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will encroach on the Northeast, but most sections will
stay dry and central New England may remain sunny. Showers,
associated with advancing summery weather, will dampen
Pennsylvania, southern New Jersey and western New York. In the
Middle Atlantic region, onshore winds will combine with thick
clouds to keep readings below seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   It will be steamy across most of the South with isolated thunder
in Florida. The progression of hot, dry air from Old Mexico into
the western Plains will lead to thunderstorms along the dry line
from the Big Bend to east central Kansas. In the vicinity of low
pressure over Iowa, a cluster of strong to severe thunderstorms may
form later in the day. The upper Middle West will be dull, damp and
mild.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front progressing into the Central Rockies will be
accompanied by thundershowers and followed by cooler, gusty winds.
A strong disturbance moving southward in California will promote
showers in the Central Valley and along the central coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Sprouting from the Ashes
</P>
<P>
   Fires continued to rage across northern and central Florida on
Wednesday. Anomalously dry, sunny weather has parched the area,
with some locations receiving less than half of their average
spring rains. Daytona Beach received a paltry 0.16 inch of rain in
May, which is only 5 percent of normal. While the fires wreak havoc
on area homes, the pine forests that cover the landscape of much of
Florida ironically benefit from the fires. Seeds in the pine cones
produced by the trees are released by the heat of the fires,
allowing new trees to germinate and replace aging trees in the
canopy.
</P>
</TEXT>
