 GEEK NOTES: Amazon Offering CD Music; Offerings of Y2K Fixes; Nader
Weighs In on Microsoft; Questions About Online Sex Survey; How Low
Will PC Prices Go?  
(ja) 
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Amazon Offering CD Music  &LR;  What a drumroll. Practically since
the day it opened three years ago, Amazon.com, the popular on-line
bookstore, has been considering an expansion into the audio CD
business. Finally, after dozens of focus groups and months of
building an editorial staff well versed in music, Amazon has
started selling tunes along with its books.
</P>
<P>
   The new music site certainly looks impressive. Customer
critiques get posted just as they do in the book section, and many
music categories are accompanied by primers. The catalog contains
more than 100,000 CD's, with 225,000 songs to sample using Real
Audio.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon executives recognize that book buyers and music buyers
can be very different breeds. ``Music people tend to take music
almost more personally than books,'' said David Risher, Amazon's
senior vice president for product development and marketing. ``You
don't hear people saying, `I hate biography, it makes my skin
crawl.' But talk to a jazz enthusiast and bring up New Age jazz
lite, and they'll break out into a rage.''
</P>
<P>
   When Amazon first began selling books on line, it largely had
the field to itself, but it faces well-established competition in
on-line music retailing. Music Boulevard  &UR; (www.musicblvd. &LR;   &UR; com) &LR; ,
CDnow  &UR; (www.cdnow.com) &LR;  and Tower Records  &UR; (www.towerrecords.com) &LR; 
are already far ahead of Amazon. Barnes &AMP; Noble is likely to enter
the audio CD business as well. Moreover, Amazon has yet to turn a
profit, and the pressure to keep spending money on building the
music business isn't likely to help its cause.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Borders and Bertelsmann are each venturing
into the on-line book retail market, as is W.H. Smith, of England,
with its purchase this week of  &UR; bookshop.co.uk &LR; , Europe's largest
Internet bookstore. Amazon can ill afford to get too distracted by
music.
</P>
<P>
   For now at least, Amazon officials are not including classical
music in the inventory, having decided that the vast library of
classical recordings is too problematic and complex.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Offerings of Y2K Fixes  &LR;  Beware of geeks bearing gifts. Lendlin
Limited, based in Britain, has made the exaggerated claim that ``99
percent of PCs in every office, factory, hospital, etc., will crash
at midnight Dec. 31, 1999, unless their programs are checked and
modified.'' For $15, the company will send you a program that tests
your machine, or you can download it free. For an additional $39.95
plus postage, you can buy a program that fixes the bug.
</P>
<P>
   The computer millennium glitch, or, as it is also known, the
Year 2000 bug, is a problem that primarily affects mainframe
computers that were programmed way back in the 1960s and 1970s to
recognize two digits for dates instead of four. Such computers
would interpret 2010, for example, as 1910.
</P>
<P>
   The digital apocalypse that some Cassandras _ consultants,
mostly _ expect to befall the planet come midnight on Dec. 31,
1999, should spare most personal computers, which each have a BIOS
(basic input/output system _ the software that starts the computer)
that contains the machine's internal clock.
</P>
<P>
   All Apple Macintoshes will accept the date change, and most PCs
made after 1995 are supposed to. Older PCs, running on 386 and 486
chips, may need a BIOS upgrade. Newer machines, even if they have a
problem, can be fixed easily by resetting the date with Windows or
DOS commands.
</P>
<P>
   If you are unsure about whether your BIOS will trip on the new
date, it is probably best to ask the computer's manufacturer. For
applications, like Microsoft Word or Intuit's Quicken, call the
software company and ask whether your program will recognize the
date change.
</P>
<P>
   Testing programs can also be downloaded free from several
Internet sites, including Survive 2000  &UR; (www.sbhs.com) &LR;  and YMark
2000  &UR; (www.nstl.com) &LR; . But be warned when using these tests. They
might cause your applications to lose data or expire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nader Weighs In on Microsoft  &LR;  As part of a year-old crusade
against Microsoft's dominance, the longtime consumer advocate Ralph
Nader has written to the chairman of International Business
Machines, Louis V. Gerstner, to say he thinks IBM should make
public the source code for its moribund OS/2 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Nader's reasoning is this: If OS/2 source code were freely
available, developers of application programs would jump at the
chance to write programs to run on OS/2, building a strong
alternative to Microsoft and Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Nader said in his letter, IBM should offer OS/2 as a
free option when selling its own computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised to learn that IBM will not permit consumers
to buy IBM Aptiva computers with IBM's OS/2 operating system
installed,'' Nader wrote. ``The only way to get OS/2 is to buy a PC
with Microsoft Windows 95 installed and then pay an extra $199 for
a shrink-wrapped copy of OS/2, which consumers will have to install
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Windows is so well entrenched on desktop computers that even IBM
shifted its strategy toward the Microsoft product. For a brief
period three years ago, IBM offered a feature called
Select-a-System, which allowed customers to choose between OS/2 and
Windows when starting up their computers. The majority chose
Windows, and IBM discontinued the program shortly thereafter. OS/2
is now used almost exclusively as a server operating system in
large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was also signed by Jamie Love, director of the
Consumer Project on Technology in Washington, who said he and Nader
had received several letters of support from OS/2 users. But they
have yet to get a response from IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Nader said in an interview: ``IBM stands for Intimidated by
Microsoft. They're doing in their own product, for heaven's sake.
It just shows you the power of Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Tara Sexton, an IBM spokeswoman, said Gerstner was traveling and
had not yet seen the letter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions About Online Sex Survey  &LR;  A survey of more than 9,000
MSNBC.com readers about their online sexual habits has generated
skepticism about the study's scientific soundness.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, 47 questions for people who had visited at least one
sex site, was posted on the MSNBC Web site over a seven-week period
in March and April.
</P>
<P>
   According to the preliminary findings, released earlier this
week, five times as many men than women responded to the survey.
Young women appear to be turning to cybersex sites in surprisingly
high numbers, more men look at visually explicit Web sites, and
more women visit sex-oriented chat rooms, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's director, Alvin Cooper, who runs a clinic for
marital and sexuality counseling in San Jose, Calif., said the
results confirmed what he had already suspected: online, at least,
women want relationships, and men want pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which has not been published in a scientific
journal, has many problems, its critics say. ``Not only was it not
random, but the self-selected sample is severely biased since you
had to have visited a sex site to participate,'' said Donna
Hoffman, an associate professor in the Owen School of Management at
Vanderbilt University. The survey, she said, should not be taken to
represent legitimate scientific research about the link between
human sexual behavior and its relation to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fun survey that tells something about what the people
who filled it out think about sex on the Net,'' Hoffman said. ``But
that's all it tells.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper agreed that the survey had its limitations but said:
``There are all kinds of ways to do science. Most people I know who
are familiar with sex and the Internet think this is a landmark
study.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How Low Will PC Prices Go?  &LR;  Just when it seemed safe to buy a
new computer, along comes another prediction of an imminent plunge
in PC prices. Last week, Ziff-Davis Market Intelligence predicted a
new shift downward. By the middle of next month, the report said,
the prices of computers selling for $1,000 will drop to $700 or
$800. And the price of a decent 17-inch color monitor will fall to
about $350. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a result of lower prices, the Ziff-Davis research group
declared, the number of homes in the United States with at least
one PC rose to 44.8 percent in 1997 from 40.7 percent in 1996. More
than 45 million American households now own PCs, the group said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
