<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3373 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VONDA-AZR &LR;      06-10 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VONDA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROONER TAKES ADVANTAGE OF NEWFOUND FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Everywhere Vonda Shepard goes, the question follows
her. It's enough to make her want to scream sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   It has nothing to do with the music on her albums, the songs she
writes, even the way she sings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask me, `How are you like Ally McBeal?' ''
Shepard says, calling from an Austin hotel room. ``And you didn't
ask me that _ yippee!''
</P>
<P>
   Her exuberance is understandable. After all, her career includes
five solo albums, backup work with Jackson Browne and Rickie Lee
Jones, even a hit duet with Dan Hill. But it took the quirky charms
of David E. Kelley's Fox sitcom to turn her into a household voice.
</P>
<P>
   That's Shepard's dusky, stars-at-midnight croon that sings the
lyrics that parallel the inner workings of the title character.
</P>
<P>
   She also appears on camera: Shepard is the ripe-looking blond
who performs in the saloon frequented by the show's cast members.
</P>
<P>
   At first, ``Ally McBeal'' seemed like it would be just another
job for the piano-playing New Yorker. But the offbeat comedy about
a career woman caught on with viewers, becoming something of a
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see it coming at all,'' a cheerful Shepard says. ``I
thought I was going to have a few songs in this show. Even once I
was on camera, with a regular gig working in the studio every week,
I didn't see it coming.''
</P>
<P>
   As the show grew in popularity, so did the call for Shepard's
music, which is featured in every episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``David started joking about doing a soundtrack, because he
wanted a CD for his own car,'' she says. ``Next thing I know, major
labels are calling about it. It was just wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony won the bidding war, and ``Songs From Ally McBeal'' has
been sitting in the nation's Top 10 since its release last month.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, especially for a performer who had scrapbooks full of
rave reviews but little luck achieving widespread success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't We Try,'' a rather anonymous duet with Canadian
balladeer Dan Hill, was a huge hit in 1987. But the next 10 years
of Shepard's shadowy career were marked by albums that sold only to
the converted. Her songwriting was sharp and literate, but it was a
small, select audience that clued in to what she was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in my career when I was not so well-known, people would
say, `God, you're so comfortable onstage,' '' she says. ``That was
a compliment, but it was also very frustrating. This last month and
a half, working on this large a scale, it's just been very
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to ``Ally McBeal,'' it's been a huge jump. A year ago you
could find her performing for small audiences at intimate LA
nightspots.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely the right time for all that's happened,''
she says. ``I'm just so thankful. I'm 34 years old. I have all this
energy, and I just love to work. It was driving me crazy, sitting
at home waiting for things to happen. Now it's time, and I want to
take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But every rose comes with its thorns. For example, ``Songs From
Ally McBeal'' may be sitting in a lot of people's homes, but it's
series star Calista Flockhart's face that smiles out from the front
cover. Shepard makes do with a photo on the rear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a strange, surreal feeling to be connected with a
TV show,'' she says. ``I'm sort of removed from it in a way. I
mean, it really makes sense to have her picture on there _ it is a
show about Ally McBeal. But the next one will definitely have my
picture on the front.''
</P>
<P>
   The next ``Ally'' disc, which is due after Shepard's next
non-``McBeal'' album appears later this year, will include a
greater number of original tunes. Much of the current album is
packed with covers of songs such as ``I Only Want to Be With You,''
`You
</P>
<P>
   Belong to Me'' and ``Walk Away Renee.''
</P>
<P>
   She handles the familiar tunes with verve and style, but she's
still a songwriter performing other people's songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, I'm sighing a big sigh,'' she says with a giggle.
``Through this medium, I've been able to expose people to the
original material, which is closest to my heart. I think of myself
as a writer as opposed to a singer, so it's strange.''
</P>
<P>
   A form of amends comes when she performs in concert. She sees
the enthusiastic way audiences respond to the cover tunes, most
which have played integral parts in ``Ally'' episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll play something like ``Hooked on a Feeling'' and I see the
fun people are having,'' she says. ``The audiences are very
high-energy and very excited to be there. There's a lighthearted
spirit to the whole thing, because the show has a lighthearted
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   But being a human karaoke machine, even one with a great
pedigree and a terrific set of pipes, was not part of Shepard's
game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, I'm the same person who writes very
diligently and spends a year perfecting a song,'' she says.
``Honestly, I guess I just don't want to be a novelty through
``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that's the big fear. Here's a gifted woman who has been
working at her craft since she was 14 years old. She doesn't want
to become this year's version of the Rembrandts, the Heights, or,
God forbid, Cyndi Grecco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that won't happen,'' she says. ``Hopefully, people
at the live shows will buy the older albums. They'll connect with
my songs. I mean, ``Ally McBeal'' is so different from other TV
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent so much time gearing the music exactly for the show,
but it had to fit my own personal specifications as an artist.
Hopefully, people will realize that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
