<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: FRANCE HONORS GONG LI;   BUSY DANCER; 
 COMMEMORATING PEGGY GUGGENHEIM ;  MATHEW BRADY RETROSPECTIVE;
SEGAL EXHIBITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., China)   (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Hong Kong Wednesday, the actress Gong Li received France's
highest arts award. Thierry Dana, the French consul general, pinned
the medal of the Officier des Arts et des Lettres to the diaphanous
dress of the star of films like ``Farewell, My Concubine.'' He
called the investiture the most pleasant duty during his two years
in Hong Kong. Ms. Li confessed to a love affair with France: ``It's
very beautiful, very romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Leap of Fete
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Scarcely will the curtain have rung down on his
American Ballet Theater season at the Metropolitan Opera House than
the star Vladimir Malakhov will vault across the plaza at Lincoln
Center to the New York State Theater to dance Romeo in the opening
of the Stuttgart Ballet's ``Romeo and Juliet.'' When the curtain
rises on the Lincoln Center Festival '98 attraction on July 7,
Yseult Lendvai will dance Juliet, and the former Stuttgart prima
ballerina Marcia Haydee will be Lady Capulet. Malakhov, whose run
with American Ballet Theater ends three days earlier, will also
appear in the Stuttgart's ``Onegin'' on July 9 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   Setting the Scene
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Commemorating the 100th anniversary of the birth of
Peggy Guggenheim, the Solomon Guggenheim Museum will trace the life
of this champion of contemporary art in an exhibition that opens
Friday. With paintings, sculptures, photographs and other
memorabilia, ``Peggy Guggenheim: A Centennial Celebration,''
continuing through Sept. 2, includes the first display of her
Venice guest books, containing the signatures, sketches, drawings,
poems, comments and musical notations of people like Jean Arp,
Cecil Beaton, Truman Capote, Jean Cocteau and Robert Motherwell.
</P>
<P>
   Image Maker
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mathew Brady, the most famous American photographer
of the 19th century, will be the focus of a major exhibition
opening Friday at the International Center of Photography Midtown.
In what is said to be the first gathering of the full range of his
work since his studio closed, this retrospective, running through
Sept. 6, will comprise more than 100 of his images, including early
daguerreotypes and Civil War scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Major Cast
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What is billed as the first major exhibition in some
20 years to be devoted to George Segal is to open on Sunday at the
Jewish Museum. The exhibition features works from 1958 to 1996 by
the Pop artist known for evocative sculptures of everyday people in
urban environments. Besides his freestanding sculptures, the
exhibition, continuing through Oct. 4, will include early pastels,
reliefs of the human body, recent larger-than-life portrait
drawings and other works.
</P>
</TEXT>
