<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3396 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LADY-DEEJAYS-AZR &LR;      06-10 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADY-DEEJAYS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMALE DEEJAYS READY TO BE JUST PLAIN DEEJAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DOROTHY PARVAZ and DAVID PROFFITT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Pop quiz: Name some hot hip-hop deejays.
</P>
<P>
   OK, who did you come up with? Rob Swift (of the X-ecutioners)?
Gearhead? Invisibl Skratch Piklz? DJ Faust?
</P>
<P>
   You're more or less on track. These guys are some of the top
spinners in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Now try and think of some female deejays.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, take your time.
</P>
<P>
   Boy oh boy, where are all the girls? They're out there, you just
don't hear much about them.
</P>
<P>
   A few female deejays across the country and in Arizona are
starting to make noise, but they still run into the attitude that
they're ``just girls'' who are hired by promoters who want to prove
their political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   It's a distinction that many of them wish would disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids don't really care (about the deejay's gender),'' says
Mara, a Phoenix area deejay who spins mostly electro, breakbeat and
house. ``The only people it really matters to are the promoter and
the other deejays . . . and it disappoints me that they're not
looking at who plays well.''
</P>
<P>
   She says everyone is too focused on bean counting.
</P>
<P>
   After all, promoters benefit from a gender gap because they can
say they've got female deejays on their fliers. But the problem is
that they still don't expect much from female deejays.
</P>
<P>
   Women get the gigs, but they don't get the respect. And the one
thing they'd like to see change _ that they're viewed as novelty
acts _ is precisely what gets them a lot of their gigs.
</P>
<P>
   The irony isn't lost on the deejays. Still, they'd rather
sacrifice a night's pay than play a gig they don't deserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're hiring me just because I'm a girl, I won't play for
you,'' Mara says. ``If you're good enough to be up there (on the
deejay stand), it shouldn't matter if you're a girl, a boy,
whatever. That's the thing that upsets me about people hiring
female deejays _ you wouldn't hire a male if he sucks.''
</P>
<P>
   After playing a couple of parties where she felt like she only
got a spot because she's female, she avoids becoming the token
woman on the flier by asking promoters who else is spinning and why
they asked her before agreeing to play.
</P>
<P>
   Mara's been playing out for about four years _ practically an
era in the high-turnover world of dance music _ but she says she
doesn't always get the same respect as her male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   DJ Symphony, the sole female member of the Beat Junkies, a Los
Angeles-based hip-hop crew, says women probably view deejaying as a
guy thing, while men don't take their female counterparts
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the male friends that have turntables might view a
girl as a groupie,'' she says, recalling how a woman she knew of
lost interest in deejaying. ``I guess they just sent her little
subliminal messages.''
</P>
<P>
   Other female deejays are beating the odds, such as the Valley's
Miss Jag, who started spinning darkstep and techstep jungle about a
year ago on a friend's decks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that I had natural beat-matching skills,'' she says.
``We ran out to Swell (Clothing and Records in Tempe), and he
bought me five or six records and told me to practice.''
</P>
<P>
   So she did.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of practice hours and a few dozen record purchases
later, she got a gig. Then another, and then another.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's getting out-of-state bookings and is about to come out
with her first mix tape.
</P>
<P>
   She said that being female definitely helped her get attention,
but that focusing on an accident of genetics takes attention away
from the most important thing for deejays _ how well they play the
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it should matter _ what would happen if I
dressed up like a guy? Would I get the attention? Probably not,''
she says. ``I think it's great to get attention, but I just want to
be known as a deejay.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucson deejay Lady Jane also started spinning jungle about a
year ago, and she's had the same quick rise as Miss Jag.
</P>
<P>
   At one point male deejays were asking (beginital)her (endital)
to help them get jobs, an uncomfortable experience since they'd
been spinning two or three times longer than she had.
</P>
<P>
   She attributes this to female deejays' being something of a
novelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Promoters talk to so many guys, they must feel like it's the
same thing all the time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the long run, deejays will earn respect for solid skills,
not the type of hormones they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that some people are like, `Girl deejays!
We need more!' but that's not it for me,'' Miss Jag says. ``For me,
it comes down to the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Such success could open the field to more women. San Jose-based
DJ Dazy is optimistic. She runs an online mailing list called
``sisterdjs'' from her Web site (www.djdazy.com), with about 90
subscribers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more female deejays everywhere,'' Dazy says.
``When I first started deejaying six years ago, I could count all
the women deejays on my hands. I think in the next couple years we
are going to see (beginital) a lot (end ital) more female deejays
playing out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3410 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUICIDE-BARRIER-HNS &LR;      06-10 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUICIDE-BARRIER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO CONSIDERS SUICIDE BARRIER FOR GOLDEN GATE BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As tourists and locals both know so well, the
Golden Gate Bridge offers breathtaking views of San Francisco, the
Bay, Alcatraz and more.
</P>
<P>
   But the bridge's darker draw is well documented too: more than
1,200 people have jumped to their deaths by simply leaping over its
four-foot railing.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to prevent that loss of life, Bridge District
officials on Tuesday unveiled a 100-foot expanse of horizontal
steel wiring that could someday run the entire length of the bridge
as a suicide barrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our best effort with the least impact (on
aesthetics),'' said district engineer Merv Giacomini, anticipating
the expected public criticism of a barrier placed on the famous
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gate Bridge, which crosses the San Francisco Bay to
connect the city with Marin County, has two huge towers more than
700 feet tall. The bridge itself is 220 feet above the water.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction already has been mixed to plans for a suicide barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist Nicole Houck of Seattle questioned the need for a
suicide barrier on such a historic bridge, objecting to anything
that obstructs the views.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person wants to commit suicide, they'll find a way to do
it even if it's not on the bridge,'' Houck, 28, said.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Killebrew of Alameda, Calif., had a different opinion,
having lost a daughter to suicide on the bridge 27 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been vitally interested intrying to prevent others from
doing what my daughter did,'' Killebrew said. ``If this can work
... then I'm all for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The barrier, designed by Z-Clip International Fence Systems, is
made of horizontal, high-tension steel wires spaced 4 inches apart
with fasteners every 6 feet or so. The design has been used for
agriculture and security purposes, but never on a bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the district has considered roughly 20 other
proposals, including a barbed wire fence, U-shaped spikes on top of
the rail, a clear plastic screen and a low-voltage electric fence.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed barrier would have to clear numerous hurdles. First
would be a series of tests to determine if a suicidal person would
be able to scale the 11-foot high fence or cut through it.
</P>
<P>
   Should it prove a successful deterrent, the barrier would then
have clear state and federal historic and aesthetic regulations.
The final challenge would be for the bridge district to fund the $2
million to $3 million project.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide prevention experts have lobbied hard for the barrier,
saying it will be an effective deterrent for many of the impulsive
individuals who want to commit suicide from the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bridge is so easily available,'' said Dr. Richard Seiden,
a psychiatrist who studied several hundred people who were stopped
from jumping from the bridge. ``There is a mystical quality to it.
A barrier would make it more difficult. The feelings of suicide
usually pass. It's a permanent solution to a temporary problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
