<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A HEAD ON STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday June 12)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say what you want about our accuracy, our credibility or our
hidden political agendas: Newspapers are still No. 1 when it comes
to goofy headlines.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are actual headlines taken from actual newspapers
produced by actual people who may or may not have been actually
awake at the time:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN BF)Hospitals Are Sued by 7 Foot Doctors(END BF)
</P>
<P>
   Why are all these extremely tall doctors suing hospitals? Was it
a discrimination thing or does it have to do with uncomfortably low
doorways or the lack of basketball courts in the operating rooms?
Or were these doctors normal-sized until they started eating the
hospital cafeteria food? I've always suspected that hospital
gelatin contained some sort of a radioactive substance.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN BF)Ban on Soliciting Dead in Trotwood(END BF)
</P>
<P>
   Well, good for Trotwood! The dead have enough to worry about,
what with decomposition and maggots and everything, without having
to put up with a bunch of overeager solicitors trying to sell them
credit cards or air conditioner tuneups. Now if Trotwood can just
take it one step further and ban soliciting of the living, then it
would really be on to something.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN BF)Local High School Dropouts Cut in Half(END BF)
</P>
<P>
   While I agree that we should do everything we can to encourage
kids to get an education, this seems a bit extreme. Perhaps we
should first suggest counseling or maybe even vo-tech before we cut
them in half.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN BF)Teacher Strikes Idle Kids(END BF)
</P>
<P>
   Once again, I have to think that this is the wrong approach to
achieving academic excellence. I don't approve of corporal
punishment in any form, but to strike kids who are just sitting
there doing nothing seems flat-out cruel. Just the same, if I were
in that class, I'd make sure I stayed busy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN BF)Juvenile Court to Try Shooting Defendant(END BF)
</P>
<P>
   Man, it's tough being a kid these days! You drop out of high
school and they cut you in half; you sit there doing nothing and
they strike you; and you make a mistake and wind up in juvenile
court and they try to shoot you! I'm as worried about juvenile
crime as the next person, but I think we're going way over the line
here. Sure, he might deserve to be shot if he's guilty, but what if
he's not? And what if all he did was steal a bicycle or soap some
windows? Does he deserve to be shot for that? All I can say is glad
not a kid anymore because Id look like a piece of Swiss cheese.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN BF)Cold Wave Linked to Temperatures(END BF)
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's good to know. I always figured it had something to
do with the Asian stock market or maybe Monica Lewinsky. But what
kind of temperatures are we talking about here? Cold temperatures?
Hot temperatures? Middle-of-the-road temperatures? Clearly, we need
to fork over a big wad of federal grant money so this matter can be
studied in more detail.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN BF)Survivor of Siamese Twins Joins Parents(END BF)
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying to put myself in the shoes (shoe?) of the surviving
Siamese twin here. Life has dealt you a really bad hand. You and
your brother or sister have just undergone an extremely dangerous
operation and you were the only one to come out alive. Maybe, just
maybe, you're not thinking real clearly at this point. You're
looking for someone to blame and your parents seem a likely
candidate. It all their fault! Well, Momsie and Popsie, let's just
see how you like it! You get out a needle and thread and ... well,
what follows is just too gruesome to write about in a family
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The HERALD TRIBUNE, SARASOTA, FLORIDA
</P>
</TEXT>
