<HEADER>
A3428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOCASTA-OPERA-REVIEW-     06-10 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOCASTA-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEMINIST LOOK AT SOPHOCLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The theater company Voice and Vision, now in its
eighth year, is committed to developing works by and about women
and girls. The strength of this commitment is clear from the latest
theater work the company has commissioned, ``Jocasta,'' which uses
opera, dance and the spoken word to tell the story of Oedipus from
the imagined perspective of Jocasta.
</P>
<P>
   This is an all-female creation: the text is an English-language
version of a French libretto by Helene Cixous, the music is by the
Hamburg-born American composer Ruth Schonthal, the director is
Marya Mazor, the conductor is Teresa P. Cheung, the choreographer
is Christine Sang and the sets, costumes and lighting were designed
by women.
</P>
<P>
   The feminist spin on this seminal Sophocles tragedy was the
work's most intriguing element on Tuesday night at the Cornelia
Connelly Center for Education on East 8th St. in Manhattan, where
Voice and Vision presents its work. Jocasta is presented as a woman
deeply scarred by having been abandoned, as she sees it, by her
father when he went off to die. So later, as the wife of Oedipus,
she is fearful of abandonment by him. When Oedipus learns that he
is in fact Jocasta's son, she claims to have known it all along.
Refusing to be bound by convention, including the ``names'' of
mother and wife, she entreats him to defy the taboo and remain with
her, and charges that he, too, on some primal level, was attracted
by her resemblance to him.
</P>
<P>
   The libretto is long, philosophical and poetically stylized.
Setting it all to music would have made the work as long as
``Parsifal,'' hence Ms. Schonthal's decision to employ almost equal
portions of spoken and sung text. Jocasta is triply portrayed by an
actress (Mary Magdalena Hernandez), a soprano (Wilma Wever) and a
dancer (Dawn Akemi Saito); Oedipus is similarly portrayed by both
an actor (Russell Hornsby) and a baritone (Thomas Meglioranza).
</P>
<P>
   But mixing large spans of spoken dialogue into opera is never
easy. Language is direct and specific and can be overpowering. It
was especially so in this production because the actors' voices
were heavily amplified through body microphones. To match them, the
singers, chorus and pianist (Max Midroit) also had to rely on
amplification (microphones placed about the stage), which nullified
the intimacy of this wonderful 110-year-old, 200-seat theater.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schonthal, who fled Nazi Germany, studied with Hindemith at
Yale, and her style has some of the thickly chromatic
Neo-Classicism of her teacher. Her musical language is essentially
tonal, though spiked with dissonance. And though not especially
innovative, her work has an authentic voice. She also uses pastiche
effectively, as in some swaths of Romanticism that sounded like
disoriented Rachmaninoff. But the constant switching from sung to
spoken lines gets tiring and prevents the drama from having an
inexorable flow.
</P>
<P>
   The production is appropriately stark, and the gifted young cast
is attractive and engaging. Yet in striving to be weighty and
gripping, ``Jocasta'' gets draggy and ponderous.
</P>
<P>
   The final two performances are Thursday night and Saturday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
