<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-STANDARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK RECOMMENDS MORE READING FOR STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RICK KARLIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If students are going to meet New York's higher
academic standards, they need to start reading 25 books a year and
write 1,000 words each month, top state educators say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big leap, and you can see it in the (bookless)
backpacks of students,'' Education Commissioner Richard Mills said
Tuesday. ``Ask students how much they read and it's not close to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills and Carl Hayden, chancellor of the state Board of Regents,
announced new English curriculum guidelines, including a list of
dozens of suggested books, poems, plays and periodicals that
students from prekindergarten through 12th grade should be reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``This also sends a powerful message to parents,'' Hayden said,
explaining that adults must ``wean'' their kids off television,
video games and other distractions, if the youngsters are to find
the time for 25 books a year.
</P>
<P>
   Some students, though, said the new guidelines were too
ambitious. ``That's too many,'' Albany High School ninth-grader
Nieishia Lloyd said. She figures she reads about a half-dozen books
a year for English class, with the most recent being ``Romeo and
Juliet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten is more realistic,'' added sophomore Latasha White, who
just polished off Stephen King's ``Misery'' in her English class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I don't really like to read,'' said Marybeth Henry,
a junior. Henry, who just finished ``Macbeth,'' reads about a
half-dozen books a year and peruses magazines like Readers Digest.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines are not mandatory, but state officials said that,
if followed, the reading and writing will help students pass the
new Regents requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines, which are outlined in workbooks and CD-ROMs
being sent to all the state's schools, also are intended to satisfy
critics, including teachers, who in the past have said they need
guidance on how to help students reach the upgraded standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted more details and we've responded to that,'' Hayden
said. ``It's part of our continuing promise to you and to the
public to make the standards clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Regents, which sets state education policy, has
embarked on an ambitious plan to have all high school students pass
a sequence of college-prep level Regents exams in order to earn a
high school diploma. This plan, which replaces the easier
non-Regents tests that more than half the state's students now
take, is being phased in over several years.
</P>
<P>
   English will be the first Regents test students will have to
take. This year's 10th-graders are all required to pass the test in
order to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Mills described the reading list as ``a series of very, very
strong suggestions'' for schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most common question in the classroom is: `What's going to
be on the test?''' Mills said. ``This is going to be on the test.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials emphasized students won't have to answer factual
questions about the books on the list, such as names and dates. But
students will perform better on essay questions if they have read
from the list.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the list, derived largely from a survey of English and
reading teachers, consists of classics that would be recognizable
to the baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   The list seemed to avoid any controversial books, though it
contains J.D. Salinger's ``Catcher in the Rye,'' which has been
criticized by fundamentalist Christians as being too racy, and Mark
Twain's ``The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn,'' which has come
under fire for use of a racial slur to describe blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``These books are books that teachers teach today; they've been
teaching them for years,'' state Education Department spokesman
Bill Hirschen said. The guidelines also call for lots of practice
for students to hone their writing skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no secrets or shortcuts,'' Roseanne DeFabio,
coordinator of curriculum and instruction, said of how writing
should be taught. ``It's repetition. Over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's largest teachers union welcomed the guidelines. ``It
sounds as if the commissioner is adding to the new standards
something we've been asking him to do for a long time,'' said Linda
Rosenblatt, spokeswoman for the New York State United Teachers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
