<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY11-COX     06-10 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yoakam again proves he's off-center but right on target
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 15-plus years since Dwight Yoakam emerged from the
honky-tonk Los Angeles club scene, a question has dogged his
career: Is he making country music, or is he pretending to make
country music? Certainly the lanky star was a product of cloning in
the early days, lifting heavily from Buck Owens' Brylcreem-era
tunes in search of his own style. These two albums _ one from the
man himself and the other a collection of others covering his work
_ show that Yoakam has evolved into much more than pouty pantomime.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he still pulls styles out of his cowboy hat like a master
mimic. The Owens-influenced tune ``The Curse'' has Yoakam
stretching the accent (``These are the thangs I wish fer you'')
with whiny backing vocals straight out of the Bonnie Owens
songbook. ``Things Change'' is built over a dramatic guitar riff
lifted from the Animals' ``It's My Life.'' And this time he dips
into circa-1965 Nashville-sound strings on ``Yet to Succeed'' and
``I'll Just Take These,'' which both sound a lot like Jack Greene's
``Statue of a Fool.'' But what a combination of flair and
experimentation. Though never quite accepted by the Nashville
establishment, Yoakam's albums are like lightning bolts over
today's predictable country landscape, making your hair stand on
end with their energy.
</P>
<P>
   The album of cover tunes, ``Will Sing for Food'' (a benefit for
the homeless), proves that he's not entirely a product of slick
production. In the hands of other artists, such as sweet Sara
Evans, sassy Kim Richey or the haunting Gillian Welch, Yoakam
classics such as ``The Distance Between You and Me'' and ``Miner's
Prayer'' show that his songs can stand alone long after his tight
pants get thrown over a chair. A gospel piano and dobro version of
``I Sang Dixie,'' by bluegrass songbird Rhonda Vincent, confirms
that this tune may be one of the best wallow-in-it country
tear-jerkers ever written.
</P>
<P>
   These two CDs prove it: Like the cousin who left home and went
to college up North, Yoakam's a little different from mainstream
Nashville, but he's still the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Long Way Home''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Yoakam. Reprise. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   ``Will Sing for Food:
</P>
<P>
   The Songs of Dwight Yoakam''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Little Dog. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A killer double dose of Dwight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
