<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN14-COX     06-10 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Curse all bad drivers and bless the good, male and female
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 14: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend brought up the old subject that I like boys better than
girls. She said she knew I was glad that our newest baby, Jack, is
a boy.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I'm glad Jack is Jack, but I would have liked a girl baby,
too. She said she knew I had always thought men drivers were better
than women drivers, and I said no such thing. I know some good ones
and some bad ones of both sexes.
</P>
<P>
   The golden-haired beauty who is bad to tailgate and will pull up
on your left side at an intersection, blocking the view of oncoming
traffic, is not my favorite _ but neither is her brother, if he
does the same. I understand, but do not like, the old lady who
scolds you by tapping her horn if she thinks you are slow to turn
right on red. I don't think her husband would do that, but then
he's never with her. Maybe he hates her, too.
</P>
<P>
   Just because I have said I find truck drivers the most courteous
drivers doesn't mean I like men truck drivers better than women. I
think truck drivers in general are taught courtesy. They will let
you change lanes in front of them, and they will stop if you have
trouble on the road and make a barrier of their truck to divert
traffic. I have even had a truck driver for one of the big lines
stop and shoo me and my children passengers back off the shoulder
and change a tire for me.
</P>
<P>
   My friend thought she had me trapped when I admitted that some
of my best friends are men. You don't work with men all your life
without developing affection and admiration for some of them. But
then, there are women very dear to me, too. It's a dumb question.
Men or women? We seem to need both.
</P>
<P>
   It gives me extra sympathy for the single-parent family. The
old-fashioned concept that a household needs a man has a lot to
commend it. I don't mean just economically. Nowadays, most women
have found ways to support their families.
</P>
<P>
   But what does a kid do when he has a splinter in his foot
calling for the blade of a little pocketknife? My mother would
wield a needle, but when I drove a big splinter from Seymour Creek
bridge into my bare heel, she couldn't find it. She simply held my
hands and made soothing noises while my father made a quick slit
with his little knife and the ugly splinter popped out. He taught
me to paddle a boat and to cast for bream in the millpond. He
showed me how to regulate the flow of water through the big dam so
I could scrub my body without drowning. He taught me how to change
the tire on the little Ford he bought me when I got a job in town.
I could even clean spark plugs then but probably not now.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to teach me to be quiet. When my mother raged about
anything, he was a tolerant listener. I may have missed that
talent, but I know it exists and is probably a special masculine
trait.
</P>
<P>
   When I was sick, I wanted my mother and did not particularly
want him sitting on the side of the bed taking my temperature. Muv
did not believe in thermometers. The palm of her hand was more
accurate, she felt.
</P>
<P>
   I was warmed and proud of his pride in military service, and I
believed implicitly in his religion. (My mother could change hers
to suit the occasion.)
</P>
<P>
   I only wish that the young boys in the family, even baby Jack,
could have benefited by his calmness, his patience, his masculine
know-how with machinery and guns and knives.
</P>
<P>
   Boy children or girl children? Give me both.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
