<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-BRACELET-COX     06-10 0190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BRACELET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slinky-style bracelets make a bold fashion statement when worn
by the bunch
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 14: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The more the merrier. That's the sentiment of women all over
town who are slipping into something cheap and slinky: the newly
popular guitar string bracelets that you buy _ and wear _ by the
bunch.
</P>
<P>
   At stores such as the Limited, these gold-and silver-toned
bracelets sell at $10 for a pack of 20. That's the going rate for
them as well at the Beth Ann Image and Accessory Boutique in
Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you put on, the stronger the statement they make,''
said the boutique's owner, Beth Ann Taratoot. ``The rage among
those customers of mine who can afford it is to buy 50 or more.''
</P>
<P>
   The guitar string bracelets _ alternately referred to as
``slinkies'' _ come in a thicker version that costs $1 each.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Limited and Beth Ann's, they're also sold at
Saks Fifth Avenue and Erika Reade Ltd..
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
