<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ROCK11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jeff Buckley release highlights our loss
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On May 29, 1997, Jeff Buckley drowned in Memphis, where he was
about to begin recording. Those sessions were to be his second pass
at a follow-up to 1994's ``Grace,'' his excellent full-length
debut.
</P>
<P>
   After recording some ``official studio demos'' with former
Television main man Tom Verlaine as producer, Buckley was to be
joined by ``Grace'' producer Andy Wallace to record an album he
planned to call ``My Sweetheart the Drunk.'' The demos have been
remixed here and, even in their incomplete state, are a sprawling
and ambitious step forward. Songs such as ``The Sky Is a Landfill''
and ``Nightmares by the Sea,'' with guitars that slash and burn,
sit side by side with the quiet beauty of ``Morning Theft'' and
``You &AMP; I.'' Buckley had a masterful way with dynamics and the
vocal brilliance to pull off most anything he put his mind to.
</P>
<P>
   The second of the two discs contains mostly solo four-track
demos that document the early stages of songs Buckley had been
working on in Memphis. He was an electrifying solo performer
onstage, and many of these low-fi tracks capture some of that
spark.
</P>
<P>
   The recording process can capture only so much, though, and it's
a tragedy that we'll never again hear Buckley's living, breathing
voice, dark, sweet and gooey as caramel. He could have made a
grocery list sound sensual. The set ends, as his memorial service
did, with a version of ``Satisfied Mind,'' which somehow gains
added poignance from the singer's clearing his throat between
verses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sketches for
</P>
<P>
   My Sweetheart
</P>
<P>
   the Drunk''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Buckley. Columbia. 20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A moving and lovingly compiled musical epitaph.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
