<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ashbury ignores critics as publishing company thrives
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Robin Asbury left the University of South Carolina Press
three years ago to launch her own publishing company in Columbia,
few of her colleagues expected her to succeed in such a risky
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically told me I was crazy,'' says Asbury. ``I was 41
and I had just had a baby when
</P>
<P>
   I started the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, thanks to unexpected tips from friends, Summerhouse
Press has become a success. A friend of a friend steered actor Jack
Palance to her with a long poem, ``Forest of Love,'' which became
her first best seller. The next bit of good fortune came when
another friend told her about Lorraine Johnson-Coleman. The
African-American storyteller's book, ``Just Plain Folks,'' resulted
in a contract as a commentator with National Public Radio and a
four-book deal with Little, Brown in the low seven figures. ``Just
Plain Folks'' is a collection of stories about African-American
burial rites, worship, courtship and cultural traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Little, Brown deal has given us a financial base we didn't
have before,'' Asbury says. And it has brought Summerhouse a lot of
attention. At the recent BookExpo America convention in Chicago,
big publishers Ballantine and Doubleday stopped by the booth to
inquire about its fall books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should develop a niche,'' says Asbury, who is publishing a
novel about Blackbeard the pirate and a Confederate housewife's
cookbook, ``but right now I'm just interested in finding good
writers.''
</P>
<P>
   -- DOWN ON PONCE: Casting is not completed for the movie version
of Fred Willard's novel ``Down on Ponce'' (Longstreet, $12), but
the Atlanta writer says everything else seems to be on track. ``No
shooting date has been set,'' he says. ``That'll be determined
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Willard has finished his second novel, ``Princess
Naughty and the Voodoo Cadillac,'' and is waiting to shop it to
publishers. Like ``Down on Ponce,'' this one is set in Atlanta.
``There are double-crosses, betrayals, shootouts and an alarming
amount of money involved,'' Willard says. One of the characters,
Ray Justice, has a porn shop that he uses to launder drug money.
Princess Naughty is his employee, and the Voodoo Cadillac is Ray's
car.
</P>
<P>
   Willard, who worked as a free-lancer and news photographer
before becoming disabled with arthritis, says one of the nice
things about success at 50 is that ``you don't have to stop and
figure out who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   -- IN THE LITERARY PIPELINE: When it comes to being prolific,
Joyce Carol Oates doesn't have to worry about competition from
Fannie Flagg. It's been 11 years since ``Fried Green Tomatoes at
the Whistle Stop Cafe'' appeared. Flagg, whose novel ``Welcome to
the World, Baby Girl'' is scheduled for fall publication, blames
the delay on screenwriting assignments and a severe case of
dyslexia. Her new novel is about a woman of Swedish descent from
Missouri, with a long-hidden secret, who becomes a famous
newscaster (think Diane Sawyer).
</P>
<P>
   -- LAMMIES: Atlanta Journal-Constitution staffer Lisa C. Moore
was a double winner recently at the Lambda Literary Awards in
Chicago. Moore won both the Lesbian Studies and the Small Press
Award for ``Does Your Mama Know?'' (Redbone), a collection of
essays that she edited.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
