<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Somebody's gotta do it
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--He's arrived, late, unaware he's late, unaware he's
arrived: a post-fired, post-walked-out-on, pre-banned Norm
Macdonald.
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald is in some big identity-challenged room inside the
Ritz-Carlton Buckhead with a bunch of people trying to work up
enthusiasm for promoting ``Dirty Work,'' a new big-screen comedy
Macdonald co-wrote and stars in. It opens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just looking forward to seeing 'Godzilla,''' says
Macdonald, who thought ``Dirty Work'' would be eaten alive at the
box office by opening the same weekend as the lizard movie. The
studio later decided to delay ``Dirty Work.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the ``Weekend Update'' host (and former ``Roseanne''
writer) was considered the funniest thing on ``Saturday Night
Live'' (Rolling Stone: ``At least there's one reason to watch
'Saturday Night Live' this year.'' TV Guide: ``(Macdonald) has
emerged as yet another 'SNL' success story'').
</P>
<P>
   Then things went in another direction: last year, virtually an
entire audience in Iowa walked out on Macdonald's stand-up act
(same thing happened later in Connecticut); late last fall, NBC
entertainment honcho Don Ohlmeyer ordered Macdonald fired from
``SNL''; and last week Ohlmeyer forbade NBC from running ads for
``Dirty Work'' (the ban has since been lifted).
</P>
<P>
   ``I retired from show business for a while,'' sums up Macdonald.
``I got to spend more time with my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's unretired with ``Dirty Work,'' a comedy co-starring
Jack Warden and Artie Lange (``Mad TV'') and directed by Bob Saget
(``America's Funniest Home Videos''). It's about two guys who open
a revenge business (the movie wasn't previewed for critics). When
we could catch Macdonald's attention at the Ritz, here's some
things he talked about.
</P>
<P>
   -- On what it's like being directed by Bob Saget: ``I've been
asked that question 10,000 times, and I've yet to come up with an
answer that doesn't sound like I'm lying. I mean, who were we gonna
get? I was pushing for Ricky Schroder, but he was unavailable.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On getting fired from ``SNL'': ``The president of the network
didn't like me so he fired me from the fake news. It never happened
before _ not in midseason. It's very hard to get hired on ('SNL'),
and it's even harder to get fired.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On Don Ohlmeyer: ``He's kind of a ... a ... idiot. He's not a
smart man.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On breaking into comedy: ``I did manual labor until I was 25.
Then I went to a comedy club and realized it pays better and it was
a very, very easy job. I was attracted by its complete easiness.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On why people have walked out on his act: ``They don't think
I'm funny. When you're trying to be funny and people don't think
you're funny, then they hate your guts.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On working on ``SNL'': ``I loved it. We had a free reign to
do whatever was funny. For a performer and writer, it's one of the
best places to be.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On his future on TV: ``I've been offered sitcoms. But I can't
think of one I would do. Every one I can think of seems retarded.
All I do now is stand-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
