<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIREVIEWS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of the latest sights on video
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Afterglow'' (R) _ Leaves so little aftertaste that if it
weren't for Oscar nominee Julie Christie's glow, you'd forget you'd
ever seen it. A long-wed, long-estranged couple (Christie and Nick
Nolte) unwittingly (and separately) become involved with a
maritally challenged younger couple (Lara Flynn Boyle and Jonny Lee
Miller). Sometimes, director Alan Rudolph's meandering character
studies end up somewhere remarkable. Sometimes, like this one, they
... just ... end.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The End of Violence'' (R) _ Wim Wenders' first American
work since 1984's ``Paris, Texas'' is set in Los Angeles, where the
filmmaker tries to take on everything from Big-Brother-is-watching
paranoia to big-bucks, no-brainer action flicks. Bill Pullman as a
producer of ultraviolent movies and Traci Lind as a sexy stuntwoman
are two of a half-dozen characters wandering through the strained
plot. What ensues is a movie in which teeny-tiny moments grab your
attention while the bulk of the film is like watching outtakes from
a failed Robert Altman experiment. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Tango Lesson'' (PG) _ A movie with two left feet.
Filmmaker Sally Potter (``Orlando'') returns in a dual role as
director and actress. She plays a filmmaker named Sally (hmmm ...)
who funnels her creative frustrations into taking up tango lessons.
She also takes up with her tango teacher, a luscious hunk named
Pedro (Pablo Veron). The movie has its good points. The seductive
sheen of the black-and-white cinematography is one. Another is
Veron, sheer poetry in motion. But the whole thing starts to remind
you of Katharine Hepburn's ``Summertime.'' But that was in the
1950s, and Hepburn could act. This is the '90s, and Potter ...
well, let's hope what she really wants to do is direct. Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
