<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SCREAM2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frightful sequel a screaming delight
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Scream 2'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   Still a scream _ in both the scary and the funny sense.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Kevin Williamson and director Wes Craven, the team that
made ``Scream'' the unexpected hit of 1996, take scary sequels as
their target this time around. Neve Campbell returns as our
beleaguered heroine Sidney, now enrolled in picturesque Windsor
College (it's actually Agnes Scott in Decatur), where a masked
killer is prowling around with a butcher knife.
</P>
<P>
   The players (and suspects) from the original movie include
Courteney Cox's ruthless TV reporter, David Arquette's goofy
ex-lawman, Jamie Kennedy as the video-clerk-turned-film-student,
and Liev Schrieber in his expanded role as the guy Sidney wrongly
fingered for her mother's death. Supporting players: Jada Pinkett
Smith, Sarah Michelle Gellar, Laurie Metcalfe and Jerry O'Connell.
The flick gets some of its best mileage from a film-within-a-film
based on the original ``Scream,'' remade with Tori Spelling in the
Campbell part.
</P>
<P>
   No, ``Scream 2'' can't recapture the bracing experience of the
first film. But it gets as close as you could hope for.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A -
</P>
<P>
   -- Other Wes Craven thrillers: ``Swamp Thing,'' ``A Nightmare on
Elm Street,'' ``Shocker,'' ``Wes Craven's New Nightmare,''
``Scream''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
