<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3469 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-ROMANCE-COX     06-10 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ROMANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Romance Reviews
 &HT;    By Helen Holzer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Hostage Bride.'' By Jane Feather. Bantam. $5.99. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The first in Jane Feather's ``Bride'' trilogy is a feather in
her cap and one of her best stories ever. Portia is the poor
relation, a brash, illegitimate 14-year-old caught between feuding
families in 17th-century England. Lady Olivia is her shy,
stuttering cousin, and Lady Phoebe is the ugly-duckling younger
sister of a great beauty who's rotten inside. The three girls meet
at a wedding and pledge never to marry but to follow their hearts'
desires.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Rough Around the Edges.'' By Susan Johnson, Dee Holmes,
Stephanie Laurens and Eileen Wilks. St. Martin's. $5.99. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Four stories. Four men. And all of them ``Rough Around the
Edges.'' But these tough guys are putty in the hands of the right
women. ``Playing With Fire'' by Susan Johnson, queen of erotic
romance, is the highlight. ``Fire'' has a young duke thrown into
marriage with an equally unwilling bride because he needs her
father's money. Wish this was the whole book instead of just 80
pages.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Perfect Scandal.'' By Kit
</P>
<P>
   Garland. Dell. $5.99. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   The murder mystery takes a back seat to romance in this tale of
a poor little rich girl sent from America to marry British royalty.
She falls for a poor painter, and the rest is elementary.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Bequest.'' By Candice Proctor. Ivy. $5.99. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Writers are advised to write about what they know. Last year,
Australian Candice Proctor wrote a brilliant first novel, ``Night
in Eden'' (B+), set in Australia. Her second book, ``The Bequest,''
is an awful western about a woman who inherits a brothel. It's
chock-full of cliches and in poor taste. If there's a third book,
let's hope it's set in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Wedding Chase.'' By Rebecca Kelley. Bantam. $5.50.
Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   This is an interesting first novel. But the murder plot is
superfluous, and the author must get rid of those names. Grizelda
and Wolfgang? Poor Grizelda wanted to marry a rich old man for his
money, while Wolf just wanted an amorous fling. Their hormones take
over, and soon ``The Wedding Chase'' is on.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Night of the Dragon.'' By Peggy Webb. Loveswept. $3.50.
Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   This ``Dragon'' is definitely a drag. It has a few interesting
moments, but this time-travel tale harking back to Camelot is
better left untold.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Texas Glory.'' By Lorraine Heath. Topaz. $5.99. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Keep the hankies handy for teary Part 2 of a trilogy about two
Texas brothers. The first, ``Texas Destiny'' (B+), told of a bride
who falls in love with the brother of the man she's supposed to
marry. In ``Texas Glory,'' the spurned brother finds another bride,
but things go wrong once again. Lorraine Heath is a powerful writer
of westerns, but she has yet to top her masterful Civil War drama,
``Always Remember.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Romance of the Rose.'' By Julie Beard. Berkley. $5.99.
Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Julie Beard has moved from grim medievals to lighter
Elizabethan themes. And what a name-dropper. William Shakespeare.
Queen Elizabeth. They're both here _ but stuck with the rest of us
_ trying to escape the Bloody Tower and the silly plot, centering
on home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Magic.'' By Kimberly Cates. Pocket. $6.50. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Fallon calls upon an ancient legend to save her Irish people
from the hated English soldiers. When it seems that her call has
been answered, as an injured, naked man appears, she believes it's
magic. This soap opera just seems to drag on forever.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
