<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-COX     06-10 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `The horror' Mary Thweatt painted helps others cope with disease
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--Draw cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Thweatt put her left hand to pen and paper, closed her eyes
and let her heart guide her through ``the horror'' of breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosis. Mastectomy. Chemotherapy. Drowning. Self-hate.
Renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Thweatt, 81, drew each step of the disease _ and her own dread _
five years ago in an art workshop after the removal of her right
breast and three months of chemotherapy. The class was taught by
Atlanta artist Sandi Grow, who suggested that Thweatt try the
unconventional method of closing her eyes and sketching with her
nondominant hand. The technique is taken from the book ``No More
Secondhand Art: Awakening the Artist Within'' by Peter London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd concentrate on a thought, a feeling, an emotion and try to
express it in one single line,'' Thweatt says. ``I kept doing it
repeatedly on different pieces of paper, concentrating on one
thought. Then, I would open my eyes and see if that's what I wanted
to say. Then, I'd go onto another thought or feeling. At the end of
the day, I would take out the colors and work on the design.''
</P>
<P>
   Thweatt, a retired international buyer for Rich's department
store, resumed drawing at her Buckhead townhouse after the
discovery of a cancerous lump on her neck last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really fell to pieces,'' she says. ``I went through the same
horror story and I started drawing again. I want to do one on my
search for peace because that's all you can do. You destroy
yourself if you just dwell on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Resembling folk art, Thweatt's images are stark and powerful,
simple drawings painted with oil color sticks. Her art will be on
display Saturday at the Swissotel at the ``Celebration of Living''
cancer survivors' events sponsored by Emory Hospitals and the
Winship Cancer Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are powerful because they come from deep within her,''
Grow says of Thweatt's work. ``Art doesn't need to be pretty. It
has to express what the artist needs to express. I think it's very
courageous of Mary to share this with others.''
</P>
<P>
   While Thweatt was taking Grow's class, she was also meeting
weekly with breast cancer survivors at an Emory Clinic support
group led by Kaye Coker, coordinator of social services.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was hesitant to show us her illustrations because she lays
no claim to being an artist,'' Coker recalls. ``But when the group
saw them, it was incredibly moving. Everyone was struck with the
resonance of the experience and how universal it is. It shows the
scars in different places, inside and out.''
</P>
<P>
   The group, which still informally gathers at members' homes, has
grown smaller in five years, from 10 women to seven. Thweatt
portrayed it in a drawing of red profiles sitting in a circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the group when it started in 1993. This is the first
one who died,'' she gently says, pointing to a white ghostly figure
among the red. ``She was only 27 years old. Then Cheri and Sandy
died. I haven't gotten around to painting them white yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1809EDT &QL; 
