A3472 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER11-COX     06-10 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Without the violence, ``Jerry Springer'' is just another talk
show
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is ``Jerry Springer''?
</P>
<P>
   Mom is bummed. Her son Jeremy dresses like a woman. ``If he
wants to be a woman, bring me some scissors. I can take care of
that,'' Mom says.
</P>
<P>
   So Jeremy comes out, dressed in a sparkly black gown and a long
brunette wig. Mom shakes her head.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Carol. Carol's bummed because her husband Billy likes to
dress like a woman, too. Carol's also bummed because Billy _ in a
short dress, curly brunette wig and five o'clock shadow _ slept
with Jeremy the night before. ``He's the top,'' Carol explains
patiently to someone in the audience, nodding toward Jeremy. ``My
husband's the woman.''
</P>
<P>
   What's missing? All the cheap peep-show tee-hees that have
always filled ``The Jerry Springer Show'' are still there. But no
wigs were yanked off. Mom didn't slap her son silly. The spurned
wife didn't knee her unfaithful husband, then wrestle with a drag
queen until they both rolled off the back of the stage, the crowd
chanting ``Jer-RY! Jer-RY!''
</P>
<P>
   Violence-free ``Springer'' debuted this week . Two impressions:
this is still really crummy programming for a network station to
air in an after-school time period (today's topic: ``You're Too Fat
To Make Porn''); and without the violence, ``Springer'' plays like
a decade-old talk show, milking its kicks out of the kind of sexual
oddities and flamboyance we've seen a thousand times before. You're
a ... transvestite! Oooooh.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Jenny Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether this plays with a daytime viewership now sophisticated
enough to expect at least a fight a day remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   But Springer's ready. ``If we see viewers are unhappy that we're
editing stuff out, then we won't edit it out anymore,'' he said
during an MSNBC interview. ``This week the fights are going to be
edited out. Whether we continue this policy or not ... we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Springer seemed to sum up the kind of icky, gratuitous,
been-there-seen-that perversion he's left with these days when,
looking over a freak show he'd assembled on the stage this week, he
turned to the audience and mumbled, ``Oh, God ...''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1809EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
