<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILA-DANCE-REVIEW-AR     06-10 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILA-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADANCO: `FIBER' THAT'S THE FABRIC OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly two decades ago, Blondell Cummings created an
epochal solo, called ``Chicken Soup,'' that explored black family
life through the metaphors of the kitchen, the kitchen table and
food. Now Philadanco, also known as the Philadelphia Dance Company,
has brought us Ms. Cummings' new ``100 Percent Cotton Natural
Fiber,'' presented on Tuesday night at the Joyce Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Too sprawling, perhaps, to assume the hallmark status of
``Chicken Soup,'' ``100 Percent Cotton Natural Fiber'' is
nonetheless the work of a choreographer with a rich sense of
theater and the human condition. It was performed with passion and
authority by some of the best modern dancers around today.
</P>
<P>
   The piece is essentially a stylized, ambling processional
through time and space. It opens with a man dressed as a plantation
field hand in the American South and then doubles back and forward
to focus on groups of people who might be everything from early
African villagers to late-20th-century urban dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   Those shifts are echoed in simple, eloquent poetry by Niamini
Mutima, projected above the dancers on a backdrop whose subtly
changing shades of blue suggest the daylong passage of time.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent mention is made of the Niger, and ``100 Percent Cotton
Natural Fiber'' unfolds with the fabled leisureliness of that
mighty, winding river. Ms. Cummings has set her piece to a score
for percussion, strings and murmuring voice, created and sung on
tape by the feminist composer Oumou Sangare, that gives the dance
an African flavor. But the message of ``Natural Fiber'' is that
life experiences and dreams are common to all people, no matter
where or how they live.
</P>
<P>
   The opening passage, in which dancers are dressed in folds of
soft cotton and manipulate swatches of the material, suggests
misleadingly that the piece will be about fabric, rather than
cotton as a metaphor for human durability.
</P>
<P>
   A projected statistic about the extent of female genital
mutilation throughout the world seems out of place. But Ms.
Cummings creates the sense of an almost filmic sweep of history,
stuffed with fleeting suggestions of individual tales, that is
unusual in dance today.
</P>
<P>
   Hope Boykin, a performer of extraordinary resonance and vivid
physicality, stood out, as she always does, in a powerful cast that
also included Desiree Lynn Pina, Allyson Triplett, Candace
Whitaker, Tracy Vogt, Curtis C. Glover, Brandon Ellis, Gabriele
Tesfa Guma, William Grinton and a tiny guest performer, Alejandro
Rivera from Louis Johnson's Henry Street Kids. The costumes were by
Nancy Bours. Pat Dignan designed the lighting.
</P>
<P>
   The program was completed by an excerpt from ``La Valse,''
choreographed by Gene Hill Sagan, and ``previews,'' as the program
put it, of pieces by Ronald Kevin Brown and Milton Myers. Brown's
handsome ``Gate Keepers,'' with music by Wunmi Olaiya, was a long,
too-even flow of sculptured, hard-dancing bodies. Myers' stylish
``Echoes: A Celebration of Alvin Ailey,'' danced to music by John
Adams, had Ailey forms but little Ailey content.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
