<SLUG> BC-ATHLETES-HEART-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG ATHLETES AREN'T GETTING THE THOROUGH SCREENING THAT CAN
DETECT HEART DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Millions of high school athletes throughout
the country will undergo physical exams this summer to see whether
they can safely play their sport in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   A new study, however, has found that many of these young men and
women won't be getting the kind of thorough screening for heart
disease critical to preventing death on the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that good clinical practice would allow us to identify
some of these athletes'' at risk, said David Glover, a St. Luke's
Hospital physician and co-author of the study in Wednesday's
Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The incidence of sudden cardiac deaths among high school
athletes is estimated at just one in 200,000, but with more than 6
million students playing that translates to 30 deaths a year.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago a North Kansas City High School tennis player
required cardiopulmonary resuscitation after her heart stopped.
Early last year a University of Kansas swimmer who had heart
disease died at practice.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association set guidelines in 1996 that call
for doctors to take detailed family and personal medical histories
and perform thorough medical exams to identify student athletes
with severe heart disease. The association had hoped to cut the
number of sudden cardiac deaths in half.
</P>
<P>
   When Glover and co-author Barry Maron of the Minneapolis Heart
Institute Foundation reviewed the physical exam forms that state
athletic associations provide to high schools, they found that 12
states were using few or none of the heart association's
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Eight states had no recommended examination forms at all. One of
the states, Rhode Island, did not require an examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one-third of states have a reasonably adequate form,''
Glover said.
</P>
<P>
   Improving the exams by adding measures recommended by the heart
association shouldn't be difficult, said Glover, who practices
medicine in Warrensburg.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's association offered the most thorough exam form in
the country, according to the researchers' criteria. Kansas tied
with the District of Columbia for the second-best exam.
</P>
<P>
   The National Federation of State High School Associations
established a sports medicine advisory committee two years ago that
is reviewing physical exams for sports participation.
</P>
<P>
   The federation, however, has no authority to require states to
use a standard medical exam, said Jerry Diehl, assistant director
of the Kansas City-based organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The national federation cannot mandate that state associations
do anything,'' Diehl said. ``Each state association must make up
its own mind on how deep they go in their requirements. They have
to do what they think is best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas State High School Activities Association issued a
four-page medical form this year that is required for sports
participation. The Missouri State High School Activities
Association recommends that schools use its form but does not
require it.
</P>
<P>
   The result, said family physician Larry Rues, director of the
Goppert Family Care Center in Kansas City, is that not every school
uses forms that meet the high standard set by the state
association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some forms I see brought in by high schools just don't make
any sense,'' Rues said. ``Some ask for things that aren't important
and don't ask for things that are needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected heart disease occurs at all levels of sports
competition:
</P>
<P>
   -- Boston Celtics star Reggie Lewis collapsed at a National
Basketball Association playoff game in 1993 and months later died
of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   -- University of Kansas swimmer Seth Dunscomb died at practice
last year. An autopsy found severe enlargement of his heart.
</P>
<P>
   -- In 1996, North Kansas City High School senior Melissa
Thompson went into cardiac arrest after playing in a tennis
tournament. A doctor performed CPR that saved her life.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier study Maron surveyed the cause of death of about
100 athletes ages 13 to 40. Most had died in or soon after
competition or practice. In about half the cases the underlying
cause was an inherited condition called hypertrophic
cardiomyopathy.
</P>
<P>
   The condition results from thickening of the wall of the heart's
main pumping chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Maron also found about 10 other genetically passed heart
abnormalities that could cause sudden death during athletics.
</P>
<P>
   The screening exam recommended by the heart association includes
checking blood pressure, listening for heart murmurs and looking
for signs of Marfan's syndrome, a hereditary disease that can cause
abnormalities of the cardiovascular system.
</P>
<P>
   The heart association said doctors also should ask athletes
whether they had experienced chest pains or trouble breathing when
exercising and whether they had a family history of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking people to do much more than they have been
doing,'' Glover said. ``What we're saying is, if you're going to do
it (exams), do it right. It seems it would be an easily fixable
problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
