<HEADLINE>
THYME TO TRY AN HERB WITH CLOVE, LEMON OR CARAWAY FLAVORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABCs: Thyme is a perennial whose many varieties bear green,
silver or variegated green-and-gold foliage. Flavors range from the
aromatic, slightly clovelike taste of standard thyme to caraway,
lemon and oregano. Native to the western Mediterranean, thyme
reaches 12 to 18 inches in height, 3 inches for prostrate
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Well-drained soil with plenty of sunshine.
Grow from transplants planted after last frost. Thyme requires no
fertilizer but can benefit from a light application of fish
emulsion at planting. Cut back woody branches to encourage new
growth, and start new plants every three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   Companion plants: Lavender, sage. Attracts bees, repels cabbage
worms.
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Meat, sausage, butter, beans, vegetables, eggs,
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Caveat: Growing in moist, heavy soil can result in root rot and
fungal disease.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN WITH LEMON THYME
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken, 31/2 to 4 pounds, cut into 8 pieces, giblets reserved
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 large onions, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   5 cloves garlic, peeled and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   1 large handful fresh lemon thyme sprigs plus 1/3 cup fresh
lemon thyme leaves, loosely packed, OR, if lemon thyme is
unavailable, substitute another lemon herb, such as lemon verbena
or lemon balm.
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a large, heavy skillet over medium-high heat until
it is hot but not smoking. Add chicken, season with salt and
pepper, and brown on both sides, about 5 minutes per side. Chicken
should be deep golden.
</P>
<P>
   Remove chicken from skillet; add onions and garlic. Cook,
stirring constantly, until onions turn deep gold on edges, about 5
minutes. Reduce heat to medium and return chicken to skillet. Add
lemon thyme sprigs and lemon juice and stir well, scraping bottom
of pan. Add giblets, cover, and cook until chicken is nearly
tender, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir 2 tablespoons of lemon thyme leaves into chicken, cover,
and continue cooking until chicken is cooked through, about 10 more
minutes. Remove from heat. Remove lemon thyme sprigs, stir in
remaining lemon thyme leaves, and taste for seasoning. Let sit,
covered, about 10 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 536 calories, 30 grams fat, 12
grams carbohydrates, 52 grams protein, 219 milligrams cholesterol,
152 milligrams sodium, 51 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``French Farmhouse Cookbook'' by Susan Herrmann Loomis
(Workman, $15.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PICKLED EGGPLANT
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 3 cups
</P>
<P>
   4 medium eggplants, ends trimmed, cut into 1/2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   3 cups best-quality red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, 2 unpeeled, 2 peeled
</P>
<P>
   10 black peppercorns, divided
</P>
<P>
   15 sprigs fresh thyme, rinsed and patted dry, divided
</P>
<P>
   3 bay leaves, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Place eggplant cubes in a colander, sprinkle with the salt and
drain for 1 to 1 1/2 hours. Rinse eggplant quickly and pat dry.
</P>
<P>
   Place eggplant in large, heavy saucepan and add vinegar,
unpeeled garlic cloves, 5 peppercorns, 1 handful thyme and 2 bay
leaves. Bring to boil over medium-high heat. Reduce heat and simmer
for 20 minutes. Drain and cool.
</P>
<P>
   When eggplant is cool, place it in a jar large enough to hold it
comfortably. Add remaining thyme, garlic, bay leaf and peppercorns,
gently pushing them down into the eggplant. Slowly pour in olive
oil, inserting a chopstick or stainless-steel knife down along the
side of jar, pushing aside eggplant pieces as necessary so the oil
will penetrate everywhere. Cover and refrigerate 3 to 4 weeks
before serving. Check occasionally to be sure eggplant is covered
with a thin layer of oil; add more oil if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Serve as an appetizer with sourdough bread or as a dip with
fresh vegetables, or on cooked pizza or mixed into pasta. Keeps for
several months and improves with age.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 63 calories, 7 grams fat, 1
gram carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 25 milligrams
sodium, 96 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``French Farmhouse Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICAN OKRA STEW
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 medium green bell pepper, sliced (1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh or frozen cut okra
</P>
<P>
   4 cups canned stewed tomatoes, with liquid
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh or frozen black-eyed peas
</P>
<P>
   2 medium jalapeno peppers, seeded and chopped (2 tablespoons)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups frozen or drained canned corn
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh thyme, or 2 tablespoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 scallions, sliced (1 cup), for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a large, nonstick frying pan. Saute bell pepper
and okra for 2 minutes on medium-high heat. Lower heat to
medium-low, add tomatoes, black-eyed peas and jalapeno peppers, and
cook, covered, 25 minutes or until peas are tender. Remove cover,
add corn, thyme and allspice, and cook 1 minute. Add salt to taste.
Remove from heat and serve over boiled rice with scallions
sprinkled on top.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 352 calories, 8 grams fat, 65
grams carbohydrates, 15 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 739
milligrams sodium, 19 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Vegetarian Dinner in Minutes'' by Linda Gassenheimer
(Chronicle, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
