<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: ART OF FOREPLAY AT THE TABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The oldest ceremony in book publishing is the
publishing lunch. It may date back to the 15th century when, myth
has it, Johann Gutenberg bought a chunk of bratwurst for an
author's agent. And it has reeled on through mead and the
three-martini lunch to today's meal of choice, grilled fish and
iced tea.
</P>
<P>
   So in the bubbling pot of the present book world, the question
is: Are these lunches (down to about two hours from the three of
not too long ago) still useful? Or are they merely for preening?
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the answer is that they are important. That is
because even in this age of the conglomerate, book publishing
remains traditional enough to depend on rapport, and ego-driven
enough to place great importance on perceptions. Since it also
feeds on gossip and speculation, the visibility of lunch with a
personage in a power restaurant meets all these needs.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Rubin, the president and publisher of Doubleday, said:
``The only way this business works is through a network of personal
relationships. It's terribly important for a publisher to remind an
agent at lunch just how wonderful that publisher is. So much of
what we do is of the moment that you've got to remind people that
you are a player.'' That, in a nutshell, is the stratagem of the
publishing lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that although the lunch mystique is so much about
people wanting to be on the radar screen, nonetheless ``you can
remind agents that they can send you other projects than what they
think they can send you, and that's very important for business.''
</P>
<P>
   Or one can look at the ritual as a sort of foreplay to the deals
that will be consummated elsewhere and will thus lead to the
publication of books.
</P>
<P>
   As such, it has its own rites and etiquette. For instance, the
publisher or the noted senior editor nearly always pays for lunch
and will eat only with celebrities, other publishers or senior
editors, important writers or very successful agents, and a select
few dreaded journalists.
</P>
<P>
   More protocol. An agent seldom picks up the check except for a
client or a potential client, and a major agent does not lunch with
a junior editor unless the introduction is extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Senior editors eat with senior agents; junior editors with
junior agents. Publishers' public relations people are interested
only in talk-show bookers or television producers and a few
reviewers and print reporters.
</P>
<P>
   What to look for: strutting. A strutting agent is one who has
just negotiated a seven-figure deal _ or at least a deep-six-figure
deal _ that everyone knows about although it's supposed to be
secret; or has a book high on the best-seller lists. A publisher
toting books means lunch with a journalist, from whom the executive
hopes to get some publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Also to be noted is the table at which the bill never arrives.
(It's quietly put on a tab in the back room somewhere, and that
means the host is truly important.) Still, the really cool appear
unconcerned and a bit careless even when given a table not quite to
their liking.
</P>
<P>
   Morton Janklow, a primal agent who actually does pay for the
lunch most of the time, says: ``It's all about schmoozing. There's
rarely something specific to talk about. You are with an editor or
publisher, and suddenly he says he could really use a book for this
fall, he doesn't have good fiction for the list, and suddenly
there's a project on the table.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Owen Laster, executive vice president of the William Morris
Agency, who also tends to pay for lunch, encourages the younger
agents in his office: ``Find the bright young editors and take them
out to lunch and be seen. I believe being seen is a kind of
important but understated part of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Book publishing is one of the few businesses in which
competitors appear to want to spend all their time with each other,
so besides the trumpery of ``I have arrived,'' the publishing lunch
allows these competitors the comfort of being together.
</P>
<P>
   The right to lunch on the corporate credit card is a rite of
passage. It took quite a time for Barb Berg, vice president and
director of publicity for Bantam Books, to get her card. Unlike the
publishers and editors, she uses the lunches for the down and
dirty: that is, for getting publicity for her authors and books.
Which mostly means television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that in their harried world, I can only get the
undivided attention of producers and bookers at lunch,'' she said.
``My lunches are all about business. It's hard to get them away
from their desks, so I always go wherever they ask, and I always
pay. It's a great coup to get their undivided attention for that
amount of time.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Berg concentrates on substance at lunch, most people in
book publishing focus on place. For instance, the Grill Room of the
Four Seasons is the first temple of the publishing lunch, and among
its regular congregation are Phyllis Grann of Penguin Putnam,
Alberto Vitale of Random House, and Jack Romanos and Michael Korda
of Simon &AMP; Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   The room itself gathers together the publishers and the editors,
the authors and the agents, and gives them a setting to show
themselves in the happiest of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's is a place for book people to be seen, and it has its
regulars among the power publishers and agents. Other book places
include Orso, Lutece, for some Le Bernardin, San Pietro, Palio and,
downtown, the Union Square Cafe, where in a recent lunch hour it
was noted that the Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux people were seriously
ignoring Grove Atlantic at a nearby table, a terrible lapse in
publishing politeness.
</P>
<P>
   Which was a scene that reminds one that no matter how sociable
the lunches usually are, no matter how comforting, no matter how
casual and coy even, book publishing is a business, and in business
there's no such thing as a free lunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
