<HEADLINE>
FALCON MAKES COMEBACK, WITH HELP FROM IDAHO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The birds from Boise took their first flight
Tuesday _ in a box. They arrived at San Francisco International
Airport on a commercial jet.
</P>
<P>
   In a week or so, though, they'll be dive-bombing hikers at the
Marin Headlands, mastering the arduous arts of falconhood and,
according to the wildlife biologists who placed them there,
repopulating a region where peregrine falcons have not been seen
for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time there were seven pairs nesting in sea cliffs of
Marin County and currently there are none,'' said Brian Walton who,
since 1975, has headed the Predatory Bird Research Group a the
University of California at Santa Cruz. Saving the once-endangered
peregrine falcon population has been part of his life's work.
</P>
<P>
   Only two pairs of peregrines remained in the Golden State when
the species was listed as endangered in 1970, largely because of
DDT poisoning and the predations of people with guns, Walton said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 150 peregrine pairs are known to inhabit California,
although none have returned to the cliffs of Marin, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walton and his team, which included rangers from the Golden Gate
National Recreation Area, sought to remedy that situation two weeks
ago. They moved two male and two female fledglings from precarious
perches on the Bay Bridge to a spot on the Marin Headlands.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, those chicks were joined by six more, imported from the
Santa Cruz group's sister organization, the World Center for Birds
of Prey in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   As Walton's team carried the young birds to their ``hack boxes''
_ or artificial nests _ they were roundly scolded by the four
peregrines already there. Having taken to wing since their arrival,
the territorial birds screeched and circled the biologists,
sometimes launching their famous attack dives, which can reach
speeds approaching 200 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Walton predicted that fewer than half the young peregrines would
survive. While they are threatened by predators like gray foxes and
horned owls, he said, the most common cause of death is starvation.
Catching food the peregrine way isn't easy, and some never get the
hang of it.
</P>
<P>
   Peregrines eat other birds, which they kill by diving _ or
``stooping'' _ from the sky at phenomenal speed, striking their
prey in midflight.
</P>
<P>
   The newly arrived peregrines will be confined to their boxes for
a week, until _ at age 42 days _ their feathers have grown in and
they'll be ready to fly, he said. Meanwhile, a team that watches
over the birds 24 hours a day will sneak up to the boxes each
night, secretly depositing dead quail for the junior birds to
devour.
</P>
<P>
   Team members observe each bird's progress, taking notes all day,
said Tim Brewton, 31, a wildlife biologist and one of the
inhabitants of the nearby team tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are long, arduous days in paradise,'' he said, noting
that the peregrine observation squad has put up with hot days, cold
days, 50 mph winds and rain since arriving at the spot in late May.
They will stay at least another 10 weeks, leaving only after the
birds have figured out how to catch their own prey, Brewton said.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's up to the peregrines to find new homes. All the local
bridges are taken, Walton said. One pair lives on the Golden Gate
Bridge, one on the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge and two on the Bay
Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Walton said the peregrine falcon _ nearly extinct three decades
ago _ will be removed from the endangered species list later this
summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
