<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATERTOWER-SCULPTOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH SCULPTOR MAKES PUBLIC ART OF WATER TOWER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By CAROL VOGEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The traffic on West Broadway in SoHo came to a
standstill on Sunday evening as a flatbed truck carrying what
looked like a translucent water tower inched its way toward a
250-ton crane waiting at the corner of Grand Street.
</P>
<P>
   Strollers stopped. Diners poured out of the restaurants to see
what the commotion was all about. Faces appeared in loft windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so interesting?'' asked a bearded man on a bicycle.
``Is it Godzilla or something?''
</P>
<P>
   There were no giant lizards in sight, just a dozen or so people
_ riggers, photographers and engineers _ all focused on hoisting
the water tower onto a rooftop.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of maneuver isn't an everyday occurrence in Manhattan,
because most of the 10,000 wooden water towers that are integral
parts of the skyline were built on site, piece by piece. But then
again, this wasn't your everyday water tower.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sculpture by Rachel Whiteread, the English artist who
over the last decade has made a considerable name for herself
casting the interior volumes of familiar objects and structures in
materials like plaster, resin, concrete, wax or rubber. Objects she
has cast in this manner have ranged from water bottles to bathtubs
to an entire house.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when the nonprofit Public Art Fund approached
Ms. Whiteread about doing a work of some sort in New York, she said
she spent days and nights walking around the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was offered various sites, like the Doris Freedman Plaza and
the Flatiron Building,'' she said. ``But I finally realized there
was no way I wanted to work on street level. New York is completely
mad. There's no peace in this city. It's chaos. I tried to find a
quiet place.'' The first time she came to New York, 15 years ago,
Ms. Whiteread remembers being amazed by the industrial brick
buildings more than the hulking skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those short, hairy buildings and the intimacy of the water
towers on top of them are what intrigued me,'' she said. ``Water
towers are like the furniture of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whiteread's work is all about taking objects familiar to the
everyday landscape and making people see them with fresh eyes.
Sometimes this has led to considerable controversy. ``House,'' a
concrete cast of the interior of a row house in London's depressed
East End, for instance, caused vociferous debate between city
officials who wanted to tear it down and neighbors who wanted it
left intact. The project, which was destroyed in January 1994,
became an excuse for the public to air its opinions about public
art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want the water tower to be controversial project,''
she said. ``I want it to seem like a peaceful moment in the sky, to
echo the atmosphere of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The skyline on the corner of West Broadway and Grand Street
looks almost the same as it did before Ms. Whiteread's
installation: a cluster of small buildings topped with water
towers. But the newest tower commands a second look: The
translucent resin changes color from green to white throughout the
day, depending on the sunlight. At one point during the
installation, one passer-by thought it was a block of ice about to
melt.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whiteread's work has always stood out. In 1995, she became
the first woman to win the coveted $32,000 Turner Prize, given
annually by the Tate Gallery in London to an artist whom its jury
considers the best representative of contemporary British art. But
even before she captured that prize, Ms. Whiteread's projects had
been known and exhibited throughout Europe and the United States.
She is at work on a Holocaust memorial in Vienna, a large concrete
casting of an inside-out library, with the books on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these projects is ambitious, and each comes with its
share of problems. In planning the water tower, for example, Ms.
Whiteread had to find the right tower to cast and the right site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted an old tank, because of the grain of the wood
embossed on the surface,'' she said. The venerable American Pipe
and Tank Lining Co. in Manhattan ended up giving her a 25-year-old
wooden tank. And the company's owners, Steven and Richard Silver,
found the site. They remembered removing an old tank from the
building and, together with Tom Eccles, director of the Public Art
Fund, approached the building's owners to see how they would feel
about having a Rachel Whiteread work on their roof. Fortunately,
they turned out to be contemporary-art lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the problem of finding the right material. ``I
wanted a tough, ultraviolet material that would withstand weather
changes,'' said Ms. Whiteread. After extensive research, she
discovered a company in California and visited it three months ago
to test the material and make sure it would give the desired
translucent effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happiest showing things in daylight,'' she said. When the
material arrived in New York, fabricators cast the tower as a whole
and eventually polished the surface until they achieved the desired
texture.
</P>
<P>
   The process sounds easier than it was. At one point, the
internal structure gave way because of the immense heat and
pressure from the casting. ``We underestimated what the problems
would be,'' Ms. Whiteread said. ``Eventually we resolved them.''
</P>
<P>
   The installation, though it had to be carefully managed, went
smoothly by comparison. Because the tower weighs about 9,500
pounds, a 250-ton crane with a 195-foot boom had to be used to
hoist it to the roof. (The weight may seem considerable, but it is
actually minimal compared to the average New York City water tower,
which can weigh 40,000 to more than 300,000 pounds, depending on
size.)
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the project, $270,000, was the most the 20-year-old
Public Art Fund has spent on a single artist. Funds came from
several sources, including the New York arts program of Beck's, the
German brewery.
</P>
<P>
   Although the average life span of a New York City water tower is
25 years, Ms. Whiteread expects hers to last a lot longer. It will
stay at its current site for about a year and then, she said, she
envisions it being shown in a gallery or museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare that I make a public piece that's movable,'' she
said. ``But I would like to keep it in New York, because that's
where its home is. It was born here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
