<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-ARABS-COX &UR;      06-10 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-ARABS-COX </SLUG>
    
 &HT;     ARAB AMERICANS TO FOCUS ON `TARGETED' DISCRIMINATION AT MEETING
 &HT;     With US-ARABS-BOX.
 &HT;     By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Labeled a ``threat to national security,'' Nasser
Ahmed has been imprisoned _ in solitary confinement _ for more than
two years. The reason: ``secret evidence'' he is not allowed to
see.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed, a 37-year-old engineer, has now gone on a hunger strike
after being transferred from a New York City detention center to a
federal prison upstate earlier this week, according to his attorney
Abdeen Jabara.
</P>
<P>
   His is one of 14 cases in which the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service is attempting to deport immigrants it deems
have political affiliations that make them a threat to national
security _ again, based on secret evidence.
</P>
<P>
   This so-called ``targeting'' of Arabs and Muslims by the federal
government will take center stage when an expected 2,000 Arab
Americans begin a four-day meeting here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who currently faces a lawsuit
pending before the U.S. Supreme Court on this very issue, is
scheduled to address the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination
Committee convention on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While spokesman Michael Gordon said it still wasn't clear if
Reno would address the issue in her remarks, it is difficult to see
how she will be able to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single one of these cases involves an Arab or a
Muslim,'' said Jabara, who called the use of secret evidence ``the
most pressing problem facing Arab Americans today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This sends a message not only that you are a suspect
community, but that you are defenseless,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Arab Americans, though one of the most affluent and
fastest-growing minority groups in the United States, often find
themselves negatively stereotyped by the same American society they
embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Tragic events such as the Federal Trade Center and Oklahoma City
bombings, and memories of the Iran hostage crisis, all bolstered by
Hollywood stereotypes in popular movies such as ``True Lies,'' have
made it difficult for Arab Americans to even move through airports
without causing suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in a healthy dose of disunity, and you've got a perfect
recipe for an ineffective lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arab Americans have to rise, and they have to make a fuss and
build coalitions,'' said Rashid Khalidi, a University of Chicago
professor who will discuss U.S. policy toward the Palestinian cause
at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He said for the Arab lobby to equal the Jewish lobby _ which he
called the strongest ethnic group in the world _ is a matter of
``hard work and assimilation.''
</P>
<P>
   But ADC president Hala Maksoud said the targeting of Arabs in
anti-immigrant, anti-terrorism legislation has brought an at times
divided community together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're identifying as Arab Americans as we haven't before,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   That will help, she said, when it comes to fighting laws such as
the Anti-terrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While ``secret evidence'' was used to deport immigrants for
years, according to Georgetown University law professor David Cole,
it wasn't until after the law was passed that the INS began
``aggressive and systematic'' use of the practice ``in a disturbing
pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole is also representing Ahmed, an Egyptian, and working with
the American Civil Liberties Union on a constitutional challenge to
his detention.
</P>
<P>
   Malea Kiblan, a Virginia-based attorney specializing in
immigration, said a part of the problem lies in an unclear
definition of what constitutes a terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man's terrorist is another man's freedom fighter,'' said
Kiblan, who will address this issue at a civil rights workshop on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   She will also discuss the sweeping changes of the 1996 Illegal
Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act _ which, among
other things, imposed new income requirements for families wishing
to bring relatives from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to know what their rights are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Also to be addressed is what the group calls the ``targeting''
of travelers going to certain destinations under a computerized
Federal Aviation Administration profiling program developed in
response to the crash of TWA Flight 800 in 1997. A commission
headed by Vice President Al Gore last year expanded profiling
procedures to include anything from putting extra tags on a
``suspect's'' bags to taking a traveler aside for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has repeatedly insisted that profiling is not based on
racial and religious distinctions, however, more than 200 Arab
Americans filed reports with ADC last year, said Ghada Khouri, a
spokeswoman for the group.
</P>
<P>
   While those complaints are down since the FAA replaced the
manual profiling system with the computerized system this year,
they have not ceased, Khouri said.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that has already sparked controversy, the ADC will
mark what they call ``50 years of Palestinian dispossession,'' a
counter-point to Israel's 50th Anniversary celebration this year,
said Muhammad Hallaj, who will moderate a discussion on the stalled
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   That theme of ``dispossession'' will be symbolized by the
display of a giant quilt project on the Mall during a final rally
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The quilt, made up of 418 pieces in the four colors of the
Palestinian flag, was stitched by women across the country.
Embroidered on each piece is the name, population and date of each
village lost in the 1948 Arab-Israeli war ``to make visual the loss
of the Palestinians,'' Maksoud said.
</P>
<P>
   Maksoud notes that the quilt project, which has toured 10 major
cities before reaching Washington, has been criticized in the
Jewish community, who ``says we have no interest in making peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We find this very disturbing,'' she said. ``Why is it that
when it comes to us, they went us to forget our past?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do it to learn lessons for the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENDIT &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
