A3513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BARBIE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-10 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BARBIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SECRET LIFE OF BARBIE': WHAT A DOLL
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ja) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The breasts of Barbie, those peaks of American merchandising,
receive their due in Thursday's report on the sexy little miss _
now 40 years old, although you wouldn't know it _ who
revolutionized global dolldom.
</P>
<P>
   Delving into ``The Secret Life of Barbie,'' Robert Krulwich goes
to Barbie's creator and developer, Ruth Handler, for an account of
how she beat down the resistance of prudish male executives at
Mattel, the big toy company that she and her husband founded, and
made them all rich.
</P>
<P>
   Our engaging correspondent talks to middle-aged women who
cherish memories of their Barbie collections and to
deconstructionists of her construction, noting along the way how
Mattel has played hardball with competitors bent on imitating the
inimitable.
</P>
<P>
   It all began on a trip to Europe when Ms. Handler came upon a
sex toy, known as Bild Lilli; Krulwich calls her a ``slutty doll
from Germany,'' but Ms. Handler's vision of pulchritude for kids
and some heavy television advertising carried the day.
</P>
<P>
   While becoming the most popular and profitable toy of all time,
Barbie gave two generations of academics something to get their
teeth into; on Thursday you can meet a woman who is identified as
``a Barbie scholar.''
</P>
<P>
   Exegetes agree that ``Barbie is about sex.'' Soon she was joined
by Ken, described here as ``a palpable idiot'' with the hint of a
bump where his genitalia ought to be. Camille Paglia, always good
for a quotable observation, sees Barbie as leading the movement
toward female liberation: a professional woman with glamour. (But
why does my 3-year-old granddaughter, Rebecca, insist on removing
her hair?)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the basic appeal, the marketeers kept pace with
fashion. During Camelot, Barbie had a Jackie Kennedy hairdo. As the
civil-rights movement gained support, Barbie gained her first black
friend, unfortunately named Colored Francie.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such signs of social awareness, sales dipped as the
1960s turned into the 1970s, when Barbie seemed out of step with
liberation movements and Mattel got into legal trouble with the
government.
</P>
<P>
   But she found favor again as a Reagan-era go-getter, ``the queen
of conspicuous consumption,'' someone crowns her. Equipped with all
manner of outfits, she was also the New Woman who could be anybody
and do anything. With sales approaching $2 billion a year, Barbie
became, in Krulwich's slightly mixed image, ``the Coca-Cola of
toys.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics like Dr. Ruth Westheimer still don't like those breasts,
which, they warn, may stir girls' anxieties over their own
imperfectly proportioned bodies, but nobody is picketing; 100
million Barbies are likely to be sold around the world this year.
The exciting promise of 1998 is a refigured Barbie: Will she be
fatter or flatter? A glimpse on Thursday reveals no dramatic
difference, except, be assured, to students of her form.
</P>
<P>
   The program ends with a scene of children making up stories
featuring their Barbies and Kens: An admirer notes contentedly that
the youngsters are in control of this little piece of global
commerce. Other adults, who have been visiting toy stores and
watching television commercials, may come away with a different
take on who is controlling these young controllers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE SECRET LIFE OF BARBIE': &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Thursday on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Robert Krulwich, correspondent; Janice Tomlin, executive
producer of ``ABC News Thursday Night''; Rudy Bednar, senior
broadcast producer; Jon Meyersohn, senior producer; Betsy West,
executive-in-charge; Lisa Jackson, producer of ``The Secret Life of
Barbie.''
</P>
<P>
   With: Krulwich, Dr. Ruth Westheimer, Paula Poundstone, Camille
Paglia and Ruth Handler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
