<HEADER>
A3517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUG-TRIALS-COX &UR;  &UR; PANE     06-10 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-TRIALS-COX </SLUG>
     PANELS OVERSEEING DRUG TRIALS ARE
OVERWORKED, UNDERFUNDED, REPORT SAYS
 &HT;     By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The safety of persons who volunteer to take
experimental drugs is being jeopardized by the fact that committees
overseeing the drug trials are overworked and underfunded, federal
investigators are to report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional Review Boards, made up of scientists and outside
``community representatives,'' review and approve proposals for
drug trials at universities, medical centers and other
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of reports to be released by the inspector general
of the Department of Health and Human Services warns that the
system is being jeopardized by the fact that the boards are
overworked and understaffed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, drug companies often ``shop'' for friendly review
boards, known as ``IRBs,'' further compromising the system's
effectiveness, the investigators are expected to report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety net intended to protect human research subjects
appears to be showing signs of age and disrepair,'' said Rep.
Christopher Shays, R-Conn., whose Human Resources subcommittee is
to release the inspector general reports at a hearing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a system in jeopardy of failing to provide even minimal
protections against unavoidable research risks,'' Shays added.
</P>
<P>
   The IRB system was created in the 1970s in response to reports
that human research volunteers were inadequately protected and
informed of the risks they faced. In effect, federal regulators
began ``farming out'' the job of policing trials to the
institutions where the research was being conducted.
</P>
<P>
   The IRBs must approve, in addition to federally funded trials,
advance plans for drug company-sponsored trials of products that
will be considered for licensing by the Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   That covers virtually all clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   However, with the explosion of drug research that has taken
place in the past decade, the committees are overworked, said
Arthur Caplan, director of the University of Pennsylvania Center
for Bioethics and himself a member of an IRB.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRBs are just swamped,'' Caplan said. ``Some large
institutions get hundreds of research proposals each month. There's
no way every member of an IRB is going to carefully read several
hundred proposals, so they end up setting up subcommittees to
review the proposals and report back to the full IRB.''
</P>
<P>
   Before approving a proposed drug experiment, the IRB is charged
with such duties as making sure the trial will be monitored to
catch any adverse reactions and ensuring that volunteers are
adequately informed of the risks they face. Subtle wording in the
``informed consent'' forms that all volunteers must read and sign
can underemphasize risks involved while playing up potential
benefits, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Caplan noted that federal regulations require that IRBs include
``outside members,'' such as physicians or lawyers, but do not
specify their qualifications. Therefore in some cases, retired drug
company salesmen have served on IRBs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, members of the boards are usually scientists who
volunteer their time and in many cases are provided with little or
no staff support.
</P>
<P>
   Simple matters such as whether minutes are taken of IRB
discussions, files are adequately maintained and the way IRB
meetings are scheduled can have profound impacts on the well-being
of trail participants, Caplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem involves so-called ``IRB shopping,'' a practice
in which a pharmaceutical manufacturers will offer researchers at
several institutions the opportunity to conduct a drug trial and
award the work to the scientists with the most pliable IRB, Caplan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies sometimes take the position that they are paying
for the research, and they might as well have it done at the
institution that gives them the least grief,'' he said. ``It's not
a malicious thing, where they are trying to smuggle in a bad
proposal, but they are often looking for speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are independent IRBs that are not connected with
research institutions, and some researchers turn to these groups
for approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, there have been occasions where IRBs were created for
the purpose of approving specific drug trials,'' he said. ``That
practice is ethically pathetic and undercuts the purpose of the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays said IRBs also are vulnerable to institutional pressures
to conform ``and to cronyism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Missing are periodic evaluations and external oversight needed
to maintain a rigorous, vigilant bioethical review system,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to representatives of the Health and Human Services
inspector general, Thursday's hearing will receive testimony from
drug companies, IRB members, ethicists and representatives of
medical colleges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
