<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MILLIONAIRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH STILL ADAPTING TO WEALTH WITH SALE OF TEXAS RANGERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, who becomes a
multimillionaire this week with the sale of the Texas Rangers
baseball team, said Wednesday he is still adjusting to his new
wealth and doesn't yet know how he will spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation Bush will spend part of the $10
million he is expected to receive from the Rangers' sale on a race
for president in 2000, should he win his re-election race this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said he hasn't decided on a race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he will ``pay a lot of tax, for starters'' on
his share of the Rangers' deal.
</P>
<P>
   He said he probably will save some but wasn't sure what he would
do with the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had time to adjust,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball owners were expected to approve the sale Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The ownership group that includes Bush has agreed to sell the
American League team to Dallas investor Tom Hicks, who also owns
the National Hockey League's Dallas Stars, for $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's profits grew from a $600,000 investment he made in 1989
for a 1.8 percent ownership in the team. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
