<HEADER>
A3529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KRAFTWERK-ART-2TAKES-     06-10 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRAFTWERK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDLY A POCKET CALCULATOR: KRAFTWERK'S STUDIO GOES ON TOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
By NEIL STRAUSS c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Concert audiences in Japan have a reputation as quiet
spectators who mystify Western musicians by hardly even clapping
between songs. But when the German electronic-pop pioneers
Kraftwerk performed three concerts at the Akasaka Blitz for a
sold-out crowd of 2,500 people a night last week, the response was
deafening.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of listeners, most of whom weren't even born when
Kraftwerk formed, whistled and applauded wildly between numbers,
even singing along with ``Pocket Calculator.''
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm made sense not just because Kraftwerk is on its
first tour in 17 years, but because Tokyo is a world of
miniaturized electronics, robotic efficiency, high-speed trains and
techno music. It is a world where Kraftwerk's electric dreams have
best come to life.
</P>
<P>
   By far the world's most influential band in electronic music,
Kraftwerk has been as mysterious as it has been important, working
quietly in its Kling Klang Studio in Duesseldorf and letting years
elapse between albums, interviews and performances.
</P>
<P>
   In an extremely rare interview, his first with an American
reporter in more than 15 years, Ralf Huetter, one of the band's
reclusive founders and conceptual masterminds, said that smaller,
affordable and portable music technology was the reason Kraftwerk
was on the road again. (The band is scheduled to perform June 13 at
the Hammerstein Ballroom in New York and June 14 at the Tibetan
Freedom Concert in Washington.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can play the music the way we feel artistically we
should be playing it,'' Huetter said. ``Before it was all
compromising, and some machines and programs were not really
transportable. Today we have access to all our computer programs
and can interact live with them. We're very lucky to be composing
music in this time. It's all at your fingertips. In the 19th
century you'd probably need to have a rich donor or king or
community giving you 80 people for an orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   For the tour, Huetter said, the band brought the entire contents
of its studio and assembled it onstage every night. ``We're playing
our studio on the road,'' he said. ``It's everything we have. We
left empty studios in Duesseldorf.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Kraftwerk was to electronic dance music what the
Beatles were to rock music: innovators who developed new standards,
codes and benchmarks for the musicians who followed them. Since
breaking into the American Top 40 with the song ``Autobahn'' in
1974, the band has been transformed from a novelty into a legend.
</P>
<P>
   Its robotlike image, automated music and concept-laden albums
from the '70s may seem like the epitome of uptight European
art-school dogma, but the music nonetheless crossed barriers of
race and nationality, perhaps because it stressed the importance of
the instrument, or machine, which has no such identity, over the
human being playing it.
</P>
<P>
   The performers who first solidified styles like disco,
electro-funk, rap, new wave, industrial and techno all acknowledged
a debt to Kraftwerk's music and its use of the recording studio not
just as an instrument but as a composer. At times, the band would
let its machines run on their own to see what developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider our music as ethnic music in a way,'' Huetter
said. ``It is from postwar Germany. As you probably know, Germany
has a very long history of art and music. Being the first postwar
generation, we were without any line of historical continuity. We
just started from zero. Culturally speaking, we didn't have our own
musical language. At first we had to find some kind of sound,
create some kind of industrial sound, and then we added voices.''
</P>
<P>
   The process began when Huetter and Florian Schneider, two
classically trained musicians, began improvising on the hippie
progressive rock of the late '60s and early '70s. They recorded
first as the Organisation and then as Kraftwerk before spurning
rock altogether and making music reflective of an industrial era
but prescient of a computer age.
</P>
<P>
   Today it's not just the band's automated dance music that still
seems current, it's also the band's ideas. Its cautionary album
``Radioactivity,'' though more than 20 years old, still relates to
current events in India. Its dreams of traveling through a
borderless Europe, related in ``Trans-Europe Express'' from 1977,
have come closer to reality.
</P>
<P>
   Its visions the next year on ``Man Machine,'' of human beings
and electronics fusing as machine beings, have in a sense come true
as people have become dependent on cell phones, electronic
organizers and other battery-operated extensions of themselves.
They have also almost literally become true as people have created
computer personalities on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Internet and immaterial transportation of information
images, technology has developed very much in our direction,''
Huetter said.
</P>
<P>
   Logically, Kraftwerk's influences would seem to be the
city-as-symphony manifestoes of the Futurists; the mid-century
electronic music studies that took place in radio studios in Paris
and Cologne, Germany; the prankish anything-goes artwork of the
Fluxus collective; the studio craft of albums by the Beatles and
the Beach Boys.
</P>
<P>
   But Huetter was reluctant to cite influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course this music was part of our cultural situation,'' he
said. ``We lived near the Cologne radio station and saw a couple of
Fluxus concerts, but to us it was part of our environment. It
seemed quite normal to create music in today's technological
society with new instruments. Why play an instrument with
19th-century technology and a limited sound range when today's
instruments have so many more variations? When you go to your
doctor or your dentist, you don't want him to use a wooden hammer.
You should expect from music the same as what you expect from
science or medicine, to be working with up-to-date technology.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kraftwerk, working with cutting-edge technology without
using excessively large, sonically limited and costly equipment
initially meant that the band had to cut and splice audiotape and
design its own instruments, like electronic drum pads, synthesizers
and sequencers. Technology has since caught up with Kraftwerk, and
the music it struggled so hard to make is now commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very long time ago we were outsiders, but always we had this
vision of electronic music as the new Volkswagen,'' Huetter said.
``It's transportable _ you can do it in your home, you can do it
anywhere _ and therefore we always had this vision of this techno
music.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In concert, Kraftwerk embraces the ambiguities of live
electronic music. It performs surrounded by banks of
mysterious-looking devices, the functions of which are unclear. For
all the audience at a Kraftwerk show knows, the music could be
entirely recorded. In fact, during the song ``We Are the Robots,''
the band is nowhere to be seen onstage. Instead, robot torsos and
heads are suspended in the air, slowly twisting and waving as the
music plays on. Huetter, however, said that much of the music is
played live, changed from night to night and even improvised at
times.
</P>
<P>
   Malfunctions aside, the biggest difficulty of touring with so
much equipment has been customs declarations. ``We have to have
long lists of inventory with numbers for every instrument or
device,'' Huetter said. ``People fear we're bringing in some kind
of weapon. In some countries, we're not even allowed to take in our
mainframes because they could be misused to program missiles. But
they're only there to make music. Art and technology are always
very closely linked.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it may seem like Kraftwerk has been on a long leave of
absence, Huetter said that the band has been working nonstop at
Kling Klang creating new songs, updating their computer programs
and instruments, making films and briefly considering a
collaboration with the German film director Wim Wenders.
</P>
<P>
   In concert, the band performs instrumental versions of two works
in progress, which it hopes to include on an album that Huetter
describes as ``nearly finished.'' He plans to follow the album with
a larger, conceptually different tour next year.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what music he's been listening to, Huetter said that
he doesn't buy many records, most of which he considers ``aural
pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just walk around, and sometimes we go out and dance, and
then we listen to the environment,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Huetter also does a lot of bicycling, and recently returned from
a cycling trip in Spain. In fact, Huetter said that when he
delivered new songs to his record company, EMI, the receptionist
mistook him for a bicycle messenger and refused to believe he
recorded for the label.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated prodding, Huetter would not reveal the concept
of Kraftwerk's next album. But considering that the band has sung
about bicycles, cars, trains and automobiles, wouldn't the logical
next step for these technology worshipers be to sing about
airplanes and space travel?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Huetter replied. ``We're afraid of flying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
