<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOFTWARE-ISSUES-COX &UR;  &UR;      06-10 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-ISSUES-COX </SLUG>
     GATES: GOVERNMENT ATTEMPTS TO BLOCK
ENCRYPTION ARE FUTILE
 &HT;     Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;     By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a digital age, crime-fighters can no longer
count on deciphering coded messages to catch spies or crooks,
several of the nation's top software executives warned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just a fact of life,'' said Microsoft's Bill Gates,
adding , ``It's a change in the world of spying and law enforcement
that we cannot affect. I realize that it makes their job tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates's views were echoed at a news by a Microsoft business
rival, Eric Schmidt, chairman of Novell, who declared: ``The genie
is out of the bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt contended that U.S. officials ``appear to be running a
jobs export program'' by barring Novell, Microsoft and others from
exporting their most advanced encryption systems even as foreign
firms craft similar or even better encoding tools.
</P>
<P>
   Despite several attempts to fashion a compromise under pressure
from the White House and Congress, law enforcement officials remain
deeply at odds with the software industry over the encryption
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI wants Congress to pass a law that requires all encoding
programs to carry a hidden ``back door'' that would permit its
agents to tap into Internet messages under a court order, as they
are able to do today with phone taps. The FBI plan calls for
providing a trusted third party with a digital ``key'' that would
be available in conducting criminal or intelligence investigations.
</P>
<P>
   But the Business Software Alliance, an industry trade that
sponsored the news conference, countered with a study which held
that a government bid to curb Internet encryption would cost users
at least $7.7 billion a year and $38.5 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we've said in the past, encryption policy must be guided by
the digital Hippocratic Oath _ first, do no harm,'' said Schmidt.
``The high cost of the key escrow system documented in this study
does not pass this test.''
</P>
<P>
   In return for a ``key,'' the Clinton administration is willing
to lift its strict export controls on more powerful U.S.-made
encryption tools. The industry holds that it has been slow to
design truly unbreakable codes, which could further advance
Internet commerce, because it has effectively ceded the world
market to overseas competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff led on Tuesday to a summit conference between
government and industry leaders, including Attorney General Janet
Reno, FBI Director Louis Freeh and Thomas Constantine, head of the
Drug Enforcement Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was sponsored by Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., a
key player on Capitol Hill on technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   About all that was decided in what Gates termed ``a good
exchange'' was that the group would meet soon again. ``There wasn't
any agreement to change our position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trade group also released a report on the benefits of
electronic commerce predicting that direct business-to-business
transactions in cyberspace in 2000 would range from $66 billion to
$171 billion. By 2002, the study foresaw electronic commerce
reaching the $300 billion level.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
