<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-ATTACK-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS JASPER `THUGS' NEED TO BE `TREATED LIKE BARBARIANS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional ending) 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush said Wednesday that the
people who killed a black man in Jasper by dragging him behind a
pickup were guilty of ``barbaric behavior'' and need to be
``treated like barbarians.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was ``sickened'' by the allegations against three
ex-convicts with suspected ties to racist hate groups. They are
charged with murdering James Byrd Jr., a 49-year-old Jasper man who
did odd jobs and was the father of three.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said the actions of ``three thugs'' shouldn't be
allowed to define Texas. But he said he believed the state has a
problem with race relations because ``there are some people who
have got hate in their hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's disturbing, but government can't make people love one
another,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody steps across the bounds, and does what happened
in Jasper, what government can do is provide a cell for a long
period of time, a courtroom with good prosecutors, and that's
what's going to happen in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor wouldn't say whether laws against ``hate crimes''
should be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that all crime is hate, particularly the crime that
went on there,'' he said. ``I think the way to get rid of hate in
people's hearts, the best course I know is religion .... The truth
of the matter is hate and evil exist, and something much larger
than government will help (heal) the hearts of man.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush called on the courts to respond quickly to the murder but
said he didn't plan to go to Jasper, a town of 8,000 about 150
miles northeast of Houston. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I think the best thing I can do is tell the revulsion I felt
in my gut when I saw what happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two state lawmakers who represent Jasper said they were appalled
at the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of this crime is despicable and worthy of great
outrage,'' said state Sen. Drew Nixon, R-Carthage, and state Rep.
Wayne Christian, R-Center, in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through our criminal justice system, East Texans will show the
nation that we will not tolerate acts of racial malice.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislators urged people to ``remain calm and allow the
system a chance to work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
