A3559 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-LUNCH-COX &UR;  &UR; SUM     06-10 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-LUNCH-COX </SLUG>
     SUMMER LUCH PROGRAM FAILING TO REACH MAY
POOR CHILDREN
 &HT;     By KIMBERLY MARSELAS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite an increase in the number of summer free
lunch programs offered across Texas and the nation, too many
children are still going hungry during the summer months, the Food
Research and Action Center reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the summer food program reached all eligible children,
millions less would go hungry,'' said Jim Weill, the president of
FRAC, a national anti-hunger group. The report, `Hunger Doesn't
Take a Vacation,'' found that many families are unaware that the
federally funded free lunch program even exists during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Only 16 percent, or about 2.3 million, of the 14.7 million
school children nationwide who participate in the free or
reduced-cost lunch programs during the school year take advantage
of similar summer programs. There were 28,387 food program sites
for children last summer, up 1,239 from the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government gives subsidies to qualified sponsors,
including schools, churches and other non-profit groups, to provide
food for low-income children during school vacations. But the
report's author, Michele Tingling-Clemmons, said the local sponsors
usually do not generate enough publicity about summer free lunch
programs in their areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program is not well-advertised,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tingling-Clemmons praised the ``Lunch's On Us!'' program in
Corpus Christi, Texas, for its outreach and promotional campaign,
which includes announcements and interviews on television and radio
talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parks and recreation department has done a mammoth job
there,'' she said. FRAC, a national anti-hunger group, named Corpus
Christi one of its eight model programs for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Tingling-Clemmons said many children still don't participate
in free lunch programs during the summer because of transportation
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even more than during the school year, children eligible to
receive free meals during the summer often have no transportation
to meal sites, and sponsors cannot afford to staff widely scattered
rural sites that have few participants,'' the FRAC report found.
</P>
<P>
   This problem was handled by another of FRAC's model programs in
Hookstown, Pa., a rural area with several mobile home parks. The
South Side School District there converted a school bus into a
cafeteria on wheels and now delivers more than 300 children's
lunches a day during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   FRAC officials said they were encouraged by increases in the
number of children served, the number of sites serving lunches and
the initiative of local sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when Congress is contributing to cuts, people at the
local level are struggling to make these programs expand,'' said
Weill. The FRAC president blamed recent food stamp and welfare
legislation for an increase in hungry children.
</P>
<P>
   But the report shows there is still room for improvement. ``All
states can do better, and that fact is shown by the diversity of
states in this report that are doing better,'' said Weill.
Twenty-nine states and the District of Columbia served more
children in the summer of 1997 than in the previous summer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
