<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3563 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUIDED-IMAGERY-NYTSF &LR;      06-10 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUIDED-IMAGERY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIO TAPES GUIDE PATIENTS THROUGH THEIR ILLNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Editors: A COLOR SLIDE of Belleruth Naparstek is available.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CHERYL HECKLER-FELTZ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Psychotherapist Belleruth Naparstek recalled the patient who
visited her in her Cleveland office more than 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The woman was dying of cancer, had been told she could not
survive more than six months and was demanding help.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had horrific cancer and her oncologist said to me, 'Just
do what you can. You can't make her medical circumstances any
worse.'''
</P>
<P>
   The woman was ``tough, committed and determined to stay alive,''
Naparstek said. ``She was very bossy, very demanding and very
appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Naparstek, who had begun to conduct guided imagery exercises for
patients during therapy sessions to promote their relaxation and
enhance their coping skills, agreed to make a cassette tape of
guided imagery for the patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recorded it at my kitchen table. I included her favorite
images and added some background music,'' Naparstek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She lived another 2 1/2 years and had a good quality of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Naparstek has since become known nationally for her ``Health
Journey'' series of guided-imagery audio tapes, which she describes
as ``a kind of deliberate, directed daydreaming.''
</P>
<P>
   Guided imagery leans heavily on sensory imagination and emotion
as a way of creating images in the mind to heal or relax the body.
It is the power of visualization, the power of mind over matter _
and it is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   For years, professional athletes have used it to see victory on
the playing field, surgeons to envision successful procedures,
stock brokers to imagine a system of success in the midst of the
chaotic trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The body, if you run images _ richly sensory images _ in an
altered state, will take those images as real,'' she said. ``It is
a way of programming the body.''
</P>
<P>
   There is growing evidence that guided imagery in general _ and
Naparstek in particular _ are dramatically improving many lives:
</P>
<P>
   _Naparstek, 54, has sold about 400,000 copies of her 20 guided
imagery audio tapes, helping patients deal with addictions,
diabetes, weight problems, asthma, AIDS and other health issues.
</P>
<P>
   _SmithKline Beecham recently purchased 200,000 copies of her
chemotherapy tape for distribution to cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   _Naparstek's tapes are now used at more than 800 hospitals and
health institutions _ from the Mayo Clinic and Cleveland Clinic
Cancer Center to Columbia Presbyterian in New York and UCLA Medical
Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   _In a three-year study of 335 surgical patients done at the
Medical Center at the University of California at Davis,
researchers found that patients who listened to Naparstek's guided
imagery tapes prior to and during surgery lost less blood, had a
shorter hospital stay and required less pain medication than
patients who listened to four other kinds of tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Patients listened to the Health Journeys tape repeatedly before
surgery; then during surgery, tapes of just the background music
were played, triggering in a patient's subconscious mind the
message that had been heard so many times before.
</P>
<P>
   The study involved four other types of tapes: one of
affirmations (positive thoughts), one of explanatory reassurance
and one of white noise and one called a ``brain wave'' tape,
designed to synchronize both sides of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Naparstek refuses to claim that guided imagery is the panacea
for all illnesses. ``I get very impatient with people who claim
that their one thing fixes everything. What I can say about my
tapes is this: They sure don't hurt you. At the very least they
help with coping. At best, they do seem to help the healing process
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after she made the first cancer tape, nurses at the
Ireland Cancer Center at University Hospitals in Cleveland asked
her to make a tape that chemotherapy patients could listen to while
waiting for their treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The success of that tape made her decide to create and mass
market tapes dealing with a variety of medical conditions. By 1991,
she had 14 titles and a contract with Time Warner Audio Books.
</P>
<P>
   She researches each disease thoroughly and then determines which
physical images will be most helpful to people with that particular
disease. She then records a tape describing those images.
</P>
<P>
   In the tape focused on weight loss, for instance, she tells
listeners to sense a light moving into the thyroid and pituitary
glands, speeding up their body's metabolism like moving a lever on
a carburetor.
</P>
<P>
   Her interest in the power of imagination has deep roots. ``As a
child, I was a left-handed space case,'' she said, ``always
imagining and acting things out in my head.'' Left-handedness is an
indication of right brain dominance, which means greater tendency
toward creative expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started using imagery for clients who were stuck in the
therapy process _ who needed to get around left-brained (more
analytical than creative) processes.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually she made personalized tapes for several clients based
on their own needs. ``I had them picture themselves achieving
specific goals I knew they were working towards or see themselves
in the best possible light.''
</P>
<P>
   Naparstek has written two books, ``Staying Well With Guided
Imagery'' published by Warner and ``Your Sixth Sense: Activating
Your Psychic Potential'' published by HarperSan Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Heckler-Feltz is author of ``Heart &AMP; Soul Of The Nation:
How The Spirituality Of Our First Ladies Changed America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
