<HEADER>
A3575 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCMANUS-TEEN-PUZZLE-N     06-10 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-TEEN-PUZZLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUZZLED ABOUT TEEN VIOLENCE? HAVE YOU SEEN `SOUTH PARK'? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MIKE McMANUS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Last month a deeply troubled 15-year-old took a semiautomatic
rifle and pistols to school, fired 51 rounds in a Springfield,
Ore., high school cafeteria, killing two students and wounding 18
others. He had murdered his parents as well.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario was disturbingly similar to other small-town
America juvenile slaughters:
</P>
<P>
   In Pearl, Miss., a 16-year-old killed his mother and father and
two classmates.
</P>
<P>
   A 14-year-old shot three girls in a West Paducah (Ky.) high
school with a semiautomatic.
</P>
<P>
   In Jonesboro, Ark., an 11-year-old and 13-year-old ambushed
classmates, killing five.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nationally, murder rates dropped 20 percent from 1993 to
1996, and fell another 9 percent last year. New York's murder rate
fell 22 percent, and Los Angeles was down 20 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, something is poisoning the youth of America that has
eluded adults.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, guns are too available, with 222 million of them in
America. In a recent year 38,166 Americans died by gunshot while
the comparable number in Great Britain was under 100.
</P>
<P>
   But the guns are already out there, and fewer adults are being
murdered, while in a six-year period, arrests for murder of those
aged 18 to 20 leapt 113 percent; for 17-year-olds it jumped 121
percent; for 16-year-olds, 158 percent and among 15-year-olds, 217
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds that a boy born in America in 1974 will be murdered
are higher than the odds that serviceman in World War II would be
killed in combat,'' says Sen. Phil Gramm.
</P>
<P>
   One solution proposed by Handgun Control Inc. makes sense: a
Children's Access Prevention law. It holds parents accountable if
they allow guns to fall into underage hands. Florida passed the
first CAP law in 1989, and 14 other states have done so.
</P>
<P>
   Result: unintentional deaths dropped 23 percent among children
younger than 15. Sen. Richard Durbin of Illinois, who is
introducing a federal CAP bill, says: ``It's time for the adults
who own the guns to act responsibly, to store them safely and to
take responsibility for guns in their possession.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there is a more sinister, insidious poison affecting
the minds of youth: nihilistic violence-inciting television.
</P>
<P>
   Have you heard of the TV show ``South Park?'' Probably not. Ask
any 8- to 12-year-old, you will get an earful. It is a cartoon
featuring four 8-year-olds in an elementary school who have foul
mouths and a love of mayhem that is aired on the cable network,
Comedy Central, at 10 p.m. Wednesdays. It is hot, generating more
ad income than any other cable show.
</P>
<P>
   In EVERY episode, one of the characters, Kenny, is murdered. He
is shot, run over, stabbed and even decapitated. Each time, the
other kids say: ``Oh my God, they killed Kenny. You bastard.'' But
they say it nonchalantly. After one killing, another character
says, ``Everybody has somebody they want to be killed.'' This is
supposed to be funny.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Kenny killed each week? Matt Stone, co-creator of the
series with Trey Parker, explains: ``Trey and I created Kenny. So
we can kill him.. Leave us alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Each show is also sexually shocking. ``An Elephant Makes Love To
A Pig'' is the title of one episode. ``I will produce a pot-bellied
elephant,'' says an 8-year-old competing in a science project. When
the animals show no sexual interest, they ask an adult what to do.
``Get them good and drunk,'' they are advised.
</P>
<P>
   When that fails, the school janitor, who sings raunchy songs
each week, advises they need music for atmosphere, and croons,
``Tonight is right for love. You know I want to touch you when the
lights go out. Love, baby. Love so sweet. I want your love. You are
burning like a dog in heat.'' That worked.
</P>
<P>
   The show's violence has had a proven devastating consequence.
Anita Ferguson of the Maryland Times Press reported last week that
a 12-year-old in Ocean City, Md. who committed suicide, left a note
telling his parents to watch ``South Park'' to learn why he killed
himself. He mentioned Kenny, the silent third grader murdered in
every episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media influence on our youth can not be underestimated,'' says
Melody Morris, director of the Christian Family Network in Dayton.
``The violence we see coming from young people is a mirror image of
what is being portrayed in so-called entertainment fields.''
</P>
<P>
   What can be done? Write your cable company demanding ``South
Park'' be removed. And write to the advertisers:
</P>
<P>
   Steve Wynne
</P>
<P>
   CEO, Adidas
</P>
<P>
   9605 SW Nimbus
</P>
<P>
   Beaverton, OR 97008
</P>
<P>
   Minoru Arakawa
</P>
<P>
   CEO, Nintendo
</P>
<P>
   4820 150th Ave. NE
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, VA 23218.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   c. Michael J. McManus
</P>
</TEXT>
