<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES STRONGER LEGISLATION ON EQUAL PAY FOR WOMEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Another day, another 75 cents _ if you're a woman.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Wednesday it's not good enough that the
wage gap between men and women has narrowed. He called on Congress
to act quickly to pass legislation giving women the ability to
punish companies that allow pay disparity to continue.
</P>
<P>
   The White House staged a full-scale event _ complete with the
president, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President Al
Gore and wife Tipper Gore, civil rights leaders and members of
Congress _ to press the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The administration released two reports to mark the 35th
anniversary of the Equal Pay Act signed by President Kennedy in
1963. The reports show the pay differential narrowed from 58 cents
earned by women to every $1 earned by a man to 75 cents earned by a
woman to every $1 for a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you will be persuaded that there is no explanation for
the gap that is complete without acknowledging the continued
existence of discrimination,'' Clinton said after reviewing the
reports.
</P>
<P>
   The president called for Republican leaders in Congress to
immediately schedule a vote on a measure by Democrats that would
allow women to sue for compensatory and punitive damages rather
than being limited to regaining back pay as they are under current
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, this should not be a partisan political issue. In a funny
way, it shouldn't even be a gender issue. More fundamentally, it is
a civil rights issue. More fundamentally than that, it is a family
issue,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The event on equal pay was one of a series the White House has
organized in recent weeks to focus on issues especially important
to women, such as reining in managed health care or curbing tobacco
use among children. Women are key constituents for Democrats going
into the congressional elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always seems the White House is aiming at women one way or
another,'' said Michael Scanlon, spokesman for House Majority Whip
Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is driving the White House is politics. That's how he ran
his last campaign. He wanted to court the women's vote and he wants
to do that again,'' Scanlon said. ``One questions whether he's
really concerned about this issue or whether he's trying to drive
up his poll ratings among women.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he knew of no plans for the House to vote on the
Democratic measure but ``that's not to say it won't become an
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said what's at stake is equity under the
Constitution and what kind of nation the United States wants to be
in the new century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore, it is ludicrous to say that 75 percent equality is
enough. You wouldn't tolerate getting to vote in three out of every
four elections,'' Clinton said. ``I wouldn't like it if someone
said you can only pick up three out of every four paychecks. But
that is, in effect, what we have said to the women of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also would allow women employees to share their
salary information with each other without reprisal from the
company and require companies with more than 100 employees to
report in general terms their pay scales for women and men.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., a sponsor of the legislation,
suggested Congress should increase the minimum wage because that
would help narrow the pay gap. He noted women account for 60
percent of the minimum wage earners. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
