<HEADER>
A3590 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-EDUCATION-SAVINGS-     06-10 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-EDUCATION-SAVINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMPROMISE REACHED ON TAX-FREE ACCOUNTS FOR EDUCATION SPENDING
 &HT;    Not for Atlanta
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress is heading toward a showdown with
President Clinton over federal education policy.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate Republicans, joined by several key Democrats,
announced agreement Wednesday on a compromise proposal by Sens.
Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., and Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., to establish
tax-free savings accounts for children in elementary and secondary
school.
</P>
<P>
   The House will vote on final passage next Wednesday, with a
Senate vote likely soon thereafter. Clinton has vowed repeatedly to
veto the measure, which would allow parents, relatives and even
corporate or union sponsors to set aside up to $2,000 annually in
tax-free savings accounts. Money in the accounts could be used for
private school tuition, after-school tutors and expensive school
supplies such as computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the president's veto still stands,'' said White
House spokeswoman Julia Payne.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, crafted a compromise that will put
pressure on Clinton to sign the bill. At the request of a
half-dozen Democrats, Republican leaders agreed to strip the
legislation of two controversial provisions that were tacked on
when the bill was first voted on by the Senate two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation agreed to by the House-Senate conference
committee does not contain a provision by Sen. Slade Gorton,
R-Wash., to allow states and communities to receive federal
education money in the form of block grants. It also does not
contain an amendment by Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., that would have
hampered Clinton's efforts to establish voluntary testing for
fourth- and eighth-graders _ though Ashcroft received written
commitments from Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., that his proposal would be
included in other legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats vowed to filibuster the conference committee bill if
it included the Ashcroft and Gorton provisions, and the removal of
the controversial measures assures easy passage in both the House
and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said the bill now embodies
``classic new Democrat'' ideals that Clinton champions, offering a
way to empower parents without costing any government money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The removal of these amendments are a step toward the
president,'' Lieberman said. ``It opens the opportunity for him to
take a step toward the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Max Cleland, D-Ga., Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., John
Breaux, D-La., Bob Graham, D-Fla., and Joe Biden, D-Del., also
threw their support behind the legislation, minus the block grant
and school testing amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Democrats were hailing the measure as a testament to
bipartisan cooperation. Jim Manley, spokesman for Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., said Democrats were effectively excluded from the
conference committee deliberations, saying Kennedy received only
three hours' notice about a meeting held last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats were shut out,'' Manley said. ``It will get the veto
that it richly deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also have to choose whether he wants to support
reading programs in the legislation. Congress appropriated $210
million for reading programs, but the money can't be spent unless
Congress also adopts authorizing legislation by July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's bill now includes the authorizing legislation for
the money to be spent on teacher training, research and grants to
local school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that education is a core component of (the president's)
agenda right now, he's got a difficult decision to make,''
Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
