A3592 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-CANOE-LADN     06-10 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-CANOE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRYING TRIP DOWN MEMORY LANE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It had become a quest, a search for identity and
the nostalgic longing for an idyllic time in the past all rolled
into one.
</P>
<P>
   As a native of Minnesota, I sought a place to canoe in Southern
California, my home for the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Was it the expression of a midlife crisis? The urge to relive
joyous boyhood hours, many of which were spent in a canoe in the
Land of 10,000 Lakes?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was just the urge to enjoy nature. A canoeist can find
so much serenity on a lake or river that he will never use _ and
hates to hear _ a motor. Paddling gives a sense of gliding, of
floating free amid the bounty of the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, I used to fantasize I was an Indian or an explorer as
I glided through the expansive Boundary Waters Canoe Area along
Minnesota's border with Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that a day trip to Orange County's Irvine Lake
might well pale in comparison to past excursions. Or that the
predominant color in the surrounding hills would be brown, not
green, and the sky would be smudged, not clear. Or that this lake
was a fake _ one of the many reservoirs that dot the arid
Southland.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I tried _ as I so easily did in my youth _ to conjure up
images of Lewis and Clark, paddling their craft silently in virgin
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Clark? Try Abbott and Costello. But at least we made a
splash.
</P>
<P>
   My partner Ron Johnson, assistant manager of Irvine Lake, and I
loaded into the canoe clumsily but with hopes high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have been 35 years since I've canoed,'' Johnson said,
a note of nostalgia in his voice. It proved an ominous
foreshadowing but went little-noticed at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Our first destination was a scenic cove, where we would land to
snap a few photos. Unfortunately, the only decent spot to land was
occupied by a couple of bass anglers. Does our intrepid party take
the nice path, leaving those guys alone, or the practical one,
paddling to the good spot?
</P>
<P>
   We chose nice. Johnson tried to get out _ splash. He was
drenched, soaked nearly to his chest.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, he remained stoic, in keeping with the day's
regional theme, rather like legendary Minnesota Vikings coach Bud
Grant, who buried dejection with a calm demeanor during the Vikes'
four Super Bowl losses.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, we swapped seats and Johnson took to the stern and
the responsibility of directing the canoe. But, try as he might, he
couldn't keep us going straight. We paddled around in a circle,
much to the amusement of folks at the lake targeting trout on a
derby day. Must have been nice to get a free sideshow while trying
to win cash prizes for the day's biggest catches.
</P>
<P>
   The trip back to the dock took about 20 minutes, and our
courageous party, Lewis and Clark II, found itself amid trees more
than once. Would this require a rescue by a patrol vessel? Has a
canoe ever been evacuated because the stern paddler couldn't paddle
straight?
</P>
<P>
   At the dock, we changed positions again and continued the
sojourn.
</P>
<P>
   What more could possibly go wrong? Life had already served up a
dollop of foul-ups. Surely our quota had been met.
</P>
<P>
   They would be exceeded. After the trip was finished, I
transported the canoe back to the business from which I rented it
only to discover that the life preserver I had also rented was lost
and I was out $50.
</P>
<P>
   Did this ever happen to Lewis and Clark? Don't think so. The
trip was becoming more like a ``Three Stooges'' short. It was time
for Moe to start pulling hair and gouging eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   But the trip wasn't a complete failure. Once onto the lake,
Lewis and Clark II enacted their dreams of being explorers.
Cormorants, herons, sea gulls and cranes greeted us.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the great advantages of canoeing. ``In a canoe,
you can slip up on wildlife,'' Johnson said. ``That's the best
feature of it.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was possible to enjoy some solitude... at least when
trolling fishing boats, and gravel-dredging equipment were out of
range. The Marine attack helicopters that hovered overhead were
also a bit unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they're ours,'' Johnson joked, expressing stoic
Minnesota-type resignation to a dark fate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the interruptions, however, the scenery was pretty good.
Clouds covered 4,000-foot mountains in the Cleveland National
Forest off to the east. The lake was dotted with coves, inlets and
even a few creeks. A canoeist can find plenty of places to track
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the voyage covered spots that ordinarily would be dry
land, including many trees that are now under water. The high water
is another effect of El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   The last part of the journey before hugging the shore to the
dock was from Sea Cliffs to Catfish Cove.
</P>
<P>
   The primary fish caught at the cove? Trout.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, why not? It made about as much sense as anything else on a
4-mile trip that may not have evoked many comparisons to long-ago
voyagers who plied the waters of the North Woods but which did
offer one of the Southland's best opportunities for a Minnesotan
hankering for a canoe ride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
