<SLUG> BC-OUT-CANOE-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE TO ROW, ROW A CANOE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Southland is not the Land of 10,000 Lakes, but
it does have its share of locales to enjoy canoeing ... and more
than one might imagine for a desert region.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are places that are jewels even though Southern
California isn't noted for canoeing,'' said Joanne Turner of
Southwind Kayaks in Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   Among the possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   _Naples area of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   _Upper Newport Bay out of Newport Beach.
</P>
<P>
   _Big Bear Lake (beware of wind).
</P>
<P>
   _Lake Perris near Moreno Valley.
</P>
<P>
   _Lake Elsinore in West Riverside County.
</P>
<P>
   _Lake Hemet in Central Riverside County.
</P>
<P>
   _Colorado River from Hoover Dam to the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   _Lopez Lake in San Luis Obispo County.
</P>
<P>
   _Santa Margarita Lake near San Luis Obispo.
</P>
<P>
   _Lake Nacimiento, northwest of Paso Robles.
</P>
<P>
   Canoeists should always check conditions and weather before
putting their craft into the water.
</P>
<P>
   While it can be a difficult mission to find a canoe available
for rent, some sporting good stores carry the crafts, including
Sport Chalet _ (818) 710-0999 in West Hills _ and Irvine's
Southwind Kayaks, (949) 261-0200.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
