<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-260&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIA SAID TO USE WARPLANES IN ATTACKS ON KOSOVO ALBANIANS
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Serbia has used military warplanes in addition to army
troops and special police units in its attacks on ethnic Albanian
villages in Kosovo province over the last two weeks, a senior U.S.
official involved in monitoring the situation there said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In light of that information, other officials said that defense
ministers of the NATO alliance might ask its military authorities
to speed up planning for possible allied air strikes against
strategic targets that could include air bases and command centers
in Serbia. Allied defense ministers meet in Brussels on Thursday to
discuss efforts to stop the Serbian offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Another U.S. official said that observers had seen bombing raids
by Serbian jets and artillery attacks that had resulted in enormous
destruction of homes, with the apparent aim of terrorizing the
ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   Military sweeps have driven 80,000 people from their homes,
according to estimates, in an effort by Serbia to quash an
independence movement in the province. Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic revoked the autonomy of the overwhelmingly Albanian
province in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the United States, Russia, and four European
countries met in Paris on Wednesday and weighed giving Serbia a
deadline for resuming talks with civilian leaders in the province,
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Western and Russian foreign ministers, meeting in London on
Friday, plan to issue a strong warning to Milosevic to stop the
attacks and resume talks with Albanian leaders, the diplomats said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   U.S. and French officials said after Wednesday's Paris meeting
that Russian representatives in the international Contact Group
that monitors developments in the Balkans agreed that Milosevic,
not the Albanian leadership under Ibrahim Rugova, was responsible
for the recent deterioration of the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian President Boris Yeltsin indicated in Bonn on
Wednesday that Russia would block moves at the United Nations to
authorize NATO military measures to halt the violence in Kosovo.
Russian officials in Moscow said Yeltsin could meet Milosevic soon
to try to get him to resume talks with Rugova and halt the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair told Parliament in London,
``The only circumstance in which we will insure that President
Milosevic responds to diplomatic pressure is if that is backed up
by the threat, the credible threat, of the use of military force.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Defense William Cohen said, on his way to the
NATO meeting in Brussels, that the United States did not exclude
the possibility that military force might have to be used to keep
Kosovo from exploding into war, as Bosnia-Herzegovina did in the
early 1990s, and drawing in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The allied defense ministers are expected to ask NATO military
planners to accelerate planning for possible troop deployments for
peacekeeping missions along the border between Kosovo and
neighboring Albania or inside Kosovo, NATO officials said. They
could also ask the military to draw up targets including Serbian
air bases or airfields from which attacks on civilians in Kosovo
have been launched.
</P>
<P>
   But the allies are still some way from actually authorizing
military action. Russian diplomats have agreed so far only that
military means cannot be excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has been circulating a draft Security Council resolution
authorizing NATO to use force to preserve peace in Kosovo, but
Russia, a permanent member of the Security Council, could veto the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Blot, the senior French diplomat who took part in
Wednesday's talks on Kosovo in Paris, said that Russia joined the
five other countries Wednesday in not excluding the possibility
that military measures might have to be considered. But France and
Germany, also in Wednesday's talks, say they believe that a United
Nations resolution would be required before NATO could take any
action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov is to meet with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other foreign ministers
in London on Friday. The ministers, representing all the countries
that met in Paris on Wednesday, plus Japan and Canada, would
probably get Russian cooperation in issuing a set of international
demands to Milosevic, Blot said.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting German concerns about the increasing flow of ethnic
Albanian refugees from Kosovo into Germany, officials in Paris said
Wednesday that the European Union would be asked to come up with
immediate proposals for channeling and handling the flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is of the essence to produce a political settlement,''
Blot said.
</P>
</TEXT>
