<SLUG> BC-AIR-FRANCE-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FRANCE PILOTS END STRIKE
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Air France began limping back toward normal operations
Wednesday after pilots accepted a seven-year pay freeze, ending a
strike that had grounded most flights since the beginning of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   The strike, on the eve of the World Cup soccer championships,
which began Wednesday, had embarrassed the airline, the official
carrier for the games, and the French government, which owns the
company and has spent millions to welcome the world to the
tournament. It also inconvenienced thousands of soccer fans, who
had to scramble to find alternative transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, 20 percent of which will be offered to the public
later this year, agreed to end a two-tiered salary system that put
pilots hired after 1997 on a lower pay scale than ones hired before
then. The settlement also allows pilots to take part of their
salaries in Air France stock instead of cash over the next seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots seemed satisfied with the settlement, which is to be
finished by Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the whole, the agreement is a good one for everybody,''
said Christian Paris, a spokesman for the SNPL, the main pilots
union. ``The company had its constraints and its objectives to
achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Air France officials said the agreement would result in an
annual saving of $83 million in salaries, an average of $26,000 per
pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Their average annual salary of $123,000 is higher than that of
any other carrier, according to the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``This global accord is aimed at assuring the development of Air
France by improving its competitiveness with regards to its
rivals,'' a statement by the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, a socialist, who had said over the
weekend that the government was prepared to intervene to end the
strike, said the settlement ensured that the airline, which nearly
went bankrupt five years ago but reported a profit last year, would
have a future.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Cyril Spinetta, the company's president, said Air France
had lost $166 million in revenue during the 10-day strike. British
Airways, which put on extra 747 jumbo jets from Britain to fly in
thousands of fans for Wednesday night's opening match between
Brazil and Scotland, estimated that it took in $1.6 million extra
every day the stoppage lasted.
</P>
<P>
   Other French transportation workers continued to make travel a
dicey experience in some cities. A railroad engineers' strike
stopped service on part of the Paris rapid-transit system but had
little effect on mainline train travel except in Marseilles, where
strikers kept several high-speed express trains from leaving the
station, the national railway said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
