<HEADER>
A3623 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BUD-NAT     06-10 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUD-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  SHUSTER PROBE ON HOLD
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 10 -- A day after seeing his most important
legislative legacy signed into law, the $200 billion highway bill,
Rep. Bud Shuster faced a less glamorous piece of his legacy: an
ongoing investigation into his top aide's role in an alleged
influence peddling scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster, R-Everett, chairman of the House Transportation
Committee, learned Wednesday that the congressional investigation
into how he raises and spends his campaign cash has been delayed at
the request of the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Justice has indicated that its ongoing
criminal investigation may relate to matters similar to those under
investigation by the committee,'' the House ethics committee said
in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   At Justice's request, the committee is delaying interviewing
witnesses or taking depositions. This could spell trouble for the
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the U.S. Attorney's Office in Boston won an indictment
of Ann Eppard, Shuster's fundraiser, on charges that she took
$230,000 in illegal payments from contractors connected to the $11
billion ``Big Dig'' highway project in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleges Eppard took the money while she served as
Shuster's chief of staff, a position she held from the early 1970s
until 1994, when she became a transportation lobbyist. She has
remained close to Shuster, and still serves as his political
adviser and fundraiser.
</P>
<P>
   When the indictment came down, Shuster aides made clear that it
did not allege any wrongdoing by the chairman himself, and denied
that Eppard had done anything wrong. Shuster could not be reached
for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the House ethics committee has probed a
complaint about Shuster's close ties to Eppard, who lobbies for
contractors and communities before Shuster's committee. She also
travels with Shuster on fundraising junkets, during which sometimes
the lawmaker conducts official committee business during the day
and then takes campaign contributions from the same highway
contractors at nighttime fundraisers.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Shuster, who question whether his support for
projects is for sale, say Wednesday's developments may mean that
the Big Dig probe could be closing in on Shuster, and that the U.S.
Attorneys don't want House investigators to get in their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be an indication that there is substantial overlap,''
said Gary Ruskin, who runs the Congressional Accountability
Project, a one-man watchdog group that filed the ethics complaint
against Shuster.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the U.S. Attorneys in Boston refused to
comment, other than to say that the investigation is ``ongoing.''
No trial date has been set for Eppard, and discovery is due in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Herald reported in March that the U.S. Attorneys
wanted to ensure that the House ethics committee didn't offer
immunity to too many witnesses in the congressional probe. Immunity
before Congress would leave witnesses free from prosecution under
the Justice probe.
</P>
<P>
   Ruskin said he was unable to confirm the Boston Herald account,
but indicated that if the ethics committee is now delaying its
investigation, prosecutors would be free to pursue the Shuster case
without congressional interference.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics committee said in its statement that the delay would
not ``affect the committee's ability to issue and enforce
subpoenas'' in its probe. It did not say what impact it would have
on immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's influence over highway projects has been legendary,
even when Republicans were in the minority. His biggest legislative
victory came on Tuesday, when President Clinton signed the $200
billion highway bill that Shuster co-wrote.
</P>
<P>
   If he were indicted in a criminal probe, Shuster would
immediately have to step down as chairman under House rules. He
could continue serving in Congress until his trial.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 1930EDT &QL; 
