A3630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-TAX-CUT-COX &UR;  &UR;      06-10 0304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TAX-CUT-COX </SLUG>
     `MARRIAGE PENALTY' RELIEF AT A GLANCE
 &HT;     With TOBACCO.
 &HT;     By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Key facts about the ``marriage penalty'' income tax
reduction approved Wednesday by the Senate:
</P>
<P>
   WHO BENEFITS: Only married couples with an adjusted gross income
below $50,000, as calculated before the marriage penalty deduction.
</P>
<P>
   HOW MUCH THEY WILL SAVE: The current standard deduction of
$6,900 for couples filing jointly would gradually increase over 10
years by $3,300, to $10,200. For a married individual filing a
separate return, the deduction would increase by $1,650.
</P>
<P>
   The deduction lowers the amount of income that is subject to
taxes. So, if a couple were in the 15 percent tax bracket, their
eventual $3,300 deduction would lead to a $495 tax savings.
</P>
<P>
   HOW IT IS PHASED IN: Next year, 25 percent of the reduction
would take effect. The percentage would increase to 30 percent in
2000, 40 percent in 2003, 50 percent in 2006, 60 percent in 2007
and 100 percent in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   INFLATION ADJUSTMENT: As inflation increases from year to year,
the size of the deduction increases accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH BENEFIT FOR SELF-EMPLOYED: The self-employed will receive
a 100 percent deduction for health insurance costs beginning Jan.
1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL COST: The tax cuts will cut federal revenue by $16 billion
through 2002 and $30 billion in the following five years. Of that
amount, $11.8 billion is earmarked for marriage penalty relief and
$4.2 billion for the health insurance deduction for the
self-employed through 2002. For the following five years, $26.9
billion is earmarked for marriage penalty relief while $3.1 billion
is dedicated to the health insurance deduction.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
