<HEADER>
A3640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABC-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-10 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABC-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: ABC LIGHTENS UP ON LAST YEAR'S TV CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No need to wonder where the yellow went, to echo the
old Pepsodent toothpaste jingle. ABC is bringing back for a second
season an irreverent, yellow-tinted campaign that satirically
salutes those intermingled twinges of guilt and pleasure felt by
most Americans as they watch television.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's initial iteration, promoting the ABC network
brand and its 1997-98 prime-time programs, was one of the most
discussed and debated in advertising annals. Critics complained
that the ads, carrying the theme ``TV is good,'' mocked the
national preoccupation with the tube by presenting arch, hip
slogans like ``Don't worry, you've got billions of brain cells,''
``The couch is your friend'' and ``You can talk to your wife
anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   For 1998-99, however, the campaign, by the Venice, Calif.,
office of TBWA Chiat/Day, is being ``evolved,'' which is adspeak
for ``You don't like it? All right, already! We'll change it.'' The
revamped ads were introduced Wednesday at a lunch-time news
conference at which everything from the pencils to the electrical
cables under a table to the liquid soap in the men's room was
colored, yes, yellow.
</P>
<P>
   The primary differences for 1998-99 are that the brand-centric
ads are supplemented by considerably more series-specific pitches
and ``TV is good'' is supplanted by the more ardent ``We love TV.''
In a promotional videotape shown at the news conference, Drew
Carey, the star of one of ABC's few hits, ``The Drew Carey Show,''
lampooned the lampoon by rendering the new theme as ``Everybody
loves everybody else on ABC.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``We'' in ``We love TV'' _ which evokes the ``I Love L.A.''
commercial that a TBWA Chiat/Day predecessor, Chiat/Day, created
for Nike for the 1984 Summer Olympics _ makes the campaign less
generic and more directly linked to ABC, a unit of Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has been struggling to overcome problems ranging from a
ratings slide among its core younger family viewers to a failure to
develop popular new programs to intensifying competition from cable
networks. Those difficulties are indicative of the troubles
confronting broadcast television as commercial time is sold to
advertisers for the new season.
</P>
<P>
   That process, known as the up-front market because the time is
sold before the season begins, will be completed soon; industry
analysts predict the amount may total $6 billion to $6.1 billion
for the four major networks, or flat with to slightly ahead of
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC share of the up-front market is projected at $1.5
billion to $1.6 billion, down slightly from or the same as last
season. That would be ``a home run,'' said Joe Mandese, editor of
The Myers Report, an industry newsletter, given the network's
travails.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story isn't so much growth anymore,'' said Mandese, who
attended the news conference, ``as preserving your share.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new ABC ads are as pointedly cheeky as their
predecessors. They include: ``Hello? It's free,'' ``Don't just sit
there. OK, just sit there,'' ``Before TV, two world wars. After TV,
zero'' and ``You're breathing. We're broadcasting. Let's get
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Many, though, are softer, less barbed and snide _ even warmer
and fuzzier, if not kinder and gentler: ``Without a TV, how would
you know where to put the sofa?'', ``TV, so good they named a
frozen meal after it'' and ``If TV's so bad for you, why is there
one in every hospital room?''
</P>
<P>
   The changes don't mean that ABC executives ``want to run from''
the campaign, asserted Alan Cohen, executive vice president for
marketing at the network, because it was ``a whole new way to use
our promotional time to entertain people so they're less likely to
reach for the remote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it had a little bite,'' Cohen said, ``and that some
people would say, `I don't want anyone to tell me to watch more
TV.''' The revisions, he added, while ``keeping the sensibility the
same,'' make the campaign ``more fun, a little more celebratory
about television,'' so ``it's easier to get the joke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be doing it again,'' Cohen said, ``if viewers
weren't telling us it was effective, that it gave us an identity.''
</P>
<P>
   The principal executives on the ABC account at TBWA Chiat/Day, a
unit of Omnicom Group, also attended the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, the campaign might have come off as defensive,''
said Rich Siegel, associate creative director, ``because it was the
first time someone stood up for the medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Gentile, creative director, said: ``Some of the press last
year took it very seriously when it was meant to be lighthearted.
You see studies about watching TV and people say they watch two
hours and the reality is they watch like eight hours. We want to
say it's OK to come out of the closet _ you can watch eight hours
and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   So that's who will be coming out of the closet next season on
ABC: devoted TV viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the 1998-99 campaign, which begins on Monday, is
$15 million to $16 million, Cohen said, compared with a budget of
$12 million last season. The goal is to reach the estimated 117
million Americans who are ages 18 to 49 _ the crucial ABC
demographic group _ 44 times each with promotions.
</P>
<P>
   A substantial portion of the campaign is devoted to commercials
on ABC. Some promote stars and their series, including Carey,
Michael J. Fox of ``Spin City,'' Dennis Franz of ``NYPD Blue'' and
Jenna Elfman of ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' with tongue-in-cheek patriotic
salutes from ``the American Broadcasting Co.'' and spoofs of
commercials for products like Nike sneakers. Other spots parody
``Great Inspirations in Television,'' like the invention of the
remote control and the TV tray table.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be print ads, billboards, transit posters and
pitches in so-called place-based, or ambient, media venues like
food carts, coffee cups, beach trash barrels, airplane banners,
personal ads in weekly newspapers (``Single, fun-loving appliance
seeks companionship'') and even fruit stickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heavy emphasis will be on bananas,'' Cohen said, laughing.
``You can guess why.''
</P>
<P>
   Bananas? Naturally. Imagine what the critics would say if ABC
chose lemons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
