<SLUG> BC-HARRY-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HARRY AND THE CANNIBALS': A MAN OF MANY PARTS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(dc) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pete, Bob and Mary walk into a bar. ``You can't run
around with primates all your life,'' says Pete (Sean Weil),
objecting to Mary's plan to adopt an ape. Mary (Eva Patton) wants
Pete and Bob (Lars Hanson) to be the ape's co-godfathers.
</P>
<P>
   But the guys have other things on their minds. Pete recently had
a liver, kidney, pancreas and partial-intestine transplant, so
naturally he doesn't ``have the guts anymore,'' as he explains, for
his former career as a journalist. Bob recently had a retina
transplant and has given up his career in seismology. Both men,
however, admire Mary's new ears, which she picked up recently at
the Cornell Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   All this transplanting (and there's more) sets up the plot for
``Harry and the Cannibals,'' Susan Mosakowski's pleasant absurdist
one-act play, which continues at La Mama E.T.C. through Sunday. Not
to give too much away, but the Harry of the title is deceased and
he was an organ donor.
</P>
<P>
   The play's bartender-waiter (Greig Sargeant) has an attitude
problem, but so would you if you'd been brought up by a father
named Frank Stein (Raphael Nash Thompson) and special-ordered from
the DuPont Institute of Eugenics.
</P>
<P>
   This group of characters is soon joined by McCoy (Malcolm Adams,
an actor with an infectious Robert Downey Jr. demeanor), a former
mortician who wants to have sex with everyone, anyone, right now.
And they're all soon mesmerized by a mysterious woman in black
(Louise Favier) who has film-noir presence and a secret connection
to Harry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Baby (David Giambusso), Mary's ape, has learned to
talk but inexplicably speaks Spanish. His first word is ``leche.''
And Dr. Lacuna (Frank Deal), who seems to be all the other
characters' favorite mental-health professional, sneaks moments
alone with his old heart, which he keeps in a jar. Yes, he's a
recent transplant patient, too. Lacuna's leopard-skin
psychiatrist's couch is one of several bright touches in Paula
Longendyke's clever, stylish set.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way to the predictable but cheerfully silly
conclusion, Adams and Ms. Favier capture a few moments of perfect
absurdism. So does Giambusso, usually without speaking. The play's
message _ ``We can't let go of anything; we need all our parts,''
as McCoy says _ seems appropriately pointless.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HARRY AND THE CANNIBALS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Susan Mosakowski; sets by Paula
Longendyke; lighting by Howard Thies; costumes by Julia Van Vliet;
sound by Joe Gallant; production manager, Merry Jayne Howard; stage
manager, Kaddy Feast. Presented by La Mama E.T.C., in association
with the Creation Production Company.
</P>
<P>
   With: Malcolm Adams (McCoy), Frank Deal (Dr. Lacuna), Louise
Favier (Harry's Widow), David Giambusso (Baby), Lars Hanson (Bob),
Eva Patton (Mary), Greig Sargeant (Joey), Raphael Nash Thompson
(Frank Stein) and Sean Weil (Pete).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
