<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA PROPOSES SPECIAL STATUS FOR EAST TIMOR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ For the first time in 20 years, the
government has signaled its willingness to address one of the
sorest points in Indonesia's international relations: the status of
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday President B.J. Habibie proposed that the territory,
which Indonesia seized by force from Portuguese control in 1975, be
granted a special administrative status, an idea that had been
rejected by his predecessor, Suharto. But Habibie ruled out
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Justice Minister Muladi announced that 15 East
Timorese political prisoners would be freed, but he said the
territory's independence leader, Xanana Gusmao, would remain in
prison, where he is serving a 20-year sentence for plotting against
the state and possessing illegal weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal for ``special status'' was immediately rejected as
inadequate by separatists who demand total freedom. But in the new
atmosphere of openness that has swept the country since Suharto's
resignation on May 21, Habibie's proposal has touched off a
free-wheeling debate, complete with raucous student demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Ali Alatas, who for years has taken a hard line
on East Timor, said on Tuesday that the departure of Suharto
offered an opportunity to reopen the issue. ``I think now is a good
time to resolve our disagreement under the auspices of the United
Nations secretary general, who has taken the initiative over the
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Muladi is also taking a moderate position, now calling East
Timor an ``international issue'' and suggesting last month, ``We
should change our position.''
</P>
<P>
   In a scene that would have been impossible under Suharto,
several hundred students marched and chanted Wednesday on a campus
in Dili, the capital of East Timor. Speakers demanded a referendum,
the right to self-determination and a withdrawal of the government
troops who have suppressed a separatist insurgency, often
viciously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring Suharto to the international court as a war criminal in
East Timor,'' read a poster at the demonstration, which was
attended by several local political figures, including a former
governor, Manuel Viegas Carrascalao.
</P>
<P>
   Government troops, who have broken up student demonstrations by
force in the past, stood by quietly, as they have during a rash of
demonstrations elsewhere in the country since Habibie became
president.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia invaded the former Portuguese colony in 1975 and
annexed it as the nation's 27th province the next year. The move
was condemned by the United Nations, which regards Portugal as the
administrating power.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Indonesia has poured development funds into the
territory, which is one of its poorest provinces. But it has also
deployed thousands of troops and security officials who have
created an atmosphere of terror. An often brutal separatist
insurgency has battled the government forces, and tens of thousands
of lives have been lost.
</P>
<P>
   The status of East Timor has been the single most difficult
question for Indonesia in international forums. Human rights groups
regularly document government abuses there.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Tuesday with Reuters and the BBC, Habibie said his
proposal was contingent on an agreement by the United Nations and
Portugal to recognize Indonesian control of the territory and its
800,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   He said autonomy was not an option. ``If you want to discuss it
in that direction, there is no way you can discuss that with me,''
the president said. ``No, we will not let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia fears that freedom for East Timor would encourage
separatists elsewhere in this sprawling archipelago, particularly
in the provinces of Aceh and Irian Jaya, where guerrilla armies are
also battling the government.
</P>
<P>
   The president's statements were immediately rejected by the
separatist leader Jose Ramos-Horta, who was awarded the 1996 Nobel
Peace Prize. ``This is not a serious proposal, and I am stating
unequivocally that we reject it,'' Ramos-Horta said, speaking by
telephone from Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   The announced plan to free East Timorese prisoners is the latest
in a series of releases of political prisoners that was announced
by Habibie almost immediately after he took office. That
announcement was followed by the extraordinary spectacle of
prisoners giving interviews to reporters inside Cipinang jail, in
Jakarta. Among those interviewed was Gusmao, the symbol of the East
Timorese resistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
