<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NILSSON-CDS-NYT &LR;      06-10 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NILSSON-CDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CDS: BEFORE NILSSON WAS NILSSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month, Birgit Nilsson turned 80, and it seems clearer than
ever that she was the dominant Wagnerian soprano of the post-World
War II period.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Nilsson moved cautiously in taking on the touchstone
dramatic soprano roles of the German repertory. During the first
decade of her career, she sang mostly Verdi, Strauss, Puccini and
Mozart, and did not attempt Bruennhilde until late 1954, when she
was 36.
</P>
<P>
   What was her voice like before she came to attention outside her
native Sweden? Few recordings exist from her youth, so a new
Bluebell compact disc (ABCD 0750) of Ms. Nilsson in two live
performances with the Swedish Radio Orchestra is of great interest.
</P>
<P>
   One performance, recorded in 1949 when Ms. Nilsson was 30,
presents her in ``The Chinese Flute,'' four songs for soprano and
orchestra by the Danish composer Poul Schierbeck. The concert took
place just weeks after the composer's death at 60. Schierbeck's
tonally grounded, harmonically restless music bears the influence
of his teacher Carl Nielsen. But this work also recalls the
Orient-tinged experiments of Debussy and Ravel.
</P>
<P>
   There is a youthful vulnerability in Ms. Nilsson's singing here
that will surprise those who only know the commanding artist of
later years. Yet the unforced resonance and clarion tone for which
she would become renowned are already present.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a similarly endowed soprano of 30 would already have been
cajoled by impatient impresarios into big Strauss and Wagner roles.
</P>
<P>
   An occasional tremulous quality in Ms. Nilsson's singing
suggests why she was wise to pace herself at this stage: it takes
time to learn to control naturally enormous voices, and Ms. Nilsson
was still learning about hers.
</P>
<P>
   The major offering, recorded in 1953, is ``Bluebeard's Castle,''
Bartok's one-act, two-character opera. This Expressionist work
tells the story of a mysterious old knight and his new young wife
(his fourth), Judith, who is determined to bring light into
Bluebeard's bleak existence by opening the doors, literally, that
contain his secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Bernhard Sonnerstedt, a fine Swedish baritone, sings the title
role in this gripping performance, sung in German, and conducted by
Ferenc Fricsay, a student of Bartok. There are drawbacks: No
libretto is provided, and about 10 minutes of the 60-minute score
are missing, though the cuts are fairly seamless.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Nilsson is the main interest and her voice at 34 sounds
fully settled and gleaming. Clearly, she could have moved in
another direction. But soon the opera world was clamoring for her
Isolde, Electra and Turandot, and she, thank God, obliged.
</P>
<P>
   During the years Birgit Nilsson reigned in the German dramatic
repertory, Joan Sutherland presided similarly over the bel canto
coloratura roles. But the Australian soprano also took chances,
more than she is given credit for.
</P>
<P>
   One came in 1978, when, at 52, she recorded the title role in
Puccini's one-act opera ``Suor Angelica,'' recently released
complete for the first time on London Records (289 458 218-2). Even
with an ideal Puccini soprano in the title role, many opera buffs
find this work weepy and sentimental, with its story of a girl from
an aristocratic family who has given birth to a child out of
wedlock and been sent, for life, to a convent. Ms. Sutherland's
refulgent sound and grandeur would seem all wrong for the role.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she delivers a fascinating performance, lyrically expansive
and, in places, surprisingly passionate. Her trademark reserve is
also evident, but here it actually helps to temper the emotive
excess of the score, allowing its musical elegance and dramatic
honesty to come through.
</P>
<P>
   In this regard, the cool conducting of Richard Bonynge, not a
typical Puccinian, is a plus. He elicits a supple performance from
the National Philharmonic Orchestra. The great German mezzo-soprano
Christa Ludwig, also stepping outside her usual repertory, is
unforgettable as Sister Angelica's imperious aunt.
</P>
<P>
   The American baritone Thomas Hampson has taken chances in his
career, too. But a new EMI Classics recording (7243 5 56443)
presents him in repertory he is ideally suited to: Mahler's
``Kindertotenlieder,'' the ``Ruckert Lieder'' and one song from
``Das Lied von der Erde.'' Hampson previously recorded these works
(except for ``Das Lied'') with Leonard Bernstein and the Vienna
Philharmonic. But here he performs them with their original piano
accompaniments, played by the musicianly Wolfram Rieger.
</P>
<P>
   Many Mahlerites consider the piano versions of these songs as
the composer's sketches for the familiar versions with orchestra.
But there are advantages to the originals: The contrapuntal
textures are clearer, and the impact of Mahler's inspired text
setting is more vivid.
</P>
<P>
   Hampson's performance is intelligent and handsomely vocalized,
especially the high pianissimo phrases, which are sung with aching
beauty. To hear the gentle, tinkling orchestral music from the
final section of ``In diesem Wetter'' performed with unmannered
simplicity on the piano, as if on some wind-up music box, makes
these unbearably tragic songs about the death of children almost
comforting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
