<SLUG> BC-BKW-SPARKS-ROUSSEAU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUSSEAU BEGINS SECOND SEASON WITH SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
RESENDING FOR SAN BERNARDINO SUN 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are plans and then there are Master plans. Julie Rousseau
is riding the wave of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   The spiritual coach of the Los Angeles Sparks owes her lofty job
to a Higher Source. In hindsight, she can track the sequence of
events that prepared her for this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I an overnight success? No,'' Rousseau answered her own
question emphatically. ``For nine years I've worked on perfecting
my craft. It's not perfect, no where near perfect. I'm constantly
learning, but that's the whole beauty of the game is that you're
constantly learning. I had no idea that the Lord was actually
preparing me for this role.''
</P>
<P>
   At 33, she is the youngest coach in the WNBA. Rousseau was
promoted from assistant to interim head coach to replace Linda
Sharp after the Sparks begin the inaugural WNBA season 4-7.
</P>
<P>
   The change was swift and abrupt and the results were immediate.
The Sparks finished the rest of the season 10-7, one victory shy of
the Western Conference title and a playoff berth. But that was just
one of the effects that surfaced. Clearly, the most apparent change
came in the players attitude. They stopped making excuses for their
obvious lack of intensity to being invigorated by Rousseau's aura.
</P>
<P>
   Management was pleased and offered the Los Angeles native a
three-year contract. By all accounts it was a good move by the
Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was really tough,'' guard Tamecka Dixon said.
``Julie did a great job of coming in and instilling confidence that
was lost. She pumped us up every time, even when we did something
wrong she was there pumping up the good thing that we did, maybe
the play before or whatever. I think that really, really helped us.
The level of respect that the players have for her; she's a
motivator, and people want to play for her. They want to go out and
make the big play so that they can look on the sideline and see her
smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Her motivational skills are highly regarded, guard Penny Toler
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing at this level is what coach can motivate
their players the most,'' said Toler, an All-American from Long
Beach State. ``You can be talented, but still if you don't have the
motivation from the bench, the confidence; when you look over to
the side and you have the confidence in your coach it makes a
difference. I know me, as a player, I feel confident with Julie.''
</P>
<P>
   Up until a couple of years ago there were no women pro leagues
in the United States (now there are two), so Rousseau never
visualized herself in this position. But through the Say No
Classic, the brainchild of Sparks general manager Rhonda Windham,
and other summer league tournaments, Rousseau had the opportunity
to coach both college and pro athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've been quote unquote kind of grooming her,''
said Windham, who has known Rousseau since 1989. ``Anytime I had
any type of pro, all-star or any type of game, I always had Julie
coach a team for me. Because she's good, she's knowledgeable, the
players respected her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's such a hard worker. She would do everything in her power
to prepare herself which would in turn prepare the players. She's
committed to basketball, she has a passion for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rousseau dreamt of becoming a college coach one day, but when
opportunity arose, her ``heart and focus'' was committed to
Washington Prep High where she coached since 1989 and won three
L.A. City championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this opportunity came as an assistant coach, I just
wanted to learn and go back to my high school kids and teach them
some new stuff and try to win a state championship,'' Rousseau
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's committed to winning a WNBA championship. She spent
the offseason studying and researching on how to execute her job.
But it's not work with Rousseau, it's a labor of love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a lot of fun. I love it. I really do. Every day's a
challenge,'' Rousseau said. ``At night I'm dreaming of things,
really, literally. I go through the day's practice in my head and
I'm like, `Yeh, we need to do this, we need to do that tomorrow.'
This team is a constant, not battle, but reflection every day.
Reflecting on what we've done and what we need to do. It's all
apart of being in tune, even in the shower.''
</P>
<P>
   SPARKS NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   A day after returning from the World Championships in Germany,
Lisa Leslie
</P>
<P>
   and Haixia Zheng
</P>
<P>
   practiced with the team before repacking to leave today for
Thursday's opener at Utah. KLAC/570 will broadcast all 30 games for
the Sparks with Larry Burnett
</P>
<P>
   as the play-by-play announcer and former Sparks assistant coach
Wanda Szeremeta
</P>
<P>
   , as the color analyst. ... All 10 WNBA rosters will be
finalized today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
