<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3670 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-GREENSPAN-ART-507     06-10 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-GREENSPAN-ART-507(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN CALLS ECONOMY `AS IMPRESSIVE AS ANY' HE'S SEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a mixture of pride and puzzlement, Alan
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, declared the economy to be
in extraordinarily good shape Wednesday and signaled to investors
that he saw no immediate need to strike against inflation by
raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current economic performance, with its combination of
strong growth and low inflation, is as impressive as any I have
witnessed in my near half-century of daily observation of the
American economy,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve chairman sprinkled his two hours of
testimony before the Joint Economic Committee of Congress with
caveats about how the combination of low unemployment and strong
growth could eventually force the central bank to raise rates. But
he emphasized that price pressures were subdued and that Asia's
financial crisis was already working to take some of the steam out
of the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he has in other public statements over the last several
years, Greenspan spoke optimistically about several economic
developments, including his belief that the nation was benefiting
from huge investments in technology that were helping companies
produce more for every hour worked, holding down overall costs even
as wages rise. And he pointed to a ``virtuous cycle'' in which low
inflation had reduced interest rates and stimulated more investment
and consumption.
</P>
<P>
   And in what has become a familiar refrain for investors in the
stock market, Greenspan said expectations of stronger earnings had
``driven stock prices sharply higher and credit spreads lower,
perhaps to levels that will be difficult to sustain unless economic
conditions remain exceptionally favorable.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's less direct but more explosive warning about the
danger of ``irrational exuberance'' spooked the markets when he
first suggested the market might be overvalued a year and a half
ago. But investors largely shrugged off his concerns Wednesday _
although reports late in the day from some big American companies
about likely earnings weakness because of the Asian turmoil jolted
the markets.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Greenspan's fretfulness about the market become old
news to investors as they have pushed the market higher, but Wall
Street is convinced that the Federal Reserve has little leeway to
raise rates anyway because of its concerns about the fragility of
Asian markets and economies. Underscoring those worries, stock
markets fell sharply Wednesday in Hong Kong, Singapore, South Korea
and other nations, largely because of concern that the plummeting
value of the Japanese yen could further harm the region's
economies.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, bond prices rose sharply Wednesday, with
Greenspan's comments extending a rally set off when investors in
Asian markets sought a safe refuge in U.S. Treasury securities.
After being up much of the day, stock prices ended lower, dragged
down in part by a warning from Boeing Co., the nation's biggest
exporter, that weak demand for airliners from Asia would cut into
its profits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his testimony, Greenspan suggested that the risks to the
American economy remained balanced between an Asia-induced slowdown
and an inflationary overheating fueled by the surging stock market
and strong demand.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said the Fed remained uncertain about whether Asia was
stabilizing or whether further economic deterioration there could
wash up in the United States later this year.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, there were signs that consumer price
inflation might be picking up from extremely low levels. And
without saying so explicitly, he suggested that a continued run-up
in the stock market could fuel excess demand and inflationary
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   But he said there was almost no evidence of the phenomenon that
central bankers fear most _ wage and price increases feeding off
each other and creating inflationary pressures that can only be
squelched by higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, at least, the adverse wage-price interactions
that played so central a role in pushing inflation higher in many
past business expansions _eventually bringing those expansions to
an end _ do not appear to have gained a significant toehold in the
current expansion,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Asia crisis, a slowdown or reversal in the rise of corporate
earnings and a reversal of the inventory buildup of the last
several quarters could all help slow the economy to a sustainable
pace, Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan was careful to say that he would be as vigilant as
ever in looking for early warnings signs of broad-based wage and
price increases, especially with unemployment at a 28-year low of
4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If developments such as these do not bring labor demand into
line with its sustainable supply, tighter economic policy may be
necessary to help guard against a buildup of pressures that could
derail the current prosperity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the optimistic tone of Greenspan's testimony put him at odds
with a small group of inflation hawks on the central bank's
policy-making committee who have been agitating for a rate increase
now. Led by Jerry Jordan, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank
of Cleveland, they have been arguing that heading off inflation
down the road requires striking now, even if there is little
evidence of current price pressure. The Fed next meets to consider
interest rate policy on June 30 and July 1, and economists say it
is now extremely unlikely that the Fed would raise rates then.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan mused at several points during his testimony about how
the old rules and assumptions about the interplay between growth,
inflation and unemployment did not seem to be holding up _ although
he quickly added that he did not know if they had been permanently
retired or just set aside by a confluence of temporary factors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that economic performance strengthened as inflation
subsided should not have been surprising, given that risk premiums
and economic disincentives to invest in productive capital diminish
as product prices become more stable,'' he said. ``But the extent
to which strong growth and high resource utilization have been
joined with low inflation over an extended period is nevertheless
extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the strong economic performance, Greenspan said,
is an apparent pickup in the growth rate of productivity, or the
measure of output per worker per period of time worked.
</P>
<P>
   A steep and largely unexplained decline in productivity growth
since the early 1970s has been the main brake on economic growth in
the United States, and economists have been debating for several
years whether heavy investments in computers and other technology
have turned the trend around. Greenspan said there is mounting
evidence that productivity gains are growing, although the extent
of the improvement remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signs of a major technological transformation are all around
us, and the benefits are evident not only in high-tech industries
but also in production processes that have long been part of our
industrial economy,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
