<HEADER>
A3674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOBOKEN-CROONER-ART-N     06-10 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOBOKEN-CROONER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOBOKEN'S OTHER CROONER MAY FINALLY GET HIS TURN TO SHINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. _ On the night after Frank Sinatra died, Jimmy
Roselli, the other Italian-American singer from Monroe Street in
Hoboken, was starting his first three-night gig of the year at
Caesars Atlantic City. All day long, the news was Sinatra, Sinatra,
Sinatra. But at Caesar's Circus Maximus Theatre, the audience was
all Jimmy's.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mature crowd, dressed for cocktails, seated at
white-clothed tables and hanging on the singer's every note. Not a
glass was tinkled. Not a throat was cleared. No one seemed to
breathe. Finally, at the middle of his set, after he had belted his
signature torch song, ``Mala Femmena,'' and moved his stool to the
edge of the stage to be that much closer to the audience, the rabid
fans broke loose. People were hollering and whistling. ``Cante,
Jimmy!'' ``Jimmy you're the greatest!'' ``Jimmy you're mine!''
</P>
<P>
   This happens to him all the time. It has been happening for 30
or 40 years. But the 72-year-old crooner never seems to get used to
it. He squinted into the audience, then glanced over to his
orchestra, as if the hoots and hollers might be for the trumpet
section. ``OK,'' he said, shrugging. ``I'm yours. What else you
want me to say?''
</P>
<P>
   It's in moments like that (and this: ``If we didn't rehearse it,
you're not gonna hear it,'' he said when fans shouted requests),
that Jimmy Roselli sounds an awful lot like you-know-who. Roselli,
who can still hit the high notes and who sells out Caesars just
about every single time he performs here in the spring, summer and
fall, has been The Other Singer From Hoboken for so long that he
has gotten used to it.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say he likes it. ``Are we gonna talk about Sinatra
or we gonna talk about me?'' he said, sitting on his leather couch
in the brick house overlooking his hometown where he lives with his
wife Donna. Still, Roselli, a favorite singer of generations of
Italian-Americans and all the big wiseguys (he sang his best-loved
song, ``Little Pal,'' at John Gotti Jr.'s wedding) expects to face
lots more Sinatra comparisons _ or, more likely, the same ones,
over and over _ in the near future. After 32 albums, the one
big-time singer from Hoboken who never really left is getting his
turn to shine far and wide.
</P>
<P>
   A biography, ``Making the Wiseguys Weep: The Jimmy Roselli
Story,'' by David Evanier (Farrar, Straus and Giroux) is due in the
stores later this year, and Roselli has promised to sit for
interviews to promote it. Not to mention a screenplay, commissioned
by Touchstone Pictures and John Travolta's production company, is
in the works, with Travolta interested in starring as the singer.
(So what if Jimmy Roselli looks more like Danny Thomas and would
prefer his pal, Joe Pesci, to play him?)
</P>
<P>
   Is he excited? ``Don't you think it's kind of pathetic for
someone to be getting noticed when they're 72 years old? Or by the
time the book comes out, 73?'' He slumped down into the sofa,
suddenly smaller, with a deep sigh. His wife, 20 years his junior,
and his two other best friends in the world, Pete Cavallo and Jimmy
Geritano, were sitting around him, fidgeting nervously, wondering
if the grumpy Roselli was about to surface. ``When you've had a lot
of hard luck like Jimmy has, you become a little hardened,'' Mrs.
Roselli said, filling the silence. ``He's had hard luck since he
was born. His mother died at childbirth and his father abandoned
him, and his grandfather was a longshoreman who was away a lot.
Jimmy has had a lot of bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just his luck to be born a songbird in the same town as
the singer who would transform pop music. Jimmy Roselli grew up
half a block from Frank Sinatra (his grandfather and Frank's father
were best friends), sang the same type of songs (even some of the
same songs), traveled in the same circles. They couldn't stand each
other.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just because one became a megastar and the other
didn't. (Or hasn't.) Roselli often turned down chances at wide
fame. ``Tell them the time you walked off the Merv Griffin Show,''
Cavallo said fondly. ``Or the time you turned down Regis and Kathie
Lee and all the other shows,'' Mrs. Roselli added.
</P>
<P>
   Most famously, he quit a seven-show stint on the Ed Sullivan
Show after three nights. (''They didn't pay enough.'') But that was
his doing. The Roselli-Sinatra feud was born, as Jimmy Roselli
tells it, when Sinatra had Roselli's records blacklisted from radio
stations.
</P>
<P>
   The story goes that Dolly Sinatra, Frank's mother, asked a
friend to ask Roselli to perform in a charity show, as he had done
for her on other occasions. But Roselli was offended that she
hadn't asked her himself, and said so. Frank Sinatra, Roselli says,
took his response as an insult and used his power to get his music
blackballed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that after that, the radio stations stopped
playing my music,'' he said. His biographer, Evanier, says the
story has some merit. ``It can't be proven,'' he said. ``But it
can't be misproven. Radio stations did stop playing his songs at
that time. WNEW (in New York) stopped playing him totally.''
</P>
<P>
   And other incidents bear out the theory. ``There was a time the
Italian-American Anti-Defamation League was doing an event at
Madison Square Garden,'' Evanier said. ``Joe Colombo asked Jimmy to
be the star. But Sinatra came in.'' Sinatra's ground rules had
Roselli and Jimmy Durante, who was Roselli's good friend, doing 10
minutes and Sinatra singing for however long he wanted. Roselli
said no, and infuriated Colombo, who had him blacklisted from clubs
and theaters and jukeboxes, Evanier said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened with Frank Sinatra, Jimmy Roselli's friends
know that the singer blessed with a two-octave range often damns
his own success. He does nine shows a year at Caesars Atlantic City
(the next are at the end of July) for $1.8 million, but has turned
down the same amount for the same number of shows elsewhere. Not to
mention that he refuses to do compilation albums of songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to get him to put some songs on one CD,''
Pete Cavallo said. ``He does the most beautiful rendition of
``Somewhere Over the Rainbow.'''
</P>
<P>
   Grudgingly, Roselli let his friend put the song on his elaborate
stereo. As the room listened raptly, Roselli paced impatiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shouldn't he put this on a special CD?'' Cavallo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whadda I need to do that for?'' Roselli said. ``I got enough
albums.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
