<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3683 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLLAR-COIN-TEX     06-10 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-COIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN NEW SACAJAWEA COIN GIVE THOSE DEAD PRESIDENTS A RUN FOR THEIR
MONEY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time in decades, the feds are changing our change.
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon to a bank near you is a newfangled $20. But as soon
as you're accustomed to the new bill, expect more change: A new
dollar coin to replace the infamous Susan B. Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   A Congress-appointed committee met Monday and Tuesday in
Philadelphia, and after much polite debate, decided which famous
female will adorn the new dollar coin. Ladies and gentlemen, empty
your pockets for ... Sacajawea.
</P>
<P>
   Philip N. Diehl, director of America's coinmaker, the U.S. Mint,
said the new coin will depict ``Liberty represented by a Native
American woman and inspired by Sacajawea.'' (That's
``sack-a-juh-WEE-uh,'' if you don't remember from Social Studies.)
</P>
<P>
   Diehl's nine-person committee met because in December, Congress
told them to. With the stock of Susan B.'s running out, the time
had come for another coin. Susan's was such a stinker that
moneymakers were glad to have another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Congress gave the Dollar Coin Design Advisory Committee its
marching orders: Make the new coin gold-colored (so it won't be
confused with the quarter); give it a distinctive edge (so it won't
be confused with a quarter); and put a woman on the head side (make
that a deceased woman, thank you).
</P>
<P>
   That meant all the country music fans who suggested Dolly Parton
were out of luck. That left Martha Washington to square off with
Pocahontas; Betsy Ross to take on the first female governor, Nellie
Ross. The rules eliminated all but roughly 25 suggestions, gleaned
from the U.S. Mint's Web site, from public telephone calls and
letters and from sidewalk conversations with committee members.
</P>
<P>
   After two days in the great halls of Philadelphia, the
runners-up were abolitionist Sojourner Truth; Underground Railroad
founder Harriet Tubman; former first lady Eleanor Roosevelt; and a
surprise candidate, early African-American aviator Bessie Coleman.
The two finalists turned out to be Sacajawea, tour guide to
explorers Lewis and Clark; and Liberty, the lady of statue fame.
</P>
<P>
   When the discussion was over, they both won. The camp that
rooted for Liberty, the allegorical candidate, convinced the others
that Americans have a long tradition of Liberty on their coins. The
camp pulling for a real woman, Sacajawea, convinced their opponents
of the great contributions of Native American women. With six in
favor, one opposed and one abstaining _ and no flipping for it _ a
decision was made.
</P>
<P>
   But Sacajawea might have had an edge. The Shoshone Indian
recently showed up in Ken Burns' PBS documentary about Lewis and
Clark, and before that, she appeared on bookshelves in Stephen
Ambrose's bestselling story of the expedition, ``Undaunted
Courage.'' Poor Pocahontas hasn't made NPR or the ``Today'' show
since the Disney movie.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the committee will submit its ``design concept'' to
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin. He'll OK it, then ship it off to
artists who'll get busy drawing. We won't hold a new dollar coin
for a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever she looks like, things don't bode well for Sacajawea.
Modern history is littered with money that didn't quite make it.
</P>
<P>
   The most maligned is the Susan B. Anthony. Hers is the reason
we're getting a new dollar coin. ``The lesson of the Susan B.
Anthony, and the lack of popular acceptance of the aesthetics,
weighed heavily on the committee,'' Diehl said. ``They very much
wanted an aesthetic design that was simple in execution, that would
not be too cluttered, because this is a small coin, but also
reflected traditional American values, and presented a role model
for young men and young women.''
</P>
<P>
   Minted between 1979 and 1981, the Susan B. seemed a good idea,
to honor the 19th-century suffragist. Too bad Americans thought it
wasn't worth a plugged nickel.
</P>
<P>
   Money designers thought they had learned a lesson from the
preceding silver dollar, the Dwight D. Eisenhower. Ike flopped
because he looked like Casper the Ghost, and the coins were heavy
enough to ruin trouser pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The mint wised up and made the Susan B. smaller. Problem was, it
was no bigger than a quarter. The Susan B. was such a stinker that
the mint still has 100 million stocked in its vaults, 20 years
later. The one place you're likely to get one is in change at the
U.S. Post Office, where a $20 bill in a stamp machine is a big
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, the poor girl never had a chance. When other
countries introduced a dollar coin, they removed the competition,
the dollar bill. But Americans cling fast to their George
Washingtons. So Susan sank.
</P>
<P>
   The John F. Kennedy half dollar, minted in 1964, never caught
on, either. The coins are still being made, but when was the last
time you saw one? Or better yet, the last time you used one?
Vending machines eat them, parking meters won't take them, and coin
laundries spit them out.
</P>
<P>
   But time was, before World War II, that the feds made money we
cherished. They printed $1,000, $5,000 and $10,000 bills, and even
if we never held them, we sought them.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question we Americans love our cash, but tinker with
it and expect complaints. You can take that to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3684 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-STING-ART-2NDT     06-10 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-STING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Carrillo Fuentes.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barely six weeks later, two senior agents were dispatched to
Mexico City to meet with Mexican officials.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of sharp criticism from opposition politicians who
are now weighing a huge bailout of the troubled banking system,
Mexican officials have acknowledged only one meeting _ one at which
the Customs agents briefed a former deputy attorney general who is
a member of the political opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, U.S. officials said the agents laid out most of what
they knew to the former deputy attorney general, Rafael Estrada
Samano, and asked for his help. They said they then gave a separate
, less detailed presentation to a deputy minister of finance,
Ismael Gomez Gordillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked him to conduct a joint investigation with us,'' said
one official with direct knowledge of the meeting with Estrada.
``That would have included them covering meetings with the
traffickers, conducting surveillance. Estrada said he had to check
with his boss and would get back to us. But they just wouldn't
respond to us. And after a couple of months, we gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Mexican Attorney General Jorge Madrazo
said he believed the Americans had been vague about both the
investigation and their needs. He acknowledged that Gomez Gordillo
also met with the agents, but said they had asked him only for
information on some Mexican bank accounts, which he provided.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. officials have defended the secrecy of the operation
as necessary to protect the lives of undercover agents, it has gone
largely unnoticed that senior Mexican law-enforcement officials
knew for more than two years that Customs agents were investigating
money laundering by Mexican banks, and that the operation was
apparently never jeopardized as a consequence. But from the Mexico
City briefings, Customs officials grew suspicious about the lack of
response they got.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious that something was screwed up, whether it was
corruption or something else,'' one law-enforcement official said.
``And that did factor into our decision not to go back to them
later on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Doctor, '' who agents identified as Victor Manuel Alcala
Navarro, introduced Javier Ramirez and his purported launderers to
an ever-widening group of Mexican bankers.
</P>
<P>
   But he also introduced the agents to his boss, a man they
identified as Jose Alvarez Tostado and came to believe was the
principal money launderer for the Juarez cartel.
</P>
<P>
   In little more than a year, the agents managed to launder more
than $62 million in drug profits funneled from sales in the United
States and Canada. But they might have done far more. At one
Illinois safehouse of the gang, they found a ledger documenting the
collection of $200 million by part of the organization over a
period of about 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so conservative about what we did and how much we
moved that we were constantly in danger of losing our credibility
with the bankers,'' said one Customs official. The bankers, he
said, far from being enticed to break laws, were uniformly
introduced to the agents by drug traffickers. ``We could have done
not millions of dollars, but hundreds of millions.''
</P>
<P>
   But senior Mexican investigators who have pursued the Juarez
gang sharply criticized the U.S. operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Customs guys didn't even get the name of their main target
right,'' one Mexican officials said dismissively. ``It's Juan Jose
Castellanos Alvarez-Tostado. And he's not such a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexicans noted that they have worked closely with agents
from both the Drug Enforcement Administration and the FBI, dealt
with a much wider part of the same drug organization, and could
easily have helped Customs agents had they been asked.
</P>
<P>
   The agents, however, received clear instructions from above.
</P>
<P>
   In briefings last November and December for Reno, Rubin and a
few of their subordinates, officials said there was considerable
discussion of possible ``collateral effects'' once the
investigation went public: diplomatic troubles; an impact on the
Mexican financial markets; even the possibility that the weak
Mexican banking industry, could have trouble getting interbank
loans.
</P>
<P>
   But several officials said it was Rubin _ whose Treasury
Department has often been depicted by other officials in Washington
as skeptical about Mexican corruption and skittish about tough U.S.
measures to fight it _ who insisted that the operation proceedin
secret.
</P>
<P>
   Those left out, they said, included not only the Mexican
government but senior officials at the White House, the State
Department and even the Treasury itself.
</P>
<P>
   While senior Mexican officials initially praised the operation
after its disclosure, they said they did so after being told that
none of the undercover work was done on Mexican soil. When they
read the indictments and saw that wasn't so they were incensed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very clear that there is an ignorance of Mexican law on
the part of the United States,'' said Madrazo, the attorney
general, ``or if not the United States, at least among the agents
who participated in this.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials acknowledged that the repercussions are more than
a matter of diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes of wrangling a form of diplomatic protection for U.S.
agents in Mexico, ``administrative and technical immunity,'' have
been discarded. Thoughts of following up the investigation are
fading. Although Customs officials have the name of a Mexican army
general and the rough identities of federal police agents who were
said by one of the suspects to have laundered illicit profits, the
U.S. agents are debating whether even to pass them on.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of the suspects who couldn't be lured to the United
States have been arrested in Mexico. But the one whom U.S.
officials believe knew the most, an investment banker named Enrique
Mendez Urena who was said to have worked for the trafficker
Carrillo Fuentes, did not fare well.
</P>
<P>
   After Mendez's name and Mexico City address were sent to Mexican
officials, he was arrested in Puerto Vallarta, and then suddenly
died of massive head injuries. The state police, who apparently
arrested him, said he was acting strangely and hurt himself in
jail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
