A3685 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-WATCHERS-TEX     06-10 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-WATCHERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB HOPE STORY BRINGS CELEBRITY DEATH-WATCHERS BACK TO LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a pre-written obituary about entertainer Bob Hope became
public, it not only stirred up the masses, it aroused a rather
morbid bunch on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It grabbed the attention of celebrity death-watchers.
</P>
<P>
   For those unfamiliar with this Internet sect, celebrity
death-watchers take part in or manage macabre online contests for
fun and/or cash prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a little guilt? Yes,'' admits Mitch MaGuire of
Voorhees, N.J., creator of the Halloween Dead Pool
(pw1.netcom.com/(tilde) mick6/deadpool.html). ``Sometimes I worry
God does not have a sense of humor. But then again, he is the one
that started this whole death thing anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hope scare, and the recent deaths of crooner Frank Sinatra,
former Sen. Barry Goldwater and comedian/actor Phil Hartman,
apparently caused several celebrity death-watch sites to spring to
life recently. Examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ Reacting swiftly to the Hope news, Tregoire's Fifth Annual
Dead Pool (www.flash.net/(tilde) mmoore72/deadpool.htm) created a
Bob Hope Dead Pool modeled after its Sinatra pool. Twenty
contestants are already entered.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cash winnings of $2,300 pooled from 593 entries highlight the
Lee Atwater Invitational Dead Pool (stiffs.com), co-created by Greg
Hicks of Van Nuys, Calif., and Zachariah Love of Hollywood, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   _ Melody Rutherford of San Francisco said her Celebrity Death
Pool site (www.melodyr.com/celebritydeathpool) doesn't offer
prizes, only ``parking space'' on the winners' page and some
``really bad karma.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Childhood friends Matt Gitkin of Long Beach, Calif., and Steve
Vogl of Middlesex, N.J., created Old Blue Eyes Celebrity Death
Watch (www.webspan.net/(tilde) pokey) eight months ago, with
Sinatra and the Rat Pack in mind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Selecting Hope because he's 95 isn't the best strategy at
MaGuire's site, which conducts a fantasy football-type draft of
celebrities. The scoring system prevents loading up your roster
with older celebrities. Points are given on how close the
celebrities are to 100 years old.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Carlin of Newark, Del., whose A Date With Charon
Deadpool site (www.wserv.com/(tilde) slacker/deadpool) also
operates like a fantasy football league, said, ``Some of these
people amaze AND scare me with their knowledge of impending death
and illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, people who think they AREN'T interested in celebrity
deaths are fooling themselves, MaGuire said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't bet on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
