A3689 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRBAG-HOAX-TEX     06-10 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBAG-HOAX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT THAT SLIM JIM ACTIVATES SIDE AIR BAG CAUSES SCARE AMONG
POLICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL WEISSENSTEIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If you just locked your keys in your
late-model Cadillac DeVille and you're thinking of flagging down a
cop here; forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth officers received a strongly worded federal alert
last month. It warned that a Slim Jim _ a thin strip of metal used
to pop a car lock from the outside _ can activate a side air bag,
launching the tool at the user's face with potentially fatal
results.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one problem. The report was a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   The Slim Jim/side air bag warning is a virulent strain of urban
legend that's duped thousands of police and fire departments
nationwide, experts said. The report has spread via e-mail and
Internet discussion groups, reaching officials from Salem, Ore., to
Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all baloney,'' said Ed Sparkman, an Illinois car theft
expert who has researched the report.
</P>
<P>
   But police officers still take the warning seriously. In Fort
Worth, many aren't using Slim Jims on vehicles with side air bags
such as 1998 Chevrolet Venture minivans and Toyota Avalon sedans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't risk the danger to one of my officers,'' said Lou
Davis, supervisor of the department's downtown traffic unit. ``We
are not unlocking any cars with side bags.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the new world of the Internet hoax, where campfire
scare stories become fast-moving electronic chain-letters _
difficult to verify and easy to send on to friends and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The Slim Jim report even reached the Environmental Protection
Agency, whose Dallas office was the source of Fort Worth's warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even have a clue as to who sent me that,'' said Josie
Hopkins, EPA safety and health manager in Washington, D.C. ``I just
read it and thought, `I'll share this with the people out in the
field.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Like most reports, the alert from Dallas says that at least
three police officers in the United States have been killed by
inadvertently deploying an air bag with a Slim Jim.
</P>
<P>
   But manufacturers say activating an air bag that way is
virtually impossible. And officials at the Law Enforcement
Officers' Memorial Fund in Washington, which tracks law enforcement
officers' deaths in the line of duty, say there are no such fatal
accidents on record.
</P>
<P>
   The hoax apparently began when an unnamed officer from Ohio
dropped by a Montgomery County, Md., police station, said Jim
Onder, a highway safety specialist for the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohioan told a Maryland police sergeant taking a cigarette
break that a fellow officer had been injured when an exploding side
air bag blew his Slim Jim into his face, said Onder.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant's supervisor sent out a countywide alert and
Maryland state police broadcast the alert nationwide, said Ron
Moore, a rescue expert who wrote an article on the hoax for
Firehouse Magazine, a firefighters' trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Fire Department officials who read the article
disregarded the Slim Jim warning, said Lt. Kent Worley, a
department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Onder said: ``Everybody was relying on someone's e-mail or memo
or newsletter. They've been flippantly passing this info on without
checking the source.''
</P>
<P>
   That's typical of an Internet hoax, said David Emery, a
freelance writer who runs a World Wide Web site dedicated to urban
legends and folklore.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, someone misattributed a supposed two-word
graduation speech _ ``wear sunscreen'' _ to novelist Kurt Vonnegut.
The specious speech to Massachusetts Institute of Technology grads
was actually taken from a column by a Chicago Tribune columnist.
Thousands of people were fooled.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you do is click the forward button and it goes to
somebody,'' Emery said. ``I didn't tell you Kurt Vonnegut gave that
speech. I just forwarded a message telling you that he did.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3690 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SILICON-POLITICS-ART-     06-10 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILICON-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILICON VALLEY FIRMS MAKE FRIENDS IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By LESLIE EATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The topic may have been an arcane change to the
securities laws, but there was the sound of old-fashioned melodrama
Wednesday in a hearing room on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the legislation talked of protecting the
hard-working companies that are trying to cure AIDS, heart disease
and other ailments. Opponents talked about protecting ``the weak,
the frail, the infirm and those not fully able to defend
themselves.'' There was even a mysterious villain in the piece,
cryptically referred to by several congressmen as the notorious
``Mr. L.''
</P>
<P>
   But the subtext of this discussion could not have been more
up-to-the minute: the growing political influence of the companies
in California's Silicon Valley, which have begun flexing their
political muscles after years of disdaining government and
politicians' increasing desire to tap into the glamour _ and gold _
of the booming high-technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology community has an advantage most industries
don't,'' said Dan Schnur, Republican political director of
Technology Network, or Technet, a year-old political advocacy group
that represents 140 California companies. ``The National Widgets
Association would have a much tougher time getting attention,
because Silicon Valley is about the future, and I don't know of any
politician who has come out against the future.''
</P>
<P>
   And the No. 1 issue on Silicon Valley's agenda right now is the
Securities Litigation Uniform Standards Act, which is the bill that
was approved Wednesday by the finance subcommittee of the House
Commerce Committee. Identical legislation has already passed in the
Senate, so if the House approves the bill _ which it seems all but
certain to do _ Technet will have scored its first federal victory.
</P>
<P>
   The actual content of the bill is hardly likely to catch the
attention of most voters. Basically, it would prevent investors and
their lawyers from filing class-action securities fraud cases in
state courts. Instead, these suits would have to be brought in
federal court under strict rules imposed by Congress in 1995 to
discourage ``meritless'' lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules would apply only to securities traded on national
stock exchanges, which supporters of the bill contend should be
covered by national, rather than state, standards.
</P>
<P>
   The connection between such legislation and the high-technology
industry may not be immediately apparent _ except to those who know
that technology companies have been frequent targets of
class-action securities frauds suits.
</P>
<P>
   And California is also home to Mr. L. _ William S. Lerach _ who
is probably the most feared of the class-action lawyers for
plaintiffs. In 1996, he tried to persuade state voters to loosen
the rules in state courts to make it even easier for investors to
sue companies. The high-technology industry spent $40 million to
beat the initiative, in what was by many accounts its political
awakening.
</P>
<P>
   Now Silicon Valley wants to make sure it never faces a similar
threat, in California or anywhere else. And it is putting its money
on the line. In 1995 and 1996, the industry gave $4 million to
congressional candidates. And in the last 18 months, even before
the campaign fund-raising season has fully swung into action,
computer companies and their executives have already given more
than $1.2 million. That includes $150,000 to members of the Senate
Banking Committee, which handled the litigation legislation but
otherwise has little involvement in technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've really opened up their wallets,'' said Jennifer
Shecter, an analyst for the Center for Responsive Politics, a
nonpartisan research group. ``This industry has so much money, and
if as a politician you can tap that successfully, you're golden.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the high-technology industry had a reputation for
being politically naive. Ms. Shecter said that is no longer the
case. She pointed out that Technet, for one, is serving as a
conduit for individual contributions, which allows the organization
to get credit for delivering funds while keeping contributions
within legal limits.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Technet funneled $37,500 to the campaign of Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., chairman of the Banking Committee,
according to a filing the organization made in March with the
Federal Election Commission. The list of contributors from Silicon
Valley includes venture capitalists, investment bankers, technology
executives and even a couple of political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has also received more than $50,000 from other
high-technology executives and corporate PACs, according to the
Center for Responsive Politics. The group's study included
information released by the FEC as of May 1, and may understate the
amounts because not all donors' professions were identified.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Is there any connection between D'Amato's support of the uniform
standards legislation, which backers say was important to its
success, and the campaign contributions? ``The New York Times'
questions get more ridiculous every week,'' said Lisette McSoud
Mondello, D'Amato's director of communications. ``This bill was
introduced by two other senators, passed the Senate overwhelmingly
and with strong bipartisan support, was supported by the White
House and the Securities and Exchange Commission. And it's good
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the sponsors of the bill in the Senate, Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., was a sponsor of the 1995 securities litigation reform
bill as well. He has raised more than $24,000 the last two years
from computer companies, almost all of them from outside
Connecticut, according to the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd, said Ellen Miller, president of Public Campaign, which
advocates publicly financed elections, ``has carried enough water
for the securities, investment, accounting and high-tech computer
industries to fill all of the bathtubs of Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement is ``garbage,'' replied Marvin Fast, Dodd's
spokesman. ``Chris Dodd fights for what he believes in. He works
for the people of Connecticut, and no one else.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbying involves more than campaign contributions, of course,
and Silicon Valley has become more adept at getting its message
across. In late May, less than two weeks before his House
subcommittee was to take up the legislation, Rep. Michael Oxley,
R-Ohio, visited California under the auspices of Technet and met
with several companies.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Oxley did not respond to questions about his
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Schnur of Technet said such face-to-face visits, rather than
campaign contributions, help explain his group's success.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, politicians are falling all over themselves to be
associated with high-technology industries. said Mark Gitenstein,
counsel for the more traditional lobbying group on this issue, the
Uniform Standards Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in policy are attracted by the new economy,'' he said.
``The percentage of jobs they are creating dwarfs the smokestack
industries. That's what this is all about. There is no question
that the very mechanism by which they flourish is chilled by
litigators.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is what the 1995 securities law was supposed to
prevent: class-action lawyers jumping on a company because its
stock tumbled, finding a plaintiff who owned a handful of shares,
and rushing to the courthouse to sue for fraud. Companies settled
almost all of these lawsuits, arguing that the cost of fighting
them was prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the 1995 legislation, however, said that it would
encourage securities fraud and deprive investors of one of the few
ways they had to recover money in a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over the 1995 legislation was extremely contentious,
pitting securities firms, accountants and, increasingly, the
technology industry, against trial lawyers and consumer groups.
Clinton vetoed the bill; Congress overrode his veto for the first
and only time.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 law requires that, when they are filed, class-action
securities fraud suits contain very specific accusations, and it
does not permit plaintiffs to demand information from a company
until a judge has ruled on the company's motion to dismiss the
lawsuit. It also provided a ``safe harbor'' that allows companies
to make predictions about their business without being legally
liable if those predictions fail to come true.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for plaintiffs fought back with Proposition 211, which
was on the ballot in California in 1996. This initiative would have
made it far easier for investors and their lawyers to file
securities-fraud lawsuits against companies. At first, it appeared
to enjoy wide public support.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Proposition 211 was roundly defeated _ primarily
through a $40 million campaign organized by high-technology firms,
venture capitalists and investment bankers. That effort led to the
creation of Technet.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, securities lawyers began filing class-action
fraud suits in state courts, where the new federal rules did not
apply. The number of such cases jumped from about 19 in 1992 and 41
in 1994 to 70 in 1996, according to a study by two Stanford
University law professors, Michael Perino and Joseph Grundfest, who
also is a former commissioner of the SEC. More than half these were
filed in California.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, a funny thing happened: The number of state
lawsuits began to decline, falling to just 24 in the first six
months of the year. ``I still haven't done the final statistics for
1997, but the raw amount of litigation is less than in 1996,'' said
Perino, who has recently joined the faculty at St. John's
University in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Lerach, the California lawyer, said the number of such suits is
declining because state courts have not turned out to be ``an
effective forum.'' Not only are the courts overburdened, he said,
but it is unclear if one can bring a national class-action case in
California.
</P>
<P>
   So why does he think Silicon Valley's executives are so intent
on getting the litigation bill passed? ``I don't say it in a mean
way,'' Lerach responded, ``but they are intoxicated with their own
power, and think they can get what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley's power clearly had an impact on Arthur Levitt
Jr., the politically astute chairman of the SEC, who reversed
himself and agreed to support the litigation bill on the day his
renomination was taken up by the Senate Banking Committee. The
commission's staff argues that he got some significant
modifications to the legislation in exchange for his support, and
that the commission wants to encourage companies to provide more
forward-looking information for investors, which they have been
reluctant to do because of their fears of state lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, said one former SEC lawyer, it was impossible for the
commission to resist. ``This is the most powerful lobbying force in
America today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have tried to stop the legislation, which they
argue will deprive investors of their rights. But they are not
optimistic. ``It's been clear Congress was going to do this, and
it's hard to justify making a massive campaign in a future
effort,'' said Barbara Roper, director of investor protection for
the Consumer Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   Just because the opponents are not mounting a big
counter-offensive, however, does not mean Silicon Valley's
executives are relaxing their push. ``One neat thing about our
community,'' said Schnur of Technet, ``is that it is filled with
people who don't take no for an answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
