<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM HELPS KIDS GET A FIRST SWING AT GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ Twelve-year-old Jason Diaz had taken three
ferocious swings and hit nothing but air on the practice range at
the Westchester Country Club here. But then the advice he had been
receiving from Ben Hoffhine, an assistant professional at the club,
finally registered, and Jason, swinging easier, laced a tee shot
right down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Jason's swings and misses were understandable because this was
the first time the seventh grader had ever held a golf club in his
hands. The same was true for about 35 of his classmates from Virgil
Grissom Junior High School in South Ozone Park, Queens, who were
getting their first exposure to golf at a clinic conducted on
Tuesday in conjunction with this week's Buick Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Asked after a dozen or so swings if he had enjoyed his first
golf outing, Jason said, ``I like it as long as I can hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   That evoked a smile from Robert Klineman, the founder and
director of Inner-City Student Golf-USA, a nonprofit organization
whose goal is to provide instruction and playing time for
youngsters 10 to 15 years of age in New York and, eventually,
elsewhere in the country. The group from Virgil Grissom Junior
High, chaperoned by three teachers, is one of the first to be
involved in the program, which Klineman said he started two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 500 schoolchildren from the New York metropolitan
area turned out at the clinic, sponsored by the Callaway Golf Co.
The youngsters received instruction from Rocco Mediate, a 13-year
professional who is entered in the Buick Classic; Rick Smith, who
coaches a number of players on the PGA Tour; Tom Patri, the
director of instruction at the Westchester Country Club, and
several of Patri's assistants.
</P>
<P>
   The one-day clinic, which has been held annually for 10 years,
is one of a growing number of such group instructional sessions
being held across the country to foster an interest in golf,
particularly among underprivileged youngsters. Many of the children
at the Callaway clinic are also involved in the Metropolitan PGA's
Golf in Schools program, in which Met PGA pros provide instruction
in golf fundamentals during physical education classes once or
twice a week for six weeks every spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program has grown tremendously since we started it 10
years ago,'' said Ben Ward, the administrator for the Met PGA
program, which now involves about 5,000 children from elementary
through high school. ``We hold workshops for gym teachers so that
they can provide golf instruction when the pros aren't there.
Beyond that, we also bus kids to driving ranges, where our pros
work with them and, whenever possible, get them to play on courses
in the metropolitan area.''
</P>
<P>
   The Met PGA also provides golf clubs to youths who need them,
along with balls and other equipment. As much as possible, the Golf
in Schools program is extended into the summer months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about 120 kids in our program, and in the spring we
take as many as we can to Pelham Split Rock in the Bronx twice a
week to play the course,'' said Michael Correa, a gym teacher at
Community Elementary School 4 in the South Bronx, who shepherded 28
of his pupils to the clinic. ``Then in the summer, I work with
about 15 of the kids who are able to get to the course.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Perez, a sixth grader at CES 4, conceded that he
approached golf with a considerable amount of skepticism. ``I
thought it was a boring game,'' the 12-year-old said. ``But now
it's my favorite sport.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, apparently, for many of the youngsters, if not most,
involved in the Met PGA program, to whom Tiger Woods, and not
Michael Jordan, has emerged as the No. 1 sports idol.
</P>
<P>
   In-school golf instructional programs have also proved popular
elsewhere. In Bridgeport, Conn., about 60 middle school pupils have
been enrolled each academic year since 1993 in an after-school
program that blends academics with golf instruction. Assisted with
donations from the U.S. Golf Association, corporate sponsors, the
Tiger Woods Foundation and other nonprofit organizations and using
equipment donated by golf manufacturers, the children meet after
school for three hours twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   Half of that time is devoted to reading comprehension and
problem-solving skills in mathematics and the other half to golf
instruction. During spring and summer, the children spend most of
their time at the Fairchild Wheeler Golf Club in Fairfield, Conn.,
which is owned by the city of Bridgeport and where, under
supervision by golf instructors, they have free access to the
driving range and the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a few of these kids are at-risk students,'' Alan
Wallack, the director of athletics for the Bridgeport school
system, said, ``and many of them have gained self-confidence from
the program.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Haven, about 150 schoolchildren, most of them black and
Hispanic, take part annually in the Inner City First Swing Golf
Association program, which is held twice a week, year-round, for
those 8 to 18 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, the reaction of most kids was negative,'' said
Cheryl Merritt, a sixth-grade science teacher at the Jackie
Robinson Middle School in New Haven, who co-founded the program.
``The kids would say golf was boring and was for old people. Or
they'd say, `Blacks and Hispanics don't play golf.' But they don't
say that anymore.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
