<SLUG> BC-DELTA-MARKETING-CHIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELTA HIRES MARKETING CHIEF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (dc) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frederick W. Reid, the president of Lufthansa, will join Delta
Air Lines as marketing chief, the latest in a series of top
personnel changes by Leo F. Mullin, Delta's new chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, who is 47 and from San Francisco, worked at Pan American
World Airways and American Airlines before joining Lufthansa in
1991 to head its operations in North and South America. He moved
quickly through the ranks, becoming chief operating officer in 1995
and president last year.
</P>
<P>
   At Delta, Reid will have wide-ranging responsibilities,
including in-flight service, sales, advertising, routes and
pricing. He will also play a crucial role in the recently announced
domestic alliance between Delta, the country's third-largest
airline, and United Airlines, the country's largest and a unit of
UAL Corp. That deal is still awaiting government approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have the primary responsibility for satisfying the
customer and improving the revenues of the company,'' Mullin said
of Reid.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment is the second major hire made by Mullin, a
former banker, who joined Delta in August. Last fall, he forced
Thomas J. Roeck Jr., the airline's chief financial officer, to
resign, replacing him in March with Warren Jenson, 41, who was
chief financial officer at the NBC television network. In April, he
forced out Robert W. Coggin, the executive vice president in charge
of marketing, and Robert G. Adams, senior vice president of
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Both Jenson and Reid will hold the title of executive vice
president, putting each of them in line one day to succeed Mullin,
who is 55. Reid was not available for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The moves are an attempt to bring fresh blood into Delta, which
has long promoted from within and is widely seen as the most
lackluster of the major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been the general view _ and I think it is the case _
that Delta has been weak in the marketing area,'' Mullin
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mullin himself was heavily criticized earlier this year
for not understanding the nuances of the airline industry after
Delta missed an opportunity to merge with Continental Airlines.
Continental's largest investors instead sold a controlling stake in
the carrier to Northwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin played down the significance of that episode and went on
to negotiate the alliance with United. He has also moved quickly to
expand into Latin America and overhaul the interiors of Delta's
airplane fleet and its airport VIP clubs. He hired a new head of
information technology and recently purchased a new computer system
to forecast demand and set prices, which he says will generate $300
million to $450 million in additional annual revenues three years
from now.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin said that he would hire a new manager of human resources
in three or four months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
