<HEADER>
A3699 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-10 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNFORTUNATELY, SENTENCE GIVEN TO NICHOLS IS LONG, NOT LETHAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch gave Terry Nichols the
toughest sentence available under the law. The sentence: Lock him
up and throw away the key.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the judge couldn't give Nichols the sentence he
deserved: a trip to Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in Denver could have sentenced Nichols to death after
convicting him of helping Timothy McVeigh plan the Oklahoma City
bombing. Federal law gives jurors the option of imposing capital
punishment for the crime of ``conspiracy to use a weapon of mass
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   But the jury couldn't reach a unanimous verdict on the question
of capital punishment vs. life in prison. They decided not to
decide, and that left sentencing up to the judge; the stiffest
penalty the law allowed him to hand out was life without parole.
</P>
<P>
   Those jurors who copped out when faced with the task of
sentencing Nichols were the same jurors, of course, who couldn't
bring themselves to convict him of murder. They opted instead for a
finding of involuntary manslaughter in the deaths of eight federal
agents who were among the 168 people killed in the April 19, 1995,
bombing of Oklahoma City's Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building.
</P>
<P>
   It is considered bad form in some circles to criticize jury
verdicts, seeing as how juries are composed of just plain citizens
who sacrifice much time and effort in return for virtually no
remuneration and mostly no gratitude from the community they serve
so selflessly. But the Nichols verdict was a major-league
head-scratcher, if not a bafflement of historic proportions.
</P>
<P>
   How in the world could jurors find that Nichols conspired to use
a weapon of mass destruction _ conspiring with McVeigh, of all
people, who was sentenced to death in an earlier trial _ and then
find him not guilty of murdering people who died in the mass
destruction?
</P>
<P>
   Even in the face of that mind-boggling lapse of logic, however,
the jury could have used the conspiracy conviction to put Nichols
in the death chamber right along with McVeigh. But they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Which set the stage for Thursday's sentencing by the judge, who
seems very much like a man who might have doled out the ultimate
punishment to Nichols if only the law had allowed it.
</P>
<P>
   Matsch called Nichols an ``enemy of the Constitution'' as he
slapped him with a life sentence on the conspiracy charge and eight
concurrent terms of six years each in the deaths of the federal
agents. To the extent that he was able to do so, Matsch threw the
book at Nichols; it's easy to imagine that the judge would have
enjoyed throwing a bigger book.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols accepted his fate with no outward sign of emotion,
although one news report said that he ``sank into a chair and began
to quietly sob'' before the judge entered the courtroom to begin
the hearing. Do you suppose he quietly sobbed for the 168 victims
who lost their lives as the result of his conspiracy? Did he sob
for the loved ones of those who were killed, or for the 500 people
who were injured in the bombing?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not, if a letter that Nichols wrote to the judge after
his trial was an accurate indication of his remorsefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did anything to contribute to the cause of the Oklahoma
City bombing, I am sorry, I'm truly sorry,'' Nichols wrote.
``Perhaps I should have questioned McVeigh more about certain
things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If'' he did anything to contribute to the bombing?
</P>
<P>
   You really have to admire a guy who takes responsibility for his
actions.
</P>
<P>
   The letter apparently represented Nichols' best bid for a
lighter sentence, and the judge properly treated the letter with
all the respect it warranted: none.
</P>
<P>
   But Matsch reportedly offered to cut Nichols some slack if he
would provide additional information about the planning and
execution of the bombing. Nichols declined that deal, his lawyers
said, because he faces further prosecution in Oklahoma and feared
that any information he provided might be used against him.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma prosecutors, by the way, will seek the death
penalty for both Nichols and McVeigh when they put them on trial
for the 160 bombing deaths that were not included in the federal
trials. Maybe those Oklahoma jurors will give Nichols the sentence
he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3702 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMF-546&AMP;ADD-NY     06-10 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-546&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF DEMANDS IMPROVEMENTS IN RUSSIAN ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The International Monetary Fund has told the Russian
government that it needs to slash its budget deficit and overhaul
its antiquated tax system if it wants to qualify for billions of
dollars in additional loans, senior Russian officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among other measures, the fund also wants Russia to strengthen
its banking system. And fund officials have even gone so far as to
suggest that the operations of Gazprom, the huge natural gas
monopoly, be split up.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF says its demands are intended to advance long-stalled
economic reforms. But the fund's critics worry that the IMF may be
asking too much of Russia at a time when its financial markets are
under enormous strain and new aides to President Boris Yeltsin are
just taking over.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has refused to outline its demands in public. Its
official position is that it is too soon to say whether extra help
is even needed.
</P>
<P>
   But the fund opened negotiations with Moscow this week by
sending the Yeltsin government a confidential letter listing steps
it would like Russia to take, Russian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not saying there will be no money for the Russian
government,'' an IMF official said. ``But we are not saying that it
is guaranteed, and we need to know if Russia can meet the
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said the measures suggested by the fund
include a commitment to slash Russia's budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Under the fund's plan, the deficit would be cut to 2.5 percent
of the nation's gross domestic product in 1999, well under the 4.5
percent target originally envisoned by the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   The fund also wants Russia to adopt a new tax code that would
lower rates and make the taxation system more fair. Tax reform has
languished in the Communist-dominated Parliament, and the IMF would
like to see that measure and a new code on budgetary procedures
adopted before the Legislature recesses in mid-July, according to
Kremlin aides.
</P>
<P>
   Other fund proposals call on the central bank to be more open
about its activities and statistics and for Gazprom's pipeline to
be split from its gas extraction operations.
</P>
<P>
   The behind-the-scenes talks are taking place at a critical time
for the troubled Russian economy. Russia has been successful in
proping up the ruble. But its financial markets have been shaky.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Russia's stock market fell for a fifth straight
day and the government failed to sell enough treasury bills to
cover its short-term debt. On Tuesday Standard &AMP; Poor's lowered its
long-term credit rating for Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Western finance ministers and Western investors are
at odds over how much help Russia should receive and how fast.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has already given Russia more than $5.2 billion of a $10
billion loan. It is soon expected to approve another $670 million
installment of this three-year loan.
</P>
<P>
   The key issue is whether to lend $5 billion to $10 billion in
additional funds, or perhaps even more, to help Russia's central
bank defend the ruble and ease the fears of foreign investors who
fear Russia's currency will be devalued.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris the Group of Seven nations said they would support an
additional IMF loan if needed. Many investment bankers, however,
say the West is moving much too slowly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Based on what is going on in the market it is clear that
Russia needs more assistance,'' said Charles Blitzer, director of
emerging markets for Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, an investment
bank. ``And the sooner the size, timing and composition of that
support is known the better. Waiting to see if words alone
stabilize the market is a form of Russian roulette.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly the discussions are also focusing on what Russia
would have to do to get any extra assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Vyugin, Russia's deputy finance minister, has flown to
Washington for talks with IMF and American officials. The issue is
also the focus of top-level deliberations in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IMF has sent a written communication to the Russians, and
there are active consultations between the Russians and the IMF,''
a senior Western official said Wednesday. A Russian official said
that the letter was drafted by the fund's top expert on Russia,
John Odling-Smee.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the fund's guiding philosophy is that Russia is going to
have to do a lot more to restructure its economy and restore the
confidence of foreign investors if it wants to tap additional
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian officials say that IMF pressure is useful in
overcoming bureaucratic resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never said the IMF is too tough,'' Boris Fyodorov, the
new head of the State Tax Service, said in an interview. ``My
personal view is that the IMF is never pressuring Russia enough.''
</P>
<P>
   But other pro-reform Russian aides say the matter is more
complex. They say the fund's pressure is useful to a point, but
they worry that Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko and his young team
of aides will not be able to meet all of the new conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fund's demands are sensible but also very difficult,''
said one Russian official. ``It is necessary to do them. The
question is whether it will be possible to do them.''
</P>
<P>
   A new tax code, for example, would require winning over the
Communist-dominated Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The new deficit target is considered to be very ambitious, and
the suggestion that Gazprom be broken up was called a political
non-starter by one Russian aide, who added that he doubted the fund
would insist on it.
</P>
<P>
   While Russia's economy is weak, it has other ways to raise
money, including through the Eurobond market and commercial bank
loans. And while the IMF position is strong, the fund has already
been encouraged by the Clinton administration to do more for the
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have supported the fund's basic line that
more Russian reforms are needed. But if the ruble began to falter,
American pressure for speedy IMF action would grow.
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers put it in
Paris Wednesday, the industrialized nations support aid ``as
necessary and as appropriate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2032EDT &QL; 
