<SLUG> BC-HONEYWELL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONEYWELL TO HIRE LAID-OFF MOTOROLA, IN TEL WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CRAIG ANDERSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Relocating, re-training, starting over at the bottom
of the pay scale: These are the travails of the laid-off worker.
</P>
<P>
   That's if you can find a new job.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Valley Motorola Inc. employees and hundreds of
Intel Corp. workers are expected to lose their jobs in the next
year, but a massive hiring effort by Honeywell Inc. could ease the
pain for as many as 500 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell, which already employs 7,500 in the Phoenix area in
three main divisions, is suffering from a shortage of engineers,
technicians, assemblers and other personnel, staffing manager
Lesley Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   The electronics and aviation systems manufacturer hopes to take
advantage of proposed layoffs at other high-tech firms to fill its
own personnel void.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company is helping unemployed workers by
finding them new local jobs which require a minimal amount of
re-training, Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Due in part to a decreased demand for semiconductor chips, Intel
recently has announced it will cut 600 jobs in the Valley of the
Sun.
</P>
<P>
   While details about Motorola's cutbacks locally haven't been
finalized, the computer giant announced last week that it would
eliminate 10 percent of its workforce worldwide. If applied across
the board, the cut would amount to 2,000 of Motorola's 20,000
workers in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly said Honeywell has 400 to 500 local jobs available and
about 80 more at a plant in Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   The company, the ninth-largest private employer in Arizona,
makes a variety of computer systems for everything from commercial
aircraft to space vehicles. Another division makes industrial
automation systems for companies that manufacturer a wide range of
products, including aspirin and paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to hire employees who have worked for big companies
like Intel and Motorola,'' Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola spokesman Larry Barton said the company appreciates
Honeywell's response to the layoffs, athough he is not sure whether
the help is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hoping to have a good response to our voluntary
severance program, so job fairs and database searches will not be
needed,'' Barton said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's response was more enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be thrilled to work with them,'' said Intel spokeswoman
Shelly Esque. ``Our recruiters did a scan of the market and felt
that there were many, many good opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Esque said she wasn't aware of Honeywell's job openings but
expects the company's recruiters to post the jobs in Intel's career
resource center as soon as details are available. The center
already has 500 postings, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Although Honeywell does not manufacture the same type of product
as Intel and Motorola, which primarily make computer chips for
personal computers, cellular phones and other devices, Connelly
said the same kind of experience is required.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the skills are transferrable,'' she said. ``Where
re-training is required, we are happy to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell plans to attend upcoming job fairs for Intel and
Motorola employees, in addition to placing job announcements in
local newspapers. &QL; 
Craig Anderson can be reached at craig.anderson(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
