<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-ART-525&AMP;AD     06-10 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN AGAIN CONSIDERS CLOSING WEAK BANKS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dc) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Six months after it retreated from closing weak banks or
allowing them to fail, the Japanese government is once again
inclined to administer such shock therapy as a cure for the
nation's sick financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Although no bank failures are expected before elections for the
upper house of Parliament in July, comments from leaders of the
governing Liberal Democratic Party suggest that they would not
rescue financial institutions, some large, that are verging on
insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are betting against the survival of at least two of
Japan's weakest banks among the top 20 in the country, the Nippon
Credit Bank and the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Lenders and stockholders are abandoning them and other weak
institutions. Nippon Credit shares traded here Wednesday at 121
yen, down 4 percent so far this week. The Long-Term Credit Bank's
stock closed at 176 yen, down 8 percent in the same brief time.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have resumed handicapping merger possibilities they
envisioned last fall, when a string of failures shook the financial
system. Those merger possibilities were dropped when government
bureaucrats insisted that no further fallout was evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a greater possibility than before that the
government would consider shutting down some banks,'' said James P.
Fiorillo, a banking analyst at ING Baring Securities of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Seiroku Kajiyama, a senior Liberal Democratic Party
leader whose outspoken criticism of government efforts to fix the
financial system have been a source of irritation, said Japan
needed only half the number of banks it now has. ``Japanese banks
can't survive with the current number,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   And Koichi Kato, the party's general secretary and a longtime
critic of the Finance Ministry, which oversees the banking system,
said last month in Washington that more bank closings ``could well
be expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's banks are struggling with an estimated $600 billion in
bad debt, a legacy of the speculative ``bubble economy'' of the
1980s. Last month, some of the largest banks reported their biggest
annual losses ever.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the banking system seemed poised for a major overhaul
when a number of overly indebted institutions collapsed. Sanyo
Securities closed in November, quickly followed by the Hokkaido
Takushoku Bank, Yamaichi Securities and a smaller regional bank.
</P>
<P>
   Investors expected more, but the torrid pace seemed to unsettle
Finance Ministry bureaucrats, who spent much of December insisting
that no more banks would fail.
</P>
<P>
   But market wisdom has held just as stubbornly that, just as
there is overcapacity in the global auto business that only
consolidation will repair, there are too many Japanese financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment has hung over the Japanese economy and stock
market, despite a rescue package of 30 trillion yen for the
financial system as well as several economic-stimulus packages.
</P>
<P>
   With few options left, politicians now seem more resigned to
further financial institution failures.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorillo and other analysts decline to identify which banks they
considered candidates for closing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last fall, the government made life difficult for the firms that
employ analysts who spoke their minds about specific banks,
accusing them of spreading rumors to support short-sellers, or
investors who bet on stock declines. Right-wing extremists
threatened the lives of two banking analysts who made the names
public.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Credit's problems have been grist for the rumor mill for
more than a year. The government arranged for a bailout for the
bank last summer, pressing insurance companies and other banks to
recapitalize it by buying preferred shares and issuing subordinated
debt, which carries a higher risk of nonpayment than other types of
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Credit now wants to extend the terms on some of those
loans because it will have trouble meeting its obligations. Lenders
are balking.
</P>
<P>
   One of those, Nippon Life Insurance Co., sent a clear signal of
its sentiments about the banking system when it announced over the
weekend that it would no longer make subordinated loans to
financial institutions because it considered them too great a
credit risk. The finance ministry has said it will not protect
shareholders or subordinated-debt holders.
</P>
<P>
   The Long-Term Credit Bank's shares have been pummeled, as rumors
circulated that its investment banking alliance with Swiss Bank
Corp. was unraveling. Both it and Swiss Bank deny that their
relationship is dissolving, but Swiss Bank has also made clear that
it feels no obligation to rescue its partner, should it need help.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorillo calls Long-Term Credit the ``hardest call'' he has. He
said the bank was not in as precarious a position as Nippon Credit
because it had no immediate need for additional funds.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Service currently gives 10 Japanese financial
institutions its worst rating for financial strength, including
Long-Term Credit, Sakura Bank and Daiwa Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Daiwa is widely regarded as a potential acquisition target for a
foreign bank. Tokai Bank and Asahi Bank are often discussed as
candidates for potential mergers or takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   And banks are expected to take advantage of changes in the
holding-company law to consolidate. Sanwa Bank, for instance, could
absorb Toyo Trust and Banking, or Fuji Bank could take in the
ever-ailing Yasuda Trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
