<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3709 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-MARRIAGE-NYT &LR;      06-10 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-MARRIAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARRIAGE-TAX AMENDMENT MOVES ANTI-SMOKING BILL ALONG IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Texas, S.C., Fla., Vt., Mass., Maine, R.I.)  (See also TOBACCO-LOTT) 
(th) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted Wednesday night to use part of the
money that would be raised from higher cigarette prices to give an
income-tax break to married couples with low and moderate incomes.
</P>
<P>
   The vote gave additional strength to anti-smoking legislation
that has been before the Senate for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage-tax amendment was approved on a voice vote, after a
procedural motion to kill it failed on a 50-48 roll call along
party lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican amendment to the tobacco bill would give all
couples with annual incomes below $50,000 a new tax deduction of
$825 this year, rising gradually to $3,300 in 2008. The amendment
was billed as a reduction in the marriage tax penalty _ the
additional income taxes some couples owe above what they would owe
if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic alternative was then rejected, 55-43, on another
party-line vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican amendment would also allow self-employed
taxpayers to deduct the full cost of their medical insurance
premiums beginning with this year's taxes. Under the current tax
law, the self-employed can deduct 45 percent of the cost of
premiums, and the percentage will not reach 100 percent until 2007.
</P>
<P>
   The tax relief seemed likely to win more Republican support for
the underlying tobacco legislation. Many Republicans have argued
that the anti-smoking bill was mainly a tax increase to finance a
big-government solution to the problem of teen-age smoking that was
bound to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the steam is taken out of the tax argument if, as
Wednesday night's amendment would require, one-third of all the
revenues generated would be used to provide a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argue that it is bad public policy to impose higher
taxes on couples who marry than on those who live together out of
wedlock. Party leaders have made elimination of the marriage
penalty their No. 1 tax priority this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the House of Representatives approved a budget
blueprint that would allot $100 billion to that end over the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Wednesday night, which followed hours of tense
negotiations, was a big step in moving the tobacco bill to final
passage by the Senate. That could occur as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   But serious obstacles remain, especially a dispute over whether
the government's price-support program for tobacco farmers should
be abolished and how much money should be allotted to ease the
financial burden on tobacco growers and communities whose economy
depends on tobacco farming and cigarette manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   And many Republican senators continue to oppose the bill, even
with the tax breaks approved Wednesday night. ``The bill is still a
tax increase bill,'' said Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Meant to reduce the number of young people who start to smoke,
the bill would raise the price of cigarettes by at least $1.10 a
pack over the next five years, expand the government's authority to
regulate cigarette advertising and marketing and impose penalties
on tobacco companies if teen-age smoking did not fall to specified
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich said Wednesday that the House of
Representatives was working on a much narrower anti-smoking bill.
He called the measure before the Senate a ``dead end.''
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the tax break for couples, said Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, the main sponsor of the amendment, was to ``help working
families shield more of their income.''
</P>
<P>
   The new break would not be limited to those who face a marriage
penalty. More than half of taxpayers who file joint returns pay
lower taxes than they would if they filed as individuals _ what
some call a marriage bonus _ but even those with a bonus would be
entitled to the new deduction under the amendment approved
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   As a general rule, the penalty applies when a husband and wife
both work and earn approximately the same amount of money. Couples
normally get a bonus if only one spouse works or if one earns much
more than the other.
</P>
<P>
   All the Senate Democrats who voted favored killing the Gramm
amendment, except for Ernest Hollings of South Carolina. But they
were joined by only five Republicans: Susan Collins and Olympia
Snowe of Maine, John Chaffee of Rhode Island, Connie Mack of
Florida and James Jeffords of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' alternative amendment, which failed, would have
given larger tax breaks than Gramm's plan to couples that faced a
marriage penalty but little if any tax relief to couples who now
pay lower taxes because they are married. ``There's no rationale
for rewarding those who get a bonus,'' said Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also argued that the Gramm amendment would become so
expensive in the second decade of the next century that it would
eat into budget surpluses that should be set aside for Social
Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said that the Democratic plan would have had the effect of
penalizing parents who stayed home to take care of children.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said that President Clinton preferred the
Democratic approach but could live with the Gramm amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco bill was approved by the Senate Commerce Committee
in April on a strong bipartisan vote. But the cigarette makers
abandoned the bill as too costly and mounted a nationwide
advertising and lobbying campaign to defeat the bill.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the bill was bogged down in the Senate. But Tuesday,
senators began to find ways to unclog the logjam. The Senate then
attached to the tobacco bill several measures meant to combat drug
abuse, an important Republican issue. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
