<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-TOBACCO-COX &UR; 520&AMP;A     06-10 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
   520&AMP;ADD  SENATE VOTES REDUCTION OF MARRIAGE
TAX PENALTY
 &HT;     With TOBACCO-TAX-CUT.
 &HT;     By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-led Senate took the first step
toward its long-cherished goal of eliminating the ``marriage
penalty'' Wednesday by offering a tax cut to families earning less
than $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The key 50-48 vote came on an amendment to the comprehensive
tobacco bill, which would raise the price of cigarettes by $1.10 a
pack.
</P>
<P>
   When fully implemented by 2008, the $46 billion measure,
sponsored by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, would eventually provide a
$3,300 income tax deduction for married couples _ $1,650 for
married individuals filing separately _ who fell below the income
cap. For 1999, the first year it would take effect, the deduction
would be $850.
</P>
<P>
   Five Republicans joined the unanimous Democrats in opposing the
amendment. A $31 billion Democratic alternative, which its sponsors
said would have given more relief to those couples who pay higher
taxes because they are married but which would have taken less
money from anti-smoking and medical research efforts, failed 55-43.
</P>
<P>
   While Gramm's amendment would produce $46 billion in tax relief
over 10 years, over 25 years it would consume about one-third of
the $516 billion expected to be raised from the tobacco bill.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage penalty amendment, plus a drug enforcement
amendment adopted Tuesday, are two elements GOP lawmakers have
demanded be a part of any tobacco bill, and their adoption raised
hopes among the overall bill's backers that it would win Senate
passage.
</P>
<P>
   But even the amendments' sponsors indicated they still opposed
the tobacco bill sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., claiming
it was too expensive and too great an increase in federal programs.
With contentious amendments relating to relief for tobacco farmers
and limitations on attorneys fees still pending, the fate of the
tobacco bill remained uncertain late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, the Senate rejected, for the second time in
two days, a Democratic motion to curtail amendments and force a
final vote within a limited time. The vote was 55-43, largely along
party lines. Another vote to limit debate is scheduled for
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the White House would have preferred the Democratic
alternative, press secretary Mike McCurry said the Republican
proposal was acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have gone from an appetite for a much more expansive
approach on tax cuts ... to what is, in effect, a fairly targeted
approach to middle-income tax relief,'' McCurry said, adding that
the GOP plan was ``consistent with what the administration's
approach to tax relief has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, House Speaker Newt Gingrich signalled that the House
would not accept anything close to McCain's bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said the House would pass a bill more narrowly focused
on reducing teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine why the Republican conference would pass a
$600 billion increase in the size of government. It is antithetical
to everything we believe in,'' Gingrich said. ``This became the
gravy train of Teddy Kennedy and every liberal in the country. The
House, I think, will never conference on the McCain bill. The
McCain bill, I believe, is a dead end because it got off the real
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The fight over the marriage tax had stymied progress on the
tobacco bill for the last two weeks, first as Gramm and McCain
negotiated the level of tax relief, then as the parties debated the
procedure they would use in considering their alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that smoking was far more prevalent among middle- and
low-income individuals, Gramm argued the marriage tax relief was
necessary because nearly half of the money raised by the bill would
come from families with incomes below $22,000 and nearly 60 percent
would be from families below $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shields tobacco companies and it squarely hits
moderate-income, blue-collar workers right in the wallet and in the
pocketbook,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argued that Gramm's proposal would not only help
couples paying the marriage penalty, but also those couples who
receive a tax benefit from being married.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, couples in which both partners earn about the same
amount of money pay higher taxes when married than they would have
if they remained single. But couples in which one partner makes
substantially more than the other _ such as in cases where one
spouse was at home _ generally pay lower taxes than if they were
not married.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic alternative, which would have given couples a 20
percent deduction on the income of the spouse earning the least,
was targeted at couples that paid a tax penalty, said Sen. John
Kerry, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But Gramm argued that it discriminated unfairly against couples
in which _ in most cases _ the wife decided to stay at home and
raise the children.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic bill, Gramm said, ``gives no relief to the family
where one parent stays home and works in the home _ one of the most
important jobs in America and one of the most difficult jobs in
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want the government to be making the decision as to
whether parents work outside the home or inside the home,'' he
said. ``The tax code shouldn't discriminate against parents ... who
chose to have one of the parents stay home to raise children.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry warned that Gramm's proposal, because it was limited to
one-third of the tobacco bill's revenues, would require additional
money from the general fund. That would have to come out of the
government surplus earmarked for Social Security, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vote for the Gramm amendment is a vote to take $90 billion
to $125 billion of surplus away from Social Security,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Sherman of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution contributed to
this story.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
