<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REPUBLICAN TRIUMPH IS POSSIBLE, BUT ONLY IF ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Republicans are excited. And they have a right to be.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party of Texas is about to take over the state _
lock, stock and barrel.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the advance PR says, anyway, as Republicans from all
over Texas gather in Fort Worth this week for their state
convention. A media ``advisory'' hyping the convention proclaims
that ``Republicans are poised to sweep all statewide seats,
maintain our majority in the Senate, and take control of the Texas
House of Representatives for the first time in over 120 years.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend toward Texas becoming a conservative Republican
state is undeniable and gaining momentum. The State Convention will
serve as the launching point for the Republican Party of Texas to
change the course of Texas history in 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   A skeptic might suspect that winning elections ``and'' changing
the course of history is an awfully ambitious agenda for
Republicans in a state where Democrats once reigned supreme _ and
not so long ago, come to think of it. An objective observer, if
there is such a thing nowadays, might wonder if the Republicans are
overreaching. There is that old saying about counting your
chickens, after all.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there's another old saying: If you can do it,
it ain't bragging.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have guessed that the Republican Party of Texas could
have grown the way it has in recent years, that untold numbers of
card-carrying Texas Democrats could have been lured into the Grand
Old Party?
</P>
<P>
   Who would have guessed? Probably some of the same people who are
now predicting a Republican takeover of the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of the GOP in Texas is no accident. It is the result
of years of hard work and dedication by party leaders and
grassroots volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans keep working _ and keep working together _ there
is no reason they can't accomplish everything that the news
releases predict they will.
</P>
<P>
   The operative words here are ``working together.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile portion of the state convention _ the official
ceremonies and business sessions to be conducted Friday and
Saturday at the Fort Worth Convention Center _ is guaranteed to be
a gala exercise in party unity and back-slapping.
</P>
<P>
   All the big names will be on hand: Gov. George W. Bush, Sens.
Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison, statewide candidates,
legislative leaders, congressional movers and shakers ...
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of rank-and-file Republicans will be there to cheer on
the party honchos, and to be cheered by the honchos in return. At
week's end, the Republicans figure to pour out of Forth Worth
energized and motivated as they look toward the history-changing
weeks and months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it will be, if the PR hype is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a potential problem. One faction of the Republican
Party wants to turn the GOP into something other than a statewide,
nationwide, majority party. What this faction wants, far more than
winning elections and prevailing in the halls of government, is to
purge the Republican Party of those it deems unworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Unworthy Republicans, by the way, are those who embrace any idea
or attitude that fails to conform with the controlling faction's
agenda. And that agenda is mostly set behind the scenes, beyond the
public's view.
</P>
<P>
   While the party celebrates its unity and ubiquitousness, while
the throngs applaud the speeches by Bush and Gramm and others, the
behind-the-scenes manipulators will be working to undermine the
widespread appeal of Republicanism. They will be working to narrow
the party's scope in a way that discourages any divergence of views
and precludes the possibility of universal participation.
</P>
<P>
   That's no way to run a party.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republican Party truly wants to dominate politics in
Texas and across America, then it should use the occasion of its
state convention in Fort Worth to reiterate its commitment to that
``big tent'' we used to hear so much about.
</P>
<P>
   If the party of Barry Goldwater and Ronald Reagan truly wants to
change the course of history, it must remember that debate and
disagreement are crucial to a political party's enduring viability.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans must remember that a political party expands its
horizons by working toward principled consensus, not by imposing
rigid doctrines that exclude all dissent.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
