<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN SIGNALS NO DESIRE TO RAISE INTEREST RATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, applauding
the economy's ``virtuous cycle'' of strong growth and low
inflation, signaled no desire Wednesday to raise interest rates
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, appearing before Congress' Joint Economic Committee,
described the economy's ability to grow at such a strong clip while
keeping inflation in check as ``extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The current economic performance, with its combination of
strong growth and low inflation, is as impressive as any I have
witnessed in my near half-century of daily observation of the
American economy,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous analysts interpreted Greenspan's ever-careful
phraseology to mean the Fed has no intention of tightening monetary
policy by raising short-term interest rates at its meeting at the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are not the words of a man who is about to pull the
tightening trigger,'' said Robert Dederick, economic consultant for
Northern Trust in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Some Fed watchers are even ruling out a rate hike at the Fed
policy-making committee's subsequent session in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of positive-type references in his testimony suggest
that we're going to get a bye on, maybe, a meeting or a couple of
meetings,'' said James Barkocy, U.S. economist for Brown Brothers
Harriman in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted positively to Greenspan's comments
Wednesday, rising slightly after his testimony. But even the
central banker's reassuring words could not head off a
late-afternoon sell-off that sent the Dow Jones industrial average
down 78.22 to close at 8971.70.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 1/4 points, or $12.50
per $1,000 bond, to 106, the biggest gain in almost six weeks. Its
yield fell 9 basis points to 5.70 percent, just above the 5.69
percent level reached Jan. 12, the lowest since the government
began regular sales of the 30-year securities in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   While maintaining an upbeat tone, Greenspan noted the economy is
feeling the effects of the economic and currency crisis in East
Asia, as well as a continued strong U.S. dollar abroad.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. exports fell during the first quarter for the first time in
four years, Greenspan noted.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of nation's domestic product was shaved by 2.5
percentage points to 4.8 percent, with the economic crisis in East
Asia, which has ravaged economies from Thailand to South Korea,
accounting for half of that reduction.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. inventories, meanwhile, are on the rise, an indication
production at many companies could slow even further later in the
year as companies work off excess stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the nation's economy has slowed from its ``torrid''
pace during the first quarter, Greenspan said, although it
continues to move ahead at a robust rate.
</P>
<P>
   All of these factors would tend to lessen concerns about a
return of inflation. In fact, inflation actually moved down further
during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan made clear the Fed has not dropped its guard
against this old enemy, run-away inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are remaining watchful for signs of potential inflationary
imbalances, even as the economy continues to perform more
impressively than it has in a very long time,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Chan, managing director and chief economist for Banc One
Investment Advisors Corp. in Columbus, Ohio, was struck by the
emphasis Greenspan gave to the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have not really seen a Federal Reserve in the past
stressing the effects of international forces,'' Chan said. ``So
given that these international forces have really become more
supportive of an unchanged policy, the message should be that the
Fed is not likely to raise rates.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During his testimony, Greenspan avoided the kind of explosive
choice of words that has rocked the markets in the past. In
December 1996, stocks nose-dived when the Fed chairman referred to
the market's ``irrational exuberance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan did raise new warning about today's stock price
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors seem to be expecting that low inflation and stronger
productivity growth will allow the extraordinary growth of profits
to be extended into the distant future,'' Greenspan said. ``These
rising expectations have, in turn, driven stock prices sharply
higher and credit spreads lower, perhaps to levels that will be
difficult to sustain unless economic conditions remain
exceptionally favorable _ more so than might be anticipated from
historical relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
