<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-ART-690&AMP;ADD-NY     06-10 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-ART-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED CHAIRMAN'S REPORT AIDS BOND-MARKET RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic showing 10-year and 30-year bonds since Jan. 1998
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(ja) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long-term interest rates fell sharply Wednesday, as
the Asian financial crisis and continuing problems in Russia
apparently sent more foreigners to the haven of the American bond
market.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve Board,
helped the rally when he indicated, in an upbeat assessment of the
economy, that an interest-rate increase to slow economic growth was
not imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year bond fell to 5.70 percent, just a tick
away from the 5.69 percent closing low it reached in January. That
yield for the 30-year bond was the lowest since the Treasury began
issuing the bonds in 1977. At the same time, yields on corporate
debt approached 30-year lows.
</P>
<P>
   Other interest rates, however, have not fallen back to their
January levels, which means that mortgage rates are still above the
four-year lows they reached at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   While Greenspan said that the American economy was ``still
enjoying a virtuous cycle,'' he also said the Asian crisis could
lead to a cut in earnings expectations, a key element in the
outlook for the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian crisis, he told Congress' Joint Economic Committee,
should lead to both a further dampening of American export sales
and a reduction in profit margins because of rising price pressures
from cheaper imports. Both developments would cut into earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market plunged in the afternoon, as Boeing Co. and
Lattice Semiconductor Corp. announced that the Asian problems were
worsening their earnings outlooks, emphasizing Greenspan's warning.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks fell 6.13 points to
1,112.28, while the Nasdaq index dropped 27.51 points, or 1.5
percent, to 1,773.25. The Dow Jones industrial average, which has
suffered the least in the recent market downturn, fell 78.22
points, to 8,971.70.
</P>
<P>
   Although Greenspan raised the issue of earnings and the stock
market, he did not make any comments that appeared aimed at talking
the market down. He has tried that in the past only to see stocks
rally after an initial negative reaction.
</P>
<P>
   But in a contorted way _ something that a quick reading of his
remarks might miss _ Greenspan did say that a decline in stock
prices would help the central bank avoid an interest rate increase
because the fall would probably help curtail the consumer spending
that has helped propel the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In listing the factors that could help slow growth and obviate
the need for an interest-rate increase, Greenspan said, ``Reduced
prospects for the return to capital would not only affect
investment directly but could also affect consumption as stock
prices adjusted to a less optimistic view of earnings prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts did not focus on this part of his remarks, however.
They were more taken by his positive outlook. He said that wages
had not risen as much as one would have suspected and that
productivity gains might offset inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sounded more optimistic about the long-run prospects of
keeping inflation down than in his previous testimony,'' said
Richard Berner, chief economist at the Mellon Bank in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the surge in bond prices, which move in the opposite
direction of yields, came after stock markets dropped sharply in
Asia, showing that the economic turmoil there that helped push
interest rates to their January lows might be deepening. The price
of the 30-year bond rose 1 7/32 to 106 2/32, as the yield fell from
5.78 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hang Seng index in Hong Kong dropped 4.9 percent, to
7,979.26, a three-year low that brought it below the 8,121.06 low
it reached on Jan. 12, the same day that the 30-year bond yield
reached 5.69 percent. The Nikkei index in Japan dropped 1.2 percent
to 15,339.
</P>
<P>
   Also adding to concerns about the world's emerging markets was
the failure of the weekly Russian treasury bills sale. The
government needed to raise $1.1 billion to cover maturing issues
but received only $742 million, raising concerns about the
government's ability to pay its debts without new international
assistance. A key Russian stock index dropped 6.2 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even though the yield on the 30-year bond is near its recent
lows, other interest rates are not nearly so low as they were in
January. For example, the yield on the 10-year note dropped to 5.50
percent Wednesday from 5.58 Tuesday. But it is still well above
January's 5.36 percent level, which is why mortgage rates have not
gone down to January levels.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Bank Rate Monitor, the average rate nationally
on a 30-year mortgage is 6.92 percent, still above the 6.87 percent
of mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   And short-term rates are so much higher than they were in
January that the 5.50 percent yield on the 10-year note Wednesday
was below that of the two-year note, 5.52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that short-term rates are high is that investors
still expect the Fed to raise its interest rates target sometime in
the next year. In January, when the yield on the two-year note
dropped to 5.17 percent, some expected the economy to slow enough
for the Fed to cut interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In some circumstances, a move of short-term interest rates above
longer-term interest rates could signal that the economy will be
slowing down if the so-called inversion is caused by the Fed's
decision to raise its short-term interest-rate target.
</P>
<P>
   But in the current circumstances, the inversion is caused more
by a fall in longer-term rates that reflects positive views on
inflation and, therefore, it is not a warning signal, Berner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
