<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3726 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-LOTT-ART-NYT &LR;      06-10 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LOTT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE GOP LEADER WALKS TOBACCO TIGHTROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Okla., Ohio, Ariz., Texas, Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the anti-smoking issue came before Congress
last year, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott had an ethical
problem: his brother-in-law Richard Scruggs was one of the lawyers
who had negotiated the tobacco settlement and stood to make
millions from any legislation.
</P>
<P>
   So to avoid conflict, Lott turned the issue over to others, and
to this day he carefully votes ``present'' on any amendments that
might affect the lawyers' fees that might come out of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But as the man who controls the Senate floor and searches for
the Republican consensus, he has now emerged as one of the critical
political players who will determine the fate of anti-tobacco
legislation this year. As the Mississippi Republican himself has
said, ``You can't really recuse yourself from being the majority
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   So on some days, he proclaims the tobacco legislation to be near
death. On others, he seeks to smooth the way for conservatives to
sweeten the tobacco bill with tax cut and anti-drug amendments that
might help them swallow it.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite plain that he does not like the bill's $516 billion
cost to the tobacco industry. It is equally clear that he
recognizes the perils to many Republicans of looking like pawns of
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   What is not altogether clear to his colleagues is whether Lott
has a carefully plotted strategy, that he sees around corners and
anticipates where he wants to be three amendments from now.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, as he deals, the buttoned-down 56-year-old
Lott has kept his ultimate intentions to himself. Even his closest
aides refuse to guess whether he will push the bill to completion.
</P>
<P>
   But how he maneuvers the Senate and judges the needs of his
sharply divided Republican conference in these coming days will
help determine whether Congress ends the year with bipartisan
legislation or a campaign issue. And for all Lott's grousing about
the bill, and all the obstacles and uncertainty still ahead, those
who want the Senate to give momentum to an anti-smoking bill this
year tentatively count him as working with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've concluded that Senator Lott isn't wild about this bill,''
said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle. ``But I've also concluded
that I think he would like to see some closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who drafted the tobacco bill, said:
``I don't have a doubt that he wants a bill at the end of the day.
At the same time, he is cognizant that there are not many
legislative days left.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lott has never been quite as distant from the tobacco
issue as he has seemed. In 1996, Scruggs, who was helping the state
of Mississippi sue the tobacco companies for Medicaid costs, called
and asked his brother-in-law whether it was possible that Congress
would sanction a national settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, Republican aides and lobbyists said, suggested that
Scruggs use two Republicans _ John Sears, a former member of the
Nixon administration, and Tommy Anderson, a former chief of staff
to Lott _ as intermediaries to approach the tobacco industry and
see if it would be interested in reaching a deal with its
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican official familiar with Lott's thinking said his
original interest stemmed from his philosophical opposition to
bringing down an industry that had been manufacturing a legal
product. He was also was aware that tobacco was turning into a
political issue that could become difficult for Republicans,
because they have traditionally received the bulk of campaign
contributions from the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1996 that President Clinton, as part of his
re-election campaign, first began taking high-profile stands in
favor of fighting smoking among the young through federal
regulation of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 contacts that Lott helped put in motion produced an
early proposal that the tobacco companies pay the states $150
billion over 15 years. That effort died.
</P>
<P>
   But those first contacts grew into the process, watched over by
the White House, that eventually produced the proposed tobacco
settlement under which the industry would pay $368.5 billion in
fines and fees and institute measures against smoking by young
people in exchange for legal protection.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment that plan was brought before the Senate, it
posed problems for Republicans. Democrats sensed a political
bonanza, an issue on which they could stand for activist government
and protecting the health of teen-agers. But the Republican Party
fractured between those who felt they needed to take a strong stand
against the tobacco companies and those who had a philosophical
objection to a measure that they saw as a Big government approach
to a social problem and one that would impose a large tax on
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   And Lott has his own special problem because of Scruggs, one of
a small group of private lawyers whom states hired to sue the
tobacco companies because they lacked the legal resources
themselves. Those lawyers took the cases on contingent fees, and
when the states won verdicts in the billions, the lawyers stood to
gain hundreds of millions of dollars. Scruggs himself stands to
share in $4.5 billion in state fees. Many lawmakers have sought to
curtail the lawyers' fees severely.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the bill that McCain crafted as chairman of the
Commerce Committee became even worse for the tobacco companies,
costing $516 billion over 25 years and containing far fewer legal
protections for the companies than the original bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lott did not participate in the drafting, and his press
secretary, Susan Irby, says he will ``probably'' not vote on final
passage of the bill. But by proxy he cast his vote in committee in
favor of the bill. He said later he was doing so only to keep the
process moving and to put the issue on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate now moves into its third week, Lott faces a
particularly difficult balancing act. For one thing, Senate
Republicans have no unity on the issue. ``It's not just black or
white, or red or brown,'' said Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio. ``We have
shades of where people are on this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's political base in the Senate has been among
conservatives. Yet conservatives such as Sen. Don Nickles of
Oklahoma, Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas, and Sen. John Aschcroft of
Missouri _ who sings in a barbershop quarter with Lott _ are the
ones most adamantly opposed to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has made clear that he believes the true tobacco
legislation, if there is any eventually, will be written in a
House-Senate conference committee. The House, even more adamant
against McCain's legislation, is expected to write a stripped down
bill to deter teen-age smoking. That will allow the drafting in
essence to start all over again.
</P>
<P>
   But the question remains of whether the Senate will manage to
get a bill to the conference. Monday, Lott said, ``There's a point,
you know, at which you say this thing is not, you know, capable of
being resurrected.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the legislation's prospects seemed to improve this
week, Daschle said Wednesday morning, ``Anybody that would declare
victory today would be a fool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
