<HEADLINE>
DAMAGE-AWARDS BILL HAS NEW BACKER 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wash.)  ( dc ) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A far-reaching measure that would set nationwide
limits on damages awarded in court for faulty products received a
significant boost Wednesday as a leading Senate opponent said he
would now support a version of the law proposed by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., said he would support the bill,
which would set nationwide standards on damage awards to people
harmed by faulty products as diverse as microwave ovens and cardiac
pacemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gorton backed out of a White House plan, ending the
possibility of a compromise. But Gorton said through a spokeswoman
that he now regarded the compromise proposal as ``a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of limiting liability has been pushed by a coalition
of manufacturers for more than two decades. But Gorton, the chief
Republican spokesman on the issue, said last year that the bill
proposed by President Clinton did not provide enough relief,
because some benefits applied only to small companies.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which was taken off the legislative calendar at the
end of 1997 might now be voted on in the Senate next month. It
would limit punitive damages available to someone harmed by a
flawed product manufactured by a company of fewer than 25 employees
to $250,000 or twice that person's actual damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0456 </DOCNO>
