<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL DEFERS TO CRIMINAL PROBE OF REP. SHUSTER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House ethics committee announced Wednesday that
it has curtailed its investigation of Transportation Committee
Chairman Bud Shuster in deference to a Justice Department criminal
probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Justice has indicated that its ongoing
criminal investigation may relate to matters similar to those under
investigation by the committee,'' said the one-paragraph statement
issued by the committee formally known as the House Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's lawyer said there was no indication the Pennsylvania
Republican had become a target of the investigation by US Attorney
Donald Stern in Boston into alleged corruption involving Boston's
$10 billion Central Artery depression project. Stern's office
declined to comment on the ethics committee announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has agreed to refrain from conducting interviews
and deposing witnesses in connection with its investigation of
Shuster and his relationship with lobbyist Ann M. Eppard, who was
his top congressional aide for 20 years and remains his top
campaign fund-raiser. The committee may continue to issue and
enforce subpoenas for documents on the case.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in Boston returned a seven-count indictment
on bribery, corruption, and income tax evasion charges against
Eppard in April. The indictment charged her with accepting $230,000
in payments from a lobbyist working on behalf of two Boston
property owners whose property was threatened by the Big Dig. She
has denied the charges, and Shuster has denounced them as
political.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster was an early supporter of the massive Big Dig project.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Shuster believe investigators were concerned an
offer of congressional immunity in return for Eppard's testimony
could damage the case pending against her. The grand jury has
subpoenaed documents from the committee, but the panel fought that
request.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Delinsky, one of Shuster's Boston lawyers, said the
ethics committee action does not suggest that Shuster is in any
legal trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' he said. ``My understanding is the United
States has absolutely no case against Bud Shuster because he did
nothing wrong, and the US attorney himself said in a public
statement that Bud Shuster is not directly or indirectly implicated
in any pending indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   Delinsky added, ``Bud Shuster has cooperated 100 percent with
the ethics committee investigation. He expects to be fully
vindicated in that investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Shuster, Scott Brenner, said, ``We are very
pleased with the ethics committee's decision concerning the
complaint filed against the congressman. ... This is exactly what
we requested from the ethics committee on March 27.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
