A3730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-542&AMP;ADD     06-10 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-542&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY IMMUNITY DEAL SAID TO BE FAVORED BY BOTH SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As they renewed their negotiations over a possible
immunity agreement, prosecutors and the lawyers for Monica Lewinsky
have two things in common: Each side wants evidence from the other
and each side would prefer an immunity deal to an indictment,
lawyers and others involved in the inquiry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Those forces could ultimately lead to the kind of agreement that
would prove troublesome for President Clinton, although the lawyers
said that the negotiations had only just begun when Ms. Lewinsky's
lawyers met on Tuesday with Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   While the issue was apparently not raised in Tuesday's
discussions, Ms. Lewinsky's legal team has long sought the details
of conversations involving Ms. Lewinsky that were secretly recorded
by Linda Tripp, a former colleague at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, meanwhile, have repeatedly asked to interview Ms.
Lewinsky in order to measure her demeanor and credibility before
approving any kind of immunity deal in which she could become the
main witness for the prosecution in any further proceedings. The
prosecutors have also sought more information from Ms. Lewinsky
about a three-page document she handed Ms. Tripp that provided
talking points about what to say when she was subpoenaed in the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky conferred with her new Washington lawyers again
Wednesday. The Tuesday meeting outlined a framework for further
discussions between the prosecutors and Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers,
Plato Cacheris and Jacob Stein, who replaced William Ginsburg after
he was unable to secure an immunity agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The talking-points memorandum and the Tripp-Lewinsky tapes form
the backbone of the independent counsel's inquiry into whether
anyone lied or obstructed justice over Ms. Lewinsky's relationship
with Clinton. The tapes reportedly contradict the affidavit given
by Ms. Lewinsky to Mrs. Jones' lawyers, in which Ms. Lewinsky said
she never had a sexual relationship with the president. The tapes
are also said to contain Ms. Lewinsky's pleadings that Ms. Tripp
lie under oath about Ms. Lewinsky's relationship in the Jones
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But the full details of the 20 hours of tapes have never been
made public and no one aside from Ms. Tripp and the independent
counsel's office knows what else they might reveal or how damaging
they might be.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is also examining whether anyone has taken steps to
intimidate Ms. Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a federal grand jury in Alexandria, Va., took
testimony from Harold Ickes, a former top White House aide who
remains an adviser to Clinton, about the improper disclosure by the
Pentagon of details from Ms. Tripp's personnel file, according to
lawyers involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon's top spokesman, has acknowledged
that he erred in releasing details from Ms. Tripp's file to The New
Yorker magazine. A statement from Ms. Tripp in her personnel file
said that she had never been arrested, though The New Yorker
disclosed that she had been arrested once as a teen-ager. Bacon has
said he acted on his own and did not release the material following
any requests from the White House or any of his superiors at the
Defense Department.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ickes, a former White House deputy chief of staff, has
acknowledged that he might have asked Bacon about Ms. Tripp before
Bacon disclosed the material from her personnel record. Ickes has
not received any notification that he is anything other than a
witness in the inquiry, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's new legal team was described Wednesday as being
unhappy about a recent spread of photographs in Vanity Fair
magazine, featuring their client in a series of seductive poses and
on a beach in Malibu, Calif., wearing an outfit reminiscent of
Marilyn Monroe's. The pictures appeared to undermine the image of
Ms. Lewinsky that she and her parents have tried to convey: a
young, former White House intern, victimized by circumstances and
hounded by the paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs, for which she was not paid, were arranged by
Ginsburg and approved by her father, Bernard Lewinsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
