r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-LADN     06-10 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHATEVER HAPPENED TO JERRY BUSS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN 
c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have a disturbing confession to make.
</P>
<P>
   I'm worried about my old pal, Jerry Buss.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because he's no longer Jerry Buss.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure, as some are saying, that he's metamorphosed into
Donald T Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not Jerry Buss, either.
</P>
<P>
   No way.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerry Buss I've always known has been the most generous
owner in the NBA, a guy who would unlock his bank vault to win a
world championship for his Lakers, a philanthropist who'd give
Magic Johnson five percent of his team and James Worthy a $12
million going-away gift.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerry Buss I've always known would rather stand up one of
his 21-year-old starlet girlfriends on a date than allow a valued
employee, Jerry West, to become so unhappy that's he's threatening
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerry Buss I've known since 1979, the Jerry Buss I've sat
with umpteen times in his private Forum box during Laker games, the
Jerry Buss I laughed with and kidded with and played cards with in
the early morning hours on so many occasions in the Forum press
lounge, the Jerry Buss I partied with in various Beverly Hills
nightclubs during the 1980s, would never get himself into a money
beef with Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   Never!
</P>
<P>
   Who is this impostor passing himself off as Jerry Buss, long the
most beloved athletic owner in L.A. because of his well-documented
willingness to do what it takes to win world titles for the Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   Should the Inglewood cops be summoned to check this guy's
fingerprints for identification?
</P>
<P>
   I know that Jerry Buss is now in his mid 60s and that aging does
do funny things to people I myself have no idea who that stranger
is that stares back at me when I look into a mirror these harrowing
days but there is no way the Jerry Buss I've known all these years
would offend Jerry West in any manner.
</P>
<P>
   But he has.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, the proud Laker organization that Jerry Buss has so
nobly overseen soon could blow asunder if Jerry West indeed does
leave in a huff, which could have a falling dominos effect of
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant following West out the door.
</P>
<P>
   And all Jerry Buss has to do to rectify this festering problem
is to give Jerry West the $2.3 million he's seeking, which really
isn't that much for a guy whose net profit from his team's $100
million gross earnings the past season probably exceeded $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   To condense a long and convoluted soap opera, Buss offered West
a $5 million bonus a while back for the exemplary work West has
done for him across the years, especially for the vital role he
played in rebuilding the post-Magic Johnson-Kareem Abdul-Jabbar
Lakers with the signing of O'Neal and the drafting of Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   This was a sporting gesture that was typical of the Jerry Buss I
once knew, although Buss did defer payment of the amount to West
across seven years, which in essence diluted the monetary value of
the bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West, whose $1.25 million annual salary ranks him in the
middle of the pack of NBA executives even though he's considered
the shrewdest judge of talent in the league, told Buss last
November that he would like the remainder of his bonus in one
payment.
</P>
<P>
   Buss surprisingly said he'd think about it.
</P>
<P>
   The two men met a couple of weeks ago to discuss the same
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Buss said he'd get back to West on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But Buss still hasn't made up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West has.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Buss coughs up that $2.3 million he owes West, the
60-year-old West will announce his retirement on August 31 from a
team he has worked for since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Buss does decide to give West what he's worth, West
probably will fulfill the final year of his Laker contract as a
consultant instead of a hands-on administrator making all the
team's decisions.
</P>
<P>
   You see, this version of Jerry Buss doesn't even listen to Jerry
West's advice any longer.
</P>
<P>
   If Buss did, Mitch Richmond would have been throwing up jump
shots for the Lakers against the Utah Jazz instead of Eddie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not sure Del Harris would be returning as the Lakers'
coach next season, either.
</P>
<P>
   Harris still might not, but Harris has a year left on a contract
that pays him more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure this guy impersonating Jerry Buss is willing to
take such a financial hit, especially since he's been so willing to
keep Jerry West in a perpetual state of distress over a money
matter.
</P>
<P>
   I just don't know what to make out of this ringer passing
himself off as Jerry Buss.
</P>
<P>
   I'm keeping my fingers solemnly crossed that Jerry Buss hasn't
been seized by the dreaded Pat Riley Personality Transformation
Syndrome (named after the celebrated former Laker coach who
overnight went from being a friendly, gracious, open, amiable
fellow to an arrogant, paranoid, uptight, secretive,
philosophy-spewing boor who takes himself far too seriously).
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Buss still smilingly says hello to me and I haven't
spotted any arrogance in his demeanor, but I'm certain this guy is
disguised to look like Jerry Buss.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerry Buss I've always known never gave even the faintest
hint of acting like Donald T Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
