<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Naming no names, Baptists urge morality
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Southern Baptists urged Americans to consider
character when evaluating the performance of public officials, but
defeated an attempt to single out President Clinton, a fellow
Southern Baptist, in the resolution they adopted at their annual
convention.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution mentions ``serious allegation'' about ``moral and
legal misconduct by certain public officials.'' An amendment
proposed by a California pastor, the Rev. Wiley Drake, would have
added ``William Jefferson Clinton in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Whitehead, chairman of the convention's resolutions
committee and a vice president at Midwestern Theological Seminary
in Kansas City, said ``including personalities would blunt the
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people will say, ``These shoes fit Bill Clinton,''
Whitehead said. ``But as our committee talked about this, we
realized there are scores of people on both ends of Pennsylvania
Avenue whom these shoes fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was directed at citizens to disregard charges of
immorality ``as long as economic prosperity prevails,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
