NYT-06-10-98 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-HEAT-COX     06-10 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-HEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waiting for the rain to reign
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALCUTTA, India -- Every morning at 7, Gita Bashak bathes,
before the water reservoir is warmed by the sun, and sits down at
her altar to pray. For the last three weeks, her prayers have been
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have asked for rain every day,'' Bashak, 47, said. ``Without
fail. Every morning I ask the gods for relief. Sometimes I look out
of the veranda at the cloudy skies and think that, yes, today, the
gods will hear me. But where? Where is the rain? This is just
unbearable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This'' in Calcutta on Wednesday meant a high temperature of
108 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   That coupled with 94 percent humidity has left this city of 11
million reeling in a relentless onslaught of heat.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been this hot on the Indian subcontinent in 50 years.
Blame it on the Gods or on El Nino or, as some joked, the
controversial recent series of nuclear tests in the northwestern
desert region, but the whole country is suffering.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,500 people have died heat-related deaths so far.
Unless the monsoons arrive immediately, more are likely to perish.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, by the first week of June, the monsoons, the result of
a unique weather pattern that develops in the Indian ocean, cross
the subcontinent into the Bay of Bengal. The storms then turn
inland, unloading torrential rain and putting an end to a
blistering Calcutta summer.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, the monsoons are late. Way late.
</P>
<P>
   Calcutta had considered itself lucky compared to New Delhi, the
capital, which has posted highs of 120-plus degrees. But now the
rains have arrived in other parts of the nation, pushing the
mercury down while Calcuttans are still waiting for relief. No one
here remembers it being this hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been here all my life and I have never felt it like
this,'' said Bipul Naskar, a 28-year-old domestic worker. ``I am
having to change my shirt five times a day. A bath is useless,
because five minutes later, you are soaked again with sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the inside of your house feeling like Turner Field at an
afternoon Braves game in August. Or consider trying to sleep at
night inside the sauna at your favorite gym. It is 10 degrees
warmer here than it was on the hottest part of the afternoon on the
hottest day of the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Bustling Calcutta streets are desolate at midday with most shop
windows shuttered. To ward off the pavement heat, water-soaked jute
mats hang on the doors and windows of state-run establishments,
which cannot afford air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   For most out in the sun, beating the heat means a few minutes
sipping lukewarm Coca-Colas at corner stands and covering their
heads with wet handkerchiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Not even a shower is that refreshing: The tap water at 3 in the
afternoon is hot enough to brew a cup of tea.
</P>
<P>
   The normally lush stalls at neighborhood markets are now filled
with yellow and wilted vegetables, and fishmongers are struggling
to keep their morning catches fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Rickshaw pullers are demanding extra fares. Taxi drivers are
sacrificing a third of their paltry $4-a-day salaries, refusing to
drive in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if I lose 50 rupees a day. I have to save my
health,'' said Shymal Maitra, a 28-year-old cab driver, who took
the entire afternoon off after spending several hours behind a
blazing metal dashboard of a 30-year-old Ambassador sedan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels as though someone is burning you alive,'' said
Maitra, pointing to the blisters on his neck and arm.
</P>
<P>
   When the lights turn red and the traffic piles up at Calcutta's
busy intersections, drivers dart out of their cars and pour gallons
of water into their parched radiators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calcutta is hot enough already thanks to the traffic and
pollution. The heat makes it intolerable,'' Maitra said.
</P>
<P>
   Most cars here are not air-conditioned. Neither are the houses
or shops or banks or offices or restaurants, for that matter. There
is absolutely no relief from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, several areas of the city were without
power Tuesday. The Calcutta Municipal Corporation blamed the power
shortages on heat-related transformer trouble and said it could not
guarantee uninterrupted service for the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   As ceiling fans came to a standstill, office buildings and
houses became veritable furnaces. Police now fear violence
especially if frustrated and very hot Calcuttans are denied live
television coverage of World Cup soccer matches.
</P>
<P>
   One local meteorological office offered hope and predicted the
monsoons, still 700 kilometers away from the city, would arrived in
two to three days.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists say Calcuttans must wait until the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   A fluke storm teased for an hour Wednesday afternoon as the
skies turned gray and a cool wind whirled through the city. It
looked as though Gita Bashak's prayers would be answered. Heavenly
drops of water fell from sky to earth, the dusty ground soaking
them up like a sponge.
</P>
<P>
   All over town, people flew out of their houses and into the
streets to taste manna from heaven. Could it be, they wondered,
that the forecasters were wrong and ``barshakal'' (the rainy
season) had finally arrived?
</P>
<P>
   ``I opened every window in the house, and stuck my head out to
feel the water,'' said Bashak.
</P>
<P>
   But it was, as Bashak said, ``too good to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   One hour later, the clouds had vanished and the raging heat had
returned.
</P>
<P>
   And the monsoons seemed a continent away.
</P>
<P>
   Moni Basu, editorial desk chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, is currently visiting her native India.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
