<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO CLOSE TO DECISION ON WHETHER TO USE AIR POWER IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ The 16-member NATO alliance is seriously considering
the use of air power against Serbia to slow the escalating ethnic
violence in the province of Kosovo, according to senior NATO
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   NATO defense ministers gathering here Thursday will examine a
range of options, including deployment of troops along the
Kosovo-Albanian border. But according to the NATO diplomats, the
ministers are more likely to order military commanders to start
planning for air strikes to stop the Serbian crackdown against
Albanian insurgents that has sent thousands fleeing from their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a new sense of urgency, and the focus of the debate
is on air strikes,'' a senior NATO diplomat said as Kosovo
Albanians gathered Wednesday outside NATO headquarters in Brussels,
waving flags and calling for NATO intervention.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is still far from ordering air strikes. Many members of the
alliance, such as Greece, are uneasy about such force against
Serbia. The United Nations Security Council would have to approve
it, and Russia has said it opposes such action.
</P>
<P>
   But air strikes are becoming a popular option as the West grows
frustrated at the offensive launched by the Serb leader, Slobodan
Milosevic, titular president of the Yugsolav Federation. Almost 300
people have been killed in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Tony Blair, the British prime minister, told
Parliament that military action may be needed if diplomacy cannot
end the crisis. US Defense Secretary William S. Cohen, speaking in
Rome, said that force could not be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   The International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia
has also increased pressure against Serbia by launching an inquiry
to determine whether war crimes have been committed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an armed conflict taking place there,'' Graham
Blewitt, a deputy prosecutor for the tribunal, said in an interview
in the Hague. ``We have an investigation under way that, in broad
parameters, will examine the ethnic cleansing and the crimes
against humanity occurring in this armed conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic launched a police action in the Serb-held Kosovo
province in February to break the back of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, the force fighting for independence.
</P>
<P>
   A second sweep last month by police and security forces, which
included heavy shelling, has left villages in ruins and has sent
nearly 12,000 Kosovo Albanians fleeing across the border to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations over the province's future have been fruitless.
Kosovo Albanians, 90 percent of the province's population, have
long argued for autonomy from Serbia. But Milosevic has refused to
cede the province, which some consider the sacred heartland of the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   While Milosevic and his forces clearly launched the brutal
offensive, the Kosovo Liberation Army is also an armed force that
has killed Serbs. And Milosevic has argued that NATO has no right
to intervene in what he calls an internal dispute.
</P>
<P>
   NATO will hold training missions soon in Albania, a member of
NATO's Partnership for Peace program. Six to eight ships are due to
visit the Albanian port of Durress and carry out military
exercises.
</P>
<P>
   One option before defense ministers today is to increase the
visibility of such exercises to send a warning to Milosevic.
Another is to deploy troops along the mountainous Kosovo-Albania
border. A third includes air strikes, which proved effective in
changing the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO diplomats increasingly see air power as the fastest way to
avoid further escalation in the conflict. ``The greatest interest
is in the use of air power,'' a senior NATO diplomat said. ``People
see preventative deployments as less relevant to the current
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO air strikes would not be limited to Kosovo, diplomats
warned. ``Once you cross the line, the whole country is eligible,''
a senior diplomat said of Serbia.
</P>
</TEXT>
