<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury awards deceased man's family nearly $1 million
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ The courtroom wars over tobacco heated up
Wednesday when a jury ordered Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. to
pay nearly $1 million to the family of a dead smoker.
</P>
<P>
   It is the largest cash verdict against a tobacco company, and
only the third courtroom loss for the industry. The award includes
$450,000 in punitive damages, another milestone that bodes ill for
cigarette companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's stunning because it's the first punitive verdict
against the tobacco companies,'' said attorney Norwood Wilner, who
represented the family of Roland Maddox.
</P>
<P>
   News of the verdict sent Brown &AMP; Williamson's stock price
plunging and other tobacco company stocks also fell.
</P>
<P>
   It is Wilner's second victory over Brown &AMP; Williamson. In 1996,
he won a $750,000 judgment for Grady Carter, a lifelong smoker.
That verdict is under appeal. Wilner has lost two cases against
R.J. Reynolds, and has dozens of other tobacco cases lined up for
trial, including three scheduled to begin in October.
</P>
<P>
   John Nyhan, an attorney for Brown &AMP; Williamson, the nation's
third-largest tobacco company, said the Louisville, Ky.-based firm
would appeal the Maddox verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disappointed,'' he said. ``The jurors didn't
recognize Mr. Maddox's responsibility for the personal choices he
made.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
