<HEADER>
A3737 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIAGRA-COX     06-10 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No Viagra without heart check?
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Cardiologists say it is imperative for men who have
heart disease, high blood pressure or circulatory problems to check
with their doctors and undergo a complete physical exam, including
a stress test, before taking the impotence drug Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not letting any patients with serious heart disease take
Viagra,'' said Dr. Barry Silverman, an Atlanta cardiologist.
</P>
<P>
   The same circulatory problems that often lead to impotence also
stress the heart and possibly put these patients at higher risk for
sudden cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are watching for possible adverse drug interactions with
Viagra, although organic nitrate heart medications are the only
drugs known to pose a problem. Some men who have died after taking
Viagra were on nonnitrate medications or blood pressure-lowering
drugs. But most of the men were older than 60, and several had weak
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing Viagra and organic nitrates, which include the common
heart medication nitroglycerin, can result in heart failure or a
large, sudden drop in blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Of 16 men who reportedly died after taking Viagra, four are
known to have taken nitroglycerin. Several others were on
nonnitrate medications, including hypertension drugs such as
Hytrin, Tenormin, captopril and atenolol.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration, which approved Viagra in
March, maintains that it is safe ``for its intended population.''
The FDA also said it cannot absolutely determine whether Viagra was
a factor in the 16 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   But FDA spokeswoman Susan Cruzan did not say whether the agency
has completely ruled out other possible adverse drug interactions.
``As with any drug, we will continue to monitor reports,'' Cruzan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer, the drug's manufacturer, said it has no plans to revise
the drug label and its warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gordon Azar Jr., a Dunwoody cardiologist, said he isn't
worried about possible interactions between Viagra and blood
pressure-lowering drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman said he lets patients on hypertension drugs such as
ACE inhibitors and calcium channel blockers take Viagra as long as
they don't have serious heart disease. And those taking nitrates
are absolutely banned from taking Viagra, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Barry Mangel, a Marietta cardiologist, won't prescribe the
impotence drug for patients who aren't on nitrates but might need
nitrate therapy soon.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra has had at least one major beneficial side effect _ the
demand for it has gotten men into their doctors' offices for
check-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a boom for cardiologists, especially cardiologists
seeing African-American men,'' said Dr. Wayne Kong, chief executive
officer of the Association of Black Cardiologists. ``Many of the
men need stress tests to see if they can stand the additional
stress of sexual activity after a period of abstinence.''
</P>
<P>
   The flood of cardiology visits may provide early diagnoses of
high cholesterol or high blood pressure for some would-be Viagra
takers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might need nitrate medication more than they need the
Viagra,'' Azar said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
