<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-BILL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE JOINS `MARRIAGE PENALTY' TO ANTI-SMOKING LEGISLATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Wednesday wedded tax cuts to
anti-smoking legislation with the expectation that the unlikely
marriage will eventually break an impasse over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers agreed to include a tax break for married couples who
earn under $50,000 a year, after Republicans narrowly beat back a
Democratic effort to kill the proposal by a vote of 50-48. The
amendment was then formally approved on a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was sponsored by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who
argued that the tax cut was the only way conservatives could accept
the $1.10-a-pack cigarette price increases included in the overall
tobacco package.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut will be paid for by a portion of the revenue raised
from the tobacco tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said that because the cigarette levy would largely hit
lower and moderate income people, they should get some money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will give a substantial tax cut to very Americans who are
bearing the burden of this increase in the price of cigarettes,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress's Joint Committee on Taxation has estimated that 73
percent of people hit by the cigarette price increase earn less
than $50,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   The Gramm amendment would also allow self-employed individuals
to deduct the entire cost of health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats voiced concerns that the tax cut would drain money
from other public health needs they hope to fund from tobacco
revenues. But they conceded that the final legislation would have
to include some form of tax reduction to ensure Republican support.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which badly wants tobacco legislation, also
signaled it could support some tax reduction for married couples.
</P>
<P>
   The Gramm plan would help married couples with annual incomes
under $50,000 by increasing their standard deduction over a 10-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   By the year 2008, those couples would end up paying an average
of $1,400 less annually in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But to placate Democrats and moderate Republicans, the amendment
stipulated that only about one-third of the tobacco revenue could
be used to pay for the tax cuts. This would ensure that other
needs, such as state Medicaid, anti-drug and smoking cessation
programs could be accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   The Gramm amendment would cost $46 billion over 10 years. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Abolishing the so-called ``marriage penalty'' has long been a
goal of Republicans who say it is unfair that married couples often
pay more taxes than if they had filed as singles.
</P>
<P>
   However, lawmakers have had hard time finding the substantial
revenue needed to pay for such a tax cut. Furthermore, it is not
easy targeting who should get the tax break.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current tax code, about 42 percent of married couples
pay more taxes than if they had filed as single people, according
to a Congressional Budget Office analysis.
</P>
<P>
   However, about 51 percent of married couples, including many one
wage-earner households, received tax bonuses that more than offset
financial setbacks from being married, the study reported.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the marriage penalty hits couples who both
earn relatively comparable incomes particularly hard.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats opposed to the Gramm plan said that in later years it
would cost so much that the government would have to dip into
surpluses to pay for the cuts. They said the surpluses should be
reserved to help shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   They proposed giving tax relief only to couples that were
specifically penalized by their marriage status and not those who
incurred tax bonuses. That proposal was defeated, 55-43.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the criticism came from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, was clearly annoyed that her
home-state colleague had taken the marriage penalty elimination
concept that she had proposed months ago and attached it to an
unrelated measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my bill,'' Hutchison emphatically noted during a speech
on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that by linking the tax cuts it to the tobacco
measure the Senate would be raising taxes on one group of people
and redistributing the money to another group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I think you have a terrible principle,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison voted for the Gramm amendment, calling it the ``lesser
of two evils.'' She said that if the money was not returned in tax
cuts it would be used for more government spending.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., who has opposed the tobacco bill,
said the tax reduction makes the measure ``a little more
palatable.''
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that a number of Senate Republicans will use the tax
measure as an excuse to vote for the overall bill.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure's fate in the House is less certain. Republican
leaders have said they are not planning to consider any legislation
as sweeping as the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
