<SLUG> BC-CANADA-HEALTHCARE-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COCKTAIL FOR CANCER HAS CANADA IN A STIR
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Italy)   (dc) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The visit this week of an 85-year-old doctor from
Italy who claims to have successfully treated thousands of cancer
patients with a cocktail of vitamins and hormones has set off a
debate within Canada's universal health care system about patients'
rights and alternative treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the Italian, Dr. Luigi Di Bella, on Sunday for a
week of meetings and appearances was reported on the front pages of
Toronto's daily newspapers and on television news reports.
Enthusiastic supporters have cheered him as he met with Canada's
top doctors in hopes of convincing them that his treatment should
be approved in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   So far he has failed. But that has not dissuaded his supporters,
many of them cancer patients like Suzy Mariotti of Toronto, who
wear buttons that proclaim, ``We Believe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are paying for my chemotherapy at Toronto General
Hospital and it doesn't work, so why don't they just give me the
money and let me try something else?'' Mrs. Mariotti, 58, said
outside the Ontario legislative building where Di Bella held a news
conference on Monday. She is suffering from ovarian cancer, and
chemotherapy has so far been only minimally successful.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other Canadians who support Di Bella, Mrs. Mariotti
wants the government to act quickly to approve the treatment, which
is used in parts of Italy. ``Canada has a good health system,'' she
said, ``but sometimes it's not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Canada's universal health care system, patients receive
free treatment without having to rely on private insurance. But
alternative treatments are usually not covered, and they would be
costly to provide.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Canadians have gone to Italy for the Di Bella
treatment _ heavy doses of vitamins, the hormones melatonin and
somatostatin, and the drug bromocriptine, which have been used in
conventional cancer treatments. Some have reported spending as much
as $28,000 for the treatment. In March, four Canadian doctors went
to Italy to see if there was any basis for the claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``They failed to show us any objective evidence that this
treatment has efficacy,'' said Dr. Victor L. Fornasier, chief of
pathology at the Wellesly Central Site of St. Michael's Hospital in
Toronto, who led the delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Fornasier said Di Bella is a physiologist and biochemist who
conducted academic research and did not start a medical practice
until late in his career. When Di Bella opened his clinic,
Fornasier said, he apparently jumped from general theories to
clinical application without undergoing normal reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian team found Di Bella's files to be incomplete.
Instead of X-rays and detailed diagnoses, they contained signed
affidavits from patients attesting that they had been cured. And
because as many as 60 percent of Di Bella's patients also received
conventional care, Fornasier said, it was impossible to determine
which treatment worked.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation recommended that the ministry of health await the
results of an ambitious Italian field study before making any
decisions. Allan Rock, the minister of health, has said he will
follow the recommendation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fornasier conceded, though, that Di Bella's visit had focused
attention on the need for changes in the way doctors care for their
patients. ``People don't trust the health care system,'' he said.
``If there is no trust in the system, doctors are not going to have
the full trust of their patients, and that is when the patients
look for alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Di Bella has distanced himself from the coming Italian report.
He told reporters that he expected the results to be manipulated by
drug companies and others threatened by his success. ``I do not
need any more proof,'' he said through a translator. ``I have tens
of thousands of patients who feel well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
