<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3740 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-GREENSPAN-BOS &LR;      06-10 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-GREENSPAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED CHIEF EXPECTS ASIAN ECONOMIC WOES WILL COOL US ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan suggested
Wednesday that the Asian financial crisis would likely cool the
nation's ``torrid'' economic growth soon, freeing the Fed from
having to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's testimony before a congressional panel was full of
hedges and contingencies, but investors took his words to mean that
the Fed does not see inflation as an immediate threat and does not
plan to raise interest rates in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which declined about 20 points
before Greenspan spoke late Wednesday morning, moved quickly into
positive territory soon after he was finished. But the market
closed down 78.22 points on concerns that Asia's economic slump is
causing US companies that do business there to report disappointing
earnings. Greenspan's comments, however, boosted the bond market to
its best showing in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation's central banker, Greenspan is always on the watch
for signs of inflation, which can hurt economic propserity. Under
traditional theory, the economy would be expected to produce
inflation by now: Unemployment is at a 28-year low of 4.3 percent,
and the economy grew a rapid 4.8 percent in the first three months
of the year. Those conditions would normally force businesses to
raise wages and prices as they seek more workers to turn out more
goods.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan said the historic link between employment and
inflation may no longer apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible that we have, in a sense, moved beyond
history,'' he told Congress's Joint Economic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said inflation has actually declined this year, and he
suggested the Asian crisis would keep US growth in check by
limiting Asia's appetite for American goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effects of the crisis in Asia will almost certainly damp
net exports further, potentially moderating the growth of domestic
production and hence employment,'' Greenspan said. But he also
warned that the Fed would raise rates if it saw signs of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, get ready, because the economy is going to
slow one way or another in the second half of the year,'' said
Wayne Ayers, chief economist at BankBoston. ``Greenspan thinks it
will come via Asia. But if it doesn't, the Fed stands ready to
raise rates and make sure inflation is contained.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,.2l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has left the overnight bank lending rate unchanged at
5.5 percent for more than a year. Changes in the overnight rate
often prompt lenders to raise or lower other interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Greenspan said the US economy had entered a
``virtuous circle'' in which low inflation convinces lenders to
keep interest rates low, which pushes up spending, factory
production and employment. ``The current economic performance, with
its combination of strong growth and low inflation, is as
impressive as any I have witnessed in my near half-century of daily
observation of the American economy,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   He also laid out the evidence that inflation and economic growth
would remain in check. Data on the number of hours that employees
work suggest that growth has likely slowed in the current quarter
from the first quarter, Greenspan said. Productivity is also
rising, meaning companies are able to do more work with the same
amount of labor and materials. When productivity rises, firms can
raise wages more easily without sparking inflation, economists say.
And firms have built up an ``unsustainable'' level of inventories,
Greenspan said. That build-up must slow at some point, ``perhaps
abruptly,'' which could help cool the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Greenspan said the most recent data
suggest that consumer prices have been rising at a faster pace in
the current quarter than earlier in the year. Most important, the
unemployment rate has fallen so low that businesses may have to
raise wages to retain workers, which could spark inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing he knows for sure: You can't sustain growth
where employment is growing twice as fast as the population,'' said
Alan Levenson, director of research at Aubrey G. Lanston, a New
York investment firm. ``He says that if you want to sustain the
expansion, you have to get job growth to slow before inflation
picks up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Material from Bloomberg News was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
