<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-HERNANDEZ-N     06-10 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-HERNANDEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL DUQUE BAFFLES BOTH FRIENDS AND FOE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Yankees pay Mike Borzello to sit behind home
plate at every game with a radar gun and write down the speed and
type of every pitch thrown. In his own way, he's an expert on
pitching, but Borzello met his match Tuesday night. There were
times he had no idea what Orlando Hernandez was throwing.
</P>
<P>
   With his multiple arm angles and speeds and his variety of
pitches, Hernandez sometimes confused the scouts and catcher Joe
Girardi, and he confounded the Montreal Expos, allowing four hits
and striking out nine in an 11-1 victory. Dominating with his
guile, Hernandez all but clinched a permanent spot in the Yankees'
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, indicated Wednesday that a
final decision on his five starters was imminent, assuming
everybody remains healthy. Ramiro Mendoza will start Friday, in the
first game of the three-game series against Cleveland; David Cone
will start Saturday. David Wells, coming back from tendinitis in
his pitching shoulder, threw in the bullpen Wednesday and reported
some stiffness in his shoulder, but no pain, and he is scheduled to
pitch Sunday, in the series finale against the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez will make his next start Monday in Baltimore, followed
by Hideki Irabu on Tuesday and Andy Pettitte on Wednesday. By then,
Torre will most likely announce his decision, and the most obvious
solution is moving Mendoza to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez will stay and continue to confuse opposing hitters,
who are batting .164 against him, as well as Borzello. Hernandez's
sleight of hand Tuesday night could be traced to the fact that he
threw his basic overhand curveball 70 to 72 mph, a slider about 80
mph _ and then dropped down and threw a breaking ball from the side
at 76 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would turn to a scout sitting next to me,'' Borzello said,
``and would ask, `Do you know what that pitch was?' And he would
say, `Your guess is as good as mine.'''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Widger, Montreal's catcher Tuesday, was hitless in three
at-bats  &QL; 
and, like the rest of his teammates, he didn't have a good swing or
even a clue as to what Hernandez might throw next.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was completely unpredictable,'' Widger said. ``One time,
the count was 2-0, and he dropped down to the side and threw me a
slider.''
</P>
<P>
   In the context of how pitchers usually pitch, throwing a sidearm
slider with a 2-0 count is like Michael Jordan shooting a
left-handed 3-pointer in the fourth quarter. ``Then,'' Widger said,
``he'll bust you inside with a fastball. With all of the angles he
throws from, you can't really focus on one release point.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``We talk about a pitcher trying to find one release
point. This guy's got three or four of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the scout sitting near Borzello filed a report that
said Hernandez has six release points. Imagine Hernandez in front
of a clock: he throws with his arm angled at 11 o'clock, 10:30, 10,
9:30 and 9, and he also throws crossfire, with his body aimed in
one direction and his arm moving in another in a sidearm motion.
With two strikes, opposing batters have just 2 hits in 35 at-bats
against him, evidence that they cannot conceive what he will throw
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``He starts out with that violent leg kick,'' said the scout,
from an American League team, who did not want to be identified,
``and then you have no idea where the ball is coming from, what
direction, what pitch. And he throws everything for a strike. I
don't think he threw a bad pitch the whole night. Every pitch had a
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to find a pattern in what he does, eliminate
possible pitches he'll throw in different situations. I couldn't
eliminate anything. I don't think you can guess the pitches. The
best thing to do might be to just look for something in one part of
the strike zone. He's like a Rembrandt, or a Barbra Streisand. The
guy is an artist. It was the best-pitched game I've seen this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Widger, Torre and the scout all dismissed the idea that
Hernandez thrived because he was facing the Expos, a struggling
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, he made all of his pitches,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Widger said, ``He would've been good against anybody.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A Yankees team doctor who examined Hernandez in spring training
believes the pitcher is the best-conditioned athlete he has ever
seen. His extraordinary flexibility is evident every time he goes
into his windup, and he draws his left leg up by his cheekbone. But
Hernandez said Wednesday that in the past, his leg kick _ which he
developed after watching Dwight Gooden pitch for the Mets on
television in 1988 _ was even more pronounced, even higher, so that
his knee would brush the side of his head.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how high he could kick his leg, Hernandez shrugged, stood
and, without any preparation or unusual effort, raised his right
foot above the locker, adjacent to Paul O'Neill's name plate on
top. Then, in one continuous motion, Hernandez did it again. No
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The lockers are six and a half feet tall. As tall as Darryl
Strawberry. ``That's incredible,'' said Strawberry, inspecting the
spot where Hernandez raised his leg. ``I wouldn't even try that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Sveum, an inch taller than the 6-foot-2-inch Hernandez,
drew his leg about halfway up the locker. ``No way,'' he said,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cardenal, the Yankees' first base coach, grew up in Cuba
and said that pitchers there are routinely taught to change speeds,
as Hernandez does, to vary their deliveries. The Texas-born Nolan
Ryan is the standard for youngsters in the United States, a power
pitcher who was clocked over 100 m.p.h. on radar guns. In Cuba,
players could emulate Luis Tiant, with his odd contortions and
change of speeds. ``In Cuba,'' Cardenal said, ``they worry about
getting the hitter out. They don't care how.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Cardenal ran into Tony Oliva, another Cuban-born
former star. He said Oliva told him that there was a pitcher in
Cuba who was better than all the rest, who could be a star in the
United States. El Duque, Oliva called him, referring to Hernandez
by his nickname.
</P>
<P>
   With Cardenal serving as interpreter, Hernandez said Wednesday
that he doesn't consider himself unusual, that he doesn't consider
himself a master of anything. ``I'm still trying to learn,''
Hernandez said. ``That's why I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears he will teach opposing hitters a thing or two along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
