<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SHOWTIME FOR SISTERS OF THE NBA 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Women's National Basketball Association, a sister of the NBA
and a beneficiary of the NBA's marketing clout, begins its second
season with four games Thursday night. One of those games _ the New
York Liberty at the Cleveland Rockers _ will be televised
nationally by the Lifetime channel.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 30 games in the 10-week regular season will be
televised nationally _ 10 each by NBC, ESPN and Lifetime. And those
networks, one or two at a time, will televise every playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   That extensive television coverage of the 10 teams (up from
eight) is part of the war between the WNBA and the equally young
American Basketball League for the public's heart and ultimately
its dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL plays in the traditional winter-spring basketball
season. The WNBA plays in the summer, when NBA arenas have more
open dates. In their first seasons, the ABL had better players and
a higher level of competition, but fewer marketing dollars and
smaller crowds. The WNBA averaged 9,669 fans a game, to the ABL's
3,536.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA scored a major signing coup this year. First, it picked
up Nikki McCray, the ABL's most valuable player last season. Then
it signed most of the best college seniors, including such
all-Americans as Ticha Penicheiro, the flashy point guard from Old
Dominion, Nykesha Sales of Connecticut and Kristin Folkl of
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Penicheiro will play for the Sacramento Monarchs. Sales and
Folkl are injured and will not play this season, but at least the
WNBA has them in the fold. Their presence has cheered such WNBA
players as Rebecca Lobo of the Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' she said, ``because it's important to us to get
the best players, and we sure did this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA's biggest score may have been the signing of Malgorzata
(``call me Margo'') Dydek of Poland, who has played in Europe for
six years. When she reported to the WNBA's combine camp, she was
listed at 6 feet 6 inches. She turned out to be 7-2 and graceful,
with a 7-foot wing span that forces opponents to alter shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Utah Starzz made her the first choice in the draft, which
should get the team out of the cellar. But the Detroit Shock and
the Washington Mystics, the expansion teams, may not be buried
there, either. Washington, coached by Jim Lewis, formerly of George
Mason, has McCray. Detroit, coached by Nancy Lieberman-Cline, has
six foreign players.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL will start its season in November with 10 teams,
including new ones in Chicago and Nashville. Like the WNBA, it is a
single-entity league, which means the league owns all the teams and
signs all the players. Its season is longer than the WNBA's, its
salaries are higher and the players get part ownership of the
league.
</P>
<P>
   But the ABL does not allow its players to play in another
league. The WNBA does, and most of its players play overseas during
the traditional basketball months.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL is privately owned, and it lacks the financial clout of
the WNBA, whose 12 sponsors include Nike, Coca-Cola, McDonald's,
General Motors and American Express, and its national television
package pales next to the WNBA's.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL teams are mostly in middle-size cities. The WNBA teams
are in NBA cities, including New York, where the Liberty reached
last year's playoff championship game before losing to the Houston
Comets.
</P>
<P>
   While Val Ackerman, the WNBA president, did not call this a
make-or-break season, she said much was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is the test,'' she said, ``because the curiosity is
lessened and the novelty is gone.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
