<HEADER>
A3746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KAN-GRAIN-ELEVATOR-     06-10 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KAN-GRAIN-ELEVATOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 MORE VICTIMS OF GRAIN ELEVATOR BLAST ARE FOUND
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)   (ART ADV: Graphic diagram of grain elevator is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA, Kan. _ For all the poetry of Kansas wheatfields swaying
in the breeze, the laborers who worked inside the big DeBruce Grain
elevator knew a job that could be brutish: dirty and low paying
work often done by Mexican immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an easy way to live. And for some, it was a violent
way to die.
</P>
<P>
   Fire and rescue crews Wednesday uncovered the remains of three
more victims inside the grain storage facility that exploded
Monday, bringing the death toll to five. Meanwhile, searchers
continued looking for one man still trapped in tunnels in the
wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dimming chances of survival, officials Wednesday
expressed hope that the remaining worker might somehow still be
found alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is air in those tunnels,'' said Ken Cox, division chief
of the Sedgwick County Fire Department. ``So breathing would not be
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The search was temporarily halted Wednesday afternoon when a
rescue worker slipped and was buried to his armpits in grain,
before being pulled to safety by other crew members.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies found Wednesday had not been identified. And
officials did not disclose the precise cause of death. Two victims
killed instantly on Monday were Jose Prajedes Ortiz, 24, and Jose
luis Duarte, 41. The others missing the explosion were Howard Goin,
Noel Najera, Victor Castaneda and Raymundo Diz-Vela. Six others
were seriously injured, including some who were badly burned.
</P>
<P>
   The DeBruce Grain elevator, one of the biggest, free-standing
storage facilities in the nation, has been cited at least twice in
the last 19 months by federal warehouse inspectors for excessive
grain-dust conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said that the company in both cases vowed to
clean up the dust, which can be flammable.
</P>
<P>
   The DeBruce facility, which towers over the flat prairie about
five miles south of Witchita, bears little resemblance to the
small, quaint wooden grain elevators found in so many farm towns of
the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is a series of cement silos that stand 120-feet
tall, with tunnels that extend 800 feet, and has a storage capacity
of about 21 million bushels of grain. The DeBruce company buys
grain from farmers and smaller elevators, then ships it to mills.
</P>
<P>
   Grain is stored and extracted from the elevator by conveyor
belts that run the length of the facility. The huge giant silos,
which stand aside a freight rail line, had vast sections knocked
away, with some holes bigger than cars.
</P>
<P>
   The men inside the tunnels, which are 7 feet by 8 feet, were
working on the maintenance crew at the time of the explosion, a
series of jolts that shook homes 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Explosions in grain elevators are caused by the mixing of grain
dust and oxygen in closed quarters. The spark for the fire can come
from an electrical short, or the cutting of some metal. Rather than
a single blast, the explosion sets off a ripple of explosions.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 10 grain-dust explosions in Kansas in the last
10 years, but no deaths. Low-level jobs at grain elevators
typically pay $5 or $6 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Working inside the tunnels can be dirty, even disgusting,
according to people familiar with grain elevators, places filled
with strong odors and scrambling mice.
</P>
<P>
   Paul DeBruce, the chief executive of the Kansas City-based
company, said during a news conference on Tuesday that he had
invested hundreds of thousands of dollars in the facility, much of
it for equipment to contain grain dust. DeBruce purchased the grain
elevator in 1996 for $1.15 million.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 searchers were combing through the wreckage of the
elevator, including local fire crews and representatives from the
Federal Emergence Management Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the friends and families of the victims gathered at the
Oatville Elementary School, about a mile from the grain elevator,
where the Red Cross and other volunteers were helping them cope.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, one of those who died, was recalled by family and friends
as a hard worker who loved life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always happy, always wanting to go dancing, to hold his
baby and be with his friends,'' said his widow, Claudia Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz had moved to Kansas from Mexico about five years ago.
Known for his trademark black cowboy hat, Ortiz loved to sit
outside and talk with friends, as he held his 6-month-old baby,
Saul, on his lap.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce said the workday Monday was proceeding as usual before
the blast. He said Goin was greasing bearings in the tunnel, while
the other three men were cleaning up spilled grain. The executive
said he had known Goin, who is in his 60s, since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Goin had recently retired, but came back to help at the grain
elevator during the busy wheat harvest season.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they had detected no signs of life since some
thudding noises about 2 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The division fire chief, Cox, said the spilled grain posed
hazards to the searchers, since it could swallow a person like
quicksand. But he said none of the workers, which included
firefighters from Oklahoma City, expressed any desire to be taken
off the dangerous assignment.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the families of the dead and missing have been told
about the work of the rescue crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saying prayers for the rescuers, too,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
