<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COCAINE-SEIZURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENTS SEIZE 1,300 POUNDS OF COCAINE HIDDEN IN PAPER ROLLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Brazil)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Customs agents seized more than 1,300 pounds of
cocaine after smugglers tried to bring it into the United States
secreted in specially made fiberglass barrels at the center of
tightly wound, one-ton rolls of brown wrapping paper.
</P>
<P>
   Four people have been arrested here so far for claiming and
dispersing the shipment, with an estimated street value of $40
million, said John Varrone, special agent in charge of the U.S.
Customs Service's Newark office. He said the cocaine arrived at
Port Newark by container ship from a paper mill in Santos, Brazil,
on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is continuing, he said, adding that the
capital investment in machinery and the sophistication of the
elaborate ruse suggested that Colombian cartels like the Cali,
Medellin or North Valle factions were involved.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the seizure resulted from a program of
intensified inspections of cargo arriving at the port area, and
followed law enforcement monitoring of two previous deliveries of
rolled paper to the same individuals in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   While not the largest seizure ever at the port, it is larger
than many of the more recent shipments traced to the big cartels,
said Anthony Senneca, head of the Newark office of the Drug
Enforcement Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, he said, it was common to have single shipments
of more than 5,000 pounds coming in from Mexico and elsewhere. But
that stopped with stronger border enforcement efforts. In recent
years, loads of 500 to 700 pounds have become more common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different techniques are used by different groups,'' Senneca
said, ``but this is a fairly large seizure in this day and age.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, who were arrested and charged with intent to
distribute narcotics, were Paulo Portella, 33, of Manhattan; Jose
Mosquette, 49, of Bellville, N.J.,; Byron Alvarado, 33, of Corona,
Queens, and Robert Pacheco, 34, of the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Buono, an assistant U.S. attorney, said that the
suspects appeared before federal Magistrate Ronald Hedges Tuesday
and Wednesday and were being held pending a detention hearing on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint filed in Federal District Court here,
two suspects got $200,000 and another received $50,000 for
retrieving more than 500 green-plastic-wrapped, one-kilogram bricks
of cocaine from barrels hidden inside four rolls of paper among a
shipment of 40 rolls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
