<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3751 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLY-SHEEDY-MOVIES-$A     06-10 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLY-SHEEDY-MOVIES-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLY SHEEDY MAKES A BID TO BE TAKEN SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 14)  
 (JT ) 
 By MARGY ROCHLIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, under a tent at the film festival in Cannes,
France, a moderator kicked off a news conference by briefly
introducing the American writer and director Lisa Cholodenko and
the cast of her movie ``High Art.'' Then, looking out into the
crowd, he said, ``Any questions?''
</P>
<P>
   Panel-weary, the standing-room-only tentful of French
journalists had shown up with very little to ask. It was almost a
relief when dark clouds drifted in off the blue waters of the Cote
d'Azur. The thumping of raindrops on the white plastic roof at
least broke the uncomfortable silence.
</P>
<P>
   To Americans there, this nonreaction was perplexing, considering
the fact that seated at the center of the royal-blue dais with her
hands neatly clasped in front of her was the 36-year-old Ally
Sheedy.
</P>
<P>
   To Americans, Ms. Sheedy is still the shining conscience of the
Brat Pack of the 1980s, the sprightly valentine at the center of
classic films about the transition to adulthood like ``The
Breakfast Club'' and ``St. Elmo's Fire,'' the touchstone for a
million awkward adolescences. She is the farthest thing imaginable
from a middle-aged lesbian drug-addict photographer, which is what
she plays in ``High Art.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted-looking and boyishly attired, Ms. Sheedy's character,
the faded legend Lucy Berliner, slumps her way through much of the
film knocking back tumblers of scotch, snorting heroin and making
love first to her equally strung-out girlfriend, a faded German
actress (Patricia Clarkson), then to a young, ambitious magazine
editor (Radha Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the slumping is what is being widely regarded as
an accomplished portrayal of loss and artistic identity. At the
Sundance Film Festival, where ``High Art'' had its premiere in
January, even critics who were set to poke fun at Ms. Sheedy's walk
on the wild side left the movie making predictions of a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``The birth of Ally Sheedy as a real actress,'' read one notice,
perhaps best conveying how disconcerted film-world observers were
to find her so masterly at projecting torment and gravity. After
all, they had never seen her do anything in a movie much more
eyebrow-raising than eating a Captain Crunch cereal sandwich, as
she did in ``The Breakfast Club.'' And yet in Cannes, at the news
conference, it was just drip, drip, drip.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, on a hotel-front beach packed with so many topless
sunbathers that an ``Entertainment Tonight'' crew that wanted to
interview her had trouble lining up a PG-rated shot, a barefoot Ms.
Sheedy sprawled on an orange chaise lounge in a beige tank top and
laced black trousers. ``I was, like, squirming up there,'' she said
in a microreview of the strange event 24 hours earlier. Still, the
bewildered stares of the French reporters were preferable to the
flat, bored gazes that casting directors had fixed on her for the
last eight years or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating to the point of being just
devastating,'' said Ms. Sheedy, who since the early '90s has worked
steadily in straight-to-video movies and cable thrillers with words
like ``haunting'' in the title. ``I couldn't get arrested. I'd go
to an audition and it'd be like: `Surprise us. Shock us. Show us
something new. We already know what you can do. Now show us
something else. Prove yourself to us.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the path to proving herself, Ms. Sheedy bled from every
slight and rejection. But she never stopped trying, and old friends
regard that as vintage Sheedy behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at her best moments, she was always extremely fragile,''
said Molly Ringwald, one of her ``Breakfast Club'' co-stars, who is
emerging from a professional dip that resembles Ms. Sheedy's
except, as Ms. Ringwald puts it, ``because of her personality,
Ally's probably more likely to remember the hard times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a strength in her,'' Ms. Ringwald continued. ``You can
see it in her face. That mixture of strength and vulnerability is
one of the things that makes her an interesting actress.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In private, Ms. Sheedy spent a decade in solo classes with the
legendary acting coach Harold Guskin. In public, she recited
confessional poetry at open-mike nights, talking about the Ally No
One Knew: her abortion at 16, repeated bouts with bulimia and a
dependency on the sleeping pill Halcion so severe that a group of
friends led by Demi Moore confronted her and persuaded her to go to
Hazelden, the substance-abuse treatment center outside Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, she passed a sheaf of her verse to James Silberman, an
old friend who was then president of Summit Books. This resulted in
the release of her book ``Yesterday I Saw the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I was expecting,'' Ms. Sheedy recalled with
a wince. ``But I didn't think that people would be that dismissive
and condescending.'' She was mocked for the book far more
aggressively than for anything she ever did on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, she has spent more time in the warmth of the spotlight
than out in the cold. She grew up in New York, the eldest of three
children; her parents, who divorced in 1971, are Charlotte Sheedy,
a literary agent, and John Sheedy, an advertising executive.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was 11, Alexandra Elizabeth Sheedy was a dancer
in pink tights and tutus at American Ballet Theater. By the time
she was 12, she had started a writing career that included a
well-received children's book, ``She Was Nice to Mice,'' and
freelance jobs for Ms. magazine and The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, after making good in the world of television
commercials, she jetted out to Los Angeles as a self-sustaining
teen-ager. Talent-spotters there found she had a luminous quality
that meshed perfectly with junior ruffians like Sean Penn (``Bad
Boys'') and with sweater boys like Matthew Broderick (``War
Games'').
</P>
<P>
   ``The best advice I've gotten is from books that people have
written who've taken the same path as me,'' Ms. Sheedy said back in
1986, when she was a touchingly earnest ingenue on a roll with no
idea that in a few years she would be banished from favor. ``Like,
Katharine Hepburn said that acting is nothing but waiting for a
custard pie in the face and that you should just learn your lines
and get on with it.''
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of the way through ``High Art,'' Ms. Sheedy's
character, who is being wooed back into the limelight by the
magazine editor, haltingly explains about the conflicting emotions
caused by public adulation. ``I loved the attention, but I couldn't
handle the impact,'' she says, her lips pulled into a pained smile.
``I sort of felt pigeonholed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheedy might as well have been reading from her own diary.
It's no wonder that after reading the ``High Art'' script, which
was slipped to her by an agent-friend early last year, she
impulsively picked up the telephone, called Ms. Cholodenko at home
in Manhattan and left a message on the answering machine. ``This is
me,'' she said, then pleaded to be given a tryout. That Ms.
Cholodenko's tastes in '80s-era cinema ran more toward
revival-house Fellini than mainstream American was something Ms.
Sheedy considered fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I didn't know who she was,'' said Ms.
Cholodenko, who was making her first feature film after working as
an editor on movies like Gus Van Sant's ``To Die For.''
</P>
<P>
   She also didn't know that Ms. Sheedy had recently been dropped
by the William Morris agency and was representing herself. But in
signing the actress, Ms. Cholodenko soon realized that she had
gained the help of someone who would do anything for the team.
``What do you need?'' the director remembers Ms. Sheedy asking as
Ms. Cholodenko tentatively blocked out the first sex scene she had
ever directed. ``Do you want me to make out with her? Fine. Want me
to take off my shirt? Whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On that day,'' the director recalled, ``she was like our
anchor.''
</P>
<P>
   Team play aside, the role of Lucy Berliner _ by turns an
irritating presence and a deeply sympathetic one _ would appear to
have been an enormous individual challenge, but Ms. Sheedy says no.
``People keep asking me, `What did you do to prepare?' And the
answer is: nothing. I felt so close to the material that I figured
that the less that I did, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Which also means that her emaciated look in ``High Art'' wasn't
the result of strict dieting. ``I am really skinny right now, and I
don't know why,'' said Ms. Sheedy, who knows that her weight is a
cause of concern among her friends. ``A lot of people have been on
my case about this for a long time _ my mother, my father,
everybody. I'm eating. I'm not doing anything anorexic. I'm highly
conscious of what that behavior is.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cannes, Ms. Sheedy was inundated with so many interview
requests from Americans that her schedule-conscious publicity
representative kept trudging across the sand, anxiously trying to
extricate his client and move her along to her next inquisitor.
Finally, Ms. Sheedy was told that an infotainment television crew
was waiting. ``I don't want to do `Access Hollywood' _ I've already
had access to Hollywood,'' she said with a laugh, suggesting in a
single quip much about lost naivete. ``I already know where they
live.''
</P>
<P>
   And she knows the rules Hollywood plays by. In exchange for a
second chance, those in the film industry will undoubtedly expect
Ms. Sheedy to draw a blank about her past and appear grateful to be
invited back to the party. Maybe Ms. Sheedy is, by nature,
forthright. Maybe it has been too long since reporters solicited
her thoughts. In any case, she comes off like someone who has
nothing left to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually people don't talk because they're worried they're
going to cause themselves problems, right?'' reasoned Ms. Sheedy,
who has been quoted delivering sharply etched opinions about
everything from how Ms. Moore turned herself into an international
commodity to what it was like to be directed in a bed scene by Joel
Schumacher (``St. Elmo's Fire''). ``Well, I already have all the
problems. So I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, how bitter and twisted up she sounds!'' added Ms. Sheedy,
as she spread a thin white film of sun block onto her reddening
cheeks. Then she laughed self-consciously, inhaled a final puff
from the smoldering stub of a cigarette and reluctantly navigated
her way back into the surreal hoopla of Cannes. In the words of
Lucy Berliner, Ms. Sheedy seemed to be loving the attention but
having trouble with the impact.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
