<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-TI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM ELBOWS ITS WAY INTO A GROWING SPECIALTY CHIPS MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK P. COUCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Instruments is getting some more
competition in the specialty computer chip business.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said Wednesday that it will spend more than $100 million on
efforts to get into faster-growing segments of the computer-chip
business, specifically targeting TI's favorite product, digital
signal processors.
</P>
<P>
   TI has bet the farm on digital signal processors, which are
special chips that translate light, sound and motion into the
digital language of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Such chips are used in cellular telephones, hearing aids, car
parts, computer modems and hard-disk drives.
</P>
<P>
   TI was never home alone in the DSP market, but the house is
starting to get a little crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lucent Technologies and Motorola said they will work
together to develop the next generation of digital signal
processors offered by their companies. The two companies said they
will share licenses on the DSPs and create a jointly owned designed
center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, IBM, another player that can't be ignored, elbowed
its way into the room. Big Blue said it will spend $100 million on
custom chips that will work in cellular phones, digital cameras,
television set-top boxes and other consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will make it more competitive, but it validates the market
opportunity of DSP recognized by Texas Instruments,'' said Dave
Powers, an analyst for Edward Jones, a stock brokerage in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   William O'Leary, an IBM spokesman, said IBM is designing two
dozen chip ``cores'' with pieces that will be interchangeable. Chip
cores are the building blocks of custom-chip making.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to making custom chips, IBM plans to offer some
basic chips, such as one modeled after a DSP chip line offered by
Texas Instruments. That chip is used in millions of cellular phones
and other communications devices.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said its chip will become the first alternative to the Texas
Instruments product.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's DSP chip will have the same powers, but it won't be a copy
of the TI chip, O'Leary said. ``IBM tends to be very
conservative,'' O'Leary said. ``From our perspective, it is a
totally clean IBM design from the ground up without any patent
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not an accident that chip makers are looking at DSPs for
salvation. The Semiconductor Industry Association recently rained
on the chip makers' sunny 1998 forecast.
</P>
<P>
   The industry had predicted a sales increase of 17 percent for
1998, but last week, the association said total chip sales will
fall 2 percent to $134.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, DSPs have been one of the strengths of the
semiconductor market. The association reported that DSP revenues
grew 39.2 percent in 1996 and 33.6 percent in 1997, and are
expected to increase 23 percent in 1998 to $3.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And TI is the strongest player in that growing market. Forward
Concepts Co. of Tempe, Ariz., estimated that TI had 45 percent of
the worldwide DSP market in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's aggressive move onto TI's turf isn't stirring major
worries at TI's home offices in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we have 15 years' experience in this market and we're
not resting on our laurels,'' said Donna Coletti, TI spokeswoman.
``We're not standing still. We have more than 1,000 third-party
producers who make tools that support our product.''
</P>
<P>
   Those tool makers are creating software that makes it easier to
use the TI chip in other products. They make software products that
handle basic functions such as detecting programming errors.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said the IBM chip will be compatible with the software
tools that work with TI's chip. And Powers noted that TI has been
pouring money into its support of DSPs.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's push into DSPs is expected to force prices lower on some
chips. Coletti said TI's chips range from $3 to more than $100.
</P>
<P>
   Will Strauss, president of Forward Concepts, said the big users
of TI's chips in the cellular telephone business might use the
competition to get a better price, but there's no promise that TI
will lose those customers.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss noted that TI has held steady at its 45 percent market
share for the past four years as the demand for DSPs has grown.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is aiming at just part of TI's market for DSPs: the
communications sector. Strauss estimated that 25 percent to 30
percent of TI's semiconductor revenues come from the chip targeted
by IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Powers said he doesn't believe that the competition will change
TI's status in the market: ``We think they'll continue to be the
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors weren't as confident that TI won't be affected. The
company's stock price fell 6 percent in active trading Wednesday,
closing at $51.50, down $3.38 a share.
</P>
<P>
   IBM shares fell $2 to close at $117.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
