<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3757 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-BAPTISTS-HNS     06-10 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-BAPTISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN BAPTISTS URGE AMERICANS TO ELECT MORALLY PURE POLITICIANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By RICHARD VARA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Southern Baptists, in a not-so-subtle swipe at
President Clinton, urged Americans to send a message to elected
officials that ``character does count in public office.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the annual meeting of the Southern Baptist
Convention voted for a resolution asking Americans ``to elect those
officials and candidates who, although imperfect, demonstrate
consistent honesty, moral purity and the highest character.''
</P>
<P>
   The 8,540 registered delegates also approved a resolution
affirming the ``finality, sufficiency and exclusivity of the
Christian gospel and of biblical revelation as the sole source of
saving truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution implies the beliefs of the Church of Jesus Christ
of Latter-day Saints were not Christian. Salt Lake City is the
world headquarters of the Latter-day Saints, also known as Mormons.
The Rev. James G. Merritt, chairman of the convention's Executive
Committee, said in a sermon that the city was ``headquarters of a
counterfeit Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a Southern Baptist, has been the subject of an intense
investigation by Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr for a
cover-up of an alleged affair between the president and Monica
Lewinsky, a former White House intern. In the course of the
investigation, numerous allegations of Clinton sexual affairs have
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   But the Southern Baptist delegates voted down an amendment that
would have named Clinton as public official involved in ``moral and
legal misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Whitehead, chairman of the convention's resolutions
committee, said the moral principle of the resolution, that
character counts in public life, would be blunted if it included
names.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of names on both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue
to whom this resolution may be applicable,'' Whitehead said.
``There are plenty of people in city councils, county governments,
state governments in both Republican and Democratic and independent
parties to whom this resolution applies,'' Whitehead said.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not stop the Rev. Wiley Drake of California from
trying to name Clinton in the resolution. Drake said he was
disappointed with Clinton's moral record. He told delegates that
the resolution did not hold Clinton accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead, an attorney and a professor at Midwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Kansas, told a press conference that the
convention was countering the idea that character in public office
did not matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the news media are saying that holding men and women
to a standard of basic honesty and fidelity to spouse is going to
screen too many politicians out of public life,'' Whitehead said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need good men and women in public office who know what good
means,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead acknowledged the resolution included Clinton and his
alleged indiscretions. ``He fits the category of this resolution,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also considered Clinton unrepentant since the president has
not publicly confessed or sought forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time the national convention has tangled
with the president. Clinton's support of gay rights and abortion
rights have upset the convention's conservative leadership. In
Houston in 1992, delegates attempted to oust the president's
Arkansas home church because of the stands. The effort was
defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead also defended the resolution implying that Mormons
were not authentic Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern Baptists are about the one true Gospel, the one true
Christ,'' Whitehead said. He denied that the resolution was
directed at Mormons but intended for those who do not believe in
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are eternal consequences to not knowing who Jesus Christ
is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Merritt meanwhile attacked the Latter-days Saints in a sermon
Wednesday morning. ``Salt Lake City is both the mainstay of a
cultural conservatism for which I am grateful but is also the
headquarters of a counterfeit Christianity of which I am fearful,''
Merritt said.
</P>
<P>
   Merritt said there was a ``gulf of doctrinal and theological
differences which separate them completely from orthodox
Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Otterson, spokesman for the Latter-day Saints Church,
said the attacks were nothing new for the denomination. ``We have
heard it all before,'' Otterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to get into a battle of theology or a
pingpong match on who is a Christian and who is not,'' Otterson
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other actions, the convention voiced continued support for
the yearlong boycott of the Walt Disney Co. In 1997, delegates
approved a boycott to protest what they considered immoral films
and literature produced by the entertainment conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still oppose moral filth and an agenda to promote
anti-family, anti-Christian values in all entertainment
industries,'' said the Rev. Tom Elliff, outgoing convention
president. The Rev. Paige Patterson is the new president.
</P>
<P>
   A convention publishing house, Broadman &AMP; Holman, issued a book
titled ``Send a Message to Mickey'' by Richard Land, president of
the Ethics &AMP; Religious Liberty Commission. Land is directing the
boycott for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boycott is very positive and growing,'' Land said. Several
other groups, including the Assemblies of God, have joined the
effort, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Land said the boycott was succeeding in cutting Disney's
profits. But John Dreyer, spokesman for Disney, said the company
was recording record profits.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer also said the company has rejected the convention's
proposal to establish an advisory committee of evangelical
Christians and conservative Roman Catholics to screen entertainment
material.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also rejecting a proposal to stop gay and lesbian
days at the Disney theme parks. ``The thing they are asking us to
do is to discriminate against the guests at our parks,'' Dreyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day annual meeting ends Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
