<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY AWARDS $450,000 TO FAMILY OF DEAD SMOKER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ky., Fla., Minn., Mass.)  (See also TOBACCO-MARRIAGE, TOBACCO-LOTT) 
(af) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a major defeat for cigarette makers that could affect the
course of federal tobacco legislation, a Florida jury Wednesday
found Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. liable for a smoker's death
and ordered the company to pay about $1 million in compensatory and
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the six-person jury in Jacksonville, Fla.,
marked one of the rare times in recent decades that jurors have
sided with individual smokers in cigarette-related lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   But the panel's decision Wednesday to award $450,000 in punitive
damages against Brown &AMP; Williamson could affect all cigarette
makers because several legal experts said that it appeared to mark
the first time that such damages had been awarded in a tobacco
case.
</P>
<P>
   An award of punitive damages, which are intended to punish a
defendant, had been made in 1995 against Lorillard Tobacco Co.,
which used asbestos in the filter of Kent cigarettes. But that
case, in which a smoker blamed his cancer on asbestos exposure, did
not pose a problem for other tobacco companies because Lorillard
was the principal user of asbestos in cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the industry's nightmare that in individual and, even
worse, class-action cases that juries will come down with punitive
damage awards,'' said Robert Rabin, a professor of law at Stanford
Univeristy who has followed tobacco litigation. ``It ups the ante
and creates great uncertainty with so many potential individual
cases out there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Florida case, the jury also awarded $500,000 in
compensatory damages to the family of Roland Maddox, who died of
cancer last year at age 67 after smoking primarily Lucky Strike
cigarettes for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found that Brown &AMP; Williamson, which acquired the Lucky
Strike when it bought American Tobacco Co., had produced a
defective product and then conspired to conceal its dangers from
the public.
</P>
<P>
   The punitive damages awared by the jury were far less than the
lawyers for the family of the plaintiff had sought.
</P>
<P>
   John Nyhan, a lawyer for Brown &AMP; Williamson, which is based in
Louisville, Ky., and is a subsidiary of BAT Industries PLC of
London, said that he expected that the company would seek to have
the award set aside and, failing that, appeal it.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed that the judge in the case had mistakenly
allowed into evidence documents stolen from a company law firm in
1994 by Merrell Williams, a paralegal.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers involved in tobacco cases said that Wednesday's
decision may encourage those who believe Congress should not bar
class-action lawsuits and punitive damages in federal tobacco
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette companies insisted on protection from such suits as
part of the $365.8 billion tobacco settlement proposal reached last
June between the industry and 41 state attorneys general. But while
that proposal has since collapsed, Congress is debating legislation
modeled on it, and some bills include protections from such
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Daynard, director of the Tobacco Products Liability
Project at Northeastern University School of Law, in Bostin, said
that many proponents of federal legislation had argued that bars on
lawsuits against tobacco companies were an acceptable trade-offs
for industry concessions because smokers has so little chance of
success in a courtroom. But Daynard said that Wednesday's decison
suggested otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   He added that many documents used in the Florida case had been
publicly released recently as the result of tobacco lawsuits
brought by states like Minnesota. Those records were now available
to lawyers on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone with a computer can download them,'' said Daynard, who
is involved in lawsuits against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, victories by individual smokers remain rare. Norwood
Wilner, a plaintiffs' lawyer in Jacksonville, who represented
Maddox's estate in Wednesday's case, also won a $750,000 verdict
against Brown &AMP; Williamson in 1996 that the company is appealing.
In the last two years, the lawyer has lost two cases brought by
individual smokers, both of them against the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco
Co. a unit of RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   He has about 100 individual claims pending against cigarette
makers.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wilner's cases, only a few other smokers had succeeded
since the 1950s in their cases against tobacco companies. But some
of those verdicts had either been reversed on appeal or juries,
while they had found against the companies, had not awarded
damages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Florida case, Wilner had asked the jury to consider
meting out substantial punitive damages against Brown &AMP; Williamson
based on the company's net worth which he placed at $836 million.
But Stephanie Hartley, a lawyer who worked with Wilner on the case,
said that jury's award of $450,000 was far less that had been
sought.
</P>
<P>
   But she added, that Maddox's family who had carried his lawsuit
forward after his death, was not disappointed by the amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jurors indicated that they wanted to send a message and
they would have given out a much larger punitive damage award if
they knew the money was going for a purpose like education rather
than to individuals,'' Ms. Hartley said.
</P>
<P>
   In its defense, lawyers for Brown &AMP; Williamson had argued that
Maddox had been aware of the dangers of smoking but choose to
ignore them and not to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed that the jurors did not find that Maddox
was personally responsible for the choices he made,'' Nyhan, the
company's lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hartley said she and Wilner had based their case in part on
previously-secret industry documents released in recent months as a
result of the lawsuit brought by the state of Minnesota against
tobacco producers. That lawsuit, which was filed to recover
tobacco-related Medicaid expenses was settled last month for $6.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   She estimated that 25 percent of the company documents used in
the Maddox's lawsuit surfaced as a result of the Minnesota lawsuit.
But she added that the documents largely added details and context
to revelations contained in previously disclosed records including
those stolen in 1994 by Williams, the former paralegal, from a law
firm used by Brown &AMP; Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these documents out of Minnesota have helped us
tighten our case,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
