<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-COIN-HISTORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS IN MONEY HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BC-DOLLAR-COIN) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1690: The Massachusetts Bay Colony issues the first paper money
in the colonies.
</P>
<P>
   1775: American colonists issue paper money to finance the
Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   1781: The Continental Congress charters the first real bank, the
Bank of North America.
</P>
<P>
   1785: The Continental Congress adopts the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   1792: Congress creates the U.S. Mint, and requires coins to have
``an impression emblematic of liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   1793: The first U.S. coins are minted, from gold, silver and
copper. Legend holds that George Washington donated some of his
personal silver for early coins. The Mint's first delivery is
11,178 copper cents.
</P>
<P>
   1864: A two-cent coin becomes the first to bear the motto ``In
God We Trust.'' That and the phrase ``E Pluribus Unum'' appear on
all U.S. coins in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   1877: The Bureau of Engraving and Printing begins issuing money.
</P>
<P>
   1909: The first Lincoln cent is produced, with stalks of wheat
on the back. (It remains the only coin in circulation in which the
portrait faces to the right.)
</P>
<P>
   1929: U.S. currency design is standardized.
</P>
<P>
   1943: Due to copper shortage during World War II, pennies are
made of zinc-coated steel.
</P>
<P>
   1957: The first paper money printed with ``In God We Trust'' is
issued.
</P>
<P>
   1990: A security thread is added to paper money to deter
counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: The U.S. Mint, the Department of Treasury Bureau of
Engraving and Printing
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
