<HEADLINE>
STAYING IN MANHATTAN: EXPENSIVE PROPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
 (Duplication warning: Also moving in `a' category) 
(dc) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Looking for a hotel room in Manhattan? You have
plenty of options.
</P>
<P>
   You could book weeks in advance and pay $300 or so a night for a
room at a modern midtown high-rise like the Crowne Plaza. If you're
willing to pay a bit more _ say, $500 a night on average _ you
could probably get something with less of a hassle at the Four
Seasons or the Pierre. Or you could do what a growing number of
visitors are forced to do: stay in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel market in Manhattan, the most expensive in the nation
and fresh off a record year in 1997, continued to tighten in the
first quarter of 1998, with the average cost of a night's stay
creeping closer to $200.
</P>
<P>
   The market has become so expensive that in the past 18 months
five hotels _ the Lowell, the St. Regis and the Carlyle, as well as
the Pierre and the Four Seasons _ began charging an average rate of
$500. No other city in the nation has even a single hotel with an
average rate so high, industry experts said.
</P>
<P>
   And even as prices rise, it is still difficult to find a room in
New York unless it is booked far in advance. That fact has forced
some visitors to stay in New Jersey or bypass the city altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot find a decent hotel room anywhere on Manhattan, it
seems, for less than a fortune,'' said Alan Bennett of Sydney,
Australia, who was planning to come to the city in August. ``We
have searched data base after data base and rung hotel chains'
reservations centers, all to no avail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has got to the stage,'' he added, ``where we are about to
scrap our plans to go to New York and instead split our four or
five days there between an extra day or two in Washington and
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who do find a room are often in for a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hundred bucks!'' said Susan Jeans of Bayport, Minn., who
booked her room at the Crowne Plaza in mid-Manhattan two weeks in
advance. ``We were expecting like $200.''
</P>
<P>
   The average price of a room in Manhattan rose to $189.70 for the
first quarter of the year, according to preliminary figures from
the Coopers &AMP; Lybrand Lodging Research Network. That's a 13.9
percent leap over the $166.58 average room price for the first
quarter of 1997 and a smaller jump over the $187.91 rate for all of
1997. By the end of the year, Coopers &AMP; Lybrand expects average
room rates to rise another 10 to 12 percent, surpassing $200, a
figure reached briefly for the first time last fall and Christmas,
the busiest months of the year for many New York hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Occupancy rates are nearing records, too. For the first three
months of the year, which are among the slowest for the industry in
New York, hotels were 80.5 percent filled, according to Coopers &AMP;
Lybrand. That's an increase of 5.4 percent over the first quarter
of 1997, and only slightly down from 82 percent in the fourth
quarter of 1997, which was the highest since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demand is unprecedented here,'' said Steven Pipes, general
manager of Le Parker Meridien, a hotel in mid-Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   John A. Fox, a senior vice president with PKF Consulting, a
hotel and real estate consulting firm in Manhattan, said that
business was good for a variety of reasons: the strong local and
national economies; a continuing shortage of rooms; the city's
improved image; a cheap dollar in many parts of the world, which
makes it affordable for foreign tourists to come to the city and
expensive for Americans to travel abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has been on a steady upward climb since 1992,'' Fox
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jeffrey C. Zawadzk from Bayport, Minn., was hoping to stay at
the Millennium in mid-Manhattan this month, where a conference he
was attending was being held. He could not get a room, though.
Instead, he, like Ms. Jeans, a colleague, stayed at the Crowne
Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do lot more planning next time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorn R. Hanson, chairman of Coopers &AMP; Lybrand's hotel and
casino division, said, ``It's a hotelier's dream, rates rising at
three to four times inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   The increased business has led not only to the planned
construction in Manhattan of more than 31 new hotels, with more
than 11,593 rooms, but also to a slight increase in hotel jobs.
According to the state Department of Labor, hotel employment in New
York City rose by 700 jobs to 36,200 in April of this year, from
35,500 last April.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fastest growth spurt I've ever experienced in the
hotel industry,'' said Kevin Murphy, regional manager for New
Boston Select Staffing, which provides hotels with personnel. ``We
are filling job requests including housekeeping-cooks-wait staff,
and it's not just body-pushing anymore. Hotel skills are in great
demand. The hotel business is searching for skilled labor, similar
to the information technology industry. With the right experience
you can write your own ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson also noted that hotels are curtailing discounts and
weekend packages because the markets are so strong. ``Everything is
priced premium,'' he said. ``And we are also finding that guests
are spending more money in the hotels.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's hotel space squeeze has sent many corporate travel
managers scrambling. J.P. Morgan &AMP; Company now often books people
into the relatively spartan Club Quarters hotel in downtown
Manhattan, which lacks amenities such as in-room faxes and room
service.
</P>
<P>
   And with the New York Convention and Visitors Bureau projecting
32.5 million out-of-towners coming to the city this year, including
5.9 million from abroad, many business travelers and tourists may
find that accommodations in New Jersey are their only affordable or
available alternative. But even there, the overflow from Manhattan
is making it difficult to find a room.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Eismeier, the treasurer of Colgate University, could
not get a room two weeks ago. ``We tried a dozen or more hotels,
plus an AAA Travel agent, plus the Williams Club,'' she said.
``Friends checked the Cornell Club and the Yale Club _ no soap.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, AAA suggested the Marriott at Newark Airport,'' she said.
``It was just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me want to see if any of our real estate investment
managers were investing in hotel development in New York City.
Seems like the city needs that.''
</P>
<P>
   The visitors bureau advises people trying to find a room to call
the Peak Season Hotel Hot Line at (800) 846-7666, which makes
reservations for more than 80 hotels in various price ranges and
can give availability information. If you're really stuck, the
bureau says, try contacting hotels after 6 p.m. to check on
canceled reservations that have not been guaranteed with a credit
card.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the new hotels going up, it is probable, according
to industry analysts, that only 4,000 to 5,000 of the approximately
12,000 rooms that are planned will be built; there are currently
about 45,000 rooms in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a drop in the bucket,'' said Fox of PKF Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Weinstein, editor in chief of Hotels magazine, noted,
however, that if the economy slips, demand could fall _ just as
additional rooms were being made available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could be dangerous,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
