<SLUG> BC-DUNKIN-THIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPS SEIZE DUNKIN' DONUTS ROBBERY SUSPECT NAMED DUNCAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The homonym was not lost on the Police Department:
The man arrested Tuesday night in the robbery of eight Dunkin'
Donuts shops in Manhattan over the last two months was named
Douglas Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan was arrested as he and an accomplice tried to rob a
Dunkin' Donuts shop at 412 Third Ave. near 29th Street, said
Detective Mark Patterson, a police spokesman. As Duncan pulled out
a knife and announced a robbery, he was stopped by Officers Kevin
Buell and Teddy Lauterdorn of the 13th Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   Police took pains to point out that the arresting officers were
staking out the doughnut shop in the hopes of preventing a robbery,
not filling up on Boston Kremes.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Dunkin' Donuts shops have been robbed since April. In each
case, the description of the robber and of his method were the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd come in, order a doughnut, and when the register was
opened he'd make a grab for the money,'' said Sgt. Randall Bush of
the Manhattan Robbery Squad. ``Sometimes, he'd show a knife.''
</P>
<P>
   So officers were given a sketch of the suspect and dispatched to
doughnut shops around Manhattan. ``Everybody was volunteering for
that job,'' another police official said jokingly, noting the
well-known affinity officers have for doughnuts. ``Guys said they
would come in on their days off for that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, 24, and his accomplice were arrested at 5:10 p.m.
Wednesday and taken to the 13th Precinct, where they were placed in
line-ups before other angry doughnut makers. Duncan confessed to
robbing all eight donut shops, police said.
</P>
<P>
   He was arraigned Wednesday on charges of robbing the shop on
Third Avenue, but the investigation is continuing and he could face
additional charges, said Wayne Brison, a spokesman for Manhattan
District Attorney Robert Morgenthau.
</P>
<P>
   Police identified his accomplice as Howard Johnson, 43. They
said they did not believe that Johnson was responsible for any
other doughnut robberies. And they said there was no indication
that he had robbed any of his namesake restaurants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
