<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3771 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-TAX-BOS &LR;      06-10 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP ATTACHES TO TOBACCO BILL RELIEF FOR ``MARRIAGE PENALTY''
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate, eyeing money to be raised by a
potential tobacco tax hike, on Wednesday approved an election-year
tax cut to address an oddity in the tax code called the marriage
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   About 42 percent of couples pay the so-called penalty, which
requires them to pay higher taxes than they would if they remained
single and earned the same income. The quirk has troubled lawmakers
for decades, but it is hard to fix without making other parts of
the tax code unfair.
</P>
<P>
   In a voice vote led by Republicans, the Senate attached the tax
relief plan to the sweeping tobacco bill now before Congress. The
prospects of that bill becoming law are uncertain, but some
senators said the tax measure will make it easier to move the
tobacco bill through the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stayin' alive,'' said Senator John McCain, a Republican from
Arizona, who is the key sponsor of the tobacco bill.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut would give couples earning less than $50,000, and
who are in the 28 percent tax bracket, a tax cut of about $238 next
year. The cut would increase to more than $900 in 2008. It would be
funded in part by a $1.10 hike in the tax on each pack of
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the measure would allow self-employed individuals
to deduct the full cost of their health insurance from their income
taxes, effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers have been pushing hard this year to end the
marriage penalty, a move that wins support from both the
tax-cutting and social conservative wings of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had been prepared to go along, and the White House
Wednesday endorsed an earlier version of the tax cut. But Senate
Democrats complained that the version finally approved cost more
than they had agreed to support. They argued that money for the
plan inevitably would come from the projected budget surplus that
the president has said should be held in reserve in case it is
needed to shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is still conceivable, which is a problem, and it is why I
believe this will ultimately be scaled back,'' said Senator John F.
Kerry, referring to the size of the tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, a single man and single woman, each earning
$37,500, would each pay about $5,550 in taxes, a total of $11,100.
But if they married, their combined income would produce a $12,500
tax bill under current law _ $1,400 more than they would pay as
single people.
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure approved Wednesday, sponsored by Senator Phil
Gramm, Republican of Texas, married couples earning less than
$50,000 a year would qualify for a new tax deduction. Those couples
could deduct $825 from their adjusted gross income next year and
$990 annually in 2000 through 2002. The deduction slowly rises to
$3,300 a year by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complained of the cost, $46 billion over 10 years.
Under terms of the measure, only one-third of the money would come
from the higher tobacco tax in most years. Democrats said the rest
would come from vital federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vote for the Gramm amendment is a vote to take $90 billion
to $125 billion away from Social Security,'' Kerry said on the
Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry also said Gramm was giving a tax cut to all married
couples who earn under $50,000, even though roughly 50 percent of
those couples receive a ``marriage bonus,'' meaning their tax bill
is lower than it would be if they paid taxes as unmarried
individuals. Seven percent of couples neither pay a marriage
penalty nor get the bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Under a Democratic proposal, which would cost $27.8 billion over
10 years, couples earning up to $50,000 could take a 20 percent
deduction against the lower of their two incomes. The deduction
would phase out for those earning up to $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   The effect would be to lessen or eliminate the marriage penalty
for those who pay it, but make little change to the tax bill of
people who receive a bonus, Democrats said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
