<SLUG> BC-GUNS-RENO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI BACKGROUND CHECKS MAY ADD GUN TAX TO TEXAS BUYERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ People seeking to buy guns in Texas may have to pay
a federal surcharge of about $15 beginning this fall unless state
leaders decide to help the FBI conduct computerized background
checks on would-be purchasers, a senior Justice Department official
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the state offers its assistance, the FBI will charge
licensed gun dealers $15 per transaction, the agency's
administrative cost of conducting the background check, once the
computer system is in place Nov. 30. The federal fee is expected to
be passed on to the gun purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   The fee is designed to encourage Texas and 30 other as-yet
uncooperative states to assist the FBI in its high-tech effort to
check criminal records of would-be purchasers, added the official,
who asked not to be identified by name.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said Wednesday that state assistance
is critical to the national effort to keep guns away from
criminals. States have the most thorough, accurate and up-to-date
records on the criminal histories of their residents, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The states are an important partner in our efforts to build a
National Instant Check System,'' Reno said, referring to the FBI's
computer program. ``By working together in the coming months and
the coming years, state and federal law enforcement have a real
opportunity to keep guns out of the wrong hands and provide for
safer streets and safer communities.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI wants _ but the law does not require _ each state to
have a ``point of contact,'' a state official responsible for
assisting the federal agency in its effort to collect data on
prospective buyers, Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows more about state records than the states
themselves, and the system will work better if the states
participate in the National Instant Check System,'' the attorney
general said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the FBI's computerized system, prospective gun purchasers
would fill out a federal form seeking information about their
backgrounds. The consumer presumably would pay the FBI's fee to the
gun dealer, who would in turn access the computer system.
</P>
<P>
   The computerized background check would be completed within
minutes, and the dealer would be informed instantly whether the
sale may be made or if the check revealed information that needed
further examination. The FBI would then inform the gun dealer
within three days if the sale may be completed or if the purchaser
failed the background check, the Justice Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Brady law requires that firearms not be sold to indicted or
convicted felons, fugitives, illegal aliens or people who have
renounced their U.S. citizenship, been dishonorably discharged from
the military, have a record of domestic violence or been adjudged
mentally incompetent. People denied guns have a right to appeal
their rejection, but none of the more than 200,000 people rejected
under the 1993 Brady law have appealed, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   To preserve the would-be buyer's privacy, the computer will not
reveal why a prospective purchaser was rejected, the official
added.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said creating a computer system that will encompass more
than 60,000 gun dealers nationwide and account for the more than 11
million guns sold each year has presented a ``great challenge'' for
the Justice Department. ``But the prospect of making America's
streets and communities safer makes it all worthwhile and all the
more important,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2120EDT &QL; 
