<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXBREAKS-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOINT COMMITTEE AGREES ON EDUCATION TAX-BREAK BILL  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., N.J.)   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House and Senate negotiators agreed Wednesday on a
final bill to provide tax breaks to parents who save for elementary
and secondary school costs, including private school tuition, a
proposal that President Clinton has threatened to veto.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's centerpiece, tax breaks for education expenses,
remained unchanged in the compromise bill. The measure, which has
bipartisan support, was sponsored by Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga.,
and Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. The agreement reached Wednesday
dropped two contentious provisions, including one that banned
voluntary national, standards-based educational testing, testing
that Clinton had proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to take up the measure next week, and
Torricelli said he believed that the Senate would have enough votes
to override a presidential veto. The House is also expected to take
up the legislation next week, but its prospects for a veto-proof
majority are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Congress will soon produce a bill to improve the
educational opportunities available to children across our
nation,'' Coverdell said. ``I urge the president to abandon his
stubborn defense of failed education policies and join our effort
to implement real education reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow family members, charitable groups or
private donors to contribute as much as $2,000 a year for each
elementary or secondary student to special savings accounts that
could be used for education-related expenses, including tutoring,
computers and private or parochial school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   The interest on the money and withdrawals from the account would
be tax free and could be used for college expenses. The accounts,
which would cost the federal government $1.6 billion in 10 years,
would be phased out for individuals who make more than $95,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said the bill favors the wealthy and does little for
the poor, arguing that the federal money would be better spent
elsewhere. Many Democrats have denounced the legislation as a first
step toward using federal money to subsidize private schools.
Republicans maintain that Clinton is merely responding to pressure
from teachers' unions, which oppose the measure.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiations, Republicans and Democrats on the conference
committee stripped two provisions from the legislation. Seven
Senate Democrats said they would drop their support for the bill if
the parts were not removed.
</P>
<P>
   One would have barred voluntary national standards-based testing
in reading and math for school children. Republican leaders said
that provision would now be included in the Labor, Health and Human
Services and Education appropriations bill. The other provision
would have converted nearly all federal education money into block
grants for participating states.
</P>
<P>
   By removing the two provisions, Republicans and some Democrats
hoped Clinton would embrace the idea of expanding the tax breaks,
which now exist for college students, and sign the bill into law.
Polls show that the proposal is popular with voters. The
negotiators also tacked on a reading bill, supported by Clinton,
that must be signed for $210 million to be spent starting July 1
for research, teacher training and grants to help improve reading
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have made the education savings bill their showcase
education initiative and have used it as an election-year issue to
tap into the frustration of some parents who believe that public
schools are not doing enough to teach their children. Some
Democrats also support the bill, saying it would help, not hurt
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is fairly deep Democratic support for this concept,''
Torricelli said, adding that the Republicans had ``made this easy
for President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
