<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3782 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAMENCO-DANCE-2TAKES     06-10 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAMENCO-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREER AND FRESHER, AN OLD FORM CATCHES FIRE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was not a dream. Late one night last month, at
Tunnel, a club in lower Manhattan, the deejay threw a curve. For
several hours a group of young men and women had been gyrating to
hip-hop, house and techno music when, out of the blue, a passionate
song sung by Alejandro Sanz filled the room.
</P>
<P>
   Without missing a beat, the dancers' posture changed. They
lifted their chests, placed their hands on their waists and
prepared for a fiery flamenco. Then, fingers clicking, hips
swiveling, feet pounding, they had a go at it. They sizzled. And
why not? Flamenco is hot.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year more performances of flamenco have been seen in
New York than ever before, at least twice the number of any other
foreign dance. Some 15 companies, both Spanish and American,
arrived in the city, among them the Cristina Hoyos troupe, Noche
Flamenca, the National Ballet of Spain and Ballet Hispanico.
</P>
<P>
   The tide shows no signs of abating. Early this month, the
flamenco star Joaquin Cortes returned to New York with his show
``Gipsy Passion,'' a huge hit in 1996 at Radio City Music Hall. Now
it's at the City Center. And starting on Tuesday, the Carlota
Santana Dance Company, with six musicians and nine dancers, comes
to the Joyce Theater for a week.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the program will be the New York premiere of
``Federico,'' a mix of dance and drama in tribute to the beloved
Spanish writer _ and champion of flamenco _ Federico Garcia Lorca,
a martyred revolutionary who died in the Spanish Civil War. This
year is the 100th anniversary of his birth.
</P>
<P>
   Why is flamenco suddenly so popular here? America's large
Hispanic population and an attendant interest in Hispanic culture
partly account for the phenomenon. But the dance's own evolution is
as much responsible for its new-found success.
</P>
<P>
   Originally a regional folk art, flamenco has found mass appeal
by incorporating new kinds of music and dance forms, from ballet to
jazz. At the same time, it has begun to modernize its look for
dance dramas. Though traditional costumes are still used, the
frilly shirts for men and the long, cumbersome trains on women's
dresses are nonetheless giving way to looser and sleeker
contemporary dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flamenco has become more sophisticated,'' Ms. Santana said.
``After a quiet revolution that was long in the making, we're now
seeing it blossom.''
</P>
<P>
   Flamenco emerged from southern Spain at the end of the 15th
century, a time when Gypsies, Arabs, Jews and other outcasts
mingled in the region. These persecuted peoples poured their
emotions into a music and dance that became flamenco, distinguished
by a regal carriage of the head, torso and arms and a fierce
projection of pride and sensuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time,'' said Miguel Marin, a producer of Spanish
dance events in Spain and abroad, ``flamenco only appealed to a
small minority. Most Spaniards couldn't identify with it. But now
it has shed many of its dated accouterments without losing its
essence. If this hadn't happened, it might have become obsolete.''
</P>
<P>
   Flamenco artists of the 1920s were the first to look for ways to
make the dance more relevant to their times. The matchless Carmen
Amaya, whose career spanned 40 years, challenged sexual stereotypes
by donning pants and dancing with the power of a man.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, another master, Antonio Gades, took flamenco into the
realm of contemporary performing arts when he produced Garcia
Lorca's play ``Blood Wedding'' for the legitimate theater, a drama
filled with flamenco sequences.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, flamenco won international exposure when
Gades teamed up with the director Carlos Saura to adapt ``Blood
Wedding'' and another Garcia Lorca play, ``Carmen,'' for the
screen. Now dance film classics, the movies were the precursors of
Saura's eloquent documentary ``Flamenco,'' released last year.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout these decades the dance itself was changing. Elements
of ballet, modern and jazz dance were added to the flamenco
lexicon: arm movements became more fluid, and dancers would lunge
deeply and bend their knees. Like any folk art, flamenco had
historically been passed down from one generation to the next. But
now it became a subject of formal study, and performers began
improving their technique remarkably.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, no longer did every flamenco work revolve around love,
betrayal and death. The noted choreographer Mario Maya, for
instance, creates dances to Garcia Lorca's poetry, some of which
deals with nature and his native Andalusia.
</P>
<P>
   Flamenco music also changed. For centuries a guitar and singers
were all that was required for the dance. But in 1975 the guitarist
Paco de Lucia added jazzy percussion to his compositions. Today, no
musical accompaniment is out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the choreographer Maria Plages created a work for the
Compania Andaluza de Danza in Seville to the folk music of Tom
Waits, the world music of Peter Gabriel and the tango works of the
Argentine composer Astor Piazzola.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This September, in the annual monthlong flamenco festival in
Seville, Spain, audiences will see how varied the dance form has
become, when 40 companies perform in the city's many theaters and
clubs. De Lucia, Ms. Pages, the singer Enrique Morente and the
composer and guitarist Manolo Sanlucar are among the major artists
on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flamenco has been freed from its strictures,'' said Marin.
``It can now be used simply as a movement language, like ballet.
Even though Antonio Canales adopts a purist approach and Joaquin
Cortes advocates a fusion, their base is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Does fusion dilute the art? Some authorities on flamenco think
so. In an interview last year in the Spanish newspaper El Pais,
Canales stressed the difference between himself and Cortes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kind of flamenco is intimate, austere and emotional,'' he
said. ``I defend flamenco at its purest. It is a great and profound
art. We're not talking about Coca-Cola Light here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Santana falls between the two camps. She established her
troupe and school in New York 15 years ago, with a mission to make
flamenco more accessible to the wider public. One way she chooses
to do this is by presenting narrative dances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federico'' was on her agenda for some time. Finally, in 1996,
partly because of flamenco's current high profile, the National
Dance Residency Project, sponsored by the Pew Charitable Trusts,
gave her $100,000 to produce it. The grant was followed shortly by
another one, from the New York State Council on the Arts, for
$10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were impressed by Carlota's concept and the high quality of
her collaborators,'' said Susan Fait Meyers, director of the dance
project.
</P>
<P>
   For her choreographer and lead, Ms. Santana picked the elegant
young flamenco dancer Juan Andres Maya, a Gypsy from Granada. (In
its American premiere in Albuquerque, N.M., on June 9, Miguel Angel
Rojas played Garcia Lorca, as he will at the Joyce.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Santana also commissioned the well-known Spanish classical
composer Juan Campos to create the score and perform it with his
group, Canadu. She then asked Manuel Duque, professor emeritus of
theater arts at Pennsylvania State University, to write the book
and direct the production.
</P>
<P>
   He had directed another Santana piece, ``For Whom the Bell
Tolls,'' based on the Hemingway novel, in 1988. ``Each of us had a
different perspective on how to represent Garcia Lorca in dance,''
Ms. Santana said. ``It resulted in a very rich drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall and stately, perhaps in her early 50s, Ms. Santana looks
like the quintessential flamenco dancer, her hair black and
flowing. In ``Federico'' she plays the part of Garcia Lorca's
mother. The work compresses Garcia Lorca's brief life into a series
of vignettes, beginning with his childhood in Granada and
continuing through his early, heady professional success in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   With sensitivity, Duque shows how the writer's poems and plays
reflected both his inner conflict about his homosexuality _
something utterly taboo in Spanish society _ and his outward
political and cultural concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the dance to be impressionistic, not literal,'' Duque
said. ``Many cultures fused in Garcia Lorca's work, as they do in
Andalusia. I bring in these influences.'' The drama ends with
Garcia Lorca's death at 36 in 1936, when he was shot by government
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   To give the story a contemporary feel, Maya used flamenco's
traditionally insistent hand claps and footwork in conjunction with
more natural movements, which lend the piece fluidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I use tense and erratic gestures, others that are
soft and gentle _ all to convey Garcia Lorca's various mental
states,'' he said. ``Granada then had a closed society. I put his
sense of isolation into the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Federico'' had its world premiere in Granada last
December, cold winds had swept into the city from the surrounding,
snow-covered Sierra Nevada. Nonetheless, local dignitaries,
townspeople and visitors from Madrid and Barcelona turned out in
record numbers for the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite a test to open among his most devoted
followers,'' Ms. Santana said, ``but it felt right. Granada was
Garcia Lorca's home.'' In a rave review, Miguel Angel Gonzalez, the
local newspaper critic, called ``Federico'' ``a beautiful flamenco
musical.''
</P>
<P>
   The next test is the United States. ``I hope through works like
`Federico' to establish flamenco in the United States as a basic
dance language, comprehensible to a vast number of people,'' said
Ms. Santana. That ambition is a tall one. But if the Radio City
audiences and the Tunnel clubgoers are any indication, it may not
be out of reach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
