<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3784 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX     06-10 1970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDRESS ROLLS DICE BY TRADING ACE MECHANICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Childress shook up the NASCAR world earlier this week,
when he ordered a swap of crew chiefs for his two underachieving
Winston Cup teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underachieving'' hardly seems to fit when speaking about
seven-time series champion Dale Earnhardt and respected crew chief
Larry McReynolds. Between them, they have been involved in 94
Winston Cup victories. Their pairing at the beginning of the 1997
season widely was headlined as the key to Earnhardt's elusive and
record eighth Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   But the union has produced more inquiries than victories 14
races into '98. So Childress has decided that Earnhardt will team
with Kevin Hamlin, formerly crew chief for teammate Mike Skinner.
McReynolds now is working with Skinner _ both swaps effective with
the Miller Lite 400 at Michigan Speedway this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the toughest decision I had to make in quite some
time,'' Childress said Tuesday, two days after he had informed the
principals. ``The drivers, everyone was ready for some type of
change. They were sitting here saying, `What are we going to do
next?' Everyone ended up buying in on it. It was a change that had
to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Childress said he opted to trade his ace mechanics Saturday
night at Richmond, Va., where Earnhardt finished 21st after
qualifying an abysmal 38th.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner finished 30th at Richmond after qualifying an abysmal
34th. Skinner, who crashed heavily at Atlanta Motor Speedway in
March and Texas Motor Speedway in April, is 38th in Cup points.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt stands 12th in Cup points. Earnhardt never has
finished lower than 12th in the final standings during his career.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds admittedly has had trouble adjusting from the Ford
Thunderbirds he worked on at Robert Yates Racing to RCR's Chevrolet
Monte Carlos. But he and Earnhardt seemingly had solved their
``communication problems'' during Speed Weeks at the Daytona
International Speedway in February. Earnhardt won his 125-mile
qualifying race and then removed 19 years of frustration by scoring
an emotional victory in the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   The wheels of this working relationship, however, may have begun
falling off as early as April, when the Cup series visited Fort
Worth for the Texas 500. The open practice on Thursday, April 2,
was considerably spiced when Earnhardt got on his radio and ripped
the handling of his No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   In language that would have made A.J. Foyt blush, Earnhardt said
he could not drive the car. He asked for a second opinion, and a
third, and Sterling Marlin and Skinner both hot-lapped the No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor circulating the garage area then was that Earnhardt
had no confidence in the chassis _ a chassis engineered by
McReynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's results since crashing at TMS have been particularly
un-Intimidating, especially in qualifying. Earnhardt qualified
fourth at Daytona and second at Talladega, the series'
restrictor-plate races. But he has started no higher than 26th _ as
the best of the second-round qualifiers _ in the remainder of the
races. Earnhardt has posted only four top-10 finishes, including
Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Skinner _ the 1997 Cup rookie of the year _ has
managed only two top-10 starts and one top-10 finish in the No. 31
Lowe's Chevy. That was his memorable eighth-place run at Daytona,
where Skinner played a key role as drafting partner for Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had the season we expected with either car,'' said
Childress, who has won 63 races and six Cup titles with Earnhardt.
``Winning the Daytona 500 was a real highlight. But as the season
progressed, it just wasn't working. We tried (changing) a whole
lot. We tried different bodies. We moved bodies backward and
forward and different setups. It was well-thought-out. We're not
pulling from the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Childress said each of his crew chiefs has a different style. At
this point, maybe different really is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Hamlin is laid-back. Working with Dale, I think Kevin's
personality might fit better,'' Childress said. ``Mike Skinner is a
very aggressive driver. He needs someone to get ahold of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest risk with the swap, Childress said, involves its
on-the-fly timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unfair to Larry McReynolds and Kevin Hamlin, with
three days, to go out to another racetrack,'' Childress said.
``None of us are expecting miracles. We just hope to see an
improvement.'' &QL; 
THE BUZZ &QL; 
NASCAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup star Dale Jarrett has cooled his jets somewhat since
Saturday night, when he roundly criticized NASCAR officials for
throwing a red flag that factored into the outcome of the Pontiac
Excitement 400 at Richmond, Va. Jarrett was leading the race when
it was stopped with seven laps remaining to clean oil and debris
from Turn 2 after a multicar wreck. Terry Labonte, who was racing
with tires fresher than Jarrett's, was able to run down and bump
his way past on lap 398 of the 400 at the three-quarter-mile,
D-shaped oval. Labonte, ironically, won under caution after Johnny
Benson Jr. hit the wall between turns 1 and 2. Mike Helton,
NASCAR's vice president for competition, said Tuesday the red-flag
decision was made to give the fans the chance to see the race end
under the green flag. But Jarrett said the call was not consistent
with NASCAR policy. ``This sport has gone on for 50 years, and it
was our contention they clean the track up as normal,'' said
Jarrett, driver of the No. 88 Ford Quality Care/Ford Credit Taurus.
``What hurt us was stopping with older tires and them having the
opportunity to cool off. Where Terry and Rusty Wallace had much
newer tires. We thought it could be cleaned in three or four laps,
and we could race a couple under green. We're not against finishing
the race under green. That's what the fans deserve to see. But we
have to have some basis to go off of when we make our (pit)
decisions. This didn't seem to go along with the norm. Each
circumstance is different. I understand it was a call they had to
make in about 10 seconds, and it was best for the sport. We're not
happy the way things came out, but down the road the decision could
benefit us.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett also sought to defuse talk about possible retaliation
directed at Labonte during the Miller Lite 400 at Michigan Speedway
this weekend. Labonte used the right front fender of the No. 5
Kellogg's Chevrolet Monte Carlo to bump-pass past Jarrett.
Immediately after the race, Jarrett said, ``That's all right. We'll
remember that, and another day will come around.'' On Tuesday,
Jarrett modified his remarks. ``I'm not looking to rub on Terry
Labonte, at 190 mph or 200 going into the corners (at Michigan),''
Jarrett said. ``I'm not going to wreck Terry Labonte. That's not
the makeup of NASCAR. Hopefully one day I'll beat him; if I have to
use the bumper a little bit, then that's what I'll do. I know Terry
Labonte is a hard racer. He could have hit me a lot harder and put
me out of the race. He did enough to get by, and I finished second.
It shows the premium of winning Winston Cup races. When you're in
that position, you've got to take that chance. As far as paybacks _
the best way we can pay somebody back is to beat them on the
racetrack.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Irvan put the exclamation point on his comeback from a
near-fatal wreck at the Michigan Speedway in August 1994 last June,
when he won the Miller Lite 400 by 2.984 seconds over seven-time
Michigan winner Bill Elliott. Irvan said he has become a more
patient driver during his comeback. ``A lot of it is just more
experience,'' said Irvan, driver of the No. 36 Skittles Pontiac
Grand Prix. ``I guess when you hit your head so hard, sooner or
later you figure out how not to do it.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   The top six drivers in the Cup standings are separated by just
93 points through the first 13 races. That pack includes leader
Jeremy Mayfield (1,868 points), Rusty Wallace, Jeff Gordon, Mark
Martin, Jarrett and Terry Labonte (1,775). This is the first time
in NASCAR history that six drivers have been within 100 points of
the lead after the 13th race. &QL; 
IRL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for someone in the Pep Boys Indy Racing
League to carry the ball once Tony Stewart heads off to a full-time
NASCAR ride next season, car owner A.J. Foyt offers his rising
star, Billy Boat. Winner of the True Value 500K at Texas Motor
Speedway on Saturday night, Boat has a catchy name, he is
approachable and quotable. And as Foyt pointed out, Boat has won
open-wheel races across the country. ``A lot of people know Billy
Boat,'' said Foyt, who believes the name recognition factor in the
rival Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series is overstated.
``The names I know over there are Bobby Rahal, Bryan Herta _
because he drove for me _ and Little Al (Unser),'' Foyt said. ``You
got Michael Andretti. I know Jimmy Vasser, but the average person
don't know Vasser. And Alex Sardi (Zanardi)? Who really knows him?
You know him, I know him because he's racing. And that's really
about it over there. You've got a lot more names over here, I
think. And you're going to have bigger names over here.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Boat was one of six drivers who traded the lead 22 times during
the 312-mile night event at TMS. That was just one lead change
short of the IRL record, set during the Indy 500 _ a race which is
188 miles longer than the True Value 500K. ...
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Robby Unser has recorded top-10 finishes in both his IRL
starts. He was ninth at TMS in the Team Cheever Dallara/Aurora
owned by Indy 500 champion Eddie Cheever. Unser placed fifth in the
Indy 500 last month. &QL; 
FAST LAPS &QL; 
`WILD CHILD' PLANS RETURN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jac Haudenschild's Pennzoil World of Outlaws season became
painful on June 1, when he injured his shoulder in a wreck at
Lebanon Valley Speedway in West Lebanon, N.Y. He qualified for the
25-lap main event, but was unable to finish the race because of the
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Haudenschild since has missed two races in upstate New York and
another in Springfield, Ill., but is expected to return at
Bloomington, Ind., tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Before a 16th-place run May 30 at Lincoln Speedway in
Pennsylvania and his 23rd-place finish at Lebanon Valley,
Haudenschild had recorded four consecutive top 10s. He since has
slipped outside the top 10 in points.
</P>
<P>
   His last series victory was on May 2 at Knoxville, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding problems for Haudenschild and his Jack Elden-owned
team, crew chief Guy Forbrook has resigned. Reports say Forbrook
plans to start his own team. Dean Bruns is Haudenschild's new crew
chief. &QL; 
NUTS AND BOLTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Zanardi's victory in the Detroit Grand Prix was the 11th of
his career, and it moved him into sole possession of ninth place on
CART's all-time list. Zanardi broke out of a tie for 10th with Tom
Sneva, Bobby Unser and Fort Worth's Johnny Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Dallenbach Jr. is scheduled to make his first start in the
No. 50 Budweiser Chevrolet this week.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Shepherd will replace Buckshot Jones in the No. 8 Circuit
City Chevy at Michigan Speedway this week.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series regular Mike Bliss is expected to
be sidelined up to six weeks after breaking his right shoulder
blade in a fourth-lap accident during the Pronto Auto Parts 400K at
Texas Motor Speedway on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Jet Motorsports plans to enter NASCAR truck series star
Ron Hornaday Jr. in the Winston Cup Save Mart/Kragen 350 road race
at Sears Point Raceway, Sonoma, Calif., on June 28. The team is
owned by Texan Tim Beverley. &QL; 
LAST WORDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like someone hit me in the back with a baseball
bat.''
</P>
<P>
   IRL driver Mark Dismore, after suffering a concussion in a crash
in the True Value 500K on Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
