<HEADLINE>
FALWELL PROCLAIMS HIMSELF FULL-FLEDGED SOUTHERN BAPTIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The Rev. Jerry Falwell, who for the first time
is a voting delegate at the Southern Baptist Convention, now says
he is a full-fledged Southern Baptist. And he believes that his
adopted denomination is one of the most powerful political forces
in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern Baptists, with 15 million members strong, is a force
to be reckoned with,'' Falwell said in an interview at the
convention, which ends Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile leader of religious-political conservatives
predicted that the leadership of the giant denomination, which now
sides with social conservatives opposing abortion and gay
lifestyles, and championing prayer in schools, will have a major
influence in electing a Republican president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's George W. Bush, John Ashcroft (a Republican
senator from Missouri) or Steve Forbes, the Baptists will be a
force in getting them elected,'' Falwell predicted. ``And President
Clinton is making it easier for a Republican to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he believes that Texas Gov. George W. Bush is the
leading prospect for the Republican presidential nomination at
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to predict, but I think it's George W. Bush's
nomination to lose,'' Falwell said. ``He has a kind and gentle
quality and maybe even more charisma than his father,'' former
President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell, pastor of the 11,000-member Thomas Road Baptist Church
in Lynchburg, Va., arrived at the Southern Baptist Convention on
Sunday with 10 voting messengers, or delegates, from his church.
But he has purposely kept a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to every session, but I always slipped out through
the back door,'' Falwell said. He said he didn't want to distract
from the convention's main business.
</P>
<P>
   But Falwell appeared on the ``Crossfire'' TV program Tuesday and
supported an amendment to the Baptist Faith and Message Statement
that said, in part, that wives are to ``submit graciously to the
servant leadership of their husbands.''
</P>
<P>
   The most significant part of the statement on the family,
Falwell said Wednesday, is that it rejected the legitimacy of gay
and lesbian marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell burst onto the national scene in the 1980s as founder of
the now-defunct Moral Majority, one of the first organizations of
religious conservatives to emerge during the Reagan era to speak
out on moral and social issues. He said he and his church have
always been identified with the independent fundamentalist Baptist
movement, which was founded in the 1930s by the late Rev. J. Frank
Norris of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   But he has moved steadily closer to the Southern Baptist
Convention as it has become more conservative. Now he says his
church is dually aligned with the Southern Baptist Convention and
the Bible Baptist Fellowship, an independent Baptist organization
based in Springfield, Mo., that grew out of the Norris movement.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell and his church became eligible to join the Southern
Baptist Convention last year when his congregation began donating
funds to the Southern Baptist Conservatives of Virginia, a group
that broke away from that state's convention controlled by
moderates.
</P>
<P>
   A major reason for coming to the Salt Lake City meeting, Falwell
said, was to vote for his close friend, Paige Patterson, as
convention president.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, former president of Criswell College in Dallas and
now president of Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary, was
elected by acclamation Tuesday. He was a driving force when
conservatives won control of the denomination from moderates in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there is no reason at all for any Bible-believing
independent conservative Baptist church not to become a part of the
Southern Baptist Convention,'' Falwell said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his Thomas Road Baptist Church has helped start several
hundred congregations and that many of those churches now are
becoming part of the Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of those churches will be in the Southern Baptist
Convention eventually,'' he said. ``We had (representatives from)
25 or 30 of the churches at this convention.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
