<SLUG> BC-EMPLOYEE-AIRFARES-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM, CHRYSLER TO RETAIN AIRLINE FOR UNLIMITED EMPLOYEE TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the first attempts by major companies to counter the
high air fares charged by the major airlines, Chrysler Corp. and
General Motors Corp. are near an agreement to pay a monthly fee for
five years to Pro Air, a start-up airline based in Detroit, in
exchange for unlimited passage on the carrier for their employees.
</P>
<P>
   The innovative deal will help Pro Air, which is not yet a year
old and flies to just half a dozen destinations, compete against
Northwest Airlines, by far the dominant carrier in Detroit. And it
will save Chrysler and GM as much as $3 million and $6 million a
year, respectively, they said.
</P>
<P>
   While the terms of the agreements have largely been completed,
Chrysler and GM are still waiting for assurances from city
authorities that certain improvements will be made at Detroit City
Airport, where Pro Air is based.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hoping to get it closed by Friday,'' Peter Rowe, a GM
spokesman, said of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes as the last-minute walk-up fares paid most often
by businesses are at record levels and there is heightened concern
in Washington about the lack of competition at many of the
country's major airports. Earlier this year, Transportation
Department proposed new guidelines designed to prevent major
airlines from driving small upstart carriers out of their home
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses, such as Kimberly-Clark Corp. and Caterpillar Inc.,
have started or financed airlines (Midwest Express and Access Air,
respectively) in the past. And some have bailed out struggling
carriers by buying tickets in advance, as has been the case with
Trans World Airlines in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say the Pro Air deal would be the first time that
major corporations have paid an airline a guaranteed monthly
retainer on a long-term basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first intervention by major corporations to lower
costs and provide some competition at a fortress hub,'' said Kevin
Mitchell, chairman of the Business Travel Coalition, a corporate
advocate who helped broker the agreement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Northwest is considered one of the most aggressive of the major
airlines. It has been accused by low-cost challengers of a number
of practices to drive away low-cost challengers. It is being sued
by the Nevada-based Reno Air Inc., which contends that Northwest
unfairly cut its prices to less than its costs. Northwest denies it
competes unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest also has one of the tightest strangleholds on its hubs
of any major airline. It makes 82 percent of its daily takeoffs and
landings in Minneapolis and 79 percent in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Air flies two 146-passenger 737 jets from Detroit to
Philadelphia, Newark, Indianapolis, Baltimore and, in the winter,
to Orlando and Fort Myers, Fla. It charges $59 to $79 one way for a
coach seat, and as much as $164 for first class. Pro Air does not
require passengers to stay over Saturday night, as many major
airlines do to force business travelers to pay higher fares.
</P>
<P>
   Since Pro Air began flying July 4, Northwest _ which flies out
of the outlying Detroit Metropolitan Airport _ has matched its
prices on every route, reducing its walk-up fares by as much as 85
percent and offering more seats than Pro Air can, said Kevin
Stamper, Pro Air's chief executive. Northwest has also offered
travel agencies higher commissions if they book passengers on
Northwest instead of on Pro Air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a pretty serious competitive response,'' added
Stamper, 49. He is the son of Malcolm T. Stamper, the former vice
chairman of Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Pro Air chief and executives at Chrysler and GM declined to
say how much the companies have agreed to pay each month to Pro
Air, which has total revenues of only a few million dollars a
month. Stamper said that while the fees were not enough to cover
Pro Air's costs the money was ``very significant'' and would allow
the airline to expand into other markets. He also said he planned
to forge similar deals with other companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clearly is a powerful thing for us,'' he said. ``If we
didn't get this, we might have to rely on government assistance
against predatory practices to make the airline work.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract, which is to last five years with an option to
renew for another five years, will let Chrysler and GM employees
reserve tickets on all of Pro Air's flights. Stamper said that the
airline would hold back some seats on flights to accommodate
last-minute travelers from the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Air will also offer Chrysler and GM employees and their
families flights for $25 a seat on leisure trips, the same discount
given to Pro Air employees and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Chrysler and GM, which receive volume discounts
from Northwest, were careful not to portray the agreement as a shot
at the larger airline, which could conceivably retaliate against
the companies if Pro Air fails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent was never to replace our dominant carrier,'' said
Charles Braswell, the manager of general services at Chrysler. ``We
just think that competition is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Austin, a spokesman at Northwest, said that the deal was
just the latest wrinkle in a highly competitive industry and that
Northwest expected to continue serving Chrysler and GM ``They've
made a determination that they want to make this type of
experiment,'' he added, ``and we will watch it closely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
