<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The latest chapter of `Will they go or not?'
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicago -- Phil Jackson has hedged on whether he'd return to the
Bulls next season as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan has left open the possibility, however remote,
that he would play another season in Chicago. But forward Scottie
Pippen has been adamant about this being his final week as a Bull.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all said and done, I heard that Phil said if I come
back, he'll come back. That gives Michael an open window of
opportunity,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen was contradictory in talking about his future. He's
said that he'd like to play in Phoenix or Houston next year. And
he's publicly ridiculed owner Jerry Reinsdorg and general manager
Jerry Krause in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said many times I don't want to come back here and
play,'' Pippen said. ``I plan to go out and explore all of my
options as a free agent. But if I'm offered the right thing, maybe
I would consider coming back if the guys are here and they're
looking forward to trying to win another title.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said someone other than Jackson as coach of the Bulls and
Pippen not re-signed would indicate ``a rebuilding'' and give him
the signal he needs to quit for good.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson left open the slim possibility of returning after
Reinsdorf said weeks ago that he'd be ``inclined to invite everyone
back'' if the Bulls win their sixth championship in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   No Utah for Rodman
</P>
<P>
   Should the NBA Finals return to Salt Lake City, expect Dennis
Rodman to return to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go back to Utah,'' Rodman said. ``My life just
goes to complete hell when I go to Utah. That means I have to
revert to going to Las Vegas or going somewhere to get some
excitement, to try to keep my mind rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl to coach Bulls?
</P>
<P>
   Fired Seattle coach George Karl was listed in Wednesday's
Chicago Tribune as a possible replacement for Jackson next year.
Krause refused comment on the matter, referring questions until
after the season and he and Reinsdorf evaluate the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr on Jordan leaving
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kerr said he'd like to see Jordan retire after the season.
``Especially if we win it,'' Kerr said. ``There's nothing left for
him to prove, to do. He's done it all. He talks about going out on
top. What would be a better way to ride off into the sunset?''
</P>
<P>
   Mike on a mission
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's pet project is to get championship rings for the team
members who have not received one. He called Scott Burrell his
``project''.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
