<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-DEVILRAYS-NY     06-10 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS HANG ON TO DEFEAT DEVILRAYS, 3-2  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even with the significant addition of Mike Piazza to the lineup,
pitching and defense are what have won games for the Mets the
majority of the time this season. And for a staff that was
criticized before the season for lacking a front-line starter, Al
Leiter certainly has pitched like an ace.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter was in a constant struggle for command of his pitches
Wednesday at Shea Stadium, but he fought his way through six
innings of one-run ball and the Mets had just enough for a 3-2
victory over the expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays. It was Leiter's
seventh victory in 10 decisions, and it lowered the veteran
left-hander's earned run average to 1.70, second in the National
League to Atlanta's perennial Cy Young award winner, Greg Maddux
(1.69).
</P>
<P>
   In 12 starts for the Mets, Leiter has allowed just 15 earned
runs in 791/3 innings. He has been on a seasonlong roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pitching as good as about anybody in the league,''
Manager Bobby Valentine said after watching Leiter allow just four
hits while striking out nine with his 116 pitches. ``He's pitched
really well and taken no-decisions and losses. And he's pitched
without his best stuff and gotten wins.''
</P>
<P>
   With luck, Leiter, who has won his last four starts, could have
10 or 11 victories. It is becoming likely that he will be heading
to his second All-Star Game in four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to call him an ace or an All-Star or the best
pitcher in the league, please do,'' Valentine said. ``I think of
him as one of my fingers. And I'm not sure any one is more
important to me than any other.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because with a rotation of Leiter, Bobby Jones, Masato
Yoshii, Rick Reed and Hideo Nomo, the Mets are off to their best
60-game start in 10 years. And all the starters, with the exception
of the newly acquired Nomo, have contributed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, since Leiter is now 3-0 after Met losses _ he would be
4-0 had the bullpen not blown a save in Houston on April 28 _ the
argument could be made that he has gradually filled the role of
stopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not feeling good about yourself, you feel like the
world is falling in on you, or that what can go wrong will go
wrong,'' Leiter said. ``I don't feel that way. I feel I can get out
of any jam that comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was an example. His first five pitches were balls, and
the first two Devil Rays reached base. But Leiter, eschewing the
changeups and fastballs on the outer edge of the plate that he has
added to his repertory this season _ bore down to strike out the
side, leaving runners at second and third.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mets scored two runs in the bottom of the first on
five walks by the starter Rick White, Leiter left another runner on
base in the second by inducing White to bounce into a double play.
Even when Leiter allowed his only run, on a double by Mike DiFelice
in the fourth, he came back to strike out Kevin Stocker. It was the
second time he struck out the side.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Leiter said he feels that he is pitching the same as
when he went 16-12 two years ago for the Florida Marlins with the
third-best ERA (2.93) in the league. That was his All-Star year.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter was quick to credit the Mets' defense for much of his
success this season. On the double play, third baseman Edgardo
Alfonzo and second baseman Carlos Baerga both made nifty plays.
Baerga also made a heady play in the sixth when he fielded a
short-hop throw from Piazza to cut down Paul Sorrento, who was
trying to steal second with two out in a 2-1 game.
</P>
<P>
   That play was magnified when Butch Huskey laced a home run in
the Mets' sixth to raise their lead to 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   For Leiter, a major positive has been his ability to click with
Piazza, the All-Star catcher the Mets traded for on May 22.
Leiter's fastball and slider have as much movement as anyone's in
the league, and Piazza conceded that ``he's definitely tough to
catch.'' Yet Leiter, who teamed with Piazza on a four-hit shutout
in the catcher's first game as a Met, is 3-0 with a 1.64 e.r.a.
with him behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Piazza, still nursing a sore left hand from being hit
by a pitch in Boston last Friday night, did not suffer a little
from catching Leiter Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of gritting my teeth every time I caught the
ball,'' he said. ``The hardest part about catching him is when he
wreaks havoc on your hand.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
