<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAN-FRAN-AIRPORT-275&AMP;     06-10 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAN-FRAN-AIRPORT-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO AIRPORT UNDERGOES MAJOR OVERHAUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
(bl) 
 By BOB NORBERG   
 The Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BRUNO, Calif. _ Summer vacationers and business travelers
hurrying through San Francisco International Airport these days are
being confronted with debris, dust and delays as a new
glass-and-steel, six-story terminal with a Disneyland look rises
above a landscape of concrete forms and twisted rebar.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to open in the spring of 2000, the new International
Terminal will double the size of the airport. It will feature a
light-rail shuttle system, new boarding gates for the larger
next-generation jumbo jets, more automobile parking, new sweeping
roadways to Highway 101, which is being widened, and a Bay Area
Rapid Transit commuter rail station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're literally building a new airport on top of the old
airport,'' said Ron Wilson, airport communications director. ``It's
the largest airport project currently in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But the massive $2.4 billion project won't fix the airport's
inadequate runway system, designed in 1930 and responsible for
chronic delays when the weather turns foul, making San Francisco
airport one of the nation's worst for on-time performance.
</P>
<P>
   Solving that problem is the next step. Airport officials hired a
consultant last week to consider how to build a new runway to allow
full operation in bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   The spacious new terminal is designed to handle 12 million
passengers by 2006. One goal is to get arriving travelers off the
plane, through Customs _ set up to handle 5,000 people an hour _
and out the door in 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The new ticket counters will stretch a quarter of a mile long,
almost three times the length of present international terminal
counters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The project is creating its share of disruptions on the ground,
causing some traffic snarls as it funnels cars and buses to the
existing terminals through tunnel-like construction zones and a
confusing web of lanes. The road narrows for taxicabs and shuttle
buses picking up arriving passengers.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, travelers find the construction irritating,
but not a major headache.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easily confusing,'' said Linda Stephens of San Mateo, who
was picking up employees of an accounting firm last week for a
training session. ``If we're a Pacific Rim capital, we need better.
It's been the pits for years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pain in the neck, but what are you going to do?''
commented Mike Martin of Orange County. ``It seems every airport in
the country is expanding right now. It gets so you don't pay
attention to it anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   Construction doesn't seem to pose a major problem for passengers
arriving for flights, but it does cause delays for shuttle buses
and people picking up travelers on the lower roadway, which is
narrower because of debris and heavy equipment parked on it.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said the airport needs the new international terminal to
handle the tremendous growth in overseas travel.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 38 million passengers who passed through San Francisco
International in 1996, 18 percent were traveling overseas, 60
percent of them to Japan and other Pacific Rim nations. The volume
is almost equally divided between tourists and business travelers
from both the United States and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand for international travel has climbed by 10 percent
a year, primarily for Asia and the Pacific Rim, because of the
economy there,'' Wilson said. ``Even European travel was up last
year by 16 percent. That's a trend we see continuing for the next
10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2006, projections are for 12 million international
passengers. Domestic travel, which has been flat, also is expected
to climb, Wilson said, to 39 million domestic passengers by 2006.
In 1996, domestic and international volume was 31 million and 7
million passengers, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travel is becoming easier, people have more disposable income
and the U.S. is a popular destination for international travel,''
Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the increase in passenger demand, another reason behind
the upgrade is that the current international terminal is outmoded.
The current fleet of 400-passenger jumbo jets doesn't even fit the
old-style boarding gates, sticking out past the apron and taking up
1 1/2 spaces. And some aircraft manufacturers are considering
building even bigger, 600-passenger planes.
</P>
<P>
   The new terminal will have room for 26 jumbo jets at the
boarding areas, the ability to handle the baggage from 12 flights
at once, and, at 2 million square feet, is as large as the present
domestic and international terminals combined.
</P>
<P>
   The three-terminal complex is now shaped like a horseshoe and
the new terminal will effectively close the open gap. The existing
international terminal will be used for domestic travelers, along
with the south and north terminals.
</P>
<P>
   The project includes two new parking garages for international
travelers, with 3,000 parking spaces. The present garage has 3,500
short-term and 7,000 long-term parking spots.
</P>
<P>
   A light-rail system will traverse the airport, running at two-to
three-minute intervals between the terminals, the new rental car
area, remote parking lots, and airline maintenance and cargo
facilities. Each of the electric trains can carry 210 people and
run at about 25 mph.
</P>
<P>
   BART, the rapid transit system serving the San Francisco area,
will have a line running from its San Bruno station to the
international terminal, stopping 250 feet away from the ticket
counters.
</P>
<P>
   Some problems are inevitable, but few people were complaining
last week at the airport, where there was the usual lineup of cars,
taxis and shuttles dropping people off and picking them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portland is much worse than this,'' said Carl Loar of Medford,
Ore., referring to a $141 million project to enlarge that airport's
terminal, build new entry roads and cover the parking lot. ``It's a
real mess up there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The dust bothers me more than anything, but it's for a good
cause, so I put up with it,'' said Carol Mason of Tiburon, a United
Airlines flight attendant who flies from San Francisco weekly.
``People understand that we will have something nice in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bob Norberg writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif. This story was distributed by The New York Times News
Service.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
