<P>
   (NYT4) DORCHESTER , England -- June 10, 1998 --
BRITAIN-POUNDSBURY-1, 6-10 -- Poundbury, in England, as designed by
Leon Krier. The planned town is an attempt to create a 21st-century
community that looks as if it grew up over time, with a long linger
in the 18th and 19th centuries when this rural part of southwestern
England Q with its stone villages, thatched white cottages and
twisting lanes Q inspired Thomas Hardy. (Jonathan Player/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- CIR-DVD-DIVX, 6-10 -- Rental
stores are beginning to carry DVD videos. This display was at West
Coast Video in Manhattan. DVD, which stands for digital video disk
or digital versatile disk, was promoted as the next hot thing by
the home electronics industry and movie companies. But its debut
has been widely rated as mildly disappointing or guardedly
promising.(Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- CIR-EYESTRAIN, 7-6 -- Dr.
Gary Tracy, an optometrist in Manhattan, gives a patient a test
that simulates the way people view computer screens. ``Some
people's eyes are thrown off by the fuzziness of letters in a
computer display,'' he says. ``In such cases, the test gives
additional, helpful information.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- June 10, 1998 -- CIR-CONDUCTORS-JACKET, 6-10 -
Conductor of the Boston Pops, Keith Lockhart wearing a
``conductor's jacket.'' The ``conductor's jacket,'' is a piece of
cyberclothing that keeps track of a director's vital signs while he
leads an orchestra. The goal is to collect data that might explain
how Lockhart's rhythm, timing, natural gestures and even emotion
become music. (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
