<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3818 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-10 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICIANS AND THE RIGHT TO KNOW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; N &UR; ancy Reagan &LR;  reveals in the July issue of Vanity Fair that
she stays at home most nights with Alzheimer-stricken  &UR; Ronald  &LR; 
 &UR; Reagan &LR; , ``often reading her White House diaries and watching
videos of state dinners and official trips.'' The magazine says
that the couple are being paid ``in the mid-six figures'' for their
cooperation in the making of a TBS TV miniseries about them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Demonstrating his astute understanding of the American way of
government,  &UR; Dan Quayle &LR;  said on CNN's ``Inside Edition'' last
week, ``Let me just be very clear that the Republican Party will
select a nominee that will beat Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 22nd Amendment prohibits a president from serving more
than two terms, the Quayle scenario seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Roger Orr &LR;  was enlightened to read, in the Auburn Journal,
that  &UR; Lowell Jarvis  &LR; of the Placer County Water Agency board, &LR;  had
spoken his mind last week about a flood control resolution. ``We
want a neutral stance and not jump on the bandwagon when we're
sitting at the crossroads,'' Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DRAMA AT THE TONYS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rosie O'Donnell &LR; , host of the Tony Awards ceremonies broadcast
Sunday night, saved her most potent cracks for the live audience,
when TV viewers were being shown ads. She used unprintable
language, chided  &UR; Charlton Heston &LR;  for assuming the presidency of
the National Rifle Association, &LR;  and said that (the
above-mentioned) Nancy Reagan ``looks like a human Pez dispenser.''
</P>
<P>
   Irish actor  &UR; Tom Murphy &LR; , who won a Tony for best performance by
a featured actor, managed to say the f word twice, in an accent
that censors apparently deemed so charming or so indecipherable
that they left it in for the West Coast broadcast three hours
later.
</P>
<P>
   And  &UR; Sean Connery &LR; , co-producer of the play ``Art,'' was so
upset at having his remarks cut off during the ceremony _ the New
York Post said he'd wanted to thank his wife for discovering the
play in Paris _ and then having to stand in line to get into
dinner, &LR;  that he stormed out before the meal was served. The
Connerys were joined in their early departure by  &UR; Liam Neeson  &LR; and
 &UR; Natasha Richardson &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   P.S.: Elsewhere in the critical world, New York magazine critic
 &UR; John Simon &LR; , renowned for his nastiness, described  &UR; Peter &LR; 
 &UR; Falk &LR; 's performance in a New York production of ``Mr. Peter's
Connections,'' a new play by  &UR; Arthur Miller &LR; , as so boring that
audience members might stay alert by ``trying to guess which of his
eyes is the famous glass one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Carl Nolte &LR;  looked out the window at the San Francisco fog
</P>
<P>
   and determined that elections really do make a difference.
``It's  &UR; Gray Davis  &LR; weather,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Washington Times reported that society bandleader  &UR; Lester &LR; 
 &UR; Lanin &LR;  committed a faux pas the other night at the Washington Opera
Ball when the orchestra struck up ``Dixie.'' ``Members of the
diplomatic corps knew enough to be flabbergasted,'' said the paper,
and ``all the black guests left the dance floor.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cruising through Mountain Bike magazine's Web site,  &UR; Peter &LR; 
 &UR; Sussman &LR;  noticed an ad for an editorial intern. Qualifications for
the job: ``Must have, be on the way to getting or at least be
thinking about a BA in Journalism, Philosophy or English. Proof of
a New Yorker subscription and an IMBA membership for the last 10
years will also suffice.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The National Gay and Lesbian Task Force recently received a
calendar autographed by  &UR; Newt &LR;   &UR; Gingrich &LR; , for contribution to a
fund-raising auction that was held Saturday night. Some time later,
a fax arrived saying the calendar had been sent without an OK from
Gingrich, who ``is not supportive of the ... task force.'' Auction
organizers packaged the fax and the calendar together in an item
they called ``Ire of Newt,'' which fetched $1,900, said the
Washington Post, the highest price of any item auctioned that
night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``It was unbelievable. The women who were around all the time,
not only were they good looking, but they knew what they were
doing. I mean, there was this group, this cult, that was very
technically proficient at everything they were doing. It was the
center of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul Anka, in a Rolling Stone tribute to Frank Sinatra, waxing
sentimental about spending time in Las Vegas with Sinatra and the
Rat Pack and ``all the mob guys'' and the women (mainly
professional) who loved them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
