<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/10/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) FARMINGDALE, N.Y. -- June 10, 1998 --
NY-FIREFIGHTER-FUNERAL, 6-10 -- As friends, family and fellow
firefighters look on at the funeral service for Lt. James
Blackmore, a New York City firefighter who died Friday trying to
rescue a woman, Brian Blackmore, 7, accepts his father's helmet.
Approximately 12 thousand mourners attended the service in
Farmingdale for Blackmore, 48. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- SCI-GIANT-SQUID, 6-10 --
Neil Landman, left, curator of invertebrates at American Museum of
Natural History, and Steve O'Shea, a marine scientist at the
National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research in Wellington,
New Zealand, examine a giant 25-food squid, one of the rarest and
least-understood animals on the planet, which was flown in to New
York on Wednesday. The beast had been frozen solid. ``It's
gorgeous, `` says Landman. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. -- June 10, 1998 -- HOBOKEN-CROONER,
6-10 -- Jimmy Roselli, left, the other Italian-American singer from
Monroe Street in Hoboken, during a recent gig at Caesars Atlantic
City. ``Are we gonna talk about Sinatra or we gonna talk about
me?'' asks Roselli, whose biography, ``Making the Wiseguys Weep:
The Jimmy Roselli Story,'' is due out later this year. ``Don't you
think it's kind of pathetic for someone to be getting noticed when
they're 72 years old? Or by the time the book comes out, 73?''
(Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEWARK, N.J. -- June 10, 1998 -- NJ-COCAINE-SEIZURE,
6-10 -- John Varrone, who heads the United States Customs Service's
Newark office, stands next to barrels at the center of one-ton
rolls of paper. The barrels were among those found to contain
cocaine valued at $40 million. (Chris Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) TORONTO -- June 10, 1998 -- TORONTO-CUBANS, 6-10 -- Only
weeks ago, Guillermo Sambra was imprisoned in Cuba, and now he's
living in Toronto with his wife, Miriam, and their daughter,
Jessica. His father, also in Toronto, jokes that Canada is
Communism's fulfillment. ``I feel like a newborn,'' Sambra says.
``When the plane left Cuba I felt as if a great weight had dropped
off of me.'' (Brian Willer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- June 10, 1998 -- TOBACCO-LOTT, 6-11 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott discussing issues at a recent
press conference. Lott's brother-in-law, Richard Scruggs, is one of
the lawyers who has negotiated the tobacco settlement and stands to
make millions from any legislation. As majority leader, he has
emerged as one of the critical political players who will determine
the fate of anti-tobacco legislation this year. (Paul Hosefros/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MONTGOMERY, Ala. -- June 10, 1998 -- REED-POLITICS, 6-11
-- Ralph Reed, a political consultant, watches the returns on
election night at the headquarters for the republican governor of
Alabama, Fob James. Reed's current challenge is to help James
through a Republican primary runoff on June 30 that centers on
whether the governor has become an embarrassment to his the state
because of his ardent advocacy of causes like prayer in the
schools. (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- June 10, 1998 -- FED-GREENSPAN, 6-10 --
Alan Greenspan with Rep. Jim Saxton, chairman for the Joint
Economic Committee, on Capitol Hill. With a mixture of pride and
puzzlement, Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, Wednesday
declared the economy to be in extraordinarily good shape and
signaled to investors that he saw no immediate need to make a
preemptive strike against inflation by raising interest rates.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- PHILA-DANCE-REVIEW, 6-10 --
A moment in the Philadelphia Dance Company's ``100 Percent Cotton
Natural Fiber'' at the Joyce Theater. The production is the work of
a choreographer with a rich sense of theater and the human
condition, and it was performed with passion and authority by some
of the best modern dancers around today. (Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BEDFORDSHIRE, England -- June 10, 1998 -- KRAFTWERK,
6-10 -- Kraftwerk, which has not appeared in the United States for
17 years, will play in Manhattan on Saturday night at the
Hammerstein Ballroom. The band is shown performing in Bedfordshire
in May. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- WATERTOWER-SCULPTOR-2, 6-10
-- Rachel Whiteread in the Soho studio where her tower, at rear,
was cast. ``Those short, hairy buildings and the intimacy of the
water towers on top of them are what intrigued me,'' says Ms.
Whiteread, who has made a considerable name for herself casting the
interior volumes of familiar objects and structures in materials
like plaster, resin, concrete, wax or rubber. ``Water towers are
like the furniture of New York.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- WATERTOWER-SCULPTOR-1, 6-10
-- Rachel Whiteread's SoHo water tower. Ms. Whiteread is the
English artist who over the last decade has made a considerable
name for herself casting the interior volumes of familiar objects
and structures in materials like plaster, resin, concrete, wax or
rubber. Objects she has cast in this manner have ranged from water
bottles to bathtubs to an entire house. ``Water towers are like the
furniture of New York,'' she says. (Linda Rosier/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) TOENEKA, Indonesia -- June 10, 1998 -- ASIA-ECON-II-2,
6-10 -- Indonesia has been hit by the Asian financial crisis, by a
drought and by political turmoil that has further ravaged the
economy. So the parents of 8-year-old Juliana Aoetpa, left, told
her to drop out of the local elementary school and spend the days
fetching water and gathering food. ``School is free,'' says her
mother, Josisna Banue. ``But the children have to buy a uniform,
and we just couldn't afford it.'' The uniform costs less than $2.
(Nicholas D. Kristof/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- June 10, 1998 -- ASIA-ECON-II-1, 6-10 --
Lamphan Ngaophumin in front of her home with her grandmother,
Samrong Harwiset, who sold her into prositution when the family
needed money. ``The brothel-owner said, 'I bought you, and I can do
whatever I like with you,' `` Lamphan recalls, a tremor in her
voice. ``They locked me up and I thought I would die. Every day I
cried. I tried to slash my wrists, but the cuts weren't deep and
they bandaged me up so that my arms eventually healed.'' (Nicholas
D. Kristof/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- June 10, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 6-10 --
Files are essentially long pieces of hardened steel with parallel
rows of cutting teeth. They are abrading tools, used to grind away
excess material and to smooth the work surface. They are
differentiated by their shape and tooth configuration. (Edward R.
Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- NY-BEDFORD-STREET, 6-10 --
Lawrence Selman's one wish is to live and die at 106 Bedford
Street, in Greenwich Village. He has lived there for 27 years, in a
one-room apartment he currently shares with his dog, Happy, and his
cats, Suzy and Lucky. From left to right, back row: Susan Wyland,
Joe Dorsten, Sally Dill, Alice LaPrelle, Selman (aka Bedford
Street's ``mayor''), Lawrence, Stanley Simbonis, Kathryn Donaldson,
Steve Gould; middle: Alice Elliot, Bill Lavelle, Leslie Sharpe,
Wendy Dubit; front: David Aaron, Catherine Aaron, Bob Oliver.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- HARLEM-SHOWHOUSE-2, 6-10 --
At the Harlem United Show House, detail of a secondhand sofa in the
Josephine Baker room by Wilbert Louis Shaw, covered in
$6.25-per-yard bridal satin from Circle Fabrics in Manhattan.
Despite the loose ends and atmosphere of resigned improvisation,
the show house, which is open through July 3, is a revelation.
(Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- HARLEM-SHOWHOUSE-1, 6-10 --
In Roderick Shade's room at the Harlem United Show House, a French
table, African art and Country Floors tile in a basket-weave
mosaic. Despite the loose ends and atmosphere of resigned
improvisation, the show house, which is open through July 3, is a
revelation. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DORCHESTER , England -- June 10, 1998 --
BRITAIN-POUNDSBURY-2, 6-10 -- Poundbury, in England, is designed by
Leon Krier, shown with Andrew Hamilton, the development director.
The planned town Q a complete city, designed for 5,000 people Q
perfectly embodies the view that modern architecture owes a debt to
the past. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DORCHESTER , England -- June 10, 1998 --
BRITAIN-POUNDSBURY-1, 6-10 -- Poundbury, in England, as designed by
Leon Krier. The planned town is an attempt to create a 21st-century
community that looks as if it grew up over time, with a long linger
in the 18th and 19th centuries when this rural part of southwestern
England Q with its stone villages, thatched white cottages and
twisting lanes Q inspired Thomas Hardy. (Jonathan Player/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- CIR-DVD-DIVX, 6-10 -- Rental
stores are beginning to carry DVD videos. This display was at West
Coast Video in Manhattan. DVD, which stands for digital video disk
or digital versatile disk, was promoted as the next hot thing by
the home electronics industry and movie companies. But its debut
has been widely rated as mildly disappointing or guardedly
promising.(Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 10, 1998 -- CIR-EYESTRAIN, 7-6 -- Dr.
Gary Tracy, an optometrist in Manhattan, gives a patient a test
that simulates the way people view computer screens. ``Some
people's eyes are thrown off by the fuzziness of letters in a
computer display,'' he says. ``In such cases, the test gives
additional, helpful information.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- June 10, 1998 -- CIR-CONDUCTORS-JACKET, 6-10 -
Conductor of the Boston Pops, Keith Lockhart wearing a
``conductor's jacket.'' The ``conductor's jacket,'' is a piece of
cyberclothing that keeps track of a director's vital signs while he
leads an orchestra. The goal is to collect data that might explain
how Lockhart's rhythm, timing, natural gestures and even emotion
become music. (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
