<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA CONVINCING METS HE KNOWS HOW TO CATCH  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLAIRE SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would not seem that a player of Mike Piazza's stature would
need to be reinvented. Yet since joining the Mets on May 22, Piazza
is happily using the change of scenery to also change the
perception of who and what he is.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, a perennial All-Star as a Los Angeles Dodger because of
his ability as a hitter, has clearly made strides in his three
weeks with the Mets in convincing people that he knows what he is
doing behind the plate as well.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Piazza worked with Al Leiter through a six-inning,
nine-strikeout effort in a 3-2 victory over the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays, 11 days after he helped guide Leiter to 10 strikeouts against
the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times in the 13 games Piazza has caught as a Met, the
opposition has scored three runs or fewer. Those seven games
include three shutouts. The first shutout came in Piazza's first
game with the Mets on May 23, when Leiter defeated the Brewers,
3-0. The most recent came on Monday against Tampa Bay, when Rick
Reed flirted with a perfect game for six and two-thirds innings
before settling for a three-hit, 3-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shook him off only once and only because he wanted me to,''
Reed said. ``All I ever heard was that he's a great hitter who
can't catch, but I tell you what, he's really busted his butt to
learn everyone, every pitch that they throw. He's done a great
job.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that Piazza has inherited pitchers with more control of
their repertories than the lively, undisciplined arms of the young
Los Angeles Dodger staff had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our staff is one that takes to a guy like Mike really well,''
Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``He's a big target. He's well
prepared and they give it to him in the zone that he's looking
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, not every catcher converts such opportunities with ease.
``In my opinion, a guy who is not a good defensive catcher takes
pitches that are strikes and makes them balls by the way he catches
them,'' Valentine said. ``On the flip side, the good guy takes
those pitches that are borderline and makes them strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, said Valentine, ``doesn't do the former and definitely
does the latter.'' And Piazza is not only framing pitches and
throwing out runners (6 of 12), but he is also calling games
without fear of passed balls or wild pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid one bit to throw a curveball in the dirt,''
Bobby Jones said. ``I have the confidence that he's going to block
it. That's something a pitcher likes.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter is not afraid to throw his slider, a tough pitch that can
also veer off course. Piazza called it often Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows it's a strength of mine and he's thinking with me,''
Leiter said.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza left the game after eight innings, partly because the
left hand struck by a Pedro Martinez fastball last week is still
sore, and he said later: ``I was kind of gritting my teeth every
time I caught the ball, but I just wanted to get on his page.''
</P>
<P>
   This speaks to Piazza's obvious effort to learn. ``I had the
impression that being the hitter that he is, when he gets into the
dugout the pitcher is some guy from a foreign land, but the pitcher
is the guy that he's sitting with,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Reed added: ``He talks catching, he talks pitching, he talks
about how he's going to approach the hitters the next inning. Where
he got the bad rap, I don't have any idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who has been slammed by former teammates like Brett
Butler and Ramon Martinez, is not only flattered by such praise,
but genuinely relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously you're only human and you're going to hear it,'' the
catcher said of the criticism. ``So it's good to turn the page and
start a new chapter in your career. And no one here really listened
to anything. They just said, let him come in here and see how it is
to work with him. That's all you can ask for, as a professional, as
a person. What these guys did shows how much maturity there is on
this club.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets will not claim that they always assumed Piazza's
catching skills would make the transition seamless. Asked whether
he initially felt any trepidation about Piazza coming aboard,
Valentine replied: ``Yes. Originally I was concerned when I first
heard about a chance of this happening. And then I made inquiries
to a couple of people I trust and they said don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza is hardly the only catcher who has had to prove he can
catch. In Philadelphia, it was said that Bob Boone couldn't catch a
cold, but he went on to win praise as the quintessential man behind
the plate in Kansas City. And Gary Carter, a slugger like Piazza,
also had perceptions to overcome when he joined the Mets in 1985,
said Ed Lynch, a former Mets pitcher who is now the general manager
of the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he joined the Mets we heard he was an offensive
catcher,'' Lynch said. ``But we found him to be an outstanding
catcher who happened to hit three-run home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of Piazza, whom the Cubs pursued before the Marlins
sent him to the Mets? ``When you're that good, people are always
looking to knock you down, so they look at your defense,'' Lynch
said. ``I think it's an undeserved knock.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, do the Mets, who seem happy to help Piazza prove it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
