<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3834 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-STJOHNS-NYT &LR;      06-10 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHNS CLOSE TO SIGNING JARVIS AS COACH  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After several days of intense and sometimes acrimonious
negotiations, St. John's appeared on the verge of reaching
agreement with Mike Jarvis, its No. 1 choice to be the new head
basketball coach, despite several sticking points that remained to
be worked out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The representative for Jarvis, Robert Ades, left New York
Wednesday and headed back to Washington, D.C., where Jarvis is the
coach for George Washington University. And while Ades expressed
annoyance at St. Johns' negotiating stance, it was not expected to
scuttle a deal that would bring Jarvis to the Big East school.
</P>
<P>
   Some contract matters still had to be worked out, and language
that would govern the new coach's behavior had become an issue, as
well as a desire by the university to ensure that Jarvis would not
soon depart for another college job or the National Basketball
Association. Still, officials at St. John's and George Washington
maintained Wednesday night that Jarvis is eager to accept the job
and that St. John's is equally eager to have him.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's officials termed the problems as not being
deal-breakers, and that an announcement could come as early as
Thursday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to an associate of Jarvis, the two sides agreed on
money, believed to be in excess of $800,000 per year for a
seven-year contract. Jarvis would replace Fran Fraschilla, who was
dismissed last month.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview before he left for Washington, Ades
said he was insulted and irritated by what he felt were
unreasonable demands on the part of the university. St. John's,
embarrassed by the problems involved in the dismissal of
Fraschilla, has wanted a behavior clause in the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been embarrassed before,'' Ades said, referring to
the school's problems with Fraschilla this year, as well as the
circus-like search for a coach two years ago in which Fraschilla
got the job only after other, more prominent coaches rejected it.
``They want to make sure that it does not happen again. But that is
why you hire Mike Jarvis.''
</P>
<P>
   He credited St. John's attorney, Ray McGuire, with keeping the
negotiations on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray McGuire, is one of the classiest, most knowledgeable
attorneys that there is in the field of labor relations today,''
Ades said. ``He is trying to drag St. John's into the '90s world of
the business of college athletics kicking and screaming. If this
deal gets done, it will only be because of him.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials would not comment publically on the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But while hurt feelings kept the happy faces on hold at St.
John's, the school still wants Jarvis and Jarvis wants the job, so
the two sides expect to plow forward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was not money that stood in the way as negotiations came to a
halt Wednesday afternoon. St. John's, which was offended by
Fraschilla's flirtations with Arizona State University, wanted
assurances of Jarvis' behavior and his loyalty to the program.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis, who has spent eight years at George Washington
University after five years at Boston University, has never had a
losing season on the court and has an unblemished record off of it.
But St. John's may be wary about his willingness to speak to other
schools about their coaching vacancies; he did so this year with
the University of Michigan and University of Virginia, and last
year with Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   But officials on each side of the negotiations believe the deal
will get done because Jarvis wants it to. People close to Jarvis
say he believes he has gone as far as he can at George Washington
and has a chance to contend for a national title at St. John's. In
addition, New York would provide a high-profile stage.
</P>
<P>
   Ades admitted that he advised Tim Welsh to spurn Providence's
offer to him, but Welsh took the job anyway, and that it was his
job only to advise and the decision would be Jarvis'. ``It's just
sad that this is where we're at,'' Ades said. ``We all sat down and
all wanted the same thing. Whether it happens, I don't know.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. John's flirtations with Jarvis actually began two years ago
when he conducted preliminary discussions with Manetta for the job
that eventually went to Fraschilla. But at that time,
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
