<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DRAGGING-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACTION TO HORRIBLE CRIME: SADNESS, SHOCK, SILENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The courthouse square in this East Texas town
seemed almost eerily quiet on this sweltering day. Few people
milled about and those who did seemed hesitant to talk to outsiders
Wednesday about the horrible crime that had brought a swarm of TV
trucks to the town and would bring the Rev. Jesse Jackson on
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Ann Reed, a cashier at the Quik Mart at the edge of town,
said few talked of the brutal slaying of James Byrd Jr., a black
man dragged to death behind a pickup truck Sunday, and the three
local white men who have been charged with the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad situation,'' said Ms. Reed, who is white. ``I don't
think anybody should be treated that way, I don't care what color
they are. Not even an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she had heard there might be whites in her town who, as
is suspected of the men charged, sympathized with white supremacist
groups, she only looked down. Asked if the killing surprised her,
she said, ``Nothing surprises me anymore,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with murder are Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, of Sulphur
Springs, and Shawn Allen Berry and John William King, both 23 of
Jasper. The three were held without bond in the Jasper County Jail,
and the local prosecutors said Wednesday that would try to seek the
death penalty against them.
</P>
<P>
   King's father, Ronald King, also a resident of Jaspar, released
a hand-written letter apologizing for his son's actions. He started
it by writing, ``My sympathy goes out to the Byrd family. There is
no reason for a person to take the life of another, and to take it
in such a manner is beyond any kind of reasoning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts me deeply to know that a boy I raised and considered
to be the most loved boy I knew could find it in himself to take a
life,'' the elder King said. ``This deed cannot be undone, but I
hope we can all find it our hearts to go forward in peace and with
love for all. Let us find in our hears love for our fellow man.
Hate can only destroy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I want to say I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton called the killing of Byrd
shocking and outrageous. He said the residents here ``must join
together across racial lines to demonstrate that an act of evil
like this is not what this country is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The president continued, ``I think we've all been touched by it,
and I can only imagine that virtually everyone who lives there is
in agony at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   At the town's beautiful old courthouse, built in 1889, with a
white gazebo in front, Neva Alexander, the administrative assistant
to the county judge, said there had been a lot of talk among the
8,000 residents in the East Texas town, with its hills and lush
vegetation looks more like the South than the parched, flat plains
found elsewhere in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks it's horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, she thinks it was an isolated act of violence.
Agreeing with her was a city councilman from Vidor, another East
Texas town that drew headlines several years when the Ku Klux Klan
rallied against the integration of the town's housing projects, who
was in Jasper on business. The councilman, David Slaughter,
defended his town from the news reports that have brought up what
happened there when talking about the killing in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the next thing, we'll have something happen in El Paso
and someone will stand before a camera and say, `I'm here reporting
live from El Paso, 850 miles from Vidor.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Vidor, Jasper is a town without widespread racial problems,
Slaughter said. ``You can not stereotype a city or a county or a
community because of the actions of some people.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the whites, as well as some blacks, seemed to believe
the crime did not reflect a deeper problem.
</P>
<P>
   But at an afternoon prayer meeting, held at the church the dead
man's family attend and featuring Rev. Jesse Jackson as a speaker,
blacks were less certain the murder was an isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It done uncovered a lot of things that should have been
uncovered before,'' said Herbert Spikes, a 58-year-old Wal-Mart
employee in Jasper. ``Maybe it took this to bring it out. I believe
it will get better now that it's exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Truman Boatner, 48, told how he and some black friends were
attacked about 14 years ago when they went to swim at one of the
lakes that dot the area and lure champion bass fishermen. ``I don't
go up there no more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Greater New Bethel Baptist Church, Jackson arrived to
a standing ovation after he first paid a brief visit on Byrd's
family. Jackson said he had talked with President Clinton. He said
he had also talked with U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno, who told
him she had dispatched civil rights officials to Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Even basketball star Dennis Rodman, originally from Texas, had
gotten involved, Jackson said, offering to pay the costs of Byrd's
funeral, which Jackson promised to attend Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time like this, we are breathless,'' he told the crowd of
about 250 squeezed into the country church, with perhaps another
200 sweating in 93-degree heat outside. ``We can't quite explain it
or understand it. We are hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
