<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANGE AT RAINBOW ROOM
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The family that owns Harry Cipriani, the restaurant
in the Sherry-Netherland Hotel on Fifth Avenue, will take over the
Rainbow Room on Jan. 1, the company that manages Rockefeller Center
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the Rainbow Room, the famous Art Moderne
restaurant on the 65th floor of 30 Rockefeller Plaza, became the
subject of intense speculation about who would be named to run the
restaurant after the landlord, Tishman Speyer Properties, decided
last year that it could bring in more revenue if it had a trendier
image.
</P>
<P>
   Guiseppe Cipriani, the chairman of Cipriani Holding Group, said
his company would pay about $4 million in annual rent for the
restaurant under the terms of the 15-year lease, which was signed
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel thrilled,'' Cipriani said. ``It's an American landmark,
and I think we can do a great job there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cipriani said that plans for the restaurant, which may include
expanding into space on the 67th floor that is currently being used
for storage, had been discussed in only general terms and that the
details would be worked out over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected the restaurant to shut down for one month in
January while the kitchen is renovated.
</P>
<P>
   At the Rainbow Room, the Ciprianis will replace Joseph Baum, a
veteran restaurateur, and his partner, David Emil, who have run the
Rainbow Room since 1985, after spending $20 million to renovate it.
Since then, the restaurant's gross income has grown from $8 million
to $32 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a wonderful time operating the Rainbow Room,'' Emil
said, ``and we wish them the best.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   INSIGNIA TO BUY COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Insignia Financial Group announced Wednesday that its commercial
real estate services unit, Insignia/ESG, had agreed to acquire the
commercial real estate businesses of Jackson-Cross Co., one of the
country's oldest commercial real estate services firms and the
market leader in the greater Philadelphia region.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase price was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Insignia Financial Group is the largest manager of multifamily
residential properties in the United States, with a nationwide
portfolio of about 275,000 units, including approximately 59,000
condominium and cooperative units in the New York metropolitan
area.
</P>
<P>
   The company has acquired nine other full-service commercial real
estate firms in the last 16 months. It also owns Realty One of
Cleveland, Ohio, a brokerage company.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson-Cross traces its roots back more than 120 years and has
been responsible for some of the largest real estate transactions
in the Philadelphia region in recent years, including 1.25 million
square feet for Cigna Corp. in Philadelphia and 675,000 square feet
for the Southeastern Pennsylvania Transit Authority in
Philadelphia. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
