<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYING IN MANHATTAN: EXPENSIVE PROPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
 NY-HOTEL-PRICES-580&AMP;ADD-NYT (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
(dc) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Looking for a hotel room in Manhattan? You have
plenty of options. You could book weeks in advance and pay $300 or
so a night for a room at a modern midtown high-rise like the Crowne
Plaza. If you're willing to pay a bit more _ say, $500 a night on
average _ you could probably get something with less of a hassle at
the Four Seasons or the Pierre. Or you could do what a growing
number of visitors are forced to do: stay in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel market in Manhattan, the most expensive in the nation
and fresh off a record year in 1997, continued to tighten in the
first quarter of 1998, with the average cost of a night's stay
creeping closer to $200.
</P>
<P>
   The market has become so expensive that in the past 18 months
five hotels _ the Lowell, the St. Regis and the Carlyle, as well as
the Pierre and the Four Seasons _ began charging an average rate of
$500. No other city in the nation has even a single hotel with an
average rate so high, industry experts said.
</P>
<P>
   And even as prices rise, it is still difficult to find a room in
New York unless it is booked far in advance. That fact has forced
some visitors to stay in New Jersey or bypass the city altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot find a decent hotel room anywhere on Manhattan, it
seems, for less than a fortune,'' said Alan Bennett of Sydney,
Australia, who was planning to come to the city in August. ``We
have searched data base after data base and rung hotel chains'
reservations centers, all to no avail.''
</P>
<P>
   The average price of a room in Manhattan rose to $189.70 for the
first quarter of the year, according to preliminary figures from
the Coopers &AMP; Lybrand Lodging Research Network. That's a 13.9
percent leap over the $166.58 average room price for the first
quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Occupancy rates are nearing records, too. For the first three
months of the year, which are among the slowest for the industry in
New York, hotels were 80.5 percent filled, according to Coopers &AMP;
Lybrand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
