<SLUG> BC-CREDITSUISSE-BRAZIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS-AMERICAN GROUP BUYS A TOP BRAZILIAN BANK
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Credit Suisse First Boston has bought Brazil's
leading investment bank, making the Swiss-American group the
largest underwriter and stock trader in that hotly competitive
emerging market, the companies announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of First Boston, Credit Suisse's investment banking
unit, said the $675 million cash-and-stock purchase of Garantia SA,
a private partnership, makes them by far the biggest investment
bank in Brazil, Latin America's largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition intensifies the race for Latin American
dominance among investment banks, which have cut fees hard in an
effort to secure a steady flow of deals from Brazil and other
countries in the region. Merrill Lynch, the American investment
bank, earlier this week won a mandate to underwrite the $6 billion
privatization of Brazil's national oil company, but accepted fees
of just 0.45 percent of the total transaction, a new low in that
market.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hester, Credit Suisse First Boston's chief financial
officer, said banks were ``cutting their throats'' to win top
underwriting assignments in Latin America. ``When you consider all
the man-hours poured into some deals, there is very little money to
be made,'' he said in an interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Hester said, First Boston's move to become a
dominant competitor in Brazil will allow it to profit from smaller
but more lucrative deals. For example, many of the major
privatization deals, like the one to bring the oil company
Petrobras to market, produce limited returns but help broaden the
market for banks that stay behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``By taking a deep leadership position, we can be more
successful and profitable there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In emerging markets, many banks tend to focus solely on the
biggest cross-border underwriting assignments, or stocks that
foreign investors might want to buy, said Raphael Soifer,
securities-company analyst with Brown Brothers Harriman. ``But
Brazil is proving itself to be a big market, and it makes sense to
build up your local presence there as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garantia put itself up for auction after it suffered $100
million in trading losses late last year, losses that were
associated with the Asian financial crisis. The sale attracted many
of the world's top investment banks, including Goldman, Sachs and
Morgan Stanley, both of which held talks with Garantia, officials
of the Brazilian bank told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Garantia is part of the Credit Suisse Group's
effort to expand its presence in all areas of investment and
commercial banking and insurance. It paid $10 billion last year to
buy Winterthur Insurance Co. of Switzerland. First Boston snapped
up some Asian and European operations of BZW, a British-based
investment bank, from Barclays.
</P>
<P>
   Like all investment banks, First Boston has sought to expand its
presence in Latin America, Hester said. But the bank found that it
was ``unlikely to get ahead'' of rivals like Merrill Lynch,
Goldman, Sachs and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter if it continued to
rely on internal growth instead of acquisitions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garantia, of Sao Paulo, was founded in 1971 by Jorge Paulo
Lemann, a Harvard-educated former tennis star. It has 320
employees, assets of $5 billion and a top-three share of Brazil's
equity and debt issuance and mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of Credit Suisse's deal, it will pay Garantia's
managing partners $200 million in cash and $475 million in stock
over three years, but could pay more if Garantia employees meet
profit goals. The purchase price amounts to 1.68 times Garantia's
book value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
