<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-COMPLAINTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLAINTS AGAINST NEW YORK POLICE RISE
</HEADLINE>
   (dc) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Civilian complaints against New York City police
officers went up by 20 percent during the first five months of the
year, according to statistics released Wednesday by the Civilian
Complaint Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   The review board _ the independent agency that monitors and
investigates accusations of police misconduct _ logged 2,176
complaints against police officers from January through May. During
the same period last year, the board reported 1,818 complaints,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the review board reported a 21 percent decrease
in civilian complaints during the first five months of the year,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Police Commissioner Howard Safir and Mel
Barkan, the chairman of the review board, held a news conference to
trumpet the figures. This year, the figures showing an increase in
complaints were released without fanfare at the board's monthly
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's troubling,'' said Norman Siegel, the executive director
of the New York Civil Liberties Union. ``For most of 1997, we heard
glowing reports from the Giuliani administration about how the
numbers from the CCRB were decreasing. But now that complaints are
going up, we don't hear anything. I guess it is what you call
selective commentary. It makes it clear that they were using the
numbers last year for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the figures at his weekly news conference, Safir
said that the number of complaints had been higher since the Abner
Louima case brought increased attention to the issue of police
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always concerned about increases in civilian complaints,''
Safir said. ``My view is that we work very hard to reduce them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
