<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-PAKISTAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT SAYS WHEAT MUST BE INCLUDED IN SANCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Washington wheat growers are bracing for the loss
of their most important market after the Justice Department
recommended Wednesday that Pakistan be prevented from buying
Northwest wheat as punishment for testing nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash, said that National Security Adviser
Sandy Berger, U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky and
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman all told her Wednesday that the
agricultural credits Pakistan uses to buy American wheat must be
prohibited under the sanctions the U.S. is required to impose on
the South Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
   Berger told Murray that only a change in U.S. law would save the
Pakistani market for Northwest wheat growers, the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the Washington state congressional delegation
are attempting to change the law to aid the wheat farmers. A House
committee Wednesday approved a measure sponsored by Rep. George
Nethercutt, R-Wash., to cancel the portion of the sanctions that
affects agricultural commodity credit programs. Murray and Sen.
Slade Gorton, R-Wash., plan to introduce similar measures in a
Senate committee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is of critical importance to the wheat industry, which
ranks second only to airplanes in its size as an export commodity
from Washington state. The Pakistani market for Northwest wheat is
about $250 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several years Pakistan has imported as much as 37
percent of the wheat grown in Washington state. The loss of the
market promises to devastate an industry already reeling from
record-low prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our wheat farmers are really hurting this year, with wheat
prices extremely low because of the Asian currency problem,''
Murray said. ``If we lose this market, that is more than one-third
of our wheat we won't have a market for. Eastern Washington farmers
should not be bearing the brunt of this nation's sanctions against
Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the State Department and Justice Department
insisted that no final decision has been made on whether the
sanctions against Pakistan will include the agricultural credit
program Pakistan uses to buy American wheat. But Murray, Gorton and
Nethercutt all said they received calls from the Justice Department
informing them that lawyers there believe the U.S. sanctions law
clearly covers those credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Justice has concluded that the sanctions do
apply to agriculture,'' said Nethercutt, whose district includes
southeast Washington where wheat farmers are concentrated. But
Nethercutt said he is still hopeful that someone in the Clinton
administration will override the Justice Department, saying ``they
have some discretion ... and it's still fluid.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton called on the Clinton administration to publicly announce
the details of its sanctions, but said ``It's very possible that
these sanctions will have a devastating impact on Washington's
wheat industry.'' He said the sanctions are a failure, because they
did not deter Pakistan and India from testing nuclear weapons, and
now, ``Instead of deterring nuclear testing, these unilateral
sanctions will only succeed in hurting U.S. workers, farmers, and
families _ and most notably our Washington state wheat growers.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a 1994 law, never before implemented. It requires
the imposition of broad sanctions against nations that test nuclear
weapons. Last month, India and Pakistan each conducted tests.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions affect development assistance; military sales and
exchanges; trade in specified technology; U.S. financial
assistance, guarantees, and credits; and loans and credits by U.S.
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Food products are exempt from the sanctions, but credits are
not. That left open the question of whether credits used to buy
food might be affected. The Justice Department's interpretation
Wednesday was that they must be included in the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Congress changes the law on sanctions, Pakistan may be
so poor or so angry that it will choose not to purchase U.S. wheat,
most of which comes from the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``While our wheat growers stand at risk of losing this vital
market, their counterparts in Canada, Europe and Australia are
celebrating the shortsightedness of the U.S. administration,''
Gorton said. ``They are happy to step in and fill the place of
American exporters in Pakistan. The Pakistani government and people
will turn to nations that are not criticizing their actions and
their imports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus and Canadian or Australian grain farmers will benefit
from U.S. actions, while Boeing and our wheat growers will be left
out in the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters even worse, the wheat farmers face the prospect
of Australia, their chief competitor in Pakistan, taking advantage
of the U.S. departure from the Pakistani market to raise prices
there and then lower them elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australia will have a market given to them by means of our
sanctions, and then they can charge a little higher price, take the
profit, and use it to lower the price against us where we go head
to head,'' said Thomas Mick, chief executive officer of the
Washington Wheat Commission. ``We're very disappointed, and we
really don't know what our next plan of action is going to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
