<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-BUDGET-265&AMP;ADD-NY     06-10 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-BUDGET-265&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI CUTS $196 MILLION FROM NYC BUDGET; VALLONE FOWS FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wielding a rarely used power of his office, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani vetoed more than $196 million from the city budget
Wednesday, asserting that the money _ from $727 for the Staten
Island Historical Society to $10 million for legal aid _
represented the reckless spending of a City Council confused in a
season of budget surplus and political ambition.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the appearances of being extreme measures in a tense
budget dispute, the vetoes are largely symbolic, as Council leaders
were quick to point out. Council Speaker Peter Vallone said that
the Council will vote soon, probably as early as Thursday, to
restore the mayor's cuts by easily overriding his vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the vetoes had aides on both sides of City Hall
frantically putting the mayor's actions in self-serving context.
The mayor was portrayed as the fiscally prudent leader guarding
against Democratic profligacy, while the speaker became the friend
to the poor and forgotten, striking back against the Snidely
Whiplash of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Peter Vallone looks at himself in the mirror, he should
see that the budget he has had the Council pass takes us back to
the huge deficits of the past, when we should be holding the line
on spending,'' said Randy Mastro, the deputy mayor for operations.
</P>
<P>
   To which Vallone responded: ``The next time I see a working
mother rushing home from work to pick up her child, a college
student working three jobs to pay his tuition or a child suffering
from severe asthma, I will remember that these are the people Mayor
Giuliani is cutting funding from.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Such are the taunts of a fight that centers on the $34 billion
budget that the Council passed unilaterally last week. This act of
defiant independence marked the first time since the City Charter
was revised in 1989 that city leaders had not adopted a budget in
consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Council leaders say the dispute centers on the the mayor's
insistence that the speaker drop his call for a referendum on
whether the city should finance a stadium in Manhattan for the
Bronx-based New York Yankees. The mayor's aides say that dueling
tax cut proposals also figured in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   One of the options available to the mayor after the Council's
act of boldness is to use his line-item veto power to slash any
additional spending that the Council tacked on to the executive
budget he proposed in late April.
</P>
<P>
   And he exercised that option with a vengeance Wednesday, cutting
$196 million from $233 million in additional Council spending, and
$315 million more from the $345 million that the Council added to
city's $5 billion capital budget.
</P>
<P>
   He cut $18 million from the Administration for Children
Services, including money for day-care programs, on the ground that
the budget already provided sufficient financing _ the same reason
he gave for cutting $1 million for a summer youth program.
</P>
<P>
   He cut $7.3 million from the Board of Education because, he
said, the programs it would finance and the supplies it would buy,
including maps and furniture, would be covered by the board's $250
million surplus.
</P>
<P>
   He cut $6.6 million set aside for various nonprofit
organizations: $718,000 for the Women's Prison Association; $2
million for the Neighborhood Defender Service; $116,500 from the
Gay and Lesbian Anti-Violence Program. The stated reason for all
was the same: ``The Executive Budget maintains adequate funding for
this type of service. The City Council's addition is an unwarranted
increase which does not include sufficient justification.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's aides argued that the Council seemed at times to be
using city money to finance the kind of grandiose gestures that
come with a $2 billion surplus. City Budget Director Joseph Lhota
said the Council set aside $10 million for the Legal Aid Society _
even though, he said, the society's representatives asked the
Council for only $6 million while appearing before a Council
finance committee earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Legal Aid Society disputed that contention
Wednesday, and supplied a copy of written testimony in which Daniel
Greenberg, the organization's executive director, told a Council
committee in May: ``We therefore reiterate our need for at least
$10 million from the City Council for our criminal defense
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Bath, the organization's spokeswoman, said, ``I'm very
confused that the mayor's office is saying we didn't want the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's aides also said Giuliani sought to trim the fat from
what Mastro called ``Peter's pork.'' The phrase refers to Vallone,
whose gubernatorial candidacy has been cited by the mayor's office
as the primary reason for the Council's largess.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the mayor went after anything that smacked of being a
``member item,'' which is money earmarked to meet the individual
needs of Council members. The term is so politically charged that
the Council now prefers the phrase ``local initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the biggest theme that runs through the
budget: we've vetoed all of the member items,'' Giuliani said.
``There are many things in this budget that are disguised as
programmatic expenses that are really member items for a particular
member to have something for himself or herself for a political
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he cut $5.5 million from various programs in
hospitals around the city _ from $1 million for a ``breast cancer
initiative'' to $250,000 for an ``asthma outreach'' contract with
the Caribbean Women's Health Association at Kings Hospital in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation for each cut was the same: ``This appears to be
a member item for which insufficient justification is provided.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani still managed to surprise Council members with his veto
choices. For example, he did not challenge the Council's decision
to restore some $15 million that he previously cut for the city's
libraries, although he did veto $7 million in enhancements _ which
the mayor said ``look to me like member items'' _ that the Council
had added to the library budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
