<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, JUNE 11
</HEADLINE>
  Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-DRUGS-U.N.-NYT (moved on Tuesday, June 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 9,
about an open letter to the United Nations Secretary General, Kofi
Annan, asserting that the global war on drugs is causing more harm
than drug abuse itself, misspelled the surname of the organizer of
the letter. He is Ethan Nadelmann, not Nadlemann.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-MCCARTNEY-NYT (moved on Monday, April 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, April 20,
about the obituary of Linda McCartney on April 20 misstated her
college background. She attended only the University of Arizona,
not Sarah Lawrence College as well. The obituary also misstated the
given name of her first husband in some copies. He was Melvin See,
not Bob. The errors were pointed out in e-mail received from a
reader yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SOLAR-NEUTRINOS-NYT (moved on Monday, June 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, June 8,
about elusive subatomic particles from the sun omitted several
words from a sentence about neutron decay. The sentence should have
read, ``Then physicists found that a process called beta decay, in
which a neutron spits out an electron and turns into a proton,
defies the law of conservation of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-INDIA-FASHION-NYT (moved on Friday, June 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, June 5,
about the popularity of visits to India by high-profile people from
the worlds of fashion, entertainment and society referred
incorrectly to the Indian guru Sai Baba. He did not die in 1982. He
is 71, has devotees worldwide and lives mainly at Prasanthi
Nilayam, a large ashram in South India near the town of
Puttaparthi, where he was born.
</P>
</TEXT>
