<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRAHAN, BURDEN GETS MARYLAND ACCOUNT
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland Department of Business and Economic Development
said Wednesday that it had named Trahan, Burden &AMP; Charles to
promote Maryland tourism as well as Maryland as a business
location. The five-year contract, with total billings estimated at
$35 million, had been handled by the Baltimore office of W.B. Doner
&AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Thomas, a spokeswoman for the department in Baltimore,
said the decision came after a three-month mandated review that had
been narrowed to Trahan, Burden and two other finalists in
Baltimore: Campbell Group and Gray Kirk/Van Sant.
</P>
<P>
   ADVERTISERS SHIFT COMPENSATION METHOD
</P>
<P>
   A majority of American advertisers have shifted from
compensating their agencies based on the traditional billings
method, according to a study conducted by the Association of
National Advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published as part of the 11th edition of the
association's survey, ``Trends in Agency Compensation,'' was based
on responses of 113 member companies. It showed that use of
billings-based commissions, both fixed rate and sliding scale,
declined from 61 percent in 1994 to 35 percent in 1997. Paying
agencies by what is known as labor-based compensation grew from 35
percent in 1994 to 53 percent in 1997. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
