<HEADER>
A3852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEATH-JUROR-NYT &LR;      06-10 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEATH-JUROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUROR EXPLAINS TORTUOUS PATH TO VOTING FOR DEATH SENTENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There had been three days of arguing and occasional
shouting, three days in which the 12 jurors in the Brooklyn murder
trial of Darrel Harris had agonized over the death penalty. By
Friday, 10 jurors wanted a death sentence. Eleanore Walker, a
registered nurse, was one of two who did not.
</P>
<P>
   Even as other jurors vacillated, Ms. Walker said in interviews
this week, her opinion did not sway until the close of
deliberations Friday. The arguments had grown so fierce, she said,
that several jurors complained of headaches. One woman's lips began
to swell. To ease the tension, Ms. Walker asked for a moment of
meditation. And in the silence, she said, she felt a stirring
within herself that she believed was God granting her a
``peacefulness,'' if not an answer.
</P>
<P>
   She found the answer the following morning. When she awoke
Saturday, Ms. Walker said, she opened her Bible and came to the
Book of Galatians. ``It said something about how the wicked must be
destroyed,'' she recalled. ``Everything I read pointed to
wickedness, destruction, reaping and repenting. I took it as a
strong sign of what my decision should be. ``It helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later Saturday, the fourth and final day of deliberation,
Ms. Walker became the last person to change her vote, and the jury
of seven women and five men unanimously sentenced Harris to death
for the slayings of three people during the 1996 robbery of a
Brooklyn social club. If his sentence is upheld on appeal, Harris,
40, could become the first person executed in New York state since
1963.
</P>
<P>
   Through interviews with Ms. Walker _ who had avoided contact
with the press since the trial ended _ and with another female
juror, a West Indian immigrant who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, a picture of the jury deliberations emerged: Four days
of anguish, of fierce arguments and finger pointing, and more than
20 votes until, finally, a decision was reached. They sat around a
long rectangular table in a jury room of the state Supreme Court
Building in Brooklyn, sometimes crying, sometimes shouting. ``We
felt the weight of just the word `death,''' Ms. Walker said.
Perhaps, the two jurors said, their decision might have been
different had Harris testified during the sentencing phase.
Perhaps, they agreed, the defense erred by calling Harris' mother
instead. She seemed honest and sympathetic, they said, not someone
that defense lawyers had described as abusive toward her son.
</P>
<P>
   That Ms. Walker, who cast the critical final vote, traced her
change of heart to a religious epiphany is not unusual, experts
say. William Bowers, who heads the Capital Jury Project, which
since 1991 has interviewed 1,000 death penalty jurors in 15 states,
said that jurors burdened by their responsibility will on occasion
invoke what they perceive to be the will of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly that it relieves them of a measure of personal
responsibility for the decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sentencing deliberations began Wednesday, June 3. The jury
could choose between death or life without the possibility of
parole. Crime scene photographs documented the brutal nature of the
Dec. 7, 1996, slayings at Club Happiness in Bedford-Stuyvesant,
Brooklyn: Harris had shot two men in the back of the head, and when
he ran out of bullets, he stabbed a woman, Evelyn Davis, in the
back as she pleaded for mercy and cried, ``I have five babies.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first votes revealed a divided jury. Ms. Walker said
she and four others voted for life without parole; five voted for
death, and two remained undecided. She said the jury repeatedly
weighed the aggravating factors of the slayings versus the
mitigating factors presented by defense lawyers _ that Harris had
``snapped'' mentally, that he had been beaten as a child and that
he was addicted to drugs and alcohol. To show good character,
defense lawyers cited a 1986 incident in which Harris, a guard at a
Brooklyn jail, saved the life of another guard during an inmate
uprising.
</P>
<P>
   But one by one, the jurors began eliminating the mitigating
factors. Listening to the testimony of Harris' mother, Ms. Walker
and the other juror discounted defense efforts to portray him as an
abused child. ``I am from the West Indies,'' said the other juror.
``I was disciplined as a child, and it didn't affect me. She just
disciplined her children because, as she said, she wanted them to
do better than her.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Ms. Walker and the other juror said those holding out for
life argued that Harris might find spiritual redemption and rebirth
in prison. But both also were frustrated that he did not testify
during sentencing. ``I wanted to hear at least, `I'm sorry that it
happened,''' Ms. Walker said. ``Something that showed some
remorse.''
</P>
<P>
   The second juror said she and others noticed that Harris often
smiled during the trial. ``Several times we saw him laugh at
people, and we didn't know what that laugh meant,'' she said.
``Whether he was glorifying in what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, the vote had shifted to 10-to-2 in favor of death,
Ms. Walker said. As many as seven votes were taken each day, she
said, and she described deliberations as heated. ``People cried,
people got upset,'' she said. ``Yelling, like getting up and
pointing. There was no fighting, but there was, like, posturing.''
</P>
<P>
   She said one juror shouted, ``You can't tell me how to think,
because this is what is deep in my heart!'' Another told her peers,
``How would you feel if this was done to someone you know?''
</P>
<P>
   The second juror, who confirmed Ms. Walker's version of events,
said she changed her vote to death on Thursday, but not before she
weighed a personal factor. ``It was a black man, and I'm a black
person, and for selfish reasons I had thoughts about that,'' the
second juror said. Finally, though, she chose death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever he did,'' she said, ``he did it mercilessly.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walker, meanwhile, said she shifted to undecided Friday
night after the moment of meditation. After reading the Bible on
Saturday morning, she said she decided for death. She said she felt
a sense of peace as she ate breakfast and arrived at the
courthouse. Back in the jury room, Ms. Walker said, the 12 jurors
voted aloud one by one, explaining their decisions. Each spoke for
death. It took about two hours.
</P>
<P>
   One other juror, a man, had been undecided on Friday night, Ms.
Walker said. When it came time for him to speak, Ms. Walker said,
he told the group that he would change to death. The brutality of
the crime had swayed him, she said, declining to identify him.
</P>
<P>
   In what she described as a ``monologue'' that lasted for several
minutes, Ms. Walker spoke last. ``I told them how I thought that
the spirit had told me to do whatever I thought was right because
God would have the final say,'' she recalled. ``Whatever we voted,
if God decided intervention was necessary, it would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them the peace that I now felt,'' she continued, ``and
that my answer was now death.''
</P>
<P>
   After delivering the verdict, the jurors reconvened in the jury
room. They all held hands and joined in a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' they prayed, ``for giving us the strength.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
