<HEADER>
A3856 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-TEXAS-TEX     06-10 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANK ON ABORTION EXPECTED AT TEXAS GOP CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAX B. BAKER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Republicans are moving forward with a
platform proposal to deny campaign funds and party support to GOP
candidates who will not publicly support a ban on late-term
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee rejected a similar proposal
this year because party leaders feared it would be viewed as a
``litmus test'' that could cost the GOP its House and Senate
majorities.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Lambert, who represents Texas on the Republican National
Committee, proposed changing the state party's platform Wednesday.
He conceded it is a litmus test, but he compared it to the debate
the party has had over racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Infanticide is on the same level as racism. And there is no
place in our party for people that support infanticide,'' said
Lambert, of Lubbock. He said other states' GOPs such as those in
California and Georgia have adopted similar resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of a handful of socially oriented platform proposals
being considered for this week's Texas Republican Party Convention
in Fort Worth. Many of the party's 14,000 delegates and alternates
are expected to arrive Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The state GOP convention, being held at the Fort Worth
Convention Center, is the largest in the country in terms of
delegates. Gov. George W. Bush will speak to the delegates Friday,
with the convention wrapping up Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the party's leadership was discussing the GOP
platform and rules, including Lambert's proposal on late-term
abortions referred to by foes as ``partial birth'' abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Known medically as intact dilation and extraction, a late-term
abortion involves removing a fetus feet first from the uterus and
piercing the head to allow it to pass through the cervix.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican controlled-Congress passed a late-term abortion
ban twice, but President Clinton vetoed the bills, citing
insufficient safeguards to protect the health and life of the
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Republican House Speaker Newt Gingrich promised swift
action on getting a ban on late-term abortions. Eighty-two percent
of Americans generally opposed the procedure in a 1996 Gallup Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert, who presented a similar proposal to the national party,
and others predicted that his plank will sail through the party's
platform committees and be endorsed by the full convention
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing is that the Republican National Party has
shown that it is out of touch, just as many of the national leaders
who opposed that effort showed they are out of touch,'' Lambert
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush and other elected officials, while supporting a
prohibition on late-term abortions, have said such a litmus test is
unproductive and that the choice of candidates should be left to
the voters.
</P>
<P>
   The State Republican Executive Committee approved a similar
measure several months ago, saying it would withhold financial
support from such candidates. Lambert's proposed plank would make
that prohibition binding.
</P>
<P>
   State party officials in Fort Worth for committee meetings on
the party's platform, rules and other internal business predicted
the measure will pass, but some dreaded the prospective news
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   With their eyes fixed on maintaining control of the Texas Senate
and taking over the Texas House for the first time in more than 120
years, many Republicans want to avoid any splashy confrontations
over issues such as abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the majority of Republicans are opposed to
partial-birth abortions as are a majority of Democrats,'' said
Bryan Eppstein, a Fort Worth Republican political consultant who
represents several state officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for the political party to start having a litmus test is a
bad precedent to start,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some people are concerned about Lambert's proposal,
there probably won't be any major scuffles over it or other parts
of the party's platform, said Michael Williams, chairman of the GOP
platform committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sensing there will be dramatic changes in the
platform,'' said Williams, an Arlington attorney and general
counsel for the state party. ``One of our objectives is to make it
more voter-friendly and reader-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Fisher, head of the subcommittee discussing family issues,
said the platform will undergo few changes and retain many of its
planks, including those opposing abortion and supporting school
choice and vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially it is going to stay very strong, very conservative
and most of what we are doing is grammatical cleanup and
housekeeping,'' said Fisher, of Bedford. ``There aren't going to be
any definitive issue changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there may be little consternation within the state GOP
convention about some of the socially conservative issues, that
doesn't mean they won't attract attention that could be detrimental
to the party, political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of some of the things done in the '60s and '70s
by the Democrats about legalizing marijuana that were just as
self-destructive,'' said Jim Riddlesperger, a political science
professor at Texas Christian University. ``They are trying to push
a social agenda, but they have little control over the candidates
or the voting public.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
