<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-UTILITY-EXEC-500&AMP;A     06-10 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UTILITY-EXEC-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY HEAD'S SEVERANCE PACKAGE TERMED `OUTRAGEOUS'
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even as he was leading one of the most troubled
utility companies in the United States, William J. Catacosinos was
working on another task: laying the foundation for a lucrative
departure from the utility, Long Island Lighting Co.
</P>
<P>
   The fruits of that labor emerged last week, when it was
disclosed that Catacosinos, 68, had received a $42 million payment
as a result of New York state's partial takeover of the utility.
Gov. George Pataki called the payments to Catacosinos and other top
LILCO executives ``disgraceful,'' ``outrageous'' and, above all,
``secret,'' and ordered an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many provisions leading to the payments were included
in public filings by LILCO with the Securities and Exchange
Commission over the years. But those documents included no specific
amounts that foreshadowed the $42 million payment, and the
provisions were so complicated and subject to interpretation that
state officials and others professed astonishment at learning the
figure.
</P>
<P>
   While $42 million may appear staggeringly high, experts on
executive compensation said packages in the tens of millions of
dollars are by no means unheard of these days for top executives.
Lucrative stock options, big bonuses and carefully crafted ``golden
parachutes'' have become standard for the leaders of many large
companies.
</P>
<P>
   And by far the biggest chunk of Catacosinos' package, $37
million, represents a lump-sum payment of pension benefits that
under other circumstances might have been spread out over many
years.
</P>
<P>
   But Catacosinos' deal was unusual in some important ways,
several experts said. His pay was above average for an executive in
the utility industry, and it rose sharply even as LILCO's
shareholders saw only modest long-term returns and as ratepayers
were saddled with huge bills. His contract language was written to
peg his pension to his most lucrative single year with the company,
rather than the average of pay over several years that other
companies often use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to recall ever seeing a set of contractual
pay arrangements that were so stacked in favor of the executive and
against shareholders,'' said Graef Crystal, editor of the Crystal
Report, a newsletter on executive compensation. ``Everything has
been set up to favor him.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Catacosinos even question whether the state takeover
of LILCO should be considered a ``change of control'' that would
trigger any special payments to him. After all, they say, he
continues to work as chief executive at Marketspan, the company
created by a partial takeover of LILCO's electrical service by the
state through the Long Island Power Authority and merging LILCO's
remaining divisions with the Brooklyn Union Gas holding company.
</P>
<P>
   Catacosinos draws the same salary from Marketspan that he got
from LILCO, but has not yet signed a contract with Marketspan's
board, said a company spokesman, Joseph McDonnell. The board will
meet for the first time Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This is not the first time Catacosinos' calculations of his
pension have been at the center of a dispute. After NCR Corp.
acquired a computer company he headed in 1980, it filed a lawsuit
contending that he had improperly inflated his pension before
leaving the company in 1982. The lawsuit was settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   After Catacosinos agreed in 1984 to run LILCO, where he had been
a director since 1978, he said in many interviews that he took the
job because he wanted to give something back to the community.
McDonnell said he had accomplished that goal by increasing the
value of his company, cutting rates and protecting workers' jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of compensation, one would have to compare it to what
he might have received elsewhere had he not taken on the challenges
facing LILCO,'' McDonnell said.
</P>
<P>
   But Catacosinos has faced sharp criticism throughout his tenure
from ratepayers and politicians, and LILCO shares have performed
poorly compared with many other utilities and broader stock-market
indexes.
</P>
<P>
   Just days after becoming chairman of LILCO, Catacosinos cut
1,000 jobs, halted the utility's dividend to shareholders and cut
salaries across the board, including his own, which fell to
$220,000 from $275,000. It was restored to $275,000 the following
year, and rose steadily, to about $700,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   His combined salary and bonus for last year was $1.9 million.
That is well below the average of $8.7 million in salary, bonuses
and stock options for all chief executives of large companies, said
Crystal, but is more than twice the median amount paid to eight
chief executives of similar-sized utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The high total for 1997 is especially significant because of an
unusual provision in Catacosinos' contract that bases his pension
in part on the highest bonus he received in a single year.
Typically, companies base that formula on an average of bonuses
over several years.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell said Catacosinos had actually argued that he should
get a $63 million payment, rather than the $42 million the board
ultimately granted, because he was counting more of his 1997
bonuses than the board was.
</P>
<P>
   The board's decision that the state takeover amounts to a
``change of control'' led to several payments to Catacosinos based
on different contract provisions.
</P>
<P>
   He receives three years' salary totaling $2.1 million, a common
provision in contracts for chief executives.
</P>
<P>
   Catacosinos is also guaranteed a five-year consulting stint with
the company after he is terminated as chief executive. For the
first two years, he receives 90 percent of his final salary. In the
third and fourth years, he receives 75 percent of his salary. For
the final year, he gets 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He gets an annual pension of $196,000 under the utility's
pension plan covering all employees. He also receives an additional
annual pension of $2.1 million, based on a formula that takes into
account his salary and bonus, among other things. But rather than
receiving that money every year, he got a lump sum payment of $36.9
million, according to Marketspan.
</P>
<P>
   Catacosinos also recently received two payments of $742,500 in
stock and $743,750 in cash under long-term incentive plans intended
to reward performance over several years.
</P>
<P>
   One or both of these was presumably included by Catacosinos in
his definition of pay in calculating the amount of his lump-sum
pension. The board disputed that definition and lowered his
requested total package of $63 million to $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   For completing transactions involving Brooklyn Union Gas and the
Long Island Power Authority, he also received $354,826 in stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
