<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-SPARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS BEGIN SECOND SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after returning from the World Championships
in Germany, Lisa Leslie and Haixia Zheng were going through the
motions in their first practice with the Los Angeles Sparks
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They were welcomed home by their teammates and then got busy
preparing for tonight's 7:30 WNBA season-opener against the Utah
Starzz and top draft pick 7-foot-2 Margo Dydek at the Delta Center
in Salt Lake City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lisa) was supposed to come in and rest and sit down, her and
Haixia,'' Sparks coach Julie Rousseau said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rousseau wasn't complaining. The sooner she can get them
into the program the better. The Sparks last year finished 14-14,
one game from winning the Western Conference title and earning a
playoff berth last year before losing to Phoenix, 73-68, in
overtime. They began last season 4-7 under Linda Sharp and finished
10-7 when Rousseau took over as the head coach on July 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were that close last year, so we got a taste of what to
expect,'' Rousseau said.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time the stakes have been raised with a substantial
increase in talent league-wide. The Sparks capitalized on the
feeding frenzy, snatching pure shooter Allison Feaster from Harvard
as their top draft pick, and Octavia Blue, another outside scoring
threat from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   They join Leslie and Zheng as the Sparks finalized their
11-player roster Wednesday with returning guards Penny Toler,
Tamecka Dixon, Mwadi Mabika, and Katrina Colleton. They added 6-3
center-forward Pam McGee from Sacramento in exchange for Linda
Burgess, along with 6-3 Sandra VanEmbricqs, and guard Erin
Alexander. Jamila Wideman, who started last season before becoming
the backup point guard, has been placed on the injured reserve list
because of lower back strain, along with Eugenia RyCraw (strained
left knee). Forward Erica Kienast was waived.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Conference race got a lot tougher with the defending
champion Houston Comets moving from the Eastern Conference to
accommodate the expansion teams from Detroit and Washington.
Rousseau is more interested in what's going on her side of the
court than worrying about the Comets, who return league MVP Cynthia
Cooper as well as a healthy Sheryl Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have enough to worry about. Yeh, we'll scout the other
teams, but we're going to take care of what we need to do - play
tough tenacious defense and be aggressive offensively. I feel
pretty good about our chances with Houston being in our
conference,'' Rousseau said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks have much more depth, speed and athleticism than they
did last year. The addition of the aggressive style of play by
McGee will open a new window of opportunity in the low post, and
while Feaster and Blue are perimeter players, they're just as
capable of taking the ball inside. The explosive backcourt,
featuring Toler (quad) and Dixon (hamstring) were slightly hampered
early in training camp, but it's doubtful those injuries will slow
either down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ferrari's are on the road,'' quipped Toler.
</P>
<P>
   The two picked up in practice where they left off last season,
Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very comfortable with Penny. Although, we've been away
from each other all off season we come right back and it's just
clicking because we know each other's game now.''
</P>
<P>
   It may take a few days for Leslie and Zheng to get over the jet
lag, but mentally and physically they feel prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling really good,'' said Leslie, who was still riding
off the adrenaline of USA 71-65 victory over Russia in the World
Championship final. `I'm very well way above where I was last
season at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Zheng, saddened because her Chinese team failed to make the
championship round, is looking to put all her enegry into the
Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this team will do much better this year than last
year,'' Zheng said. ``We'll do our best.''
</P>
<P>
   SPARKS NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   KCAL Channel 9 will televise the Sparks on June 21 against
Houston and Aug. 16 against Detroit. Chick Hearns
</P>
<P>
   , the voice of the Lakers, will team with Ann Meyers
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
