<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-ITALY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAGGIO BACK, SEEKING WORLD CUP GLORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It's been nearly four years since Roberto Baggio, the
``Divine Ponytail'' whose heroics lifted Italy into the 1994 World
Cup championship game, missed the most famous penalty kick in
history, handing Brazil its fourth crown on an ill-fated afternoon
in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The ponytail is gone now, but Baggio despite all evidence to the
contrary remains, and against all odds he could be the central
figure this evening when the Italians open their 1998 campaign
against Chile in Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   The gifted forward, 31, who has endured a difficult time on the
field since single-handedly lifting the Azzurri into the '94 title
game, lives these days in the shadow of 23-year-old Alessandro Del
Piero, his successor at Juventus and with the Italian squad.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Baggio, because of an abductor muscle injury to Del
Piero, who will play the key role in the most crucial of his team's
first-round encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In July a year ago, how many of you would have bet on me being
here?'' he teased reporters. ``I was the only one.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a long time in coming Baggio has made only one start for
Italy, in a warmup match earlier this month, since November 1994,
but if he's looking for redemption or to prove that he belongs,
he's keeping it to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that the first choice is Del Piero,'' he says. ``I've
already won my World Cup by just being called up to the squad. ...
(But) if the opportunity arises, I'll do what I can to make people
remember me, just like at USA '94.''
</P>
<P>
   He is remembered best for what he couldn't do in '94, place a
penalty kick past goalkeeper Claudio Taffarel and into the net. His
shot cleared the crossbar, and he sank to his knees as the
Brazilian celebration raged around him.
</P>
<P>
   What too often is forgotten is what he accomplished up to that
point, scoring sensational late goals against Nigeria and Spain to
prod a plodding Azzurri into the semifinals, giving a spirited
performance in the final and playing 120 minutes despite a badly
pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty kick miss seemed to lead him into a downward spiral.
Arrigo Sacchi, Italy coach Cesare Maldini's predecessor, dropped
him from the squad in late 1994, and a lauded transfer to
then-power AC Milan quickly soured, with Baggio relegated to the
bench for much of his two years there.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't considered for the 1996 European Championships, a
disastrous event for Italy, and played no impact on the Azzurri's
difficult qualification for this tournament. But a move to Bologna,
where he scored a career-high 22 goals this past season, paid off
when Maldini selected him last month for the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be back on the field today, seeking to create a little
more magic to start the Italians toward what they hope will be
their fourth World Cup title. Soon, he knows, he will be back on
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Maldini says as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Del Piero is the No. 1 player of the Italian team,'' says the
coach, whose son, Paolo, is Italy's captain and top defender. ``I
believe he will be one of the stars in the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Baggio hasn't a problem with that. He'll do whatever's necessary
to aid the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come here knowing the way things are,'' he says. ``It's
true I'm Roberto Baggio, but in this squad, there are people who
were chosen before me. All I'm saying is that if the need arises,
I'll be ready. I'm living through this with a sense of calm, and
obviously, with hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
