A3866 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      06-10 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSPAN FINDS ECONOMY IS EXTRAORDINARILY SOUND
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan declared the economy to
be in extraordinarily good shape and signaled that he saw no
immediate need to strike against inflation by raising interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony before the Joint Economic Committee of Congress
was sprinkled with caveats about how the combination of low
unemployment and strong growth could eventually force the Fed to
raise rates. But for now price pressures are subdued and Asia's
crisis is taking some of the steam out of the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO COMPANY LIABILITY FOUND
</P>
<P>
   A Florida jury found Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco liable for a
smoker's death and ordered the company to pay $1 million in
compensatory and punitive damages. The case was viewed as a major
defeat for cigarette makers that could affect the course of federal
tobacco legislation, and tobacco stocks slumped.
</P>
<P>
   A TAX BREAK FROM CIGARETTE MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Giving strength to anti-smoking legislation, the Senate voted to
use part of the money that would be raised from higher cigarette
prices to give an income-tax break to married couples with annual
incomes below $50,000, to reduce the marriage tax penalty.
</P>
<P>
   BIG HEALTH CARE COMPANIES MERGE
</P>
<P>
   Health Care and Retirement and Manor Care Inc. agreed to merge
in a stock swap valued at about $2.45 billion. Analysts applauded
the deal, which will create one of the nation's largest operators
of nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   FURTHER DECLINE IN YEN EXPECTED
</P>
<P>
   Japan is in such an economic straitjacket, some veteran analysts
contend, that the yen must fall even further than it has _ 4.4
percent in the last month to 141.43 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Japan's governing Liberal Democratic Party are
suggesting that they will not rescue financial institutions on the
verge of insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   A SWISS-AMERICAN DEAL IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston bought Brazil's leading investment
bank, Garantia SA, for $675 million in cash, making the
Swiss-American group the largest underwriter and stock trader in
that hotly competitive emerging market.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES TO TIGHTEN BANKRUPTCY
</P>
<P>
   The House passed far-reaching legislation to tighten the
bankruptcy laws for the first time in a generation, to discourage
declarations of personal bankruptcy to erase debts.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLIC AND HONDA SETTLE SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Republic Industries and Honda Motor's American unit said that
they had settled a lawsuit and set conditions that would allow
Republic, the nation's largest group of car dealers, to buy more
Honda and Acura dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   DOW FALLS ON ASIAN CONCERN
</P>
<P>
   Concern that Asia's economic slump is causing companies that do
business there to report disappointing earnings pushed stocks
lower. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 78.22 points, to
8,971.70.
</P>
<P>
   IMF IN WARNING TO RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has told the Russian government that it needs to slash
its budget deficit and overhaul its tax system if it is to qualify
for billions of dollars in extra loans, senior Russian officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA PICKS LUFTHANSA HEAD
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines has selected Frederick Reid, the president of
Lufthansa German Airlines, as its new marketing chief. Delta's new
chairman is bringing in fresh talent. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
