<HEADLINE>
EEOC SUES TWA OVER SEXUAL HARASSMENT CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission sued
Trans World Airlines on Wednesday, saying the company failed to
intervene after three female employees accused three high-level
managers of engaging in unwanted touching, using crude language and
demanding sexual favors.
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC filed the lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn
after investigating complaints of sexual harassment made in October
by three Long Island women against Ino Sylman, the manager
responsible for TWA's ground-safety and security operations at
Kennedy International Airport, and two other senior managers, said
Elizabeth Grossman, a trial lawyer for the federal agency. She said
that eight current and former TWA employees had signed affidavits
supporting the women, and that other women were expected to come
forward with accusations against the officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Wednesday, TWA strenuously denied the
allegations. ``Trans World Airlines does not tolerate
discrimination in any form, including sexual harassment,'' the
statement said. ``We took these allegations seriously and
investigated them thoroughly when they were brought to our
attention. We found no corroboration of the charges made by these
three individuals, and we consider these charges to be false and
without merit.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jim Brown, a spokesman at TWA's headquarters in St. Louis, said
that the company would have no further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three women named in the complaint, the most senior was
Veronica Saunders, 37, of Farmingdale, a supervisor of passenger
service who left the company in April. Ms. Saunders, who said she
has been unable to find a new job, was responsible for monitoring
baggage and passenger security check points and insuring that
safety and security requirements were met, according to a separate
lawsuit she filed with the two other women: Joanne Geskie, 32, of
Franklin Square, and Susan Congema, 28, of East Meadow.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Geskie, a flight information coordinator whose duties
included assigning gates to aircraft and handling police and
medical emergencies, also left TWA in April, after working for the
company for 10 years. During that period, she said in a telephone
interview, Sylman's behavior worsened. ``As time went on,'' she
said, ``he would be grabbing and groping, pulling my shirt out to
look. He'd show me his erection by pulling his pants up against his
body so you could see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grossman said that Sylman and the two other TWA officials
named in the lawsuit _ George Cintron, a manager in the Building
and Maintenance Department, and Garfield Harris, a manager in the
Passenger Service Department _ had distracted the women from their
duties and could have endangered the public. ``They had jobs that
were very important in terms of insuring the safety of aircraft,''
she said. ``Despite the harassment, they were able to perform their
jobs, but it's not easy when you have someone propositioning you
day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, Ms. Saunders took her complaints to
three high-level TWA managers, but instead of taking action, the
airline retaliated against her by taking away her private office
and denying her any time off. Ms. Congema, also a flight
information coordinator, was denied a promotion earlier this year,
the lawsuit said. She continues to report to Sylman, but her work
hours no longer coincide with his, said Robert Lipman, one of the
lawyers representing the women.
</P>
<P>
   Lipman, who has litigated other sexual harassment complaints,
said that this case was unusual in that most harassment incidents
involve smutty remarks and behavior. ``They don't actually involve
supervisors wanting to have sex,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
