<HEADER>
A3868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FIREFIGHTER-FUNERA     06-10 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FIREFIGHTER-FUNERAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLEN FIREFIGHTER IS BURIED IN FARMINGDALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ at the funeral of Lt. James Blackmore, who died
last Friday fighting a fire in Brooklyn, Blackmore's youngest
child, Brian, 6, holds his father's helmet _ will be sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(af) 
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMINGDALE, N.Y. _ There was familiar pageantry Wednesday, a
sea of dark suits and white gloves as thousands of somber
firefighters paid homage to a fallen colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a procession of drummers in green kilts, a lone
bagpiper marked the passing of Lt. James W. Blackmore, a New York
City firefighter who died on Friday trying to rescue a missing
woman who, unknown to him, had already escaped a burning house.
</P>
<P>
   To his colleagues, he was more than just someone willing to give
his life for the job. Some remembered Jimmy Blackmore and his
quirks: he was seldom without a bottle of liquid that he said was a
good mouthwash and eyewash, but could also be used to fight fires.
</P>
<P>
   He was legendary for his messy desk. But most of all, he was
known as a family man, and Wednesday's service was as much about
his four young children and the legacy they were left as about
Blackmore.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as Jimmy gave us, the real center of his universe was
his family,'' said Capt. Francis Johnston. Addressing the children
by name, he said, ``Brian, when you're fishing, your father is
helping you pull the fish out; Sara, Claire, when you're acting,
your father is clapping like crazy; Jackie, when you draw a
picture, he's smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire that took Blackmore's life in East New York, Brooklyn,
last Friday also injured eight other firefighters, including Capt.
Scott LaPiedra. More than 70 percent of his body was burned, and he
is battling for his life at Jacobi Medical Center in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Blackmore a hero, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, like the
other speakers, mentioned the unassuming nature of the fallen
firefighter. The mayor noted that one of his brothers had no idea
that Blackmore had five commendations from the Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he went into that building,'' the mayor said, ``he didn't
ask if the person was Jewish, Protestant or Catholic, black, white
or Hispanic. He just went.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Blackmore's widow, Susan, and his children, Sara, 13,
Jacqueline, 11, Claire, 9, and Brian, 7, he said: ``He's not gone.
He's in each of the four children. He's in the lessons he taught
them. They can draw on that for strength.''
</P>
<P>
   The funeral Mass for Blackmore, 48, held in the auditorium of
the St. Kilian Roman Catholic Parish in his hometown of
Farmingdale, drew an estimated 12,000 firefighters, along with an
array of dignitaries, including the mayor, Gov. George E. Pataki,
Fire Commissioner Thomas Von Essen and the Nassau County Executive,
Thomas Gulotta.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki called Blackmore and other firefighters ``the greatest of
the greatest heroes,'' and said there is ``no greater sacrifice''
than risking one's life to save the life of another.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most touching tribute to the firefighter came from
Johnson, the head of Engine Company 332, to which Blackmore was
assigned, who remembered the lieutenant as someone who avoided
praise but delighted in praising others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to be away from the center of attention,'' he said.
``But he liked to tell the men they did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Msgr. John P. Martin, associate pastor of St. Kilian, told a
story about Blackmore's heroism that got scant attention, just as
he wanted it. While driving home from the hospital with his
youngest child, Brian, then a newborn, Blackmore and his wife
witnessed an accident. Blackmore stopped, pulled the driver from
the car, got back in his car and kept going, never taking credit.
To this day, it is believed to be an act of an unknown good
Samaritan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Msgr. Charles W. Swiger said many are asking why this death had
to happen. The better question, he said, ``is not, `Why did Jimmy
die?' but, `Why did he live?' '' He invoked the book of Job, noting
that God told Job, after Job's trials, ``You don't know my mind and
you can't plumb my reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin offered an answer. ``He was a gift,'' he said. ``God who
gave him has called him back to himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
