A3869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-LILCO-NYT &LR;      06-10 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-LILCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CATACOSINOS CASHES IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 11:
</P>
<P>
   For years Long Island Lighting Co., or LILCO, has been very
unpopular on Long Island. People resented its rates _ the highest
in the nation _ and politicians found it easier to run against it
than against each other.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it appeared to be a brilliant political stroke _ if not
exactly consistent with traditional Republican philosophy _ when
Gov. George Pataki engineered a state takeover of LILCO's
distribution capacity. Thanks in part to the refinancing of LILCO's
huge debt with tax-exempt municipal bonds, most electric bills are
being cut by about 20 percent. If all goes as planned, electricity
customers will be getting rebate checks of $101 to $232 this fall,
not long before the governor stands for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   But the political benefits of all that could be in jeopardy
because some former LILCO executives, most notably William
Catacosinos, the company's chairman and chief executive, are
getting $67 million in payouts, with $42 million going to
Catacosinos. Pataki is furious, saying the payouts are
``disgraceful'' and ``outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the payments to Catacosinos do strain logic. He gets
$2.6 million to compensate him for losing the right to consult for
LILCO after retirement, and $2.1 million as a golden parachute for
losing his LILCO job. But he has not lost his job, although Pataki
thinks he should. He is chairman of Marketspan, the company that
was formed by the merger of the old Brooklyn Union Gas Co. with the
parts of LILCO not bought by the state, with a base salary of
$700,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rest of his compensation _ $34 million _ is said to
be a lump-sum settlement of Catacosinos' pension benefits under his
extraordinarily generous LILCO employment contract.
</P>
<P>
   The amount going to Catacosinos is outrageous, especially
considering LILCO's poor record as an electricity supplier. Of
course, in one respect he did a great job, but it was not for the
people who pay electric bills. The costs of the never-opened
Shoreham nuclear plant fell not on the investors, as they might
have, but on ratepayers and taxpayers. LILCO shareholders ended up
doing reasonably well.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is right in saying this is a disgraceful cash-in for an
executive of a public utility that did such a spotty job of serving
the public. But Marketspan appears to be correct when it says the
payments were due under contracts that were previously made public.
In other words, Pataki should have used his bargaining clout to
restrict Catacosinos' windfall before he started selling his LILCO
takeover plan to the public. Pataki's outrage is well aimed, but
way too late. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
