A3870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      06-10 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE GAME OF BUDGET GOTCHA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 11:
</P>
<P>
   New York's City Hall these days has the feel of a student
government convention, with grown politicians scrambling to reread
the city charter in search of new and unimagined ways to check or
ultimately checkmate the opposition. What has provoked this extreme
case of governmental gamesmanship is this year's budget process.
While it is generally a sleepy debate between the mayor and the
City Council, this year the two sides have been walloping each
other with parliamentary brickbats. This sudden vigor would be
terrific sport, except that it involves $34 billion of the public's
money.
</P>
<P>
   Each side has a different version of who upended the budget
process this year. Council Speaker Peter Vallone and his team have
said that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's people simply refuse to
negotiate until Vallone drops his idea of a referendum on Yankee
Stadium. The mayor's corner has argued that Vallone, who is running
for governor, is using the referendum and the budget to help him
get the big job in Albany next year. While the mayor and his staff
have an elaborate method for bumping the Vallone referendum off
this year's ballot, it would be far better if Vallone voluntarily
scrapped his referendum. It is a political ploy that would yield a
crude decision on a matter that should take a great deal of complex
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the referendum suddenly disappeared, however, the city
budget is now launched into uncharted territory. For all the unease
about this process, it has provided a chance to study the city's
fiscal matters in a new way, with a Council alternative budget
being the focus of debate instead of Giuliani's.
</P>
<P>
   While the differences between them are modest, the City
Council's budget does offer a few improvements over the mayor's
version. The Council's plan to use $165 million to pay down the
debt, as well as extra allotments for a new after-school program
and weekly recycling, look like sensible expenditures from a huge
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than negotiating these items and differences over
proposed tax deductions, the mayor has vetoed his list of budget
items, and the Council is ready to override them. The mayor can
then refuse or delay writing the checks, and both sides can go to
court. But rather than escalate the conflict this way, it is time
to drop the outside issues _ like any referendum _ and go back to
negotiating the budget. In all but rhetoric, the two sides are very
close. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
