<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-FRENCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFLECTIONS ON OWN GOALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS Tommy Boyd and Youssef Chippo may have been inconsolable
Wednesday night, but they should be thanking God --- indeed, they
may be --- that they are from civilized lands.
</P>
<P>
   Each scored an ``own goal'' --- that is, a goal against their
team --- on an extraordinary first day of the 1998 World Cup, a
minor crime in soccer that can carry a heavy price, at least in,
say, Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare occurrence, but it happens, but neither Boyd nor
Chippo wanted to hear that after keeping their squads from what
would have been tremendous accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd, who had a fine match for a gutty Scotland side that
battled Brazil to the end, knocked in the winner in the reigning
champs' 2-1 triumph at Saint-Denis. And Morocco's Chippo,
desperately trying to prevent a goal seconds before the halftime
whistle, helped Norway overcome an early deficit in a 2-2 draw at
Montpellier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly wasn't the type of goal that you like to score
but there was absolutely nothing I could do about it,'' said Boyd,
who watched helplessly as the ball ricocheted from Cafu's foot to
Scottish goalkeeper Jim Leighton's face to his arm and into the net
to break a 1-1 tie with 17 minutes to go. ``It's probably the worst
feeling I've ever had in football.''
</P>
<P>
   Chippo's error, during first-half injury time, erased a 1-0
lead; it followed a Stig Inge Bjornebye free kick that Moroccan
goalkeeper Driss Benzekri misplayed. The ball bounced off Norway's
Henning Berg, and Chippo, trying to head the ball wide of the far
post, nodded it into his net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very disappointing to make silly mistakes after
taking control of the game and giving ourselves a good chance of
victory,'' complained Morocco coach Henri Michel.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. It's only a game, and players make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   But tell that to Andres Escobar, the Colombian defender who lost
his life over an own goal four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Again, a simple error.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. midfielder John Harkes sent a cross into Colombia's box,
and Escobar, trying to keep it from finding another Yank, stuck his
foot out. His goalkeeper was leaning the other way, and neither
could do a thing aside from watch it roll into the net. The
Americans pulled out a 2-1 stunner and Colombia, one of the pre-Cup
favorites, returned home in disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Before the tournament was over, Escobar was dead, shot by a man
who first thanked him for the own goal. U.S. and Colombian
authorities believe the killer was a hit man for a gambling
syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   It was, true, an isolated incident. No other World Cup star has
ever died because of an on-field mistake. But Colombian players and
coaches must live with the threat of death daily. Colombia's coach,
Hernan Dario Gomez, has received dozens of death threats, some
directed at his family, usually after his team gives a poor
performance or he makes an unpopular decision.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of the job, although that doesn't mean Gomez accepts
it. He has urged Colombians to be ``patient and forgiving'' if
things don't go as they hope in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do well here, I will go home a god,'' he says. ``But if
things go badly, I'll be a devil.''
</P>
<P>
   No such fate awaits Boyd and Chippo. They'll be back on the
field Tuesday, when Scotland takes on Norway and Morocco meets
Brazil, then again on June 23, when their teams tangle in a Group A
finale.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, possibly both, will head home when that game's
over. They'll be greeted by a pat on the back, a ``good job,
mate,'' and go on with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Escobar deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
