<HEADER>
A3872 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WorldCup-HNS &LR;      06-10 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World </SLUG>
 Cup-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. team gets shot of confidence for Germany
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAINT DENIS, France _ The biggest confidence boost came Tuesday
night, when the U.S. national soccer team put on an overwhelming
offensive show in a 4-0 exhibition victory over French professional
team Gueugnon.
</P>
<P>
   It was the final game for the Americans before facing the
heavily favored German team in both squads' 1998 World Cup opener
next Monday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. win over Gueugnon was a significant game if only
because as strong as the Americans have played for the most part
lately, scoring goals was becoming a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got what we needed out of that game,'' U.S. defender and
captain Thomas Dooley said. ``We got our offense going.''
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday, as the veteran U.S. team gathered at its plush
Chateau de Pizay near Lyon, it got a bit more of a confidence
boost.
</P>
<P>
   The team watched Scotland hang in with the best team in the
world, Brazil, and fall just short of earning a tie and gaining a
point in Wednesday's Cup opener.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have long admitted that their most realistic goal
for their opening World Cup match was to tie Germany and then try
to defeat Yugoslavia and Iran to secure a berth in the second round
of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have ever been better prepared for a World
Cup, but a lot of this has to do with just understanding the
pressures involved in a World Cup and understanding that anything
can happen,'' U.S. coach Steve Sampson said. ``Of course, we are
underdogs. I think this can work in our favor. If (Germany) has any
weakness, it might be that they are overconfident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a very special effort to do well in this World Cup.
Coming together as a group and focusing and concentrating will be a
big part of our ability to achieve that kind of success.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at that, oddsmakers are not considering the Americans to be
second-round material. Widely considered to have its best national
soccer team ever, the U.S. drew a group that includes the
three-time champion Germans and Yugoslavia, which some are picking
as a dark horse to win the entire tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is a 2-5 favorite to win the group, Yugoslavia is 4-1,
and the Americans are 15-1, with Iran considered a three-and-out
team in the round-robin phase of the Cup. Overall, Germany and
Yugoslavia are ranked among eight teams considered most likely to
win the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the U.S. team has played confidently, and the coach says
the long odds won't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are close to starting, and we're happy with how we've
prepared,'' Sampson said. ``There are two phases to our preparation
in France. The first was to acclimate to the time zone, continue
with physical fitness, gain confidence on the ball and focus and
concentrate on why we are here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second phase, which started after (the exhibition
game), we're trying to make sure we are injury-free and understand
tactically how we will approach the Germany match. We will refine
set pieces and make sure everyone is comfortable with their role.
We'll be ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
