<HEADER>
A3874 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-MOOD-TEX     06-10 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-MOOD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TEXAS TOWN TRYING TO COME TO GRIPS WITH SLAYING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ There are no likenesses of African-Americans in
historic photographs displayed in the old but striking Jasper
County courthouse. The newest, dated 1955, depicts the first woman
admitted to a jury in this community, tucked in the folds of
conservative East Texas' Piney Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no easy stereotype can be drawn of Jasper, a town of 8,000
where three white ex-convicts with white supremacist ties are
accused of carrying out one of contemporary Texas' most heinous
crimes: the dragging death and decapitation of a disabled black
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``JASPER TEXAS IS MOURNING HURTING CRYING,'' read a sign at the
Splish Splash Car Wash, summing up the mood of many. ``AMERICA
PLEASE PRAY FOR US.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a foregone conclusion that the nation will see Jasper as a
racist community, said Joline Larecy, the white car wash owner.
Locally, she only got ``thumbs up'' from customers for putting up
the sign, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the murder is going to give Jasper a bad look
for a long time,'' Larecy said of the Saturday night killing of
James Byrd Jr., 49.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully people from around the country will realize this is
an isolated incident. People in this area don't feel this hatred
for others.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's business leaders, concerned that Jasper might be
indelibly stamped a redneck community, have scheduled a meeting to
see if it's too late to repair the town's image. The meeting was
called by a hospital administrator who is black, as are the mayor
and two of the five city council members. Blacks also serve on the
school board, which has had an African-American president, and the
hospital district board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not without its racial problems, but we work things
out,'' said Willis Webb, publisher of the weekly Jasper News-Boy,
who is white.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King, whose son John William King is one of the three men
accused in Byrd's death, released a letter of apology to news
agencies Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sympathy goes out to the Byrd family. There is no reason
for a person to take the life of another, and to take it in such a
manner is beyond any kind of reasoning,'' King said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts me deeply to know that a boy I raised and considered
to be the most loved boy I knew could find it in himself to take a
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deed cannot be undone, but I hope we can all find it in
our hearts to go forward in peace, and with love for all. Let us
find in our hearts love for our fellow man. Hate can only
destroy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Greg Chambers says Jasper is far from a perfect
community. But not until Byrd's death had there been an act of
outright racism since Chambers moved from Beaumont north to Jasper
six years ago. And no one has made a major complaint to the local
NAACP chapter during that time, the black minister said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are underlying fears and prejudices here, but they're
not overt. People here treat you in a dignified, professional
manner,'' said Chambers, who was the only black member of the
Jasper Rotary Club when it elected him president in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers was not star struck by Jesse Jackson's visit Wednesday
and confided that the timing was not helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is calming down and things are heading in the
right direction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, we were worried that there were more than three
involved. Just a lot of fear in the community. But the sheriff
assured the black community that justice would be done. And when he
heard the `N' word used so often, he recognized it was a racial
crime and brought in the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first word of the torture-murder came out, Chambers
and other blacks and whites immediately speculated that it was in
revenge for the beating death of a white contractor, Jerry Lynn
McQueen, the previous Sunday. A black former employee, Donald
Kennebrew, was arrested on suspicion of murder.
</P>
<P>
   But Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles has said publicly that
there is no indication that retaliation was a motive in the assault
on Byrd. And few in Jasper see Byrd's torture death as a
tit-for-tat racial killing.
</P>
<P>
   But many blacks, who compose about 46 percent of the population,
remain unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me myself, I'm worried, worried scared, enough to make me want
to leave here,'' said Belinda Garrett, 26, Byrd's neighbor. She
recalled a gentle, joyful man who loved to sing and quiz children
on their math skills. The right answer earned a dollar bill, she
said. And he would eagerly fulfill requests to sing the Prince
song, ``Purple Rain.'' ``He just loved to sing, and asked us to
call him, `Purple Rain,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jasper is a quiet town until this happened, but we had racism
in the schools,'' Garrett said. Still, she could recall only one
minor incident in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   At a bench on the courthouse square, a recent high school
graduate said he didn't recall that clash but remembered a scrap
between a white girl, his sister, and a black girl in 1988. Now,
friendships between whites and blacks are anything but rare, said
Jason Cowart, 18.
</P>
<P>
   Like others, he fretted for his hometown's image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jasper is being labeled as a typical, ` ``To Kill a
Mockingbird,'' Atticus Finch' town,'' he said of the novel and
movie about a defense attorney confronting entrenched racism in a
small Southern town. ``It's not like that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Jesse Jackson arrived, a standing-room-only prayer vigil
was under way at the Greater New Bethel Church. The crowd inside
and a larger one outside were predominantly black but scores of
whites mixed easily, many wearing small primrose ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They symbolize peace and unity,'' explained red-haired Melanie
Radcliff, 14. ``We'll be wearing them till justice is served.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the white minister of the city's biggest Southern
Baptist church was called to the microphone and beseeched God to
``bind us together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope you take this tragedy and work it toward that end,''
said the Rev. Ed Robinson of the First Baptist Church. ``Bind us
together in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Mays, publisher of a black biweekly newspaper in Jasper,
turned to a neighbor at the rear and said she was moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before in my life have I heard a white man say something
like that from a pulpit in Jasper.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
