<HEADER>
A3876 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-swoopesreturns-HNS &LR;      06-10 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-swoopes </SLUG>
 returns-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Air cleared as Swoopes 
meets with Chancellor
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By W.H. STICKNEY JR. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Whatever problems may have arisen the day before because of Sheryl
Swoopes' unexcused absence from two Comets practices had all but
vanished by Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   All of the involved parties _ Swoopes, coach Van Chancellor and
Cynthia Cooper _ issued that as the company line at least, saying
any problems were solved in a couple of Wednesday meetings, one a
45-minute, face-to-face session between Chancellor and Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 11:30 a.m., I met with Sheryl Swoopes,'' Chancellor said.
``At 12:15, all the problems between Sheryl Swoopes and myself and
this basketball team were solved.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a team meeting that lasted almost an hour, Chancellor
said any further problems unrelated to Swoopes' absences similarly
were put to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had some situations on this team that had to be
resolved on who was going to be the rebounder, who was going to be
the passer, who was going to be the shooter, and who was going to
be what,'' Chancellor said. ``Being honest with you as a coach, I
think this was one of the best things that ever could have happened
to us. We just needed to get some things out in the open, get them
solved. We got them solved.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes on Tuesday was a no-show when the Comets went through
two workouts, the second a two-hour drill at Rice's Autry Court
that was open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the team said Swoopes' absence was a means of
underscoring her displeasure over having to play a secondary role
to Cooper during an 81-79 exhibition loss at Cleveland on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. It had nothing to do with that,'' Swoopes said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the problem were serious enough for her to consider
asking to be traded, Swoopes said, ``No. I would never want to be
traded. I want to come back here and play with the Comets and
hopefully defend our championship. That's what I'm looking forward
to doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes seemed amazed Tuesday's incidents became a major issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this kind of got blown out of proportion,'' she said.
``Honestly, I did the wrong thing. I did not call coach Chancellor
Tuesday morning to let him know why I wouldn't be there. And it
wasn't just basketball. There were some personal things I had to
take care of.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we worked it out, and I'm ready to come out here and do
what I've got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The major reason Swoopes gave for being absent involved
baby-sitting problems.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case last summer when she joined the Comets in July,
Swoopes has brought her mother from Lubbock to serve as chief
sitter for her 10-month-old son. On Tuesday, Swoopes said, her mom
was ill and her husband was away from home, leaving her with no one
to baby-sit, morning or evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met with coach. We talked. Everything's fine now,'' Swoopes
said. ``There's no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Texas Tech standout discounted the notion she and
Cooper have been at odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since I came back,'' Swoopes said, ``Cynthia and I sat
down and talked, and I feel like both of us complement each other's
game well. And I think we have an opportunity to do something that
probably will never be done again. That's hopefully win four or
five (WNBA) championships together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Cynthia is a tremendous player, a tremendous athlete.
She'd better think the same thing about me,'' Swoopes said,
laughing. ``I hope she does. Not only the two of us, but Tina
(Thompson), also.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely no problem between me and Cynthia, between
me and Tina, me and anyone else on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor said Swoopes remains subject to punishment for
missing practice. But as of Wednesday night, he hadn't determined
what that would be.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, too, tried to lay to rest lingering speculation about a
clash between her and Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no problem between Sheryl and Cynthia Cooper,''
Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Cooper turned her attention toward the hourlong team
meeting, which came three days before Saturday's season opener at
home against the New York Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always personality problems when you bring a lot of
different players together,'' she said. ``The key is whether you're
able to work them out as a team. We were able to work them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came together, we voiced all of our opinions, we got them
out on the table, and we got it taken care of. Now, we're looking
forward to starting the season. It's going to be great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
