<SLUG> BC-BANKRUPTCY-BILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES BILL TO DISCOURAGE PERSONAL BANKRUPTCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House passed far-reaching legislation Wednesday
to tighten the bankruptcy laws for the first time in a generation,
in an effort to discourage the growing practice of consumers'
declaring personal bankruptcy to erase their debts.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would make it harder to declare bankruptcy,
passed 306 to 118, with the support of 222 Republicans and 84
Democrats. No Republicans voted against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The bill ``represents another example of this Congress' efforts
to encourage individual responsibility,'' said Rep. Scott McInnis,
R-Colo. ``We will re-notify people that they do need to be held
accountable for their debts that they have accumulated. We will
remind them about keeping their word. We will remind them about
`Don't go out and spend money that you don't have.'''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would prohibit anyone earning more than the
national median income for his or her family size _ $50,000 for a
family of four, for example _ from declaring personal bankruptcy
under chapter 7 laws, in which virtually all debts are forgiven.
Those earning more than $50,000 and deemed able to repay at least
20 percent within five years would have to adhere to a payment
schedule under chapter 13.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's Republican sponsors in the House gained valuable
last-minute support by softening their stance on child-support and
alimony payments. They originally would have given credit-card
companies equal legal footing with single parents in trying to
recover such payments from someone who has filed for bankruptcy.
But a new provision appeared to ensure that payments to families
would be given priority over credit-card debts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the change, critics maintained that the bill was still a
billion-dollar gift to what they described as a voracious
credit-card industry that inundates consumers with promises of easy
credit even when those consumers are already deeply in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., said the bill had ``one central
purpose _ to take large sums of money from middle- and low-income
American families in distress and give it to the credit-card
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the provisions of the House bill will
become law. This summer, the Senate is to take up its own version,
which would give bankruptcy judges more leeway to set repayment
schedules. And, administration officials have said that President
Clinton objects to using income to determine whether someone is
eligible to file for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said that tightening the rules would reduce
bankruptcy filings _ 1.3 million last year, a record high for the
seventh year in a row, despite the robust economy. They also said
that too many consumers casually file for bankruptcy as a financial
planning tool. The bill would force those who file for bankruptcy
to pay most debts they accumulate within 90 days of filing.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., the principal sponsor, said debtors
needed to be yoked into bearing more responsibility and that he was
``bored to tears'' by the argument that credit card companies were
to blame for offering easy credit.
</P>
<P>
   This reasoning helped persuade swing voters, including
conservative House Democrats who have formed a group called the New
Democratic Coalition. Filing for bankruptcy ``shouldn't be as
convenient as going into a 7-Eleven,'' said Rep. Tim Roemer,
D-Ind., a coalition leader. Another leader, Rep. James Moran,
D-Va., noted that more Americans file for bankruptcy than graduate
from college.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates predicted the bill would inflict disaster
on those already struggling. Mary Rouleau, legislative director of
the Consumer Federation of America, called the bill a ``debtor's
prison without walls'' because it would deny people a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Sommer, a lawyer with the Consumer Bankruptcy Assistance
Project in Philadelphia, said that about 70 percent of those who
filed for bankruptcy did so under chapter 7. Of those filing under
chapter 13, two-thirds _ about 280,000 a year _ already fail to
meet their repayment schedule, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between supporters and opponents were
crystalized by an exchange between Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas, and
McInnis.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis said that no one was forcing anyone to use a credit
card.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said that was like saying drug dealers should not be
held accountable for drug abuse. ``If that's the kind of personal
responsibility that's behind this bill,'' he said in disgust, ``I
don't want any part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   McInnis responded that merchants were not responsible for the
customers' debts. ``If you can't afford it,'' he said, nearly
shouting, ``don't buy it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
