<SLUG> BC-SKINNYDIP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARE-BONES REALIST WELCOMES NEIGHBORS AT NUDIST RESORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA HELSER   
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (NEW RIVER, Ariz.) - New River When a New River nudist invited
neighborhood children over for free swimming lessons, skepticism
was as rampant as the saguaros surrounding his L-shaped pool.
</P>
<P>
   But Horst Kraus, the retired plumber who lives to bask in the
buff on his 38-acre spread called Shangri-La II Resort in New
River, 30 miles north of Phoenix, is also a bare-bones realist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know other people think we're weird,'' he said. ``So
anything we can do to change or kill that stigma, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Working under the premise that ``to know us is to love us,'' the
German-born naturalist who purchased the nudist resort 1{ years ago
opened his gates to neighbors so that any myths or
misunderstandings about naturalists might be dispelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, we have this pool and there's no place around here
for these kids to swim,'' he said. ``And if this avoids just one
water accident, then it's well worth keeping our clothes on for the
four hours every Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   In a flyer he circulated through the neighborhood, Kraus vowed
to make the ultimate sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised that resort residents would be `textiled' during
the lessons,'' said the grandfather of five. In other words, they
would be wearing their clothes between 10 a.m. and 2 p.m. every
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 22 families who live at Shangri-La full-time balked
at the proposed cover-up. To add an air of credibility, Kraus
enlisted the endorsement of the local Kiwanis Club, asking that one
or two members make an appearance at lessons.
</P>
<P>
   And after hiring a water safety instructor, Kraus and his wife,
Gigi, sat back and waited to see if anyone would accept their
hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured maybe 12 to 15 at the most,'' he said. To his
amazement, 56 children rolled up to the pink-colored gates June 2
for the first of 11 weekly classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been curious about this place but I'd never come
over here for something other than this because I'd be too shy,''
said Deanna Wakeling of New River. She rubbed sun block lotion on
her 10-week-old son, Micah, the youngest of the students, as her
four-year-old son, Seth, splashed nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Another mom admitted she was nervous about her first on-site
encounter at Shangri-La.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did sort of worry that we'd get here too early,'' said
Connie Rohkohl. ``But we looked at the clock and it was 10:08 so we
thought we were OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned there could be an accidental slip-up on the promised
cover-ups, Kraus asked two residents to post themselves near the
pool area. ``That's so someone doesn't stumble out of their
trailer, you know, who forgot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the swim instructor had a few fabricated misgivings about
her new job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the ad in the paper for an instructor and when I called
they asked if I knew what Shangri-La was,'' said Becca Dolk, 17.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I found out that they'd wear clothes, it was like,
yeah, because otherwise I'm not ready to handle that if they
didn't,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If Shangri-La members and residents had any reservations about
intruders into their turf, they, too, found their fears unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good idea,'' said Dot Crane of Black Canyon City, as
she watched at least 60 children enjoying the pool Tuesday. ``It
opens us up so people can see we're not a bunch of freaks.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Kraus, financing swim lessons for the neighborhood
children barely cost him anything.
</P>
<P>
   . ``My biggest expense was to buy myself some swim trunks,''
said Kraus, who usually swims in the all-together.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Helser can be reached at Linda.Helser(at)PNI.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
