<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3879 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACIAL-ATTACK-SUSPECT     06-10 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-ATTACK-SUSPECTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTERS REPORTEDLY REVEAL RACIST SIDE OF ONE OF THREE SUSPECTS IN
TEXAS MURDER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (12:01 a.m., EDT, EMBARGO for electronic media) 
 
By T.J. MILLING 
and KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ In a series of letters from prison that
frightened even his friends back home, one of three suspects in the
murder of a black man here proclaimed hatred for African-Americans
and allegiance to the Aryan Brotherhood, a relative of a
co-defendant said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think they came straight from a magazine,'' said the
woman, who agreed to be interviewed on the condition that her
relationship to Shawn Berry be kept confidential. ``They were just
unbelievable, all about being racist, about hating black people,
`Hail to the brotherhood!' and all that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The letters, she said, came from John William ``Bill'' King
while King was in a Texas prison for violating his parole on a
burglary charge. Berry had earlier served time for his role in the
same burglary.
</P>
<P>
   King and Berry, both 23, and Lawrence Brewer Jr., 31, now are
charged with the murder of James Byrd Jr., a black man allegedly
dragged by the ankles with a towing chain behind Berry's pickup for
nearly three miles early Sunday. Byrd's head and right arm were
ripped off in the attack that has generated national attention with
its savagery.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit largely is based on statements by Berry, who was
arrested first. It implicates the two other men for actually
beating and killing Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   All of the suspects are white, and state and federal officials
suspect the crime was racially motivated. On Wednesday, they said
they hope to upgrade the charges so they can pursue the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the the Rev. Jesse Jackson visited the small
East Texas timber town about 150 miles northeast of Houston and
urged reconciliation and unity among the races. As the crime
lingered in the spotlight, President Clinton and Texas Gov. George
W. Bush each condemned the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   And the search for answers continued.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Buentello, assistant director of the Texas prison system's
gang task force, said both King and Brewer had been monitored for
possible affiliation with the Ku Klux Klan and the Confederate
Knights of America, a skinhead group, while they were housed at the
Beto I Unit in Tennessee Colony in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Buentello said one of the men had been disciplined for
involvement in a 1995 racial disturbance between Anglos and
Hispanics at Beto. Prison records show that only King was in that
prison at that time.
</P>
<P>
   While at the Beto Unit, correspondence from King and Brewer was
monitored once officials there identified them as possible members
of racist groups. Guards also monitored which inmates they
associated with and their activities.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the three suspects was linked to membership in the
Aryan Brotherhood, one of the most violent gangs operating inside
the state prisons, Buentello added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Aryan Brotherhood is a whole different ball game,'' he
said. ``The Aryan Brotherhood is a group that has caused extensive
problems ... all kinds of acts of violence, including deaths. It's
a very dangerous group.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the KKK nor CKA is considered a violent prison gang
whose members must be segregated and sometimes placed in isolation
cells, Buentello said.
</P>
<P>
   He is awaiting photographs from Jasper County officials that
depict tattoos that could indicate gang affiliation. But even if
they do, Buentello said it is possible they were obtained outside
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of two prominent Klan groups in Texas have said they had
never heard of any of the suspects and were not aware of their
involvement in white supremacy activities.
</P>
<P>
   But before his release from prison last July, King wrote racist
letters to several people in the area, including some to a teen-age
girl whose parents were so disturbed by them that they called
prison officials to make him stop, Berry's relative said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were crazy letters,'' she said. ``It really scared
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The relative said King had long been known for making racist
jokes and remarks though she never knew of his acting on his
beliefs. She said she and Berry didn't take the letters seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has always done the racial thing, and all that, but we
didn't believe he felt it in his heart,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to laugh about it ... not laugh because it was funny,
but we were just amazed he would say it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even that comes as a surprise to Deanna Tubb of nearby
Woodville, who knew King from elementary and high school and whose
family often took the young King with them to church in Jasper. She
eventually married a cousin of King's. Tubb on Wednesday recalled
King as a low-key youth, not so much shy as unassuming.
</P>
<P>
   She said King participated in ``all the normal hell-raising'' in
high school, drinking and such, but she never heard any racist
language or noticed any aggressive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the last time she saw King a few months ago, after his
release from prison, she almost didn't recognize him. He was
bigger, of course, but he also sported tattoos up and down both
arms. Tubb didn't know what they meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I just noticed there were a lot of them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (King's father, Ronald King of Jasper, declined to speak with
the Houston Chronicle. In a brief written statement, he expressed
his sympathy for the victims and said, ``It hurts me deeply to know
that a boy I raised and considered to be the most loved boy I knew
could find it in himself to take a life.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tubb disputed the contention of some city officials that Jasper
does not have racial problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The n-word is pretty common,'' she said. ``A lot of people say
that around here, even if they don't admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry and King attended Jasper High School together in the
1990-91 school year, after which Berry transferred to Zavalla High
School in nearby Angelina County, Jasper school records show. King
attended Jasper High one more year, then the pair were arrested in
a Jasper County burglary.
</P>
<P>
   They were both sentenced to 10 years, but after a shock
probation ``boot camp'' in January 1993, Berry stayed out of
prison, Texas Department of Criminal Justice records show. King
also was given shock probation, and in January 1994 his academic
records were sent to Vidor High School, though it was unclear
whether he attended classes there.
</P>
<P>
   He was sent back to prison in June 1995 as a parole violator.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family warned Berry not to hang around King when he
was released from prison last July, the relative said. But, she
said, Berry was ``easily influenced'' and felt King had
``changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the relative and another older female relation, who also
would talk only if promised anonymity, said they had never met or
seen the third suspect, Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   The younger relative said Berry ``got in a fight or two'' and
got depressed now and then but was well-known in town, an outgoing
and likable young man who loved rodeo bull riding.
</P>
<P>
   The older woman said Berry had never known his father and had
some behavioral problems. But, she said, he was kind-hearted and a
hard worker who did everything from timber work to clearing fields
and mowing yards to working in the local theater box office.
</P>
<P>
   And, she said, he is not a racist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn is not a prejudiced young man,'' she said. ``Red,
yellow, black or white, it made no difference to him. ... He is not
a monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry's testimony in the affidavit states that he had offered
Byrd a ride in his pickup, which upset King, who cursed and shouted
racial epithets. He says that after the group stopped at a
convenience store, King took the wheel and drove into a remote
area.
</P>
<P>
   Berry also claims in the police statement that he ran a short
distance away when King and Berry first started beating Byrd but
King drove after him. He also says he asked King to let him out of
the truck while Byrd was being dragged on a chain, but that King
replied, ``You're just as guilty as we are. Besides, the same thing
could happen to a n-----lover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know with all my heart that Shawn wasn't involved with the
actual murder, in the hate,'' the younger relative said, ``but
there's no excuse for it no matter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
