u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-YANKEE-STADIUM-525     06-10 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-YANKEE-STADIUM-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLONE INTRODUCES STADIUM REFERENDUM BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Following through on a pledge that has contributed
significantly to his current budget battle with Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, Peter Vallone, the City Council speaker, introduced a
bill Wednesday that would put a referendum about the future of
Yankee Stadium on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing Giuliani of not caring about the opinion of ordinary
New Yorkers, Vallone said he wanted voters to decide whether
government money should be used to help build a new ballpark for
the Yankees in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The taxpayers of this city have every right to say, `Yes, I
want a new stadium in Manhattan,' or, `No, I want the Bronx Bombers
to stay in the Bronx,''' Vallone said at a news conference. ``That,
ladies and gentlemen, is what democracy is about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration immediately attacked the bill,
saying it was driven by the political ambitions of the speaker, who
is seeking the Democratic nomination for governor. The
administration also said the referendum would handcuff the city in
its negotiations with the Yankees. The team's principal owner,
George Steinbrenner III, said last week that Vallone's referendum
plan had pushed him to the edge of moving the team out of New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics and leadership in politics requires a certain degree
of wisdom, and not just pandering constantly to what public opinion
polls tell you,'' Giuliani said Wednesday at a news conference,
adding that a referendum would likely increase the Democratic voter
turnout for Vallone in the general election in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the calculation was he felt he would get 100,000 more
votes if he put this on the ballot,'' Giuliani said. ``So to create
a difficult problem in a very sensitive negotiation, which this
will no doubt do, for a city that has had a terrible record of
keeping sports teams, just in order to get yourself 100,000 votes
on the ballot, seems to me the wrong thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The referendum bill is considered certain to become law, because
Vallone has tight control over the Democratic-dominated council.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker introduced the bill as Giuliani vetoed more than
$196 million from a budget that the council passed on Friday in
defiance of the mayor. The budget negotiations collapsed last week,
in part because of the political impasse between the mayor and the
speaker over the Yankee Stadium issue. The Giuliani administration
has insisted that it will not agree to a budget unless Vallone
drops his plans for a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock caused the council to pass a budget without the
mayor's agreement for the first time since it acquired the
authority to do so under the 1989 city charter revision.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the budget implications raised by the referendum,
Giuliani and Vallone have starkly different views of where a new
Yankee Stadium should be and how to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor is trying to block Vallone's proposal from appearing
on the ballot this fall by creating a special commission to
recommend changes to the city charter. By state law, a charter
question takes precedence over all other ballot questions, and
would block the Yankee Stadium issue from being considered this
year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Vallone camp, in turn, is also helping a grass-roots
organization gather enough signatures in a petition drive intended
to put the stadium question on the ballot. If the group gathers
30,000 signatures, the question would be put before the voters
separately from the referendum called for by Vallone's bill, but a
charter commission initiative would knock both questions off the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum fight began after a half-ton steel beam fell on a
section of Yankee Stadium seats in April. The mayor revived a
proposal to build a stadium on the West Side of Manhattan, a
project that by some estimates could run as high as a $1 billion.
Giuliani said he wanted the team to stay in the Bronx, but a new
stadium was needed to keep the team profitable, and eliminating the
option of Manhattan could push Steinbrenner to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that a stadium in Manhattan would require both public and
private money, the mayor proposed extending a commercial rent tax
that he had previously sought to abolish, a tax scheduled to expire
in 2001 that would raise at least $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   But while Vallone said officials should study the possibility of
using public funds to help build a new stadium, he added that the
stadium should stay in the Bronx. He said moving the team out of
the Bronx would be an economic disaster for that borough and
financing a Manhattan stadium would be an undeserved gift to
Steinbrenner, whose ball club has earned him millions.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker proposed letting the voters decide the issue by
having the council put a referendum on the November ballot. And
members of his gubernatorial campaign are helping the grass-roots
organization _ Keep the Yankees in the Bronx _ in its separate
petition drive to put the stadium question on the ballot, Peter
Ragone, a spokesman for Vallone, said.
</P>
<P>
   By pushing for a referendum, Vallone is likely to derive
substantial benefits in his drive to challenge Gov. George Pataki
in the fall. In addition to increasing his name recognition,
Vallone, if he gets his referendum on the ballot, could drive up
voter turnout in Democratic strongholds like Manhattan and the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   In a defensive move, the mayor created a City Charter Revision
Commission to place a question on the November ballot. Under the
arcane rules governing the city charter and the state's Municipal
Home Rule Law, a charter question would bump from the ballot any
other referendum questions, either from the council or from a
petition drive, said Eric Lane, the executive director of the 1989
Charter Revision Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But because charter revision commissions were set up in the past
to review the fundamental workings of city government, Vallone's
aides said they are hoping to prevent Giuliani's commission from
putting a question on the ballot, possibly by arguing in court that
the question is not a serious one but merely an attempt to block
the stadium referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be legal and governmental reasons why the mayor's
charter commission won't be able to put its proposal on the
ballot,'' said Richard Weinberg, the council's general counsel. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
