A3884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FOSTER-PROFILE-NYT     06-10 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FOSTER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY DIRECTOR KNOWS THE NEEDS OF CHILDREN HARDLY CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like breezes off the Hudson River a few feet away,
new theories and fads in child welfare tend to blow through the
rolling campus of Leake and Watts Services every few decades,
ruffling the paperwork. Families should be preserved at all cost.
No, abusive families must be split up. Neglected children should
live together in a bucolic country setting. No, they should stay in
the neighborhood where they grew up.
</P>
<P>
   What hasn't changed much are the needs of the children
themselves. Since 1831, Irish, Polish, Italian and, more recently,
black and Hispanic children who could not or should not live with
their parents have depended on Leake and Watts to look after their
health, to straighten their lives, to guide them into adult
society.
</P>
<P>
   James Campbell, the nonprofit agency's executive director, has
helped lead them through the crises of AIDS and crack over the last
22 years, but an institution this old remembers far greater
upheavals in the lives of children: the Irish potato famine, the
Civil War, the Great Depression, the world wars.
</P>
<P>
   Given those 167 years of history, a new directive from City Hall
last week that once again rethinks the administration of child
welfare in New York City is not exactly shaking the foundations of
Leake and Watts, whose campus on the Bronx-Yonkers border was
designed by Frederick Law Olmsted back in the days when an ``orphan
asylum'' was a welcoming refuge from the horrors of 19th-century
life.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, like most people in the world of child welfare, says
his agency welcomes the changes toward more neighborhood-based
care, and he believes his staff is prepared for them. His response
demonstrates why, paradoxically, it may be some of the city's most
venerable institutions that possess the flexibility to weather
these moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a good idea, it will evolve and have its place,'' he
said this week, sitting in the Gothic main building that used to
house orphans in long, dormitory-style wards. ``When these places
got started, they called them asylums, and children were
indentured. Now we look back and say, `My God, that's awful.' Well
it wasn't awful at the time. Life was brutal at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Leake and Watts is one of a handful of social-service agencies
that arose from the industrialization of New York in the 19th
century that continue to dominate child welfare in the city,
matching children to foster parents, boarding children who cannot
be placed, and working with troubled families to reduce the need
for foster care.
</P>
<P>
   The agency was founded by John Watts, the last royal recorder of
New York City under British rule and a member of Congress, using
money from the estate of his brother-in-law, John George Leake, son
of the British commissary for stores during the French and Indian
Wars. Currently it serves some 2,500 children a year, about 95
percent of whom are black or Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, 61, a former Roman Catholic priest from Philadelphia
whose parents were Irish immigrants, is a bit of a departure from
the High Protestant churchmen who made Leake and Watts the epitome
of establishment noblesse oblige. (An 1848 cornerstone lists as
trustees the rector of Trinity Church and the senior ministers of
the Reformed Protestant Dutch Church and the Presbyterian Churches,
along with such names as Mayor Robert Morris and James Roosevelt,
the founder of Roosevelt Hospital.)
</P>
<P>
   He studied social work at Fordham University on orders from his
bishop and eventually ran Catholic Charities in Philadelphia before
leaving the priesthood and working for New York City's Child
Welfare Administration in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   His work running the Children's Center _ one of the city's least
successful efforts to gather children under one roof _ which was
closed in 1977, helped convince him that child welfare required a
much broader approach than the old-line agencies had traditionally
provided. After joining Leake and Watts, Campbell helped develop
one of the first programs for foster children with HIV., and began
to focus the agency's efforts almost exclusively on the Bronx,
where it opened several group homes, a family services center and
various Head Start and day care programs. It also established
alliances with Bronx community service groups like Banana Kelly and
Unitas.
</P>
<P>
   The concentration on one borough was prescient, because the
Giuliani administration's new proposal requires agencies to create
neighborhood-based networks in order to keep children in their
communities and bring foster families into regular contact with
their children's parents.
</P>
<P>
   John Courtney, a contributing editor of Child Welfare Watch,
said: ``They've been concentrating on the Bronx for some time, and
I think the city's new decentralization and community-based
approach should fit in comfortably with their structure. Other
agencies with a more citywide scope could have a more difficult
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, whose agency is the fourth largest of the 38 agencies
that contract with the city for foster care work, receiving about
$26 million a year in city money, says that while he's a bit
worried about the new applications to fill out, he has learned not
to be terribly surprised by any new idea that comes along.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call us traditional and established and all of those
things, but it's not like we haven't come up with a few new ideas
of our own over the years,'' he said. ``People who work in places
like this, who've been doing it for a long time, have a certain
accumulated knowledge.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
