<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3890 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOO-KOO-ROO-LADN     06-10 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOO-KOO-ROO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRENDY KOO KOO ROO CHICKEN CHAIN TO JOIN FAMILY FLOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The parent company of Chi-Chi's and El Torito
restaurants is buying Koo Koo Roo Inc. for $158.3 million in stock
and assumed debt, the companies announced.
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered Santa Monica-based chicken restaurant chain will
merge with privately held Family Restaurants Inc. of Irvine to form
Koo Koo Roo Enterprises Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, announced Wednesday, Koo Koo Roo shareholders
will exchange one common share for one share of stock from the new
company, giving them a 33 percent stake. The acquisition is
expected to close in 60 to 90 days, with the new company retaining
Koo Koo Roo's ticker symbol, KKRO.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will control 325 restaurants in 31 states and 11
foreign countries. No restaurants will be closed as a result of the
acquisition, and any potential layoffs will come from corporate
offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a great concept that has tremendous potential
for growth, in our opinion,'' said Kevin Relyea, chairman,
president and chief executive officer of Family Restaurants, who
will retain the same position at the new company. ``We believe that
Koo Koo Roo's proven that customers love the product.''
</P>
<P>
   William Allen, CEO of Koo Koo Roo, who will become a director of
the new company, said the chicken chain explored alternatives that
included borrowing more money or issuing more shares to raise
capital for growth. In the end, finding a buyer was the better
option, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Family Restaurants) was clearly the best partner for us,''
Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the merger agreement, Family Restaurants also
provided a $3 million loan to Koo Koo Roo, agreed to issue senior
debt for net proceeds of $21 million and will expand its existing
credit line by an additional $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Koo Koo Roo acting Chairman Lee Iacocca will join the new
company's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Iacocca calls the marriage ``an ideal strategic
fit,'' saying both companies will benefit by combining purchasing
power and administrative support.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts questioned the viability of the deal, given Family
Restaurants' current financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Family Restaurants had enough on its plate turning
around its own restaurants,'' said Mike Rowan, a senior analyst at
Moody's, a New York bond-rating agency. ``It's a highly leveraged
company. Its cash flow is barely meeting interest obligations. It
has pretty weak credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Moody's rated its bonds Caa2, which is ``deep junk'' and signals
a ``high potential of default'' within 18 to 24 months, Rowan said.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's, another New York bond-rating agency, rated
Family Restaurants' debt at CCC+ -- bonds of poor standing with a
negative outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Rowan said what's also troubling is that Family Restaurants
carries $200 million in long-term debt, which exceeds the total
value of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Chi-Chi's sites -- which generate more than half the company's
revenues -- only broke even for the first time last year, Rowan
said, based on EBITDA, or earnings before interest, taxes,
depreciation and amortization. The El Torito unit is profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Family Restaurants had $462 million in revenues and an EBITDA of
$18.4 million for the 12 months ended March 31. Over the same
period, Koo Koo Roo's revenues were $79.5 million with an EBITDA
loss of $22.7 million, which included $20.6 million in
restructuring and other charges.
</P>
<P>
   Koo Koo Roo, known for its flame-broiled chicken and fancy side
dishes, has not made money since at least 1993. While overall
revenue continued to rise -- from $5.8 million in 1993 -- losses
mounted yearly as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company, over the last several years, has accessed an
awful lot of capital and not employed that capital very
effectively,'' Allen said. ``We got into noncore businesses, as
well as hopscotching around the map opening up some stand-alone
units in outlying markets.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, the chicken chain appointed Iacocca, 73, a shareholder
and former Chrysler chairman, as its acting chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Iacocca took over in the midst of a company restructuring that
included the layoffs of some corporate employees and closures of
underperforming restaurants. Koo Koo Roo is seeking a buyer for
Color Me Mine, a ceramics painting chain it purchased in 1996. It
also has cut overhead by $8 million to $9 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Koo Koo Roo shares lost 7/16 to close at 2 7/16 on heavy trading
of 3.2 million shares, up 33 percent from its three-month average
daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
