<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-ATTACK-JACKSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON BRINGS MESSAGE OF RECONCILIATION TO REELING TEXAS TOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ As the Rev. Jesse Jackson brought a message of
reconciliation to this community reeling from a brutal murder,
local and federal authorities said they hope to get the death
penalty for two of the three white men accused of dragging a black
man behind a pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a new Jasper,'' Jackson told an overflow crowd of more
than 200 inside the Greater New Bethel Baptist Church as at least
that many more waited outside. The audience was overwhelmingly
black.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not tolerate hate on either side of town. I see a new
Jasper, a new heaven and new Earth where all of our children can
walk in peace together.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he came at the invitation of the family of James
Byrd Jr., who was killed early Sunday. He had been beaten, then
chained to a pickup by his ankles and dragged for almost three
miles along back country roads. His head and right arm were severed
from his body.
</P>
<P>
   The crime has shocked the nation, drawing statements of outrage
from President Clinton and Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said only religion can cure such sickness as the one that
killed Byrd, whose suspected attackers have ties to racist hate
groups. Clinton called upon the residents of Jasper to ``join
together across racial lines to demonstrate that an act of evil
like this is not what this country is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This family is hurting,'' Jackson told his church audience. He
said he plans to return Saturday for Byrd's funeral. He also said
that pro basketball player Dennis Rodman of the Chicago Bulls has
offered to pay for Byrd's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Don Clark, special agent in charge of the Houston FBI office,
said Wednesday that it is likely the slaying will be prosecuted as
a federal hate crime and civil rights case, making it possible to
seek a death sentence. But that decision may not be made for a
month.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney for Jasper County also plans to pursue
state capital murder charges. The maximum punishment for the charge
of murder is life in prison. Conviction for capital murder can mean
life in prison or death by injection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly have a murder and it is clearly a hate crime,''
District Attorney Guy James Gray said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pretty well satisfied that this deserves to be a
capital case,'' he said. ``We have three people here and we may
have to back off on one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the three white men accused in Byrd's &UR;  &LR; slaying gave
investigators a detailed account of the crime. That suspect, Shawn
Berry, 23, of Jasper, contends he had no role in the beating or
slaying. However, for the time being, he has been charged with
murder along with his companions, 23-year-old John William ``Bill''
King, also of Jasper, and 31-year-old Lawrence Brewer Jr. of
Sulphur Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said Berry has been the most cooperative of the three
defendants and the only one who has shown signs of remorse.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, a capital charge can be sought if a murder is
committed along with another felony. Gray said investigators are
now trying to make a case that Byrd was kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said his office is awaiting forensic evidence
before upgrading the charges, and it may take three weeks for a
crime laboratory to process it.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Denney, death investigator for the district attorney's
office, said the final autopsy was not complete. However, he said,
Byrd may have been unconscious but was alive when a towing chain
was put around his ankles and he was dragged from Berry's pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt very much that he could stay alive very long being
dragged down an asphalt road,'' Denney said, explaining that it may
be impossible to determine exactly at what point Byrd died.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement to investigators, Berry said Byrd was dragged
behind the truck along a twisting, hilly blacktopped road for
almost three miles.
</P>
<P>
   The three suspects, who remain in the county jail, will probably
be indicted after a new grand jury goes into session in July, Gray
said. All three have asked for court-appointed attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said that while he expects defense attorneys to seek a
change of venue to have the men tried elsewhere, ``this thing has
gotten plenty of publicity all over the state. I think we could try
it here just as well as anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said Byrd's slaying poses a character test for Jasper.
``That you have not extended the violence is a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   The test, he said, will be to see if the shock felt by both
black and white Jasper residents can be the catalyst for finding
new ways for different parts of the community to work together.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when he arrived at the home of Byrd's parents
Wednesday afternoon, he was met by a line of both white and black
ministers. He also noted that Jasper's black mayor and white
sheriff seem to be working together during the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has an amazing way of doing great things through small
towns,'' Jackson said, noting that Jesus was born in a small town
and Rosa Parks did not stand up against racism in New York but in
Montgomery, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Using Byrd's boyhood nickname, he said, ``Just maybe Toe Byrd
has become a mark of a new day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reporters Carlos Byars and Ronnie Crocker contributed to this story
from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
