<HEADER>
A3904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HATE-COURT-COX     06-10 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HATE-COURT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three suspects held without bond in Texas mureder
 &HT;    By Mitch Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Authorities in the small East Texas town of
Jasper said those guilty in the gruesome slaying of a 49-year-old
black man deserve to be charged with the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Those same authorities asked that their own town not be judged
guilty by association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our opinion that this horrible crime warrants a capital
offense,'' Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles said.
</P>
<P>
   James Byrd Jr.'s body was found on a dirt road Sunday about five
miles east of Jasper. Byrd was beaten into unconsciousness, tied
with a chain to the rear of a pickup truck, then dragged behind the
truck for three miles.
</P>
<P>
   His head, neck and right arm were ripped away from his body
during the murder. His face was shredded beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, of Sulphur Springs, Texas, and
Shawn Allen Berry and John William King, both 23 and both of
Jasper, have been charged with murder in the slaying and are being
held without bond in the Jasper County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray said murder
charges could be upgraded to federal charges or capital charges,
but it may take anywhere from a few days to three weeks before
those charges can be filed.
</P>
<P>
   Murder charges carry a maximum sentence of life in prison, while
conviction on a capital murder charge can be punished by life in
prison or death by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Gray explained that, before capital murder charges or federal
charges under the hate crime statute can be brought, strict legal
criteria must be met.
</P>
<P>
   Hate crimes must also have a violation of civil rights component
and Texas law requires a murder to be committed while in commission
of another felony to warrant capital crime status in this case,
Gray explained.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said investigators are pursuing a kidnapping angle and
federal agents are wrestling with the violation of civil rights
aspect of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The state may have to offer one suspect a plea bargain agreement
in order to pursue upgraded charges with the other two suspects,
but Gray said the state has not reached that point yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we have three people here and we might have to back
off one to establish the facts in the case,'' Gray said. ``We're
not ready right now to make that call.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said it is evident that the murder was a hate crime. King,
Berry and Brewer are suspected of having connections to white
supremacist groups and two have tattoos that have been linked to
the Aryan Nation, a white racist prison gang, Rowles said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the suspects also owned a lighter with a triangular
symbol identified as a sign of the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   In a sworn affidavit Berry said King referred to the ``Turner
Diaries,'' a book read believed to espouse white supremist ideas.
</P>
<P>
   All through Berry's statement, he referred to racial comments
and derogatory references made toward Byrd as King and Brewer
allegedly beat Byrd, then tore his body to pieces, leaving him dead
at the end of a bloody three-mile trail.
</P>
<P>
   Rowles took the last few minutes of a Wednesday press conference
in Jasper to say that most of the people in Jasper are good,
hard-working people. He asked that the world not brand the
community because of the horrible nature of the crime that was
committed there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jasper County Texas is typical middle America,'' Rowles said.
``The white community is just as appalled about this as the black
community is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the country to know that Jasper, Texas, is the best
place in the world to raise your family.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
