<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0573 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASTLE-COX     06-10 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judges sets bail in Castle Case
 &HT;    By Christine Stapleton and Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A judge in Seattle set bail at $10
million Wednesday for Darion ``Sam'' Northrup Castle, the fugitive
sailor, lumberjack and boat builder who fled Florida in 1977 to
avoid a 10-year prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The bail covers the only new charge that Seattle prosecutors
filed against Castle: being a fugitive from justice. Castle will
return to a Seattle courtroom June 24 to determine the status of
his extradition to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach County, Circuit Judge Ron Alvarez signed court
papers Wednesday to hold Castle without bail in his 1970 arson case
when he returns to Florida. Local prosecutors said they're barred
from filing new charges against Castle for fleeing the state
because Seattle prosecutors already have filed a fugitive charge.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no chance that Castle will face a first-degree
murder charge for the burning death of his girlfriend, Mary
Patricia Kirby. Castle and Kirby were severely burned on Labor Day
weekend in 1970 when they burned the 30-foot sailboat named Kuewa,
``vagabond'' in Hawaiian, which Castle had built. Castle, embroiled
in a nasty divorce, had a $15,000 insurance policy on the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby died three weeks later after the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Under Florida law a person can be charged with first-degree
murder if someone is killed during the commission of a felony, such
as arson. Both Castle and Kirby were initially charged with arson,
but the charges were not upgraded to murder after Kirby's death.
</P>
<P>
   Local prosecutors say they're barred from filing a murder charge
against Castle now because court rules require prosecutors to file
all charges stemming from one incident at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972 a jury convicted Castle of three counts of arson, and he
was sentenced to 10 years in prison, the maximum sentence. But he
remained free for five more years while he appealed. Castle claimed
that firefighters had illegally seized evidence, including plastic
bags full of gasoline, when they put out the blaze on the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Florida appeals courts rejected Castle's appeals, and he took
his case to the U.S. Supreme Court, where he also lost.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 2, 1977, Castle was supposed to surrender to begin
serving his sentence. He never showed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents believe Castle _ a towering figure at 6-feet-7
and the scion of a wealthy Hawaiian pioneer family _ and his second
wife had lived in the Seattle area for about five years until his
arrest Tuesday. All that time, Castle's apartment manager knew him
as Mark Bradfield _ the name of the Palm Beach County prosecutor
who convicted him 26 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Castle's wife, a Tallahassee woman who has traveled with the
fugitive since the 1970s, apparently uses the name Linda Sue
Castle, agents said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI in West Palm Beach learned a few months ago that the
couple might have been living in the western United States. Agents
began looking for them in Hawaii, California and Washington state,
said Reid Robertson, agent-in-charge of the FBI's West Palm Beach
office.
</P>
<P>
   They found out that Linda Sue was scheduled to fly Monday into
Seattle from Hawaii, where Castle's family lives, said agent Gary
Schoenlein. After landing, she changed clothes and led
investigators in circles before driving to the apartment where
Castle was arrested, agents said.
</P>
<P>
   At the King County jail, Castle has not admitted his identity,
refusing to be fingerprinted or photographed, Robertson said. He
may be forced to submit to both by court order. His lawyer, Michael
Nance could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics, along with his family's wealth and a well-timed
blizzard, helped Castle elude capture for 21 years, agents say.
</P>
<P>
   After Castle failed to surrender in 1977, agents tracked him by
following the travels of his father's private plane across the
Northwest, said Jim Cavanaugh, a retired FBI agent now living in
Bangs, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Cavanaugh tried for 14 years to catch Castle, and he still keeps
a picture of Castle and his wife taken along a fenceline in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Castle never held a steady job though he did work for a time as
a lumberjack, Cavanaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was basically a loner,'' Cavanaugh said. ``I saturated the
Northwest with his photograph.''
</P>
<P>
   It nearly paid off in 1979, when authorities in British Columbia
thought they found Castle, calling himself Sam Coleman, living in a
trailer park. But Canadian officials, working under legal time
constraints, had to let him go when they couldn't confirm his
identity in time.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian courts required Castle's original fingerprints to
verify his identity, Cavanaugh said. But the fingerprint card was
at FBI headquarters in Washington, D.C., where a snowstorm closed
the airport and prevented Cavanaugh from getting his man.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Castle asked an Alaska lawyer if he still could be
extradited; the lawyer called the FBI's West Palm Beach office to
make sure the warrant was valid, Cavanaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Castle later was featured on the television show Unsolved
Mysteries, prompting sightings of the giant sailor in Mexico,
Australia and other far-flung locales. Castle is a descendant of
Samuel Northrup Castle, one of the earliest settlers in Hawaii and
co-founder in 1851 of Castle &AMP; Cooke, a mercantile company that
eventually became part of the Dole produce company. Castle &AMP; Cooke
now is a Los Angeles real estate company with properties in
Florida, California and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   A person reached Wednesday at Castle's family's home in Volcano,
Hawaii, refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
