<SLUG> BC-NY-UPS-THEFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 DRIVERS CHARGED IN THEFTS FROM UPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Six drivers for the United Parcel Service were
charged Wednesday with participation in a theft ring that federal
prosecutors said stole more than $175,000 in jewelry, computers and
other goods from delivery trucks and the services' midtown
distribution center.
</P>
<P>
   A 74-count indictment unsealed Wednesday, which stemmed from an
undercover operation run by the FBI, accused the six drivers in
Manhattan of selling the stolen property to bureau agents.
Officials of UPS said it was the biggest theft ring involving its
drivers in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Four doormen and two elevator operators who work in the Chelsea
area, as well as a former truck loader in UPS' midtown distribution
center, were also charged in the case.
</P>
<P>
   A law enforcement official who spoke on condition of anonymity
said some of the property was stolen from company conveyer belts in
the large distribution center at 632 West 43rd St., as well as from
trucks making pickups and deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   Because the federal investigation paid only about a third of
what the stolen property was actually worth, the official said, the
actual value of the stolen property was closer to $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   The company first reported suspicions about a theft ring to the
FBI last year, and has cooperated fully ever since, a company
spokesman, Robert Godlewski, said by telephone from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take seriously all threats to the security of the 12
million packages entrusted to our care every day,'' Godlewski said.
``I've heard of the isolated incidents where you've got a driver
who works in the hub who is taking stuff out of there _ penny-ante
stuff. Man, this is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the year-long investigation, an agent posed as a middleman
who trafficked in stolen merchandise and worked out of a warehouse,
whose location was not disclosed in the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. Attorney in Manhattan, and Lewis D.
Schiliro, assistant director in charge of the bureau's New York
field office, said in a joint statement that there were 67
instances in which stolen property was sold to an undercover agent
and a witness who was working secretly with the government.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers were based in the company's 43rd Street distribution
center, which handles more than one million packages a week, and
some held routes that took them through Chelsea, the indictment
said.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the doormen and elevator operators was not fully
described, but the law enforcement official said that in some
cases, the drivers would entrust the stolen property to the doormen
and elevator operators, who had access to areas in their buildings
where the stolen items could be stored.
</P>
<P>
   Among the drivers charged in the case, Robert Volpe, whose 19
years as a driver for the company was the longest service among
those charged, was assigned a route that included West 19th Street
between Fifth Avenue and Avenue of the Americas, the indictment
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors accused Volpe of conspiring with a doorman at 16-20
West 19th St., who was described in the indictment only as Ralph,
to steal more than $90,000 in gold rings, New York State lottery
tickets, cameras, jewelry, beepers, Swiss Army knives, watches and
women's T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Volpe and Ralph sold the stolen property directly
from Volpe's delivery truck, the indictment said. Volpe and the
doorman were also charged with offering to sell about 15 pounds of
marijuana to the undercover agent.
</P>
<P>
   In court Wednesday, Judge Sharon Grubin released Volpe on
$75,000 bail. Others charged in the case were also released on
bond. Volpe's lawyer, Leonard Joy, said that neither he nor his
client would comment. Volpe could face up to 15 years in prison on
conspiracy and theft charges, as well as five years on the drug
charge, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as Manny Lopez, a driver for the company, was making
his deliveries on West 19th Street, some of his customers were
surprised to see him, instead of their regular driver, Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's saying, `Where's Bobby? Where's Bobby?''' said
Lopez. ``I didn't know if he was on vacation or sick.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
