<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUEEN RETAINS STAR APPEAL  
 ROYAL ART  
 SUITS AND COUNTERSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 BY JAMES BARRON WITH MATTHEW J. ROSENBERG AND JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few quick facts about Dinah Washington for those
who have forgotten or were too young to remember:
</P>
<P>
   In her prime she was known as the ``Queen of the Blues.'' And
she made it onto a postage stamp before Elvis did. And the premiere
of ``Dinah Was,'' a musical about Ms. Washington's life starring
Yvette Williams, was produced by Jean Doumanian. Which explains the
star power of the opening-night audience at the Gramercy Theater,
on 23rd Street near Lexington Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   About five minutes before curtain time, Woody Allen (whose films
are produced by Ms. Doumanian) was fingering a fortune-cookie he
said he had found in the pocket of the suit he was wearing: ``You
will be fortunate in the opportunities presented to you.'' But he
was reluctant to apply that to Ms. Washington's life. (She was
married seven times and died at age 39.)
</P>
<P>
   Jason Alexander, who is directing the upcoming film ``Cherry
Pink'' (which is also being produced by Ms. Doumanian), feigned
confusion. ``Dinah Washington?'' he said with a smile. ``I thought
the show was about Dinah Shore.''
</P>
<P>
   A Prince's Art to Be Auctioned
</P>
<P>
   The New York Academy of Art said Wednesday that Prince Charles
had joined the list of artists who have contributed items to be
sold at its ``Take Home a Nude'' auction next Wednesday. So are
there any subjects without clothes in the Prince's lithograph? ``I
have no idea,'' said Joe Heissan, the academy's director of
development, explaining that it had not been delivered yet. ``They
could be hiding.'' Already at the academy are an Eric Fishl
watercolor and a William Wegman photograph (of his dogs, of course,
and of course, they are ``not dressed,'' as Heissan put it).
</P>
<P>
   Prince Harry is headed for the playing fields of Eton. Harry,
13, was thrilled to pass the entrance exam for the exclusive
boarding school that his big brother, Prince William, entered three
years ago, the royal family said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Entangled In a Legal Brawl
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those late-night arguments in a bar, and like so
many late-night arguments in bars, it ended with an arrest and a
court date. But Elaine's, the watering hole of the rich and famous
on the Upper East Side of Manhattan, is not just any bar. The
person arrested on April 4 was the owner, Elaine Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   The court date was Wednesday, and the assault charges against
Ms. Kaufman, 69, were dismissed. But the legal battles have only
just begun.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaufman's lawyers said they planned to file a million-dollar
lawsuit against the customer who accused her of slapping him during
a dispute over a drink. And lawyers for the customer, James
Sorrels, said that they are suing Ms. Kaufman for $12 million for
``infliction of injury'' and slander.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrels, a 49-year-old marketing executive, said in court papers
that he was having a drink with a friend when Kaufman pounced on
him. He said that she appeared annoyed that he had bought just one
alcoholic drink (for himself) and a soft drink (for his friend). He
said she told him, ``You people look to me like poor white trash.
I'll bet you $50 you can't afford to buy another drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ms. Kaufman nor her lawyers appeared before Judge Thomas
Farber in Manhattan Criminal Court Wednesday, when prosecutors
asked that the criminal charges be dismissed. ``The dispute did not
rise to criminal conduct,'' Luke McGrath, the assistant district
attorney in charge of the case, said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaufman's lawyer, Ronald Fischetti, said she would file her
own lawsuit for malicious prosecution. Referring to Sorrels,
Fischetti said, ``We have witnesses that will come forward and show
his version is completely wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
