A3956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LILCO-NYT     06-10 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LILCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGED POWER COMPANY IS GETTING OFF TO A ROCKY START
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y., _ The first 13 days of corporate marriage
between Long Island Lighting Co. and the Brooklyn Union Gas holding
company has turned into a stormy honeymoon, with both sides
fighting over their prenuptial agreement and vying for control of
their partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The directors of their newly merged entity, Marketspan Corp.,
will gather in the old LILCO headquarters in Hicksville on Thursday
for the inaugural board meeting. But what might have been a festive
occasion may now become a battle zone.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan's chairman, William Catacosinos, is under attack by
Gov. George Pataki for getting $42 million in special compensation
as LILCO chairman on the eve of the state's takeover of the
electricity service.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's call for Catacosinos' ouster from Marketspan was
fortified on Monday. A letter from 22 of Long Island's 23
Republican state legislators pleaded with the merged company's new
president, Robert Catell, to seek the chairman's removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a full-court press to get Catacosinos out,'' said a
state senate staff member, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But Catacosinos, a wily infighter, has refused to budge. Some
insiders say that to bolster his own position, Catacosinos has been
fomenting opposition to Catell, who before the merger was chairman
of Brooklyn Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard talk about a move to dump Catell _ that would be a
huge mistake, a big, big mistake,'' said the state attorney
general, Dennis Vacco, at a news conference here. His staff is
investigating $67 million in executive payments _ $42 million to
Catacosinos and $25 million to 25 other LILCO officials.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki contends that the payments violated a provision in the
state's takeover agreement barring severance pay because all 8,000
LILCO and Brooklyn Union workers were guaranteed jobs with
Marketspan. The former LILCO executives say their payments were
legal entitlements.
</P>
<P>
   Public furor over the payments grew Wednesday. Three
class-action suits seeking restitution for LILCO shareholders were
filed in State Supreme Court here. (This may be difficult, as the
LILCO executives have already received their money.) And a series
of elected officials and candidates denounced the payments and
called for federal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   There was also private anger within Marketspan. Catell has told
some people that he was surprised and disturbed by the last-minute
LILCO payments. It stirred resentment and distrust among Brooklyn
Union's executives, who received no bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Catacosinos nor Catell responded to requests for
interviews, but a Marketspan spokesman, Joseph McDonnell, denied
there was internal dissension. He said that both executives still
supported the plan for Catacosinos to become the chairman and chief
executive, while Catell serves as president and chief operating
officer for a year. Then Catell is to assume the post of chief
executive. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2303EDT &QL; 
