<SLUG> BC-BOEING-ROLLOUT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING'S NEWEST, SMALLEST PLANE ROLLS OFF THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Although they came to see the rollout of
the new 717, what many Douglas workers had on their minds Wednesday
was a plane that is now built in Seattle and soon could be built
here _ the 737.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has already shifted some 737 work to its Long Beach plant
to help ease production bottlenecks in Renton, and is seriously
considering opening a Long Beach line for some versions of the 737
such as the Boeing Business Jet and 737s sold as convertible
freighters.
</P>
<P>
   Although the issue was not addressed by any of the rollout
speakers, Boeing executives in interviews afterward said their
study of a new 737 production line is about half finished and a
decision will definitely be made this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we are trying to do is make the right decision for the
total Boeing Co. and use all the assets we have,'' said Boeing
President Harry Stonecipher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred Mitchell and his team will make that decision. They will
come forward and make a recommendation, and we generally follow the
recommendation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is executive vice president of airplane production for
Boeing. He came to Long Beach Monday to check on the 737 work
already under way here.
</P>
<P>
   Five 737s have so far been flown from Seattle for final interior
work and refurbishment at the underused Douglas factory. Five more
737s are to come.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has announced it will end production of the MD-80, MD-90
and MD-11 here, leaving only the new 717 rolling out the factory
door after early 2000. Douglas workers interviewed over the past
few days all said they believe the future of the Douglas plant
depends more on getting a 737 line than production of the 717.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Chairman Phil Condit said the bottom line for any
decision on a new Long Beach production line is the unit cost of
building planes here vs. Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it cost to produce the airplane? What facilities do
we have? What are the costs of moving? What are the costs of
building more capability in Seattle? You are looking at what it
takes to produce that airplane because in the end that's what
drives the market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Boeing Business Jet and 737 convertible
freighters, Condit said Boeing has not ruled out producing the
next-generation 737-900 in Long Beach. The model, for which Alaska
Airlines is the launch customer, has not yet entered production.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the largest 737 ever
</P>
<P>
   built.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has more than 800 back orders for its next generation 737
family, which has become the fastest-selling airplane ever.
</P>
<P>
   But its Renton plant is being taxed as the company ramps up
production to 24 planes a month by the second quarter of next year,
thus the close look at the underused Douglas facility.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he is impressed with the Douglas work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are really working hard to show they have the
capability to stay in this business,'' he said, standing a few feet
from the 717 as Douglas workers crowded around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This product right behind us (the 717) is a typical example,
where they took a tough assignment and came through on it. Now we
have some 737s down here and they are doing an excellent job. We
have a very, very efficient work staff here that's going through
some really trying times.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said only a ``handful'' of Boeing people will be
involved in deciding whether a new 737 line will be set up in Long
Beach. He would not discuss the cost of tooling for the line, which
some analysts have said could be as as much as $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at efficiencies,'' he said. ``We have to make
sure we can do it cost-effectively. To move an airplane is a very
big decision. You don't do that overnight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
