<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-MERCURY-OPENER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY  AFRAID OF SLOW START  
 LATE ARRIVALS IN CAMP SPUR CHEMISTRY CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ When the smoke cleared from some agonizing Mercury
cuts, a hard fact remained.
</P>
<P>
   A team with more than one-third of its active roster in training
camp for only two days must open the WNBA season at 7 tonight
against an opponent it beat four times last year by an average of
17 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento Monarchs (10-18 in 1997) are hungry and
dangerous. They have what could become the league's best backcourt
in rookie point guard Ticha Penicheiro and Ruthie Bolton-Holifield,
hero of the U.S. team that won the gold medal in the World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Defending Western Conference champion Phoenix (16-12) had better
beware. No matter how much deeper the Mercury is on paper, any team
fresh from hand-shaking introductions is vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to understand the first two weeks are going to be a
little bit difficult for us,'' said point guard Michele Timms, one
of a half-dozen players who arrived this week from the World
Championships. ``I think our expectations can't be too high.
Obviously, we don't want to lose any of the games, but we've got to
understand it's going to be pretty ugly out there. Especially for
our supporters, just bear with us until we jell as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   All the late arrivals made the team, although 6-foot-5 center
Marlies Askamp (plantar fascia/left foot) and guard/forward Mikiko
Hagiwara (tendinitis/left knee) begin the season on the injured
list. They will miss at least three games. When either returns,
June 21 at the earliest, someone off the active roster of 11 must
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (cut) has been very difficult to go through,''
Coach-General Manager Cheryl Miller said. ``They've given us
everything we wanted. I pleaded with the league for 13 spots, but
they didn't give them to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate this part of the job. You can call it a character flaw,
and I'm the first one to admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the final five players released were Tia Jackson, a 1997
second-round draft pick whose career never took off because of
injuries, and Dena Evans, a free agent with American Basketball
League experience who lost out as Timms' backup to Australian
Kristi Harrower.
</P>
<P>
   Harrower and Michelle Griffiths, a 6-foot-1 power forward who
survived the cut, were teammates with Timms on the bronze
medal-winning team at the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kristi is going to fill my shoes on the national team,'' Timms
said. ``And Michelle is going to surprise everyone. Back home and
around the world, she's known as poetry in motion. She can be a
nice surprise packet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury is expected to open with the starting lineup that
finished the season: Timms and Bridget Pettis at guards, Umeki Webb
and Toni Foster at forwards and Jennifer Gillom at center. Webb is
the most vulnerable because of the offensive skills that
third-round draft pick Brandy Reed offers.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the last player on her bench is capable of playing
20 or more minutes and could start elsewhere in the 10-team league.
Timms agreed that the Mercury is much deeper and better prepared
for a Western Conference that now includes defending champion
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``No offense to anyone, but there is no comparison between the
two years (in talent),'' she said. ``We're bigger, we're stronger,
we're faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento is rebuilt, its only returners being Bolton-Holifield
and forwards Latasha Byears and Bridgette Gordon. They will be
joined in the starting lineup by Penicheiro, the league's No. 2
overall draft pick out of Old Dominion, and Linda Burgess, obtained
from the Los Angeles Sparks in a trade for Pam McGee.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton-Holifield made back-to-back three-pointers in the final
two minutes of the World Championships gold medal game Sunday as
the United States overcame Russia, 71-65.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarches were 0-2 in exhibitions, losing to the Sparks. The
Mercury won twice over the Utah Starzz. Sacramento is undersized
and has an inexperienced bench that includes Arizona's Adia Barnes,
the Pac-10 Player of the Year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
