A4086 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-ACKERMAN-Q&AMP;A-AZR &LR;      06-10 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ACKERMAN-Q&AMP;A-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECTATIONS RISE IN YEAR 2 FOR WNBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Success in the inaugural season of the WNBA brought honors for
league President Val Ackerman. She was named Grand Marketer of the
Year by Brandweek magazine after the league had a regular-season
attendance average of 9,669 (more than twice its conservative
predictions), signed multiyear agreements with the likes of
Anheuser-Busch, Coca-Cola, General Motors, McDonald's, Nike and
Sears, and, through its three-network national television alliance,
attracted more than 50 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman also was awarded the Distinguished Alumna Award from
the University of Virginia, where she was a four-year basketball
starter and two-time Academic All-American. She graduated from
Virginia in 1981 and from the UCLA law school in '85, then joined
the NBA as a staff attorney in '88. After eight years as an NBA
executive, she was named to head the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent conference call with reporters, Ackerman discussed
Year 2 of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Question: What will be the early impact for teams with so many
players coming off the World Championships?
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman: My hope is that they can assimilate as quickly as
possible. In some cases, we do have players that were in the league
last year and to the extent they are accustomed to their coaches
and teammates, they will at least have a head start on what the
offenses and defenses will be. Obviously when you have new players
like Rachael Sporn, Alessandra Santos de Oliveira, Michelle
Griffiths or Maria Stepanova, just to name a few, I think there
will be an adjustment period. It may well take weeks for them to
become acclimated not only to their teams, but to living in the
United States. It is just one of the areas we're going to have to
do the best we can because we expect going forward, there will be
scheduling issues with international events.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you view the signings of this year's college seniors as a
turning point in terms of people wanting to join your league?
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman: The fundamental difference between this year and last
year in our acquisition efforts was we hadn't yet had a season last
year. No one could imagine, no matter how hard we tried to explain
it, just exactly what the league would be like, the fans we would
attract and the amount of exposure we would generate. We found all
the players that we had discussions with had seen a game on
television or had come to games, and they had read about us. In
many cases, they had teammates who were with one of our teams who
could speak firsthand about the way they were treated by our teams,
what it felt like to play a game in Madison Square Garden or
America West Arena in front of 16,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you anticipate any problems with sustaining momentum in
Year 2?
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman: We're very sensitive to the issue. We don't take
anything for granted at this point. We were very surprised by the
results last year. It has made us work even harder to make sure
this year that not only our internal expectations but the
expectations of others will be met. We have projected this year a
leaguewide attendance average of 10,000 fans. We're hoping to crack
the five-figure mark, a little bit of an increase from last year.
Nevertheless, we recognize this year is a test because the
curiosity is lessened and the novelty is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the status of the players union?
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman: It's a league issue, but it's not a league process.
It's in the hands of the players as to whether or not they feel
like they want to be unionized as a way to deal with management,
and what the timing would be. If the union came to pass, they would
have to identify what the issues would be from their standpoint. If
it were to happen, we would try to be as constructive as we can in
dealing with the issues that were brought before us. In the
meantime, what we do is continue to try and make the league as
positive an experience as we can for the players, keeping in mind
our business objectives and our intended interests in operating in
a way that's going to give us the best chance of staying in
business. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
