<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-RECRUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNCIL SIDES WITH OLDER POLICE CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The City Council voted overwhelmingly Wednesday to
override Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's veto of a bill that would allow
40 candidates to enter the Police Academy although they exceed the
age limit of 34 for recruits.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates for the police force, some in their mid-40s, had
come within two days of joining the academy last year when they
were told they were ineligible because the age limit, which had
expired at the time they took their entrance tests, had been
restored. After passing the physical and psychological exams
required to enter the academy, many of the would-be recruits had
sold their businesses or quit their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   They turned to the Council for help, hoping to join an academy
class that is scheduled to begin on July 1. The Council responded
by passing a bill that exempted the 40 candidates, and the mayor
promptly vetoed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, after passionate speeches invoking civil-rights
leaders, the Council voted 43-4 to override that veto. In a rare
move, three of the seven Republicans on the council broke with the
mayor to support the override.
</P>
<P>
   Council members contended that the bill was a matter of simple
fairness for the 40 older candidates who still want to be officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is reached where whatever the exact legalities, the
decent thing to do when you have such qualified people is to let
them through,'' said Councilman Sheldon Leffler, chairman of the
Public Safety Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani and his police commissioner, Howard Safir, asserted
that giving those candidates a break would open the city to
lawsuits from scores of would-be officers. The older recruits,
police officials say, could endanger citizens and other officers
because they would be slower and less fit.
</P>
<P>
   Safir called the vote ``outrageous and ridiculous.'' He added,
``There are, indeed, many 70-year-olds who are quite active and
robust, but that certainly is not the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the Council said they hoped Wednesday's vote would
help energize members before a special meeting Thursday, when party
leaders will ask the Council to flex its political muscle again and
override the mayor's veto of major parts of the new city budget.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Annette Robinson, D-Brooklyn, said, ``We have a
right and a responsibility to serve as a check and balance to the
mayor.'' And Councilman Stanley Michels, a Democrat from Manhattan,
said, ``In my 21 years here, I don't remember being more proud of
the Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Mastro, the deputy mayor for operations, said the city was
likely to go to court to try to prevent the older candidates from
joining the academy class that begins July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there anyone in New York City who wants 60-year-old rookie
cops on the beat?'' Mastro said. ``No _ except for the City
Council.''
</P>
<P>
   The class of officers took the entrance examination during a
brief period when the age requirement had lapsed, but it later was
restored. A lawsuit on behalf of the candidates by the New York
Civil Liberties Union is pending in state Supreme Court in
Manhattan, but the candidates turned to the Council in hope of
quicker action. The 40 people who still hope to join the force
range in age from 36 to 49, according to their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the candidates, Aida Perez, 40, of Queens, said she
believed that the older candidates had proved they would make
effective officers by ``taking a very adverse situation and
demonstrating problem-solving abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald DiPippo, 42, of the Bronx, said, ``We weren't trying to
slip in. This was something I'd wanted to do all my life, and they
told me this was my chance. They said it was an equal-opportunity
test, and I trusted the Police Department.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
