<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NIGHTCLUB-BEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LAWYER FOR DEFENDANT IN BEATING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. _ A white man from Queens, who was charged with
the near-fatal beating of a black man outside a Westhampton Beach
nightclub two years ago, had his lawyer replaced Wednesday by a
judge who noted that the defendant owed more than $73,000 in legal
fees and had no way to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The bills were from Bruce Barket of Garden City, who for nearly
two years represented the indigent defendant, Austin Offen,
including a five-week trial that ended on April 8 with a hung jury.
Barket told the judge he would be willing to defend Offen in a
second trial, but only as a court-appointed lawyer paid by the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Offen, 27, is accused of beating Shane Daniels, 23, of Riverhead
with an iron bar outside the Club Marakesh on May 26, 1996, causing
severe skull injuries. He is being held in the Suffolk County jail
in $500,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-page decision dated June 9 and issued Wednesday
afternoon, Judge Joel Lefkowitz of Suffolk County Criminal Court
rejected Barket's request for state assistance and relieved him as
Offen's counsel. The judge requested that the Legal Aid Society of
Suffolk County assign Offen a new lawyer from its list of
volunteers and ordered Offen to return to court on Friday for a
hearing with his new lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Barket had asked the judge to dismiss him and then reappoint him
as Offen's Legal Aid lawyer at the society's rate of $40 an hour.
Barket's original agreement with Offen provided for payment of
$1,500 for each day of trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lefkowitz said Barket's request to be dismissed stated that
trying the case a second time would result in a conflict of
interest between Offen and his other paying clients. While granting
Barket's motion for dismissal, the judge declined to reappoint him.
</P>
<P>
   Lefkowitz noted that Barket had recently left a partnership and
was now a sole practitioner. ``Therefore he has no one to rely on
in order to properly maintain his practice or assist his other
clients,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any event, a defendant does not have the right to select an
attorney'' from the Legal Aid Society's list of lawyers willing to
represent the poor, the judge concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Barket could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Offen's new lawyer will have to become familiar with the
testimony of the more than 40 witnesses presented by the
prosecution during the first trial. Daniels, whose peripheral
vision remains severely limited, says he has no memory of the
early-morning attack.
</P>
<P>
   Offen's defense will be further complicated because his second
trial will be merged with that of his co-defendant, Constantine
Chronis, 37, a former New York City detective charged with holding
back Daniels' friends with a gun while, witnesses say, Offen beat
Daniels and shouted racial epithets.
</P>
<P>
   Chronis, who has since resigned from the police, is charged with
assault and criminal misconduct and is free on $200,000 bond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0583 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4094 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WorldCup-HNS &LR;      06-10 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World </SLUG>
 Cup-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Brazil shows Scotland 
the stuff of champions
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAINT DENIS, France _ Every few minutes before Wednesday's 1998
World Cup opener, metro trains pulled into the Porte de la Chapelle
stop outside the Stade de France and swells of painted Brazilian
fans surged out the doors.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unstoppable Brazilian rush, like a tidal wave of
green-and-yellow energy swarming France.
</P>
<P>
   The doors swung open, and hundreds of bodies pushed their way
out of the overstuffed car, elbowing, squeezing, falling over one
another. They were beating drums and blowing whistles. They were
carrying each other on their shoulders, waving flags and holding
beers or bottles of wine in each hand.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Later on the way to a 2-1 victory, Brazil's Ronaldo, Bebeto,
Denilson and Cesar Sampaio seemed to reflect the train-station
scene, bursting to an overwhelming early display when the doors to
the 1998 World Cup opened against Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Each Brazilian player who touched the ball seemed to be trying
to top the previous one, slashing across the field and tiptoeing
the soccer ball around the defense. Brazil scored a goal barely
five minutes into the match on a beautiful curving corner kick by
Bebeto to Sampaio, who headed it in.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians had five corner kicks and a dazzling 10 shots on
goal in the first 20 minutes alone. The wild Brazilian fans who
helped fill Stade de France to capacity (80,000) seemed ready to
start doing the samba in the aisles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted an open game,'' said Brazil coach Mario Zagallo, who
has been harshly criticized for what has been considered a
conservative style. ``I wanted a traditional Brazilian game.''
</P>
<P>
   Early, it looked like Brazil and Zagallo would get just that.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, the pace slowed and Brazil's victory did
not look nearly as awe-inspiring at the end as it did in the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Brazil managed to accomplish what few defending Cup
champions have done in the past _ it won. And despite falling into
a more methodical game in the second half, Brazil clearly showed
considerable explosiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult because it was the first game and
everyone was nervous,'' Zagallo said. ``But there's great
satisfaction with the win. Getting the three points right from the
start was very important.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, defending a World Cup crown has proved to be
difficult for championship teams, especially in the
much-anticipated and widely watched opening game four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1974, West Germany (1978), Argentina (1982 and 1990),
Italy (1986) and Brazil (1974) all either lost or tied the first
World Cup game they played after taking the crown.
</P>
<P>
   But this Brazilian team, thanks to the wonderful play of
Ronaldo, who had the Scottish defense backpedaling all day, and the
wonderful good fortune of a decisive 73rd-minute sequence, was
victorious.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were better than us; they clearly showed that they
were,'' Scottish coach Craig Brown said. ``But we fought the whole
time, and we were in a position to get a point out of it (for a
tie). Instead, we get nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing, but I think we proved that Brazil is not
an amazing team. It's very good in the midfield and up front but
with weaknesses at the back.''
</P>
<P>
   The clinching goal, in fact, came on an own-goal by Scotland's
Tommy Boyd, but it was Brazil's superiority up front on the attack
that sparked the smart play by Cafu.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo began the flurry from midfield, where he showed
spectacular skill throughout the day, twice nearly scoring. On the
way to the winning goal, he first got the ball to Denilson, who had
replaced Bebeto moments earlier and played well over the game's
final 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Denilson fired a quick shot that Scottish goalie Jim Leighton
saved but could not hold. The ball caromed to Cafu, who was
standing between players six yards in front of the net as Leighton
was trying to get back into position.
</P>
<P>
   Cafu quickly chipped an awkward shot at the goal, and it bounced
of Leighton's face toward Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in front of the net, you just try to get a shot
away and maybe get it to bounce in,'' Cafu said.
</P>
<P>
   It did _ off Leighton's face, then off Boyd's shoulder and into
the net for an own-goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were keeping the pressure on them as much as we could,''
Cafu said. ``We can play better. We had a lot of chances, but at
least we made the most of the last chance we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Scotland, which scored its goal on a penalty kick after Kevin
Gallacher was pushed while chasing a free ball inside Brazil's box,
never recovered after the own-goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Scots dropped to 0-1 in Group A, with games left against
Norway and Morocco. Only the top two teams in each group during
round-robin play advance to the second-round single-elimination
phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great day because we won,'' Zagallo said. ``We were
lucky to get the ball to bounce into the net, yes, but we had a lot
of other shots barely miss that could have gone in.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even with the second-half lull, the Brazilians outshot
the Scots 23-10 and had 11 corner kicks to Scotland's five. If not
for Leighton's many saves, it easily could have been 3-0 at the
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this game, I said that I wanted to find out if we were
just a talented team or a great team,'' Zagallo said. ``I think we
can be great. If there's luck involved, too, then that makes it
even better. That improves our odds. All champions have luck.''
</P>
<P>
   These defending champions, again, seem to have it all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
