<HEADLINE>
HOW TO STOP THOSE MESSY FIGHTS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime soon, possibly before the All-Star Game, Major League
Baseball officials probably will announce the formation of a
special committee to look into ways to stop fights during games.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Commissioner  &UR; Bud Selig, who needs to decide whether he
wants to own the Milwaukee Brewers or be the real commissioner,
announced last week that the league and the players association,
which laughingly must approve the slightest of changes to the game,
are looking into ways to deter brawls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am distressed by the recent on-the-field fighting that has
detracted from the spirit and character of Major League Baseball,''
Selig said in a release. ``It has placed the safety of players in
jeopardy and reflected poorly on that large majority of players who
respect and maintain the tradition of sportsmanship long associated
with the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds good, but fighting in baseball is not a new
phenomenon. Some changes can be implemented. For instance,
relievers who leave the bullpen and run more than the length of a
football field to join in a fracas can, and probably will, be
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   But to expect players in the dugout not to come to the aid of
their teammate, usually a lone batter against what could be nine
players, is ridiculous. It's been part of the big-league game since
the days of  &UR; Ty
 &UR; Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball fights are not new. Watching them from six angles with
slow-motion replays, however, is a more recent trend. The
proliferation of televised games is the only new thing baseball has
encountered with fights.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when these fights would occur just as routinely
as now, and it was no big deal, mostly because the entire nation
could only read about them, not actually watch them time and again
on TV. &QL; 
On the warpath &QL; 
The Cleveland Indians, one of the American League's kingpins five
years running, have added an impressive pitching staff to what once
was a one-dimensional ballclub intent on banging its way though a
season with muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, an Indians staff that has been hit hard by injuries
leads the league in ERA. Since bottoming out with a 20-18 record on
May 13, the Indians have gone 18-7.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason for the upsurge belongs to starters  &UR; Charles
 &UR; Nagy, Dave Burba and  &UR; Jaret Wright. That trio has a combined 13-1
record since the Indians began their winning ways. Throw in  &UR; Dwight
 &UR; Gooden, who has allowed four earned runs in his past two starts,
and
 &UR; Bartolo Colon (5-4), and the Indians are looking like a club that
could scare once the playoffs begin.
</P>
<P>
   It's true Cleveland is fortunate to reside in the AL East, a
division filled with mediocrity and where only the Indians are
above .500. Cleveland's front office is fully aware they are in a
weakened division, something they do not need to apologize for.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland General Manager  &UR; John Hart knew the Indians could slug
their way into the playoffs. He also knows, once there, pitching
will get them to advance, which is exactly what Cleveland did last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're hoping history will repeat itself on the north side
of Ohio. &QL; 
The great Moises &QL; 
 &UR; Moises Alou, who voiced displeasure when he became the first cog in
the Marlins' World Series championship club to be jettisoned last
fall, appears to be over the initial hurt and is now one happy
Houston Astros player.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Alou's teammates have welcomed their new slugger with
open arms. He leads the Astros in home runs and RBIs and is one
point behind  &UR; Carl Everett in average, pushing him alongside  &UR; Jeff
Bagwell and
 &UR; Craig Biggio as go-to guys on the defending Central Division
championship club.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I wasn't as happy as I am now,'' Alou said.
``I wasn't used to being in Houston and playing with these guys. It
takes a lot to get adjusted to playing with a new team. At the same
time, I never felt like a new guy because I was proven. I didn't
have to show anyone what kind of player I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou began his stint with Houston hot and has been basically the
same ever since, no matter what he recently said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I was driving in enough runs early in the
season, but I feel like I'm doing much better now,'' said Alou, who
was batting .335 and had 13 home runs and 53 RBIs entering
Wednesday's game against Detroit. ``I'm getting a lot of two-hit
(games), which is something I feel like I'm supposed to do. It also
helps to be on a club like ours where there are so many weapons in
the lineup.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
