<HEADLINE>
HORRIBLE RE CORDS RUN IN MINORS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Not only are the Diamondbacks trying to avoid having a
worse record than the Florida Marlins, a similar battle is being
waged at the minor league level.
</P>
<P>
   The worst team in the minors is Brevard County, the Marlins'
Class A affiliate in the Florida State League. Through Tuesday, the
club was 17-44, No. 118 out of 118 minor league teams.
</P>
<P>
   But right within striking distance are the South Bend Silver
Hawks, the Diamondbacks' Class A team in the Midwest League. After
losing 12 of 13 games through Tuesday, the Hawks were 18-42.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Diamondbacks, their other, more advanced
Class A team, High Desert, is doing much better.
</P>
<P>
   How bad are the Silver Hawks? Let us count the ways.
</P>
<P>
   Item: They had a league-leading 125 errors, more than two a
game. Next in the league was Beloit with 102 errors.
</P>
<P>
   Item: They had a .238 team batting average, last in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Item: During a recent four-game sweep by West Michigan, the
Hawks were outscored, 32-6.
</P>
<P>
   Item: During another four-game span, one of them a victory, the
Hawks struck out 52 times, or just less than half of 108 possible
outs.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of offense and defense has taken its toll on a decent
pitching staff. But right-hander  &UR; Jeff  &UR; Andrews has suffered the
most. In each of Andrews' past eight starts, he has not given up
more than two earned runs. His record is 0-2 with six no-decisions.
Overall, Andrews is 1-5 with a 2.22 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Rival managers know how good Andrews is. He was one of four
Hawks picked for the All-Star Game. Another selection was
lefthander  &UR; Ben Norris, who has an 0-4 record to go with a 3.09
ERA. Yet another pitcher,  &UR; Jason Jensen, was good enough to make
it. He has a 2.78 ERA. And pitcher  &UR; Ynocencio de la Cruz was
outstanding until suffering a separated shoulder during a brawl.
He's out for a full year.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, job opportunities are available.  &UR; Mel Didier, the
Diamondbacks director of player development, said some of the
recent draft picks, notably pitcher  &UR; Javier Lopez (a fourth-round
selection), will start out at South Bend.
</P>
<P>
   The other piece of good news is that the All-Star break is at
hand. The other two All-Stars are second baseman  &UR; Jackie Rexrode,
who will start, and first baseman  &UR; Wyley Steelmon, who probably
won't play because of a separated shoulder. &QL; 
Brief stints &QL; 
Right-hander  &UR; Martin Sanchez was suspended by High Desert for
disciplinary reasons and sent to extended spring training in
Tucson. The Mavericks' closer, Sanchez had eight saves.
</P>
<P>
   High Desert placed catcher  &UR; Keith Wilson on the disabled list
(root canal) and sent catcher  &UR; Jose Lopez and infielder
 &UR; Jared Martin to South Bend. Joining the Mavericks were left-handers
 &UR; Jason Martines and  &UR; Jeff Wilson, righty  &UR; Don Peters (rehab
assignment) and catcher  &UR; Brad Allison.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hanley Frias, recovering from a broken bone in his hand, made
his first appearance Tuesday. Playing third base for Tucson, Frias
went 0 for 1 and had three walks and a stolen base. He is on 20-day
rehab assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Joe Verplancke, who won five games in relief for
High Desert, moved into the starting rotation and won two more
games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
