<HEADLINE>
BEST SHOW IS BEFORE GAME WITH MCGWIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Buck Showalter looked out toward Bank One Ballpark's
upper deck in left field, near a restaurant. That's the area where
Mark McGwire likely will park a bushel of balls during batting
practice this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe instead of soup specials, they should have helmet
specials,'' the Diamondbacks manager said.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe stand-up comedy isn't what Showalter should do if he
ever needs another job, but you get the idea. When Big Red comes to
town, expect to get showered with horsehide.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that thousands of fans will congregate in left and
left-center field stands a couple of hours before each of this
weekend's games for the opportunity to snag a drive by the St.
Louis Cardinals slugger, who has 30 home runs and is on pace to
break the single-season record of 61.
</P>
<P>
   At stadiums across the country, the lure of taking home a
McGwire blast has been hard to resist. At some parks, almost 10,000
early arrivals have dashed for baseballs.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Regas, general manager of Friday's Front Row Grill at Bank
One Ballpark, said the restaurant that offers outdoor seating will
be jammed for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could watch, but I'll be too busy,'' he said.
``Nobody else has ever had this kind of effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the pre-game radio host will get in the act. Brad Cesmat of
KTAR-AM (620) will be in the outfield stands with a net starting at
6 p.m. Any balls he catches will be donated to the Blind Children's
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Batting practice pitchers do their best to accommodate the
hitters, which in turn means accommodating the fans in the outfield
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just put the ball where the hitter wants it,'' said Marcos
Garcia, one of three batting practice hurlers for the Diamondbacks.
``The big thing is to keep it in the strike zone and keep it at the
same speed. If you change speeds, they might complain. In batting
practice, a player wants to get his stroke down, and he may want a
pitch in a certain spot every time.''
</P>
<P>
   So you catch a McGwire homer during batting practice, and you
have . . . exactly that, a scuffed ball, maybe hit a dozen times,
worth maybe a buck. If you're lucky enough to latch onto a home run
he hits during the game, the sentimental value will far outweigh
the monetary value, even if the slugger eventually surpasses Roger
Maris' mark of 61 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make any difference what number it is, other than
60, 61 or 62,'' said Chuck Simo, owner of Nostalgia Stadium in
Scottsdale. ``Any other is just a home run ball, no more
significant than any other. And batting practice home runs are
meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're in the right place at the right time and catch the
ball that breaks Maris' mark, keep your senses about you, Simo
warns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get it verified,'' he said. ``Get the names and addresses of
people around you who saw you get the ball. If he does break the
record, whoever gets that ball will probably hold onto it for an
auction for collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to say what it would be worth at this time. For
instance, the ball that Mickey Mantle hit for his first home run
went for $27,000 at an auction. The most expensive ball ever, and
it will go up for auction in November, will be the first home run
ever hit in Yankee Stadium. It was hit by Babe Ruth, and will bring
well over $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even though big money won't be involved, if you're anywhere near
the vicinity of a McGwire home run this weekend, be prepared for
pushing, shoving and maybe a few bruises in the scramble for the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   But if the unthinkable happens, and McGwire just hits grounders
or pop-ups during batting practice, don't start yanking your hair
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize it's not that easy to hit a home run in
batting practice,'' McGwire told columnist Mark Whicker of the
``Orange County Register.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a good idea to keep something else in mind when you're
scratching and clawing for baseballs. In many cases, you'll be
invading the territory of fans who have bought seats, and instead
of going home with a ball, your only souvenir might be a shiner. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2329EDT &QL; 
