<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4103 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HATE-JESSE-COX     06-10 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HATE-JESSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson call Texas murder``most heinous'' racial crime in almost
50 years
 &HT;    By Andy Adams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Rev. Jesse Jackson told about 300 people crammed
into a small Baptist church for a prayer vigil Wednesday evening
that the murder of James Byrd Jr. was the nation's ``most heinous''
crime of racial hate in almost 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he visited Jasper, an East Texas town of about
8,000 people, to console Byrd's family because, ``At a time like
this, we are breathless. We can't quite explain it. We don't
understand it. We are hurt, we're embarrassed, we are humiliated,
we are afraid. What can we do?''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a 49-year-old Jasper man, was dragged to death behind a
truck early Sunday morning. Three white men are being held by
Jasper authorities on murder charges in connection with the death
of Byrd, who was black.
</P>
<P>
   In the Greater New Bethel Baptist Church, where 59 of 133
members attended services Sunday, area residents flooded the chapel
for two hours of prayer and singing followed by Jackson's speech.
Another several hundred people gathered outside, as did numerous
members of the local and national media.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation is in shock today over this heinous crime,''
Jackson said. ``It is the most heinous crime of this sort to happen
since Emmett Till in Mississippi nearly 50 years ago. So why are
people here from Chicago or Houston or other parts of Texas? He was
not killed because of geography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone said, `Well, at least, it was not a planned killing.
It was not a conspiracy arbitrarily.' That's worse than a plan
because, if our lives are in jeopardy in general because of our
race, our sex, our religion _ that's worse than a plan. We should
be safe in general, not in jeopardy in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson opened and closed his appearance with prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come by here, my Lord. Come by here,'' he prayed. ``Come by
here, my Lord. Come by here. Somebody needs you, Lord. Come by
here. We're waiting on you. We can't do nothing without you. Came
by here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Search our hearts. You know our ways. Find the things in our
hearts that should not be: hatred, jealousy, malice. Remove any
racism, sexism, anti-Semitism or meanness. Remove it right now and
make us better, not bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson visited Byrd's family before attending the prayer vigil.
He told them of professional basketball player Dennis Rodman's
desire to help by offering to pay Byrd's funeral cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis is from Texas and he has an acute sensitivity to the
family's pain,'' Jackson said. ``It's just a joy for me to know
that they always try to portray Dennis as some buffoon, because he
_ like most Texans _ likes funny hairstyles. I do think it was just
a tremendous gesture on the part of Dennis Rodman to say to the
mayor, `Send me the bill for the funeral expenses.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson compared the racial tension in East Texas to a parable
in the Bible about how lions and lambs learned to live in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because lions are stronger than lambs, they have the press on
their sides,'' he said. ``Because they're stronger than lambs, they
have more life options than lambs. Lambs learn early on to stay out
of lions' way. And lions, because of the stress of their character
deficit, destroy lambs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jasper will never be safe for whites until it's safe for
blacks. It will not be safe for blacks until it's safe for whites.
What the lion and the lamb have in common is that neither lamb nor
lion wants the forest to catch on fire. Neither lion nor lamb want
acid rain on their backs. Neither lion nor lamb wants the water
poisoned. Surely, if lion and lamb can find common ground, then
black and white _ all of God's children _ must find common
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, Jasper is not starting its effort to build racial
harmony from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he was glad to see both white and black ministers
lined up to attend to the Byrd family's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's not one side of town mourning and the other side of
town observing. There's a sense of agony everywhere. And that's a
step in the right direction, because we should go from agony to
ecstacy together. We should go from tragedy to triumph together. We
should say to those killing, `Never again,' together. We must live
together as brothers and sisters together.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson concluded by referring to two more parts of scripture:
John's story in Revelations and the parable of the good Samaritan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a new heaven and a new earth,'' he said, quoting
Revelations. ``I see a new Jasper. The old one has passed away. We
must not tolerate hate on any side of town. We must not tolerate
violence on any side of town. There must be a new Jasper, for the
old one has passed away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
