<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980610.0590 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4108 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUNS-AZR &LR;      06-10 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SISTERS OF NO MERCY GIVE HECK TO FOES OF PHOENIX WNBA TEAM
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Sacramento isn't sacred, they'll proclaim at
Thursday's Mercury season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is much of anything else to the Sisters of No Mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Mary Hoops and Sister 3-Point are taking their act on the
road for the first time, along with their rulers, habits, wimples
(head covering) and puppet, ``Sister Box-Out.'' Then Sunday,
they'll be back at their familiar loca tion _ section 103, row 5,
seats 3-4 _ behind the opponents' bench at America West Arena,
giving Los Angeles Sparks center Lisa Leslie the kind of grief they
couldn't during April's U.S.-Argentina exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told her as long as she's playing for the USA, we'll be
nice,'' Mother Mary Hoops said. But that courtesy doesn't extend to
the WNBA season and particularly the Sparks, whom the Mercury
subdued in overtime of last year's reg ular-season finale to win
the Western Confer ence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nun of your business'' and ``Nun of the above'' are etched in
heavenly script on the women's wimples to answer the most asked
question: Are you really sisters?
</P>
<P>
   Yes they are, Mother Mary Hoops admits, but not to each other or
in a religious sense.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Newman, 56, the not so good mother, and Beth Ells, 49, the
somewhat wicked sister, both of Phoenix, both have biological
sisters. In fact, the genesis of their Mercury personas was the
Halloween that Newman and her real sister dressed up as nuns.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have become a symbol of one of the most raucous
audiences in town. The Mer cury led the WNBA in attendance (13,703
aver age) during its inaugural season and has doubled its season
ticket base to more than 9,000. These are not the corporate,
sit-on-the-hands types who can afford Suns tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Newman has seats for both, although her Suns tickets are in the
upper-bowl boonies, and she said the biggest difference is the ear
ringing that won't go away until hours af ter a Mercury game. Not
to men tion an almost symbiotic rapport with the players that
Newman said brought her to tears at the 1997 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   She and Ells played college basketball in the pre-Title IX days,
when resources and opportu nities for women were scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started playing bas ketball in grade school, one could
only dribble the ball a total of three times, and only the rovers
could go as far as half court,'' Sis ter 3-Point says on the duo's
Web site (www.sistersofnomercy.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``As a freshman at Ohio State, I played varsity, which meant I
rode the pine quite a bit. All of this leads me to say that I'm
used to sitting on the sidelines cheering my teammates on . . . the
biggest difference is that now I get to carry a sign, a ruler and
cover my gray hair with a wimple.''
</P>
<P>
   To explain themselves, the sis ters quote Swiss psychologist
Carl Jung: ``The attainment of whole ness requires one to stake
one's whole being. Nothing less will do; there can be no easier
conditions, no substitutes, no compromises.''
</P>
<P>
   In simpler terms, no mercy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to do positive things,'' and not offend Catholicism,
Mother Mary Hoops said. ``Peo ple ask us to hold their babies or
have their picture taken with us. And you can't believe how many
people want to tell us their life story about going to Catholic
school, bloody knuckles, the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters pulled together some novices to play in the Mer cury
3-on-3 tournament in Janu ary. The novices and postulants will
carry on the sisters' mission at four home games in July while they
are out of town, chaperoning students to Ireland, Wales and
England. Ells is an professor in the art department at Scottsdale
Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Their comings and goings are posted on their Web site. For ex
ample: June 11, Sacramento; June 18, Tempe Spaghetti Com pany (for
a Mercury appearance); July 16, Westminster Abbey, Lon don.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters drove here for the opener, a commitment even Mer
cury Coach Cheryl Miller couldn't believe when she was told. How
they'll be received at Arco Arena, where Sacramento averaged 7,858
last season, is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   At home, where the show is bigger and better, the sisters are
just part of the scene, but a prom inent part. When they were
invited on the court to dance with the Mercury Hip-Hop Spirit Squad
near the end of an exhibition game last week, ``our dream came
true,'' Mother Mary Hoops said.
</P>
<P>
   About all that could better is if owner Jerry Colangelo took the
advice of one of their early signs: Hire Nuns, Fire Galaxy (who has
been lost in space since the 1997 home opener) as team mascot.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Mary Hoops claims on the Web site to have prayed for the
WNBA since 1965. When that prayer was answered, ``I distinctly
heard God renew my call and to say that although I was too old to
play for the WNBA, I would never be old to play with the WNBA.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
