<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4111 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-ARIZONA-PREDATORS     06-10 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-PREDATORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL NINO BRINGS PREDATORY FEAST  
 POPULATION LEVEL UNLIKELY TO SPIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's about 5:30 a.m. on Memorial Day. The driver heads north on
Arizona 87 toward Payson. He is beyond the Saguaro Lake turnoff and
enjoying the cool wind coming through the window.
</P>
<P>
   A sleek-looking coyote appears from the median and trots across
the highway, stopping nonchalantly to watch the vehicle pass. The
driver smiles. The cool, early morning is a wonderful time to see
all kinds of wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle begins its climb out of the lower desert. The driver
has not yet donned sunglasses to face the morning sun. He is
admiring the lush vegetation around him when he spots movement to
the right. Another coyote?
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. A mountain lion emerges from the roadside
vegetation and lopes across the highway. The driver has seen
mountain lions in the wild but never one crossing a highway. He
starts to pull over, but that spooks the lion, which disappears
into the dense cover of the median.
</P>
<P>
   The driver picks up his camera but decides plunging into the
cover to ``play with kitty'' might not be a good idea. On a hike
near Strawberry several years ago, he was stalked by a young lion.
He remembers that, smiles again and drives away. This already is a
good day.
</P>
<P>
   It's spring turkey season. The hunter has a permit and is along
the East Fork of the Black River in the White Mountains. He'll fish
for trout first, then go call up a turkey.
</P>
<P>
   He uses a prepared trout bait (stinky stuff), then heads back to
his vehicle and stows his fishing gear. He picks up his turkey call
and single-shot shotgun then heads off. He is being followed.
</P>
<P>
   A black bear apparently has followed the scent of the trout
bait. It reaches the vehicle after the hunter has left, works over
the vehicle a little, then eats a plastic saguaro cactus atop on
the vehicle's radio antenna.
</P>
<P>
   Then it follows the hunter. The encounter is inevitable. The
hunter shoots the bear with the shotgun. Asked later by wildlife
officers if he could have fired into the air to possibly spook the
bear, the hunter says that he had no intention of trying to spook
it with a single-shot gun.
</P>
<P>
   The officers cut open the dead bear and find the plastic saguaro
in its stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The turkey hunter can't quit shaking after the encounter.
</P>
<P>
   These stories, both thrilling and chilling, aren't at all
unusual in Arizona. Such events occur probably a hundred times
every year. Arizona's two biggest predators, the black bear and the
mountain lion, are exceptionally fascinating creatures.
</P>
<P>
   The past few years were extremely dry and brought with them many
bear stories. Times were tough. These extremely adaptable creatures
found an easy meal when they could. If food and water were scarce,
some would come into town to find relief, knocking down a few doors
in search of food, eating garbage and even the occasional cat or
dog.
</P>
<P>
   This year has been different. El Nino's rains has meant
plentiful prey throughout the state. Rabbits, quail and other
wildlife that seemed to disappear are evident everywhere. Does that
mean the state will see a corresponding spike in the number of
predatory animals?
</P>
<P>
   No, says John Phelps, the fur-bearer biologist for the Arizona
Game and Fish Deartment.
</P>
<P>
   The big animals _ bears, lions, elk and deer _ don't respond in
the short term to spikes in the number of smaller game and
vegetation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not nearly as much reproduction from (bears and lions)
as with small animals,'' Phelps said. ``You can see improvement in
good years, but it's not nearly as significant as in smaller
animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bears, Phelps said, are ``reproductively incapable.'' A female
typically is four years old before her first cubs are born. After
that, she typically will give birth every other year.
</P>
<P>
   Lions aren't quite the same, he said, but even in good years,
survival of the young isn't good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Population density is limited by interspecific strife,'' he
said. ``That means they kill each other. They're territorial
animals. It's a survival thing. If another animal of their kind
invades their territory, they might kill it.''
</P>
<P>
   Male bears are especially protective, he said. Cub survival rate
is no good because males often eat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know exactly why,'' Phelps said. ``The cubs may be a
food source. Or it may be a sexual thing. They want to spread their
own genes and don't want anything to interfere with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Territory limits the number of large predators. Thus, it doesn't
matter how much food is available. The dominant creatures want no
intruders on their territory.
</P>
<P>
   Phelps said bears are more tolerant of each other. For instance,
if acorns or prickly pear fruit is abundant, a large number of
bears might share territory. They all have plenty and tolerate one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Lions are different.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not like bears,'' Phelps said. ``They are meat eaters
(bears are omnivorous). They seldom eat anything but something
they've killed. They don't allow an intruder.''
</P>
<P>
   Lions fear humans and will stay away, apparently deciding that
humans are too large for their prey base.
</P>
<P>
   Although bears are opportunists that will eat what they can,
most will stay away from civilization when their natural food is
plentiful, as it is this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most trouble we should have this year . . . are with bears
the are habituated to eating human garbage and things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish officers will try to relocate those that do
venture into campsites and outlying areas, though Phelps said that
relocations seldom are successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fed bear usually is a dead bear,'' he said. ``Once they get
used to feeding off humans, there's usually no way to get rid of
them but kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   So you probably won't see much difference this summer in
predator problems. These creatures seem to limit themselves. But
with abundant food, they'll probably be really healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The populations won't increase or decline much. These creatures
keep their hunting grounds in order. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
