<SLUG> BC-HKN-FINALS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT'S JUST HOCKEY,' HUNTER SAYS OF ROUGH STUFF
</HEADLINE>
  (dc) 
 By ED WILLES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Dale Hunter has only been playing in the National
Hockey League for 18 years, so he did not see what all the fuss was
about. But his Washington Capitals teammates read a larger meaning
into his mugging of Steve Yzerman, the Detroit Red Wings' captain,
during Game 1 of the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just hockey,'' said Hunter, a rugged center who is making
his first appearance in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Berube, Hunter's linemate, said: ``Dale had him down and
he showed him we're here to play. We're not happy just be here and
we're not happy just to be the Eastern Conference champs. We're
here to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, the Capitals' 37-year-old captain, tangled with Yzerman
twice during the Red Wings' 2-1 victory Tuesday night. In the first
instance, Hunter rapped Yzerman. In the second, Hunter sat on
Yzerman behind the Capitals' net, then landed a series of noogies
to the back of his head before the Red Wings' leader took a
retaliatory minor for slashing. The two incidents were the only
moments of unruliness in an otherwise uneventful Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just holding him down,'' Hunter said. ``If I was banging
his head he would have been knocked out. We're aware of their good
players. We're just trying to play hard against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals, in fact, turned the tables and accused the Red
Wings of taking liberties with Peter Bondra and Joe Juneau,
Washington's finesse players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bondra got kneed, another one of our guys got speared,'' said
the Capitals' Chris Simon, the third member of the Hunter-Berube
line. ``If they want to play that way against our good players,
we'll play that way, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Berube said: ``If Darren McCarty runs Joe Juneau there's nothing
much I can do about it at the time. This is the Stanley Cup final.
You can't take a punch at the guy and take a penalty. But you can
play hard against their stars.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   LOW RATINGS? NOT TO WORRY
</P>
<P>
   The television ratings are down on both sides of the border for
the Stanley Cup finals. That is not surprising considering that the
NHL is suffering from a general lack of goals, excitement and
interest.
</P>
<P>
   But Commissioner Gary Bettman sees the league's well-documented
travails as a temporary aberration, not a deep-rooted set of
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reject the notion this is a game in trouble,'' he said. ``On
the contrary, I think the vital signs are good. We have strong
ownership and the franchises have never been more stable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said the weak television ratings have been skewed by
poor numbers in New York, Los Angeles and other major centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were the same there as last season, the overall
numbers would be about the same,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
