<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-kj </SLUG>
 scuttlebutt-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
KJ holds 
appeal for 
Rockets
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barkley endorses &QL; 
free-agent guard
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ You've heard of a mother-and-child reunion. Feuding
families eventually reconcile. And there are a million stories of
long-lost friends getting back together after years of separation.
</P>
<P>
   So are you ready for Chuck and KJ, the sequel?
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley said Wednesday he has talked with former Phoenix
Suns teammate and free-agent point guard Kevin Johnson about the
possibility of joining the Rockets for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Sources at the NBA Finals confirmed Johnson is high on the
Rockets' list of free-agent possibilities. Teams cannot begin
contacting free agents until July 1, and the league's strained
labor-relations situation could delay that date further.
</P>
<P>
   But it's clear the Rockets are prepared to make a run at
Johnson. And, Barkley said, Johnson has indicated he would be
interested in joining the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would automatically make us better,'' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley and Johnson were not the closest of friends when they
were teammates. But Barkley said the past two seasons apart have
drawn him closer to KJ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm better friends with Kevin now than I was when I was
playing with him,'' Barkley said. ``I would love to have him here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked with Kevin a few times, and I think he'd be happy
to come here, because we'd have one more shot to win it all. I
think he showed last season he can still play.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 32, averaged 9.5 points and 4.9 assists for the
guard-heavy Suns in 1997-98. He split time with Jason Kidd and
Steve Nash. But in the second half of the season, when Johnson was
recovered from hamstring and knee problems, he was a productive
player for the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders at the NBA Finals said the Rockets' primary competition
for Johnson might be the Sacramento Kings. Johnson grew up in
Sacramento and maintains a close connection to the area, where he
is heavily involved in youth organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But going to Sacramento would yield Johnson virtually no chance
to win big. Even making the playoffs would be iffy.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, who can't comment on their pursuit of any free
agents until after July 1 and whenever the collective-bargaining
agreement is settled, likely will have between $7 million and $10
million available under the salary cap this summer. They would like
to get two quality players with that money. Johnson, it is
believed, would be available for a relatively low sum by NBA
standards and could leave enough money for another good free agent.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the Rockets plan on pursuing Chicago's Scottie
Pippen, acquiring somebody of Johnson's caliber might not be
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Barkley combined in 1993 to lead the Suns to the NBA
Finals, where they lost to the Chicago Bulls in six games. That was
Barkley's first season in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Barkley and Johnson grew apart, partly because of
their diverse lifestyles. Barkley is a free spirit, to say the
least, while Johnson is regarded as a clean-living churchgoer.
</P>
<P>
   But their differences were only part of the problem. Barkley
said the Suns organization is partly to blame because executives in
the organization pitted Barkley against Johnson at times, which
resulted in a polarization of the two.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard is a position the Rockets have wanted to shore up,
although Matt Maloney did a good job in the playoffs against Utah's
John Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Western Conference is getting overrun with quality
point guards, with Stockton, Seattle's Gary Payton, Phoenix's Kidd,
Portland's Damon Stoudamire, Minnesota's Stephon Marbury and others
commanding respect at the position.
</P>
<P>
   The main needs for the Rockets heading into the offseason were
to get younger and more athletic and to find another ball-handler.
The trade of Kevin Willis on Tuesday was a step in addressing the
age issue.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson would give the Rockets a supreme ball-handler who also
can create his own offense. As for athleticism, a player like
Cedric Ceballos or Jim Jackson could be brought in, and with
Rodrick Rhodes' extra year of seasoning, that void might be filled.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, getting Pippen would mean getting an athletic
ball-handler _ at a price tag probably starting in the $8 million
to $10 million range and going up 20 percent each season
thereafter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
