<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRABU AND YANKS BEAT EXPOS, 6-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Hideki Irabu has been the Yankees' best pitcher and
perhaps the best in the American League this season. He stifled
Montreal Wednesday night, 6-2, striking out five in six innings as
his league-best earned run average rose to 1.59. With a 6-1 record,
he is a candidate to start the all-star game.
</P>
<P>
   But Irabu is probably the Yankees' worst athlete. Fielding bunts
is a challenge for him, and he sometimes doesn't bother to move to
first on ground balls to the right side of the infield. Earlier
this week, his manager anointed him as the team's worst hitter. In
addition to everything else, his helmet doesn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   With a line single in the second inning, Irabu became the first
Yankees' pitcher to get a hit since Larry Gowell hit a double on
Oct. 4, 1972, the season before the American League adopted the
designated hitter. Irabu also dropped a perfect bunt on an
impossible pitch in the fourth. There has never been greater
evidence that the Yankees are in the middle of a season to
remember.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have won nine straight, the longest streeak of the
season, and are 46-13 overall, which matches the best early-season
record in club history; the 1939 Yankees, who beat Cincinnati in
the World Series, also started 46-13.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Yankees lose the final game of the series with the
Expos, they have already won the series; they have won 23 straight
series, dating back to the first two days of the regular season.
The last team to win 24 straight series was the Cincinnati Reds in
1970.
</P>
<P>
   To say Irabu does not look the part of a hitter is like
suggesting Don Knotts doesn't appear presidential. His head seems
to bulge out of his ill-fitting helmet, and when he swings, his
first movement often is to move his back foot backward. Irabu
batted in an exhibition game in March and, after barely topping the
ball, simply returned to the dugout. There was no practical reason
to run to first.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, when Irabu batted in the second inning,
Montreal's Dustin Hermanson threw him a first-pitch fastball. Irabu
stepped backward with both feet, almost out of the box. Hermanson,
who typically throws in the mid-90s, then threw another fastball.
</P>
<P>
   This time Irabu stepped forward and ripped a line drive to
center field. Whoops could be heard coming from the Yankees' dugout
as Irabu ran stiffly to first base, a smile splitting his face. To
mark Irabu's first major-league hit, the umpires tossed the ball
out of the game..
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, Irabu came to bat with runners at first and
second and one out, an obvious bunt situation. Before the second
pitch of the at-bat, with the Montreal infield anticipating the
bunt, Torre signaled for Irabu to try pulling back his bat and
slapping the ball _ which he nearly did, fouling off the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   With two strikes, Hermanson threw a neck-high fastball. Irabu
somehow reached up and bunted the ball past Hermanson. Shortstop
Mark Grudzielanek rushed in, fielded the ball and threw it wildly
to first, with one run scoring. Irabu was given credit for a
sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   Sanity was restored in the sixth inning. Hermanson threw a
breaking ball with two strikes and Irabu tumbled onto his back
although the pitch never came close to hitting him. Irabu flailed
weakly at the next pitch and struck out.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched pretty well, too, in the recent tradition of Yankees'
starting pitchers. During the nine-game winning streak, the
starters have compiled an ERA of 1.70, and averaged seven and
two-thirds innings per start.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu had a good fastball, as usual, against the Expos. But he
threw his curveball with more effect than in any of his other
starts this season, and after the first two innings, his
split-fingered fastball was diving. Irabu struck out the side in
the fourth inning; he has 54 in 68 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu was taken out of the game after a 36-minute rain delay in
the bottom of the seventh, the first delay since the roof was
removed from Olympic Stadium on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored early without Irabu's help. An error by
Montreal's Jose Vidro gave Tino Martinez a chance to bat with two
outs in the first inning, and Martinez blasted a two-run homer. Two
more runs scored in the fourth _ the Irabu inning _ and Scott
Brosius singled home Bernie Williams in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had a scare in that inning in a play they hope will
not have long-term ramifications. Williams slid awkwardly into
third as he stole the base in the sixth inning, his right knee
bending strangely. Williams grimaced and called for time, and
Yankees manager Joe Torre and Steve Donohue, the trainer, charged
onto the field to tend to him. Williams tested his knee and stayed
in the game another inning before leaving for a pinch-hitter in the
seventh. Williams' knee was to be examined late last night.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Tim Raines stole the 800th base of his career in the eighth
inning, joining Rickey Henderson, Lou Brock and Ty Cobb in reaching
that plateau in this century. Raines, 38, played with Montreal from
1979 to 1990 before going to the American League. Before the first
game of this three-game series, Raines was honored here, given a
standing ovation, but he did not play. He was in the starting
lineup Wednesday night and was given a standing ovation again when
he was announced before his first at-bat. Raines walked to lead off
the eighth and, with Shayne Bennett pitching, Raines broke for
second. The throw from Chris Widger, the Montreal catcher, actually
beat Raines to the bag, but it eluded the shortstop. As his
teammates and the fans stood and cheered for Raines, he raised his
arms happily. Early in his career, Raines was the game's premier
base-stealer, swiping 70 or more bases in his first six full
seasons in the majors, including 90 in 1983, and 71 in 88 games in
the strike-shortened 1981 season. Raines' steal Wednesday night was
his fifth for this season, and the Yankees' 78th of 1998. The
Yankees stole a total of 99 last year ... Paul O'Neill beat out an
infield single in the fifth inning, extending his hitting streak to
17 games _ the longest of his career, and the Yankees' longest
since Derek Jeter hit in 17 straight games in 1996 ... Joe Torre,
the Yankees' manager, said he has no intention of using a six-man
rotation, despite the depth of his staff. Torre's feeling is that
regular extra rest might diminish the performances of David Wells,
Andy Pettitte and Ramiro Mendoza, three pitcher who badly need
regular work to remain sharp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-10-98 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
